<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS CAN'T STOP IVERSON, SIXERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ After an amazing comeback Monday night against
the Boston Celtics, the Mavericks didn't have anything left in the
tank last night.
</P>
<P>
   They left a lane open for Allen Iverson to make a bee line to
the basket as the Philadelphia 76ers drove away with a 106-87
thumping of the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we had nothing,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson said.
``This is the worst game we've played all year, and I definitely
credit Philly's defense. It's very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't give very much competition tonight, but that's the
NBA. You have a few of these every year, and this was one of them
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with a slightly torn rotator cuff in his right shoulder,
Iverson poured in 35 points on 15-of-18 shooting, with most of the
All-Star guard's shots coming on uncontested forays to the basket.
He scored on 11 layups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was going to play, but I kind of wish he didn't,''
Mavericks guard Michael Finley said. ``\RThe injury\S forced him to
go to the basket more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was making the layups and pretty much playing as if it
wasn't bothering him.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with a patch over his right shoulder, Iverson wound up
hitting seven of nine shots and scoring 15 of the 76ers' 29
first-quarter points. Iverson came in averaging 30.1 points but had
31 after three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, that patch was a decoy,'' Mavericks guard Robert Pack
said. ``Allen put that patch on like something was wrong with his
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an all-star player, but tonight we made it a little
easier for him. Unfortunately for us, defensively we weren't
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers shot 63 percent from the field, which also was a high
this season for a Mavericks opponent. It was like target practice
for the 76ers; Theo Ratliff made nine of 10 shots and scored 19
points, and Toni Kukoc added 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mavericks forward Dennis Rodman left early in the
third period with a right calf injury and did not return. He
finished with a season-low three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My calf was a little sore today,'' Rodman said. ``I thought I
was going to tear a muscle in my calf like I've done the last
couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played \Rhorribly\S anyway. We didn't have a chance to win
it, so I said I wasn't going to go out there and exert myself any
more than I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who scored a team-high 15 points, said the Mavericks
have started a dangerous trend lately. Although the Mavericks were
able to beat Denver, 98-96, Saturday and come from 20 points down
Monday to beat Boston (108-100), Finley doesn't like the pattern of
falling behind early and having to play catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won two games playing terrible,'' Finley said. ``Sooner
or later it was a false sense of security, and it came to a head
tonight where we played terrible and a team played great.
</P>
<P>
   ``When those two things are going, we were on the losing end of
that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Iverson's heroics, the Mavericks only trailed 29-28
after the first period. But a late 14-4 run in the second quarter
gave Philadelphia a 53-42 lead at the half, and the 76ers poured it
on in the third, leading at one point by 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth time this season the Mavericks have lost a game
by 19 or more points. The last time they lost this badly was Nov.
29, a 107-82 loss to the New York Knicks at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those games that we were going to be out of it,
and it was going to be a blowout,'' Nelson said. ``You could see
that, I think, fairly early that we didn't have anything.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
