A2808 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-VERN-KAN &LR;      03-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Ex-lawmaker pleads guilty to felony mail fraud  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Former state Rep. Vernon Thompson pleaded
guilty Tuesday to two felony mail fraud charges and agreed to
cooperate with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas before U.S. District Judge Gary A. Fenner closed two
unrelated federal cases against Thompson, a Democrat who resigned
from the Missouri General Assembly in January. Thompson's plea
added another name to the long list of public officials convicted
in federal court since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After his hearing, Thompson said, ``I just hope young people
don't get in this kind of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also agreed to pay at least $9,100 in restitution. The
final amount will be established before he is sentenced. The
remaining charges against him could be dropped at his sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   He could face from eight to 21 months in prison, according to
preliminary estimates. Prosecutors could ask Fenner to sentence
Thompson to less than that range if his cooperation is substantial
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Whitley, a spokesman for U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill
Jr., said the irony in Thompson's case runs throughout a five-year
string of public corruption prosecutions in western Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a man who was elected seven times to the Missouri House
of Representatives,'' Whitley observed. ``Now, as a result of his
criminal wrongdoing, he can't even vote, let alone hold public
office. It's another unfortunate example of a public servant
abusing the public trust and having to pay the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's pleas clear the federal docket in Kansas City of
public corruption cases. Since the February 1995 guilty plea of
former Kansas City Councilman Michael Hernandez, Hill's office has
prosecuted 24 public officials or their associates on criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Those included former Kansas City Council members Chuck Weber
and D. Jeanne Robinson, former Jackson County Legislator James D.
Tindall and former Missouri House Speaker Bob Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline of public corruption prosecutions is unlikely to
remain empty for long, Whitley said. Such cases tend to generate
tips that take a while to flesh out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look back over the time line and you can see what
might be called lapses or quiet times,'' Whitley said. ``It's never
really been down. Public corruption cases begat one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Thompson, his son, a campaign aide and a Kansas City
property manager were accused of conspiring to steal more than
$250,000 from seven low-income apartment developments.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found that Thompson and the others transferred
money from the housing developments into an account controlled by a
real estate management company and then spent the money on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, prosecutors followed with a second set of
charges, alleging that Thompson and his campaign aide used a
nonprofit program to defraud Kansas City and a public employment
agency of up to $54,855 in public funds meant for youth and
anti-poverty programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and another man conspired to take state and federal
grant money and spend it on themselves, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was the last of the defendants to plead guilty in the
two cases.
</P>
<P>
   The property manager, Tucson D. Redd, pleaded guilty in November
to conspiracy; he is awaiting sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Thompson's son, Jamil Thompson, pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor tax charge and prosecutors agreed to dismiss more
serious counts against him.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, charges in the housing fraud case against
campaign aide Kevin Sallard were dropped in exchange for a guilty
plea to a felony mail fraud charge in the second case.
</P>
<P>
   All have agreed to help prosecutors develop new cases.
</P>
<P>
   Though Thompson's plea agreement does not list areas of interest
for investigators, court records in Sallard's case disclosed an
``ongoing investigation into the Citizens Housing and Information
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   The now-defunct council, which Thompson helped to create,
controlled millions of dollars in public inner-city housing funds
in the 1990s. No one in the organization has been charged, and
various officials over the years have denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 56, represented the 37th House district _ which covers
much of Kansas City south of the Missouri River _ since his
election in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   He was chairman of the House Urban Affairs Committee, which
handles much of the state legislation that deals specifically with
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's guilty plea will have no effect on his legislative
pension, state officials said. Gary Findlay, executive director of
the Missouri State Employees Retirement System, said Thompson is
eligible for a pension of $12,600 a year, based on serving seven
terms in office. Because Thompson is older than 55, he is eligible
to receive benefits immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
