<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AREA JOINS ASTHMA CLINICAL RESEARCH CENTER PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Six Kansas City physicians are joining with
researchers in 18 other cities across the country for what the
American Lung Association calls the largest search ever for better
treatments, and eventually a cure, for asthma.
</P>
<P>
   The research program, expected to start this fall, will involve
thousands of asthma patients nationwide in a series of studies into
a lung disease that has become a growing health threat in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of studies already are done for cancer or heart
disease, but these will be the first large-scale studies of
asthma,'' said Gary Salzman, a lung specialist at the University of
Missouri-Kansas City School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of the center was announced Tuesday at a news
conference at Benton Elementary School in Independence. In
November, an 8-year-old student at the school died during an asthma
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman will lead a team of UMKC physicians in the new Asthma
Clinical Research Center. The center will operate out of existing
space at the medical school, Truman Medical Center and Children's
Mercy Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The center is being funded by a five-year $750,000 grant from
the American Lung Association of Western Missouri. The asthma
research centers in other cities are being sponsored by local lung
association chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is a disorder marked by recurring bouts of wheezing,
coughing and breathlessness. During these asthma attacks, the
breathing tubes in the lungs constrict and fill with mucus. The
attacks may be triggered by allergic reactions, stress, exercise or
even changes in temperature.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons doctors don't yet understand, the number of asthma
cases has been rising steadily, increasing 60 percent in the past
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 14 million people in the United States now live with
asthma; about 5,000 per year die from it.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, more than 84,000 people, including
30,000 children, have asthma, the American Lung Association of
Western Missouri estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is the leading cause of hospitalization of children. And
among chronic diseases, it's the leading cause of school
absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, the national American Lung
Association has made asthma research a priority, said Susan
Glassman, executive director of the American Lung Association of
Eastern Missouri in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Collaborating with the American Thoracic Society, a professional
organization of lung specialists, the lung association created
National Asthma Research Centers at the University of Utah,
University of New Mexico and the National Jewish Medical and
Research Center in Denver, to conduct basic research into the
causes of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   The American Lung Association then began to seek medical centers
to conduct studies on large numbers of patients. The initial goal
was to have five such regional centers, Glassman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was so much excitement about this that we ended up
with 19,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Kansas City, regional asthma research centers
have been established in New York, Philadelphia, Atlanta and other
sites along the East Coast. In the Midwest, centers are in place in
Columbus, Ohio; Chicago; Minneapolis; Denver; and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore will
collect and analyze data from the centers and maintain a computer
link among the centers.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, all 19 centers will participate in every study. Each
center will typically recruit several hundred patients per study,
creating a pool of thousands of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, patients will be recruited from Truman
Medical Center and Children's Mercy Hospital and from physicians in
the community.
</P>
<P>
   The large numbers of patients in these studies will allow
researchers to draw strong conclusions from their results, and also
allow the studies to be completed in a year or two, rather than the
five to 10 years some previous asthma studies have taken, Salzman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest multicenter asthma research program ever
attempted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman said there is a possibility that later on, some studies
will be done by smaller groups.
</P>
<P>
   A steering committee with members from each center will meet
every month or two to plan the studies they will undertake. The
committee will probably announce its first study in May or June; it
is scheduled to begin in October.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is considering studies of the roles played by
genetics and environment in asthma, ways to prevent children from
developing asthma, and the effectiveness of different medications.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one study under consideration would look at whether
flu vaccines can help prevent asthma attacks, said Dennis
Pyszczynski, one of the asthma center researchers and president of
the board of directors of the American Lung Association of Western
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Viral infections, such as the flu, can worsen airway function,
Pyszczynski said. ``Even just getting the vaccine may help (prevent
attacks),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Salzman and Pyszczynski, the Kansas City asthma
center researchers include Sandra Willsie, Michael McCubbin, Jay
Portnoy and Paul Dowling.
</P>
<P>
   While the asthma research centers will rely at first on money
from American Lung Association chapters, they also will seek
government grants and financing from drug companies, Salzman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a potential for growth and self-sufficiency,'' he
said. ``I think the American Lung Association would like to see
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The association is committed to getting the findings of the
research to doctors as fast as possible, Glassman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this will have enormous benefits to the public,'' she
said. ``We plan to very quickly make this knowledge part of
standard practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
