<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-INSURANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT TARGETS STATE HEALTH CARE INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ Despite an economic era of unparalleled growth
and prosperity, the number of Californians lacking health insurance
now stands at more than 7.3 million, according to a report to be
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report titled ``The Importance of Healthcare in
California,'' also focused on the impact the health care industry
has on the state's economy and as a component in all of industry's
need to have a healthy work force.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the health care industry is a $63 billion business
with more than 920,000 employees, according to the report compiled
by the Office of the State Controller and the Healthcare
Collaborative at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Our health care system, however, is in a state of crisis as the
uninsured ranks rise, the quality of health care falls and the baby
boom generation grays, state controller Kathleen Connell said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe California cannot expect to continue its
current economic expansion without adequate and comprehensive
health care coverage for its residents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She gets no argument from some in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't agree more,'' said David Olson, a spokesman for
Woodland Hills-based Foundation Health Systems Inc. ``Many of the
uninsured in California do get the care they need; unfortunately
they get very expensive care in an emergency room.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 48 percent of California firms offer their employees health
insurance, compared with 61 percent nationally, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of several responses to the continuing problem
of the uninsured. Two new bills now being considered by the state
Legislature would help provide funding for the uninsured and
increase accessibility to the state's Healthy Families program.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller-employer tax credits bill (AB 1734) would provide a
$65 per employee per month tax credit to firms with 25 or fewer
full-time employees, provided the employees earn less than $34,700
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assembly Bill 1734 offers a way for government to partner with
the private sector to extend health insurance to the working
uninsured in California,'' said Assemblyman Bill Campbell,
R-Orange, who co-authored the bill with Assemblywoman Helen
Thomson, D-Vacaville.
</P>
<P>
   The W-4 form check-offs for Healthy Families Program enrollment
bill, (AB 1974) authored by Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San
Francisco, would allow employees to indicate their interest in
Healthy Families enrollment on their state tax form.
</P>
<P>
   The check-off would indicate interest in the program, and would
authorize payroll deductions to cover premiums. With this form
being completed by every employee statewide it would help to
increase awareness and accessibility of enrolling in the Healthy
Families program.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in 1998, the program is low-cost insurance that
provides health, dental and vision coverage to nearly 240,000
children who are uninsured and don't qualify for noncost Medi-Cal.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
