<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2819 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FLA-CLINTON-VISIT01-C     03-01 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CLINTON-VISIT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton stops motorcade twice to shake hands
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANALAPAN, Fla. _ Maureen Vinyard could hardly believe it. Just
a few feet away President Clinton was still shaking hands. She was
shaking her head in disbelief. So was the White House staff and the
Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was in a Leap Day mood Tuesday, bounding all over the
county and twice leaping out of his car to shake hands with
startled onlookers. It was a chaotic five hours with Clinton
snarling traffic as he traveled from West Palm Beach to Manalapan
back to West Palm Beach then to Palm Beach Gardens before finally
returning to West Palm Beach to board Air Force One for a quick
trip to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is highly unusual,'' said a White House aide as Clinton
waded into a crowd near where the president had just made his last
stop of the day. ``Getting out of the motorcade once is unusual
enough, but twice?'' said the bemused aide.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton stopped the 23-car motorcade on Lantana Road,
Vinyard was standing outside her office at the Department of Motor
Vehicles hoping to catch a glimpse of Clinton as he sped by. ``I'm
speechless,'' she said after Clinton said ``hello'' and shook her
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Torres and her friend Bethany Rocha had business at the DMV
office when employees said they were closing to see the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we decided to hang out and meet the president,'' Torres
said.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service cordoned off an area with yellow tape near the
road. Then they patted down and waved a metal detecting wand over
those who wanted to get close to the motorcade. ``We had to keep
our hands in front of us,'' Torres said. And they made her put away
her car keys because an ornament on her key ring had a sharp edge.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was in a playful mood. He came to Florida to raise money
for the Democratic National Committee with a lunch at the Manalapan
estate of Mel and Bren Simon and with cocktail parties and dinners
in Miami. He also attended a money-raising event for the
congressional campaign of state Rep. Elaine Bloom (D-Miami Beach).
</P>
<P>
   Crowds stood on corners as he motored around the county. One
woman was so enthused she rushed out of a beauty parlor on Lantana
Road clad in a smock and wearing tin foil in her hair to catch a
glimpse of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton turned somber, however, when he talked about Tuesday's
tragic child shooting in Michigan. He called for tougher gun laws
and said he felt ``very sorry'' for the family of the 6-year-old
girl who was shot by a 6-year-old boy in their first-grade
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   RACK OF LAMB FOR LUNCH
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One touched down at 12:25 p.m. at Palm Beach
International Airport. Clinton stepped from the 747 about 10
minutes later accompanied by U.S. Rep. Peter Deutsch (D-Fort
Lauderdale) and his wife, Lori. Among the local dignitaries waiting
for Clinton were state Rep. Lois Frankel, D-West Palm Beach, state
Sen. Tom Rossin, D-West Palm Beach and Palm Beach County Democratic
Party Chairman Monte Friedkin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's motorcade departed at about 12:49 p.m. for the
20-minute trip to Manalapan. About 45 people attended the $10,000
per person lunch under a white tent behind the oceanfront mansion.
For lunch they dined on rack of lamb with cherry sauce, Florida
stone crab salad, golden potatoes, asparagus spears and a desert of
caramelized bananas and mixed berries.
</P>
<P>
   It was catered by tuxedo and white-gloved waiters from the
nearby Ritz-Carlton, which is owned by Mel Simon, who also owns the
Palm Beach and Boynton Beach malls and Boca Raton's Town Centre.
</P>
<P>
   TAKES CREDIT FOR ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, Clinton spoke for about 25 minutes, offering his
belief that the four presidential candidates have all convinced
voters that they are capable of being president and the winner will
be the one who shows the best vision for the future. Clinton also
rattled off a host of his administration's accomplishments,
including taking much of the credit for the strong economy. He also
chastised Congress for not fixing the problems with Social Security
and Medicare and predicted that some progress would be made this
year because of the election.
</P>
<P>
   When he left Manalapan to go to the Sheraton in West Palm Beach
for a private meeting with supporters of his proposed presidential
library in Little Rock, Ark., Clinton's motorcade was noticeably
missing something. There are always two, nearly identical
presidential limos. One broke down.
</P>
<P>
   After dropping Clinton off, the limousine was driven to the fire
bay at the South Palm Beach Town Hall. Apparently, something was
wrong with the water pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all went into the garage to see it,'' said Mayor Margot
Roberts. ``I asked if I could put my card on the steering wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Town officials offered to help or to call a mechanic. ``The
Secret Service wouldn't let anyone else touch the car,'' she said.
``They rolled up their sleeves and worked on it. We told them if
they don't get it fixed, the president could sleep in the barracks
upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the senior center, Laverne Leonard, a bus driver for the
center, had a lot of questions for Clinton about saving Social
Security and Medicare. Clinton promised to keep working on it.
</P>
<P>
   The President also watched seniors working on computers in the
center's library and called the moving screen savers ``amazing.''
Clinton admitted he still doesn't use e-mail in the office.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the airport, Clinton strolled over toward a
5-year old Sandpiper Shores Elementary student wearing a dark-olive
skirt and a hand-colored badge: VICTORIA is a kindergarten writing
whiz kid.'' ``You're a kindergarten whiz kid? ... Good for you,''
Clinton said before posing for a picture with her. ``You're a
beautiful child.'' Victoria could only smile, nod her head and
twist her shoulder length hair.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Clinton boarded Air Force One and at about 5:45
p.m. he flew over the thousands of cars stuck in the traffic jams
presidential visits always cause. Clinton arrived back in
Washington well after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff writers Tim O'Meilia and Bob King
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
