<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-JEBBUSH-BOBJONES01-CO     03-01 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEBBUSH-BOBJONES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeb Bush defends G.W.'s visit to Bob Jones U.
 &HT;    By S.V. Date
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida's Catholic, interracially married
governor went on national television Wednesday to defend brother
George W. Bush's visit last month to a South Carolina college that
frowns on both Catholicism and interracial marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush said he himself would speak at Bob Jones University,
even though its published rules would mean he and Mexican-born
wife, Columba, would have been expelled for dating had they met
there as students.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it was incumbent on political candidates to spread
their message to groups they might not agree with, and accused GOP
presidential rival Sen. John McCain of stooping to a divisive
``wedge issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To even have a conversation about this in a political campaign
shows how far we've fallen,'' Jeb Bush said in a taped interview
broadcast on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``Shame on Senator McCain. Shame
on him for doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones University, founded by the stridently anti-Catholic
fundamentalist preacher of the same name, did not admit black
students until the IRS took away the school's tax-exempt status in
the 1970s. It continues to ban interracial dating and marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The school nonetheless has been a stop for Republican candidates
for president over the past several campaigns. But this campaign,
McCain used George W. Bush's Feb. 2 visit there to criticize the
Texas governor for failing to condemn the university.
</P>
<P>
   Bush for weeks defended his visit, even though current President
Bob Jones III called the pope ``the anti-Christ'' and Bush's own
father, former President George Bush, ``a devil.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush issued an apology to New York Cardinal John
O'Connor this weekend, after exit polls in the Michigan primary
election last week showed that many Catholic voters had indeed
punished Bush after receiving phone calls from the McCain camp
describing the school and its views.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Democratic Party spokesman Tony Welch, who is black,
called Jeb Bush's defense of his brother reprehensible. ``He's
apparently appointed a new ambassador for Bob Jones University, and
it's Jeb Bush,'' Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   Welch wondered whether Jeb Bush's willingness to talk to groups
he disagrees with would extend to hate groups. ``I would assume
that means a Klan rally?'' Welch said. ``Where do you draw the
line?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in an e-mail, told The Palm Beach Post, ``I would not
speak to the KKK,'' but did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCarron, director of the Florida Catholic Conference, said
he thinks the Bob Jones controversy has gone too far, although he
was gratified by candidate Bush's apology for not speaking out more
forcefully against the school's ``offensive'' views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been blown out of proportion. And I think that
it's highly political,'' McCarron said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
