<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONEOK01-CJENKINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONEOK INC. SUES STATE OVER MERGER FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MAX JARMAN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Oneok Inc. is seeking to recover $85 million from the state in the
wake of its collapsed bid to acquire Southwest Gas Corp.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest litigious volley in a snowstorm of lawsuits
swirling around the failed deal.
</P>
<P>
   In a notice of claims, filed Monday, Oneok alleges Arizona
Corporation Chairman Carl Kunasek and aide Jerry Porter improperly
worked to scuttle the deal to exact political revenge on
Commissioner Jim Irvin and ex-Corporation Commission executive
secretary Jack Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Kunasek would not comment on the Oneok action; Porter said the
allegations are baseless.
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa-based Oneok alleges Kunasek and Porter funneled misleading
information to jilted Southwest bidder Southern Union in an effort
to embarrass Irvin and Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The information led to criminal investigation of the pair's
alleged activities and to Southern Union filing a $750 million
lawsuit against Irvin and Rose as well as officers of Oneok and
Southwest Gas. Both the investigations and lawsuit are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest move, Oneok also alleges that Kunasek established
a procedure of posing accusatory questions to Oneok that
contributed to a Jan. 4 corporation commission staff recommendation
that the merger be tabled or denied.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 21, Oneok formally withdrew its $912 million offer for
Southwest, the state's largest natural gas utility, citing concerns
over stockholder liability.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal led Southwest to sue Oneok, alleging it
fraudulently used Irvin and Rose to induced Southwest to accept its
bid over a higher offer by Southern Union.
</P>
<P>
   In its notice of claim, Oneok alleges the company has been
defamed by Kunasek and Porter and as a result of having to defend
claims that lack legal merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their collaboration with Southern Union makes them, the state
and the ACC liable for the loss of benefits as a result of the
failed deal,'' Oneok asserted, saying it will settle for $85
million, although actual damages may greatly exceed that sum. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Max.Jarman(at)Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-7351. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 0029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
