r a BC-PM10-AZR &LR;      03-01 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PM10-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARICOPA COUNTY TO CITE DUST VIOLATORS ON THE SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY MARY JO PITZL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Maricopa County inspectors issued six citations for
construction-related dust pollution this year, equal the number
issued in all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And more are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The county announced Tuesday that it will start issuing
on-the-spot citations for 14 types of dust violation. Previously,
only two infractions had been deemed worthy of an immediate $2,500
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be clear to our citizens and the public that we are
serious about dust control,'' said Andy Kunasek, chairman of the
Maricopa County Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   The stepped-up enforcement comes as the Valley is about to enter
a penalty phase for failing to meet federal clean-air standards for
particulate pollution.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Environmental Protection Agency sanctions kick in Thursday
because the Valley failed last year to produce an acceptable
dust-control plan.
</P>
<P>
   A new plan is expected to win EPA approval next month. But if it
also fails, Arizona could lose federal highway dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Particulate pollution that is 10 microns or less in size, or
PM10, about one-seventieth the width of a human hair, is a nagging
health problem in the Valley. Tiny bits of soot and grime can lodge
deep in the lungs, creating major respiratory problems. The main
sources of PM10 are construction, agriculture and dust dragged up
by vehicle travel on both paved and unpaved roads.
</P>
<P>
   The county's new policies target construction activity.
Previously, inspectors could issue immediate citations to companies
or individuals who were working without a dust-control permit and
to anyone who was hauling a load of dirt and debris without
covering it.
</P>
<P>
   That list of infractions has mushroomed from two to 14,
including such actions as not using a water truck on a construction
site, not controlling dust from being tracked out of a site, and
operating an unpaved parking lot if it holds 100 or more vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the immediate citations, the county later this
month will get a full-time prosecutor to handle dust violations.
</P>
<P>
   The get-tough action was welcomed by the trade group that
represents builders.
</P>
<P>
   ``No fine can be as great as the loss of the highway revenues,''
said David Martin, executive director of the Associated General
Contractors. ``We want to get to compliance just as much as
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaching federal clean-air standards may be difficult. Since
January, there have been four cases when particulate levels
exceeded federal health standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're off to a bad start for calendar year 2000,'' said Al
Brown, director of the county's Environmental Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Brown's office received 1,690 complaints about dust
stirred up by earthmoving equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with eight people in the field, we're overwhelmed,''
Brown said of his inspection staff. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at MaryJo.Pitzl(at)Arizona Republic.com or (602)
444-8963. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 0031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLA     03-01 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSING HELPS LAKERS MAKE GRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ If the Lakers were to peg their recent winning
ways to one weapon, it might be the pass.
</P>
<P>
   During the 11-game winning streak they carried into Tuesday
night, the Lakers' assist totals jumped dramatically, from a season
average of 22.9 per game to 27.2.
</P>
<P>
   They registered new team highs in consecutive games, getting 34
at Cleveland last Wednesday, then topping it with 35 against Boston
two nights later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've just kind of gotten back to the basics,'' said
Derek Fisher. ``Things are coming out of the flow of what we're
trying to do, instead of guys creating situations. I think the
problem that we ran into is after we started to get comfortable
with our offense earlier in the year, sometimes when you get
comfortable with things you start to (improvise). . . . I think the
offense is one where you just have to stick with it and things will
come out of that, instead of going outside of the offense to come
up with things.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest improviser on the roster has also been the Lakers'
best assist man. Kobe Bryant, leading the team with 4.5 per game,
averaged 5.8 during the 11-game stretch. Shaquille O'Neal was next,
with 5.3 per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just getting better at reading defenses,'' Bryant said.
``Shaq's doing an excellent job, as well, reading how teams are
playing. With the triangle offense, what it does is you know where
your guys are at all times. You know how teams are coming. On any
given night, you can almost throw a pass without even looking
because players are supposed to be in certain spots.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendency to make the extra pass has spread throughout the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very contagious,'' Bryant said. ``That's been one of our
strengths . . . is our selflessness, everybody getting everybody
involved, making the extra pass.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Shaw rising: Coach Phil Jackson has made few changes to the
rotation over the first two-thirds of the season, but he made a
change Sunday and it could be permanent. Brian Shaw was the first
guard off the bench against Houston and he got the first call
Tuesday night as well. Fisher had been the third guard for most of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw also has been gaining minutes for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just play well with him on the court,'' Jackson said.
``There was a time when I felt like he might have been a little too
opportunistic with the ball, trying maybe too many opportunities to
create shots for Shaq and moving the offense at a faster speed than
I want it to operate at.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shaw's play of late has been steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing more in the fourth quarter, just try to play
solid, not make any spectacular plays, but just take whatever the
defense gives you,'' Shaw said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
