<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-DEMOCRATS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE EASILY WINS WASHINGTON PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore won the Washington primary
Tuesday night and was poised to deal a serious _ if not fatal _
blow to the presidential hopes of former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore easily out-distanced his only rival for the Democratic
nomination but the Bradley campaign, braced for defeat, downplaying
the significance of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley vowed to carry on through next week's Super
Tuesday primaries, some of his aides were reportedly urging him to
quit the race, and avoid embarassing defeats next week. He has yet
to win a primary or caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Gov. Gary Locke, one Gore's leading supporters, said
Bradley should think about leaving the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to be a decisive margin, especially after Senator
Bradley spent almost six days in the state,'' Locke said. ``I think
he's going to have to reconsider his staying in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington might well prove to be the contest that cinches the
nomination for Gore. The state, with an open primary, a large pool
of independent voters, and a tradition of supporting mavericks,
seemed tailor-made for Bradley's insurgent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He gambled heavily that the state would give him a victory and
the bounce he needed to carry on the fight to delegate-rich primary
states like California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the gamble appears to have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't do well in this type of situation, you're not
going to do well in any other state,'' Carolyn Long, a political
science professor at Washington State University, said of Bradley's
showing here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're making a push, and not getting anywhere, then you're
sunk,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Bradley campaign officials began lowering
expectations over the weekend. Tuesday night, they tried to
downplay the significance of the Washington vote, which was a
``beauty contest.'' Democrats will select delegates to the party's
nominating conventions in caucuses next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never said that this was a must-win,'' said Mo Elleithee, a
Bradley spokesman. ``We've always said March 7 was when this
campaign has to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore supporters said the vice president appears all but
certain to capture the party nomination. The next round of
contests, closed to all but Democrats, heavily favor Gore because
he has the backing of most of the party establishment and its core
constituances, such as organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Gore had the support of Locke, Sen. Patty Murray
and state party Chairman Paul Berendt, as well as major labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty Bradley has had in this state is he just wasn't
able to convince many people that he was better than Gore,''
Berendt said. ``There was only room for one insurgent, and it
turned out to be (GOP presidential hopeful John) McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Berendt said, voters were sticking with Gore because
of the unprecedented prosperity overseen by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Enoch McNary, a 55 year-old Seattle pre-school teacher, was one
of those voters. She said she stuck with the administration she
likes when she cast her vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel Gore has more experience,'' McNary said. ``As far as
running the country, I like what Clinton has done and I think Gore
will have picked that up.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's white-hot candidacy almost certainly hurt Bradley,
poltical observers said. Since New Hampshire, when McCain won a
stunning upset of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, McCain has been
siphoning away the independents that Bradley needed to overcome
Gore's institutional advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Jones, director of the Center for American Politics and
Public Policy at the University of Washington, said Bradley was
unable to bring new voters into the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   By running left _ he positioned himself as a proud liberal _
Bradley ended up fighting for the traditional Democratic
constituency that had largely pledged itself to Gore, Jones said.
With voters seeing little difference between the two candidates,
they went for the favorite, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was reaching back to the most liberal Democratic
constituencies, and trying to energize them, and it didn't work,''
Jones said. ``If you want to appeal to independents, you have to
move to the Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley targeted Washington early, making forays into the state
in 1998. He was able to attract many prominent supporters, and had
great success raising money here.
</P>
<P>
   He raised significantly more money than Gore in Washington
state, and made at least five visits to the state. In the week
leading up to the primary, he devoted six precious days to the
state, forsaking the bigger Super Tuesday prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign here called about 50,000 voters and passed
out about 100,000 flyers, said his spokesman, Elleithee. Bradley
did 70 interviews with local reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did everything,'' Elleithee siad. ``We brought in more
staff. We did a tremendous amount of grass-roots campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Bradley couldn't overcome Gore's advantages in
organization, fund-raising and party support.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Mayor Paul Schell, one of the first elected officials to
endorse Bradley, said the senator had little choice but to gamble
on Washington, and try to step out from McCain's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably his only choice to get the national media's
attention,'' he said. ``He was starting from a long way back, it
was an uphill battle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
