<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S TURN PROFIT, BUT PUBLIC GETS SHORTCHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Since the civic parade has been slow to assemble, let
me be the first to line up, with my piece of confetti, to celebrate
the Mariners owners' announcement that they made a profit last
year.
</P>
<P>
   (begin agate) Hurrah. (end agate)
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, they turned $372 million of the public's money
into $2.5 million profit for 1999, according to their annual
release about financial operations. With that kind of acumen, it's
a wonder these guys don't get out of the baseball dodge and go into
investment counseling. They could help end this robust economy and
bring it to a cold, dead stop.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're unfamiliar with the number, the $372 million
represents the public investment in the new park.
</P>
<P>
   The number is relevant, because it appears nowhere in the
Mariners' snapshot statement.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it is hard to fathom how the most sizable public
contribution in U.S. history to a modern ballpark's construction
could be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only because those observers don't understand that
the owners, whether the current group or its predecessors, have
always argued it is about them and the cash they've spent, never
about baseball and the asset they've created.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner president Chuck Armstrong was at it again this week,
eagerly pointing out that this ownership in its seven years has
made an investment of about $337 million, which includes the
disputed cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Deducting the $45 million for naming rights that doesn't come
from ownership, that leaves the owners' claimed investment at
roughly $290 million ($100 million purchase price, $75 million in
annual operating losses and around $105 million in stadium cost
overruns).
</P>
<P>
   A handsome chunk of cash. But it's not as if it were thrown out
the window.
</P>
<P>
   They have ownership of a valuable _ and now profitable _
franchise housed in a magnificent theater with an enormous fan base
in a booming market in a monopoly industry that is weathering the
darkest economic period in its history _ the backlash from the 1994
work stoppage, from which national revenues have yet to recover.
</P>
<P>
   What is this asset worth? Hard to say exactly, but it's always
useful to find, as they say in real estate, a comparable.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians last month were sold for $323 million.
</P>
<P>
   As with any comparison, there's always an apples-and-oranges
problem. But consider that the seller, Richard Jacobs, bought the
club in 1986 for $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians then were much like the M's in '92 _ moribund, a
hapless franchise housed in an inadequate stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But after a similar public investment in a new Cleveland
stadium, the Indians built a team that has won five consecutive
division titles and made World Series appearances in 1995 and 1997.
They have sold out 373 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was that Jacobs' investment over 13 years produced a
seven-fold increase in asset value. Not a bad return for a sport
whose leaders continue to harp on the bogus premise that player
salaries alone are imperiling the empire.
</P>
<P>
   In coming off two consecutive losing seasons, the Mariners are
not among the baseball elites as are the Indians, and would not
generate the same sale price on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little reason to think that the Mariners are not on
a similar arc.
</P>
<P>
   Already profitable in just a half season in the new yard, the
Mariners' only real impediment to success is mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of new GM Pat Gillick has resolved some of that.
Bumping up the payroll to nearly $70 million is another positive
sign.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing the Mariners are doing that the Indians never did
is contemplate suing the public that paid for and built their
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know what the impact of an ugly, bitter trial will
be on the ticket-buying public. It is interesting to note that in
the seven months since the yard opened, ownership hasn't yet
summoned the guts to file suit.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't stupid. Stubborn, megalomaniacal and occasionally
oblivious, maybe, but not stupid. They know the risk is high of
souring the fan relationship that is fundamental to success.
</P>
<P>
   Before the situation gets any uglier, the Mariners would do well
to show some true wisdom in the battle against the Public
Facilities District and recognize their cause is doomed to be more
costly than the overruns.
</P>
<P>
   However valid are any Mariners claims, the stadium package was
sold in the Legislature in 1995 on the premise that public
contribution would be capped. Period. It simply doesn't matter what
happened in the mud on Occidental.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 profitability confirms what many have known _ in a
short time, owners will have their net investment covered by
franchise appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   When they sell, they will come out ahead, as has every baseball
ownership in the game's history.
</P>
<P>
   The only real threat to being made whole is their own lack of
vision and stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
