<SLUG> BC-IMAC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING IMAC TO GIRL TOUGH ON RESERVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BETTY REID  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
In the Web world, news, graphics and e-mail move at the click of a
finger. On the Navajo Reservation, news still travels at the pace
of a pickup truck or a broadcast on the tribe's KTNN radio station.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the two worlds intersect, even the fastest drivers on
the superhighway can be baffled, as Web boss John Raess found out
while trying to unite a 13-year-old computer winner with her prize.
</P>
<P>
   The managing editor at AWZ.Com, a San Jose-based Web site for
teens, allowed a computer to randomly select a teenager nationwide
to win a fancy-schmantzy iMac. Out of 25,000 youngsters, it nailed
13-year-old Navajo Myra Jodie.
</P>
<P>
   Myra, however, lacked a home telephone. So Raess e-mailed Myra
in early February with the happy news.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, no response.
</P>
<P>
   The editor started a paper-trail investigation on Myra's
whereabouts, crisscrossing the remote, 16,000-square-mile
reservation. He had an e-mail address, a ZIP code, a date of birth,
and a state.
</P>
<P>
   He located Myra at Ganado Middle School through the ZIP code she
gave, which belongs to the historic Hubbell's Trading Post. Raess
left a message at the school urging Myra to check her e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   A week sailed by and still no return e-mail. Raess became more
persistent, asking that Myra be pulled out of class.
</P>
<P>
   What Raess didn't know was he had tapped into a remote Navajo
community where students are usually shy and reserved. Many travel
70 miles round-trip daily to attend Ganado Middle School in
northeastern Arizona. And for many families, paying a utility bill
or having enough money for groceries is more important than having
a phone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, the two made contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Hi, Myra, this is John Raess with AWZ.Com. You won an
an iMac.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He expected the Navajo child to squeal with delight. There was
dead silence on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's an iMac?'' Myra asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know an Apple?'' Raess asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Myra said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `Computer' and she got that,'' Raess said.
</P>
<P>
   I &QC;  &UR; o`3ho lives with her two older siblings and her mother in a
house near a thicket of
juniper trees north of Steamboat Chapter, said she didn't take
Raess' call seriously because she couldn't remember entering a
contest.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Myra, an eighth-grader, had plugged into her
teacher's desktop. Her teacher, Ella Earl, uses the computer for
her lesson plans and allows the children to use it once they
complete their social studies work. So, Myra wasn't on the computer
daily. She remembers entering the contest, but says she was
admiring a pearl necklace, not a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Myra's world couldn't be more different from that of the execs
trying to track her down. She lives in Bal Kai, a mesa with
slightly more than 1,000 residents where the average family income
is about $12,000 a year; the average income for a family in San
Jose is several times that. There, shopping is taken for granted;
in the Steamboat community, a trip to the Rio West Mall or the swap
meet in Gallup, N.M., is a big event. And while youngsters in San
Jose might come home and watch television, play Nintendo or call
their friends, youngsters on the reservation most likely are
helping relatives with livestock and chores at home after school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just fried,'' Raess said, given that President Clinton
talks about connecting each classroom in America to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Raess' boss, Tapan Joshi, president of AWZ.Com, plans to travel
to Ganado on Friday and personally deliver a turquoise-colored iMac
to Myra. Joshi also is incredulous about Myra's lack of a telephone
line. He is from India, where a city could be built of wealth or a
village can exist without water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (Myra's story) took me back 10 years,'' he said,
remembering his homeland. ``If Myra were in India, she would not be
in school. She would be hauling heavy things.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is America, where the economy is strong and many
school districts brag about a 95 percent connection to the
Internet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That came as a real shock to me,'' Joshi said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Citizens Communication, which serves Navajoland,
said it provides a majority of residents with phones. In situations
such as that of Myra's family, which lives 10 miles from the
nearest pay phone at Steamboat Thriftway Store, major construction
of a telephone line is needed before a house is wired.
</P>
<P>
   The more relevant question then becomes, can Myra's family
afford a telephone?
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Myra said her mother might request a telephone line
given that Myra will get a new computer. Then again, Myra said she
doesn't have to have the Internet _ she'll be just as happy working
with CD-ROMs or software, because the family does have electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all making a big deal out of it,'' Myra said. ``I just
want a computer.'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Betty.Reid(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-7954. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
