<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN GASOLINE PRICE BEARS BIG TAX LOAD  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The recent history of gasoline prices is a
story of declining oil costs offset significantly by government
profiteering.
</P>
<P>
   Government, particularly Uncle Sam, took advantage of falling
fuel prices as an opportunity to raise taxes when low-cost gas made
consumers more willing to go along with gas tax hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists upset about surging pump prices need reminding that
the average inflation-adjusted retail price of gasoline was at a
record low only a little more than a year ago, according to the
American Petroleum Institute. Except for the 1973-81 period of
mounting U.S. inflation exacerbated by OPEC embargoes and
government regulations, gas prices have been on a steady decline
for more than 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   There are occasional price spikes, of course, but this is the
way markets work. The psychological problem for consumers is how
they tend to remember painful bouts of rising prices but forget the
happier times of falling prices. As for prices since 1981, when
they began declining from a dramatic spike, the biggest problem for
consumers has been the government's mounting take.
</P>
<P>
   Total average gasoline taxes last year amounted to 43.5 cents,
according to the institute. This included 18.4 cents in federal
taxes and 23.1 cents in weighted average state taxes. The remaining
2 cents is estimated local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1980, the year before gas prices peaked, federal
and state gas taxes amounted to only 13.8 cents. To put what has
happened in perspective, the gas tax load increased more than 200
percent even as pump prices were declining by more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tax hikes could be defended if the money were used entirely to
maintain roads, but Uncle Sam apparently has been putting much of
the federal share to other uses. Moreover, gas taxes also have been
levied for purposes other than keeping roads and bridges in good
repair.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the '90s, for instance, gas prices were increased to
help defray record federal budget deficits. Subsequently, as the
budget was moving from deficit into surplus, those levies were
rededicated to the Highway Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   That, of itself, was objectionable. As a deficit reduction tax,
it should have been repealed instead of rededicated to a purpose
for which it wasn't originally intended. The levy should have been
relegislated.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of argument, however, let's say it was acceptable
because Uncle Sam planned to put the extra money to good use
improving highways. Unfortunately, a lot of the money seems to have
been short-stopped along the way. Since the mid-1990s the Highway
Trust Fund's balance has swelled more than 150 percent. That may
sound good, but the increase represents revenue collected but not
used for highways. The trust fund contains Treasury securities,
which are IOUs to be cashed in whenever Congress appropriates the
money to redeem them for road work. The tax money collected at the
pump but still unused, meantime, has gone to finance other budget
outlays.
</P>
<P>
   This raises a question: If Washington is unable, or unwilling,
to use more gas tax money as intended, why not cut gas taxes?
America's motorists need the money at least as badly as the federal
government, which is rolling in extra dough these days. Or so it
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
