<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANNY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANNY MARCHES ON CAPTIOL HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; WASHINGTON _ You go, Granny!
</P>
<P>
   Promoting campaign finance reform, Doris ``Granny D'' Haddock
completed her 425-day, 3,200-mile trek and joined with more than
1,000 supporters on the steps of the U.S. Capitol. She called for
Congress to end ``soft money'' political contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like 'Alice in Wonderland.' I can't believe we're all
here,'' said Haddock, a 90-year-old grandmother from New Hampshire
who launched her cross-country walk at the tail end of the
Tournament of Roses parade in Pasadena on Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Her fellow walkers along the last leg on Capitol Hill on Tuesday
included Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer and Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., support efforts to
ban unlimited soft money contributions to political parties from
business, labor and other special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   While praising House members for passing a soft money ban in
1999, Haddock chided senators for failing to approve a similar
measure authored by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russ Feingold,
D-Wis. The Senate's soft money ban died in 1999 amid a
Republican-led filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come, senators, for reform or new senators,'' she
said. ``Tell us which it will be, and then we will go vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock plans to begin lobbying the Senate Wednesday with a
weapon she has utilized since her days as an anti-nuclear activist
in the early 1960s: a nice, hot cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's rally, Haddock and her supporters headed for all
100 Senate offices, delivering engraved, personalized invitations
to a tea party that will get under way at 11 a.m. in a park next to
the Capitol. Haddock will do the pouring and will ask senators to
sign a pledge to vote for a soft money ban.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock's triumphant march through Washington, D.C., which
included a loop around the White House and past offices housing
some of the capital's most powerful lobbyists, was a far cry from
her early days on the road. She took the byways, including a lonely
stretch of Mojave Desert highway between Twentynine Palms, Calif.,
and Parker, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, she preached campaign finance reform to groups
ranging from civic clubs to biker gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last hurrah,'' Haddock said before setting out on
the final leg of her odyssey. ``This isn't about me; it's about the
message. I don't care one whit if anyone remembers Granny D. What's
important is campaign reform and giving our government back to the
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe one person can make a difference,'' she added. ``And
if I'm the one who can make that difference, why not try?''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock's loved ones had serious doubts when she announced plans
for her grueling journey back in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to talk her out of it,'' recalled her daughter, Betty
Lawrenz. ``My husband is a doctor, and he told her there was no way
she could make it. But she proved us wrong. I believe she dropped
20 years on the road. She's never been healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   Walking 10 miles a day, six days a week, Haddock set a brisk
pace. Except for a short hospital stint for pneumonia, contracted
in a Mojave dust storm, she stayed healthy the entire trek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any doubt that she'd make it,'' said Ken Hechler,
West Virginia's secretary of state and, along with the reform group
Common Cause, one of Haddock's most steadfast backers. ``This is a
woman with confidence, determination and optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   Hechler, 85, joined Haddock on the first 500 miles of her trek.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock said she gained self confidence on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always been shy and reticent to approach strangers,''
she said. ``But once I found how kind and good people are in this
country, I just came out of my shell.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock's official Capitol welcoming committee included Reps.
Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Marty Meehan, D-Mass., co-authors
of last year's House bill banning soft money. ``You walked to save
our Republic,'' Shays told Granny D.
</P>
<P>
   Other official greeters included Feingold, who conveyed
greetings from McCain, a candidate for the Republican presidential
nomination, and veteran rock musician David Crosby of Crosby,
Stills, Nash &AMP; Young, whose Back Porch Foundation supported
Haddock's effort.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money - the object of Haddock's wrath - is a loophole in
the federal law that limits individual donations to candidates to
$1,000 per election. There is no limit on soft money, funneled by
corporations, labor unions and nonprofit special interest groups to
political parties for party-building activities.
</P>
<P>
   The parties actually use much of the money to advertise their
stands on issues. Labor unions and special interest groups can use
their own soft money on advertising for the candidates they have
endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission recently reported that, as of
Feb. 1, soft money donations to the Democratic and Republican
parties had topped $200 million for this year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   After her tea party, Haddock hopes to campaign against incumbent
senators opposed to campaign finance reform. The widowed activist,
who lives on Social Security and a small pension, will also be
looking for some hard money to cover more than $7,000 in debts she
incurred on the road.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
