<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-PARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CHIEF SAYS PROBLEMS STARTED YEARS AGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
and GREG GITTRICH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ Arguing that problems with the Los Angeles
Police Department go back at least two decades, Chief Bernard C.
Parks said Tuesday that the department's failings and culture of
mediocrity were heightened by budget cuts that replaced supervisors
with civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fewer supervisors now than we did at our lowest
point,'' Parks said in an interview with the Los Angeles Daily
News. ``There was this push to hire civilians to get more people
out of administrative jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they might be able to write letters just as well, but
there is more to that in policing.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks acknowledged that many LAPD critics will be disappointed
with the Board of Inquiry report because it deals largely with
systemic issues and does not reveal whether other divisions have
the same problems as the now infamous Rampart Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the criminal investigation will deal with,'' Parks
said. ``What I hope gets through is that this department was able
to take a critical look at itself, identify problems and begin to
make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   To deter misconduct, Parks said he has authorized the use of
surprise inspections modeled after the U.S. military. The first
such inspection was conducted Tuesday at the Hollywood Division,
where teams of supervisors were sent in to review everything being
done at the station.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he didn't look at the Board of Inquiry report and its
108 recommendations as being an extension of the landmark
Christopher Commission report that came after the 1991 Rodney King
beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget that report is almost 10 years old now,'' Parks
said. ``To a certain extent, we have to get beyond that and begin
dealing with the problems of today and tomorrow and what the
department will look like in 2001 and 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Christopher Commission report did do, however, was
create a system of individual officer accountability within the
LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Inquiry has recommendations that go well beyond
that, including case audits, polygraph tests for officers and
allowing the department to check into officers' financial records.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he hopes the release of the report will help begin to
restore some public confidence in the agency and its ability to
correct its own problems as well as public attitude toward
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's tough out there for our officers,'' Parks said.
``They go into court and are asked if they're honest. They're the
butt of cartoons and jokes. It's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
