<SLUG> BC-ELN-RDP-ART-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WINS IN VIRGINIA AND NORTH DAKOTA; TAKES LEAD IN WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs for new 2nd and 12th grafs with results of Republican
primary in Washington state; Subs 3rd graf for rewriting) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Gov. George W. Bush won a forceful victory over
Sen. John McCain in Virginia and North Dakota on Tuesday, picking
up a large cache of delegates as well as a considerable morale
boost after his discouraging loss in Michigan a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush held a solid lead over McCain with about a
third of the votes counted in the Republican primary in Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   The largest delegate prize of the day was here in Virginia,
where both candidates drew heavily from the voter groups that have
supported them in earlier contests for the Republican presidential
nomination. Bush captured faithful Republican voters, as he did in
his victory in South Carolina 10 days ago, particularly
conservatives and those who call themselves members of the
religious right.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won the overwhelming support of independents and
Democrats. While those voters were responsible for the Arizona
senator's first-place finishes in Michigan and New Hampshire before
that, they accounted for a much smaller proportion of the
electorate here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The results also showed that the wave of publicity after
McCain's upset victory in Michigan and his fresh appeal that he was
``a proud Reagan conservative,'' were not sufficient to carry him
over the finish line. And McCain's blunt attacks on leaders of the
religious right on Monday failed to rouse independents and
Democrats, although the senator argued that message will play
better in upcoming states with higher proportions of moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took 53 percent of the vote in Virginia; McCain won 44
percent and Alan Keyes took 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The governor later characterized his victory as a repudiation of
McCain's drive to paint him as a captive of the religious right.
``The voters of Virginia rejected the politics of pitting one
religion against another,'' Bush declared at a rally in Cincinnati.
``This campaign is winning and we're doing it the right way. We are
uniting our party without compromising principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on his campaign bus in central California, McCain said
he had called Bush to congratulate him on his victory in Virginia.
But he minimized the governor's accomplishment, suggesting that
Bush had only regional appeal. ``It seems as if he has a Southern
strategy, doing well in Southern states,'' McCain said. ``We'll
look forward to Super Tuesday when we have a broad section _ a
cross-section of America _ voting all on that same day.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he felt his speech against the Christian right on
Monday had damaged him with Virginia voters, he replied: ``No. We
were talking nationally, not to Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   In the North Dakota caucuses, only 19 national convention
delegates were at stake, compared with 56 in Virginia. Bush won an
impressive 76 percent of the vote, McCain, 19 percent, and Keyes, 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, 12 delegates were up for grabs, about a third of
the total in the state. The rest will be picked next week.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Bush and McCain were no where near Virginia as the
votes were being counted underscored how the looming jumble of
contests next Tuesday overshadowed the voting. The election on
March 7 is tantamount to a national primary, with Republicans going
to the polls in California, New York, Ohio, Georgia, Missouri and
seven other states. As a result, the contenders have raced from one
coast to the other _ and in between.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not stumped in Virginia since Friday night, when he
spoke in Richmond at a party dinner. McCain rushed out of the state
early Monday afternoon after condemning Pat Robertson and the Rev.
Jerry Falwell, two leaders of the religious right, in a speech in
Virginia Beach. On Tuesday, as he bounced in California from
Stockton to Fresno to Bakersfield, McCain was clearly focused on
next Tuesday. ``California is a critical state,'' he said. ``And I
need to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Virginia was the largest delegate prize of the day,
Washington state also held a primary on Tuesday. Both candidates
spent as much time in recent days competing there as in Virginia.
The McCain campaign viewed that state _ with a history of rewarding
insurgents _ as more hospitable to their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also went to caucuses on Tuesday in North Dakota, which
has only 19 delegates. There was also a Democratic primary in
Washington state, where no delegates were at stake. Bill Bradley
campaigned vigorously there, struggling for a symbolic victory as a
first step in catching Vice President Al Gore. By Tuesday night,
definitive results in Washington and North Dakota had not been
tallied.
</P>
<P>
   In this roller-coaster of a primary season, the outcome in
Virginia was a substantial victory for Bush because by capturing
all of Virginia's delegates to the national convention (1,034 are
needed for the nomination), he surpassed McCain in the total
delegate tally. The state has the 10th largest share of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was well organized in this state, relying on the energetic
support of the state's most prominent elected Republicans,
particularly Gov. James S. Gilmore III and Sen. John W. Warner, and
vastly outspending McCain. McCain had boasted that he would beat
the ``Gilmore-Warner machine'' just as he had topped Gov. John M.
Engler's organization in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain just played it wrong in attacking the Gilmore-Warner
machine in Virginia,'' said Mark J. Rozell, a professor of politics
at Catholic University and an expert on Virginia politics. ``He
named probably the two most popular figures in Virginia politics.
And by making several campaign stops in Virginia, McCain raised the
expectations for his candidacy and failed badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they played down the significance of the outcome on
Tuesday, McCain's aides had significantly stepped up his budget for
the state in recent days after the senator's victory in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCain folks were working very hard; they bought our whole
voter file,'' said Ed Matricardi, executive director of the
Republican Party of Virginia. ``They ran a full-fledged campaign
here. The Bush people did too.'' Told that the McCain operation
said it was never particularly serious about Virginia, Matricardi
said, ``How can you advertise heavily in the most expensive
television market _ Northern Virginia _ and say you didn't campaign
here?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While McCain's supporters dismissed Bush as simply winning
another Southern state, this state is more diverse than South
Carolina, from the tobacco country in the South to the coal country
in the West to the Washington suburbs to the North.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know that the western tip of Virginia is further west
than Detroit?'' Matricardi said on Tuesday as he pointed to a
brightly-colored map on the wall of his office. But although this
state is more diverse than South Carolina, it is significantly more
conservative than Michigan _ and that helps explain why Bush won.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's continued difficulty in winning significant support
from loyal Republicans may also be a promising sign for Bush as the
contests turn largely to states where only Republicans can vote.
More than six in 10 of the voters on Tuesday described themselves
as Republicans and they overwhelmingly backed Bush, according to a
survey of voters leaving the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly three in 10 said they considered themselves
independents _ and they just as overwhelmingly backed McCain. Less
than one in 10 voters described themselves as Democrats, and they
overwhelmingly backed McCain. Bush was far more successful here
than in Michigan because voters in Virginia are more conservative.
Nearly six in 10 of voters here described themselves as
conservatives, compared to just over four in 10 in Michigan. The
conservative voters in Virginia backed Bush over McCain by a margin
of more than two to one.
</P>
<P>
   But moderates, who accounted for about three in 10 of the voters
on Tuesday, backed McCain over Bush by nearly the same margin.
Liberals, who made up one in 10 of the electorate, overwhelmingly
backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of how the Republican rivalry has deepened the
divide between two very different wings of the party, Republicans
who voted Tuesday were split over McCain's ideological stripes.
Half said he is not conservative enough; half said he is
conservative by the right amount.
</P>
<P>
   People who describe themselves as religious conservatives were
less crucial to Bush's victory here than in South Carolina. Two in
10 Virginia voters said they were part of the religious right
movement; of those,nearly eight in 10 voted for Bush. In South
Carolina, more than threein 10 voters said they were part of the
religious right; nearly seven in 10 supported Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While the closing days of the campaign here were dominated by
bitter exchanges between the Bush and McCain camps over the
Christian right and over which candidate is the true conservative,
that may not have had much influence on the outcome because fewer
than one in 10 voters left their decision until Tuesday. Those who
did decide backed Bush overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign moved aggressively to tap into hostility from
tobacco farmers about McCain's support for higher cigarette taxes
and from voters in Northern Virginia who were distressed by his
advocacy for more flights _ and more noise _ at Reagan National
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's organization delivered automated telephone calls to
10,000 residents of Northern Virginia, accusing McCain of pressing
for ``48 additional noisy flights.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, there had only been one presidential primary in
Virginia, and that was in 1988. Bush's father, George Bush,
defeated Bob Dole and Pat Robertson in that primary. Since then,
the state has picked its convention delegates through caucuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
