<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE ON SCORING TEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Luc Robitaille's assist on Ziggy Palffy's
first-period goal Tuesday against Vancouver gave him a point in 14
consecutive games, a career high.
</P>
<P>
   During that stretch, Robitaille has 10 goals and 13 assists,
giving him 499 assists as a King. His 61 points this year puts him
at 1,137 in his 14-year career and moves him within 15 of Michel
Goulet (1,152) for 33rd all-time.
</P>
<P>
   Two other players in Robitaille's range are still playing and
producing. Former King Larry Murphy, now with Detroit, has 35
points this season and 1,205 points. Dave Andreychuk has 33 points
for Boston this season, giving him 1,177 for his career.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, says Robitaille, was the Kings' 9-4 record
during that stretch entering Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our line has really been playing well the past few weeks, but
that has only been part of our turnaround,'' Robitaille said. ``Our
defense has been great clearing pucks in front of the net and
getting it to us quickly. That's what gets you to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Mogilny returns: Right-winger Alexander Mogilny, who missed
eight games with a separated shoulder and 23 overall this season,
returned to the Vancouver lineup. The move forced rookie Steve
Kariya to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny, who has been bothered by injuries the past few seasons,
was teamed with center Andrew Cassels and left wing Todd Bertuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to the point where it's not going to get any better for
quite some time, but it's also at the point where I don't think
it's going to get re-injured,'' said Mogilny, who scored 76 goals
for Buffalo in 1992-93 and 55 three years later for the Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny, who had 32 goals combined the two previous seasons, has
15 goals and 28 points in 40 games this year. He had a good scoring
chance late in the first period before getting tied up by Kings
defenseman Sean O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick Whistles: The Canucks played their first game at the
Staples Center. They were 29-47-13 at the Forum. . . . Steve
McKenna, Marko Tuomainen and Jaroslav Modry were the Kings' healthy
scratches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
