<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2845 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRITETH     03-01 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE EASILY DEFEATS BRADLEY IN WASHINGTON PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Subs throughout for updating, rewriting; note byline change.
The story is now an added starter on The New York Times front
page.) 
 (sw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr. with JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore delivered a crushing blow to
former Sen. Bill Bradley in Tuesday's Democratic presidential
primary in Washington, winning the state where Bradley said he
would make his most defiant stand, and where he concentrated his
resources for the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who enjoyed the overwhelming support of most of the
state's Democratic establishment and many of its powerful labor and
environmental groups, beat Bradley by more than two to one in a
non-binding ``beauty contest'' primary in which no convention
delegates were at stake but the political viability of Bradley was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful to the people of Washington state because it
looks like a big win but I'm not going to take a single thing for
granted,'' Gore told reporters in his hotel room in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   With 33 per cent of the state's precincts reporting, Gore had 72
percent of the vote and Bradley 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Given the humiliating margin of defeat, and Bradley's earlier
losses in Iowa, New Hampshire and Delaware, it was difficult to see
where he could make his next stand with any great expectation of
turning things around.
</P>
<P>
   About 2{ hours after the polls closed at 7 p.m. Pacific time,
Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman, conceded the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost,'' Hauser said. ``We are a little disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, Bradley had no intention of quitting. ``This
campaign is unanimous in its desire to move forward to March 7.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Bradley was spending six full days of campaigning
here, other candidates, both Democrats and Republicans, were
concentrating on those 16 primaries and caucuses next Tuesday. Many
of his top supporters questioned his decision not to campaign in
New York this week.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, that commitment was a huge political
gamble, an effort to post a win of any kind, anywhere. His
desperate hope was that a win here would help him regain some of
the traction that at one point earlier on in the nominating process
had him nipping at Gore's heels and even briefly ahead of him in a
few places. But it was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of the Washington contest, the harder Bradley
hammered Gore, calling him a closet conservative and matching him
television advertisement for television advertisement and mass
mailing for mass mailing, the more difficult the course got.
</P>
<P>
   Then over the weekend Gore dropped into the state and locked up
victory with a series of quick appearances in which he determinedly
defended his credentials as a solid Democrat and, at the same time,
proudly paraded the big array of Washington state Democratic, labor
and environment leaders who were backing him.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the results were in Bradley's campaign was fending
off questions about whether he was about to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation swept through Washington, D.C., on Tuesday that
Bradley would drop out of the race if he failed to win in
Washington state. But Bradley's aides strenuously denied that he
would quit before March 7, or that he was being advised to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This camp is working hard towards March 7 and beyond,'' said
Douglas C. Berman, Bradley's campaign chairman. ``I know everybody
wants to write a different story. But the velocity with which
things change in this political climate is incredible. And that's
the view of the campaign, and certainly the senator.''
</P>
<P>
   A top New York adviser to Bradley said he had heard speculations
all day about the former senator dropping out, but attributed it to
Gore's supporters. He said that Bradley's advisers, particularly
those in New York, were firm in advising that he should continue
his campaign through the March 7 primaries. California, New York,
Missouri, Ohio, Georgia, most of New England, and 10 other states
hold Democratic primaries or caucuses on March 7, when nearly a
third of the delegates to the Democratic national convention will
be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley announced on Tuesday that he would buy five minutes of
prime time on national television this Thursday to make a direct
appeal to voters five days before those races.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said the taped spot, which will be broadcast at
the end of the CBS news magazine ``48 Hours,'' will feature Bradley
speaking directly into a camera about why he would make the best
president of the four major candidates now running.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign's extraordinary decision to buy national television
time reflects not only Bradley's difficult straits _ he is running
well behind Gore in almost all state polls _ but also his
frustration with the small amount of media attention he has been
receiving. News coverage of the race has been dominated by the
Republican battle between Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's spot will be competing with ``ER'' on NBC, one of
television's most popular programs. Asked why they had not bought
time on ``ER,'' Bradley's aides said it was probably too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign declined to say how much the spot would
cost. But several political consultants who buy television time for
candidates estimated that it would be about $1 million. They also
estimated that the commercial would be seen by more than seven
million people, though many would be in states that do not vote on
March 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 0124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
