<HEADER>
A2858 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RAMPART-REPORT-LADN     03-01 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMPART-REPORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS MEDIOCRITY RULED COPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV,  
 GREG GITTRICH and BETH BARRETT  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ A devastating internal probe of the LAPD
corruption scandal to be released Wednesday condemns the command
staff for fostering a culture of ``mediocrity'' that poisoned the
rank and file and allowed a few rogue officers to commit crimes and
frame innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   Officers at every level of the Los Angeles Police Department
were failing to do their jobs, the LAPD Board of Inquiry concluded
based upon its exhaustive review, which was conducted by about 300
ranking officers and investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The board's nearly 400-page report, obtained Tuesday by the
Daily News, found no evidence of widespread corruption. But the
findings, which will be given to the Police Commission today,
include 108 recommendations to overhaul the management and
oversight in the LAPD, once considered among the nation's finest
law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scandal has devastated our relationship with the public
we serve and threatened the integrity of our entire criminal
justice system,'' the board concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distrust, cynicism, fear of the police and an erosion of
community law and order are the inevitable result of a law
enforcement agency whose ethics and integrity have become
suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, public safety in the city has been harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented condemnation of his own department, LAPD
Chief Bernard C. Parks agreed there is strong evidence that the
department's failings are pervasive, but still could have been
prevented.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are to get out of mediocrity, we have to have the
courage to begin to expect more,'' Parks said during an interview
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter attached to the board's report, the chief promised
that the officers involved in ``disgraceful activity will be dealt
with.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned: ``We as an organization must recognize that,
while they individually and collectively provided the motivation,
we as an organization provided the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Inquiry said its five-month probe found no reason
to believe that the actions of dirty cop Rafael Perez were
representative of the entire department. It portrayed Perez as a
rogue officer who sold out his department's value system to steal
cocaine from an LAPD evidence room in order to live the lifestyle
of a ``high roller.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, now the key informant in the largest police corruption
scandal in the city's history, has told investigators that he and
other corrupt cops in the Rampart Division's special anti-gang unit
shot unarmed suspects, brutalized suspects, framed innocent people
for crimes and lied in court to send many to prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Inquiry was convened in September by Parks to
investigate corruption related to the Rampart Division. Based upon
the analysis of tens of thousands of documents and hundreds of
interviews, the board examined the top-to-bottom management of the
LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the problems uncovered by the board boiled down to
``people failing to do their jobs with a high level of consistency
and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we found this to be true at all levels of the
organization, including top managers, first-line supervisors and
line personnel,'' the board noted. ``Clearly, pride in one's work
and a commitment to do things correctly the first time seems to
have waned.''
</P>
<P>
   Specific recommendations by the board include toughening the
LAPD's screening process for potential cops, limiting the tour of
duty of officers in specialized units, expanding the Internal
Affairs Division, placing more senior officers in the field,
conducting sting operations to catch dirty cops and raising
standards for promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The board added that it should continue to investigate and audit
at least seven different areas of concern within the LAPD,
including the activities of every special Community Resources
Against Street Hoodlums (CRASH) anti-gang unit and the department's
use of confidential informants.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape will be shown at roll calls during the coming week
to express to officers what the Board of Inquiry report means and
how it will affect them. In addition, a follow-up report will be
issued next year when a special task force concludes its
investigation into the widening corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   According to the board, mediocrity ``flourishes'' in the LAPD
largely due to incompetent senior officers who fail to challenge
the rank and file. In many cases, the top cops make excuses for an
overall laziness and lack of commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mediocrity was alive and well in Rampart up until about 1998.
We are sad to report that we also found mediocrity threatening to
engulf many of our other workplace environments as well,'' the
board wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to say or imply in any way that corruption is
occurring throughout the department, for we do not believe that is
the case. However, there are strong indicators that mediocrity is
flourishing in many other workplaces and the mind-set of too many
managers and supervisors is allowing it to occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than challenging our people to do their best, too many
of our leaders are allowing mediocre performance and, in cases,
even making excuses for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to the Police Commission, Parks said the
department ``created the opportunity for this cancer to grow'' by
failing to review officers' reports, examine events to identify
patterns of misconduct and provide effective oversight and audits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who has experienced the death of a child, or suffered
through the humiliation of being victimized by a violent crime,
knows they can never again look at the world in the same way.
Organizations, too, have those defining moments and the events that
have been uncovered in Rampart will and should be just such a
life-altering experience for the Los Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must never forget that this occurred and be ever vigilant
that we never allow the opportunity for this to occur again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Parks said he believes the problems go back
more than two decades, when the department was at its lowest
strength and officers began to cut corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was being asked to do so much and then you begin
taking shortcuts,'' Parks said. ``Then people begin doing more and
more and soon it becomes ingrained. And then people with
administrative experience leave and once that level of knowledge is
gone, it can't be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks noted that the Board of Inquiry identified other areas of
the department in which there are the same systemic problems that
existed at Rampart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had officers working their own sources without reporting to
supervisors. We had officers writing reports and their own booking
instructions with no supervision. We were just accepting what was
being written,'' the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Inquiry categorized its recommendations into nine
general areas: the testing and screening of police officer
candidates, personnel practices, personnel investigations and
management of risk, corruption investigations, operational
controls, anti-corruption inspections and audits, ethics and
integrity training, job-specific training and work that the board
should continue to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are ``both critical to ensuring a
corruption-free Department and achievable with minimal budgetary
impact,'' the board said.
</P>
<P>
   The board's probe was launched after investigators discovered
the disturbing link among three serious crimes that occurred
between late 1997 and early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In each incident - a November 1997 bank robbery; a February 1998
station-house beating, and the March 1998 theft of three kilos of
cocaine from an LAPD evidence room - cops were identified as
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   All the suspected dirty officers were closely associated, either
working as partners or close friends. All but one of them were
assigned to Rampart.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those cases, Parks said he believes the LAPD training
system does not need to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Perez and some of the other officers involved,
they knew that what they were doing was a violation of
procedures,'' Parks said. ``To that extent, the training worked, in
they knew that what they were doing was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he expects the criminal investigation to be completed
this year, but that the lawsuits and other effects will go on
several years more.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, bolstered last week by the addition of eight
FBI agents, has resulted in the suspension or dismissal of 20 cops
and the reversal of 40 criminal convictions. At least 15 civil
lawsuits have been filed against the city, seeking hundreds of
millions of dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The full Board of Inquiry report is available on the LAPD Web
site, www.lapdonline.org.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
