<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: HAVE YOU SEEN THESE INTRIGUING STORIES?...(2-28)  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (These ``separate-buy'' articles are from the Independent of
London, distributed by the New York Times Syndicate.)  
  
 (To publish these articles, they must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HAIDER GOOSE-STEPS DOWN AMID DER FUROR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The Austrian far-right leader Joerg Haider stunned
political friends and foes alike by announcing Monday that he
wanted to step down as leader of the Freedom Party. But there is no
danger of Haider, the most successful politician in postwar Austria
and an ambitious chancellor wannabe, disappearing from the scene.
In fact, his retreat is likely to prove a tactical gambit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Imre Karacs, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-HAIDER-GOOSESTEPS-DOWN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MCCAIN TURNS UP THE HEAT ON BUSH, RELIGIOUS RIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH _ Senator John McCain dramatically turned up the
heat in the battle for the Republican presidential nomination
Monday, attacking influential religious right-wingers as hypocrites
in a speech described as ``astounding'' and ``epoch-making.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Tuesday, Feb. 29 primaries) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MCCAIN'S-HOLY-WAR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSH OR MCCAIN: WHICH ONE IS THE REAL REPUBLICAN? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just after learning to his evident amazement that
his presidential ambitions were still alive, thanks to the voters
of Michigan, Senator John McCain issued a curious appeal. ``Don't
fear my campaign, fellow Republican,'' he pleaded, ``join it, join
it.'' Mindful that only 40 percent of all U.S. voters are
Republicans and that anyone who wants to be president must appeal
across party lines, George W. Bush responded with an appeal of his
own, calling on ``Republicans and like-minded independents'' to
support him. Which candidate will capture the hearts _ and votes _
of Republicans? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-`MCBUSH'-DISSECTED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE REMARKABLE ODYSSEY OF MADELEINE ALBRIGHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you know U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, you will also know that the notion of her becoming the
next president of the Czech Republic is both absurd and utterly
logical. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By David Usborne, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WHY-NOT-MADELEINE?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALBRIGHT IS HAVEL'S HANDPICKED SUCCESSOR, RUMOR CLAIMS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrives
in Prague next week on a trip that many in her native capital see
as a declaration of interest in the country's presidency.
Czech-born Albright is being touted as a possible replacement for
Vaclav Havel, whose term of office ends in 2002. Havel told
Albright a year and a half ago that he wanted her to replace him,
according to a report in Time magazine Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Adam Lebor, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-AUSTRIA-ALBRIGHT-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JITTERY GEORGIA FEARS BEING SUCKED INTO THE CHECHEN WAR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TBLISI, GEORGIA _ In the snow-covered mountains of northern
Georgia, soldiers can hear the roar of battle across the border in
Chechnya creeping gradually towards them. Georgia, the fragile
republic on the southern slopes of the Caucasus Mountains, is
trying hard to stay out of the Chechen conflict. A weary-looking
Georgian President Edouard Shevardnadze told The Independent
Saturday, ``we are doing everything we can to avoid getting
involved.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Cockburn, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-GEORGIA-JITTERS-CHECHNYA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. `COVERED UP' SCIENTISTS' WARNINGS ON GM FOODS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair's fresh skepticism
about GM (genetically-modified) foods was bolstered Monday by
claims that the U.S. government has covered up the safety fears of
its own scientists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Jack O'Sullivan, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-GM-FOODS-`COVERUP'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
