<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA: WHERE JUSTICE IS TAINTED BY A LETHAL CYNICISM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's too easy to get angry about the death penalty in America.
Indeed, the legal process permits people to be executed with a
casualness _ and callousness _ that is shocking. There are now more
than 3,000 on Death Row across the country. And America can, and
may, kill all of them: it's just that easy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Provocative Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 29) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-TOOEASY-EXECUTIONS-US-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET SURFING HARMS YOUR SOCIAL LIFE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People who use the Internet for as little as five hours a week
are less likely to talk to or visit their family and friends and
are in danger of shutting themselves off from society, according to
new research. Is it time to log off and live? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Cherry Norton, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 29) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (350 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-LOG-OFF-AND-LIVE!-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY MUST WE WAIT TO ENJOY OUR LEISURE TIME WHEN WE'RE OLD? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why on earth do we have a tax and benefit system that encourages
workers to take all of their leisure time when they are older, and
none when it would be most desirable to them _ in the prime of
life? When will governments have the vision to lift their eyes
above the problem pensions pose for their budgets and tackle the
crazy structure of lifetime work incentives? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Coyle, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 29) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 100-word trim at 800; total uncut is 1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WHAT-LEISURE?-800&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE CAN LIVE WITHOUT THE NET, BUT WE'LL ALWAYS NEED SHAMPOO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is, as someone once said, a funny old world. Two global
corporate titans, Ford and Unilever, announced recently that they
are getting rid of thousands of their workers. But we are
undoubtedly going to go on needing Unilever's detergent powder,
shampoo and frozen peas. And we will certainly be driving around in
Ford cars for another generation. The old economy may be out of
fashion in the cyber-new world, but we still need the things it
produces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Hamish McRae, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tues., Feb. 29) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 575; total uncut is 1,125 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CYBER-SHAMPOO-550&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
