<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY BLOWN AWAY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ It has been said of this America's Cup
match that if the teams had switched boats in the beginning, the
outcome would be the same. Never was the observation more clearly
true than in Tuesday's 1-minute 49-second thumping of Italy's Luna
Rossa by Team New Zealand, which took a 4-0 lead in this
best-of-nine match.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Italian afterguard called Tuesday's race, Team New
Zealand could have beaten Prada had the Kiwis been sailing a
Duxbury Duck.
</P>
<P>
   In light winds, Prada appeared a bit quicker than the heavier
NZ60 of New Zealand. But as if the boys from Milan wanted to go
home early, halfway up the first leg, Prada literally gave the race
away to Russell Coutts _ a present, perhaps, on the TNZ skipper's
38th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the start to Coutts and tactician Brad Butterworth
_ who wanted the left _ Prada found itself on the right side of the
course for the first time in four races. All three New Zealand
victories have begun with TNZ on the right.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, both teams' weather departments determined the left
was favored for shifts, and in its attempt to recover the left,
Prada gave up a lead it could have used to take control of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   The critical moment came halfway up the first leg. In the first
two crosses upwind, Coutts tacked NZ60 into a lee bow position,
forcing skipper Francesco de Angelis back to the right. But as if
de Angelis and tactician Torben Grael had forgotten the huge power
of the right (owning the starboard tack advantage), at the third
cross, Prada simply gave the race away.
</P>
<P>
   As they came together, Luna Rossa was ahead of NZ60 for the
first time, forcing Coutts to steer bow down and take Prada's
stern. Had Prada then tacked on top of New Zealand, the Italians
would have had control of the race, forcing the Kiwis back to the
left, where they would have had to follow them in ``dirty'' air up
the port layline and around the first mark.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, Grael had the left side implanted in his brain and
apparently did not understand what an advantage Luna Rossa had.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand did exactly what Prada could have done _ force the
left-side boat to the port layline, where the only option was to
trail to the mark in the lead boat's dirty air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that with light wind, the left was favored all
day,'' said de Angelis. ``That is what our weather information
said, and we wanted the left.''
</P>
<P>
   Grael agreed: ``Our plan was to have the left side, because
that's where the wind was. But then it went both ways. When you
guess the right way it is one thing, but sometimes you guess the
wrong way. That is just the wind. That's sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Grael was heavily criticized in Race 7 of the semifinals, when
in a similar move _ taking the left rather than covering the
trailing boat _ he let AmericaOne run away with the race.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Grael was scolded by Prada syndicate boss Patrizio
Bertelli, who said the Brazilian tactician, an Olympic gold
medalist, was sailing too much by instinct and not enough by the
match racing book.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli reacted to the latest loss with strong words: ``On a
day when wind conditions were in favor of Luna Rossa _ who proved
to have the same speed as New Zealand, if not faster _ suicidal
tactics gave the race away.''
</P>
<P>
   Coutts, the two-time skipper of Team New Zealand, Tuesday tied
an America's Cup record for consecutive victories _ nine _ since
the start of the 1995 Cup in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were crossing their stern, I thought it was not a
great situation, but then it turned out to be OK,'' said Coutts.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts said he and his team were not affected by four days off,
which included two cancellation days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This regatta has gone on a lot longer than we wanted it to.
Our plan is to go out and end it tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With moderate to strong winds forecast for Wednesday's race (No.
5), New Zealand could put an end to the 30th America's Cup, winning
again the oldest trophy in sports, first awarded in 1851.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts represents the second generation of New Zealand sailors.
Having won an Olympic gold medal in Star Class in 1984 as a
24-year-old, he watched another young Kiwi skipper, Chris Dickson,
lead New Zealand into its first America's Cup in Freemantle.
</P>
<P>
   The Kiwis came close, but Dickson lost the Louis Vuitton Cup to
Stars &AMP; Stripes that year. Coutts was the backup helmsman in 1992,
when New Zealand again lost the challenger trials to Paul Cayard on
Il Moro.
</P>
<P>
   Back with a new program and its two ``Black Magic'' boats in
1995, Team New Zealand began its streak of seeming invincibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
