<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY HAS BEATEN CANCER, HOLOCAUST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Scott Greenberg doesn't need to run the Los
Angeles Marathon. He could easily continue his thriving career as a
motivational speaker by relating inspirational stories of his
triumph over cancer and his grandmother's survival of the Holocaust
as an employee in Oskar Schindler's factory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Greenberg will put his body on the line Sunday, and
despite the fact that he had no running experience at this time
last year, he will attempt to complete the 26.2-mile course, if
only to prove that he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``My motto has become, `Even if it's not a good time, it's a
good story,' '' said Greenberg, 29, a Sherman Oaks resident who
travels the country to speak to businesses, schools and various
groups. ``When I give my presentations, one of my primary subjects
is overcoming adversity, and in order to maintain some credibility
I need to expose myself to adversity, to prove that my message is
valid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked myself, `What's the most-extreme thing you can do
besides getting cancer again?' and I came up with running a
marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens this weekend, Greenberg realizes it will pale
in comparison to his current tale of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg grew up in San Diego, and after graduation from UCLA
in 1992 embarked on a promising career in the movie industry as a
graduate student at New York University, which has one of the
country's top film schools.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg enjoyed New York and its contrasts to his Southern
California suburbia upbringing, but his stay would be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night, near the end of my first semester, I came home from
a film shoot,'' Greenberg said. ``I was laying in bed, and when I
scratched my neck I felt this bump, and it was large, about the
size of a golf ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the next day I went to the doctor, and he said it
was just a swollen lymph node, and that there was a small chance it
could be HIV but that it was probably nothing to worry about. He
told me to come back in four or five days.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, however, Greenberg's phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted me to come back into the office immediately,''
Greenberg said. ``For 30 or 45 minutes, I was convinced that I had
HIV because why else would they want me to come in right away?''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg didn't have HIV, but his diagnosis wasn't much more
positive. Greenberg, at age 22, was told he had Hodgkin's Disease,
a form of cancer particularly prevalent among young adults.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly eight months of chemotherapy and radiation were in
Greenberg's future, which forced him to drop out of school and
return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't understand it,'' Greenberg said. ``My family
had always had good health care, I didn't smoke and I didn't do
drugs, so I didn't know how I could have changed my lifestyle to
prevent this.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that moment, when I found out, was a defining moment. My
first thought was, `OK, what do I need to do to get better?' It
wasn't, `Oh my God, why me?' even though I'm sure I was in shock.
But if anything, based on my grandmother's experience, it was `Why
not me?'
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's grandmother, who still does not want her name
revealed today for fear of Nazis, lived in Krakow, Poland, at the
onset of World War II. Her parents were both taken away and killed,
but she was sent to work for Schindler, who helped prevent the
deaths of thousands of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thinking about my grandmother truly made me appreciate life,
and I made the decision to live life to its fullest,'' Greenberg
said. ``I didn't know if I was going to live or not, but either I
was going to die, or I was going to live and have a wonderful story
to share with people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out to clubs, I tried to meet girls and generally live
my life the way I wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   In August of 1993, on the eve of his final radiation treatment,
Greenberg was invited to Santa Barbara by a friend to speak at a
banquet. He spoke of his triumph and began to mold his current
presentation of inspiration mixed with humor.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, several youths asked Greenberg to speak at their
school, and a career was born. Greenberg now travels the country
(he will leave for Hawaii shortly after completing the marathon)
and established his own Web site (www.ScottGreenberg.com) to help
spread his message.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, now married, has been cancer-free for more than six
years, even though the radiation increases his chances of
developing leukemia in the future. Last year, his brother Brent ran
in San Diego's Rock and Roll Marathon in his honor to raise money
for the Leukemia Society, which sparked Greenberg's interest in
running in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at all those people, and I thought, `I'm such a
loser,' '' Greenberg said with a laugh. ``Running requires such a
high level of discipline, and I'd love to finish in four-and-a-half
hours, but the number one thing is just to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know life is short, and no matter what, I intend to enjoy
it.''!dlim!!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
