<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GEORGEWASHINGTON-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS UPSET BY GW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ After 28 games, including a midseason surge
that presumably offset a sluggish start, it's difficult to believe
the University of Massachusetts is mired in misfortune again. But
one game remains in the Minutemen's regular season, and coach
Bruiser Flint is still shaking his head and sighing heavily at
postgame press conferences while trying to explain how another
winnable game got away.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, it was thought that such moments were over for this
season. UMass was beating teams it could beat, and playing well
against squads with more talent and depth.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, George Washington made the Minutemen take a
giant step backward. The younger, quicker Colonials rallied from a
7-point deficit with 6:51 left by taking advantage of several UMass
miscues down the stretch for an 87-86 Atlantic 10 upset, spoiling
the Minutemen's Senior Night before a crowd of 5,430.
</P>
<P>
   Following the debacle, Flint didn't mince words: ``We played
dumb basketball. That's why we lost. We had our chances. We shut
them down. But we have to play smart basketball. And we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   GW freshman guard SirValiant Brown, the A-10's top scorer and
one of the national leaders, had 35 points, including the
Colonials' last 7. He sank 1 of 2 free throws twice over the final
23 seconds to seal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those games we felt if we could get it in the
80s, 90s, we have a chance,'' said coach Tom Penders, whose team
leads the A-10 in scoring but is last in defense. ``If we got into
a slug-it-out, halfcourt game, we had no chance. We did the right
things down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   And UMass didn't.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by as many as 8 in the second half, the Minutemen
rallied and took a 78-71 lead with 6:51 to go. But GW regained the
lead and went ahead, 85-82, with 1:24 left on a layup by Brown.
</P>
<P>
   UMass (15-13, 9-6) had several chances to silence GW's rally.
But with 5:16 left, guard Shannon Crooks was whistled for a
backcourt violation. With 2:45 left, he missed on a dunk attempt.
Then forward Mike Babul missed two free throws with 2:16 left and
turned the ball over with 1:41 to go.
</P>
<P>
   GW (15-13, 9-6) scored after each of the Minutemen miscues.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:07 left, guard Monty Mack (22 points) hit a left baseline
jumper, pulling the Minutemen within 1 (85-84), and when Brown
turned the ball over on GW's next possession, Mack raced up the
floor with a chance for the lead. But he missed a pullup jumper
with :27.6 left, and Brown got the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   He was fouled and sank one free throw to put GW up by 2, but on
the ensuing possession, Crooks was hit with an offensive foul in
the paint with 12.7 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The officials) said the guy was there,'' said Flint,
referring to GW forward Antxon Iturbe, who drew the charge. ``What
else can you say?''
</P>
<P>
   With 11.6 seconds left, Brown sank another free throw, putting
GW up, 87-84. Mack misfired on a trey attempt at the other end, and
teammate Chris Kirkland (a team-high 26 points) scored on a putback
with 2.1 seconds left for the game's final margin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defeat, the Minutemen took solace that they can
still claim a first-round bye in the Atlantic 10 tournament with a
win Saturday at St. Bonaventure. The Bonnies beat UMass, 70-60, in
Amherst Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen need 16 wins to assure themselves a winning
season, which would make them eligible for the National Invitation
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go and just win the game,'' said Flint. ``I know
it's disappointing, because I've never lost a game on Senior Night
(as a coach). I lost my last college game on Senior Night, and you
never forget that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
