<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTONCOLLEGE-SYRACUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY, EAGLES SOAR TO RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With just over a minute to go in the first half
Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night against Syracuse, Boston College guard Alissa Murphy
went down, the team trainer came to the floor, and the crowd went
silent as the senior hobbled into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Would this be the way she would say goodbye to her career at
Conte Forum?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy scored a season-high 25 points and was 4 for 4 from the
3-point line as the BC women's basketball team trounced Syracuse,
80-60. The Eagles (23-7, 12-4 Big East) have not lost at home all
season, and they have the best record in school history.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance that No. 19 BC will host the first and second
rounds of the NCAA tournament in three weeks (March 16-19).
</P>
<P>
   After Syracuse struck first with a field goal by center Leigh
Aziz and two free throws by forward Beth Record, BC came back with
two layups by center Jamie Cournoyer and a jumper by Murphy to go
in front, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles led from that point, building a 15-point lead, 32-17,
at 5:04 behind the outside shooting of Murphy and the inside
shooting of Cournoyer.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Orangewomen would whittle the lead to 5 on a
3-pointer by guard Jamie James of Plymouth and another by Jazmine
Wright, by far the scariest moment for the crowd was when Murphy
went down with 1:07 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just rolled my ankle,'' said Murphy after the game, with ice
on her right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Cournoyer, who closed the half with a jumper at the buzzer, gave
the Eagles a 36-29 lead going into the locker room. She set them in
motion again when she hit another jumper to open the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse (10-17, 3-13) responded with a 3-pointer by Wright and
two free throws by Tara Trammell to bring the Orangewomen to within
4 at 38-34. But the Eagles then went on a 14-0 run, powered by
three field goals by Cournoyer, two more by Murphy, and a 3-point
play by guard Brianne Stepherson.
</P>
<P>
   Three more 3-pointers by James didn't make a dent as the Eagles'
lead grew to 24 with 4:48 to go. Record led the Orangewomen with 15
points, but had just 2 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't patient enough with the ball,'' said Syracuse
coach Marianna Freeman. ``We never picked up the intensity we
needed to play against Boston College. We tried to force Jamie
(Cournoyer) to the middle, then she'd set up on the lefthand side
and start hitting that baby hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Cournoyer, who finished with 22 points and four assists,
shrugged off her exploits under the basket: ``I guess I just
smelled blood.''
</P>
<P>
   BC coach Cathy Inglese said she had confidence in her team,
which shot 57 percent (31 of 54) and pulled down 37 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syracuse has a lot of weapons, but we knew we had to put
together a full game,'' Inglese said. ``It's been our goal all
season to go undefeated at home, so I couldn't be more pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepherson finished with 13 points and four assists, while Cal
Bouchard was uncharacteristically quiet with no first-half points
and a total of 6 points and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   But Bouchard said she isn't ready to close the book on Conte
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully it won't be our last game here,'' she said. ``It was
an emotional night, but we're all hoping there will be a couple
more here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
