<HEADER>
A2878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MICH-SHOOTING-NYT &LR;      03-01 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY, 6, ACCUSED IN CLASSMATE'S KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ A 6-year-old boy sneaked a loaded handgun into a
crowded elementary school here on Tuesday and shot a classmate to
death early on Tuesday morning in front of a large group of
first-grade students, said police officials here.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that they did not know the motive for the
shooting but that they recovered a stolen .32-caliber semiautomatic
handgun at the scene and took the boy into protective custody.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the shooting at Buell Elementary near Flint, 60
miles from Detroit, occurred just before 10 a.m. When they arrived,
Kayla Renee Rolland, 6, was found with a gunshot wound to the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the shot was fired, the school principal made
an announcement on the school's public address system telling all
teachers to close their classroom doors and lock them.
</P>
<P>
   A young girl who said she was in the school said: ``We just put
our heads down and started praying.''
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, parents, some of them visibly distraught or
angry, rushed to the school to pick up their children. The school,
where additional police officers were sent for crowd-control duty,
was closed for the day at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The wounded girl was treated by paramedics at the school and
then rushed to the Hurley Medical Center in Flint, Mich. She was
pronounced dead at 10:29 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting, which occurred in a first grade classroom in front
of about 22 students, is the latest in a series of violent acts
that have struck schools in Colorado, Kentucky, Arkansas and Oregon
and reverberated across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the first grader involved in Tuesday's incident is the
youngest involved in any of the multiple shootings at schools
around the country over the last few years or other more random
shootings in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   One of the youths found guilty in the schoolyard shootings that
left five dead in Jonesboro, Ark., on March 24, 1998, was 11 at the
time of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1994, a 10-year-old who said he had been taunted by
classmates admitted to fatally shooting a fifth-grade boy. A few
years before, another 10-year-old shot a school bus driver in the
head, critically wounding her.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1995, the death of 51-year-old substitute teacher
with heart disease was ruled a homicide after she was repeatedly
punched by a 9-year-old student.
</P>
<P>
   And in March 1996, a 6-year-old Newark, N.J., boy was arrested
after bring a 9 mm handgun to Our Lady of Good Counsel School and
firing one shot. No one was injured in that incident.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor in Michigan said on Tuesday that the boy could
not be prosecuted, but he added that he was considering charging
the boy's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I think should be done,'' said Arthur A. Busch,
the Genesee County prosecutor. ``I don't think putting 6-year-old
boys in prison or lock-up is what should be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said he did not know if the shooting was
intentional but added that he was investigating reports of a
playground scuffle that may have happened before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they were also investigating reports that the
gun had been used in other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The police, who said they believed the boy hid the gun in his
pants pocket, questioned the boy on Tuesday and then released him
to the state's Family Independence Agency, a social services
organization.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, there were candles and flowers left in front
of the door at the Buell Elementary School in Mount Morris
Township, Mich., in remembrance of the young girl.
</P>
<P>
   The young girl's grandmother, Ingrid Javor, told a local
television station on Tuesday that the boy's family must bear
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a 6-year-old could do this alone,'' Javor said.
``It would have to be his parents. He'd have to watch a lot of
crime to do what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in Florida for a Democratic fund-raiser,
said: ``Why could the child fire the gun? If we have the technology
today to put in these child safety locks, why don't we do it?''
</P>
<P>
   There were reports on Tuesday night on the local television
stations that the boy had been troubled in school. There were also
press reports that his father and grandfather were in prison and
that the boy lived with his mother and an uncle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
