<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENCIA WOMAN IS WALKING MIRACLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While the elite runners in Sunday's Los Angeles
Marathon will be pushing themselves to the limit for a chance at
$35,000 and a new car, one woman near the back of the pack would
find the biggest thrill of all in simply crossing the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years after suffering devastating injuries in an
automobile accident, Valencia resident Brianne Chierighino will
attempt to walk the 26.2-mile course, not knowing if she will be
able to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my accident, for several months I could barely walk to
the bathroom, let alone walk a marathon,'' Chierighino said. ``So
the concept of completing a marathon is invigorating to me. I have
been working so hard to get to where I am and I can't wait to meet
the dare I have placed upon myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, walking is painful and crossing the finish line
will bea miracle for me. I hope to gain a better image of myself
and feel good about who I am as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   A rear-end accident in July of 1996 nearly left Chierighino a
quadriplegic. She underwent spinal-fusion surgery to help correct
some of her back ailments but says she remains in 24-hour pain.
</P>
<P>
   With the assistance of her husband, Deven, Chierighino will
participate in order to raise money for the National Spinal Cord
Injury Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am testing the limits of my body in ways I never thought
were possible,'' Chierighino said. ``I am slowly gaining confidence
in myself and am feeling better about my body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standing and sitting for more than a few minutes is
excruciating and walking for more than 10 minutes is a killer . . .
so getting through the marathon will be a challenge and an awesome
accomplishment for me, one that I have to try.''
</P>
<P>
   __ By the numbers: Here are a few of the item amounts needed for
the Los Angeles Marathon:
</P>
<P>
   __ 68,000: T-shirts for runners and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   __ 8,200: Credentials for staff, volunteers and media.
</P>
<P>
   __ 4,000: Balloons.
</P>
<P>
   __ 40,000: ``No Parking'' signs.
</P>
<P>
   __ 250: Stretchers.
</P>
<P>
   __ 17,000: Pounds of ice.
</P>
<P>
   __ 1.5 million: Paper cups.
</P>
<P>
   __ 50,000: Gallons of water.
</P>
<P>
   __ USA? No way: An American male has not won the Los Angeles
Marathon since 1994, and that trend is not expected to change
anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has fallen far behind the African countries in
its development of marathon-caliber runners, and the highest-seeded
American this year is Daniel Gonzalez at No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Sayre of Ashland, Ore., won the city's first race in 1986,
when first place was worth just $10,000 in prize money and the race
didn't attract anywhere near the level of runners it does now.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Plaatjes, a political refuge from South Africa, won in
1991, and three years later, Paul Pilkington of Utah, the race's
designated pace-setter, never stopped running and won the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 0204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0059 </DOCNO>
