<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DEFEAT SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ The Anaheim Mighty Ducks did not want to admit that
Tuesday night's game with the San Jose Sharks was as close to a
must-win situation as they have faced all season.
</P>
<P>
   But there wasn't much doubt they knew exactly what was at stake
when Oleg Tverdovsky put them ahead to stay in the second period at
San Jose Arena. Anaheim players banged their sticks in a rare
mid-game celebration, a celebration that was completed after the
Ducks defeated San Jose 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The much-needed victory moved them into ninth-place in the
Western Conference standings, two points behind both Colorado and
San Jose, which are tied for the final playoff spots.
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky's power-play goal at 18:18 of the second period gave
Anaheim the lead, but the Ducks couldn't breathe any sigh of relief
until Mike Leclerc scored at 11:37 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sharks leading 2-1 early in the second period, the game
turned into a track meet on ice. Both teams traded chances, putting
the pressure squarely on goalies Guy Hebert and Steve Shields.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose had some excellent chances to take a two-goal lead, but
Hebert made a big save on Ronnie Stern's bid from the right circle
eight minutes into the second and the Sharks failed to get a shot
on net on a three-on-one at the 10-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Anaheim appeared snakebit. Ruslan Salei hit the post
and Shields made a great save on Matt Cullen's 15-footer from the
slot before the San Jose goalie wowed the crowd with a sprawling
Dominik Hasek-style save on a breakaway by Ted Donato with nine
minutes left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   But as the crowd screamed its approval of Shields stopping
Donato's bid with his head and shoulder, Steve Rucchin fought
through Marco Sturm on an offensive zone faceoff and pushed the
puck to Marty McInnis, who tapped in the tying goal at 11:30.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Nolan hit the crossbar and Hebert made two saves on Vincent
Damphousse before Mike Ricci was called for interference on
Rucchin, giving the Ducks a chance to take the lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 0212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-2NDLD-WRITETH     03-01 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ADMINISTERS HUGE DEFEAT TO BRADLEY IN WASHINGTON STATE
PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Subs for updating and rewriting throughout story) 
 (sw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr. with JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore delivered a crushing blow to
former Sen. Bill Bradley in Tuesday's Democratic presidential
primary in Washington, winning the state where Bradley said he
would make his most defiant stand, and where he concentrated his
resources for the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who enjoyed the overwhelming support of most of the
state's Democratic establishment and many of its powerful labor and
environmental groups, beat Bradley by more than two to one in a
non-binding ``beauty contest'' primary in which no convention
delegates were at stake but the political viability of Bradley was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful to the people of Washington state because it
looks like a big win but I'm not going to take a single thing for
granted,'' Gore told reporters in his hotel room in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   With 67 percent of the state's precincts reporting, the vote
was:
</P>
<P>
   Gore: 123,993 (70 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Bradley: 53,458 (30 percent)
</P>
<P>
   Given the humiliating margin of defeat, and Bradley's earlier
losses in Iowa, New Hampshire and Delaware, it was difficult to see
where he could make his next stand with any great expectation of
turning things around.
</P>
<P>
   About 2{ hours after the polls closed at 7 p.m. Pacific time,
Eric Hauser, Bradley's spokesman, conceded the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost,'' Hauser said. ``We are a little disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, Bradley had no intention of quitting. ``This
campaign is unanimous in its desire to move forward to March 7.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley was spending six days of campaigning here, other
candidates, both Democrats and Republicans, were concentrating on
those 16 primaries and caucuses next Tuesday. Some of his
supporters, particularly in New York, began to publicly question
the wisdom of his huge commitment of time and money to a state in
which delegates would not be selected until caucuses next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By Bradley's own admission, the commitment to Washington was a
huge political gamble, an effort to post a win of any kind,
anywhere. His desperate hope was that a win here would help him
regain some of the traction that at one point earlier on in the
nominating process had him nipping at Gore's heels and even briefly
ahead of him in a few places. But it was not to be.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his eye had long been on Washington because its
voters, particularly independents, have a tradition of voting for
underdogs and of switching across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   But with that tack, he suddenly found himself competing not only
with with Gore but also with Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who was
scrambling hard to persuade independents and dissident Democrats to
join him in his uphill effort to snatch the Republican presidential
nomination from Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. And, in fact, McCain,
though he fell short in winning core Republicans, succeeded on
Tuesday in picking up large numbers of independents and dissident
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of the Washington contest, the harder Bradley
hammered Gore, calling him a closet conservative and matching him
television advertisement for television advertisement and mass
mailing for mass mailing, the more difficult the course got.
</P>
<P>
   Then over the weekend Gore dropped into the state and locked up
victory with a series of quick appearances in which he determinedly
defended his credentials as a solid Democrat and, at the same time,
proudly paraded his array of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the results were in, Bradley's campaign was fending
off questions about whether he was about to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation swept through Washington, D.C., on Tuesday that
Bradley would drop out if he failed to win in Washington state. But
Bradley's aides strenuously denied that he would quit before March
7, or that he was being advised to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This camp is working hard towards March 7 and beyond,'' said
Douglas C. Berman, Bradley's campaign chairman. ``I know everybody
wants to write a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   A top New York adviser to Bradley said he had heard speculations
of this sort all day, but attributed it to Gore's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   California, New York, Missouri, Ohio, Georgia, most of New
England, and 10 other states hold Democratic primaries or caucuses
on March 7, when nearly a third of the delegates to the Democratic
national convention will be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley announced on Tuesday that he would buy five minutes of
prime time on national television this Thursday to make a direct
appeal to voters five days before those races.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said the taped spot, which will be broadcast at
the end of the CBS news magazine ``48 Hours,'' will feature Bradley
speaking directly into a camera about why he would make the best
president of the four major candidates now running.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign's extraordinary decision to buy national television
time reflects not only Bradley's difficult straits _ he is running
well behind Gore in almost all state polls _ but also his
frustration with the small amount of media attention he has been
receiving. News coverage of the race has been dominated by the
battle between McCain and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign declined to say how much the spot would
cost. But several political consultants who buy television time for
candidates estimated that it would be about $1 million. They also
estimated that the commercial would be seen by more than seven
million people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
