<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2896 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-RDP-ART-4THLD-WRI     03-01 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-RDP-ART-4THLD-WRITETHRU-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BUSH TRIUMPHS OVER McCAIN IN VIRGINIA, NORTH DAKOTA AND (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) 
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Gov. George W. Bush won forceful victories over
Sen. John McCain in Virginia, Washington state and North Dakota on
Tuesday, picking up a large cache of delegates as well as a
considerable morale boost after his discouraging loss in Michigan a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   In this roller-coaster of a primary season, Bush's three-state
sweep raised sobering questions about McCain's potency as the
campaign moves next week to a rush of a dozen contests across the
nation, including New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   The largest delegate prize of the day _ 56 _ was here in
Virginia, where both candidates drew heavily from the voter groups
that had supported them in earlier contests for the Republican
presidential nomination. Bush captured faithful Republican voters,
as he did in his victory in South Carolina 10 days ago,
particularly conservatives and those who call themselves members of
the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won the overwhelming support of independents and
Democrats. While those voters were responsible for the Arizona
senator's first-place finishes in Michigan and New Hampshire before
that, they accounted for a much smaller proportion of the
electorate here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The results also show that the wave of publicity after McCain's
upset victory in Michigan and his fresh appeal that he was ``a
proud Reagan conservative'' were not enough to carry him over the
finish line. And McCain's blunt attacks on leaders of the religious
right on Monday failed to rouse independents and Democrats,
although the senator argued that message would play better in
upcoming states with higher proportions of moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took 53 percent of the vote in Virginia; McCain won 44
percent and Alan Keyes took 3 percent. The governor later
characterized his victory as a repudiation of McCain's drive to
paint him as a captive of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters of Virginia rejected the politics of pitting one
religion against another,'' Bush said at a rally in Cincinnati.
``This campaign is winning and we're doing it the right way. We are
uniting our party without compromising principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in central California, McCain said he had
called Bush to congratulate him on his victory in Virginia. But he
minimized the governor's accomplishment, suggesting that Bush had
only regional appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look forward to Super Tuesday when we have a broad
section, a cross-section of America, voting all on that same day,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he believed that his speech against the Christian
right on Monday had damaged him with Virginians, he replied: ``No.
We were talking nationally, not to Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his losses on Tuesday night, the returns from Washington
state contained a glimmer of good news for McCain: voters who did
not declare themselves aligned with either party were able to cast
nonbinding ballots. When those were added to the total, McCain and
Bush ran neck and neck.
</P>
<P>
   But only Republican votes can be counted toward delegates. And
while McCain can trumpet his win in the popularity contest, the
outcome in Washington was especially disappointing for him because
his campaign viewed the state _ which has often been hospitable to
insurgents _ as his best chance for victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the North Dakota caucuses, only 19 national convention
delegates were at stake. Bush won an impressive 76 percent of the
vote, McCain, 19 percent, and Keyes, 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, 12 delegates were up for grabs, about a third of
the total in the state. The rest will be picked next week.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Bush and McCain were nowhere near Virginia or
Washington as the votes were being counted underscored how the
jumble of contests next Tuesday overshadowed the voting. The
election on March 7 is tantamount to a national primary, with
Republicans going to the polls in California, New York, Ohio,
Georgia, Missouri and seven other states. As a result, the
contenders have raced from coast to coast _ and in between.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not campaigned in Virginia since Friday night. McCain
rushed out of the state early Monday afternoon after condemning Pat
Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell in a speech in Virginia Beach.
On Tuesday, as he bounced from Stockton to Fresno to Bakersfield,
McCain was clearly focused on next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is a critical state,'' he said. ``And I need to win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome here in the capital of the Confederacy was a
substantial victory for Bush because by capturing all of Virginia's
delegates to the national convention (1,034 are needed for the
nomination), he surpassed McCain in the total delegate tally. This
state has the 10th-largest share of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also trumpeted that in the last four days, Bush has
piled up delegates in Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands, Guam and
American Samoa. ``Start adding up the delegates,'' he told
reporters aboard his campaign plane this evening. ``It's been a
pretty good week.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was organized in every county in Virginia, relying on the
energetic support of the state's most-prominent elected
Republicans, particularly Gov. James S. Gilmore III and Sen. John
W. Warner, and vastly outspending McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had boasted that he would beat the ``Gilmore-Warner
machine'' just as he had toppled Gov. John M. Engler's organization
in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain just played it wrong in attacking the Gilmore-Warner
machine in Virginia,'' said Mark J. Rozell, a professor of politics
at Catholic University and an expert on Virginia politics. ``He
named probably the two most-popular figures in Virginia politics.
And by making several campaign stops in Virginia, McCain raised the
expectations for his candidacy and failed badly.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they played down the significance of the outcome on
Tuesday, McCain's aides had stepped up his budget for Virginia
after the senator's victory in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCain folks were working very hard; they bought our whole
voter file,'' said Ed Matricardi, executive director of the
Republican Party of Virginia. ``They ran a full-fledged campaign
here. The Bush people did too.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that the McCain operation said it was never particularly
serious about Virginia, Matricardi said, ``How can you advertise
heavily in the most expensive television market _ Northern Virginia
_ and say you didn't campaign here?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While McCain dismissed Bush as simply winning another Southern
state, this state is more diverse than South Carolina, from the
tobacco country in the south to the coal country in the west to the
Washington suburbs in the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know that the western tip of Virginia is farther west
than Detroit?'' Matricardi said today as he pointed to a
brightly-colored map on the wall of his office.
</P>
<P>
   But although this state is more diverse than South Carolina, it
is significantly more conservative than Michigan, and that helps
explain why Bush won. The only place McCain swamped Bush was in the
affluent Northern Virginia suburbs, a stronghold of moderates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's continued difficulty in winning significant support
from loyal Republicans may be a promising sign for Bush as the
competition turns largely to states where only Republicans can vote
in the party's primaries. More than 6 in 10 of the Virginia voters
on Tuesday described themselves as Republicans, and they
overwhelmingly backed Bush, according to a survey of voters leaving
the polls. Nearly 3 in 10 said they considered themselves
independents, and they just as overwhelmingly backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 1 in 10 voters described themselves as Democrats, and
they overwhelmingly backed McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was far more successful here than in Michigan because
voters in Virginia are more conservative. Nearly 6 in 10 of voters
here described themselves as conservatives, compared with just over
4 in 10 in Michigan. The conservative voters in Virginia backed
Bush over McCain by a margin of more than 2 to 1. Moderates, who
accounted for about 3 in 10 of the voters on Tuesday, backed McCain
over Bush by nearly the same margin.
</P>
<P>
   People who describe themselves as religious conservatives were
less crucial to Bush's victory here than in South Carolina. Two in
10 Virginia voters said they were part of the religious right
movement, and nearly 8 in 10 of those voted for Bush. In South
Carolina, more than 3 in 10 voters said they were part of the
religious right, and nearly 7 in 10 of them supported Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While the closing days of the campaign here were dominated by
bitter exchanges between the Bush and McCain camps over the
Christian right and over which candidate is the true conservative,
that may not have had much influence on the outcome because fewer
than 1 in 10 voters left their decision until Tuesday. Those who
did decide on Tuesday backed Bush overwhelmingly.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign moved aggressively to tap into hostility from
tobacco farmers about McCain's support for higher cigarette taxes
and from voters in Northern Virginia who were distressed by his
advocacy for more flights _ and more noise _ at Reagan National
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's organization delivered automated telephone calls to
10,000 residents of Northern Virginia, accusing McCain of pressing
for ``48 additional noisy flights.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, there had only been one presidential primary in
Virginia, and that was in 1988. Bush's father, George Bush,
defeated Bob Dole and Pat Robertson in that primary. Since then,
the state has picked its convention delegates through caucuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
