<HEADER>
A2901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BUSH-VIRGINIA-1S     03-01 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUSH-VIRGINIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MR. BUSH'S COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 1:
</P>
<P>
   With his sweep in Virginia, North Dakota and Washington, Gov.
George W. Bush's troubled presidential campaign has wrung an
essential victory from three disparate states. But once again Sen.
John McCain pointed up the soft spot in Bush's candidacy by drawing
strong support in Virginia and possibly elsewhere among
independents, moderates and Democratic crossovers. Bush's partisans
argued on Tuesday night that McCain's challenge to religious
fundamentalists had backfired, rallying loyal Republicans to the
governor's side. All of the results set up a tremendously important
showdown in the March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' primaries. The
battleground states of California and Ohio, where Bush leads, and
in New York, which is a toss-up, may well determine whether McCain
will be remembered as a transforming or a transitory figure in the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, Vice President Al Gore's victory in
Washington state threatens yet another blow to former Sen. Bill
Bradley's candidacy. Bradley needed at least a credible showing
against Gore in order to revive his chances in New York and
California, where he has been running behind. A bad defeat when all
the votes in Washington are counted could feed pressures on him to
withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   For both parties, Tuesday's voting set the stage for a more
nationalized phase of the nominating process. Republicans
everywhere are wondering whether McCain's daring attempt to
redefine his party is an act of historic farsightedness or
self-destruction. The party's establishment is working hard to push
Bush to the nomination, and his triple win will restore their
wavering faith. But they are not yet sure whether to ignore
McCain's disturbing message that catering to religious
conservatives is becoming an outdated strategy, especially outside
the Sun Belt.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's success so far has arisen from his ability to set the
terms of the debate. To that end, it was smart of him to reverse
his decision to skip the final debate before the March 7 round of
primaries. By agreeing to participate from a live hookup in New
York, McCain shores up his support in New York and the New England
states that vote on Super Tuesday. McCain's future may depend on
how much strength he shows in those states, given Bush's expected
appeal in the Southern states voting that day.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia, a keystone state of the GOP's Sun Belt base, took
regional revenge on McCain for his attacks on Pat Robertson, Jerry
Falwell, Bob Jones University and other icons of the religious
right. McCain wants his party to hold the votes of Bible Belt
Republicans without following their every dictate on policy. In
that sense, he was betting that sacrificing Virginia to Bush would
strengthen him among moderates next week. The loss of Washington,
where moderates are dominant, casts a shadow over that goal.
Tuesday, indeed, belonged to Bush as the undisputed champion of the
voter blocs that have dominated the GOP for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   With the lines so clearly drawn, no one will have trouble
reading the results over the next two weeks. McCain must hope his
party is ready for a more moderate and inclusive kind of
conservatism than the one that gave Bush his victories on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
