<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2903 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS2-LADN-WRIT     03-01 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS2-LADN-WRITETHROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN BIG REGULAR-SEASON SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Somewhere, it seemed, the James Naismith trophy
must have been jiggling in its case.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime, down the road a bit, there will be playoff games with
less electricity than the one played here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, a game with no long-lasting stakes to speak of took on
the dramatic proportions of an NBA championship series.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe it was appropriate, considering the league's two best
teams were going head to head for the final time this season,
battling for control of their division, their conference and the
rights to the NBA's best record as of March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriate, too, that the Los Angeles Lakers and Portland Trail
Blazers played this ultrahyped event right down to the wire, where
the Lakers pulled out a 90-87 victory before a sold-out sea of red
shirts and red faces at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal scored a game-high 23 points and hit 9 of 13
free throws as the Lakers extended their winning streak to 12,
grabbed the NBA's best record at 46-11 and pulled a game ahead of
the Blazers in the West.
</P>
<P>
   They also evened the regular-season series at 2-2, snapped a
losing streak at the Rose Garden at seven games and ended the
Blazers' home winning streak at 16.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for one night's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big win for us,'' said Glen Rice, who chose the upbeat
occasion to break his two-week silence with the media. ``I think
all the games are very important for us. We just try to go out
there and treat them all the same. I'm sure down the road this
game's going to come back and have a lot more meaning, but right
now it's just another game that we've won. I think it's definitely
going to help us mentally, knowing that we can come here and beat
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   That they did was a testament to defense and unheralded bench
play.
</P>
<P>
   The deep Blazers had four players score in double figures, but
their vaunted reserves were outscored by the Lakers' reserves
25-18. And Portland, the league's best-shooting team, struggled to
hit 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen had 19 points but was 7 for 18 from the field.
Arvydas Sabonis went 6 for 15. Steve Smith, 5 for 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the game was played rather high intensity,
energy-wise,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``They got off to a
good start, they had a fourth-quarter run that I thought was pushed
a lot by the energy in the building. We had an 11-point lead, that
kind of carried us through the fourth quarter. . . . It wasn't an
`A' game by the team, but we did a good defensive job.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant shook off early foul trouble to finish with 22
points and seven rebounds and was the only other Laker to score in
double figures. Rice and Brian Shaw chipped in nine points each,
and the Lakers shot 44.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It all came down to a frantic conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   After losing leads of 10 and 11 points, the Lakers clung to a
one- point advantage after Bryant's go-ahead free throws with two
minutes to go. Ron Harper and O'Neal each hit 1 of 2 from the line
to make it 88-85 with 24.3 seconds left. The Blazers' last gasp
ended when Pippen missed a 26-footer. Smith grabbed the rebound and
tossed up a wild desperation shot from the corner that came nowhere
close.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when O'Neal was just 7 for 17 from the field, Jackson
said his free-throw shooting was the key to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I concentrate, I shoot 'em like Jerry West,'' O'Neal
said. ``Whenever I don't concentrate, I shoot them like Wilt
(Chamberlain).''
</P>
<P>
   Portland's usual array of big bodies (minus Brian Grant, out
with a foot injury) kept O'Neal from dominating. But the Lakers did
an equally good job of holding Rasheed Wallace (15 points, 7 for
16) in check.
</P>
<P>
   As if the game needed extra hype, the NBA put a historical
footnote on it: Never before had two teams faced each other with
matching 11-game winning streaks on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a bigger game in the NBA, in my history of the
game, in 33 years,'' said Jackson, ``where two teams, almost 60
games into the season, are tied and they have the best record in
the league, and they're still thumping it out in a divisional race.
I just haven't seen anything quite this dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   And does Jackson still think, as he predicted, the winner of
this game will win the division? ``Yeah,'' he said, ``I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
