<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2914 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     03-01 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDE S.F.'S TROLLEY INTO L.A.'S PAST
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ The new palm trees along the Embarcadero, tied
up for months, have let down their fronds, and the old waterfront
is starting to settle into its new look, just in time for a big
weekend.
<P>
   Saturday and Sunday, the vintage F Line trolleys will finally
begin to rumble along the Embarcadero from Market Street to
Fisherman's Wharf, and we'll be going back to the future.
</P>
<P>
   But the F Line will finally be rolling bayside, and the cars
will be staffed with volunteer docents from the Market Street RR
and S.F. Tour Guide Guild, Jean Feilmoser of the Guild tells me.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the ``Tour'' part scare you away, Mr. and Ms. San
Francisco. You don't have to be a tourist to enjoy a pleasant ride
along a section of the waterfront that is starting to look like a
living postcard _ fronds down, trolleys up, cobblestones gleaming.
</P>
<P>
   If Hollywood is searching for a location for period movies set
in Los Angeles in the '30s and '40s, it knows where to come. We
could paint a few more of the F Line trolleys red, to simulate the
old L.A. Red Car, the Pacific Electric streetcar line that once
snaked 1,150 miles through the City of the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I saw a Red Car,'' says my travel guru, Seymour
Seitz, ``was in `Who Framed Roger Rabbit' _ which should have been
called `Who Killed Wapid Twansit.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In L.A., the streetcar killer was the Big Oil/Tire/Auto axis
that bought out the streetcar lines and ripped up the tracks, which
made it hard for the trolleys to steer. Thus was ushered in the
golden era of road rage, drive-by shootings and drive-thru fine
dining.
</P>
<P>
   Following in L.A.'s tire tracks, San Francisco sold out, too. In
'57, Big Oil/Tire/Auto bought out the Bay Bridge Key System
Electrical RR and shut it down, which was in sync with the city's
own systematic elimination of cable cars and streetcars. Rail
travel became tres uncool.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're reversing the trend. Let's get ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   POOR DARRYL STRAWBERRY of the Yankees, flunked another cocaine
test, despite all the time he'd spent studying.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl had been scheduled to host a fund-raising event for a
Florida boys and girls' club, and the club is trying to decide,
should they have him host the event anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Straw is no role model, but say this about him: Over the
years, he has kept a lot of street drugs from falling into the
hands of youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   IN OTHER SPORTS NEWS: I'm still not able to confirm the rumor
that figure skater Tonya Harding tossed that hubcap at her
boyfriend because he told her, ``You skate like Marty McSorley.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE RAIN COMING, and Cuffs Corbett says, ``Hell with it, I'm
taking the brick out of my toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad I'm too young to know what he's talking about.
</P>
<P>
   DIGNIFIED DINGBAT: Jean (Edith Bunker) Stapleton is starring as
Mrs. Roosevelt in her one-woman ``Eleanor: Her Secret Journey''
(Marines Memorial).
</P>
<P>
   Dining at John's Grill, Stapleton was heard loudly proclaiming
that San Francisco is the best theater town in America.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it: We're No. 1! Woohoo!
</P>
<P>
   EWWWW. Cary Sekoff says he was watching the Channel 5 news
Tuesday morning, and leading into a commercial break was a teaser
for ``Bad Stuff,'' a news expose on restaurant meat contaminated
with E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Then, boom, into a commercial for Carrows restaurants and their
big $8.99 sirloin special.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS ILLUSTRATED's swimsuit issue is out, and this year's big
tech breakthrough is a pair of 3-D glasses inside each magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Which removes much of the dignity and subtlety that men strive
for in perusing the photographs.
</P>
<P>
   But at least SI is coming to terms with a widespread problem _
that a lot of their readers are leersighted.
</P>
<P>
   MORNING CALM, the in-flight magazine of Korean Air, informs its
readers that there is a train from SFO to downtown S.F., the fare
is $1.75 and the trip takes 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   How come nobody told us about this mystery train? What's it
called, the Disorient Express?
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC T-SHIRT: When Mark McGwire was on his record home-run
binge in '98, he reportedly hit homers No. 48 through 70 while
wearing a Bechelli's Restaurant T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Bechelli's is McGwire's favorite a.m. protein-loading zone when
he's playing in the Bay Area (he starts with a 10-egg-white
omelet), and owner Pat Bechelli gave Mac some T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   So McGwire autographed the lucky shirt and sent it back to
Bechelli, who is auctioning it online via Sothebys.Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Estimated to fetch ... $200,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is scary that someone will pay a quarter-mil for a used
T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Comforting, though. I've shaken hands with McGwire many times,
so I figure if I ever get in a financial bind, I can sell my right
hand.
</P>
<P>
   MANY STATES support capital punishment, but there are varying
degrees of gung-ho-ness, and George W. Bush's Texas seems to rank
fairly high on that scale.
</P>
<P>
   So if W is elected president, the suggestion here is for at
least a change in terminology. Convicted criminals won't be
executed, they'll be bushwhacked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
