<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2926 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-PRIMARIES-ROUNDUP-SFC     03-01 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-ROUNDUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BEATS MCCAIN IN THREE STATES; GORE TROUNCES BRADLEY IN 
 WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush picked up decisive
victories in three states Tuesday with rock-solid support from
Republican voters, dealing a harsh blow to Arizona Sen. John
McCain's insurgent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore easily beat Bill Bradley in
Washington Tuesday, an ominous development for the struggling
campaign of the former New Jersey senator.
</P>
<P>
   With 56 delegates at stake, Virginia's Republican primary was
the prize in Tuesday's contests. Bush took 53 percent of the vote
to McCain's 44 percent, while Alan Keyes got the remaining 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also trounced McCain _ 76 percent to 19 percent _ in North
Dakota's caucuses, and he scored a win in the first round of
Washington's GOP primary, where he captured the support of nearly
60 percent of voters.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, the Washington state vote was a symbolic one, as
delegates will not be chosen until party caucuses next week. But
Bradley, who has not won a primary, had hoped to score a symbolic
victory a week before Super Tuesday primaries.
</P>
<P>
   With 81 percent of Washington precincts reporting, Gore was
beating Bradley by a wide margin, garnering 68 percent of the vote
and leaving Bradley with just 31.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spent five days campaigning in Washington, but recently
his campaign had shifted from saying a victory was needed to saying
that a strong performance would do.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Bradley's campaign tried to put the best light
they could on the numbers. ``We lost,'' said Bradley spokesman Eric
Hauser. ``We're a little disappointed. But there are some things
that went quite well ... the energy that we generated in Washington
in five days will carry us forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauser said Bradley is looking ahead to March 7 and beyond and
there are no plans to drop out. He also denied that some advisors
are urging Bradley to give up the race. ``There is a unanimous
desire within the campaign to move agressively forward to March
7,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will work almost non-stop over the next week, with
the debate in Los Angeles tonight, a five-minute national
advertisement tomorrow night and campaigning back on the East coast
this weekend, Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an uphill fight _ but it's been an uphill fight for 15
months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, exit polls showed that Bush won resoundingly among
GOP voters, with McCain pulling in just 1 in 4 Republicans. But
McCain pummeled Bush among independents, 63 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's Christian conservatives voted 8 to 1 for Bush; Bush
also won 2 to 1 among moderately &LR;  conservatives. Women favored Bush
60 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Just one day ago, McCain had chosen southern Virginia _ the home
of the Christian Coalition _ to lash out at televangelists Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell as ``agents of intolerance'' in a
daring attempt to broaden his appeal to swing voters in this
Republican bastion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had hoped for an upset in Virginia, which would send Bush
into a tailspin going into Super Tuesday when 16 states, including
California, New York and Ohio choose delegates, with Republicans
selecting more than half the 1,034 needed to win their nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was Bush who hauled in all of Virginia's 56
delegates and much-needed momentum after last week's defeat in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush vaulted ahead of McCain in the delegate count, with the
Texas governor winning 77 delegates to McCain's nine Tuesday to
lead 170 to 105.
</P>
<P>
   In the North Dakota caucuses, where 19 delegates were at stake,
Bush picked up 14 delegates, McCain four and Keyes one.
</P>
<P>
   And in Washington, Bush picked up seven delegates to McCain's
five in the first round of that state's GOP primary. The remaining
25 delegates will be chosen Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With 65 percent of precincts reporting, Bush had 156,840 of the
GOP vote, or 59 percent, McCain had 100,982 votes, or 38 percent,
and Keyes had 2 percent. ``Tonight, we are one step closer to
victory,'' Bush said. ``One step closer to a united party, and the
Clinton-Gore administration is one step closer to the exit door.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush declared that his campaign is ``winning the debate of
substance _ the contest of ideas. Republicans and independents are
rallying to our cause because we are speaking to their hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Stockton, McCain retorted,``I congratulate
him on his victory. ``It seems as if he has a Southern strategy
here,'' a veiled reference to Bush's strength among Christian
conservatives. ``We'll look forward to Super Tuesday when we'll
have a broad section of Americans voting ... all on that same
day.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain insisted he is the GOP's best hope in the fall to take on
Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, and rescue the GOP from its
electoral defeats in 1996 and 1998. ``I am the one who can beat Al
Gore,'' McCain told a rally. ``I am the one who can bring in
independents.''
</P>
<P>
   Some polls show McCain surging ahead of Gore in a general
election, while a Bush-Gore contest is close.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's challenge has forced Bush to the right and made
religion a focal point of the GOP race so far, even  &LR; though Bush
had intended at the outset of his campaign intended  &LR; to court
moderates as a ``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   But after McCain's independent-fueled win in New Hampshire, Bush
courted the Christian right in South Carolina. After Bush won in
South Carolina, McCain attacked Bush in Michigan for speaking at
Bob Jones University, which espouses anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called McCain's attack on Robertson divisive and accused
his rival of injecting religion into the campaign. Bush also
claimed to be the rightful heir to Ronald Reagan _ a claim McCain
has been making at every stop _ saying Reagan ``had an optimistic
agenda, as I do,'' rather than a ``spiteful agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the McCain campaign scrutinized Tuesday's results,
campaign manager Rick Davis told reporters that the senator's
economic message had not gotten through, even though McCain had
chosen to make Pat  &LR; Robertson the issue in Virginia. ``We haven't
been saying enough about Social Security,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, the candidates took wildly different paths courting
the state's voters.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did McCain choose Virginia to attack Robertson, but he
also went out of his way to taunt Virginia's top Republican
officials, Gov. James Gilmore and Sen. John Warner, telling a crowd
in Alexandria on Sunday, ``I say to the Gilmore-Warner machine,
babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had campaigned in Virginia with Gilmore, Warner and popular
former Gov. George Allen at his side, courting votes in Virginia's
high-tech corridor at America Online headquarters in Vienna, and
then attending a GOP party banquet in at the capitol in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   McCain targeted the moderate suburban voters of northern
Virginia, hoping to draw independents, Democrats and former
supporters of Ross Perot, while trying At the same time, he tried
to appeal to conservatives by declaring himself a ``Reagan
Republican'' and a true conservative battling special interests in
nearby Washington. McCain also drew a heavy following among
veterans who are heavily concentrated near Washington and the big
naval base at Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said that even though Bush lost
among independents by 30 percentage points, the result was better
than in New Hampshire, where Bush picked up just 19 percent of
independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as we continue to beat Sen.ator McCain by such an
overwhelming margin among Republicans, and continue to make inroads
among independents, it's going to be impossible for John McCain to
defeat us,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   When the campaign started, the Virginia and Washington primaries
were considered little more than blips between the opening curtain
in New Hampshire and the big primaries next Tuesday. Instead, they
became critical and hard fought battles in a major war for the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Virginia and Washington primaries were open to voters
in both parties, giving extraordinary weight to independents and
party crossovers. The effect was magnified by the excitement
generated by the tight Republican contest that drew in voters who
might otherwise have ignored the race.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia ballot had only Republicans, and Virginians who
voted were required to ``pledge'' not to vote in the later
Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won among voters without a college education 2-to-1, while
the two candidates were close among those with a college degree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
