<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2927 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CAMPAIGN-CALIFORNIA-S     03-01 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN INTENSIFIES HIS ATTACK ON RELIGIOUS RIGHT; REVERSES 
 HIMSELF ON CALIFORNIA DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI, LYNDA GLEDHILL and JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO _ Courting California's victory-starved Republicans, Sen.
John McCain ramped up his talk against leaders of the religious
right Tuesday and, in an abrupt turnabout, announced that he has
agreed to a satellite TV debate with Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, riding his ``Straight Talk Express'' through
California's GOP- rich Central Valley on a three-day state swing,
attacked evangelists Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell as ``the
forces of evil'' dividing the GOP. The Arizona senator continued to
pound his message of being a ``Reagan Republican,'' telling
enthusiastic crowds, ``I'm willing to take on the forces of evil
... (who) have driven us to the extreme right.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's decision to participate in the satellite television
debate with Bush tomorrow night was a sharp about-face. As late as
Tuesday morning, he insisted to reporters aboard his bus that he
would not take part in the event.
</P>
<P>
   But during a later a press conference, McCain changed direction
and said he would change his schedule to accommodate the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's camp, too, agreed to the face-off. ``We will debate in
Thursday's debate, but the debate planners are still working out
the details,'' said Margita Thompson, a Bush campaign spokeswoman.
She said it was still unclear whether Bush would be in California
for the event, or if he, too, would make the debate via remote.
</P>
<P>
   As he rode through the Central Valley last night, McCain called
Bush to congratulate him on the Virginia victory, but he said he
did not believe the losses would affect his success in the March 7
``Super Tuesday'' primaries, which include California's.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's three-day California trip came only a week before the
primary here, as polls show that the senator has a formidable sales
job ahead with state Republicans _ and that he is trailing by a
double-digit margin.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain farmed the state's Central Valley for votes, Vice
President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley were also
in California, preparing for their debate tonight and trying to
pick up momentum for next week's all-important election.
</P>
<P>
   A confident-sounding Gore spent the morning in Cudahy, a heavily
Latino community a few miles from downtown Los Angeles, where he
worked on themes he plans to use against the Republicans in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, lagging far behind in the polls, hopes the debate,
along with a late rush of advertising and campaigning, can boost
his chances of victory in California.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's toughest talk came from McCain, who made his
appeal directly to California Republicans, arguing that only he can
give them what they want most: the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to put California back in the winning column,''
McCain said in Stockton. ``I now firmly believe that I, only, can
make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain argued that ``the voters fully believe I am prepared for
combat with the vice president, and George Bush is not.''
</P>
<P>
   While registered voters can cast ballots for any candidate,
regardless of party affiliation, in California's open primary, only
GOP votes will count in the winner-take-all Republican primary. The
highest GOP vote-getter will be awarded the 162 GOP delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Field Poll released this week shows McCain trailing
Bush by 20 points among party faithful, even as they show that
McCain is viewed more positively by all voters and _ unlike Bush _
leads both Gore and Bradley in head-to-head matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited, I'm enthusiastic, I'm hopeful,'' McCain said.
``Yes, I need to win California. Yes, it's a critical state.
California has enormous impact on the nomination, and I need to win
_ I think we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   In his harsh talk against the two pre-eminent Christian
conservative leaders, McCain was reprising a speech he made this
weekend in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reject individuals such as Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell,
who take our party in the wrong direction. We're the party of
Abraham Lincoln, not Pat Robertson,'' McCain told a town hall
meeting in Stockton. ``We are the party of Ronald Reagan and not
Bob Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   California also is a do-or-die state for Bradley. The former
senator hopes to cut into Gore's margin with a prime-time,
five-minute-long television ad that will be broadcast on CBS at
10:54 p.m. tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign ad, still under production, will include Bradley
talking directly to the camera, telling people why he would be a
good president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always felt the best way to communicate with voters is
simply and directly and without adornment,'' said Eric Hauser, a
Bradley spokesman. ``This is a good way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign said it didn't have any choice but to go up against
a brand-new episode of ``ER,'' one of the country's most popular
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sweeps month,'' said Hauser, adding that it was hard to
find network time for the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's message in California is that there is still plenty of
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Californians don't make up their mind until the last week,''
Bradley said in San Francisco Tuesday. ``I think it is possible to
move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's plodding campaign style does not seem to be
energizing many voters. At San Francisco General Hospital Tuesday
morning, he spoke on gun control, one of his main campaign themes.
He repeated his call for registration of all handguns and mandatory
trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 hospital employees gathered around as Bradley spoke,
but the event in the hospital's cafeteria competed with the sounds
of employee pagers and workers eating breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's appearance in Cudahy drew more than 600 people to a local
gymnasium to hear the vice president talk about the need for
improvements in education, health care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's tragic shooting in Michigan, in which a 6-year-old
girl was killed at school by a classmate, turned Gore to the
subject of guns and violence.
</P>
<P>
   When first-graders can get a gun and shoot their playmates at
school, it's past time for something to be done, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long will it take before we say to opponents ... of
commonsense (gun control) measures `Enough is enough. We're going
to protect our communities and our children?' '' Gore asked.
</P>
<P>
   He scorched the National Rifle Association for its opposition to
mandatory trigger locks and told the cheering crowd that it is up
to them to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get guns out of the hands of people who shouldn't
have them: criminals, children, students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd included dozens of military veterans and young
children from a nearby school. Around the students were
Spanish-language signs saying ``The children of Cudahy (love) Al
Gore,'' and ``With Al Gore, the children will have a better
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president pointed to those children as he wound up his
20-minute-long speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children deserve to grow up in communities with clean
air, clean water and a bright future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stop in the 1.2-square-mile community underscored the
importance Gore puts on California's growing Latino vote. With him
at the speech were Art Torres, chairman of the state Democratic
Party, local Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, whose father represented
East Los Angeles in Congress for decades, and Los Angeles County
Supervisor Gloria Molina, one of the state's most powerful Latina
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   (Carla Marinucci reported from the Central Valley, Lynda
Gledhill from San Francisco and John Wildermuth from Cudahy.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
