<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 03:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2928 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEMOCRATS-CAMPAIGN-SF     03-01 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BRADLEY AND GORE STRUGGLE TO STAND OUT  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the past is any guide, Wednesday night's
Democratic debate will feature indignant exchanges and fierce
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone but an avid loyalist, the hostile jargon may seem like
a fight over milk chocolate vs. dark chocolate. Each has a distinct
flavor and a stable core of devotees, but for most connoisseurs,
the similarities far outweigh the differences.
</P>
<P>
   Both Al Gore and Bill Bradley are pro-choice, pro-trade, pro-gun
control centrist Democrats, with long records of public service and
strong ties to the party's liberal base. Both have strong support
from environmentalists and labor unions, and they are regarded more
highly for their intellect than their charisma.
</P>
<P>
   To choose between the two requires either a deep understanding
of narrow policy nuances or a decision based on something that goes
beyond issues.
</P>
<P>
   Did Vice President Gore vote for the 1984 Siljander Amendment
which defined ``unborn children'' as people? Did Bill Bradley vote
for experimental school vouchers? Is Gore a ``fighter'' or a
vestige of ``entrenched power?'' Is Bradley a ``quitter'' or a
practitioner of a ``new kind of politics?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy differences between these two candidates are
minimal,'' said California Gov. Gray Davis, who, like most elected
officials, has staked his claim on the vice president. ``I think Al
Gore has earned the nomination of his party based on his exemplary
performance in the (Clinton) administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's forum in Los Angeles is the final face-to-face
confrontation for the two men before Tuesday, when California and
more than a dozen other states hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign has revealed how different they are,'' said
Thomas Mann, director of government studies at the Brookings
Institution in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said that Bradley's notion of governing is reminiscent of
Franklin Roosevelt, addressing problems with ``bold steps and
transforming ideas.'' Gore more closely resembles President
Clinton's style of moving to the center and proposing ``modest,
bite-sized solutions,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump, Gore has been consistently more aggressive,
raising his voice to underscore his passion and winning the
endorsement of political allies and organizations that have long
courted his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The differences between Sen. Bradley and Vice President Gore
are very minimal in relation to the issues,'' said David Smith of
the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay lobbying group,
which endorsed Gore two weeks ago. ``But with Gore we have
longevity and commitment. He's been fighting since the beginning of
the (Clinton) administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is a more deliberate and cautious speaker who has
promoted what he calls ``deeply held beliefs'' over flashy sound
bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen him confront money, power and special interests
when few were prepared to make the fight,'' said Rep. George
Miller, D-Calif., who endorsed Bradley in December. ``I have seen
him stick with his principles against tremendous odds and
prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither seems to be comfortable with politicking. Gore's ability
to connect with voters is more evident in person than on
television, though it pales in comparison to President Clinton.
Bradley often seems downright uncomfortable with small talk and
glad-handing.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gore and Bradley had remarkably similar voting records
during the eight years they served together in the Senate _
Congressional Quarterly found they voted together about
three-quarters of the time _ Bradley has staked out more
comprehensive and liberal positions on several social issues over
the course of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On health care, Bradley favors replacing Medicaid with a more
sweeping plan of subsidized insurance that would cost about $65
billion a year and provide insurance to 95 percent of all
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has advocated a more incremental approach costing about $25
billion a year to expand Medicaid and Medicare and guarantee
coverage for children.
</P>
<P>
   In one of their few major areas of disagreement, Bradley, who
voted against the U.S. intervention in Iraq in 1991, does not favor
any increase in the military budget. Gore, who voted in favor of
Iraq involvement, favors an increase by as much as $20 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue of disagreement is on campaign finance reform, a
central part of the platform of Bradley, who maintains that
big-money interests have caused gridlock on Capitol Hill. He
supports a ban on soft-money donations and has criticized Gore for
advocating restrictions on soft money while directing fund-raisers
to solicit such cash.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of recent Democratic fund-raising scandals, Gore has
not highlighted the issue but has said he would make campaign
finance reform a priority as president. Both candidates offered to
pass up soft money in the general election if the Republican
nominee did the same.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first Democratic debate in New Hampshire last fall,
each meeting between the two has grown more barbed and
confrontational. If the words get harsh, it is useful to remember
that the two centrists &LR;  Democrats are elbowing for space from
within a very small ideological band.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
