<HEADER>
A3065 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u k BC-MARRY-A-MILLIONAIRE-N     03-01 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRY-A-MILLIONAIRE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION VERITE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By AMY WU  
 &HT;    The Fox Network's controversial game show ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire'' proved that, in America, love has lost any shred
of innocence it once had. It has become something to be selected
and chosen like a commodity.
 &HT;    As an Asian-American female, I have noticed how this dynamic _
women ``falling in love'' with men who have large wallets _ has
infiltrated the Asian community. Wealthy Asian males now have their
choice of mate across racial boundaries.
 &HT;    In a new book titled ``Asian-Americans: Intermarriage and the
Social Construction of Love'' (Beacon Press), demographer Larry
Hajime Shinagawa writes that more and more Asian-American men are
marrying outside their ethnic group _ something that was once very
rare. Part of the reason comes down to dollars and cents.
 &HT;    How so? Because Asian males have a reputation for being
wealthier than other ethnic groups, and those dollar signs are
attracting women of all colors.
 &HT;    Don't get me wrong _ many men find Asian women alluring, but for
very different reasons.
 &HT;    As a young, Chinese-American woman, race has played a major part
in all my relationships. At 15, I swore I would marry for love. At
17, when being Asian was no longer so fashionable, I swore I would
only marry a white man. My goal was to become as ``American'' as
possible.
 &HT;    At 21, I traveled to Hong Kong to work as a journalist, and
while I was there I witnessed firsthand how fashionable it was for
white men to date and marry Asian girls.
 &HT;    One of my white male colleagues, who had been dating an Asian
airline stewardess for three months, offered an explanation: ``I
like the way Asian women look, how polite they are and how they
seem so demure and innocent.''
 &HT;    The Asian women who I encountered in Hong Kong restaurants and
public places dutifully leaned against their lovers for support and
giggled with their hands over their mouths. They were thin-boned,
longhaired and looked like high school girls. And on the flip side,
these Asian women viewed white men as coveted prizes.
 &HT;    I also befriended an American music executive whose girlfriend
was 20 years his junior _ a local girl who looked every inch the
Asian princess. He lived in an impressive penthouse overlooking the
city and took her out to dinner every night.
 &HT;    She giggled and charmed him, and he was delighted. In return,
she got to live in a penthouse and had a closet filled with Gucci.
I only hope it was true love, but I have my doubts.
 &HT;    In Hong Kong, my adolescent dream of being considered completely
American became a reality. In fact, I met many men _ both Asian and
Caucasian _ who thought I was too American. I am not a Suzy Wong
look-alike. I laugh freely. I ask many questions. I am opinionated.
Most of all, I like talking about current events.
 &HT;    I once went on a date with a local guy, an accountant who drove
a Mercedes-Benz. His interest in me soared after he discovered I
was a transplanted New Yorker. My colleagues who were local women
coaxed me into going out with him even though I thought he was
about as exciting as a brick.
 &HT;    ``He has a Benz, a big bank account. He'll take care of you for
the rest of your life,'' they said, perhaps secretly hoping I would
drop him like a hot potato so that one of them could scoop him up.
 &HT;    After two dates he tired of me. I knew too much about the stock
market and current events. I explained I loved to travel to exotic
places. I didn't lean against his arm, fetch his slippers and wash
his laundry. It was at that point I had decided that I would rather
spend my time with a starving poet than a wealthy numbers-cruncher.
 &HT;    Call me a traditionalist, but I think the new love landscape is
shameful and bizarre _ and Fox's alarmingly popular TV debacle is a
perfect example. True Love only lasts when fate is allowed to do
its work, and when the feelings aren't tainted by other motives.
 &HT;    For now, I think I'll stick with feng shui and fortunetellers.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Amy Wu is a free-lance writer who spent three years as a
journalist in Hong Kong.)
 &HT;    -----
 c. 2000 Amy Wu 
