<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3071 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN02-COX     03-01 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families battling insurers' refusals
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At first, Angie King didn't believe it when her
husband, Mark, suspected their 6-month-old daughter, Erica,
couldn't hear. ``I dismissed it,'' she recalled, ``because there
was no family history.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, however, the couple observed Erica.
When the dog barked, Erica didn't startle. When they clanged pots
and pans, Erica didn't react.
</P>
<P>
   That brought them crashing ``back to reality,'' Mrs. King
recalled, and forced them to confront a harsh truth: Erica suffered
from profound hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial reaction was shock,'' Mrs. King said. ``As a mom,
you feel grief that part of your hope for that child suddenly
disappears. My biggest fears were, 'What if there's a fire?' and
'She'll never be able to hear me say, 'I love you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The family needed a miracle, and they got one: A cochlear
implant placed in Erica's ear in May. The nickel-sized implant
serves as an artificial inner ear.
</P>
<P>
   Since the procedure, Erica, now 4, marvels at sounds most of us
never notice: a bird on the roof; a bathroom door squeaking open; a
refrigerator's hum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would never know that she's deaf,'' Mrs. King said.
</P>
<P>
   The implant has given Erica nearly normal hearing. Her speech
and language skills went from ``age equivalency,'' her father said,
to well beyond it. ``With the implants she just zipped ahead,''
Mark King said, ``and we were ecstatic about that.''
</P>
<P>
   They were less than ecstatic about the $53,000 bill their
insurance company, Benicorp Insurance Corp. of Indianapolis, has
refused to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Their battle against their daughter's condition has proven in
many ways less formidable than their battle with their own insurer.
The Kings have sued Benicorp, saying the Ohio Department of
Insurance ruled that the implant was covered by the family policy.
</P>
<P>
   Their dilemma is now twofold: younger daughter, Jaime, 17
months, has the same condition. Will any hospital perform the
surgery with a pending bill from the other procedure? Can they
really go $100,000 into debt?
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are determined to find a way: ``If we have to sell the
house, we'll do it; that's how important it is to us for our
daughters to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Their case has received national publicity, including an
appearance on ``Good Morning America.'' After Mrs. King contacted
Gov. George W. Bush's domestic policy adviser, the Bush team called
the couple Monday night. They wanted the Kings to meet the
candidate Tuesday afternoon during a campaign swing through the
Columbus suburb of Westerville.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings met privately with Bush before the rally, along with
four other families.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' impressions?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got my vote. Need I say more?'' Mrs. King said.
</P>
<P>
   Was it genuine empathy, or politicking as usual?
</P>
<P>
   ``His track record stands for itself because Texas has numerous
programs for the hearing-impaired,'' Mrs. King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush told us that Texas has an appeals board where
you can appeal your insurance company's decision, and that Texas is
the only state in the country where you can sue your HMO.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, however, won't need to rely on George W. Bush's
intercession. They're relying on their own considerable resources
and determination. Mrs. King, a stay-at-home mother who spent 10
years as an insurance adjuster, has already formed her own advocacy
group, Hear US, with its own Web site (www.hearus.org).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, but I honestly believe all things happen for
a reason,'' Mrs. King said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
