<HEADER>
A3073 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-COX-     03-01 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-COX-FILE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 1 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was Sam Hill, as in the expression ``What in Sam Hill?''
</P>
<P>
   A: Edwin V. Mitchell mentions Col. Samuel Hill of Guilford,
Conn., in his Encyclopedia of American Politics (1946), but whether
there was such a person in reality is a matter of conjecture.
Legend has it that this man Hill perpetually ran for office, which
eventually gave rise to the phrase ``go like Sam Hill'' or ``run
like Sam Hill.'' But no evidence of his existence could be found in
any historical record, according to the Facts on File Encyclopedia
of Word and Phrase Origins.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the absence of such record, it concludes that Sam Hill
must remain ``a personified euphemism our Puritan ancestors used
for `hell.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Pope John Paul II's frailty has caused rumors of his possible
resignation someday. Has a pope ever resigned? If so, who was the
last one?
</P>
<P>
   A: Popes have resigned, ``but certainly not in modern times,''
said Bill Ryan of the U.S. Catholic Conference in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Wilson at the Archdiocese of Atlanta said the last to do so
was Celestine V, who was in his 80s when he was elected pope on
July 5, 1294. He accepted only because the papacy had been vacant
for two years. Although a holy man, he lacked administrative
ability and considered the papacy a distraction from his ascetic
struggle for salvation. After encountering great difficulty,
Celestine V realized it would be dangerous for the church and for
his soul if he continued as pope. So, after consulting the
cardinals, he resigned on Dec. 13, 1294.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My cable TV company is replacing the wire cable with fiber
cable. Rather than dig up the whole neighborhood, the workers are
using a process in which the new cable is forced underground with
water. Can you explain the technique?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are two ways to bury these lines: directional bore and
trenching. In trenching, large holes are dug in order to place the
lines next to other utilities in the public right-of-way. This can
cause minor damage to sod, landscaping and the roadway.
</P>
<P>
   With a directional bore, a long rod goes into the ground,
shooting water to loosen the dirt. When the rod is pulled back, it
threads the conduit back through a hole for running fiber optics
and cable. This causes less damage to property and allows workers
to go several hundred feet with only limited disruption.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What causes a sonic boom?
</P>
<P>
   A: The noise, which to a person on the ground sound like a
thunderclap, results from a shock wave produced by the object _
usually an airplane. A shock wave is a pressure disturbance that
builds up around the craft flying at a supersonic speed. It results
from a change in the air flow pattern around the craft's leading
edges. Sonic booms can't hurt people, but may damage plaster walls
and break windows.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could President Clinton stay out one term and then run for
president again? Or is he limited to two terms, whether consecutive
or not?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 22nd Amendment to the Constitution, enacted in 1951,
reads: ``No person shall be elected to the office of president more
than twice, and no person who has held the office of president, or
acted as president for more than two years of a term to which some
other person was elected president, shall be elected to the office
of the president more than once.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible for a person to serve for more than two terms only
if he or she succeeds to the office and serves less than two years
of the departed president's four-year term, then is elected two
times on his or her own. But serving two terms, then staying out
for a round or two, and trying again, isn't permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting: Dwight Eisenhower, the first president to whom the
22nd Amendment applied, would have liked to run for a third term in
1960, according to John Eisenhower, his son and deputy chief of
staff. And Ronald Reagan, in his second term, campaigned for a
constitutional amendment to repeal the two-term limit, although not
in such a way as to apply to him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm 64 and working. What can you tell me about a new bill
that is being introduced in Congress that would allow people 65 and
older to draw their Social Security benefits and continue to work,
without a limit on the amount of money they can earn? How can we
encourage passage of this bill?
</P>
<P>
   A: The bill, which would eliminate the Social Security earnings
test that reduces benefits for workers 65 to 69 has been approved
by the House Ways and Means subcommittee on Social Security. Those
retirees now are penalized $1 in benefits for every $3 in earnings
above $17,000. A vote before the full House could come March 2.
After that, it would go to the Senate for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr. (R-Fla.) said he expects quick passage in
the House, but expressed some concern that when it goes to the
Senate, it could become a vehicle for other Social Security
changes. President Clinton, who called for repeal of the earnings
test two years ago, has said he would sign the repeal if Congress
sends him a ``clean bill'' without other provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Constituents always should call or write their representative or
senator to indicate an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security Commissioner Kenneth Apfel testified Feb. 15
before the subcommittee on this bill. The Social Security
Administration's Web site _ www.ssa.gov _ has the full text of his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were the populations of the North and the South at the
time of the Civil War? And in the South, is it known how many
individuals actually owned slaves?
</P>
<P>
   A: When the Civil War began, about 22 million people lived in
the North. About 9 million people, including 3 1/2 million slaves,
lived in the South. The Encyclopedia of the Confederacy reports
that 26 percent of Southern white families owned slaves. While the
typical Southern slave owner possessed one or two slaves, the
typical white Southern male owned none, according to the
encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter will be applying to colleges soon. Can you list
all the Ivy League schools?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are eight institutions in the grouping, which is widely
regarded as high in academic and social prestige: Harvard, Yale,
Princeton, Columbia, Brown, Dartmouth, Cornell and the University
of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported last fall that Sandra Ann Rosas, wife of Los
Lobos singer-guitarist Cesar Rosas, was missing. I haven't read
anything about it since. Was she found?
</P>
<P>
   A: Investigators think she was killed by her half-brother,
Gabriel Gomez, and have charged him with kidnapping and murder.
Gomez, 39, of Whittier, Calif., could face the death penalty if a
jury finds that she was killed during a kidnapping. Her body has
not been found.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by the Orange County (Calif.) Register in late
December, Gomez pleaded not guilty to the charges. He was arrested
the day after Sandra Ann Rosas vanished from her home in the Los
Angeles suburb of Rowland Heights.
</P>
<P>
   She was last seen by her three daughters before they went out
for the evening on Oct. 23. When they returned a few hours later,
they found the front door to their home open, her van gone, and
broken glass from the vehicle in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Scott, a Los Angeles County sheriff's detective, said one
of the daughters called her mother's cell phone and, after it was
activated, overheard a conversation in which someone sounding like
Gomez ``was making threats regarding their mother's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time back, I read about a scholarship for minorities
established by Bill and Melinda Gates. Where can I get more
information?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation _ 877-690-4677 _
for recorded information. The message indicates that the deadline
has passed for applications for the 2000-01 school year. But you
should try the number again over the next few months for updated
information about new applications.
</P>
<P>
   When the scholarships and fellowships were announced, it was
said that the Gates Millennium Scholars Program would be for 20
years, starting in the fall of 2000, for outstanding low-income
African-American, American Indian, Alaska native, Hispanic-American
and Asian-American students. The United Negro College Fund
administers the program.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
