<HEADER>
A3077 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-COX-     03-01 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-COX-FILE2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call (404) 222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   FILE 2 OF 2
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is the Indian woman with papoose on the new golden
dollars?
</P>
<P>
   A: She is Sacagawea, a young Shoshone explorer who in 1804-06
assisted the Lewis and Clark expedition from the Northern Great
Plains to the Pacific Ocean and back. Sacagawea is credited with
contributing to the success of the expedition through her
navigational, diplomatic and translating skills. Translated, her
name means ``Bird Woman,'' according to the U.S. Mint
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the model for the image of Sacagawea on the on the
new golden dollar coin?
</P>
<P>
   A: The mysterious face behind the golden dollar belongs to
Randy'L He-Dow Teton, a Shoshone who was a student at the
University of New Mexico in 1998 when the U.S. Mint invited New
Mexico sculptor Glenna Goodacre to submit proposed designs for the
coin.
</P>
<P>
   No portraits existed of the Shoshone teenager who assisted the
historic Lewis and Clark exhibition between 1804 and 1806, and even
the explorers' journals didn't include sketches or other clues as
to what she looked like. So Goodacre, knowing that even the best of
sculptors can't create out of thin air, went to the Institute of
American Indian Arts Museum in Santa Fe, N.M. Upon arrival, she
asked if any young Shoshone women were in the area. As luck would
have it, a woman who worked at the museum showed her a photo of her
three daughters, one of whom was Teton. Soon the deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   Teton's stint modeling for a few hours paid off. A few weeks
later, Goodacre called with the big news: ``We got it!''
</P>
<P>
   When she saw the coin's design, Teton said she was proud of
being the model. Of the image, she said she especially liked ``its
strength, gracefulness and humbleness.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that the image doesn't represent just her, but all
Native American women. ``All (Native American) women have the
dignity of the golden dollar's image,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please settle an argument. Who was the first American athlete
to run a sub-4-minute mile?
</P>
<P>
   A: This isn't a trick question, is it? It you said Don Bowden,
you'd be correct. If the other party in the argument said Jim
Beatty, he or she would be correct, too.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why, as ``Famous First Facts'' explains. Bowden, of the
University of California, was the first U.S. runner to better the
4-minute mile outdoors. He did it in 3 minutes, 58.7 seconds, at
the Pacific Amateur Athletic Union Meet at Stockton, Calif., on
June 1, 1957.
</P>
<P>
   The first to accomplish this feat indoors was Beatty, of the Los
Angeles Track Club, who ran the mile in 3 minutes, 58.9 seconds, in
the Los Angeles Memorial Sports Arena on Feb. 10, 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, incidentally, was the 11th man in the world to better
the 4-minute mile.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The House vote on a posthumous Congressional Gold Medal for
``Peanuts'' cartoonist Charles Schulz was 410-1. Who was the single
member of Congress to vote against it, and what was his or her
explanation?
</P>
<P>
   A: The single dissenter was Rep. Ron Paul (R-Texas). While Paul
``has no problem with the Congressional Medal of Honor for military
heroes, he votes against all Congressional Gold Medals,'' said his
spokesman, Tom Lizardo. Congressional Gold Medals are the highest
civilian honors handed out by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Lizardo added that Paul ``has taken an oath to uphold the
Constitution and the separation of powers as outlined by the
founding fathers.'' In Paul's view, the doctrine of enumerated
powers is at the heart of the separation of powers. This doctrine,
Lizardo said, states that the federal government is limited to
taking such acts as specifically authorized by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some argue that the `necessary and proper' clause gives
the Congress broad powers to do whatever it wishes, this
interpretation is clearly contrary to the intent of the founders,''
Lizardo said. ``Thus, while it may be constitutional to award
honors to men and women who fulfill the constitutional function of
defending the nation, Congressman Paul can find no constitutional
authority to spend $30,000 in taxpayer funds to give awards to
great people such as Mr. Schulz.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you list the top five states in the number of people
executed since the death penalty was reinstated? Can you compare
that number with the executions in some other countries, such as
England , France, Germany and Canada?
</P>
<P>
   A: The top five, as listed by the National Coalition to Abolish
the Death Penalty: Texas, Virginia, Florida, Missouri and
Louisiana. Twelve states and the District of Columbia have no
capital punishment. Brian Henninger of the coalition said no
Western European countries maintain the death penalty. Nor does
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The National Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty maintains a
Web site _ www.ncadp.org/ _ with statistics and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was an autopsy performed on Wilt Chamberlain?
</P>
<P>
   A: No autopsy was reported. The 7-foot-1-inch ``Wilt the
Stilt,'' who played 14 NBA seasons, died Oct. 12. He was found dead
in bed at his home in the Bel-Air suburb of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   As reported at the time, it had been said as early as the 1960s
that Chamberlain had a heart problem. In 1992 he was hospitalized
for three days with a slightly irregular heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Sy Goldberg, his attorney, agent and longtime friend, told the
Associated Press that Chamberlain died of congestive heart failure.
Shortly after his death, Goldberg said Chamberlain had deteriorated
relatively quickly ``over the last month or so.'' In the few weeks
before his death, Chamberlain had lost 30 or 40 pounds as doctors
drained his legs of fluid that had accumulated before his heart
trouble, Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters just after Chamberlain's death, Barbara
Lewis, his sister, said he had undergone dental surgery the week
before his death and looked worse than she had ever seen him.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
