<HEADER>
A3078 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-BACONSOUP02-COX     03-01 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BACONSOUP02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flavorful soup great way to savor good bacon
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Some culinary moments are so special they are
etched in memory.
</P>
<P>
   So I remember the summer day in 1996 and lunch on the patio at
The Winds in Yellow Springs. That's when I first tasted Nueske's
applewood smoked bacon on a state-of-the-art BLT. I quickly asked,
``Where did you get that bacon?''
</P>
<P>
   They told me, but I had to struggle to get my hands on Nueske's
bacon. Nearly four years later, delivery to area supermarkets
remains irregular even when the butcher begs suppliers for it.
Fortunately, Nueske's now has a mail-order catalog and a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   When you have the bacon in hand, try it in this recipe, a real
showstopper adapted from Ming Tsai's ``Blue Ginger'' cookbook
(Potter, $32.50). It's full of the flavor of good smoked bacon plus
the smoky hot flavor of chipotle chiles.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe takes a bit of work, but the soup can be made ahead
and refrigerated. Even the red pepper and bacon salsa can be made
in advance and warmed just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   CHIPOTLE SWEET POTATO SOUP WITH RED BELL PEPPER AND BACON SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Salsa:
</P>
<P>
   4 slices smoky bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime (half a lime if they are big)
</P>
<P>
   Soup:
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves, smashed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon finely chopped fresh ginger root
</P>
<P>
   2 small yellow onions, roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 teaspoon pureed chipotles in adobo sauce
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   3 large sweet potatoes (not yams) peeled and cut into 1/2-inch
dice
</P>
<P>
   6 cups fat-free chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   Creme fraiche or equal parts of sour cream and nonfat yogurt
mixed together
</P>
<P>
   To make the salsa, cook the bacon, turning once, until crisp in
a large, heavy pan over medium heat. Drain bacon on paper towels;
crumble and set aside. Strain the bacon fat into a container and
wipe pan. Return just enough bacon fat to the skillet to coat the
bottom lightly. Add the diced red onion and red pepper and cook
over medium heat about 6 minutes. Season with salt and pepper and
add the lime juice. Transfer to a small bowl and set aside at room
temperature (or refrigerate and rewarm later).
</P>
<P>
   Add some of the reserved bacon fat to the pan (bacon fat
provides essential flavor), using enough to coat the pan. Add the
garlic, minced ginger, chopped onions and brown sugar; season with
salt and pepper and cook about 6 minutes, until onion is lightly
browned. Add the wine and stir up any brown bits in the bottom of
the pan. Add the chipotle puree and cook the mixture over medium
heat until the mixture is reduced by three-fourths, about 6
minutes. Add the sweet potatoes and chicken stock and simmer until
the potatoes are very soft, about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a blender, puree the soup mixture in batches. The soup can
be made ahead to this point and refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Reheat the soup. Warm the salsa and bacon crumbles in
a 300-degree oven for 5 minutes, then combine the salsa and bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle soup into soup bowls, add a spoonful of creme fraiche and
top with a generous spoonful of salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Puree 1 chile and a little of the sauce and in a mini-processor.
Keep the remaining chiles in a well-sealed jar in the refrigerator
and they will last for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
