<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3089 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-LIFEINAMERICA-0302-CO     03-01 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 IN AMERICA-0302-COX &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA 0302: There's something funny about this family
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters.
Photos and a sig/locator map are available.)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ In many ways, Jay and Kristin Stewart are just
your average young married couple with a toddler, a minivan and a
house in suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, when they began dating in Las Vegas, she was a
professional clown and he alternated playing Moe and Larry in a
``Three Stooges'' show at the MGM Grand Hotel. And yes, every day
it takes both of them about an hour to get dressed for work and _
ahem! _ put on their makeup.
</P>
<P>
   OK, and their co-worker, the Human Comet, sets the suit he's
wearing on fire daily _ six times on weekends. And the Wheel of
Wonder's wife helps run the nursery where the Stewarts'
18-month-old daughter, Karen, stays when they're working.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas many people just feel as if they're living in a
three-ring circus, Jay and Kristin Stewart actually do. Four months
ago, the couple signed on as clowns with the Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus. Taking the jobs meant arranging for family
to stay in their house. Except for a few days spent at home for
Christmas, they'll be hitting the road through November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Atlanta,'' said Jay, who will nonetheless stay with
his little family on the circus train.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the effort is worth it to the Stewarts, who this year
will perform in some 500 shows, taking countless pratfalls and pies
in the face in pursuit of a shared dream. Indeed, in a setting
where a high-wire walker teeters precariously over a pit of tigers,
trapeze artists boast more nerve than net and even bouncing on a
pogo stick can be downright lethal, Jay and Kristin Stewart
arguably are courageous figures in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   They have made the very serious decision to be funny for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to join the quote-unquote normal circuit that most
people do,'' Kristin Stewart, 30, who looked positively normal in
street clothes some two hours before showtime in Raleigh, N.C.
``But it wasn't for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after marrying in 1996, in fact, the couple settled down in
Atlanta and took what they describe as ``administrative'' jobs with
a vinyl flooring company. But clowning eventually called them back:
first to Japan, where Jay took a job with a different circus last
year, and then to the big top big time with Ringling Bros. last
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought for a while maybe we should try to have a `real'
life _ who knows, maybe be more stable or those words that people
throw around,'' Jay, 35, explained, sitting in a temporary circus
office in the Raleigh arena not far from the elephant holding area
and the acrobats' dressing rooms. ``But then we realized Karen's
got to know us for who we are. I want her to be proud of me, and
for me to do what I'm good at, so that when she's able to say what
her daddy does for a living, it's something kind of cool.''
</P>
<P>
   For Massachusetts native Kristin, this is her first year with
the acknowledged creme de la clown performing unit. For Jay, this
year marks both his return to the circus he first joined in 1989
and a step up the career ladder: He is the official ``Boss Clown,''
which only sounds like Tony Soprano in red nose and oversize shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it's just nitpicking,'' said Jay. ``It sounds like
it's unimportant. But the littlest thing, like someone not checking
their props beforehand, can ruin a gag for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It was P.T. Barnum himself who said clowns and elephants were
the ``pegs'' holding up the circus. During one 2 1/2-hour show in
Raleigh, only the cotton candy vendors were more constant presences
than the clowns, who juggled and danced their way through
ringmaster Johnathan Lee Iverson's opening and closing numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there were clown numbers, including one in which a
comically exasperated Jay portrayed _ what else? _ the boss of the
world's most inept group of bakers. Plus clown hijinks to direct
the audience members' eyes away from apparatus being moved out of
one ring or toward dogs doing handstands in another.
</P>
<P>
   Difficult balancing acts are something the Stewarts know all
about. Under that clown makeup, they face many of the same
challenges as people who don't work in a spangled bodysuit and top
hat, or hide seven feet of handkerchief up their sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   They live in a one-room apartment on the train, but keep the
minivan in case they need to take Karen to a doctor or run errands.
The circus provides a traveling school and a nursery, and Karen's
sleeping schedule has been adjusted to jibe with performance times.
They've even developed a routine to deal with that well-known bane
of working parents _ getting dressed with a toddler underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of us will start and the other will watch her and then
when the first person gets to the point where they can watch the
baby and continue to get dressed, we'll switch off,'' Kristin
explained, while Karen blew on a souvenir ringmaster's whistle.
``So that within an hour, both of us have gotten our makeup on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stewarts plan to have more children, just as they plan to
stay with the circus ``as long as we have fun and everything's cool
with Karen,'' Jay said.
</P>
<P>
   Ask how things are with Karen and the Stewarts react with that
typical blend of parental pride and modesty _ albeit with a
three-ring twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't seem to be scared of anything,'' Jay said. ``When
we were in Japan, she had her own personal giraffe and zebra. The
giraffe would lean down and lick her on the top of the head and she
loved that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, I think she has a really strong sense of balance,''
Kristin said. ``And she's strong, because she learned to walk over
cables and stuff. She didn't learn to walk on a rug in my living
room.''
</P>
<P>
   They wouldn't necessarily discourage their daughter if she
wanted to step into their comically oversize shoes someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want her to do what she wants to do,'' Jay said. ``Now
obviously, if she chooses to be a clown, we're going to be very
happy and very proud. If she chooses to be a doctor, we're going to
be even happier, probably!''
</P>
<P>
   ``If she chooses to be a high-wire walker, I'll be very
scared,'' Kristin admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Not your average parents' concern. But this is not your average
couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few people who are happy with what they do for
a living, and I think they really are,'' said Jay's mother, Marye
Fincher. ``And I think they love each other very much. In this day
and age, it's hard to do either of those things. In any setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, though, there was no funny business between the
couple. They met in passing in 1993 at the Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Clown College, where Jay, an '89 graduate, was
teaching and Kristin was a student. After graduating, she took
clown jobs at Circus Circus and several other Las Vegas hotels.
They reconnected when Jay joined the ``Stooges'' show there, and
married on Cape Cod in what Karen describes as a ``traditional''
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were clowns and Stooges in attendance, but everyone was
in civilian clothes,'' Jay explained.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after came that experiment with a ``real'' life and those
office jobs. On paper, they were ideal candidates: Kristin has a
political science degree from Brown University and Jay has a
master's degree in communications and theater arts from Wake
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   But for these two clowns, an office is no competition for a
three-ring circus.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Raleigh, children of all ages roared their approval
as the clown-garbed Jay chased the pink-haired Kristin around in
circles after she had repeatedly swatted his rear end with a broom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't imagine making your living by making people
laugh,'' Jay had said a few hours earlier, winking at Karen. Then,
as he and Kristin beamed with pride, the toddler performed to
perfection the exaggerated move on him whereby one clown pretends
to poke another in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   See? Just your average young family.
</P>
<P>
   photos by LOUIE FAVORITE / Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
