<HEADER>
A3090 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-UNUSUAL-HOTEL-PERKS-T     03-01 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNUSUAL-HOTEL-PERKS-TRAVEL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: UNUSUAL HOTEL PERKS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. ONE COLOR SLIDE, AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE, CAN BE
SENT TO YOU ELECTRONICALLY. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER  
 &HT;    How do hotels attract guests in a fiercely competitive market?
By going way beyond overnight shoeshines, 24-hour room service and
pet goldfish in guest rooms to offer something that their rivals
don't.
 &HT;    Here's a rundown of some of the unusual perks that hotels are
tempting visitors with these days.
 &HT;    Anyone who's skilled with a pool cue may get a chance to cut a
deal at the Hotel Loretto, where the ``Rack 'em! Rate'' rules.
Guests who win a game of pool against Janine Shelton, the general
manager, can get a reduced room rate _ 25 percent off one night's
accommodations or 5 percent off one night's accommodations for each
ball left on the table, whichever is greater.
 &HT;    For example, if a guest beats Shelton and she leaves seven balls
on the table, the guest would receive 35 percent off their room
rate. But if Shelton fails to pocket any balls during the game or
if the guest sinks the eight ball on the break, the guest receives
his first night's accommodations free. The ``Rack 'em! Rate'' is
based on space availability. For more information: The Hotel
Loretto, 211 Old Santa Fe Trail, Santa Fe, N.M. 87501; (800)
727-5531; www.noblehousehotels.com/loretto/index.html.
 &HT;    At the Four Seasons Las Vegas, the usual poolside amenities such
as Evian mist and cold towels are supplemented with sliced
cucumbers to relieve eyes tired out by late Vegas nights. The hotel
says it hands out 3,000 slices of cucumbers per week. For more
information: Four Seasons Las Vegas, P.O. Box 98881, Las Vegas,
Nev. 89193; (800) 819-5053; www.fourseasons.com.
 &HT;    In car-obsessed California, the Pan Pacific San Francisco offers
on-site auto detailing with car expert Joe Newhoff. Available by
appointment only, standard cleaning is $35 and extended cleaning is
$60. Add a hand polish and wax and the cost is $145, while complete
auto detailing is $295. For more information: Pan Pacific San
Francisco, 500 Post St., San Francisco, Calif. 94102; 800-533-6465;
www.panpac.com.
 &HT;    At Villa del Sol in the Mexican resort of Zihuatanejo, guests
can take the ``Interactive Spanish and Mexican Cuisine Course.''
Participants tour the town markets, learning about herbs, spices,
fruits, vegetables and fish, while shopping for the ingredients for
a Mexican meal.
 &HT;    Afterwards, guests can help prepare a Mexican meal or merely
watch the demonstration. Tequila, wine, beer and soft drinks are
served with the lunch, along with a booklet of recipes. The
five-hour course is $80 per person and limited to a group of eight.
For more information: Villa del Sol, Playa la Ropa, Zihuatanejo,
Mexico; (888) 389-2645; www.hotelvilladelsol.com.
 &HT;    At Hastings House, each guest's name is hand-lettered on the
door to their room and a personalized greeting card welcomes them.
In the evening, guests receive a personalized dinner menu. Every
morning, a wake-up hamper filled with fresh coffee or tea and
homemade pastries is delivered to the door of their suites. For
more information: Hastings House, 160 Upper Ganges Road, Salt
Spring Island, B.C., Canada V8K 2S2; 800-661-9255;
www.hastingshouse.com.
 &HT;    The Four Seasons Hotel Washington, D.C., has a ``Quiet Room''
for $30 per hour. It's a private, soundproofed getaway where guests
can relax or listen to CDs while sitting in a leather recliner with
built-in massage functions. The room is lit by recessed, adjustable
``mood'' lighting. There's a remote-controlled audiovisual system
as well as a sound machine that can emulate noises like ocean
waves. In addition, a mini-fridge stocked with complimentary
refreshments, hot and cold face towels and a lava lamp are at their
disposal. For more information: The Four Seasons Hotel, 2800
Pennsylvania Ave. N.W., Washington, D.C. 20007; 800-819-5053;
www.fourseasons.com.
 &HT;    An Irish Yogi is what the Fitzpatrick Family Group of Hotels
offers at the Fitzpatrick Manhattan Hotel and the Fitzpatrick Grand
Central Hotel. Yogi Paul Dallaghan of Dublin teaches private
Vinyasa-style yoga to guests in their rooms. Sessions must be
arranged 24 hours in advance, and the cost is $80 per hour or $100
for 90 minutes. For more information: Fitzpatrick Hotels, 687
Lexington Ave., New York, N.Y. 10022; 800-367-7701;
www.fitzpatrickhotels.com.
 &HT;    The Towers at The New York Palace features ``maitre d'etage'' or
butler service. Room service is through Le Cirque 2000, one of New
York's most lauded restaurants, as well as a neighboring Japanese
restaurant, Sushisay. The Towers also has its own concierge, and
guests receive personalized stationery and business cards that
include the number of the fax machine in their room. For more
information: The Towers, 455 Madison Ave., New York, N.Y. 10022;
(800) NY-PALACE.
 &HT;    At the Broadmoor in Colorado Springs, golfers can schedule a
massage right on the course. The massage therapist meets the player
at the ninth hole for the massage, but the $90-per-hour charge _
and the massage _ can be split among a foursome. For more
information: The Broadmoor, 1 Lake Ave., Colorado Springs, Colo.
80906; 800-634-7711; www.broadmoor.com.
 &HT;    Aruba Sonesta Resorts has an ``Island Nanny Program'' that
provides a nanny for the duration of the family's stay. The rates
start at $120 per day, and the nanny is on duty from 8:00 a.m. to
midnight for two children. For more information: Aruba Sonesta
Resorts, Orangestad, Aruba; (800) SONESTA; www.arubasonesta.com.
 &HT;    Finally, the 5th Avenue Suites Hotel allows guests to ``Spend
the Night with Doug.'' Ecology-minded guests can request to have a
miniature Douglas Fir, the state tree of Oregon, brought to their
room. Trees that outgrows the hotel will eventually be donated to
Portland's Hoyt Arboretum. For more information: 5th Avenue Suites
Hotel, 506 S.W. Washington, Portland, Ore. 97204; (800) 711-2971;
http://135.145.16.183/5thavenuesuites.com/.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.) 
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
<TEXT>
