<HEADER>
A3092 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-ADVENTURE-TRAVEL-FOR-     03-01 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVENTURE-TRAVEL-FOR-SENIORS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: ADVENTURE TRAVEL FOR THE 50-PLUS SET  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only byspecial arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. ONE COLOR SLIDE, AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE, CAN BE
SENT TO YOU ELECTRONICALLY. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 &HT;    This year, many tour companies are including adventure-travel
excursions for the senior set. Here is a sampling.
 &HT;    
 SOUTHWESTERN STYLE  
 &HT;    Interhostel, an international study/travel program for adults
ages 50 and older, is adding six new domestic trips for 2000 _
including two that explore the Southwest and its heritage.
 &HT;    The trips are sponsored by the University of New Hampshire's
Continuing Education Program. Travelers can head for Palm Springs
(April 2 to 7) or Palm Desert, Calif., (April 9 to 14), where they
will learn about the wonderful activities of such organizations as
Animal Advocates for Life.
 &HT;    The Palm Desert program includes a tour of the Wildlife
Ambassadors facility to meet Belgian tigers, a meeting with the
curator scientist of the Palm Springs Desert Museum and a trip to
the Living Desert, a outdoor museum where wild creatures are
rescued and cared for.
 &HT;    The Palm Springs outing will include guided tours of the Agua
Caliente Indian Canyons as well as a ride on the Aerial Tramway.
Depending on the trip you choose, the price is about $830, double
occupancy, without airfare.
 &HT;    Interhostel is also offering a trip to the Butler Wash
Archaeology and Rock Art Service Project in Eastland, Utah, from
April 15 to 21. Tour-goers are given the chance to explore the Comb
Ridge area, which is particularly rich in archaic sites. Here, rock
art dates back as far as 8000 B.C. Participants also learn how to
locate and survey cliff dwellings, learn how to document sites and
participate in lectures and discussions about the ancient people of
the area.
 &HT;    Interhostel requires that travelers be able to hike two to four
miles in hilly canyon land. The price is $935 (no singles), without
airfare.
 &HT;    For more information about Interhostel's travel selections, call
(800) 733-9753 or visit www.learn.unh.edu on the Web.
 &HT;    
 WHITE-WATER RAFTING  
 &HT;    Dave Warren's River Expeditions in Salmon, Idaho, is posting
nearly a dozen white-water rafting trips designed especially for
the 50-plus set with lodge stays.
 &HT;    Accommodations vary, with some more rustic than others. The
six-day trips down Idaho's main Salmon River (also known as the
``River of No Return'') start with a stay at the Salmon River
Lodge. Space remains on the Seniors Only trips that depart April 9,
16, 23, 30, May 4, July 14 and 22, Aug. 23, 31 and Sept. 8. Prices
start at $1,525, per person, plus taxes.
 &HT;    Warren also offers two Grandparents/Grandkids rafting trips,
with lodging included, July 30 and Aug. 7. The trips are designed
for families to get closer while enjoying the great outdoors.
 &HT;    Although the tours start and end in Salmon, the nearest airport
is in Boise. Participants need to use an air taxi or jet boat to
get back and forth. The Warrens will help you organize the
transfer. For more information, call (800) 765-0421 or visit
www.raftidaho.com On the Web.
 &HT;    
 RV ADVENTURES IN ALASKA  
 &HT;    Alaska Travel Adventures (ATA) offers one-stop shopping for
mature travelers interested in a motor-home rental and a tour of
Alaska. Its new brochure, ``2000 Alaska Motor-Home Rental,''
features special discounts to members of AARP and AAA.
 &HT;    Three different RV Fly-Drive itineraries are listed, including a
new Alaska Highways Adventure tour. Rates range from $99 to $195
per day, depending on the season, RV size and length of rental.
Members of AARP, CAA or AAA get 5 percent off standard rentals.
 &HT;    These are prearranged, self-guided RV tour packages that include
motor home and transfers, airfare between Seattle and Anchorage, a
reserved private campground each night, detailed daily itineraries
with maps and free mileage.
 &HT;    ``Alaska Motor-home Rentals recreational vehicles are designed
for first-time RVers,'' says Gary Odle, vice president of ATA.
 &HT;    For brochures, call (800) 254-9929 or visit www.alaskarv.com on
the Web.
 &HT;    
 RV/CRUISE COMBOS  
 &HT;    Alaska Highway Cruises, a subsidiary of Alaska Travel
Adventures, offers cruises with RV land journeys.
 &HT;    The itinerary for its Northern Highlights Trip, A 15-day tour,
includes a one-week RV land trip to Anchorage, Denali National Park
and Fairbanks, along with a seven-night cruise onboard the Glacier
Discovery that begins at Seward, Alaska, and ends at Vancouver,
B.C. Prices range from $107 to $295 per person, per day, depending
on the specifics of your package _ for example, the size of the RV,
etc.
 &HT;    Combination programs offer a 10 percent discount for bookings
made by April 28. For more information, call (800) 323-5757 or your
travel agent.
 &HT;    
 REMEMBERING THE KOREAN WAR  
 &HT;    Fifty years after the start of the Korean War, Korea is
encouraging veterans to see how the country has changed. Between
June 25, 2000, and June 27, 2003, mature travelers can participate
in special events to commemorate the war period. Several tour
operators, listed below, are already offering packages that
dovetail with memorial events:
 &HT;    _ Four Seasons Tour and Travel's seven-day program centers
around the re-enactment of the Inchon Landing. Call (213) 381-8000
and ask for J.H. Song.
 &HT;    _ California Pacific Tours is offering an eight-day trip that
includes a tour to the Demilitarized Zone. Call (650) 615-4750 and
ask for Roy Montgomery.
 &HT;    _ The U.S. Navy Memorial Foundation has A 12-day tour with stops
in Honolulu and Yokosuka, Japan. Contact Chuck Randolf Tours and
Travel at (800) 336-1490.
 &HT;    You can also contact the Korea National Tourism Organization at
3435 Wilshire Blvd., Suite 1110, Los Angeles, Calif. 90010; (800)
868-7567.
 &HT;    
 NEW GRANDTRAVELS  
 &HT;    GrandTravel, now in its 14th year of specialized trips for
grandparents and grandchildren, is offering three new itineraries
for 2000.
 &HT;    The new destinations _ Israel and Jordan, the Galapagos Islands
and Massachusetts _ make for a total of 20 tours now being offered
by Grandtravel.
 &HT;    The nine-day Massachusetts trip lets families explore the
history of the witch trials of 1692, see a Red Sox baseball game
and July 4th fireworks celebration and tour eastern Massachusetts _
specifically Cape Cod, Martha's Vineyard and Boston. The price of
the trip, which departs July 1, is $5,755 per person, double
occupancy, for land only.
 &HT;    The itinerary for the 12-day trip to the Galapagos Islands
includes a visit to a volcano, opportunities to see ancient
tortoises, as well as the chance to explore Quito, Ecuador's
capital, and Otavalo, a market village where Indians sell their
crafts. The tours, which depart June 29 and July 20, cost $6,720
per person, double occupancy, including airfare from Miami to
Quito. This trip is for children AGES 12 to 17.
 &HT;    For more information, contact Grandtravel at 6900 Wisconsin
Ave., Suite 706, Chevy Chase, Md. 20815; or call (800) 247-7651. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.) 
 ---- 
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
