<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Madonna soundtrack covers world territory
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though its sales hook is Madonna's new dance cover of '70s rock
anthem ``American Pie,'' this soundtrack from the star's latest
movie is more world buffet than a serving of traditional Top 40.
The tunes here are mostly European-flavored, electronic pop and
Afro-Latin music _ light.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 tracks hop from one mood to another like a series of
patients occupying the couch. There's Franco-Spanish
singer-songwriter Manu Chao with the fun-time novelty tune ``Bongo
Bongo,'' a Latin lounge rap that layers a hypnotic chant over a
pogo stick beat. DJ-turned-folk-revivalist Moby mixes pre-1945 folk
melodies with thickly textured keyboards on ``Why Does My Heart
Feel So Bad?'' off his ``Play'' CD.
</P>
<P>
   Four tracks are brand new: Madonna's ``Pie'' and ``Time Stood
Still,'' a Latin-flavored remake of her 1995 hit ``Take a Bow;'' an
updated cover of 10CC's bloated '70s ballad, ``I'm Not In Love,''
by the electronic hip-hop group Olive; and a new song from teen
warbler Christina Aguilera called ``Don't Make Me Love You,'' which
sounds much like every other Mariah Carey rip-off song she has
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   With its radio-friendly, mainstream pop leanings, this is
probably not the album for electronic dance or world music purists,
but it's a great primer on the broadly defined genres for folks
outside the club scene.
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Next Best Thing''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Maverick.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
