r e BC-VIDEO-BESTMAN02-COX     03-01 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-BESTMAN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `The Best Man' is a joyous occasion
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Best Man'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   In Malcolm D. Lee's often funny, sexy and prickly comedy-drama,
Taye Diggs heads a talented ensemble cast in an outright contender
for one of last year's best date movies: a glossy wedding film
punctuated with soul-stirring music (Bob Marley, Stevie Wonder,
MeShell Ndegeocello, Maxwell), flurries of flesh and real dramatic
bite.
</P>
<P>
   It's a plot that occasionally digs deep into the intricate
nature of friendship, love and sex among a group of successful
20-somethings gathering for the union of two old college friends.
Many quickly dismissed this movie as a rip-off of ``The Wood,'' the
remember-when, good-times movie that not only had a wedding at its
core but also starred Diggs. But ``Best Man'' focuses far less on
flashbacks and, more than once, provokes the same kind of dramatic
shivers that made Lawrence Kasdan's reunion hit ``The Big Chill''
such a big thrill.
</P>
<P>
   Diggs plays Harper Stewart, the film's title groomsman and an
up-and-coming writer. His steamy new book about a collegian and his
guy and gal pals, is about to get played large on ``Oprah.''
Naturally, Harper's friends _ nicely played by Morris Chestnut, Nia
Long, Harold Perrineau, Monica Calhoun and, especially, Terrence
Howard _ are more than curious about how their lives are portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   One key scene involves a poker game, in which the guys'
requisite male bonding turns into a frank and challenging thesis on
fidelity. It evokes the kind of raw, emotional power you just don't
get in all-jokey relationship films like ``The Story of Us.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3141 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS02-COX     03-01 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS02-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``MP4 (Days Since a Lost Time Accident)''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Penn. Epic. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Here comes the millenium,'' Penn warbles on the first track of
this clever, concise collection of pop ditties. He sounds ready for
it. For sheer catchiness, the singer-songwriter's fourth outing
(hence the title) surpasses even his 1989 debut, ``March,'' which
yielded the irresistible sing-along hit ``No Myth.'' Dipping into
his family's pool of talent _ wife Aimee Mann sings backup on three
tracks, actor-brother Christopher Penn croons on one _ Penn has
fashioned an intricate work that echoes past efforts by fellow
brainy popsters Lindsey Buckingham and Elvis Costello, but with a
new energy. Such songs as ``Lucky One,'' produced by Atlanta's
Brendan O'Brien, and ``Beautiful'' radiate warmth even as Penn's
lyrics explore the uncertainties of love and career. ``I can't
belong to any future,'' Penn insists on ``Footdown,'' which recalls
Costello's ``Imperial Bedroom'' period. But he does, whether he
likes it or not.
</P>
<P>
   _Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Before Insanity''
</P>
<P>
   Gov't Mule. Capricorn Records. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   This Allman Brothers Band splinter group may never entirely step
out of the shadow of Gregg, Dickey &AMP; Co. But on the power trio's
third studio album, Mule makes its biggest leap yet from its
Southern-rock roots to the 1970s metal-rock territory mined by
Mountain, Zeppelin and Wishbone Ash. Unlike the band's last outing
(``Live ... With a Little Help From Our Friends,'' a two-disc set
of extended jams), ``Insanity'' is a collection of concise tunes
that clock in at five to eight minutes each. Yet even within these
truncated songs, the band's signature improvisations are the main
draw.
</P>
<P>
   Guitarist Warren Haynes is a credible singer-composer, with his
whiskey-cured bark and world-weary lyrics. But his speed-with-soul
fretwork is what elevates Mule's sound. And most vocal passages
here seem to exist only to frame Haynes' stirring solo breaks _ on
everything from restrained acoustic ballads such as ``In My Life''
to full-throttle boogie-rockers like ``Wandering Child'' and the
Lowell George-inspired ``Bad Little Doggie.''
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``D.I.T.C.''
</P>
<P>
   D.I.T.C. . Tommy Boy Music. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   D.I.T.C. stands for the rap collective Digging in the Crates,
but back in 1988 when it released its first album, the term meant
something else. ``Digging in the crates'' was a way of saying that
someone had done some serious hunting in their collection of albums
(often kept in milk crates) to find a certain obscure _ and usually
appropriate _ hip-hop sample. Not that the music was as much of a
concern in this genre as it is now. Then it was all about whether
you could attack the microphone as confidently as KRS-One on ``Drop
It Heavy'' here or say something as cleverly as recently departed
Latino rapper Big Pun on ``Where Ya At.'' And this second, sparely
produced album from D.I.T.C. is a much-needed reminder of those
sorely missed attributes.
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
