<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-PUMKINS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Passionate Pumpkins pounce on metal, melody
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crunchy guitar goodness is back.
</P>
<P>
   After 1998's ``Adore,'' a soft, low-key record that was a
commercial and critical disappointment, the Pumpkins thunder back
with an amped-up set of tunes. It's not all head-banging and
rampaging drums, but even in the
</P>
<P>
   quietest moments it feels a lot more like rock 'n' roll than
``Adore.'' Head Pumpkin Billy Corgan never lost his fondness for
'70s metal, and that influence is all over the album, especially in
the thunderous riffs of ``The Everlasting Gaze'' and ``Heavy Metal
Machine.'' When Corgan and fellow guitarist James Iha crank up the
guitars, it rumbles like a freight train.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviness is tempered with a nice assortment of hooks and
melodies, and several genuine beauties. ``Wound'' swirls like a
lost Psychedelic Furs gem, while ``Raindrops + Sunshowers'' is
reminiscent of the melodic melancholy of ``1979'' from the Pumpkins
third album, ``Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   The dense wall of sound that characterized the band's 1993
masterwork ``Siamese Dream'' has been opened up. There's still a
lot going on, but the music gets a little more room to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Corgan and company seem fired up and ready to take on the world
again, sounding more passionate than they have since ``Siamese
Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``MACHINA/the machines of God''
</P>
<P>
   Smashing Pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
