<HEADER>
A3143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-NAMES-$ADV04-     03-01 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NAMES-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT'S IN A NAME? FOR WOMEN IN THE CZECH REPUBLIC, IT'S 'OVA'
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.2000 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scan the entertainment sections of any Czech magazine or
newspaper and you'll find Julia Robertsova and Meryl Streepova, not
Julia Roberts and Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   In Czech and other Slavic languages, the suffix ``ova'' is added
to the last names of all females. It's an ending long-ingrained in
the vernacular that quite literally means ``belonging to'' the
male, as in belonging to a woman's father or husband. (In English,
``ova'' is plural for ``ovum,'' a female egg cell.)
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make any American feminist wince. But Europe _
and especially Central Europe _ has long fought against
American-style political correctness, a term often derided as
describing a tortured sensitivity resulting in ridiculous changes
to the language.
</P>
<P>
   But times are changing, even in post-Communist countries like
the Czech Republic, meaning the use of the suffix ``ova'' may soon
be over.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation recently proposed by the Czech Republic's Ministry
of Interior would enable a woman to remove the suffix from her last
name.
</P>
<P>
   According to government officials, the legislation is expected
to pass and could take effect by the end of the year. They insist
the impetus for the proposal is not a rise in complaints, but is
simply the result of a changing world in which women are seeking
more control.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Kavkova, who runs Relocation Management International, a
Prague-based firm that helps companies relocate to the Czech
Republic, said some women have started to consider the use of
``ova'' demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they use it reluctantly because they accept it as part of
life here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, language is not as scrutinized in Europe as it is in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, for example, people who deliver the mail are still
called postmen, even if they are women.
</P>
<P>
   And even though British Prime Minister Tony Blair often speaks
out in favor of women's rights, no one bats an eye that the female
members of Parliament belonging to his Labor Party are popularly
referred to in the press as ``Blair's babes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Czech Republic is even more traditional than
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   It is, for example, the kind of country in which high-level
female involvement in business or government is rarely encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   In the Czech Republic there are no women in the Cabinet, whereas
in Sweden, 12 of 20 Cabinet positions are occupied by women.
</P>
<P>
   But many post-Communist countries are introducing laws these
days to put them in line with the European Union, which they aspire
to join.
</P>
<P>
   In the Czech Republic, legislation to combat sexual harassment
was recently proposed following the publishing of a study by the
daily, Lidove Noviny, indicating that almost half of the country's
working women had been sexually harassed in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Zuzana Roithova, one of just nine female members in the
81-member Senate, said Czech women have been slow to push for more
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good family life is more important to many than their
rights,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Women right's advocates said it's no surprise then that the
Czech government is just now considering giving women the option of
removing the suffix ``ova'' from their last names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feminism is not so popular in post-Communist countries as it
is elsewhere,'' said Jirina Ciklova, founder of the Center for
Gender Studies in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think this new proposal is a positive one and that, as a
result, many women, at least many of those from the younger
generation, will change their names,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Ciklova said, however, the change may not go over so well with
older women, who favor the suffix for making it immediately clear
whether someone is male or female.
</P>
<P>
   Even she agreed that some Czech names just won't sound right
without the ``ova.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she pondered, ``Can you imagine saying Martina
Navratil, instead of Martina Navratilova?'' She certainly can't.
</P>
<P>
   (Shelley Emling, a former foreign correspondent, is now a
freelance writer living in London.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-BREADPUDDING-REC     03-01 3029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BREADPUDDING-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bread pudding _ admirably adaptable
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cookbook author Carole Lalli is so convinced of the ease of
making a bread pudding she declares only the ``seriously inept or
scatterbrained'' fail to produce a decent one.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to go that far, having had my share of failures
with ``foolproof'' recipes. But bread pudding is darn easy. Tear
some bread in chunks, mix up a custard and pour it over and add
some sweet or savory ingredients. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few things to keep in mind while making the recipes
below. While they call for specific kinds of bread, feel free to
use what you've got. A mixture of breads works, too. I often have
whole wheat slices left over and find they mix well with white in
many bread puddings.
</P>
<P>
   You can tailor a bread pudding to your personal taste, though
you may have to prepare a recipe by the book the first time. Then,
if it's too moist, cut back on the custard next time. Too dry?
Double the custard. Don't like raisins? Throw in your favorite
dried fruit instead. Or chocolate chips.
</P>
<P>
   Most recipes allow for 15 minutes of soaking time before baking.
This is important for a moist pudding. And most cook slowly between
300 and 350 degrees. If your oven runs hot, turn the heat down.
</P>
<P>
   Lalli, author of ``Yesterday's Bread'' (HarperPerennial,
$12.95), highly recommends baking bread puddings in a water bath.
To do that, place the baking pan in a larger pan and fill with
water halfway up the pudding pan. This will produce a tender
texture. But some actually prefer it a bit crusty. So let your
taste be the guide.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutesResting time: 15 minutesCooking
time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   This is it _ the classic but versatile bread pudding recipe from
the New Orleans School of Cooking that I've used for years. Try it
once as written, then have fun improvising. My favorite is to add
about 2/3 cup chocolate chips. You can also add pineapple or other
fruit chunks, coconut and your favorite nuts. Our stylist, Mary Ann
Clayton, added dried apricots. Let your imagination run wild. I
usually use only 6 cups of bread cubes so it will be more custardy.
The sauce is good enough to drink!
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dark raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup whiskey or bourbon
</P>
<P>
   6 to 7 cups lightly packed bite-size cubes of day-old French or
Italian bread
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Whiskey Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks, lightly whisked
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons whiskey or bourbon
</P>
<P>
   Combine the raisins and 1/3 cup whiskey in a small bowl. Preheat
the oven to 350 degrees. Butter a 13-by-9-inch baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the bread in the baking dish and scatter the pecans over
it. When the raisins have absorbed most of the whiskey, scatter
them and any remaining whiskey over the bread. Whisk together the
eggs, milk, half-and-half, granulated sugar, butter, vanilla,
cinnamon and nutmeg, and pour the custard mixture evenly over the
bread. Lightly pat the bread down into the custard. Let the mixture
sit at room temperature for about 15 minutes, then stir and pat
back down again. A bit of the bread should remain just above the
custard. Bake the pudding for 50 to 55 minutes, until the pudding
is slightly puffed and golden brown, with a few crunchy spots on
top.
</P>
<P>
   While the pudding bakes, prepare the sauce. Combine the butter
and confectioners' sugar in a medium saucepan and warm over medium
heat until the butter and sugar melt together. Stir 2 tablespoons
of the butter-sugar mixture into the egg yolks, then pour it back
into the rest of the butter-sugar mixture and whisk until combined,
about another minute. Remove from the heat and immediately whisk in
the whiskey. The sauce will be somewhat thin, but it thickens as it
cools.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the pudding warm, spooned onto individual plates, with a
few tablespoons of the sauce poured over each. Pass the remaining
sauce separately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 665 calories, 9 grams protein, 37 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 51), 75 grams carbohydrates, 214
milligrams cholesterol, 224 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Corn Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   With Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Resting time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This quickly prepared dish is excellent and beautiful, with the
yellow corn bread, red tomatoes and green jalapenos, green onions
and cilantro. It's one of several savory bread puddings found in
Carole Lalli's ``Yesterday's Bread'' (HarperPerennial, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-inch) square stale corn bread
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced green onions, including 1-inch green tops
(about 6)
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 minced jalapeno peppers
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cherry tomatoes, halved
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cilantro leaves, roughly chopped, plus additional for
garnish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   Cut the corn bread into strips about 1/2 inch wide by 2 inches
long. (If the bread is not dry to the touch, place it on a baking
sheet and put it in a 300-degree oven for 5-10 minutes, until it is
dry but not browned.)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, bring the broth to a low simmer and keep
it warm over low heat. In a separate pan, melt the butter. Add the
green onions and saute until they soften but do not take on color;
add the jalapeno peppers and cook briefly. Stir in the flour and
cook for about 2 minutes, stirring constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the pan from the heat and whisk in the broth. When the
broth is fully incorporated and the mixture is smooth, place it
over medium heat and cook, stirring frequently, until thickened,
about 10 minutes. Remove the sauce from the heat and season to
taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly butter or oil a baking dish about 9 by 13 inches and
line the bottom with the strips of corn bread. Distribute the
tomatoes and 1/2 cup cilantro over the bread. Carefully pour the
sauce over and sprinkle on the cheese. Let the pudding sit for
about 15 minutes to allow the bread to absorb the sauce, then place
it in the oven. Bake the pudding for 30-45 minutes, until the top
is golden brown and bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   The pudding will still be slightly saucy; let it rest for about
10 minutes, then serve, garnished with additional cilantro if
desired, warm or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, the pudding can be briefly reheated in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 313 calories, 9 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 35 grams carbohydrates, 59
milligrams cholesterol, 758 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Pear
</P>
<P>
   Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Resting time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This bread pudding is pretty, with the pears and cranberries
sitting on top. If you like a lot of custard, you'll want to try
this one _ soft, silky and melt-in-your-mouth good.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pear eau de vie such as Poire William or pear nectar
</P>
<P>
   3 medium-ripe but firm Bosc or d'Anjou pears (about 1 pound)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   6 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   6 slices challah or brioche bread or 10 to 12 slices French
baguette, about 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Place the cranberries in a small bowl and pour the eau de vie
over them. Peel, core and slice the pears into six pieces each.
Melt the butter in a large skillet over medium heat and, when it
ceases foaming, add 1/4 cup sugar and the pears along with the eau
de vie and cranberries. Cook, stirring gently, until the sugar
melts and the mixture is warm.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the eggs, then whisk in the remaining sugar, half-and-half
and vanilla. Lightly butter a baking dish and line it with bread,
overlapping the slices slightly. Distribute the pear mixture over
the bread, then pour the custard over. Let the pudding rest for
about 15 minutes, then set the dish in a water bath. Bake the
pudding for about 45 minutes, until it is set but not dry. Serve
warm or at room temperature, dusted with confectioners' sugar. _
From ``Yesterday's Bread,'' Carole Lalli (HarperPerennial, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 493 calories, 13 grams protein, 24 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 58 grams carbohydrates, 291
milligrams cholesterol, 289 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Peaches and Pecan
</P>
<P>
   Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   We pulled this one from our archives because it combines two
Georgia favorites _ peaches and pecans.
</P>
<P>
   1 large loaf French bread
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 (29-ounce) can peaches, drained and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Wet French bread and squeeze the
water out of it. Pull the bread apart into 1- to 2-inch pieces and
place in a bowl. Melt the butter and add to bread. Add eggs,
evaporated milk, nutmeg, vanilla, peaches, pecans and sugars. Stir
to combine well. Turn mixture into a 9-by-13-inch baking dish. Bake
30 minutes, then remove from oven, remix, and return to oven. Bake
about another 30 minutes, or until knife inserted into the center
of the pudding comes out clean. Serve warm with Rum Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 547 calories, 9 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 74 grams carbohydrates, 154
milligrams cholesterol, 362 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Rum Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   Rum to taste
</P>
<P>
   Mix butter and sugar until it forms an icing consistency. Add
rum to taste. Put a spoonful on top of warm pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 161 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 12 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 65), 15 grams carbohydrates, 31
milligrams cholesterol, 119 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Banana Bread Pudding With Rum Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   If you love banana desserts like I do, this will be
irresistible! It's a cross between a classic bread pudding and
Bananas Foster. Yum!
</P>
<P>
   Banana Bread Pudding:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup raisins or currants
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons dark rum
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3 bananas, peeled, halved crosswise and then lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces firm white bread slices (10 to 12 slices), crusts
trimmed, each slice cut into 3 strips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped toasted pecans (about 2 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   Rum Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dark rum
</P>
<P>
   For Banana Bread Pudding: Combine raisins and 2 tablespoons rum
in a small bowl. Let stand 20 minutes. Melt 2 tablespoons butter in
large heavy skillet over medium heat. Add bananas and 2 tablespoons
sugar and cook until bananas are tender, about 2 minutes per side.
Remove from heat. Combine whipping cream, eggs, vanilla extract and
remaining 1/4 cup rum and 3 tablespoons sugar in a medium bowl and
whisk to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter 9-by-5-by-3-inch loaf pan.
Arrange 1/3 of bread strips crosswise in bottom of prepared pan.
Arrange 6 banana pieces atop bread. Sprinkle with half of raisins
and half of pecans. Arrange 1/3 of bread strips crosswise atop
bananas. Pour half of egg mixture over. Arrange remaining banana
pieces atop bread. Sprinkle with remaining raisins and pecans.
Arrange remaining bread strips crosswise atop bananas. Pour
remaining egg mixture over. Press gently on top layer to compact.
Let stand 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until bread pudding is puffed and golden and knife inserted
in center comes out clean, about 45 minutes. Transfer to rack and
cool slightly. Cut bread pudding into slices. Arrange on plates;
drizzle with warm Rum Sauce and serve.
</P>
<P>
   For Rum Sauce (Makes about 1 cup): Melt butter in heavy medium
saucepan over medium-high heat. Add cream, sugar and salt. Bring to
boil, stirring until sugar dissolves. Remove from heat. Stir in
rum. (Can be prepared 2 days ahead. Cover and refrigerate. Rewarm
over low heat, stirring constantly.) _ From Epicurious.com (Bon
Appetit, March, 1995)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 513 calories, 9 grams protein, 32 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 56), 48 grams carbohydrates, 234
milligrams cholesterol, 261 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servingsPreparation time: 25 minutesCooking time: 1
1/4-1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   Mexican-style bread pudding is different. It combines sweet and
savory ingredients and uses a syrup of brown sugar and spices
instead of a milk-based custard. Yes, it sounds unusual, but it's
most delicious and will be especially popular with peanut lovers.
And aren't most Georgians?
</P>
<P>
   3 cups firmly packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   5 (3-inch) cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons anise seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 loaves French bread or 18 to 20 slices good-quality sandwich
bread
</P>
<P>
   1 stick ( 1/4 pound) unsalted butter, melted (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsalted shelled peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded white cheddar or Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   20 colaciones (candied peanuts such as honey-roasted or
Planter's ``sweet and crunchy'')
</P>
<P>
   Make the syrup: In a small pot, combine the brown sugar, cloves,
cinnamon sticks and anise seeds with 8 cups water. Bring to a boil
and cook, uncovered, stirring occasionally, until the sugar
dissolves. Reduce heat and simmer vigorously, uncovered, until the
liquid reduces to 4 cups, about 35-40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the bread: Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Grease two
cookie sheets. Arrange the bread on the cookie sheets and bake
until golden, about 5 minutes on each side. Using a pastry brush,
coat or drizzle the bread with melted butter, if desired. Turn oven
down to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the casserole: Butter a 13-by-9-inch baking dish. Place
a layer of bread on the bottom. Slowly pour 1 cup of syrup evenly
over the bread layer and allow the bread to soak up the syrup.
Sprinkle with a third of the shelled peanuts, a third of the
raisins and a third of the cheese. Repeat the layers twice, ending
with cheese. Pour the remaining syrup over the casserole.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and bake for 30 to 45 minutes at 350 degrees. During the
last 10 minutes, uncover the casserole and top it with the
colaciones, if desired. _ From ``A Gracious Plenty: Recipes and
Recollections From the American South,'' John T. Edge (G.P.
Putnam's Sons, $30)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 859 calories, 17 grams protein, 34 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 35), 128 grams carbohydrates, 62
milligrams cholesterol, 596 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate and bread make a beautiful pair, so it's no surprise
that there are numerous versions of chocolate bread pudding. But we
loved this one from Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split
</P>
<P>
   3 cinnamon sticks (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 day-old loaf brioche or good-quality white bread (about 1
pound)
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces bittersweet chocolate, roughly chopped, plus 1/2 ounce
or 1/4 cup shavings for garnish
</P>
<P>
   8 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) container creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   Place the cream, milk, vanilla seeds and pod and cinnamon
sticks, if using, in a medium saucepan and bring to a boil. Remove
from heat, cover with plastic and let sit for 30 minutes to infuse
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the brioche into 1/4-inch-thick slices. Cut each slice into
quarters, setting aside the rounded top pieces. Fill a 9-by-12-inch
gratin dish or 9-by-13-inch glass baking dish with the remaining
pieces of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Return milk mixture to a boil, remove from heat and discard
vanilla pod and cinnamon sticks. Add chocolate and whisk until
smooth. Whisk egg yolks and sugar in a large bowl. Very slowly pour
chocolate mixture into egg yolk mixture, whisking constantly, until
fully combined.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly pour half the chocolate mixture over the bread, making
sure all bread is thoroughly soaked. Arrange the reserved bread
tops on top in a decorative pattern, and press firmly so bottom
layer of bread absorbs chocolate mixture. Spoon remaining chocolate
mixture over bread until completely covered and all cracks are
filled. Place a piece of plastic wrap over dish, and press down to
soak bread thoroughly. Remove plastic, wipe edges of the dish with
a damp towel, and allow to sit for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place dish in a larger pan, and fill with hot water halfway up
the sides of the dish. Bake until set, about 35 minutes. Cool on a
rack for 15 minutes before serving. Whisk creme fraiche until soft
peaks form. Serve pudding warm garnished with creme fraiche and
chocolate shavings. _ From: ``Favorite Comfort Food: The Best of
Martha Stewart Living'' (Clarkson Potter, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 752 calories, 15 grams protein, 53 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 64), 62 grams carbohydrates, 344
milligrams cholesterol, 371 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
