<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Random Hearts (R) _ A meandering mystery/drama/romance that
never hits the right groove. Harrison Ford is a cop and Kristin
Scott Thomas a congresswoman who discover that their spouses, both
killed in a plane crash, were having an affair. The stars' ensuing
romance never taps beneath the surface. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stigmata'' (R) _ Let it bleed without you. This mishmash of
``The Exorcist,'' ``The Omen,'' etc., stars Gabriel Byrne as a
Vatican investigator sent to examine a young woman (Patricia
Arquette) who's showing signs of the story of us, i.e., the wounds
suffered by Christ on the cross. Unfortunately, despite some early
good scenes and a decent performance by Byrne, the movie prefers
sensationalism to making sense. It's enough to make you long for
the good ol' days of pea soup and spinning heads. Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Suburbans'' (R) _ A bland project that can't decide
whether it's a music-biz satire or a midlife-crisis comedy-drama,
this concerns a one-hit wonder teenage band from 1981 (named the
Suburbans) that gets rediscovered by a music industry executive,
played by Jennifer Love Hewitt, who wants to market their
retro-music to the ``post-boomer, pre-millennial demographic.''
Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Best Laid Plans'' (R) _ Reese Witherspoon, Alessandro Nivola
and Josh Brolin work hard, but only end up proving how difficult it
is to pull off modern noir. They're caught in a twisty plot
involving a charge of statutory rape, false identity, betrayal and
debt. Unfortunately, it becomes increasingly implausible as it
nears an ending that's tricky, but a little too pat. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Love Is the Devil'' (unrated) _ Derek Jacobi stars as
Francis Bacon in this rivetingly dark, fractured drama about the
painter's sadomasochistic relationship with a young burglar (Daniel
Craig). Often hard to watch, and more of a study than a portrait,
the movie is impressive in its way of finding a cinematic
equivalent for the painter's grotesque work. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
