<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3148 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-BREADPUDDING-COX     03-01 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BREADPUDDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bread pudding: Humble or jazzed up, these custardy delights have
stood the test of time
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are telltale signs of a favorite recipe: If on a notecard
or piece of paper, it's yellowed and a bit crumpled. Usually, a few
notes have been added to reflect tinkering. And there are age spots
where years of joyful alchemy have splashed onto the page.
</P>
<P>
   I have such a recipe I like to pull out at this time of year. I
acquired it on a college road trip in 1984, when I wandered into
the New Orleans School of Cooking. My companions quickly informed
me that a cooking class was not their idea of living it up in the
French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But even they'd have to admit I came away with the best souvenir
_ cooking school owner Joe Cahn's recipe for bread pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 16 years, I've made the sweet, sopping stuff
straight up, with raisins and plenty of whiskey sauce. And I've
tried many variations _ with pineapple and coconut, ``pina colada''
style; with pumpkin puree and pecans; and with loads of chocolate
chips. Sometimes, it's rum sauce instead of whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a more happy marriage of frugal and
festive. And though the revelers in the French Quarter may prefer
King Cake this week, my favorite Fat Tuesday indulgence has to be
bread pudding.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's a food that has comforted through the ages. Just
read this 1747 description of ``boiled loaf'' that Richard Sax
found while researching bread puddings for his book ``Classic Home
Desserts'' (Chapters, $29.95):
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a Penny-loaf (ordinary bread, milled from coarse flour),
pour over it a half a Pint of Milk boiling hot, cover it close, let
it stand till it has soaked up the milk then tye it up in a cloth
and boil it a quarter of an hour, '' wrote Hannah Glasse of London
in ``The Art of Cookery, Made Plain and Easy.'' ``When it is done,
lay it in your Dish, and pour melted Butter over it, and throw
Sugar all over, a Spoonful of Wine, or Rosewater, as well in the
Butter, or Juice of a Seville Orange.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, in fact, a whole class of desserts that use bread
crumbs, chunks or slices, such as queen's pudding, summer puddings
and some types of charlottes, explains Alan Davidson in the
``Oxford Companion to Food'' (Oxford University Press, $60.)
</P>
<P>
   But the simplest has always been taking stale bread, soaking it
in milk, sweetening it by one means or another and baking the
result. Versions of this dessert can be traced back to medieval
``sops'' in Europe and to the countrysides of the Middle East and
India centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   It no doubt has survived because the central ingredient _ stale
bread _ has never gone away. What family today doesn't find itself
with a considerable bread supply _ sliced bread for sandwiches,
buns for hot dogs and burgers, loaves of French or Italian bread
for dinner. Inevitably, some of it goes stale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take all of that bread and throw it in a dish and put
a custard on it and it will be good,'' said Carole Lalli, author of
``Yesterday's Bread'' (HarperPerennial, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   Slices of white and wheat sandwich bread work great. So does
fancy brioche, panettone and even stale cake. All work beautifully
as sponges for rich custards of milk and eggs or, as in the Mexican
tradition, syrups of brown sugar and spices.
</P>
<P>
   Fillings also can vary, from sweet to savory. Wild mushrooms and
leftover boiled potatoes (cut into chunks) mix well. Inside we give
one of Lalli's recipes, sure to be useful to many a Southerner,
using corn bread and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   A classic New Orleans bread pudding, coming from the rustic
French and English traditions, simply has raisins as a sweetener.
But dried apricots, cherries or cranberries are delicious. So are
fruits like pears, apples and peaches. And, of course, chocolate is
divine.
</P>
<P>
   The classic New Orleans sauce is a buttery whiskey concoction,
but it can be altered as well. Rum is nice. Kahlua is good.
Basically, the whole dessert can be modified to use what's on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Try some of the recipes inside, like Martha Stewart's sinfully
delicious chocolate bread pudding or Lalli's cranberry/pear combo.
And, of course, we included Joe Cahn's recipe _ that gem from my
first trip to the French Quarter. It's a classic that will be
friendly to whatever is in the pantry. One bite, and we promise the
good times will roll.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
