<HEADER>
A3149 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP02-COX     03-01 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cake gives visitors the royal treatment
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lois Fenderson of Prineville, Ore., came through just in time
with a Mardi Gras King Cake for Jane Johnson of Powder Springs, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet egg bread is as much a part of the pre-Lent party as
strings of cheap purple, gold and green beads _ festival colors
repeated in tinted sugar sprinkled on top of the cakes.
</P>
<P>
   This version, from the cookbook ``Jambalaya'' by the Junior
League of New Orleans, calls for a cinnamon filling and a
sprinkling of sugars on an egg wash before baking. Others, like the
one on the front of this section now available from la Madeleine
stores, are frosted first, and then decorated with tinted sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Bakers always put in a plastic baby, toy or bean to symbolize
the baby Jesus. Find it in your slice and you'll be treated as king
or queen for the day, but you'll also be obliged to buy or make the
next King Cake or even to host the next party.
</P>
<P>
   Bon chance!
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mardi Gras King Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 cakes, about 16 slices each
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Rising time: 2 1/2-3 hours, divided
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the cakes:
</P>
<P>
   9 tablespoons (1 stick plus 1 tablespoon) butter, divided use
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup evaporated skim milk (99 percent fat free)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar, divided use
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 envelopes dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated lemon rind
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated orange rind
</P>
<P>
   6 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter, melted, divided use
</P>
<P>
   For the topping:
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar, divided and colored (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 plastic babies ( 3/4 inch), trinkets or beans
</P>
<P>
   For the cakes: In a small pot, place 1 stick butter, milk, 1/3
cup sugar and salt. Stir occasionally over low heat until butter
melts. Set aside to cool to lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine 2 tablespoons sugar, yeast and
warm water. Let stand until foaming, about 5 to 10 minutes. Beat
eggs into the foaming yeast, then add the cooled milk mixture and
the grated rinds. Stir in the flour, 1/2 cup at a time, reserving 1
cup flour on the kneading surface. Knead dough until it is smooth,
about 5 to 10 minutes. Grease large mixing bowl with 1 tablespoon
butter. Place dough in prepared bowl, turning once to grease the
top of the dough. Cover and let rise in a warm place until double,
about 1 1/2 to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: Mix brown and white sugars with cinnamon and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   When dough has doubled, punch it down and divide in half. On a
floured surface, roll one half into a rectangle about 30 by 15
inches. Brush with half the melted butter and cut into three
lengthwise strips. Sprinkle half the sugar-cinnamon mixture on the
strips, leaving a 1-inch lengthwise strip free for sealing. Fold
each strip lengthwise toward the center, sealing the seam. You now
have three 30-inch strips with sugar mixture enclosed in each.
Braid the three strips, working from the center, and make a circle
by joining the ends. Repeat with the other half of the dough and
filling. Place each cake on a 10-by-15-inch baking sheet, cover
with a damp cloth and let rise until double, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. When doubled, brush each cake with
beaten egg and sprinkle top with colored sugars, alternating
colors. Bake 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from pans immediately so the sugar won't harden. While
warm, place 1 plastic baby, trinket or bean in each cake from
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To tint sugar, separate into thirds to make yellow, purple
and green. Drop food coloring into each 1/3 cup sugar, mixing until
desired color is reached. To speed mixing and keep from getting too
moist, sugar may be tinted in the food processor.
</P>
<P>
   To free
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
