<HEADER>
A3153 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-JOB-INTERVIEWS-HNS &LR;      03-01 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-INTERVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHEN INTERVIEWING JOB APPLICANTS, KEEP `WHY' IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you're a boss preparing for a round of job
interviews, there is one question you should focus on more than any
other: Why?
</P>
<P>
   No, not ``Why do you want to work for us?'' or ``Why did you
leave your last employer?'' This ``why?'' is not a question to ask
your applicants, but to ask yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Why do you base so much of your company's future on an hour or
two of conversation? The job interview has been the standard
practice for decades, but in this era of downsized work forces and
overstressed employees, hiring mistakes are even costlier than they
used to be. And the job interview needs to be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to look back 100 years from now and look
at interviews like we look on gaslights or silent movies or Model T
Fords,'' said Pierre Mornell, the psychiatrist who wrote ``Hiring
Smart: How to Predict Winners &AMP; Losers in the Incredibly Expensive
People-Reading Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers realize this, sort of. They're asking more questions
about how the candidate has behaved in the past, such as, ``Tell me
about a time you had a problem with a co-worker and how you
resolved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two cottage industries have even sprung up, with one set of
books offering tips on how to answer job interview questions, and
another set of books offering tips on how employers can surprise
workers with questions that aren't covered in the first set of
books.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody has stopped to ask: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, an interview measures chemistry, poise and communication
skills, but mostly what it measures is the ability to do well in a
job interview. So someone who goes job hunting every six months
will probably be great at it. But is that a skill you really need _
or want?
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry is certainly crucial, but you'll probably decide in
the first five minutes whether the applicant would be a good fit,
even if all the two of you do is sing ``Kumbaya'' together.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, relying too much on chemistry can backfire. If you and
the applicant have a mutual friend or went to the same high school
or share a particular hobby, you might feel an instant connection
that leads you to overlook a weakness. You might also penalize
those who are different from you because you don't have that same
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to your gut feeling, certainly, but don't let your brain
take a holiday. Remember that con artists excel at chemistry, too.
</P>
<P>
   Poise is also important, but interviews give it more emphasis
than it deserves. Suppose you ask that chestnut, ``What's your
biggest weakness?''
</P>
<P>
   Applicants familiar with job interviews will know what to do: Be
as insincere as is humanly possible, coming up with some innocuous
weakness or explaining how you've overcome a past weakness.
</P>
<P>
   But suppose your applicant sputters and has trouble answering,
or says something lik, ``Well, you know, I really should work more
on my computer skills.'' He flunked the poise test. But you'll
probably give that answer more weight than it deserves when you
decide whom to hire.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking quickly is a good skill _ especially if you're in
something like customer service or public safety _ but how
important is it really for your workers? Do most problems have to
be solved instantly, or can you think about them overnight? Do you
need a marketing plan in 15 minutes, or in 15 days?
</P>
<P>
   Does your hiring process reflect that? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me about a time you had a problem with a co-worker and
how you resolved it,'' for example, could be a useful question. But
what types of people are going to have an answer to it on the tip
of their tongues? Those who have done a lot of job interviews or
those who have had such a big conflict that it still stands out in
their mind, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make them better applicants than everyone else?
Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you give applicants some questions like that a few days
before the interview. Tell them you will ask those questions during
the interview or ask them to write their answers and bring them to
the interview. You'll still be measuring communication skills _
even written communication, if that's important _ but you'll get
more thoughtful answers.
</P>
<P>
   To protect yourself from phoniness, try to see samples of the
applicant's work. Sometimes, too, you can give an assignment before
or after the interview, such as preparing a marketing plan for a
product.
</P>
<P>
   Mornell also suggests asking applicants to call back at a
specific day and time after the interview. That shows
responsibility and attention to detail. (My two cents: If they call
back at the right time and you already have their thank you note in
hand, you may just have a winner.)
</P>
<P>
   All these things will put the interview into perspective, and
you still won't be ignoring chemistry and communication skills. You
should save some surprises for the interview to measure poise, but
use questions that demonstrate work-related skills rather than
job-hunting ones.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite interview question sounds flaky: ``What's your
favorite Web site?'' I ask it mostly to weed people out; if you're
in the working world and you haven't tried the Web by now, you sure
don't seem to have much in the way of initiative or curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   I also like it because there is no ``right'' answer. There are
few absolutely right answers in the world of work, but that
shouldn't stop you from asking the right questions. And make sure
one of them is always: Why?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
