<HEADER>
A3164 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-SHOW-COX     03-01 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-SHOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOWTIME!
 &HT;    Wrestling fans know what they want and the industry knows how to
throw a show
 &HT;    By Todd C. Duncan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's 15 minutes before a live taping of the World
Wrestling Federation's ``Raw is War'' event in Atlanta and the
faithful can barely handle the wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to rock,'' said Mickey Davies of Fulton County, Ga.
``I want to see my boys. Whoooohooooo!''
</P>
<P>
   Davies, 19, is not the only one fidgeting in his seat. The crowd
of 28,000 is waiting to go nuts. They want to crank it up. They
know what's coming.
</P>
<P>
   The house lights go down. The Dome erupts. It's so loud you
can't hear the person yelling next to you.
</P>
<P>
   Handmade signs of all different shapes and colors are hoisted in
the air as if they were colors raised in battle.
</P>
<P>
   It's show time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw's'' heavy metal theme music blares from the arena's sound
system. The crowd screams as images of their favorite wrestlers are
flashed on a giant television screen.
</P>
<P>
   Dads put children to their shoulders to improve the view for the
little ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to see this,'' one dad says, hoisting a preschooler
above his head. ``It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   What would make thousands of people go bananas for a sporting
event whose outcome the spectators know has been predetermined?
</P>
<P>
   It's all about the show, baby!
</P>
<P>
   The head honchos of this pile-driving sports entertainment
industry know what the people want and seem to respond to fan's
desires better than the folks at the NFL, NBA, NHL and MLB.
</P>
<P>
   With soap opera-style storylines, good villains, sex appeal,
explosions and laser effects, today's professional wrestling has
become the new American theater.
</P>
<P>
   WWF, the Stamford, Conn.-based company, has generated hundreds
of millions of dollars in revenue and its two weekly TV programs
attract millions of viewers. The stars of the WWF are known
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities and sports stars can't even resist these events.
Mike Tyson and Dennis Rodman have entered the ring and actor Arnold
Schwarzenegger recently got into the act during a WWF
``Smackdown!'' At the ``Raw'' show, Atlanta Falcons star running
back Jamal Anderson and rapper/producer/record company executive
Jermaine Dupri were trying to figure out where they could sit
without being mobbed by fans. They didn't want to answer a
reporter's questions about their love for wrestling, but Anderson
did snap photos with his fans. Their group ended up watching the
matches near the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have as close to a full house as you can get in
here,'' said Adam Hopkins of WWF Entertainment Inc. about the
Atlanta venue.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage, there is no tension.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestlers _ in different stages of dress _ mill about. Some are
trying to break a sweat before their match, while others joke with
each other.
</P>
<P>
   At a table, a couple of seamstresses mend several colorful
outfits. If you're a wrestler, you don't want to lose your Lycra.
</P>
<P>
   During the preliminary matches, the crowd is subdued. Fans walk
around and talk to each other during matches. A few bouts involve
wrestlers with a name, but the early bouts are usually for the
rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a chance for the guys (wrestlers) to tryout,''
said Hopkins. ``When we go on the air, they'll (the fans) get a
show.''
</P>
<P>
   And that they do.
</P>
<P>
   With all of the drama of a Broadway play, an evening with the
WWF unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The hated Triple H enters the ring and is meet with a chorus of
boos. He and his ``wife,'' Stephanie McMahon, daughter of WWF
founder and CEO Vince McMahon, bask in every negative comment.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, the lights go out, and the entrance music for the man
most of fans came to see starts playing. A woman screams, ``Oh my
God, here he comes.''
</P>
<P>
   As planned, at exactly 9:04 p.m., the Rock _ better known as the
``people's champion'' _ enters the Dome. Hundreds of fans rush to
the stage to take his photograph or just to get a closer look.
Security officers in yellow jackets do a great job of keeping
everyone in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   One woman declares, ``he's the most beautiful man on earth.''
Now that's something to live up to.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock, however, doesn't disappoint. ``Finally, the Rock has
come to Atlanta,'' He bellows.
</P>
<P>
   The fans chant. ``Rock. Rock. Rock. Rock!'' He has them in the
palm of his hand and he doesn't even have to get in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Four guys from Conyers, Ga., Rich Cannon, 28, Jordan Canon, 17,
Mark Jones, 16 and Alex Smith, 16, each hold up silver letters that
spell, R-O-C-K.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love this, '' said Rich Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling industry has been criticized for its violent and
misogynistic storylines and characters.
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlanta show, the Godfather _in full pimp attire _
entered the ring with a dozen scantily-clad women and asked the
crowd to ride the ``ho train.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana University and the TV program ``Inside Edition''
recently surveyed 50 episodes of the USA network's Monday night
fixture ``Raw'' between January 1998 and February 1999. Researchers
found 1,658 instances of crotch grabbing, 128 simulated sexual
activities, 157 flippings of the finger, 47 instances of simulated
satanic activity, and 42 cases of simulated drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Fans don't seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' said Jon Weaver, 20, of Athens, Ga. ``It's
the Rock and the hos.''
</P>
<P>
   What a show.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
