u s BC-BKN-CARTER-BOS &LR;      03-01 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCE CARTER: A STAR IS AIRBORNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's a new section in the Toronto Raptors game
notes. It's called ``Time Changes.'' The Raptors have been forced
to make some scheduling adjustments lately, something they're not
accustomed to doing.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, the Raptors were switched to a national game on NBC
to spotlight and showcase Vince Carter. He then went out and set a
franchise record by scoring 51 points in a 1-point win over the
Suns. That snapped the previous franchise record of 47 held by,
yup, Carter. That one stood for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   NBC already has decided to pick up the Raptors-Timberwolves game
in prime time March 26. The Toronto game next Monday in Portland
has been moved to accommodate TNT. The TV basketball folks are only
a part of the rush.
</P>
<P>
   Carter already has done Letterman. The Make-A-Wish Foundation of
Greater Boston has arranged for a Nantucket teenager to visit with
Carter this week and play some one-on-one after attending a Raptors
practice.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, the Celtics will get him twice in the next three
days: Wednesday in Boston and Friday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since his performance in the Slam Dunk competition during
All-Star weekend _ ``It put me on the map,'' Carter acknowledged _
and the explosion eight days later against Phoenix, Carter has been
hot. As in Jordan. In the Raptors' first home game after the
All-Star Game, the penultimate line of ``Oh Canada!'' was amended
from ``Oh Canada, we stand on guard for thee'' to ``Oh Vince
Carter, you are amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   He's the current Sports Illustrated cover boy. He's the NBA
Player of the Week for the second time this season. He is among the
top five scorers in the league, the top vote-getter for the
All-Star team (fans), the reigning Rookie of the Year. He's an
attention grabber on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Asked recently if he was surprised by all the hoopla, Carter
said, ``I'm overwhelmed. It's happening so fast. I have the ability
to play in this league and to be where I am. I just didn't think it
would happen so fast . . . I try to make it as easy as possible.
The guys expect me to contribute and give 100 percent to the team,
regardless of Letterman or All-Star Weekend. I take a valiant
effort to focus on what I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He's already the latest in a long line of Next Jordans. He
shares an alma mater with Michael _ North Carolina _ as well as an
ability to play above the rim and to dunk, spectacularly. In
talking about his Make-A-Wish meeting with Carter, 13-year-old
Michael Ferreira of Nantucket said Tuesday, ``I've liked him for
about a year. I like his dunks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carter can do other stuff that you don't see on
``SportsCenter.'' He leads Toronto in steals. He's second in
assists and third in blocked shots and rebounds. He's put Toronto
on the NBA map and made the Raptors must-see basketball. Fans in
that hockey-mad city have filled the Air Canada Centre to capacity
nine times. Jordan did that for a moribund Chicago franchise, too.
</P>
<P>
   And, Rick Pitino observed, Carter already can do something
Jordan couldn't do at a similar age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, the only way you could play Michael was to play off
him and hope he would miss,'' Pitino said. ``Then he became a very
good outside shooter. This young man (Carter) is becoming a better
outside shooter earlier on in his career. He's shooting the three.
There are so many different ways that he can hurt you . . . You
have to concentrate on him because obviously he's capable, as he
did the other night, of getting 51 points. You have to concentrate
on him because he's capable of having an unbelievable game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics know all about Carter. They were witness to what
many felt was his Coming Out Party last year in Toronto March 7,
when he dropped 26 on Paul Pierce, then the presumptive leader for
Rookie of the Year, in a 105-92 Toronto victory. There was no
stopping him the rest of the abbreviated season.
</P>
<P>
   But they've held him in check this season in taking both games
from the Raptors. Carter was an Iversonian 8 of 28 in a 94-90 loss
to the Celtics Jan. 19 in Boston and a Walkerian 3 of 12 in the
season-opening 103-90 loss to the Celtics in Toronto. That is the
one blemish on Carter's resume; his team isn't that good.
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Vince, All-The-Time stuff started after the
All-Star Game, the Raptors have managed to lose to Denver and
Dallas at home and are playing .500 basketball. They are in a pack
of conference wannabes right now, although they have beaten the
Knicks twice since the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be looking for payback against Boston. Calbert Cheaney,
who hasn't played a almost three weeks, will draw the unenviable
task of guarding Carter out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney has had other things on his mind since he last played.
His wife delivered a baby son Tuesday morning after a complicated,
difficult pregnancy. He didn't go west with the Celtics and he
wasn't at Monday's game against the Mavericks. He'll be there
Wednesday, but only as the first of many foils of the man everyone
wants to see these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
