<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3193 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-GOODMAN-2TAKES-BO     03-01 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GOODMAN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODMAN GOING ON FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHLAND, N.J. _ ``How's Jewish Jordan doing?''
</P>
<P>
   The query was repeated over and again by many who walked into
the dimly lit gym late. The people were of all races, colors, ages,
and gender. They uttered it, and then they scanned the court,
eventually homing in on the lanky player whose yarmulke was
fastened to his closely cropped, fire-red hair.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Tamir Goodman touched the ball _ which, to the chagrin
of many in the crowd, wasn't often in the first half _ much of the
chatter stopped. Whenever the 18-year-old player, an Orthodox Jew
from Baltimore, let the basketball fly, someone in the crowd
uttered the moniker again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to get Jewish Jordan the ball more.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd at the Atlantic Cape Classic game knew him as
the high school basketball player who made national headlines for
his Division 1 skills and his commitment to a life of Torah
observance _ notably, his refusal to play on Shabbat (the Jewish
Sabbath, sundown Friday to sundown Saturday), when many college
games are held.
</P>
<P>
   His notoriety grew when the University of Maryland offered him a
scholarship halfway into his junior season. When the school's
interest waned, Goodman opted for America East member Towson (Md.)
University and cited friction with the Maryland coaching staff over
his unwillingness to play on Shabbat.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented attempt to help a player observe his
beliefs, the America East, at the request of Towson and with the
concurrence of league members, moved Towson's league games next
season away from the period of the Jewish Sabbath. The issue will
be revisited each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get him the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman began playing at Talmudical Academy, a yeshiva in the
Baltimore area that has fewer than 100 students, where he averaged
35.4 points, 7.5 assists, and 6.5 rebounds per game. Wanting to
improve his level of competition, he transferred to Takoma Academy,
a Seventh Day Adventist school in suburban Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his move, many coaches at the major college level _
Maryland included _ question whether the 6-foot-3-inch, 170-pound
player can compete at their level.
</P>
<P>
   Over the latter portion of the second quarter of Takoma's game,
Goodman made believers of most everyone in the crowd. He scored 13
of his team's 15 points in 2:02 _ on three consecutive NBA-range
3-pointers, a nifty pass fake and layup, and a steal and finger
roll that set off a high-fiving, fist-clenching frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Some folks dropped the first word from the nickname, and for a
moment, it didn't matter whether he topped his crown with a
yarmulke or turban or headband or nothing at all. On a court that,
like the crowd, consisted of players of all races, he was the best
on it, as Michael Jordan used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``That dude's a player.''
</P>
<P>
   What a wonder it is when the heavens throw a wrench at
preconceived notions _ just as folks believe they have enough
evidence to confidently assert how some cannot play quarterback in
the NFL, some cannot win a 100-meter dash, some are best suited for
housework.
</P>
<P>
   It seems irresponsible to link a high school player with the
greatest who's ever played the game. (Some who do so hardly know
the difference between Michael Jordan and Michael Bolton.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Goodman's story should be an uplifting one _ an
18-year-old whose quickness and athleticism defies the stereotype
that young Orthodox Jews would be more comfortable in a clasroom
than on a basketball court. He's a mature young man with his
priorities in order, and whose devotion to his faith is ahead of
his passion for basketball.
</P>
<P>
   He might take inspiration, as so many young Jewish athletes have
over the years, from Sandy Koufax. The outstanding Dodger pitcher
repeatedly declined to pitch on Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur, the
holiest days of the Jewish year, which often coincided with the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Like Koufax, Goodman has become a walking topic for debate, on
where the sacred begins and the secular ends, where individual
concerns fall with respect to team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving it a shot
</P>
<P>
   The 8-year-old wanted to be like his older brother. To him,
Reuvane Goodman was the coolest guy at Talmudical Academy, a small
Orthodox yeshiva in the Baltimore area, and he wanted to be the
same when he got older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm on the basketball team,'' Reuvane told him, and he
took Goodman to practice with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never left the gym,'' Goodman said. ``I went to all his
games and all his practices, and I watched on the sidelines. I just
loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he went home and tried emulating what he saw on the court.
For six days a week, rain or shine, day and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would wake up at 6 in the morning and shoot, and then go
and shoot at 11 o'clock at night with no lights outside,'' said
Harold Katz, the former coach at Talmudical and Goodman's current
adviser. ``Then he would come over and tell me about a move, as a
coach would, and most kids at 8 or 9 couldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman was still pipe-cleaner thin, but he began to grow, and
though he didn't play organized basketball until 10th grade, he
developed a flair for finesse and athleticism in pickup games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put together a scrimmage with our players and Tamir and
other players when he was in ninth grade,`` said Katz. ``Tamir
didn't make a shot, but there was one possession where he went into
the paint and hung up there for a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made you _ whew _ Jews can't do that. It was those things
that made you say, `What's that all about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman joined the Talmudical team as a sophomore and became a
scoring, passing sensation. As a junior, he scored 40 points in a
game 15 times. Once, he notched 24 points in one quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Fans dubbed him, the ``Jewish Jordan,'' and one time, the
moniker blared over the Talmudical public address system as Goodman
finished a play with a two-handed reverse dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Katz's teams began faring well against non-Orthodox schools in
Baltimore, a recruiting hotbed. ``Tamir got everyone's best game,''
Katz said, adding that Goodman was often hit with racial slurs and
overly physical play from those unaccustomed to guarding an
Orthodox player with his skills.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman scoffs at the notion that his background makes him
unique. ``I hear it a lot, and it's kind of a stereotype,'' he
said. ``People think a lot of kids like me aren't developed for the
field I want to go into because of their background, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's totally opposite. Because of my background, it
has helped me out more than anything. It's the biggest advantage I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there were days he could not play while others could.
``When you become a teenager, you stay out of trouble because of
your religion, and you become a better player because of all the
discipline you have because of your religion,'' he said. ``It just
transfers onto the court.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
