<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3203 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GARAGE-DOOR-TRIAL-HNS     03-01 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARAGE-DOOR-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIREFIGHTER'S SUIT AGAINST DOOR OPENER COMPANY NEARS COURT
DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The case of a severely injured firefighter who
has sued a leading manufacturer of garage door openers is scheduled
to go to trial next week in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Stapper, 39, is seeking nearly at least $8 million from
the Genie Corp. She contends that she and a fellow firefighter were
trapped inside a garage while fighting a house fire on March 9,
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyers contend that the garage door opener did not work,
and that the nylon cord that can disengage the door from the
automatic system had burned.
</P>
<P>
   Stapper, who no longer works for the Fire Department, suffered
burns over 40 percent of her body and was left permanently scarred
and legally blind.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Mambretti, a 25-year veteran of the department, died in
the fire. Two other firefighters, Keith Onishi and John Pieretti,
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melanie can't work anymore,'' said Browne Greene, a lawyer
representing Stapper. ``It was one of the most tragic fires the San
Francisco Fire Department ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   During a pretrial hearing on Tuesday, Genie lawyers argued that
their product was not at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that what happened to Melanie Stapper is a tragic
situation,'' said Mary Wirth, one of the lawyers representing the
company. ``But it didn't happen because of a faulty garage door
opener. She was injured because the firefighters did not watch her
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapper and the other firefighters entered the burning home
through the garage door. According to reports, there was no smoke
or flames in the garage when the firefighters carried a hose
through the garage to get to the burning house.
</P>
<P>
   Heat and smoke forced Stapper and Mambretti to retreat to the
garage, but by then the door had closed and would not open. It took
firefighters outside more than 10 minutes, according to reports, to
cut a hole in the door and get their colleagues out. Stapper was
badly burned and Mambretti died a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   Stapper's lawyers said they were seeking more than $1 million
for medical expenses, $5 million for future medical bills, more
than $2 million for lost wages and an unspecified amount for
general pain and suffering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-GOODMAN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     03-01 2422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GOODMAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 RICHLAND, N.J.: ... the court.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he grew as a player, Division 1 colleges took notice, most
notably Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Katz said Maryland offered Goodman a scholarship after attending
two Talmudical games, and Goodman accepted early last January.
Still, he said, Goodman met with the coaches, and the Sabbath
issue, which had been raised by Maryland, was discussed at length.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told them if it was a doable thing, he would love to come
to Maryland,'' said Katz, ``but he said if not, he couldn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz said Maryland coach Gary Williams raised a hypothetical:
What if the Terrapins were playing Duke Sunday afternoon and left
Saturday? He said Goodman offered to leave Friday or late Saturday
and to pay for travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   He said Williams said the school would take care of the costs if
it came to that. ``He told Tamir, and this is a direct quote, `I
don't think that's much of a problem,' '' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, Katz said he began hearing otherwise. ``The
word on the street was that they were saying, `If he's good enough
we'll be happy. If not, he'll be a practice player or go
elsewhere,' '' he said. ``I kept calling them, asking about it, and
they kept saying, `If you didn't hear it from us, it isn't true.'
''
</P>
<P>
   By May, Katz said Goodman had heard it so often that he began
doubting it would come to fruition. Then he suffered a medial
colateral ligament sprain prior to attending two of the nation's
most prestigious summer camps, ABCD and Five Star. He went anyway,
but struggled at both.
</P>
<P>
   After a Sept. 2 meeting among Goodman, his mother, and Williams,
presumably to iron things out, Goodman announced he would not
accept the school's offer. He signed a letter of intent to attend
Towson in November.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, many college coaches insist he still isn't suited
for the major college game and that he is better off at Towson.
When told about his exploits at the recent Atlantic Cape Classic,
some coaches asked first about the level of competition he was
playing against.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem I have with that is that most of those guys who
have those opinions of Tamir either saw him play at ABCD or Five
Star, when he was hurt, or never saw him play at all,'' Katz said.
``I think Maryland eventually lost interest because of the Sabbath
and because people forgot he was a junior. With all that hype he
got, they thought he should make every shot, dunk every ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman and Maryland officials agree on two things: It's time to
move on from the matter, and he's better off at Towson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known about Towson at the time, I would have gone
there in the first place,'' said Goodman. ``Maryland is over with
as far as I look at it. I don't hold any grudges against them. It
just wasn't a match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like finding out something bad about your fiancee before
you get married, but you break up. Sometimes things aren't meant to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   But there seems to be a difference of opinion on his ability to
perform at the ACC level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has nothing to do with my skill,'' said Goodman. ``They've
seen me. I've been up there, playing against their team. They've
seen me playing against all the best players in the world. They
offered me a scholarship because they thought I was good enough to
play there. They offered it to me after two games, so obviously
they were impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams chronicled the events this way: ``We offered Tamir
Goodman a scholarship. At this time last year, his junior year, he
verbally committed to us. In the spring and summer, he didn't play
well _ he may have been hurting with a knee. We called him in and
said we would still honor the scholarship, but would he be happy
not playing? He walked out of the office, and he was still happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he is going to Towson. He may or may not be good
enough to start at Towson. He couldn't play at the ACC level. We
made a mistake. But we were still prepared to honor the scholarship
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``About playing on the Sabbath: For 46 years the ACC has played
on Friday, Saturday, and Sunday. He knew that. Then you have
television commitments. He knew all this. We said, maybe, we could
change an occasional Saturday game from 1 to 7 . . . maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole story is that if he's a star player, you might make
more concessions. But if you're an eighth or ninth man, you take
your chances. If you can't play, and the other guy does the job in
your absence, he should play. Every once in a while, you make a
mistake. We made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Night and day
</P>
<P>
   Towson's game at Northeastern next year, originally scheduled
for Saturday afternoon, Feb. 10, has been moved to the night. The
Tigers' game at New Hampshire Saturday afternoon, Jan. 27, has been
moved to the following afternoon. Their game Saturday afternoon,
Jan. 6, at Hartford, has been moved to night.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Goodman will not miss a regular-season game next
season because of his religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   And, should Towson advance to the America East championship
during Goodman's tenure at Towson, America East officials might ask
ESPN, which usually televises the contest on Saturday afternoon, to
schedule it for another time.
</P>
<P>
   America East officials say they have less leeway during the
postseason, as teams play according to seeds. They say the matter
will be addressed in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Said America East commissioner Chris Monasch, ``I think there
are a lot of factors that go into when we schedule games, from
whether an arena will be available to whether it's a people thing,
to if we conflict with hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Towson has requested to play games, whenever possible, on
Thursday and Saturday. Other schools said they would accommodate,
so on that basis, it's much ado about nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman would hardly call it such.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Towson and the America East are concerned, there
aren't enough words in the English language to thank them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman added that if any school cannot reschedule games during
his tenure at Towson, he will sit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I owe (Towson) my life. It's an unbelievable thing,''
Goodman said. ``When I was going into everything, I felt all alone.
Just me, my coach, and my family. To find out, a couple of years
down the road, that my dreams could come true, with people actually
fighting for me, is something I thought was never possible, and I
could never thank them enough for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change for the better
</P>
<P>
   There are some who, like Monasch, wonder what all the fuss is
about. Why not make such allowances for players who give time and
effort being representatives of such institutions?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that comes to my mind is the guy who inspired
the movie, `Chariots of Fire,' who took a stance for his beliefs,''
said Campbell University athletic director Tom Collins, whose
Baptist school, along with Brigham Young University's Mormon-based
student body, doesn't play or practice on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA makes allowances for the schools by scheduling their
postseason contests for other days. ``It's good for institutions to
stand up and support Tamir the same way,'' said Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The three America East coaches whose schedules are affected say
they are also willing to help accommodate Towson. ``Any time our
league can get a quality player, I think everybody in the league
has to be happy about it,'' said Northeastern's Rudy Keeling, ``and
we have to do what we can to facilitate whatever is needed for
getting that player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only negative in moving games is if the games are moved
and it makes us miss more class. I don't think that's fair. But
other than that, I think moving a game, staying a day, moving from
day to night, those things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some question the extent to which a school or conference
accommodates one player in a team sport. Others wonder whether the
America East would be going to such measures if Goodman weren't
someone capable of making an immediate impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talked with (the league's) athletic directors, they
understood the issue and wanted to be supportive,'' said Monasch,
``yet their concern was what if there are five more cases next
year? My feeling is, to not do something because down the line
there are so many other issues is a presumption I don't want to get
into.''
</P>
<P>
   With regards to Goodman's talent, Monasch said, ``The
institution made the request, and we said we would try to work with
it. At that point, we left it at that. We didn't evaluate how good
the player was. I guess the only way I would see the quality of a
player having an impact is if you're talking about integrity of
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   As a hypothetical example, Monasch used Towson's playing in the
America East championship game. ``To go all the way to the end and
not do something reasonable in terms of balancing things out for a
more significant player or two, I don't think that would be doing
right in terms of integrity of competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, would a TV network move a conference
championship game to allow for a player's religious observances?
</P>
<P>
   Said ESPN manager of communications Josh Krulewitz: ``If the
conference considered that request to be that important and if it
fit our schedule and made logical sense, we would consider it.
However, it's not something we can do on the spur of the moment. In
a request like that, a lot of time would be needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Krulewitz said the network begins compiling its postseason
tournament package in the spring and summer prior to the season. He
said the America East has not contacted the network about such
matters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Believable lifestyle
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches already taking steps to accommodate players'
religious beliefs have mixed reviews about the process.
</P>
<P>
   One coach at a prominent major college in the Northeast, who
asked that his name not be used, said his program has taken major
steps to accommodate a player's beliefs with regards to practice
time and game meals.
</P>
<P>
   But the coach said he later discovered the player was having
premarital sex, which ran contrary to the player's religious
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him out on it,'' the coach said. ``My thing is, if
you're asking me to make concessions because of your religious
beliefs, I'm saying you should follow those beliefs all the way.
For you to get us to help you observe one facet of your faith while
you're violating another is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we practicing early in the morning and doing all sorts
of things for him if he's going to turn around and go out and do
whatever he wants?''
</P>
<P>
   Does that make a coach an unfair judge on whether a player is
following his beliefs _ or does the player put himself or herself
in that position by asking a school to help him or her observe such
tenets?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see how coaches could have a problem with that, but
that situation is unique because you're talking about an
individual,'' said BYU athletic director Val Hale.
</P>
<P>
   He said his school never runs into such problems because it has
made observing religious beliefs part of school policy, and those
who violate them are dismissed from the school.
</P>
<P>
   Many do not believe much will change for Orthodox Jewish
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most yeshiva players that go into American society should know
that it does not,'' said Garry Katz, principal at Maimonides
School, a modern Orthodox day school in Brookline. ``As a former
all-city track runner in college, I suffered enormously because I
could not make Friday or Saturday practices and meets. It is
difficult, because Friday and Saturday are such staples in college
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is a part of a Jewish boy's life, but it is not a
dominant factor, nor should it be. If it can work out, great, but
most schools will not, nor should they be, expected to play, or
tailor, their schedules to one or two players.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there were circumstances under which an Orthodox Jewish
player could participate in a game but not travel, Rabbi David
Ehrenkranz, the Orthodox rabbinic adviser at Brandeis, gave an
unequivocal, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No Jew who reaches bar mitzvah age for boys or bat mitzvah for
girls, would be allowed to play on Shabbat, late Friday afternoon
through Saturday night,'' he said. ``Now, I'm sure some people will
read this and say, `No, that only applies to Orthodox Jews.' But
the Torah applies to all Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, increasing numbers of reform and conservative Jews are
Sabbath observant. That means that from sundown Friday through
sundown Saturday, they don't drive, don't do any work, often
worship at a synagogue, and generally try to spend the day with
their families in a more reflective mode.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the transition
</P>
<P>
   Towson coach Mike Jaskulski, who met with Goodman's family for
five hours before signing Goodman, said he addressed the
recruitment of Goodman and matters concerning it with current
players beforehand, and they had no problem with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to work very hard to make sure he doesn't miss any
practices or games so he is indeed accountable like anyone else on
the team,'' said Jaskulski. ``If that means having practices
earlier on Friday afternoons, we'll do that. If someone else has
classes on Friday afternoons, we'll have practices on Friday
mornings, to make sure everyone is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaskulski said he believes the school has a gem in Goodman. ``He
is probably about as well-prepared cerebrally as any player I have
come in contact with,'' the coach said. ``That will make his
transition to college basketball better in terms of our style of
play.''
</P>
<P>
   How Goodman fares at the next level remains to be seen, as is
the impact he will have on other Orthodox Jewish players looking to
do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question here is, where is a player's priority?'' said
Garry Katz of Maimonides. ``That is the question Tamir will have to
ask himself. ``He will not play in the NBA. If he thinks he will,
he shouldn't, because the NBA is not going to revise its schedule
for him. For him to use basketball to get a good education is, as
far as I'm concerned, the most important thing for a Jewish boy to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Katz said, folks should drop the ``Jewish Jordan''
reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction to it was how unfair it is to do that to
him,'' he said. ``He's not Jordan. He has an identity of his own.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
