<HEADER>
A3211 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     03-01 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A STEW? HERE'S HELP. STUFFING, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wanda Fox-Thetford, Graham, saw Lisa Day Johnson's request for a
stuffing that her grandmother made in the 1950s. Fox-Thetford got
the recipe from an Italian friend from Michigan in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Herron saw the request for a beef stew that includes
onions and mushrooms. She responded with the ``town stew'' recipe.
``This sounds very much like a recipe I've made for winter dinner
parties. It's from ``The Southern Junior League Cookbook,'' edited
by Ann Seranne. This is a stew for the purist. When it is
well-made, the result should be beautifully brown gravy containing
tender pieces of meat, whole small onions and mushrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The third recipe was sent by Brenda Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ITALIAN STUFFING FOR TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10-12
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ground pork
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground veal
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dried or 1/3 cup fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   Saute all meat, together, until done. Drain. Add all other
ingredients and stuff turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 389 calories, 20 grams fat, 20
grams carbohydrates, 32 grams protein, 126 milligrams cholesterol,
173 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   OUR TOWN STEW
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds beef stew meat, cut into chunks or cubes
</P>
<P>
   Flour
</P>
<P>
   Shortening (or half olive oil and half butter)
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, sliced (may use more)
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces beer
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   30-35 small pearl onions, peeled
</P>
<P>
   30-35 fresh mushroom caps
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper meat well.
</P>
<P>
   Dredge in flour, making sure all sides are well-covered.
</P>
<P>
   Brown meat in shortening in a heavy pot, along with 1 clove of
garlic. When the meat is richly brown, pour the beer over it.
</P>
<P>
   Add water to cover meat. (More beer may be used, but too much
will give a slightly bitter taste.) Add second clove of garlic and
a bit of cayenne. Bring to boil, reduce heat, simmer 1 1/2 to 2
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Correct seasoning, add onions and cook until onions are tender
but still whole. During last 10 minutes, stir in mushroom caps. Add
just a little water if desired to increase amount of gravy. Stew
should be served with mashed potatoes or noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 354 calories, 27 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 23 grams protein, 91 milligrams cholesterol,
64 milligrams sodium, 69 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BEEF BURGUNDY
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 slices bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds beef stew meat, lean
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces sliced mushrooms, fresh or canned/drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Italian seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red wine, preferably burgundy
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked noodles
</P>
<P>
   Saute the bacon in a large, heavy skillet until crisp. Remove to
plate to cool, then crumble into a large casserole. Brown the beef
in the bacon fat. Place beef in the casserole. Top with onion,
mushrooms, Italian seasoning, parsley and bay leaf. Add olive oil
to skillet, if necessary, to bring the remaining fat to about 3
tablespoons. Add flour and brown. Add beef broth and wine. Bring to
a boil and simmer until slightly thickened. Pour over meat and
other ingredients in the casserole. Bake, covered, at 325 degrees
for 2-3 hours. Remove bay leaf and serve over noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can double this recipe; after it has cooled, place the
beef mixture only in single-serve freezer bags, and freeze for
future use.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 346 calories, 9 grams fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 32 grams protein, 81 milligrams cholesterol,
221 milligrams sodium, 24 percent of calories from fat. Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Christine Allums would like to replace a missing recipe. It's
called harvest cake, and she think it included nuts and raisins.
She got if off the back of an Imperial sugar box but can't remember
if it was white sugar or brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Lowe, Granbury, would like a recipe for a caramel custard
pie that her grandmother used to make. She referred to it as
``burnt caramel custard.'' Most pies that go by the name caramel
custard don't have the same ``burnt'' caramel taste that Wanda
remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Hardy, Fresno, Calif., attended a Tupperware party years ago
and was given a recipe for refrigerator rolls that included yeast
in the mix. The rolls could be sealed and stored for up to 3 weeks
and were handy in that you didn't have to make up the whole batch
of biscuits at once.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Jobe would like a recipe for a layer cake made with candied
orange slices. It has a glaze frosting that soaks into the layers
of the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader would like the recipe for Nancy Ware mandarin
orange cake.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Clark, Fort Worth, would like to replace a recipe for
caramel corn made in the microwave. The ingredients include dark
corn syrup or molasses, butter, brown sugar and baking soda that's
poured over popped corn.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader would like to replace a recipe for a peach
cobbler made with buttermilk and mixed in an ovenproof bowl.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
