<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB JONES UNIVERSITY: CONSERVATIVE FROM THE START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Jones Sr., the founder of the university that today bears
his name, was a well-known evangelist at the turn of the century
whose family has over the years remained committed to the most
conservative, and occasionally separatist, form of fundamentalist
Protestantism.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th child of an Alabama sharecropper, Jones Sr. started Bob
Jones College in College Point, Fla., in 1926 when his followers
complained that their children were losing their faith upon
attending college. The college opened just two years after the
Tennessee trial of high school biology teacher John Scopes for
teaching evolution, an event that helped fuel hostility toward
fundamentalist Christianity in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones College struggled under Jones Sr., even going bankrupt
in 1933, but moved to Cleveland, Tenn., and then in 1947 to its
current location in Greenville, S.C., where it was revitalized
under the leadership of Jones's fiery-tongued son, Bob Jones Jr.
The school now has about 5,000 students and is run by Bob Jones
III.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Sr. and Jones Jr. were so conservative that they distanced
themselves from the Revs. Billy Graham, a one-time student, and
Jerry Falwell, as well as the National Evangelical Association,
because they worked with ministers perceived as liberal, according
to Washington and Lee University historian Mark Dallhouse, author
of ``An Island in the Lake of Fire : Bob Jones University,
Fundamentalism, and the Separatist Movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Joneses argued that fundamentalists should remain separate
from people with heretical beliefs, and even from other
fundamentalists who did not do the same, according to the book
``Religious Leaders of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The university teaches that the Bible is literally true, and
requires every faculty and staff member annually to sign a document
affirming belief in the university's creed.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Sr. was a member of the Methodist Episcopal Church, and
traveled the country as an evangelist leading revival-style prayer
gatherings. He started preaching at the age of 12. He ran the
college for six years before turning over day-to-day administration
to his son in 1932. Jones Sr. died in 1968 at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Jr., a member of the Missionary Christian Alliance church,
was trained as a historian and first became known as an interpreter
of Shakespeare traveling the country and acting out various roles.
Jones Jr. was president of the university from 1932 to 1971, and
served as chancellor and board chairman until his death in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Jones Jr., the university broadly
expanded its academic offerings. Jones Jr. was also an avid
collector of religious art and a supporter of an active cultural
life, including theatrical performances, on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was much more academically oriented, but he also had quite
a tongue,'' Dallhouse said. ``He's the one who called the Catholic
Church a satanic cult. He could wield quite a venomous tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   The university has long had problems with Catholicism. In 1928
Jones Sr. campaigned in Alabama against the presidential candidacy
of Governor Alfred Smith of New York, the first Catholic to be
nominated for president. Years later Jones Jr. was quoted comparing
the Catholic eucharist to cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, its Web site proclaims the school's
``anti-Catholicism,'' saying, ``We love the practicing Catholic and
earnestly desire to see him accept the Christ of the Cross, leave
the false system that has enslaved his soul, and enjoy the freedom
of sins forgiven that is available for any of us in Christ alone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the university lost its federal tax exempt status
because of its policy prohibiting interracial dating among
students.
</P>
<P>
   The university now is run by Bob Jones III, the university
president, and Dallhouse said that two of Jones III's sons, Bob
Jones IV and Stephen Jones, are considered possible successors.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones IV, a frequent contributor to World magazine, recently
drew attention for his critical profile of GOP presidential
candidate John McCain, a senator from Arizona. The magazine is
edited by an adviser to GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush,
the governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters reported that Democrats said Tuesday they would push for
Congress to condemn the fundamentalist Christian college for
barring interracial dating and espousing anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans slammed the Democrats' plan as an effort to
embarrass Bush, who for weeks has fended off accusations that his
appearance at the South Carolina university was a tacit endorsement
of the college's teachings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
