<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ORGAN-RESTORATION-ART     03-01 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-RESTORATION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 RESTORERS RUSH TO RESCUE THEATRE ORGANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. _ Donald Phipps and his friend Ken Duffie
wouldn't cross the street to hear a conventional church-style
organ.
</P>
<P>
   But for almost as long as either can recall, they have loved the
theatre organ, a lesser-known instrument designed to accompany the
silent films that launched the US motion-picture industry.
</P>
<P>
   The theatre organ could duplicate not only a full orchestra, but
also a range of real-world sounds: ocean waves roaring, birds
tittering, train whistles screeching, the clip-clop of horses'
hooves. And the human voice could hum hopefully, or sound ominious,
as the film unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of ``talkie'' pictures in the late 1920s, most
of these organs _ which sat in 6,000 of the nation's movie houses
in their heyday _ were junked or sold as parts.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, devotees like Phipps, 67, and Duffie, 74, have
been rescuing and restoring them, pipe by pipe.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, at least four societies and dozens of private
enthusiasts are preserving the old organs and offering concerts and
silent-film festivals, which are increasingly well attended.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans attribute this minirevival to a love of swing-era
music, show tunes, and ballads, which these organs reproduce so
well. Some are drawn by nostalgia for a simpler, more
black-and-white world where good triumphs and evil dies
ignominiously.
</P>
<P>
   Still others say that to understand the importance of film in
contemporary society, you need to know where it came from, and you
can't understand silent film without studying the music that
accompanied it.
</P>
<P>
   In New Bedford, a red-metal warehouse that still houses the
Warrior Fuel Co. and a boat settlements business is the unlikely
site of one of Phipps's and Duffie's restorations. There, amid the
debris of Phipps's former marine electronics business, with its
rusty paint cans, clamps, saws, and sandblasters, sits an antique
Wurlitzer with the horseshoe-shaped console that characterizes a
theatre organ.
</P>
<P>
   Atop a small, metalworking shop is the percussion section: a
tambourine, castanets, snare and bass drums, sleigh bells, a
xylophone, wood blocks, a Chinese gong. In a loft and elevated
chambers on the east and west walls, pipes, some tapered, in
several sizes make the sounds of harps, trumpets, violins, oboes.
Against another wall stand the elongated pine boxes of diaphones
and tubas, some as tall as 16 feet _ all activated by an elaborate
electrical relay system.
</P>
<P>
   A banner hanging above a bank of lacquer cans, nail boxes, and
plastic sawhorses identifies this as ``Phipps' Pipe Organ Concert
Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   After a lot of cleaning, said Phipps, who also founded the
Eastern Massachusetts branch of the American Theatre Organ Society,
his glorified garage seats 125 concertgoers.
</P>
<P>
   Phipps and Duffie spent 10 years assembling this 12-ton,
2,235-pipe organ from discard piles of movie houses being
demolished or converted: the old Strand Theatres in Quincy and
Clinton, the Olympic in Boston's Scollay Square, the Majestic in
Providence, Somerville's Teal Square theatre.
</P>
<P>
   It's a consuming interest, requiring devotion, detective work,
and anywhere from $4,000 for a low-end small organ to $120,000 for
a large, elaborate one, plus many hours of maintenance and
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   The silent films that developed at the turn of the 20th century
initially were accompanied by a single piano or a lone violin,
explained Duffie, who helped found the New England Theatre Organ
Society in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   As the films' popularity grew, some movie houses hired small
orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   About 1915, to economize and expand the dramatic range of the
accompaniment, the musicians' ensembles were replaced by one
organist playing a special ``unit orchestra,'' or theatre organ.
The cadillacs of this genre were the Wurlitzers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most celebrated contemporary performers is Chad
Weirick, 36, of Braintree, who at 16 was the youngest musician ever
hired to play the mammoth 35-ton organs at New York's Radio City
Music Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he plays on restored theatre organs around the country,
including the Zeiterion Theatre in New Bedford and Wellesley's
Babson College, where silent-film concerts draw up to 500 people.
</P>
<P>
   Creating an entire soundtrack on one instrument is a daunting
experience, said Weirick, who also teaches music in Wellesley
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the entire orchestra. It's like being the conductor
without having all those temperamental musicians to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   With their primitive cameras and limited filmmaking techniques,
the silent films could seem disconnected and hard to watch, said
Linda Dittmar, who teaches film studies at the University of
Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But the music could give depth and coherence.
</P>
<P>
   Movie producers did not issue musical scores, so accompanists
improvised. There were legendary tales of organists who played
whatever they wanted, inserting the birdcall when a car's honk
should have sounded.
</P>
<P>
   But a good organist could add emotional nuance and clarity,
heightening the dramatic impact, Dittmar said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the great 1928 silent film ``The Wind,'' with Lillian
Gish, as Weirick says he would accompany it.
</P>
<P>
   Letty, an innocent Virginia girl represented musically by a
happy American ballad, moves to the Texas prairie to live with
cousins. But they are mean and the incessant wind, conveyed through
low and breathy sounds, unnerves her.
</P>
<P>
   To escape her relatives, Letty marries a well-meaning but clumsy
cowpoke, represented by a jaunty, comic tune. But his awkward
attempts at lovemaking repel her. The organ gasps and sputters
notes that sound as if she's saying, ``Oh, my God!''
</P>
<P>
   As Letty prepares to leave her husband, an intruder breaks in
during a windstorm and attacks her. Sustained diminishing chords
let the violence speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Letty shoots him dead and seeks refuge from the wind in a
closet, where she lives like a caged animal.
</P>
<P>
   Her musical theme merges with the wind's maelstrom as she
descends into madness.
</P>
<P>
   At last, Letty reunites with her husband. Her theme, intertwined
with his goofy macho melody, plays against a low timpani roll. As
the film ends, a tuba emits a faint, flat sound in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Such performances can be mind-blowing, said Dorothy Bromage,
president of the Pine Tree chapter of the American Theatre Organ
Society, with members inMassachusetts, New Hampshire, and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit in the theatre with pipes in front of you and on each
side, and sound rolls over you and absorbs you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And audiences are encouraged to boo and applaud, making the
``silent'' film experience more interactive than current movies.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate ``pipe'' dream for those who love these old organs
may be the Shanklin Center in Groton. F. Garrett Shanklin, 69,
whose family owns a packaging-machinery company, has created a
facility to house just one theatre organ.
</P>
<P>
   This instrument, which once graced Boston's Metropolitan Theatre
(now the Wang Center), was used in an Oregon pizza parlor until
Shanklin rescued it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the ornate, white-and-gold console sits atop a red-carpeted
turntable, with elaborate lighting from colored spotlights and a
mirrored ball overhead.
</P>
<P>
   He has wanted to own one of these magnificent instruments ever
since he first heard one at the Stoneham Town Hall in 1968,
Shanklin said, as merry organ music resonated throughout the
building so loud that the floor vibrated.
</P>
<P>
   Barely audible above the din, Shanklin voiced the views of many
enthusiasts when he said, ``I just love the sound of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
