<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWS MIXED ON FEDERAL DIALLO TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The four policemen who killed Amadou Diallo have been
found not guilty of a crime, but that doesn't mean their legal woes
are over.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the victim's parents and some New York supporters,
including the Rev. Al Sharpton and Representative Charles Rangel,
will meet in Washington with US Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder
to push for a second trial, this time in federal court, on charges
that the officers violated Diallo's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Legal specialists are mixed on whether such a trial is likely or
justified.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers were acquitted on charges of second-degree
murder, manslaughter, and other lesser offenses in a state court
last week, a verdict that set off massive, angry, but nonviolent
protests across New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who was US Attorney in New York in the
1980s, said Friday that civil-rights law does not apply to the
Diallo case. For federal prosecutors to bring a case, they would
have to find ``a gross miscarriage of justice'' in the state trial,
or conclude that the officers ``purposefully'' deprived Diallo of
his rights. The facts, he said, support neither premise.
</P>
<P>
   However, Laurence Tribe, a constitutional specialist at Harvard
Law School, said in a telephone interview that there could be other
grounds for a federal trial.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers fired 41 bullets at Diallo, a West African
immigrant, as he stood in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment
building the night of Feb. 4, 1999. At the trial, they said they
acted out of self-defense, believing Diallo was pulling a gun out
of his pocket. (It turned out to be a wallet.)
</P>
<P>
   Tribe said, ``If you concluded that these officers were
suspicious of this guy or scared of this guy almost entirely
because he was black, and wouldn't have killed him if he had been
white, you could argue that they violated his constitutional right
to equal protection under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``It might make little sense to go after these
officers on this theory,'' because it would be ``very hard to prove
that they had it in for Diallo, that they intended to deprive him
of his rights.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Justice Department could argue that their action
represented, as Tribe put it, ``the tip of a systematic iceberg,
involving institutional racial profiling that made it more likely
that this sort of thing would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, instead of filing a criminal case against the officers,
federal prosecutors might file a civil suit against the New York
Police Department, seeking to monitor its practices, order changes
in policy, or even place the department under federal control.
</P>
<P>
   Two federal investigations into the department's racial
practices are under way, prompted by the Abner Louima
torture-and-sodomy case of two years ago: one by the US Attorney's
office in Brooklyn, another by the US Civil Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary Carter, the former US attorney who started the Brooklyn
inquiry, said he could imagine the Diallo case prompting a move to
tie these investigations into one federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said it will instead ``provide an occasion'' for
city and federal officials ``to discuss necessary police reforms
and resolve the matters in ways short of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several precedents for taking police officers who have
been acquitted in a state court, and trying them on civil-rights
charges in a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The Rodney King case, in which Los Angeles police officers
severely beat a black man after pulling him over after a highway
chase, is the best known instance. In another case, in New York
City, Officer Francis Livoti put a deadly chokehold on Anthony
Baez, a young Hispanic man, after Baez hit his car with a ball.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Diallo shooting differs in at least one crucial
way. ``In Rodney King, the facts could establish that the officers
were very deliberately administering punishment,'' Tribe said.
``You could say they were holding a sort of kangaroo court,
intentionally depriving him of his constitutional right to due
process.'' It would be ``very difficult'' to prove such a claim for
the officers who shot Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Obbermaier, another former US attorney in New York, also
noted that second trials of this sort of rare. ``The federal
government just can't say, `I think we ought to retry this case
because I don't like the result,' '' he said. ``New York is a
sovereign state. There is a reluctance to intrude without extremely
good cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, what happens will be determined by Attorney General
Janet Reno or possibly by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Some suspect politics might play a role. It is widely believed
that the Clinton administration brought the federal case in the
Rodney King beating in part because the officers' acquittal in
state court triggered riots in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, head of the New York Civil Liberties Union, said
a federal trial of the Diallo officers might be contemplated ``as a
backdrop for the Rudy Giuliani-Hillary Clinton Senate race.''
However, he added, it is unclear which direction, if any, politics
might tilt the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Carter scoffed at the notion. ``Politics enter into these things
a lot less than people like to imagine,'' he said. ``If there is a
federal trial, it won't happen because Al Sharpton wants one, or
because Rudy Giuliani doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
