<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN UNIVERSITY LIMPING BACK TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It's now a strange sight for Eduardo Mendoza,
seeing students and professors walking around the campus of the
National Autonomous University, its brick towers and
picture-windowed classrooms lit at night and filled with activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pleasure to see the university like this again,''
Mendoza, 23, a part-time management student, said last week after
class. ``I got used to seeing it empty.''
</P>
<P>
   After being shut down for nearly 10 months by students who
seized the main campus to protest a proposed tuition increase,
Mexico's most important institution of higher education, known by
the Spanish acronym UNAM, is lurching back to life.
</P>
<P>
   The barbed-wire barricades put up by protesters have been
removed. Several graffiti-stained walls have been painted over, and
classes have resumed for most of the 260,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly everyone in this academic community called University
City, which sprawls across three square miles in the southern part
of the capital, admits that many scars remain from the strike. The
strike ended Feb. 6 when more than 600 students surrendered to a
force of 2,000 federal police officers during a surprise predawn
raid.
</P>
<P>
   There is concern about students _ about 250 of them _ who remain
jailed, whose fate continues to spark small confrontations between
pro- and anti-strike students.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a palpable sadness that the high-profile conflict
and the loss of nearly a year's worth of research and teaching may
have permanently dented UNAM's image as one of Latin America's most
prominent universities.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, there are worries about UNAM's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This conflict will accelerate some of the changes that UNAM
has needed to make for years, like its structure and its academic
programs,'' said Carlos Munoz Izquierdo, director of educational
research at the private Iberoamerican University in Mexico City. ``
</P>
<P>
   Education experts like Munoz said the main question is how UNAM
will recover and whether it can compete with other universities
despite its constitutional mandate to provide nearly free
education.
</P>
<P>
   UNAM's challenge is in many ways Mexico's daily reality: Finding
a midpoint between its populist past and a more modern, reformist
future.
</P>
<P>
   The university received nearly $1 billion in subsidies from the
government last year, roughly a third of the total given to all of
Mexico's public higher education institutions. Tighter spending
policies by President Ernesto Zedillo have kept those subsidies
nearly flat in recent years even as enrollment grew.
</P>
<P>
   To make the UNAM more financially independent, officials decided
last spring to raise the tuition from 2 cents a year to about $140
_ the first hike in 50 years. Administrators said the increase
would bring in nearly a tenth of the annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   But that proposal, as well as fears that the government was
preparing to privatize the university, led a group of angry
students to take over the campus. Officials eventually backed down,
agreeing to make the tuition hike voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   The strike reached far beyond UNAM's main buildings, closing
dozens of university-affiliated prep schools, libraries, and
cultural centers across Mexico City. It closed university-run
dental and medical clinics and even quieted the instruments of its
renowned philharmonic orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the strike's end, federal officials and
private business groups pledged to come up with money to help
repair buildings and get restart classes as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But when students re-registered, the toll of the shutdown began
to take shape. About 40,000 who had previously been enrolled at
UNAM didn't show up. They either dropped out, officials guessed, or
signed up at other universities.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the protests last April, UNAM had begun losing
prestige, students, and research opportunities to aggressive
private universities and technical schools in Mexico, whose
enrollments have grown significantly over the last twenty years.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators are now planning to organize a university-wide
congress whose main objective is to come up with a blueprint to
revamp the university, from its bureaucracy and budget to its
academic programs and admissions standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of view that I have is that all issues of university
life should be revised (as part of) the congress,'' said Jose Narro
Robles, general coordinator of the congress, in an interview with
the Mexico City newspaper Reforma.
</P>
<P>
   Taking their cue, perhaps, from the UNAM strike, protests have
sprouted at other state-sponsored institutions. At a rural teachers
college in Hidalgo state, students and parents demanded more
tuition subsidies. Workers took over the administration building at
a public university campus in northern Sinaloa state demanding
higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, in fact, say UNAM's dilemma is at the heart of a
larger problem facing the public higher education system: how to
become more efficient without becoming too elitist.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz and other observers say UNAM will have no choice but to
tighten its academic standards if it wants to survive in a more
competitive industry. But, they add, all levels of government will
have to come up with a clearer and more modern policy toward higher
education to make sure a college education remains accessible and
affordable.
</P>
</TEXT>
