<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME ON SHARPTON; THE DEAD AND THE PROFITABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The solemn face of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed West African
immigrant shot to death last year by four white police officers
outside his Bronx apartment, stares from the cover of this week's
Time magazine. With the officers' stunning acquittal on all charges
last week, Howard Chua-Eoan probes the painful questions concerning
racial profiling by law enforcement, police brutality, and the
politics of outrage that have echoed since Diallo died in a hail of
bullets. He also considers how these issues will shadow New York's
Senate race between Hillary Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani, as well
as the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even more compelling is Jack E. White's provocative essay on
the Rev. Al Sharpton. Ever since Sharpton popped up at the side of
Tawana Brawley, the young woman whose false accusations of a
kidnapping and rape by a group of white men almost broke New York
in two more than a decade ago, he's been viewed as a reckless
rabble-rouser and a public nuisance. Many believed Sharpton, with
his thick build and that absurdly processed hair, was nothing more
than a bombastic media hound romping through the volatile minefield
of race just to raise his own profile. But White argues that from
the ashes of the Diallo case, Sharpton has finally shown himself to
have ``the makings of a moral leader.'' And for those who would
scoff at such a thing, White reminds us that it was Sharpton who,
in the wake of the verdict, told the agitated throng outside the
courthouse, ``Let not one brick be thrown, not one bottle be
thrown. Those that believe in Amadou should not betray his memory
by acting like those who killed him.'' And while there were
numerous protests after the verdict, all were nonviolent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As career moves go, death is killer.
</P>
<P>
   Tupac Shakur, dead since September 1996, is somewhere in the
cosmos enjoying the success of his third posthumous release of
``new'' music, ``Still I Rise,'' while the Notorious B.I.G.
returned to the charts with ``Born Again,'' nearly three years
after he was gunned down. Such beyond-the-grave productivity, of
course, isn't limited to deceased hip-hop stars. Last year, novels
from two long-dead authors, Ernest Hemingway and Ralph Ellison,
made the bestseller lists. And from Biggie to Ellison, there were
legitimate arguments that these works were little more than sloppy
seconds cobbled together to turn a buck, products hardly
representative of the artists at their best. Hence, every
post-mortem book or CD begs the question posed by Erik Tarloff in
The American Prospect: ``Did the artist responsible regard the work
under consideration as finished and publishable?'' In a fairly
brief but entertaining essay, Tarloff works this question from
every possible angle. He first considers our inability to let go:
``Once we've experienced the complete canon of a favorite artist,
it's natural to feel frustration that all the ore has been
extracted from a particular lode; it's only human to want more,''
he writes. ``We want a solution to the murder of Edwin Drood. We
want to see Michelangelo's Slaves liberated from their blocks of
marble.'' But finally he nails it for what it really is: capitalism
at its most lazy and cynical. Like Coke or Kleenex, Hemingway and
Tupac are also brand names that sell. ``Brand names narrow the
field for us; they make selection (and frequently, response) less
risky; they reassure us with their apparent imprimatur of quality.
Mediocre art with an impressive brand name is often preferable _ or
at least safer _ than art of obscure provenance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If any hip-hop artists make it into the Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame, Run-D.M.C. _ eligible 2008 _ should be among the first. Back
in the 1980s, the Hollis, Queens, trio took rap to the masses when
many still believed it was a novelty. Such songs as ``It's Like
That'' and ``Sucker MCs'' established the group's style, and ``Rock
Box'' and ``Walk This Way'' laid the groundwork for the rap-rock
dabblings of Limp Bizkit, Rage Against the Machine, and Korn. In
XXL, Matt Diehl considers these hip-hop pioneers as they put the
finishing touches on their long-awaited seventh album, ``Crown
Royal.'' The album features the de rigueur guest spots _ from Kid
Rock, Everlast, and Limp Bizkit _ something, by the way, that
Run-D.M.C. never needed back in the day. But these are different
times for these b-boys turned b-men. For one, Darryl ``D.M.C.''
McDaniels seems to be moving away from the group, working on a solo
project that he says better reflects who he is now. He describes
his music as ``a mix of Neil Young, Chuck Berry, and Led Zeppelin,
with a little Ike and Tina Turner.'' Hmmmm. As for his days with
Run-D.M.C., which seem to be numbered, ``I'd rather do my stuff and
fail than be in Run-D.M.C. goin' through hell.'' I guess for
D.M.C., it's like that, and that's the way it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
