A3230 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION0     03-01 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shopping destination: CNN Center
 &HT;    By Sabine Morrow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug Lambe was a man on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   Lambe, who works downtown, recently wandered into the Braves
Clubhouse Store searching for a birthday present for his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad's a serious Braves fan, so I figured that the Clubhouse
is going to have something he'll like. I'm thinking about getting
him a sweatshirt, and I'll probably throw in a Braves cap,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been to the CNN Center in a while, you might be
surprised at what you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN Center complex _ billed as a ``1.5 million-square-foot,
multiuse megastructure'' _ includes two 14-story office towers, the
Omni Hotel, CNN studios, several restaurants and stores and a
multiscreen movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   To go hand in hand with the new Philips Arena, to which it is
attached, CNN just underwent some major renovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philips and CNN Center complement each other,'' says Lisa
Tobias of Turner Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a flashy new glass-and-steel front on Marietta
Street, the main atrium area was opened up to allow for increased
Philips Arena traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created even more of a studio environment by adding six
large screens throughout the atrium where people can watch the
Turner networks. Also the tour area and the tour itself have been
revamped,'' Tobias says.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the recent facelift, 27,000 square feet of new retail
space has been made available.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cindy Brieske with Turner Properties, more stores
are on the CNN horizon, including the possibility of a national
chain book store as well as another upscale restaurant facing
Marietta Street with outdoor seating overlooking Centennial Olympic
Park.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the big draw for shoppers is, for the most part,
sports related.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves Clubhouse, which opened its doors in 1986, is the
first store owned and operated by the Atlanta Braves, according to
store manager Don Shields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers are true Braves fans, but we also get a lot of
international travelers that come through,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   At this well-stocked store fans can find team jerseys,
collectibles including signed baseballs and even wrist watches
sporting Braves logos.
</P>
<P>
   During baseball season, when the team is in town, selected
players will come to the store one Saturday a month and sign
autographs for fans.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the Clubhouse, you'll find the Turner Store. Here
you can pick up stuffed Scooby Doo toys, a selection of ``Gone With
the Wind'' souvenir items ranging from a Scarlett O'Hara doll to a
GWTW coffee mug.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the Turner Store, CNN fans will find sportswear
emblazoned with the CNN Sports Illustrated logo.
</P>
<P>
   And if you were impressed with CNN's coverage of the dawning of
the new millennium, you'll find a copy of the video here as well.
</P>
<P>
   Wander over to Collage and you can pick up an assortment of
Atlanta souvenirs that run the gamut from gift packs of Touch of
Georgia Vidalia onion salad dressing and Georgia muscadine sauce to
bath and body products _ in magnolia and peach blossom scents,
naturally.
</P>
<P>
   For more exotic finds, consider the Continental Shopper. This
postage-stamp-size store offers gifts from around the world.
Dramatic sunburst metal sculptures from Haiti share space with
woodcarvings, jewelry and even a line of scented candles and
incense.
</P>
<P>
   As you pass through the gamut of eateries at the food court,
you'll end up at Hawk Walk, which leads to Philips Arena. Glass
doors along the walk allow for a peek into the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Only two stores make their home here, but for Hawks and
Thrashers fans, it's shopping bliss.
</P>
<P>
   At Team Gear, true to its name, you can load up on Thrashers and
Hawks sportswear, slightly dressy long-sleeved cotton shirts and
even neckties bearing the team logos. Games, beer mugs, wallets and
even hockey pucks filled with candy make for sporting mementos.
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From the north, take I-75/85 south to Williams
Street. Turn right onto International Boulevard, then left onto
Techwood Drive. Cross over Marietta Street and CNN Center is on
your right.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Vary. But most stores are open 9:30 a.m.-6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Wheelchair accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Public parking is available in the CNN Center Decks
after 4:30 p.m. Parking is also available in surrounding lots near
CNN Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Public restrooms in the food court and at Hawk
Walk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Web site,
</P>
<P>
   www.cnn.com/cnncenter.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CNN Studio Tour. Get an up-close and personal look at this
popular news broadcast seen around the world. The tour offers a
behind-the-scenes look at the writers, editors, producers and
technicians who put together the round-the-clock news coverage.
Tours are available 9 a.m.-6 p.m. daily. $4.50 children; $5
seniors; $7 adults; $25 VIP tour. For reservations call
404-827-2300.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visitors will find plenty of places to grab a quick lunch on
the run at the food court, or they can choose one of CNN Center's
sit-down restaurants. At The Great Wall you can get a spicy
concoction of Mongolian Beef sauteed with green onions and chiles
($7.95); also recommended is the House Special Shrimp tossed with
broccoli, Chinese greens and bean sauce ($7.95). 11 a.m.-10 p.m.
Mondays-Sundays. 404-522-8213.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a taste of the British Isles, step into Reggie's British
Pub. At this traditional Victorian-style tavern, you can sample
bangers and mash ($7.95), shepherd's pie ($6.95) and the
not-so-low-cal Scotch eggs, which are hard-boiled, wrapped in
sausage, rolled in bread crumbs, then deep-fried. 11:30 a.m.-11
p.m. Mondays-Sundays. 404-525-1437.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CNN Center also is home to the Omni Hotel, which recently
opened Prime Meridian restaurant. This upscale eatery claims to
serve ``cuisines from around the world.'' For lunch you might try
the buffet ($13), which changes daily and has included anything
from pizza to salmon. Dinner offerings range from Texas cowboy-cut
ribeye steak ($24) to seared Chilean sea bass ($16). Daily:
breakfast 7-10 a.m.; lunch 11:30 a.m.-2:30 p.m.; dinner 6-10 p.m.
</P>
