<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3232 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-McCAIN-ADS-TV-NYTSF &LR;      03-01 2537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCAIN-ADS-TV-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE FEAR of LOATHING on the CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax, By JAMES BENNET  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Earlier this month, as the Republican contenders for president
were bickering over who was the bigger meanie, I paid a visit to
Greg Stevens, who was hard at work creating two commercials for his
candidate, John McCain, in a rent-by-the-hour video editing studio
across the river from Washington in Arlington, Va.
 &HT;    The son of a minister, Stevens, who is 51, speaks in mild tones
and dresses in muted colors. That day he was wearing pressed gray
flannels, a light gray shirt and a dark gray and black sweater. His
commercials, in contrast, sparkle with color, swoop through
blurring camera pans, shake with sound.
 &HT;    Of the TV ads Stevens was producing, one, called ``Leader,'' was
the kind that political operatives and obliging reporters refer to
as ``positive.'' It was a 30-second confection intended to
introduce McCain to California viewers.
 &HT;    The second spot had a less inspiring name. ``OK, Polly,''
Stevens said, shortly after I entered the shadowy studio. ``I guess
we can go to the 'New Low.'''
 &HT;    Polly Bryan, a video editor, drew a stylus across a flat control
panel, and the image of George W. Bush, bigger than life, smirked
on three screens, a five-foot screen against one wall and two
smaller desktop ones.
 &HT;    Nearly 12 years ago, it was Stevens who burned the now-legendary
image of Michael Dukakis peeping from a tank into our collective
memory. Now he was working on finding a similar place in the
American mind for a smirking Bush. The new commercial used
slow-motion footage of a startlingly goofy Bush to mock him as
having reached a ``new all-time low'' in attacking McCain's record
on assisting veterans. But Stevens was not satisfied with the cut.
 &HT;    The last image, a head-on shot of McCain speaking in front of an
aircraft carrier, was not dramatic enough to create the hoped-for
contrast between one man who should be president and another who
should be spanked.
 &HT;    On Stevens' instructions, Bryan used her machine _ a sort of
image processor with cut and paste tools like a word processor's _
to copy frames from existing footage of McCain and stick them into
``New Low.''
 &HT;    Dizzyingly, McCain's image jerked back and forth, and his brisk
voice spoke normally and in reverse, as she adjusted the new clip
to fit near the end of the advertisement.
 &HT;    ``Let's try it 20 frames sooner,'' said Stevens, who is known as
a perfectionist in his trade. (To give you a sense of the hair he
was splitting, there are 30 frames in a second, 900 in a 30-second
commercial.)
 &HT;    In the end, none of this effort mattered. No voter ever saw this
commercial.
 &HT;    Even as Bush intensified his barrage of critical advertising in
South Carolina and Michigan, McCain ultimately decided to put ``New
Low'' on the shelf and to rely only on positive commercials such as
``Leader'' in a bid to reclaim the high ground.
 &HT;    Earlier he had seemingly abandoned that high ground by
broadcasting a spot comparing Bush to Bill Clinton. History may
someday sort out whether or not this attack ad hurt McCain. What is
already clear is that it, along with Bush's more frequent attacks,
fueled one of the most tiresome aspects of this campaign: grown men
calling each other negative ... and then calling each other
negative for calling each other negative.
 &HT;    Yes, the doubling negatives have served as a kind of proxy
debate over the character of the candidates, but that debate is not
terribly enlightening.
 &HT;    Any debate about TV spots and radio ads and the nature of
telephone polls is ultimately a debate about tactics rather than
issues and agendas. That is, it's the very sort of insider
preoccupation that the critics of negativity say they want to
avoid.
 &HT;    Perhaps the most unsatisfying aspect of this debate about
negative campaigning is that, having monumentally distracted the
political world, it has not addressed directly the basic questions
it raised.
 &HT;    Are negative advertisements so much worse than positive ones? Is
either category actually a bad thing? And does either really
matter? The answers are no, no and a lot less than you probably
think.
 &HT;    At the national level, the brainwashing powers of political
advertising have long been exaggerated _ in part by some
advertising men, who make their money on commission, as a
percentage of the purchase of TV time. Given the rise of channel
surfing, mute buttons, the Internet and irony, traditional
advertising is becoming only less effective, in the view of a
number of media consultants.
 &HT;    What still matters most in a national race, candidates and
operatives will tell you, is what they rather patronizingly call
``earned'' or ``free'' media _ the press.
 &HT;    McCain has proved that this year. Even as his campaign was
taking off, he could not afford much advertising. On the other
hand, Steve Forbes proved _ as he already had in '96 _ that
abundant and skillfully produced advertising can get you only so
far.
 &HT;    Now, paradoxically, one way to ``earn'' free media is through
advertising, particularly negative advertising. Reporters tend not
to build stories around spots like ``Leader,'' a paean to one
candidate, but they are very likely to pay attention to ads in
which one candidate levels a charge against another.
 &HT;    And so Stevens had intended to pay to broadcast ``New Low'' only
a handful of times, knowing that news programs, delighting in its
acerbity, would work up stories about Bush and veterans and then
broadcast the commercial free.
 &HT;    There is really nothing wrong with this. One role of campaign
reporters is to relay and evaluate what the candidates are saying,
in their ads as on the stump, and they are simply doing their jobs
when they analyze such attacks.
 &HT;    One of the grounds that critics use in attacking negative
advertisements is that they twist the truth _ without necessarily
breaking it _ by manipulating words and images to undercut an
opponent. Yet positive commercials can be just as manipulative and
sometimes less truthful than negative ones.
 &HT;    Indeed, so-called positive ads are just as likely to rely on
anonymous narration that skips inconvenient details, music that
summons emotions, and images stripped of context _ all of this
carefully arranged to tell the producer's chosen story.
 &HT;    Now, turning attention to his positive spot, Stevens led me down
a hall in the warren of windowless studios to a room where Steven
Lipton, another editor, was assembling the images for ``Leader.''
 &HT;    Like other employees of the studio, Lipton, 33, is a gun for
hire. He once cut a commercial for Bill Clinton and one for Bob
Dole in the same room on the same day, erasing all traces of one
campaign's work before the next entered.
 &HT;    Stevens had written the script for ``Leader'' the night before.
He usually does write a script first, then scribbles in the margins
what images _ which he believes are far more important than the
words _ should go with each line.
 &HT;    ``A young Navy pilot who volunteered for duty in Vietnam,''
boomed the bass Voice of God _ actually, the voice of Terry
MacDonald, a burly actor with a wry wit _ as pictures of a youthful
McCain flashed by on a large screen.
 &HT;    Following Stevens' written instructions for the imagery
(``Reagan,'' ``big crowd,'' ``flag profile''), Lipton had spliced
shots of a pilot bailing out of a falling plane with footage of
McCain in prison in Hanoi along with scenes of him with Ronald
Reagan and on the campaign trail. The parachutist, however, was not
McCain; the campaign purchased footage of an unnamed pilot from the
military.
 &HT;    The closing shot showed McCain standing before a blue field of
stars as he earnestly addressed a crowd. In fact, the senator,
deadpan, was telling a joke about how, when he showed up with his
kids on the first day of school, a teacher congratulated him for
bringing his grandchildren.
 &HT;    But as the narration gave these images new meanings, the
pictures now told a compact, powerful story with no punch lines.
That story was true enough, but the ad, in reality, was more
postmodern pastiche than documentary.
 &HT;    Indeed, this ``positive'' commercial had managed to underscore
implicitly that McCain, unlike Bush, had gone to Vietnam, not into
the National Guard. Just imagine the reaction to a spot that
bluntly, negatively, made the same point.
 &HT;    By now, Rick Davis, McCain's campaign manager, had entered the
room. Watching the ``Leader'' spot, he arrived at a new concern.
``You've got to have a female announcer,'' he said.
 &HT;    Stevens rolled his eyes.
 &HT;    ``It's California,'' Davis continued. ``We've got to get out of
a South Carolina mindset.''
 &HT;    Stevens suggested that there was no evidence that women
responded more to female voices. In fact, he said, there was some
evidence that they were put off by them.
 &HT;    Soon Jay Payne, Stevens' production manager, set to work with
Lipton editing ``Leader'' _ which is to say, manipulating the
sounds and images _ while scarfing down lasagna from the production
studio's mess. Payne, a 25-year-old from South Carolina, had been
in the studio until 3:30 that morning, and his thick, brown goatee
was merging into several days' worth of beard.
 &HT;    Payne and Lipton began riffling their file footage for a good
sound bite. They settled on a shot of McCain declaring to a crowd,
``I'm going to give the government back to you, and I promise you
that.''
 &HT;    But there was a hitch. McCain was speaking outside, and the
preceding image was of an indoor rally.
 &HT;    ``You can't lead in from that crowd now,'' Payne warned.
 &HT;    Lipton eliminated the crowd shot, then went searching for a good
outdoor crowd to follow McCain's remark.
 &HT;    ``I don't want a shot of that guy,'' Payne said, as a man in
dark glasses and a tie appeared. ``He looks like he's in the Secret
Service.''
 &HT;    Lipton finally found a nice crowd shot at the same event at
which McCain was speaking. People of varying ages, oblivious to
Stevens' cameraman, were listening intently and then clapping.
 &HT;    But they were not clapping loudly enough. So Lipton embarked on
a hunt for better crowd noise. The cheering and whistling from
another event sounded ``too young,'' he concluded, and the sounds
from other rallies he sampled at head-spinning speed did not work
either.
 &HT;    He returned to the original speech and fast-forwarded, turning
the senator into a caffeinated chipmunk, until he found a
satisfying cheer. He picked up that piece of sound and laid it over
his preferred crowd shot. So in the end, a group of people clapped
and cheered with others' hands and voices for a remark no one seen
or heard in the ad was actually applauding.
 &HT;    As a presentation of reality, ``Leader'' had become as
misleading as many other campaign commercials, positive, negative
or otherwise. Still, as a representation of one reality _ of the
dynamism of the McCain campaign _ it was dead on.
 &HT;    After lunch, Stevens pushed a sheaf of papers toward me.
Political organizers still think in terms of precincts and
counties. But Stevens is reaching voters through their televisions,
not their front doors. So he was working off color-coded maps of
the media markets in California and elsewhere that listed the
percentage of the Republican vote that would come from each.
 &HT;    Stevens can cut a commercial in about 12 hours, at a cost of
$12,000 to $15,000. The great expense in TV advertising comes when
you put it on the air. And so by using ratings data, some pop
psychology and sophisticated computer programs, campaigns carefully
pick particular times and particular shows to ship their messages
to particular voters.
 &HT;    Ideally, Stevens wants every viewer to see an ad 10 to 12 times
to absorb its message. He tends to buy time during morning and
evening news programs, as well as during ``Nightline,'' to reach
the audience that is most likely to go to the polls. Then he
pursues prime-time slots to get the most possible viewers.
 &HT;    Going a step further, Stevens planned to place ``Leader'' during
``Oprah,'' ``Judge Judy,'' ``Live With Regis and Kathie Lee'' and
even an afternoon rerun of ``Matlock'' in hopes of appealing to the
suburban women McCain has had trouble rallying.
 &HT;    Later, as he screened the revised ``Leader,'' Stevens murmured,
``That's good ... good, good, good.''
 &HT;    The McCain campaign is not testing its advertisements in focus
groups or polls. Generally, Stevens just picks the images and
sounds he thinks are most effective, freely incorporating the
suggestions of his underlings or colleagues.
 &HT;    The new version of ``Leader'' with McCain speaking, he readily
conceded, was better than the original. He scribbled out some
graphics, like ``Ready to Lead,'' which he handed over to Bryan,
who had now taken control of the commercial to edit it on a
superior and _ at $500 an hour _ more expensive machine.
 &HT;    As Bryan worked, and narrative shards like ``defying special
interests'' periodically filled the room, Stevens talked about his
candidate and advertising.
 &HT;    ``He hates this,'' Stevens said. ``He understands its value, but
it's something that isn't reality to him.''
 &HT;    Unlike McCain, his candidate, Stevens is fascinated by
advertising, with its simultaneous appeals to two senses, its iron
discipline of money and time, its overt messages and subtle cues
and its blend of politics and art, high technology and sometimes
low blows.
 &HT;    McCain's decision to shelve ``New Low'' may have been the only
one he could have made politically, given his image as an
unconventional candidate. But his decision should not be read as
addressing the underlying question of whether negative advertising
should have a place in campaigns generally, including in primaries.
It should.
 &HT;    Granted, politics would probably be more enlightening if
political advertising, positive or negative, relied less on
gimmickry. Campaigns would surely be better if candidates told
their own stories and made their own attacks, addressing the camera
directly in their commercials.
 &HT;    But don't make the easy assumption that politics would be more
serious and more moral if all candidates were positive all of the
time.
 &HT;    The truth is not always pretty, and there can be just as much of
it in a slow-motion smirk as in a cheering crowd.
 &HT;     c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (James Bennet is a staff writer for The New York Times
Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------
