<HEADLINE>
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE GRUNTS of GROZNY  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax, By MICHAEL GORDON  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    The first thing Lt. Vyacheslav Kiselyov did before leading his
platoon into Grozny was to yank the metal plates from his
bulletproof vest, leaving only the panel that covered his heart.
Then he crammed the jacket with extra cartridges of ammunition.
 &HT;    It was one of those trade-offs Russian soldiers make to maximize
their chances of survival.
 &HT;    The regular supply of ammo _ four magazines with 32 cartridges
each _ is good for only about 20 minutes of fighting. The fire from
Chechen rebels can sometimes get so intense, however, that it
sounds like eggs on a griddle, and Vyacheslav felt his best
protection was having enough bullets to answer back.
 &HT;    He also put aside his helmet. It was nice to have if you were
manning a checkpoint. But when a soldier has to run for his life
and dodge snipers, the ill-fitting helmet just gets in the way.
 &HT;    As Vyacheslav recalled not long ago, he was creeping up on a
warehouse in the eastern part of Grozny when he saw that two of his
soldiers were pinned against the ground, bullets whizzing over
their heads.
 &HT;    He began lobbing smoke grenades so that they could make their
escape. It was then that a 5.45-millimeter bullet ripped into his
hand.
 &HT;    That, Vyacheslav now says, was a bit of luck. If it had been a
7.62-millimeter, it would have torn off a finger.
 &HT;    Vyacheslav told me his tale in Room No. 8, which was not a room
at all but a tent set up on the grounds of the military hospital in
Mozdok, just a few miles northwest of the Republic of Chechnya.
 &HT;    He spoke in a low monotone, as if he were talking about another
soldier in some far-off battle. It was a dirty little war, but it
was his lot to fight it. He had not bothered to tell his parents
about his wound. It would only worry them, and there was nothing
really that they could do.
 &HT;    ``I don't know whether we are fighting for the motherland or
not,'' Vyacheslav said. ``But if it was up to me all the bandits
would be destroyed. It's not nice to see your friend's head blown
off by a grenade.''
 &HT;    I was one of a handful of foreigners who had tagged along with
Russian TV crews as they helicoptered in and out of Chechnya this
winter, the Russian forces blasting their way into the Chechen
capital. An obsequious military press service generated publicity
for Russia's field commanders.
 &HT;    These officers were a blustery lot, boasting about their
triumphs and reveling in the medals that Vladimir Putin, Russia's
acting president, bestowed on them. What interested me, though, was
not these officers but the soldiers who fought under them _ young
men who, like Chechnya's civilians, bore the brunt of Russia's
``victories.''
 &HT;    These soldiers were not the grizzled combat veterans the Kremlin
insisted it was sending to the front. They were untested conscripts
plucked from Russian factories and farms in the provinces,
down-on-their-luck mercenaries unable to find steady work at home,
militiamen more accustomed to policing a rock concert than
searching for snipers.
 &HT;    And they were young officers like Vyacheslav, who went to a
military school to become a border guard and never imagined he
would end up in the Chechen caldron.
 &HT;    They suffered thousands of casualties in the course of seizing a
ruined capital and chasing bands of battle-hardened militants into
