he was from the southern Russian city of Krasnodar, where his
father works as a truck driver and his mother serves as an
administrator in a nursery school. He completed nine years of
schooling and then transferred to a trade school to learn how to be
a bricklayer. The army grabbed him before he found a job.
 &HT;    ``My mother did not want me to go into the army,'' he said with
a shrug. ``She said, 'Why do we need all that?' But she said I
should go if I had to, and I never thought about faking a health
problem. After they took me I told the army I did not care what
kind of unit I was in but wanted to serve in Krasnodar, where my
parents live.''
 &HT;    Instead, the army sent him to Chechnya in October. To comfort
his parents, he did not tell them he was in Chechnya. When Viktor
writes his parents he tells them that he is with his brigade in
Budyonnovsk, a town in southern Russia.
