<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, March 2,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DAY _ Daily file on McCain and Bush. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution/Herman, Austin American-Statesman). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Leading in California polls, an embattled Bush must win
the state's 162 delegates while McCain needs to take New York's
closed primary _ along with its 101 delegates _ and sweep the
northeast (polls show McCain leading in Mass., Conn. Rhode Island
and New York) on Tuesday. Are we headed for an east-west showdown?
Plus any Bush daily developments. (Heath/Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSHTV _ The always-tentative dance every political season
between national candidates and the powerful electronic press is
swaying to a new beat this election year. Republican candidate Sen.
John McCain welcomes reporters onto his bus with open arms, and his
so-called ``Straight Talk Express'' has produced lots of stories
that show the Arizonan in a positive light. Accesibility, the
theory goes, leads to more _ and usually more favorable _ coverage.
But has the ``McCain Phenomena,'' as some reporters have dubbed his
renegade campaign, resulted in coverage that serves the voting
public? (Holloway,Austin American-Statesman). 37.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-JEB _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida's Catholic, interracially
married governor went on national television Wednesday to defend
brother George W. Bush's visit last month to a South Carolina
college that frowns on both Catholicism and interracial marriage.
Jeb Bush said he himself would speak at Bob Jones University, even
though its published rules would mean he and Mexican-born wife,
Columba, would have been expelled for dating had they met there as
students. Bush said it was incumbent on political candidates to
spread their message to groups they might not agree with, and
accused GOP presidential rival Sen. John McCain of stooping to a
divisive ``wedge issue.'' (Date, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE _ LOS ANGELES _ Coverage of the Gore-Bradley debate
in Los Angeles. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-BAXTER _ Watching a campaign die at the Gore-Bradley
debate. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of
the House immigration subcommittee, submitted a bill Wednesday that
would increase the number of immigrants allowed under the H-1B visa
program by 45,000 this year. That is far fewer than a technology
industry-backed bill introduced last month in the Senate to boost
visas by nearly 300,000 over the next three years. (Geewax, Cox
News Service). 18. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH _ NABATIYEH, Lebanon _ Hidar Madloum is ready
to die in his fight against Israel, but that's not the only reason
for his army's success. In 12 years with the Lebanese Hezbollah
guerillas, he has witnessed advances that make the small force a
surprisingly tough adversary. Today, Madloum's Hezbollah appears to
be on the verge of driving Israel out of Lebanon. In the rugged
mountains of south Lebanon, guerrillas like Madloum have matched a
superior force with self-sacrifice, adaptability and a keen use of
propaganda. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Updating, re-sending for those Cox papers trhat have not
run it previously.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-DAYTON _ WASHINGTON _ Michael Turner, mayor of Dayton,
Ohio, discusses how his community has sustained a wide-range of
contacts, including humanitarian assistance and rebuilding efforts
with the people of Bosnia since the Dayton Peace Accords as the
National Press Club's morning newsmaker. (Schultz, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ELIAN _ WASHINGTON - The Senate Judiciary Committee hears
from Fidel Castro's daughter and Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez
as it considers legislation to make him a U.S. citizen. (Lipman,
Cox News Service). 15. WITH PHOTO (by Rick McKay).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-FLOODS _ Photo essay on Venezuela's slow recovery from
recent floods with short story. (Text by Melvin, phoos by
Karas/Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-PLEA _ ATLANTA _ T.J. Solomon, the teenager who shot
and wounded six classmates at Heritage High School in the Atlanta
suburb of Rockdale County last May, will have an opportunity to
enter a plea in Rockdale County Superior Court on April 6. Judge
Sidney Nation informed Solomon's attorneys of the date this week.
At the arraignment, Solomon could plead guilty, not guilty, not
guilty by insanity, or one of a handful of other available pleas.
(Farber, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN-SMITH _ Susan Smith's mother says her daughter is so
mentally ill that she has attempted suicide while serving a life
sentence for murder in South Carolina for the ghastly 1994 drowning
of her two young sons in a lake. ''She has mutilated herself,
cutting her arms and wrists with whatever object she could find,''
Linda Russell writes in ''Susan Smith My Daughter,'' scheduled for
publication April 1, the latest book and one of several new media
projects focusing on the case. ''It is still as simple as everybody
still wants to know why,'' said Andrew Yex, a Los Angeles producer
working on a Learning Channel documentary, one of several recently
produced or in the works about the crime that shocked America.
Production crews for MSNBC, the British Broadcasting Corp. and
Tampa television station WTSP recently interviewed people around
Union, S.C., who were involved in the case. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-RACE _ ATLANTA _ Lt. Mike Smith is the commander of
Atlanta's homicide unit. He also is the investigator who arrested
football great Ray Lewis. Smith also gave the most damning
testimony at Lewis' bond hearing, calling the football star a liar.
Now Smith is in hot water for allegedly making a racial remark to
two witnesses who know Lewis. The men walked out of the city's
homicide office about three weeks ago after the remark was made and
would not talk to or cooperate with police. Now the incident is
under investigation by the APD's Office of Professional Standards
and the Criminal Investigations Division. Smith confirms he said
something that was taken the wrong way. We have on the record
confirmation about the investigation, as well. (Longa-Sanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
