<HEADER>
A3241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GARAGE-DOOR-TRIAL-HNS     03-01 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARAGE-DOOR-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIREFIGHTER'S SUIT AGAINST DOOR OPENER COMPANY NEARS COURT
DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUSTINO AGUILA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The case of a severely injured firefighter who
has sued a leading manufacturer of garage door openers is scheduled
to go to trial next week in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Stapper, 39, is seeking nearly at least $8 million from
the Genie Corp. She contends that she and a fellow firefighter were
trapped inside a garage while fighting a house fire on March 9,
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyers contend that the garage door opener did not work,
and that the nylon cord that can disengage the door from the
automatic system had burned.
</P>
<P>
   Stapper, who no longer works for the Fire Department, suffered
burns over 40 percent of her body and was left permanently scarred
and legally blind.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Mambretti, a 25-year veteran of the department, died in
the fire. Two other firefighters, Keith Onishi and John Pieretti,
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melanie can't work anymore,'' said Browne Greene, a lawyer
representing Stapper. ``It was one of the most tragic fires the San
Francisco Fire Department ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   During a pretrial hearing on Tuesday, Genie lawyers argued that
their product was not at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that what happened to Melanie Stapper is a tragic
situation,'' said Mary Wirth, one of the lawyers representing the
company. ``But it didn't happen because of a faulty garage door
opener. She was injured because the firefighters did not watch her
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapper and the other firefighters entered the burning home
through the garage door. According to reports, there was no smoke
or flames in the garage when the firefighters carried a hose
through the garage to get to the burning house.
</P>
<P>
   Heat and smoke forced Stapper and Mambretti to retreat to the
garage, but by then the door had closed and would not open. It took
firefighters outside more than 10 minutes, according to reports, to
cut a hole in the door and get their colleagues out. Stapper was
badly burned and Mambretti died a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   Stapper's lawyers said they were seeking more than $1 million
for medical expenses, $5 million for future medical bills, more
than $2 million for lost wages and an unspecified amount for
general pain and suffering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1419EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3242 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CALIFORNIA-GOVERNOR-H     03-01 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA-GOVERNOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DAVIS' REMARKS ON JUDGES IRKS LAWMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis shocked some legal scholars and
high-powered members of the Legislature by saying he had a litmus
test for appointing state judges.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, said the judges ``are there to reflect the
sentiments that I expressed during the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that if judges broke their promise to follow his
philosophy, they should resign.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks, made Tuesday at a breakfast meeting while attending
the National Governors' Association in Washington, reminded
lawmakers in Sacramento of Davis' declaration last year that the
Legislature's job was to implement his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the former lieutenant governor of California, was elected
governor in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said Davis showed contempt for the legislative
process. Now, they say Davis is showing contempt for the judicial
process and could jeopardize fair trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could abolish state government and let him run it
by fiat,'' said state Senate President pro tem John Burton, D-San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't support an independent Legislature,'' Burton said,
``so why would he support an independent judiciary? It's consistent
with his view that the other two branches are irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he had told all prospective judicial appointees his
views on important issues, including the death penalty and
abortion. He supports both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've let every judge know that while they do have to follow
the law, they're there because I appointed them, and they need to
keep faith with my electoral mandate,'' Davis said. ``Obviously
judges have to follow the law. But in interpreting the law, I
expect them to keep faith with the representations I made to the
electorate. Otherwise, we're doing a great disservice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's outrageous,'' said Erwin Chemerinsky, a law professor
at the University of Southern California. ``A judge is not a
Cabinet member who is there to carry out a governor's or a
president's policies.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, the governor appoints trial judges directly. For
appellate court and state Supreme Court positions, the governor
makes appointments that are reviewed by a commission made up of the
attorney general, chief justice of the state Supreme Court and a
senior appeal court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Davis so far has appointed 16 judges to the state trial courts
and four to the state courts of appeal, all of whom have been
confirmed by the state Commission on Judicial Appointments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
