<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOGIE-FILMS-HNS &LR;      03-01 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOGIE-FILMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WARNER LAUNCHES VIDEO TRIBUTE TO `BOGIE' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim; with: BOGIE-LIST)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB STEPHENS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In celebration of Humphrey Bogart's cinematic
achievements and irreducible status as a cultural icon, Warner Home
Video has launched a ``Humphrey Bogart Collection'' on DVD with
``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``Key Largo'' and, in two versions, ``The
Big Sleep.'' (``Casablanca'' was released some time ago, but it has
been repackaged as part of this project.)
</P>
<P>
   Warner also has made the DVD titles available on VHS, along with
15 other movies featuring Bogart. Furthermore, the video company
has put together a ``Bogart &AMP; Bacall Collection'' that contains
four films the witty, romantic couple made together.
</P>
<P>
   Because the most memorable of Bogart's characters _ damaged,
reluctant heroes _ are from the film noir period, the DVDs
concentrate on them. They are good examples of the work that gave
birth to the legend. In these movies, few of the men he portrays
are old-fashioned protagonists, courtly men who make no mistakes:
Bogart's greatest characters are busted by the depression,
brutalized by war, made violent by their dealings with criminals
and, sometimes, broken by the loss of love.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to misconstrue the offscreen ``Bogie,'' as he
came to be affectionately known, as an on-the-level, average Joe
with whom male moviegoers could identify. He possessed an
off-handed amiability, even in some of his criminal parts, that
audiences recognized as genuine. In the beginning, he seemed like a
blue-collar actor, and his studio, Warner Bros., did produce
populist melodramas, works that depicted poverty and class conflict
as major sources of crime.
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, he was the privileged son of a Manhattan surgeon
who briefly attended Yale. Behind his down-to-earth facade resided
a worldly man respectful of his own limitations, who rarely
harbored aspirations that defied the odds.
</P>
<P>
   The working-class, ill-defined Bogart of the 1930s often played
second fiddle to James Cagney and Edward G. Robinson in the Warner
films. Cagney became a star by combining the graceful movement of a
dancer with his psycho-killer frenzy, and Robinson, occasionally
maniacal himself, played crime bosses who were, to some degree,
insulated by their position in the mob aristocracy, a hierarchy
that mimicked that of big business.
</P>
<P>
   But Bogart plugged away, paying his dues and perfecting his
skills in roles that ranged from comedy to tragedy and all points
in between. He appeared in Westerns, comic parts, a trucker movie,
crime films, a Runyonesque spy spoof and, of all things, a horror
movie in which he was made up to look like the sinister Boris
Karloff (``The Return of Dr. X'').
</P>
<P>
   Bogart wasn't an ideal leading man in a moral sense because he
specialized in frightening displays of hatred, uncontrolled
violence and a bitterness toward the world that are remarkable for
one who became such a beloved figure.
</P>
<P>
   Three things contributed to his rehabilitation, in spite of the
nihilistic impulses that often were hinted at: The idolization of
Bogart by the French, particularly in Jean-Luc Godard's use of his
image in ``Breathless,'' a film in which he's alluded to in a
stripped-down version of himself, a representation of debonair
nonconformity (the snap-brim hat, trench coat, shot of whiskey and
ever-present cigarette); the extremely romantic reduction of his
``Casablanca'' character, Rick Blaine, as someone worthy of
emulation in the Herbert Ross/Woody Allen ``Play It Again, Sam,''
and, during the existential disenchantment that swept American
campuses in the 1960s, the developing presumption that he embodied
a vogueish anti-heroism.
</P>
<P>
   The last conclusion was a consequence of a slight, but critical,
misreading of his celluloid nature. It wasn't that Bogart's
characters refused to do good, but recognized, as denizens of noir,
that they were operating under severe constraints, locked into
morally compromised positions from which the idea of what
constituted victory or virtue was unclear. Such men have no strict
code of honor like a knight, a soldier or a cowboy: They just
continue on as best they can, with whatever they have left to give,
or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Bogart's characters are surprisingly complex, but, in noir,
their faces are transformed into impenetrable masks, purposefully
designed by the wearer to obscure expression. Smoking a ritualistic
cigarette, a sign of confidence and virility in the 1940s, they
withdraw into the shadows of fatalistic movies, penumbras that
conceal their motives and unspeakable vulnerability. Their verbal
forays are evasive, ironic, sardonic, even cruel _ straightforward
only when a life is on the line and then, overcompensating,
violently assertive. It's clear such men were deeply hurt.
Isolation suits them.
</P>
<P>
   But, had Bogart the actor remained a stereotypical Lone Wolf, he
might have been forgotten. For at his best, he was defined in
relation to a woman, and that is how we remember him.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Maltese Falcon,'' Bogart sells out Mary Astor, whom he
loves, to satisfy his obligation to his dead partner; in
``Casablanca,'' he sacrifices his affection for Ingrid Bergman to a
greater cause than that of the individual; in ``High Sierra,'' his
death is protective of Ida Lupino's future; and in every picture
with the woman who became his wife, Lauren Bacall, he's overcome by
her affirmation of his worth and gives in to her unique, sexy
humor.
</P>
<P>
   Movie dancer Fred Astaire was incomplete without Ginger Rogers,
and that's the way Bogart was without his Bacall or Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Bogart's image was made whole by actresses, so were the works
of talented directors and novelists complemented by his presence.
Through his collaborations with John Huston and Howard Hawks, and
his interpretations of the detectives that communicated the beliefs
of Dashiell Hammett and Raymond Chandler, Bogart helped compose the
essential visage of the alienated, urban, 20th century man.
</P>
<P>
   In Huston's ``Falcon,'' Sam Spade resigns himself to Hammett's
pessimism, the author's view that love is impossible, that lies are
the true language of the world and that anything salvaged from a
bad situation by a good act is, itself, inevitably corrupted.
Hammett accepts the world as he sees it and wastes no time with
regrets. It is to Bogart's credit that he creates so much tension
in his final, condemnatory tirade against Astor's Brigid
O'Shaughnessy that he momentarily flirts with the escape that love
might provide, then, in a gesture of utter bleakness, rejects it.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, on the other hand, is a romantic who's disheartened by
the fallen paradise of Los Angeles, and his detective, Philip
Marlowe, barely survives by leading a life of unrewarded morality
and poetic solitude. In Hawks' ``Sleep,'' Bogart captures Marlowe's
ethical quality when, after his repudiation of all commitments, he
watches a little guy die to keep secret his unworthy lover's name
and whereabouts. Marlowe then pursues the crime boss and hit man
responsible for his death.
</P>
<P>
   As illuminating as these roles are, however, it's most fruitful
to consider Bogart's turning point role as ``Mad Dog'' Roy Earle in
Raoul Walsh's ``High Sierra.'' After the enjoyable, but not
likable, grotesques of Cagney and Robinson, Bogart ingeniously
humanizes the criminal. In this breakthrough performance, just
before he was assumed into the elite pantheon, exalted as a
permanent part of the Hollywood mythos for ``Casablanca'' and the
other classics, he hooks up with the general audience for the last
time as one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   With the Great Depression only a few years in the past, and the
people's memories still fresh with experiences of deprivation and
predatory capitalism, Bogart identifies with them, takes up the
iron pride of the worker and creates a fugitive hero. He strikes
back at the repressive monolith of a society that does not
recognize redemption and becomes a legendary outlaw for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sierra,'' Bogart undergoes the metamorphosis into Bogie, a
man in whom the audience has a loving investment, and takes his
first step, with guns blazing, into film history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
