<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CALIFORNIA SKI RESORTS ARE BRIMMING WITH SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Notes from the outdoors:
</P>
<P>
   Wall of snow: As March opens, Kirkwood Ski Area south of Tahoe
on Highway 88 near Carson Pass now has 24 feet of snow at its top
lift staging area. Other ski areas with more than 200 inches of
snow are Sugar Bowl with 228 inches (19 feet) and Alpine Meadows
with 210 inches (17.5 feet).
</P>
<P>
   Wall of water: Shasta Lake, California's biggest reservoir, has
been climbing so fast from storm runoff that water officials are
now dumping water to make room for spring snowmelt. Releases into
the Sacramento River are now at 34,000 cubic feet per second (seven
times that of a month ago), and the lake is still only 26 feet from
filling. The inside word is that the giant lake, with 370 miles of
shoreline, will be allowed to fill in early May.
</P>
<P>
   Earthquake watch: You might start bracing for a big earthquake.
California typically has 1,500 to 1,600 earthquakes per week, but
that number has fallen to under 200 for two weeks running, perhaps
indicating that pressure could be building up at the faults for a
significant shaker.
</P>
<P>
   The real record: After a 30-inch, 17-pound trout was caught two
weeks ago at Shadow Cliffs Lake in Pleasanton, it was mistakenly
reported that the fish was a lake record. Nope: An 18 1/4-pound
rainbow trout was caught last year by Roland Gove of Fremont,
raising talk that it is inevitable that a first-ever 20-pound trout
will be caught at a Bay Area lake.
</P>
<P>
   Deer draw: The Department of Fish and Game will implement a new
deer tag drawing system, called ``Draw By Choice,'' designed to
give California deer hunters a better chance of hunting in their
first-choice deer zone. In the old system, there were lots of valid
squawks where some hunters received premium tags with their second
or third choice over hunters who selected the same zone with their
first choice.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon experiment: Another 10,800 salmon have been planted at
Del Valle Reservoir south of Livermore, joining 15,000 planted a
year ago. The salmon from last year's plant now weigh almost 2
pounds, and with plenty of non-game forage available in the lake,
are expected to start hitting 3 to 5 pounds by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   California ranked No. 2?: The most recent boat registration
statistics have been released, with California (894,347 boats)
ranked No. 2 behind Michigan (980,378), but ahead of No. 3 Florida
(805,581), No. 4 Minnesota (780,097) and No. 5 Texas (625,754). But
hey, California does not require registration of non-motorized
canoes, kayaks and rowboats, as does Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Boating up, Jet Skis down: Every segment of boat sales is up
except for Jet Skis and other personal watercraft. Up: Outboard
boats and motors, inboard runabouts, inboard cruisers, canoes and
sailboats. Down: Personal watercraft, with only 106,000 sold
nationally last year.
</P>
<P>
   Camping way up: Of 59 recreational activities, wilderness
camping had the second-highest increase nationally last year of all
recreational activities, up 58.9 percent with 14.6 million
participants. Analyst Kathryn Kloppenburg credited outdoor family
adventuring for the increase.
</P>
<P>
   Slam dunk for Forest Service: A majority of America's 50 million
hunters and anglers want existing roadless areas in national
forests to remain roadless, according to a recent national survey
commissioned by the Theodore Roosevelt Conservation Alliance. The
survey found that 86 percent of anglers and 83 percent of hunters
supported efforts by sportsmen and women to keep the remaining
roadless areas in national forests free of roads.
</P>
<P>
   No logic: The U.S. commercial catch quota for small coastal
sharks is 790,000 pounds. But the number of dead sharks discarded
as unwanted by shrimp netters in the Gulf of Mexico is 5 million
pounds, the International Game Fish Association report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
