<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-ALVAREZ-2TAKES-BO     03-01 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ALVAREZ-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIAN ALVAREZ DRAWS ON HIS LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ From the time Leonel Alvarez was a
youngster in Remedios in the mountainous region of Antioquia,
Colombia, he knew soccer would be his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only 7 or 8 years old and my mother used to lock me in
the house,'' Alvarez recalled recently. ``I would have to climb out
the window to go play soccer. Everyone always wanted me to play but
I would have to make a deal with them _ after the game, they would
have to lift me up so I could climb back through the window so I
wouldn't get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez grew up to become one of Colombia's most revered
sportsmen. The image of the innocent youngster sneaking out the
window contrasts with the imposing, even threatening-looking
Alvarez, his long, curling black locks framing a sharp nose and
steely eyes. Alvarez, who joined the Revolution late last season,
can be an intimidating presence on the soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   But when Alvarez is explaining the tactics of soccer to younger
players, or conducting an interview, he exudes the confidence and
warmth of a gregarious person who is comfortable with his celebrity
status.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was a part of the most celebrated generation of
Colombian soccer players ever, along with exuberant midfielder
Carlos Valderrama, extroverted goalkeeper Rene Higuita, and the
late Andres Escobar.
</P>
<P>
   They brought Colombia to the World Cup finals for the first time
and became the first Colombian team to win the South American
championship, the Copa Libertadores. They captured the imagination
of a nation and attracted a following that included Nobel
prize-winning author Gabriel Garcia Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   But Colombia was ill-prepared for this sudden success. And the
combination of fame and fortune, plus a volatile socioeconomic
situation, led to disappointment and tragedy in the 1994 World Cup
as Escobar was assassinated after a 2-1 loss to the US.
</P>
<P>
   This signaled the beginning of a decline in fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The group aged. Higuita was imprisoned after intervening in a
kidnapping. Freddy Rincon moved to Brazil, Alvarez and Valderrama
to the United States, where they are helping to guide and inspire a
new enterprise called Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined playing in the US,'' Alvarez said. ``But this
is a league that, in time, will be very strong. I don't know how
long it will take, though it will become a very competitive league.
The players have the qualities, they work hard, they have the
conditioning. They need a little more professionalism. They don't
need foreign players coming here on vacation, but they need the
help and support of experienced players.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez is a natural for the guidance role. On the field, he is
a commanding, composed presence, reading the game and distributing
the ball with poise and precision. In Colombia, Alvarez's hard
tackling and physical presence allowed the midfield creators such
as Valderrama to express themselves. If Colombian soccer were a
Latin Jazz band, Alvarez would be the bassist, able to lay down a
strong background rhythm whether they were playing cumbia,
merengue, vallenato, or straight-ahead jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played my first professional game Dec. 18, 1983, for
Medellin,'' Alvarez said. ``They saw me in the pre-Olympic
tournament in Bolivia, and that is where this generation all
started. Colombia always used to go home after the first round of
those tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we had Luis Perea, Bernardo Redin, Arnoldo Iguaran,
Andres Escobar. We went to the Copa America 1987 in Argentina. We
played Argentina, which had that whole band of guys, including
Maradona, who had just won the 1986 World Cup in Mexico. And we
defeated them, 2-1.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the Colombians began capturing attention. Guided by
coach Francisco Maturana, an orthodontist, they expressed the
creativity and passion of the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Copa America, we toured Europe and it was the first
time at Wembley for a Colombian team,'' Alvarez said. ``We made a
pact to present a great image of Colombian football.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the game, and ping, ping, ping _ 18 touches, all
over the field, the English could not do anything about it. It was
a full stadium, we tied, 1-1, Andres Escobar scored the goal and
(England coach) Bobby Robson gave us great compliments. People said
we played like Brazil. In my whole life this was the very best
experience I have ever had in soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   But signs of trouble soon appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the national team players joined Maturana with Nacional,
the Medellin club that traditionally comprises only Colombian
players. Nacional won the Dimayor title and became the first
Colombian club to win the Copa Liberatores. Next would be the
Intercontinental Cup in Tokyo, another chance to project a positive
image for Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, a (linesman) was killed and they suspended the season,''
Alvarez said. ``We had no games and we trained only sporadically.
And there we were, in Japan, playing a great organization like
Milan. We lacked rhythm, fitness. Despite this, we played 118
minutes even with them before (Alberigo) Evani scored.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Colombian national team adventure was only starting. It
qualified for the World Cup for the first time and brought an
adventurous and inspiring style to a conservative Italia '90.
Higuita was caught far out of goal by Cameroon's Roger Milla, and
the Colombians were eliminated in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   But the Colombians had established themselves as a factor, not a
fluke or a novelty act. They would be back for USA '94.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1993, La Seleccion went to Buenos Aires and
defeated Argentina, 5-0. They were applauded off the field by a
crowd that included Maradona, who said the Colombians ``played like
we used to play.'' Pele' designated the Colombians as heirs to the
Brazilian legacy and predicted they would win the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   This was the highest of praise from the living masters of the
South American game. After decades of being trounced by the
Argentines and Brazilians, the Colombian Aguila (Eagle) was flying
over everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The populist bandwagon expanded to every sector of the Colombian
population. To Gabriel Garcia Marquez, the team was the
personification of magic realism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Marquez came to the games and we met him and talked a
lot,'' Alvarez said. ``He is an excellent person, very intelligent,
spirited. He had a lot of hope for us. He believed we represented
the color and imagination of Colombia.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fervor went beyond reason. Even Marquez got into the
spirit, wagering his automobile that Colombia would defeat the US.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started receiving threats before the game,'' Alvarez said.
``One of our players (Gabriel `Barabbas' Gomez) did not play
because they threatened his family and the family of the coaching
staff. It's very difficult to play with threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was this. We had beaten the US almost every time
we played, 95 percent of the games, so everyone was betting on
Colombia. Everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably 95 percent of the population had wagered on Colombia.
So, it would have been disastrous for those controlling the bets
had Colombia won.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere around the team had been damaged. But it
started because of the game before that, with Romania. If we had
won that game we would only need a tie against the US. We could
have tied and advanced.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
