<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-ALVAREZ-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     03-01 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ALVAREZ-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla.: ... and advanced.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 22, 1994, the US broke a 10-year losing streak against
the Colombians. Escobar, retreating to cover a sharp cross from
John Harkes, deflected the ball into the Colombia net. The bookies
breathed easier and an entire populace went into shock. The
Americans were actually winning. Ernie Stewart would make the score
2-0. A desperate rally cut the deficit to 2-1 on a late header by
Adolfo ``El Tren'' Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Escobar was gunned down outside a Medellin
nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard the news I broke into tears and couldn't stop
crying all night,'' Alvarez said. ``We had played together and been
through so much, counting on Andres to give us security in the back
in so many big games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian soccer boom effectively had ended. The Colombians
would continue to enchant with their imaginative play. They would
produce precocious talents such as Ivan Cordoba, who is starting
with Inter in Milan, and 16-year-old Johnnier Montano of Parma.
</P>
<P>
   But the inconsistencies and incongruities persist. One day,
Colombians are euphoric because the team has reproduced the magic
of the recent past and the next day it has lost to Brazil, 9-0.
Coach Javier Alvarez was fired after that defeat, and noted ``a
week ago we were gods.''
</P>
<P>
   La Seleccion has provided an avenue of hope, sense of pride, or
at least an outlet from tensions, for Colombia. But the
socioeconomic problems are now inhibiting the progress of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people don't have work, so they can't buy a ticket to the
stadium,'' Alvarez said. ``They can't get work because of what is
going on there. Trucks are stuck on the road with fruit rotting.
The people want to work, but jobs are becoming scarce. And now, no
one is going to invest in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seleccion needs to play games against top teams to
improve. Look at who they have played and lost to recently _ El
Salvador, Trinidad. But you call Scotland and tell them you will
pay them $100,000 to come to Colombia and they will say they can't
come. They are afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Seleccion can help the image of the country but not if they
lose, 9-0. But the problem is not coaches or players. The new coach
could lose a game, 8-0, then what happens? The problem is the
directors. They always remain the same and this is the cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombia and the US could be headed for another showdown in the
Gold Cup in Miami. The Colombians beat Jamaica and the US defeated
Haiti in their opening games. Alvarez is there, a symbol of his
country, but with sensibilities for both nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia is a small country and we have a civil war, yes,''
Alvarez said. ``We have bombs, narcotrafficos. But it is a very
beautiful country, very pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I am worried. Everybody has fear in a civil war. I want
my family to come here but they want to stay in Colombia. It is
their home.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez's wife, Maria, and children, Leo Estefano, 8, and
Valentina, 6, will join him in Boston. His mother, Fabiola Zuleta,
a clothes designer, and sisters, Maria, Gudiela, and Sandra, will
remain in Colombia. And his father?
</P>
<P>
   ``My father is Dios,'' Alvarez said. ``I say that because he
abandoned us when we were kids. So, God became my father. Now, I
remember that when my kids are sick, and I run to get them what
they need because I remember the sadness of not having a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to mature quickly. I had to supervise my sisters with
their boyfriends, tell them what time to leave. It would be 10:30
at night and they would have to leave because I had to get up to
play soccer the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my sisters got married, since we had no father, I had to
go to the church to give away the bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was acquired by the Revolution from Dallas in a trade
for Ecuadoran striker Ariel Graziani late last season. The team
struggled under player-coach Walter Zenga but his replacement,
Fernando Clavijo, is building the team through the middle, using
Alvarez as a foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect for (Zenga) as a player and as a coach,''
Alvarez said. ``Unfortunately, things didn't work out. He did the
best he could and the important thing is, he put his heart into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fernando was a great player and knows a lot about futbol. We
have to be willing to die for him and the other coaches on the
field. It's all about heart. You play every game like it is a
final, and you are playing for the title. We have a coach with a
human side and if we don't play for him they are going to bring in
an army-style coach to order us around. We have to set our goals
high, to win the title, and then we will at least make it into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in two World Cup finals, the Copa Libertadores,
Copa Intercontinentale, Copa America, Olympic qualifying. And now,
I want to win a title in the US.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
