<SLUG> BC-EXPENSIVE-CHECKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW EARNERS, DISTRUSTFUL OF BANKS, TURN TO CHECK CASHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Armed with utility bills and clutching checks, the
crowd begins forming every morning shortly before 8.
</P>
<P>
   One recent frigid day, the regulars hovered in the cold,
patiently waiting for the doors to the Boston Checkcashers office
to open so they could pay bills, send money electronically to
relatives, and cash weekly paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd and some say pernicious twist, low-income Americans
are so distrustful of banks that they are shunning offers of free
checking and savings accounts and choosing instead to pay stiff
fees at check-cashing outlets and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   These businesses are booming, enjoying the support of the 10
million Americans who do not have checking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust banks and I don't trust myself with checks,''
said Carolyn Brown, 31, a single working mother who frequents a
Boston Checkcashers store near her home.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a cashier at a grocery store, used to have a checking
account, but had to give it up after she ``bounced too many
checks.'' She decided then that her banking days were over. No more
ATM cards, no monthly checking-account fees, and no worrying about
balancing checkbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the high fees that the check-cashing stores
charge, but I'm generally satisfied with them,'' Brown added.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's suspicion of banks is not rare. About 40 percent of US
families with incomes below $10,000 don't have a checking account,
compared to the 1 percent of families with incomes above $50,000,
according to a 1995 Survey of Consumer Finances, released by the
Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these ``unbanked'' citizens and many community activists
say check-cashing stores have historically served as an alternative
to established banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The check-cashing stores have been here for residents when
banks wouldn't come into our neighborhoods,'' said Joyce Stanley, a
community activist and executive director of the Dudley Square Main
Streets, a city-run effort to help revitalize economically
depressed neighborhoods. ``I think they'll be around for a long
time, especially since certain people have established a loyalty
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics charge that check-cashing companies, which charge as
much as 10 percent of a check's value to cash it, are draining the
wallets of poor and working-class people already struggling to cope
on limited means.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford the check-cashing fees, but many of us have
tried to get bank accounts before but were turned down,'' said
Regina Woods, 44. ``It's a no-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with a fundamental ignorance,'' said Kevin
Dillard, executive director of the Organization for New Equality, a
Boston-based national organization that has been critical of the
check-cashing industry. ``It's all in the spirit of good
old-fashioned laziness. These people go into the same check-cashing
store, and they don't look at the fact that they're being taken
advantage of by the check fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond having to pay high fees, people who patronize
check-cashing outlets also are hurting their financial future,
Dillard said, because ``saving money isn't possible, and
establishing credit isn't possible either.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Powers, a spokesman for the Massachusetts Department of
Transitional Assistance, said expensive fees at check-cashing
firms, along with fraud problems, led the department three years
ago to give clients Electronic Benefit Transfer cards instead of
checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get rid of the exorbitant charges that
check-cashing stores charged,'' Powers said. ``Now, individuals can
go right to the ATM machine and withdraw funds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials for check-cashing companies say that while it may
cost more to do business with them, the higher price allows them to
provide better services to customers who do not want to deal with
the rules and regulations of traditional banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the people who come into our lobby are here for a
reason,'' said David Backman, assistant director of Boston
Checkcashers Inc, which operates a chain of 19 stores in and around
Boston. ``We provide a service to the blue-collar person who
doesn't have an ATM or checking account and who don't want to be
nickel and dimed by the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Backman noted, many check-cashing stores do things that
many banks don't, such as wire money electronically or allow
customers to pay utility bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like a 7-Eleven,'' Backman said. ``You can come to us
for convenience, but you're going to have to pay for the
convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation and popularity of check-cashing companies has
made it difficult for banks trying to move into neighborhoods and
attract customers they had in the past ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Bank has launched a $250,000 campaign in Massachussetts to
encourage residents to open up basic checking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check-cashing stores offer a convenience to many customers
that banks didn't offer several years ago; that convenience now
exists with banks,'' said Jim Schepker, a spokesman for Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling residents that if they establish a relationship
with a bank, they'll gain access to a full gamut of products and
services,'' Schepker said. ``They can open a lifeline checking
account and deposit their check in an ATM machine and immediately
draw funds from that check. But I don't think many people are aware
of this.''
</P>
<P>
   A basic checking account, Schepker noted, could cost customers
as little as $2.50, which allows for 10 monthly transactions _ a
much lower cost than traditional check-cashing fees.
</P>
<P>
   But with more than 100,000 people streaming in and out of Boston
Checkcashers stores every year, Backman said, the industry is now
branching out beyond low-income customers to try to tap
middle-class residents.
</P>
<P>
   Backman would not release profit figures for his company, but
nationwide the industry makes millions of dollars each year,
specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Sowyrda works for Boston Cashcheckers as a Beacon Hill
lobbyist. One result: MBTA bus passes are sold at the check-cashing
stores. ``In the last five years, we've become respected.'' he
said. ``The stigma of welfare mothers coming in here to cash their
checks has disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Backman said, there is a price to be paid for making it
easy for customers to cash checks. Sitting at his desk, he
periodically glanced down at the returned checks piled high on a
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these people walked away with money,'' he said,
pointing to checks that were sent back after payment was stopped or
rejected due to insufficient funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making money, but we still lose money each year,'' he
said. ``We've got to spend money and time trying to collect on
these checks. We don't like cashing personal checks. It's too much
of a risk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
