<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3314 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     03-01 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RAIN ON THIS PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take that, Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   The wealth effect bothering the Federal Reserve chairman so much
got a little richer Tuesday, as the Nasdaq stock index roared ahead
by another 118 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index, loaded with the hot technology stocks worrying
the Fed, has gained a whopping 15.4 percent over the first two
months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is everybody else. Though the Dow Jones
industrial average enjoyed a relatively upbeat session Tuesday,
gaining 89.7 points to 10,128.3, the ``old economy'' benchmark is
still down 11.9 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The widening gulf between old economy stocks and the shares of
high-tech ``new economy'' companies is startling by any measure. It
certainly isn't what Greenspan had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   He is not wholly responsible for what analysts today call a
bifurcated market. But there is no doubt that the Fed's push toward
higher interest rates has dragged down many stocks while having
virtually no impact on the most speculative highfliers Greenspan
would like to temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he intended to do was take the wind out of the sails of
the speculators, but all he did was kill the old economy,'' said
Scott Black, president of Delphi Management Inc. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates to slow an economy it believes is
growing too rapidly. But Greenspan has clearly raised a ``wealth
effect'' caused by huge stock market gains as a factor stoking the
hot economy. He may not really care about the value of stocks, but
is keenly worried about how those high prices ripple through the
American economy.
</P>
<P>
   The problem: Those higher rates, the traditional stick used by
Fed chairmen to tame excesses, haven't made a dent in the dot-com
stock world. The Nasdaq index has soared by 71 percent since Sept.
30. Tuesday was just another sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to dampen the expectations of investors today you'd
need to have a lot higher than a 7 percent Treasury bond,'' said
Robert Goodman, chief economist at Putnam Investments in Boston.
``You would need 10 percent to kill the market, expectations are so
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the rest of the market has been wilting in the face
of rising rates. Some sectors, such as bank stocks, are slumping by
25 percent or more since last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more (Greenspan) has jawboned and the more the Fed has
acted to raise rates, the more he's harmed these old economy
stocks,'' said Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer at
FleetBoston Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For all the impact Greenspan has had on the stock market in
recent months, he has been explicitly reluctant to use one tool at
his disposal that would likely hit those hot stocks in his sights.
</P>
<P>
   Initial margin requirements, the rules that govern how investors
can borrow money from brokers to buy stocks, are controlled by the
Fed but have not been touched since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Current rules require buyers to put up at least 50 percent of
the cost of stock purchases. Increase that ratio and you deflate
some leverage in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you changed the margin requirement, it would be
targeted directly at the frothiness of the market,'' said Samuel
Hayes, a professor emeritus at the Harvard Business School. ``My
guess is the Fed is afraid to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes thinks there is a good reason to think twice about that
course, comparing it to a ``firecracker'' that could spook stocks
and send them sharply lower. He's not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing margin requirements is a very public, symbolic event
that can possibly lead to a significant correction and he wants to
avoid that at all costs,'' said Mark Zandi, chief economist at RFA
Dismal Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   But Hayes, Zandi, and others think there are more discreet ways
for the Fed to put more pressure on borrowing by stock investors.
</P>
<P>
   Margin debt has increased substantially over the past two years,
but has absolutely soared since last November. Margin loans
increased by 25.4 percent to $228 billion in the last two months of
1999 and jumped by 62 percent for the full year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth of margin is stunning,'' said Frank Fernandez,
chief economist for the Securities Industry Association. ``The rise
we saw toward the end of the year exceeded our expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is evidence that brokerage companies have already
begun to tighten some margin requirements on their own. Many have
increased so-called maintenance margin requirements on the market's
most volatile stocks, even refusing to loan customers any money to
purchase a select few.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance margin, the rules governing cash-to-borrowing
percentages in a brokerage account on an ongoing basis, is changed
daily on specific stocks at some brokerages based on market
volatility.
</P>
<P>
   The list of stocks with higher maintenance margin requirements
set by US Clearing, a division of Fleet Securities Inc. whose rules
affect accounts at Quick &AMP; Reilly, Suretrade, and other brokerages,
rose to about 100 by January 1999. The same list covers about 250
stocks today.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy borrowers are not always buying stocks with all the
online discount brokerages you might expect. Fidelity Investments
reports only about 6 percent of its online brokerage customers are
borrowing on margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As markets get more volatile, that's why you look at it more
closely,'' said Tracey Curvey, executive vice president of Fidelity
Online Brokerage. ``We've always looked at this stuff very closely,
particularly in those accounts that are concentrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Greenspan would have no better luck cooling the market's
hot engine by pressing banks and brokers on their stock lending.
But it can't hurt to aim a little closer at the real target.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
