<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3317 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-PEOPLE     03-01 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEAUTIFUL-PEOPLE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIA MEETS LONDON IN `BEAUTIFUL PEOPLE'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 3 or later. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's hope for Europe yet in ``Beautiful People,'' Jasmin
Dizdar's absurd, mean-spirited and finally optimistic comedy about
Yugoslav refugees and multiculti Londoners, contrary to all their
basic impulses, finding ways to get along.
</P>
<P>
   A Bosnian living in England, Dizdar packs this multicharacter
roundelay with what initially appear to be ideas borrowed from
leading British filmmakers of the moment: Danny Boyle's visual
flash, Mike Leigh's eccentric character condescension, Ken Loach's
lefty social agenda. But gradually, a surreal yet humanistic humor
all his own emerges in Dizdar's film. ``Beautiful People,'' like
any number of movies from Britain or the Balkans, wallows in the
self-destructive tendencies of both individuals and tribes. The
difference with this one is in how it draws sentimental jollity out
of any number of ugly messes.
</P>
<P>
   Types from opposite ends of the continent, the class system and
the tolerance pool find their generally unsatisfactory lives
improved by interacting with foreign individuals. Dizdar, who also
wrote the screenplay, follows through on this central premise
without letting things get too schematic _ different story lines
have nicely varied comic tones and gradations of nastiness _ and
allows stories to overlap in a loose, natural-seeming way.
</P>
<P>
   On the wackier end of the narrative scale, a Croat and a Serb,
former neighbors, end up in side-by-side hospital beds after
chasing and pummeling each other through half the city. With the
ingenuity of determined invalids, one continues trying to kill the
other, always to be thwarted by an unflappable nurse and their ward
mate, an angry Welsh arsonist burned in his efforts to destroy
English vacation houses in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Even crazier is the tale of the young, junkie soccer hooligan
(Danny Nussbaum) who, too stoned to make it across the tarmac to a
plane headed for a Dutch World Cup qualifier, passes out on a
pallet of supplies that is then air-dropped into the war zone,
where his vice takes a topsy-turvy heroic turn.
</P>
<P>
   On the soapier side of things, a schlubby ob/gyn, his own family
in tatters, convinces a war rape victim and her husband to love the
baby that they don't want. There's also a BBC reporter who goes
barmy in the Balkans, comes back thinking he's a refugee and
somehow confuses his employer with Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In the plotline that best combines humor, horror and feel-good
forgiveness, a romance blooms between a displaced Bosnian
basketball player (Edin Dzandzanovic) and the rebellious
doctor-daughter (Charlotte Coleman) of a family of Tory twits. ``I
am, personally, very much against ethnic cleansing'' the sniggering
future brother-in-law says at one of those painfully awkward
meet-the-family dinners, but darned if the snooty Brits and the
regretful, penniless athlete don't find some kind of common ground
through love.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there's a lot of wishful thinking in ``Beautiful
People.'' The ongoing refrain of the oversimplifying peacemaker _
if only we could get to know each other as people, we'd discover we
have nothing to fight about _ echoes throughout the film. But
Dizdar and his cast (which blends experienced actors with talented
amateurs) go to great lengths to ensure that we do get to know the
people on screen. And he doesn't let any of them off easy, which
helps a great deal to make the film's polemics personal and alive.
We're glad when these characters' conditions improve, and even
happier that most of them learn how to be a little kinder in the
process. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Beautiful People'' (R; violence, language, drug use). &QL; 
The stars: Faruk Pruti, Dado Jehan, Charlotte Coleman, Nicholas
Farrell, Danny Nussbaum, Edin Dzandzanovic, Gilbert Martin. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Jasmin Dizdar. Produced
by Ben Woolford. Released by Trimark Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 47 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
