<HEADER>
A3319 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-01 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the famous place, after all, that not so long ago
licensed its famous name for T-shirts sporting that famous
yabba-dabba-doo Harvard man Fred Flintstone. It did, however, say
no to Bart Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   And now Harvard University is saying no _ maybe _ to Harvard
Pilgrim as it teeters on the brink. Let's see: Fred Flintstone yes,
Harvard Pilgrim, maybe, maybe not. This makes sense?
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is, indeed, one famous name. Punch up Switchboard.com,
the online telephone directory, and you'll come up with 725
individual listings for Harvard nationwide. There are more than 250
in Massachusetts alone.
</P>
<P>
   It's all so confusing. Maybe I can help. My credentials? I live
on Harvard Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard Business Review is part of the university, the
Harvard Gay &AMP; Lesbian Review is not. Harvard Book Stores in
Cambridge, Harvard Gulch Golf Course in Denver, Harvard Coney
Island in Detroit, and Harvard Drive-In Liquors in Santa Paula,
Calif., are not. The Harvard Course of Bartending, on the other
hand, is. So is the Harvard Independent, a magazine, though it
isn't independent.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard has been making news in recent years. Harvard Financial
Services (not to be confused with the keeper of Harvard's billions)
admitted it was broke several months back. Harvard Industries,
however, has been out of bankruptcy protection for more than a
year. Harvard International Technologies (stock symbol: HIT) folded
when its french fry vending machine fizzled. My favorite: Harvard
Scientific Corp. recently ran afoul of the Food and Drug
Administration for misleading test results on its male
anti-impotence drug. The stock sells for 51 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard tells me it is most concerned about protecting its good
name when it involves its core missions like education. These
schools then should be receiving a letter any day similar to the
one the university just sent Attorney General Tom Reilly on Harvard
Pilgrim: the Harvard School in Chicago; Harvard Academy in
Flushing, N.Y.; Harvard Academy in Sunrise, Fla.; Harvard-Westlake
School in North Hollywood, Fla.; Harvard-Kent School in
Charlestown; and Harvard public schools from Tacoma, Wash., to
Harvard, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard says the move to assert its rights regarding Harvard
Pilgrim is in line with its increased vigilance in protecting the
name over the last few years. The university's doomsday scenario in
Harvard Pilgrim's case is that a for-profit firm will buy it and be
able to use the name to sell almost anything without the
university's permission.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Harvard? It's happening. There's Harvard Group (in five
cities), Harvard House (in four cities), Harvard Hall in
Washington, and Harvard Hall Bingo in Philadelphia. It's hard to
figure out what is not being hawked with the Harvard name.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard (the university) is, in fact, a jewel that is woefully
underappreciated here. Without Harvard and MIT, Cambridge, on a
good day, wouldn't be Topeka. The two universities, hands down,
have done more than any other two institutions to make Boston the
place it is today.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard, for all its good intentions, has managed to pull
off a remarkable feat: In the course of a couple of weeks the
university has gone from a potential hero in the Harvard Pilgrim
mess to a potential goat. Harvard has no responsibility to bail out
Harvard Pilgrim from its own stupid mistakes, but it also shouldn't
be throwing a monkey wrench into Reilly's delicate attempts to save
the HMO, either.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, the Coke of education, has a responsibility to protect
its name. But it must pick its spots; Harvard Pilgrim is neither
the time nor the place. If Harvard wants exclusive control of its
name, it should find a name that every pizza shop and financial
planner on the block isn't already using.
</P>
<P>
   Something catchy like The World's Greatest University, which was
coined by my modest pal Alex Beam. And Beam might just be willing
to license it to Harvard _ for a fee and subject to the proper
restrictions, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey is a Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
bailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1509EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3321 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-MONA-REVIEW-LADN     03-01 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MONA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DROWNING MONA' DEEP IN CLEVER WRITING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 3 or later. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proving you don't necessarily need to whack somebody over the
head with zaniness to get them giggling, the makers of ``Drowning
Mona'' get a lot of mileage out of elements that its characters
don't acknowledge. Consider the vanity plates on the Yugos driven
by every character in the town of Verplanck, N.Y.; or the ``As Seen
on TV'' sign above the local mortician's shingle. Wacky stuff of
that ilk is constantly flitting across the screen and disappearing
before we're even aware we've been goosed.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, this screwy whodunit starring Danny DeVito and
co- produced by his Jersey films doesn't exactly get by on nuances.
Writer Peter Steinfeld milks a running gag about a character having
one hand _ the local cops are practically obsessed with it. And
exactly how subtle can you be depicting a town floozy (played with
seen-it-all blowziness by Jamie Lee Curtis) who totes a Wheel of
Fortune board game to her motel room trysts? (``I let you buy a
vowel. Then you wanted a free spin!'')
</P>
<P>
   Forced? Occasionally. Offbeat? Definitely. Funny? Oh yeah.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of a trailer trashy ``Ruthless People,'' ``Drowning Mona''
has Bette Midler at her shrewiest, DeVito doing Columbo and any
number of brain-challenged Verplanckians acting like they've been
spent the past 10 years sniffing model airplane glue in a Mayberry
watering hole. Nobody's a great character study, but they're sure a
kick to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins with much-hated Mona Dearly (Midler) driving a
sabotaged Yugo off a cliff into the lake, thereby forcing the
town's Broadway show tune-loving sheriff Wyatt Rash (DeVito) to do
some actual detective work. The suspects include Mona's
philandering husband Phil (William Fichtner), her son Jeff (Marcus
Thomas) and possibly even Phil's mistress Rona (Curtis).
</P>
<P>
   Also under suspicion is Bobby Calzone (a blond-mopped Casey
Affleck), a sweet but dim-witted type who operates JB landscaping
with Jeff. Bobby is someone the sheriff would rather not have to
arrest, since the kid's about to marry Wyatt's daughter, Ellen
(Neve Campbell). Through flashbacks, dear old Mona gets plenty of
opportunity to show why she richly deserves to sleep with the
fishes.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt's work isn't all that challenging, since every citizen
seems to live within a 10-mile radius, and, except for Bobby,
nobody in Verplanck seems to work much. They're too busy moteling,
boozing, fishing or composing musical odes to Mona's death. Wyatt's
deputies are far more interested in finding out what
!ital!really!ital! caused Jeff to lose his hand than in determining
who took Mona down.
</P>
<P>
   Director Nick Gomez, who has directed episodes of ``Oz'' and
``The Sopranos'' for HBO, demonstrates a deftness at comedy both
broad and deadpan. Certainly we're expected to laugh at these
upstate yokels, but their foibles resonate as well. (As a favor,
Bobby asks his brother to perform a ``brotherly de-boning'' for the
wedding dinner.) Steinfeld's script zings one-liners pretty much
from start to finish. Not all of them hit, but those that do are
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Since her turn in ``Ruthless People,'' Bette Midler has turned
playing a harpy into an art form; Mona's a cakewalk for her.
DeVito, who might otherwise have been cast as Phil, plays it
straight and calm here, although Sheriff Wyatt's a bit of an
oddball himself. Nearly walking off with the movie in a great cameo
is ``Saturday Night Live's'' Will Farrell (a dead ringer for Chevy
Chase) as Cubby the mortician.
</P>
<P>
   And just in case anybody wants to visit Verplanck _ a real
place, by the way, population less than 4,000 _ its on-screen
version is played primarily by Sierra Madre, a little town east of
Pasadena which, I would wager, does not have a single Yugo in its
entire city limits. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Drowning Mona'' (PG-13, language, some sexual
material). &QL; 
The stars: Danny DeVito, Bette Midler, Neve Campbell, Jamie Lee
Curtis. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Nick Gomez. Screenplay by Peter
Steinfeld. Released by Destination Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 31 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1510EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3326 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-PLANET-REVIEW-LA     03-01 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLANET-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD BUZZ FOR `WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM?'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 3 or later. Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women are from Venus, men are from Microsoft in Garry
Shandling's shaggy, soft-centered comedy ``What Planet Are You
From?'' Created and co-scripted by the erstwhile star of ``The
Larry Sanders Show,'' it features Shandling as an alien from an
all-male world of technologically advanced, emotion-free,
genitalia-deprived takeover artists whose assignment is, with the
help of a loudly buzzing mechanical aid, to get an Earth woman
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   While the line ``What's that noise?'' invariably proves a
running joke in the movie, what comes out of Harold the alien's
mouth elicits a wider range of puzzled responses because, of
course, the space guy's come-on lines aren't exactly deft. That's
to be expected from this kind of premise, as is, perhaps, Harold's
eventual conversion by a good woman to a guy-thing with feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise here, though, is that rather than the burlesquey
tone you'd reckon would go hand-in-hand with interplanetary sex
comedy (remember ``Earth Girls Are Easy''?), director Mike Nichols
keeps the humor behaviorally based and psychologically credible.
The film is greatly aided in this by an Annette Bening performance
that's every bit as good as her Oscar-nominated work in ``American
Beauty.'' She may marry a man from outer space in this one, but
it's more of a relationship than anything she had with Kevin
Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming to come from Seattle (see? Microsoft), Harold pretends
to be a banker and makes a fool of himself on the Phoenix dating
scene until his smarmy, duplicitous co-worker Perry (Greg Kinnear)
shows him where to really score: at an Alcoholics Anonymous
meeting. And he does, more or less, with Bening's winsome
recovering groupie Susan.
</P>
<P>
   She's led a pretty indulgent life up until then, and even though
Susan's sworn off sex before marriage as determinedly as she's
kicked the juice, something about Harold's straightforward yearning
for a family really turns her on. Against her and her best friends'
better judgment, Susan rushes into a Vegas quickie with the earnest
suitor. The weeklong honeymoon breaks all previous consummation
records. Susan doesn't even mind the buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   But serpents slither around this galactic Eden. An obsessed FAA
investigator (John Goodman) is onto Harold's true origins. The
visitor's own world leader (Ben Kingsley, appropriately humorless)
is impatiently asking why all the furious activity is taking so
long to produce a zygote. Meanwhile, the once attentive Harold not
only seems interested in only one thing when it comes to Susan; she
starts suspecting that he's incapable of even understanding
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Reductive as all this sounds, Nichols and his two leads do an
impressive job of making the story's dating manual insights feel
organic. In his first movie starring role, Shandling refracts that
Sandersian discomfort through a detached, slightly surreal mask
that fits remarkably well on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   And when Harold starts to get it _ I mean the emotional stuff _
the expressions on Shandling's face are priceless.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Bening who really anchors the piece. She brings out all
of Susan's disappointments, longings, high hopes (her impromptu
pajama performance of the old song, by the way, is the most
disarming movie moment so far this year), affection, insecurity and
distemper without ever straining a feeling or transition between
them. And, somehow, she remembers to stay funny most of the time.
Nichols keeps a light comic rhythm percolating, too. He paces the
laughs, and the attempted laughs, at a leisurely enough clip to
give us time to get involved with the characters. There's also
ample opportunity to savor Bo Welch's production design, which
makes the most of Arizona red rocks, sterile otherworld sets and
airplane bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In his maturity, the director of such word-driven movies as
``The Graduate,'' ``Carnal Knowledge'' and ``Who's Afraid of
Virginia Woolf?'' has developed a deeper appreciation for film's
visual pleasures. At the same time, Nichols' instinct for what can
go right and doesn't between women and men-creatures remains
sophisticated and, still, a yearning, exploratory thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Planet Are You From?'' never reaches real
out-of-this-world heights. But it's grounded in smart, solid human
comedy of a kind that's all but alien to Hollywood these days. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``What Planet Are You From?'' (R; sex, nudity, language,
violence). &QL; 
The stars: Garry Shandling, Annette Bening, John Goodman, Greg
Kinnear, Ben Kingsley. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Mike Nichols. Written by Garry
Shandling, Michael Leeson, Ed Solomon and Peter Tolan.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: One hour, 40 minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
