<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-LIMERICK-ART-B     03-01 1874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-LIMERICK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 GUNSLINGER OF THE NEW WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDOVER, Mass. _ The Oakland Museum was planning an exhibition
on the California gold rush. Among experts whose advice the museum
sought was Patricia Nelson Limerick. Why not have a ``smell''
booth, the University of Colorado historian suggested, a display
where museumgoers could experience the odors of a 19th-century
mining camp: ``sewage, rotting food, and a collection of people not
overly committed to bathing''?
</P>
<P>
   The museum demurred, but the suggestion was classic Patty
Limerick: iconoclastic, unblinking, very down to earth. It was also
good for a laugh. These qualities have helped make Limerick, 48,
the best-known living historian of the American West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody asks `Patty who?,' '' says Richard White, Byrne
Professor of History at Stanford University and a longtime friend
of Limerick's. ``They always know who you're talking about.'' It's
a knowledge that extends beyond academe. Throughout much of the
Mountain time zone, Limerick is a familiar figure as no academic is
two hours to the east. From newspaper op-ed pages to legislative
conferences, she maintains a very high profile.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Limerick so influential _ and controversial _ is her
central place in the New Western History, the revisionist movement
that came to dominate the field in the '90s. ``I really don't know
`New Western History' is a term we would have chosen,'' Limerick
says, ``but it exists.'' To critics such as Gerald D. Nash,
Distinguished Professor of History emeritus at the University of
New Mexico, the movement ``politicizes'' and ``oversimplifies''
with a ``politically correct'' version of the Western past. To
adherents, it offers an understanding of the region that is far
richer and more nuanced, as well as darker and more overtly
ideological, than did the largely triumphalist interpretation of
Western history that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   The movement received its calls to arms in 1987 with the
publication of Limerick's ``The Legacy of Conquest: The Unbroken
Past of the American West.'' ``It aroused more controversy _ or got
more attention _ than any book I can think of in Western history,
unless you go back to Frederick Jackson Turner'' in the 1890s, says
Nash. The New Western History has produced more impressive works of
scholarship _ William Cronon's ``Nature's Metropolis,'' for
example, or Donald Worster's ``Rivers of Empire'' _ but none has
had the impact Limerick's did.
</P>
<P>
   Partly that was happenstance: She was writing at the right time
about the right place, with the old Western history starting to
crumble and its successor about to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Partly it was personality: ``The worst thing you can ever do is
to try to follow her on a podium,'' says White, who along with
Limerick, Cronon, and Worster formed what came to be known as the
movement's ``Gang of Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a cross between Diane Keaton's Annie Hall and Jane
Darwell's Ma Joad in John Ford's version of ``The Grapes of
Wrath,'' and you have some idea of what Limerick's presence is
like. Setting off her sad eyes and grave face are the merriest of
laughs and a gently madcap manner. Indeed, when she was an
assistant professor at Harvard in the early '80s, she had herself
appointed the university's first, and as yet only, official fool.
At Colorado, she holds no such post, but comedy has contributed no
small part to her intellectual impact. She doesn't so much tell
jokes as offer an endless stream of antic throwaways. When she
compares her situation as a present-minded historian to that of ``a
medical practitioner getting stuck in a coroner's office: The
coroner's work is very interesting, but it's sort of after the
fact,'' she delivers that ``sort of'' with an aplomb worthy of Bob
&AMP; Ray.
</P>
<P>
   At once self-effacing and forthright, Limerick is that rarest of
creatures: a soft-spoken fast talker. A murmury cataract of words
and ideas issues from her. She digresses. She rambles. She
digresses within a ramble, as when she likens herself to ``a bull
out of a chute _ well, a heifer out of a chute _ of course, heifers
don't come out of chutes, do they? _ so let's say a highly
energized animal coming out of a chute.''
</P>
<P>
   Limerick's surname befits her style. She owes it to her husband,
Jeff, an architect. ``It's a shame to think that that name could be
wasted on people who don't make the most of it. But even the
options that would be closest to it _ Patricia Nelson Doggerel? _
are nowhere near as sprightly and satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Limerick's first book since ``Legacy'' has just been published,
``Something in the Soil: Field-Testing the New Western History.''
The subtitle is somewhat disingenous: The results are long since
in, as Limerick's own career attests. In the past decade, she has
served as president of the American Studies Association, won a
MacArthur Foundation ``genius'' grant, and is currently on the
board of the Organization of American Historians. Most notable of
all, she's current president of the Western History Association _ a
state of affairs that only a few years ago might have been likened
to Crazy Horse taking command of the Seventh Cavalry. ``We're now
what the people we attacked were in the 1980s,'' laughs White,
himself a past WHA president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad in some ways. I was such a good young
rebel,'' Limerick laments. ``My editor said a few weeks ago, `We'll
probably do a reissue of ``Legacy'' with a new foreword. You can
describe how the field's changed and you've moderated some of your
positions.' I said, `What! Moderated my positions? I haven't
moderated my positions.. . . All that's happened is I've gotten
sneakier!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The sneakiness is a function of Limerick's having become such a
public figure in the West. She long ago outgrew preaching just to
the converted. Limerick may be the only historian, for example,
ever to have addressed the International High-Level Radioactive
Waste-Management Conference (``I got some very funny looks when I
stepped up on that dais, let me tell you, but afterwards at least
20 engineers asked for my business card and a copy of the
speech'').
</P>
<P>
   Her critics write off Limerick's public speaking as self-
promotion. ``I don't know any other historian who holds press
conferences,'' says Nash. Limerick sees it quite otherwise: as, for
lack of a better term, good citizenship. Her goal is nothing less
than ``the reinvigoration of the academic world through engagement
with public audiences.'' She considers the idea of the university
as ivory tower _ detached, aloof, oblivious _ to be inimical to its
educational function and lethal to its long-term survival.
</P>
<P>
   Limerick's critics also indict her for confusing history with
current events. If there's one complaint about her work that
friends and foes agree on, it's that she's much more a synthesizer
than researcher and far more at home writing polemical essays than
roaming archives. Limerick concedes the point, but doesn't
necessarily see what the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   ``An armchair quarterback is what a historian is,'' she says.
``Now some historians are in denial about their involvement in the
present: `I am writing about the past purely on its own terms and
transcend my presence in this moment.' I guess that's nice work if
you can get it, but it's not the most productive kind of work.''
</P>
<P>
   What brings Limerick to Andover is an example of the unexpected
approach she can bring to the study of the West. She's here to give
a talk at Phillips Academy about a guide she is helping to prepare
on, of all things, cultural literacy and etiquette for the West.
That would seem to have about as much to do with the region as does
Phillips Academy (which if it were any less Western would quite
literally be in the Atlantic Ocean). What does Annie Oakley have to
do with Amy Vanderbilt _ and at an august New England prep school,
no less?
</P>
<P>
   Well, raised pinkies and finger bowls is the least of etiquette.
What it really concerns is the maintaining of a common set of
assumptions about how people should behave in society. And it's
precisely a society that's diverse and fractured that most needs
one. The idea of Western etiquette helps reminds us of just how
varied the West is: native Americans, Hispanics, Asians, Anglos,
Mormons (a category that can comprise all the preceding), the list
goes on. A guide to cultural literacy and etiquette for the region
is, in fact, nothing so much as a sly and user-friendly venture
into thick-description sociology.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to Andover also underscores one of the fundamental tenets
of Limerick's writing. As White puts it, ``She's hammered on a
theme, which because she's been so successful people don't realize
how original it was: You simply can't write about the history of
the United States as if it happened mostly in the Northeast and,
during the Civil War, for a little while in the South. This is a
large and diverse country, and what happens in the West makes a
great deal of difference in how it turns out. She's never been
somebody who's tried to segregate Western history from larger
American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Herself a product of the West, Limerick grew up in the small
Mojave Desert town of Banning. ``It was very interesting,'' she
says, ``though I did not know that at the time.'' She recalls a
youth mostly spent playing Ping-Pong, reading too much, and looking
forward to leaving.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from the University of California at Santa Cruz
(the most countercultural campus in the UC system), then went to
Yale with the intention of studying aging in America. Limerick had
never been east of Salt Lake City, and things did not get off to an
auspicious start. ``I was in tears for three months,'' she says
with a laugh, but it wasn't so funny at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In her second year, Limerick took a course on the American West
with the Yale historian Howard Lamar. ``He was so kind and so nice
and so pleasant and so encouraging and so human,'' she says, ``I
think I would have followed him anywhere.'' Her intellectual course
was set. After completing her doctorate, she spent four years at
Harvard, then went to Colorado in 1984. Neither Limerick nor the
region has been quite the same since.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came to Boulder, even though I was grumpy and
homesick and missed Cambridge (Mass.), I still was aware that I had
received one great boon in life. If I left a very irritating
department meeting and started walking home, when I did that in
Cambridge all I did was walk into crowds in Harvard Square and get
more irritated as I crammed onto the Arlington bus and got
crankier. In Boulder, especially if the faculty meeting let out at
sunset, you start walking home and you're stalking along, and you
look at the Flatirons, and that golden glow they get, and within a
block or two you're thinking, `I don't know if that meeting was so
important.' It's a wonderful thing . . . to be in a place where the
wonder of the Creation is called to your attention as often as it
is there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
