 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of THURSDAY, March
2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS &LR;  (``a' code)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-DENTAL-SCHOOL (Undated) _ Starting this fall, students at
seven dental schools will be spared the strain of toting heavy
textbooks to and from the library. They won't even need to go to
the bookstore to buy a single textbook, workbook or laboratory
manual. Instead, each incoming student will be asked to purchase a
DVD containing the entire curriculum _ textbooks, manuals and
lecture slides _ for all four years of dental school. By Lisa
Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-PAYMENT (Undated) _ Cyberspace is littered with the
flotsam of online-payment schemes that have failed. Companies like
DigiCash, First Virtual Holdings and CyberCash have either gone
bankrupt or undergone extensive makeovers. Now, just when the
language has begun to absorb the letter ``e'' as a prefix, comes
the latest twist on electronic money and the language of the
digital age: mobile commerce, or m-commerce, which promises to turn
your cell phone or handheld organizer into an electronic wallet. By
Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly computer column: A
look at electronic photo frames, small screens that display digital
pictures. For their pricetag (several hundred dollars and up) you
could buy an awful lot of real frames. By Peter H. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Techno news and notes.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ON-THE-WEB (Undated) _ Selected sites and events on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The column: The problem with
Marthastewart.com has nothing to do with the selection. Covering
all facets of housekeeping from kitchen storage to soap making, the
site sells useful, high-quality tools to help you in many
endeavors, from dispensing aluminum foil to treating your skin to
the exfoliating wonders of crushed apricot seeds. No, the problem
is this: many of the nonexclusive products at MarthaStewart.com are
overpriced. By Michelle Slatalla.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17, 10-11.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-POP-STAR (Undated) _ A new appalling virtual pop star. By
Ian Austen.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-SWAP-SITES (Undated) _ Much of what is on the Web these days
has a price tag attached. But with a string of new sites devoted to
swapping unwanted items, it is now possible that what you want can
be bought with that old sewing machine in the garage or your
lightly dog-eared Dean Koontz novels. By Catherine Greenmabn.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-3D-ROTATION (Undated) _ 3-D rotation of streaming video. By
Michel Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-VIDEO-GAMES (Undated) _ Are video games, now at the
quarter-century mark, at a crossroads between developing into a
widely appreciated art and remaining an amusement for a select
group? Henry Jenkins, director of the comparative media studies
program at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, would say
they are. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-OPERA (Undated) _ Websites on Opera. By Peter Dizikes.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ROCK-HOUNDS (Undated) _ Gemologists (rock hounds). By
Michael Pollak.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-PHOTO-SHARING (Undated) _ Photo sharing sites are all over
the Web these days. A look at how they function. By Roy Furchgott.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-NANOTUBE (Undated) _ The nanotube is the Hercules of the
submicron materials world, for it is nearly a hundred times as
strong as steel. Now, like a '90s update of the manly man, the
molecules are turning out to be sensitive as well. By Anee
Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Techno questions answered: Upgrading a
computer's central processing unit. By J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-VILLAGE-HOUSE (New York) _ Like many people who meander
regularly through the storybook streets of the West Village, Tom
Fontana had always wondered about the strange house on 13th Street
near Eighth Avenue. Set at the end of a row of brownstones, with
its elegant Moorish window arches and stepped gable, the
three-story brick house looked like a reproduction of a
17th-century Dutch guild hall. But the formal front doors and a
chunk of the ground floor had been hacked away. By the time that
Fontana _ the television writer and mastermind of ``Homicide'' and
``Oz'' _ first stumbled upon house, in the 1980s, it looked as
though it had been through a bummer of a trip. By Nancy Hass.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT6,7,8.
</P>
<P>
   COLLECTING (Undated) _ It was a night like any other. Until I
knocked over the two and a half foot tall Finnish glass candle
pedestal, designed by Oiva Toikka in 1964. It stood in my living
room behind the Florence Knoll sofa. I paid $1,600 for it two years
ago at the Triple Pier Expo, a collectibles show in New York. The
purchase broke the ceiling on my expenditure for glass, ever. It
smashed into loose change in seconds. But that was only the
beginning of the crisis. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   LEWITT-MURAL (Undated) _ Last fall, Carole and Dick Cline were
looking for something to hang over the fireplace in the sitting
room of their new home, which overlooks a golf course near Chicago.
The couple's art consultant, Deborah Lovely, brought by a few
paintings but none that worked with the couple's antique furniture
and multicolored rug, Cline said. Then Ms. Lovely suggested a Sol
LeWitt mural _ a ``wall drawing'' in the artist's parlance. By
Christmas, the couple had something to match the rug: a geometric
drawing in diluted inks applied with sponges, covering two walls of
their sitting room _ about 250 square feet. They just didn't have a
chance to meet LeWitt. By Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-DOORS (Undated) _ Leave it to Italians to solve a design
problem homeowners didn't know they had: clunky doors. Try
achieving a sleek and modern interior while dealing with throwback
terms like doorjambs and thresholds, lintels and hinges, much less
carved paneled doors. It's enough to make a minimalist swoon. By
Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   FLOWER-SHOW (Undated) _ The snowdrops are blooming and the
species tulips are popping up. Some mornings, the air is balmy and
the sun has that golden light that says, ``Spring!'' And you put on
a lighter coat and freeze to death by the afternoon, when the
winter wind blows up again. That's the signal to get on the train
and head for your favorite flower show _ to wallow in woodland
gardens impossibly blooming with dogwoods and shadbush; to bury
your nose in acres of orchids, to drool over English gardens
stuffed with blue delphiniums you could never grow. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
