<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPEFRUITGROWERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDUCED BY THE CITRUS FRAGRANCE, A COUPLE TAKES A GAMBLE ON
GRAPEFRUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those who believe the joy in farming has disappeared, we'd
like to introduce Clare and Bill Braden.
</P>
<P>
   They call themselves fruit peddlers. We'd say they're symbols of
Texas spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a late-life entry into the business, despite a
devastating freeze, despite farming as corporate culture, this
couple has made a success of the orchard business in one short
decade.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't come by their 44-acre citrus grove in the usual
inheritance manner. Instead, they sailed around the world before
they found their senior calling.
</P>
<P>
   An engineer by training, Bill designed and built projects as
diverse as marinas and meat plants. Finding the 1970s a frustrating
business climate, the couple sold their business north of Amarillo
and took off on a seven-year sea voyage that registered 44,000
nautical miles. They sailed to California and over to Hawaii, and
then spent three years in the West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really thought we'd retire in St. Croix,'' says Clare,
``but if you need a doctor there, you're out of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   While sailing the oceans blue, the couple tied up at Port Isabel
for several weeks. They fell in love with the Rio Grande Valley and
the possibility of a retirement surrounded by fragrant citrus
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a sharp decline in farming in the Valley (before 1962
there were 176,000 acres in citrus cultivation, today there are
35,000) the Bradens figured they could build the house of their
dreams and hire a grovekeeper to ``do the citrus thing.'' In 1987,
they bought their property.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Rio Grande Valley, as in most agricultural areas,
time is marked by the last weather disaster. In the Valley,
conversations are constantly peppered with the phrases ``the 1983
freeze'' and ``the 1989 freeze.'' In 1989, the Christmas freeze was
so devastating that acreage in citrus production plummeted to zero.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Braden says the freeze was the best thing that happened
to his little grove, the smallest commercial property in the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We designed our new farm by the book. We had the planting
areas laser-leveled; we installed a new irrigation system; we
planted the newest varieties of grapefruit and orange; we enclosed
our 6,000 trees with a chain-link fence.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, the couple had also designed and built a processing
plant for their fruit. But that wasn't quite enough.
</P>
<P>
   Bill bought and installed a tram for the property, to entertain
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had ordered the thing to run back and forth from Texas
to Mexico and then found out there were all sorts of international
regulations. He told the guy to sell it to the first sucker who
came in,'' Braden says.
</P>
<P>
   So now the tram and Clare's ``shed,'' actually a gift shop at
the orchard, make up a ``citrus Knott's Berry Farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the gift shop and the fruit production, the couple have
made the orchard self-sufficient. They also have an interest in son
Jim's Las Colinas Pharmacy _ ``it's nice to get a check every
month.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998-99, the couple shipped more than 5,000 cartons of citrus
and sold an additional 800 tons in their gift shop. And you just
know that when there is another freeze, the Bradens will weather it
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Getting there:
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Pride Orchard is at 14748 Hoss Lane, Harlingen. The
orchard sells its fruit through its Web site, www.riopride.com, and
by phone at (800) 864-7728. Grapefruit season begins in late
October and runs for 25 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GRAPEFRUIT GUACAMOLE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 large ripe avocado
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove glaric, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grapefruit sections cut into bite-size pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grapefruit juice
</P>
<P>
   Peel and mash the avocado, leaving it somewhat chunky.
</P>
<P>
   Add onion, garlic, mayonnaise and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Gently stir in pieces of grapefruit and juice. Chill until
serving time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clare Braden
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
