A3408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      03-01 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRONX DA, DIALLO JURORS TRADE ACCUSATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MELISSA GRACE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Two jurors on the panel that acquitted four New
York City police officers of murder have criticized Bronx District
Attorney Robert Johnson for saying they ignored key evidence in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am livid about what he said,'' juror Charise Smith said
Tuesday. ``He threw it back on us. ... It was sickening, to throw
it back in our laps.''
</P>
<P>
   Another juror, Timothy A. DeTraglia, said: ``Where was the DA?
Why wasn't he there?'' Johnson did not go to the Albany County
Courthouse, where the trial was held, until four weeks into the
case, when the jury started deliberating.
</P>
<P>
   The four white officers, Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward
McMellon and Richard Murphy, were cleared of murder, manslaughter,
criminally negligent homicide and reckless endangerment charges for
the shooting death of Amadou Diallo. The 22-year-old immigrant from
Guinea was gunned down in the vestibule of his Bronx home on Feb.
4, 1999. The officers fired 41 shots, striking him 19 times.
</P>
<P>
   Under criticism for the way the case was handled, Johnson on
Monday said the evidence was ``loud and clear that Amadou Diallo
was prejudged.''
</P>
<P>
   DeTraglia, who is white, disputed that. ``This was not a black
and white issue that I could see from them,'' he said. ``He was so
concerned about racial profiling, why wasn't he there? ... This is
not a slam on him, but if he wants to make it a racial issue, he's
got to prove it, and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson criticized the legal system for moving the trial from
the Bronx to Albany. The Appellate Division of state Supreme Court
ruled that pretrial publicity would make it difficult to conduct a
fair trial in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson told a news conference that he disagreed with some
jurors who said they had no choice but to acquit based on the
evidence presented to them. ``I don't think anybody can say that
they couldn't come to those conclusions if they wanted to,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson called the news conference to answer charges that his
office mishandled the case. The jury announced its decisions on
Friday after 21 hours of deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Johnson's remarks were irresponsible. ``He's putting
fuel on a fire that's already burning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, Lavette Freeman, said in a television interview that
the prosecution had given her no basis to return a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me that hurts,'' said Freeman, who is black. But, ``I have
to take it back to the district attorney's office. They didn't give
me anything. Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another juror, Helen Harder, said the panel was ``unhappy'' with
the result of the case, but that the jury as a whole felt the
evidence against the officers was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Bronx prosecutor declined to comment on the
juror's statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough. We are not commenting,'' said spokesman
Steven Reed, adding, ``We don't beat up on jurors.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also sharply criticized the prosecution's case, saying she
could not understand the decision not to question a key defense
witness, who testified that the officers acted properly when they
approached Diallo. She said that left the impression that the
officers acted properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only testimony we had on the approach,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like several other jurors, Smith and DeTraglia said they had
received harassing telephone calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
