<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ROCK-HOUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB'S INTERNET ROCK SHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., Ark., Mo.)   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the different ways rock and mineral fans can amuse
themselves _ gem cutting; jewelry making; prospecting; fossil,
mineral and crystal collecting; and micromounting (preparing
dime-size crystal specimens that would cost a fortune or be
impossible to obtain in large sizes but that look gorgeous under a
microscope) _ one would expect a bewildering maze of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of sites, but a huge number of them are linked
to one pre-eminent address: Bob's Rock Shop (www.rockhounds.com).
</P>
<P>
   This is the Amazon effect: the Web site that gets there first
often rules, sometimes even by accident. There is no rock shop.
Never was. There is a Bob: Robert D. Keller, 47 a computer
programmer and electrical engineer in Tucson who describes himself
as a ``common-as-quartz rockhound.'' He is not a mineral or gem
dealer and never took a college course in geology. He will,
however, show you some pictures of his crystals if you're
interested. Rockhounds understand that impulse.
</P>
<P>
   He distinctly recalls his first find. Growing up on a farm
outside Kansas City, Mo., he used to play along Lime Creek and
found a crinoid stem, a limestone fossil of an ancient marine
animal. It looked like a pile of stacked coins, and he imagined
that he had Indian wampum.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1995, he decided to advertise his computer-related
services _ putting people and their pictures on the Internet. ``My
first Web site was not so much about rocks as how to make Web sites
and image acquisition,'' Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   He built a site of his own to serve as an example, but he had to
name it and illustrate the home page. So he took a picture of one
of his specimens, a nice quartz crystal from Mount Ida, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Bob's Rock Shop, he said, was a joke name, ``kind of intended to
be a parody of the very first commercial sites that were beginning
to appear on the Web.'' The pictures were just window dressing.
</P>
<P>
   He sat back and waited. Nobody flooded his In box with requests
for help on building Web sites. ``What people were sending me
e-mails about were pictures of rocks,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The niche he began filling was extraordinary: an estimated
100,000 members of 1,000 rock and mineral clubs (a friend, Albert
Zabinski, helps list them); dealers, many of whom work out of their
homes and find the Internet a blessing; teachers (Keller said his
proudest moments are when he gets letters about taking classrooms
to his site); and buyers (his most popular page is the
classifieds).
</P>
<P>
   Information runs from basic (how to make a kind of unfaceted
polished gem known as a cabochon, by Keller) to advanced (a
nine-part online course on crystallography). An arrangement with
Rock and Gem magazine, the most popular American publication on the
hobby, provides Bob's Rock Shop with online articles and features
in return for its serving as the magazine's host.
</P>
<P>
   A RockNet line lets obsessed hobbyists ask and answer questions.
Keller said 40,000 people browse the site each month.
</P>
<P>
   Bob's ``You know you're a rockhound when ...'' page is magnetic
for fellow sufferers. Contributors' finishing lines include:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your pet turtle hisses and spits every time you walk near his
aquarium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can distinguish agate from quartz by the sound they make
in the clothes dryer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't even consider dating a woman unless the directions
to her house contain the phrase, `then you turn onto the gravel
road.'''
</P>
<P>
   Keller moved to Tucson 15 years ago. Soon afterward, a friend
asked, ``Bob, you ever been to the Tucson Gem and Mineral Show?''
He had not. He hadn't heard much about it. It was like moving to
Kansas City and being asked, ``Ever tried steak?''
</P>
<P>
   Keller went and his jaw dropped. It is simply the World Series
of mineral shows.
</P>
<P>
   From 40,000 to 50,000 people attended this year, Keller said.
During show week, he doesn't just cover it, he transfers his home
page to his Tucson show site, as if assuming that is why anyone
would be visiting Bob's.
</P>
<P>
   Keller now sells enough advertising to have quit his day job,
but Bob's is not a money machine, he said, just enough to keep
``food in my mouth, a roof over my head and an ISDN connection.''
That's all right, he quickly added; the site is fulfilling a goal
of bringing people together. ``I would not trade the job that I
have here with Bob's Rock Shop for any job I've had,'' he said. ``I
truly enjoy this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1559EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
