<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYS TO INSTALL SINGLE-STRIP OR COMPOSITE BASEBOARD MOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseboard molding is the wood trim that runs around the
perimeter of the wall at floor level. It serves as a decorative
accent; it also conceals the expansion joint between the edge of a
wood floor and the wall and covers gaps and flaws created as the
house settles and heaves.
</P>
<P>
   At its simplest, baseboard molding is just a single strip of
wood with a simple contour, but it can also be made up of several
moldings with different profiles, called composite molding.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you choose to install single-strip molding or composite,
the same basic techniques _ mitering, coping and scarfing _ are
needed.
</P>
<P>
   First, you must buy the molding. To calculate the amount of
molding you need, measure the perimeter of the room. When
purchasing molding, try to buy long lengths to avoid having to
splice pieces together and, if possible, hand-pick the boards so
you can match grain patterns and color.
</P>
<P>
   Start the installation by locating all the wall studs with a
stud finder. Mark their location with light pencil lines slightly
above the molding height. Next, cut the pieces to approximate
length and place them against the walls around the room. If you
have two shorter pieces that must be spliced, plan for the joint to
fall over a wall stud.
</P>
<P>
   Choose the longest wall and cut the molding so it fits the
length exactly, from corner to corner. Both ends of the piece
should be cut square. Use 8d finishing nails to attach the molding
directly to the wall studs. If you are installing hardwood molding,
first drill pilot holes (the diameter of the holes should be
slightly smaller than the nails) to avoid splitting the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the molding for the adjacent wall. It should be long enough
to run from wall to wall and not from the wall to the face of the
newly installed piece. This extra length will give you enough stock
to cut the coped joint.
</P>
<P>
   You will now cope the end so it fits snugly against the face of
the installed piece. To do this first cut an open miter (a
45-degree bevel with the back of the molding longer than the face)
at the end. This bevel will highlight the profile of the molding.
Clamp the molding on a flat surface and use a coping saw, held
vertically, to cut along the profile and remove the mitered
section.
</P>
<P>
   The newly coped end will be shaped so it mates perfectly with
the face of the molding attached to the wall. Use sandpaper or a
file to remove excess wood and adjust the shape of the coped end to
ensure a tighter fit.
</P>
<P>
   When the joint fits snugly without any noticeable gaps, nail the
molding to the wall studs. Move to the opposite wall and use the
same technique to install the molding along it.
</P>
<P>
   In a simple room with four straight walls, the four corners will
be inside ones and you will be able to install all of the molding
using the coping technique described. Some rooms, however, may have
walls that project outward to wrap around a chimney or form a
divider. Here you will have outside corners to contend with.
Outside corner molding must be joined with a miter.
</P>
<P>
   First, determine the length of molding by placing it along the
wall and against the corner. Use a pencil to trace the inside
dimension (the length of the wall) directly on the back of the
molding. Clamp the molding in a miter box, making sure that the
back of the molding is flat against the wall of the miter box, and
use a back saw to make the cut. Before cutting, make sure that the
saw is angled correctly for an outside, or closed, miter. With an
outside miter the face of the molding will be longer than the back.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pieces, then test fit them to make sure the joint is
square with no noticeable gaps. If the pieces are too long, you can
file the mitered surface down a little. If the pieces are too
short, you will have to try again with fresh molding. When the
pieces fit together precisely, apply glue to both surfaces and nail
the molding to the studs.
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal situation, you will have long lengths of molding to
span the wall. Sometimes, however, you may have to joint two pieces
together. You could, of course, butt the two pieces together, but
over time the molding may contract, allowing the joint to open to a
noticeable gap. It is better to join them with a technique called
scarfing.
</P>
<P>
   To scarf a joint, cut both pieces a little longer than
necessary, then cut the ends at opposite angles so they overlap.
Nail the molding in place. If the wood does contract, the outside
piece will still cover the joint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1559EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
