r d BC-GRAPEFRUITPIE-TEX     03-01 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPEFRUITPIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRET OF GRAPEFRUIT PIE RIPE FOR SPECULATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rio Grande Valley has its share of Texas staples _ Tex-Mex,
southern-fried blue plates and barbecue. But the Valley is also
home to grapefruit pie, a dessert that showcases the ruby red fruit
of the surrounding citrus groves.
</P>
<P>
   The pie, in its homey gelatin-based guise, has vague roots. But
it was at Ferrell's Pit, a barbecue spot in Mission, that it gained
commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Ferrell introduced the pie to the restaurant menu in
the late 1960s. She got the recipe from a friend and was sworn to
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, her sister-in-law Louise Waymire owns the restaurant _
and keeps the secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not Jell-O,'' she says by phone. And it's not whipped
cream on top? ``It's your story, write what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``no-I-won't-tell-you-my-age-but-I'm-over-60'' Waymire says
the restaurant sells 50 to 150 of the pies daily, many sold whole,
to-go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell a lot of them for Valentine's Day and birthdays and
holidays. We've sold them to people who've taken them to San
Francisco and Mexico City.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrell's bakes the pie crusts in advance and assembles the pies
as they're ordered _ probably by combining peeled grapefruit pieces
with a glaze and then topping it with a stabilized cream topping.
</P>
<P>
   Home cooks in the area each seem to have their own variation on
the grapefruit pie _ some with gelatin, some without.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is now an upscale version that is a
specialty of Valley caterer Diane Shea. She makes a custard from
scratch but says that boxed vanilla pudding made with heavy cream
would work equally well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BERRY BEST TEXAS CITRUS PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   2 Texas red grapefruit (sectioned and strained)
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce package frozen blackberries, thawed
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce package raspberry gelatin
</P>
<P>
   9-inch baked pastry pie shell
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream, optional
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely crush blackberries. In medium saucepan, combine
blackberries, sugar and cornstarch. Cook mixture over medium-high
heat, stirring constantly. Bring mixture to a boil; cook 1 more
minute. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in gelatin and blend well; chill 30 minutes. Fold
grapefruit sections into berry mixture and stir into gelatin
mixture. Pour into pie shell and chill until set. Top with whipped
cream if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 296 calories, 8 grams fat, 52
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 141 milligrams
sodium, 25 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ TexaSweet Citrus Marketing
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   RIO STAR GRAPEFRUIT PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   4 medium to large Texas red grapefruit
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cup strained grapefruit juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce package wild strawberry gelatin
</P>
<P>
   8- to 9-inch baked pastry pie shell, cooled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   Peel and section grapefruit. Place sections in strainer over a
bowl. Leave overnight in refrigerator. The next day, cook sugar and
next 3 ingredients until thick and clear. Add gelatin and mix until
dissolved. With a large spoon, spoon a small amount of the gelatin
mixture over the bottom of the baked pie crust, covering it about
1/4-inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve rest of the mixture briefly until ready to use _ there's
no need to refrigerate. Chill pie until gelatin congeals, place
drained grapefruit sections in a close circular fashion in the pie
shell. Pour in reserved gelatin mixture and chill pie until gelatin
sets. Topped with whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 383 calories, 14 grams fat, 61
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 21 milligrams cholesterol,
184 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ TexaSweet Citrus Marketing
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STAR RUBY GRAPEFRUIT AND ORANGE TART
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3 pies, each serving 8-12
</P>
<P>
   Cornmeal crust:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces (1 1/2 cups) unsalted soft butter
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces (1 1/8 cups) granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest from 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces (2 cups) bread flour
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces (1 1/2 cups) cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 7 ingredients. Add flour and cornmeal and blend.
Chill before using. Line three 11-inch tart pans with crust by
pressing it into shape evenly. Chill. Fill bottom of each shell
with parchment paper and pie weights (or beans) and bake at 375
degrees for 12 minutes. Remove paper and pie weights. Reduce heat
to 350 degrees and continue baking for about 10 more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Divide orange filling between shells. Bake an additional 30
minutes or until orange filling is set.
</P>
<P>
   Orange filling:
</P>
<P>
   18 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   9 ounces (1 1/4 cups) granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs and sugar together and add cream and liqueur. Pour
into baked crust and bake at 350 degrees about 30 minutes or until
set. Chill.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly:
</P>
<P>
   3 Star Ruby grapefruit and 3 Texas oranges or 6 grapefruit only
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup orange marmalade, rind removed, OR 3/4 cup currant jelly
</P>
<P>
   Melted dark chocolate, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Melted white chocolate, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Peel and section the fruit and allow to drain in a colander in
the refrigerator overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Place fruit, patted dry, in a circular pattern on top of orange
filling. Melt the marmalade or currant jelly. Using a pastry brush,
paint the fruit with the marmalade or jelly. Garnish with streaks
of white and dark chocolate. Serve chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 258 calories, 17 grams fat, 24
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, 165 milligrams cholesterol,
44 milligrams sodium, 58 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diane Shea, Shea Catering
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   How to section a grapefruit
</P>
<P>
   With a sharp knife, cut off both ends (the flat ends) of the
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Place fruit on flat end and cut away peel from top to bottom
along curvature of the fruit. Remove all white pulp.
</P>
<P>
   Place fruit on its side and cut down along section to center.
Turn knife to loosen section and lift out. Remove remaining
sections in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
