<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BRIDGETJONES-BOOK-TEX     03-01 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGETJONES-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTE TO SELF: READ NEW BRIDGET JONES BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSIE MIllIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday, Feb. 15
</P>
<P>
   12:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Editor arrives at my desk, breathless. ``Bridget Jones: The Edge
of Reason'' to arrive on bookstore shelves Feb. 28. We need story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write in her style,'' editor tells me. Agree, but wonder: If I
could write in the style of smashing British author Helen Fielding,
why would I be working at a newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   Fielding created fictional character Bridget Jones in a
serialized column in the London Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget, painfully single, struggles in frenetic fashion through
a world of unfaithful boyfriends, maddening jobs, spicy e-mail with
a romantic interest, hostile co-workers and wacky parents.
</P>
<P>
   In the runaway bestseller of 1998, ``Bridget Jones's Diary,''
she shares hopes, dreams, foibles and a chronicle of the number of
cigarettes she smoked (5,277), pounds she gained (74) and lost (72)
as she stumbles through the course of a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones: The Edge of Reason'' is the much-awaited madcap
sequel. The same characters and the same up-and-down ride through
giddiness and suffering run like rapids through this second look at
Bridget's diary. In fact, the second is oh-so-similar to the first,
although her relationship with that caddish former boss, Mark
Darcy, finally gets resolved after many anxious moments.
</P>
<P>
   Write in her style? Editor must realize my life isn't half as
interesting as Bridget's. I am so not Bridget. I wear sensible
shoes. Bridget never would.
</P>
<P>
   And I am far more private than Bridget. I will not account for
each cigarette (5-10 daily, v. good!), each calorie (2,000-10,000),
each romantic encounter (0).
</P>
<P>
   I am so private, the sole reason I moved to Texas is that the
Department of Public Safety does not require that weight be printed
on driver's licenses, unlike other insensitive states where I have
lived and lied. It was a long search, but finally I found Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   One preview copy of ``The Edge of Reason'' exists. It is on the
desk of the book reviewer who sits across from me. Book reviewer
will not surrender the copy. I reach across the partition and grab
it. Consider running down hall with book.
</P>
<P>
   Book reviewer is nice person. She just organized an all-girl
outing to see ``Tap Dogs.'' This tap dance at Bass Hall adds up to
the sum of my social life for coming week (tragic).
</P>
<P>
   No need to make scene. I give the preview copy back.
</P>
<P>
   I call New York directory assistance. Operator has never heard
of the publisher, Viking, nor does operator give any sign he could
find his own name and number. I look on the Internet and find
46,352 references to Viking, the scanning of which will take longer
than a trip to New York on a camel.
</P>
<P>
   I walk to Barnes &AMP; Noble in downtown Fort Worth, find Writer's
Market on the shelf, look up Viking and find the telephone number.
Worry I might leave fingerprints from the sausage kolache I just
bought at Stein's Deli. I wipe hands on my skirt (a hideous $5
dry-cleaning mistake). I buy February Vogue. In it, and this is
from God as well as a tip from my editor, is excerpt of ``The Edge
of Reason.'' There goes that completely mad Bridget again,
drenching her diary with references to popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Leave B.&AMP;N. feeling wan, like shorter, OK maybe wider, version
of model in Donna Karan advert in Vogue. Buy another kolache.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Viking publicity person has not returned calls.
</P>
<P>
   I try to remember why I laughed so hard and so frequently when I
read the first of Fielding's Bridget books. Bridget encounters
common problems, but in their comic extreme. Embarrassment caused
by mothers, for instance, becomes in Bridget's world embarrassment
caused by her married mother returning from a trip to Africa
wearing Bo Derek braids and dressed in a batik caftan like Winnie
Mandela, with a man in tow.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   4:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   I look up ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' on Amazon.com and discover,
to my delight, that Amazon has rated the book highly among readers
in the U.S. Senate as well as the House of Representatives. (How
funny! Those Congress people must have read Starr report just
looking for the ``good'' parts.)
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D.C., John McCain's ``Faith of My Fathers'' is
only slightly more popular than ``Bridget Jones's Diary,'' which is
ranked as 13th among people who are supposed to be working to make
America an even better place, but really are spending time looking
for their own names in co-workers' books, plus reading Bridget's
wonderfully ditzy fictional diary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Dumb Century'' is rated 20th.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Feb. 16
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   I check e-mail for spicy notes. Ha! Transdepartmental e-mail
from co-worker advises me that Girl Scout cookie order is in.
Nutrition is part of latest endless self-improvement plan, a la
Bridget. I read box: each Caramel deLite supplies 1 percent of my
daily iron. (V. good!)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   10:11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Joe from mailroom comes in with copy of ``The Edge of Reason''
sent by magical overnight mail service. Hurrah! as Bridget would
say.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Feb. 17
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m. I am still reading ``The Edge of Reason,'' plus working
on two stories _ OK, let's make that four. I am working on four
stories, but after entering Bridget's world I find my mind drifting
back to etymology of word ``shag.'' Think of calling long-lost
English friend who married computer guy in Seattle. Maybe she
knows. Then have to admit I work in job describing popular culture
and I didn't see ``The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' Feel humiliated, just
like Bridget, who always feels humiliated due to silly antics of
parents, boyfriend, boss and self.
</P>
<P>
   Look helplessly around office, wondering about origin of word
``shag.''
</P>
<P>
   Pop music critic is walking out the door playing air guitar.
Senior writer is trying to get all the other features writers to
snap their fingers, as if maybe if we practiced we could do a music
video. Can't see another writer because she's sitting behind a rose
bouquet so big it looks like a beautiful shrub. Not that I am
jealous. Note: forget how ``shag'' came into the language. Another
note: must learn to snap fingers in case music video opportunity
arises; must send self roses.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   11:06 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Gaaaahhhh! Another editor arrives at my desk. Urgent tone. He
stands above me and I feel like patient ready to be intubated by
Dr. Greene on ``ER.'' He wants story on why there is so much bird
poop downtown (glamorous story!). This is why I got into
journalism, I tell myself. I go for walk to see just how bad of a
problem we have here on Fort Worth sidewalks. It's pretty bad. Walk
with purpose and carry a notebook; pretend I am not really out
walking around looking for bird poop. Can't wait to get back to
``The Edge of Reason.'' What a great title.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1607EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
