<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3425 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-CHEERLEADERS-AIRLINE-     03-01 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEERLEADERS-AIRLINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIRIT IN THE SKY: SOUTHWEST AIRLINES WOOS CHEERLEADERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Dallas Convention Center opened the floodgates Saturday
to thousands of pleated polyester miniskirts and white anklets,
there was surely no more spirited a place on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Throngs of little- to medium-sized girls scooted through the
hallways, hair pulled tightly off their bright faces and glitter
schmeared across their eyelids. Music from the adjoining arena
thumped steadily, and, as the line for free chicken sandwiches
swelled, Gina Taylor waded into the crowd, offering a barf bag to
anyone willing to pause.
</P>
<P>
   The cheerleaders had arrived, and Southwest Airlines was right
there to greet them.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Dallas-based Southwest had a brainstorm. Anyone
who flies the airline knows its staff takes a comparatively
irreverent, fun attitude toward the whole business (I was once
personally serenaded on a trip from Detroit to Chicago by a hammy
steward). The company prides itself on its perky disposition.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the cheerleaders _ or rather, a savvy effort on
Southwest's part to recruit cheerleaders and their presumably
equally peppy friends and family to work for the airline. Southwest
sends representatives across the country to events like this one,
the National Cheerleading Association All-Star National
Championship, to, as they say, ``plant the seed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Taylor and Leigh Hassell stood at the Southwest
Airlines booth, passing out little white bags printed with the line
``Sick of Your Job?'' The bags included a ``Now Hiring'' brochure
explaining how to apply and which positions are available, a mini
``Boarding Pass'' with the job hot-line number, and a bag of
peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Hassell, both in-flight recruiting coordinators for
the airline, stuffed the bags with the help of Hassell's
13-year-old daughter, Danielle, and good-naturedly worked the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you go, Southwest Airlines, tell your friends and family
about us,'' Taylor calls over the din. ``Hi, do you have a bag?''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has worked for the company for five years and says this
effort is ``just another sourcing way to get the word out about
Southwest Airlines.'' These young people, she stresses, possess the
kind of qualities _ ``spirit, teamwork, confidence, attitude'' _
that make successful employees. (An NCA survey found that 82
percent of cheerleaders and dance-team members maintain a B average
or higher and 82 percent are accepted to college.)
</P>
<P>
   Southwest plans to hire 1,000 flight attendants this year and
hired an equal number last year. The company is confident that its
recruiting strategy works, despite the fact that most of the
potential applicants sidling up to the booth today have yet to get
their first zit.
</P>
<P>
   (You have to be at least 20 and able to lift 50 pounds ``from
floor to above shoulder height,'' among other things, to qualify as
a Southwest flight attendant.)
</P>
<P>
   A trio of older girls confess that, though the job of flight
attendant doesn't top their list of career choices, they might be
willing to give it a try. Sixteen-year-old Chelsea Hooten, a member
of Houston's Texas Cheer team, really wants to be a ``play
therapist,'' but her mom has suggested that she be a flight
attendant ``because I pick up languages really fast,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Fowler and Kristofer Gertsen, two college-age competitors
from New Jersey, each take a barf bag from the Southwest booth and
agree that the airline came to the right place to find ``outgoing,
friendly'' people. Fowler, who's taking flying lessons, says he
would ``definitely'' think about pursuing a career with Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the Southwest booth falls somewhere between
the neighboring, always crowded Pantene Pro-V table _ where girls
are lined up for a satiny bag of free shampoo and conditioner _ and
the lonely, unmanned Nair display _ a table strewn with sample hair
remover.
</P>
<P>
   To Southwest's right, Princeton doctoral student Mary Wright is
having a tough time luring kids and coaches to fill out a survey or
give an interview. She's writing her dissertation on the evolution
of cheerleading music and its reflection of the larger culture, but
by 11:30 a.m. she had run out of jelly beans.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Southwest gives away 2,000 bags of information on
Saturday. Most of the girls competing at the NCA championship
couldn't care less. But somewhere out there, a tired cheerleader is
unpacking her suitcase and curiously studying the ``Now Hiring''
pamphlet she half-consciously picked up over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   She might just be serving your next bag of in-flight peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
