<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SOCSEC-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      03-01 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE LIFTS LIMITS ON EXTRA INCOME FOR MOST SOCIAL SECURITY
RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted 422-0 Wednesday to allow most
Social Security recipients to work without sacrificing any of their
retirement benefit, repealing a Depression-era policy intended to
discourage older people from holding jobs so younger people would
have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous vote was a rare display of bipartisanship in the
House, and reflected a consensus that the earnings limits placed on
Social Security recipients had long since become counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to take up a similar measure soon, and
President Clinton has said he would sign the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, people aged 65 through 69 lose $1 of their
Social Security benefit for every $3 they earn above $17,000. A
67-year-old man who earned $20,000 last year, for example, would
have lost $1,000 of his Social Security retirement benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings limit, which does not apply to people 70 and above,
is already scheduled to rise to $30,000 in 2002, but the
legislation passed Wednesday by the House would eliminate the limit
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted under the terms of the House bill, the change would
apply retroactively to earnings since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 people aged 65 or above lost some or all of their
benefit last year because they earned more than the limit,
according to the Social Security Administration. But the real
significance of the shift might come only over the next few decades
as the population ages and the baby boom generation moves into
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsors said repealing the earnings limit would
benefit the entire economy by making a bigger pool of experienced
workers available, especially now, when the unemployment rate, at 4
percent, is so low that employers are having trouble filling all
the jobs they are creating.
</P>
<P>
   They said the change also reflected increases in life expectancy
and the fact that more and more people 65 and older continue to
work at least part time by choice or necessity. But they said the
main justification for the change was simple fairness, calling it
unconscionable for the government to deny workers benefits they had
earned over their careers simply because they chose to remain
employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in the world would we want to discourage any American _
whether they're 17 or 67 _ from working?'' said Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, chairman of the Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are living longer now, and older Americans can work,
they want to work and they shouldn't be punished by an outdated law
if they choose to work,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   But the provisions that the bill would repeal are more complex
than Wednesday's debate on the House floor would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   While Social Security recipients lose some of their benefits in
years in which they earn more than the limit, they get some or all
of the reduction back after age 70, when their benefits are
readjusted to reflect their decision to continue working.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the change would not apply to people who take early
retirement benefits from Social Security. People age 62 through 64
would continue to be subject to a strict earnings limit, losing $1
in benefit for every $2 in earnings above $10,080 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties agreed to leave the earnings limits in place for
early retirees _ effectively encouraging people not to take Social
Security before 65 _ because research has shown that people who
take a reduced Social Security benefit at age 62 are more likely to
end up in poverty than those who work to full retirement age. The
problem strikes particularly hard at widows of men who retire early
and rely on their late husbands' benefits to live.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
