<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO UPGRADE THE PROCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like to increase the speed of my computer and have
already added more RAM. What is involved if I wish to upgrade my
processor? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Upgrading the computer's central processing unit, or CPU (or
microprocessor, as it is often called), is another way to extend
the life of an older machine. While the hard drive, with all your
programs and personal files, may be the heart of your computer, the
CPU is the brain, sending out instructions for the rest of the
machine to follow. In an older CPU, the rate at which it can send
out these instructions is slower, which affects the speed of the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Your upgrade options will depend on the type of computer you
have, so consult your system's manual or manufacturer to see what
is possible. Upgrade kits for specific types of machines are
available in computer stores. Depending on the type of kit, you may
be able to plug in an upgrade ``daughtercard'' to your motherboard
or stack the upgrade processor on top of your existing one. Some
kits have you replace the entire processor with a new one.
</P>
<P>
   You will probably notice improved performance after you upgrade,
but don't set your standards too high, as there is only so much
even an upgrade can do for an older machine. New computers are
relatively inexpensive these days, and if the upgrade kit costs
more than a few hundred dollars, you may want to weigh all your
needs carefully before deciding which way to go. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
