<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3450 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-PAYMENT-AR     03-01 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-PAYMENT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL THAT BE CASH OR CELL PHONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cyberspace is littered with the flotsam of online-payment
schemes that have failed. Companies like DigiCash, First Virtual
Holdings and CyberCash have either gone bankrupt or undergone
makeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just when the language has begun to absorb the letter ``e''
as a prefix, comes the latest twist on electronic money and the
language of the digital age: mobile commerce, or m-commerce, which
promises to turn your cell phone or handheld organizer into an
electronic wallet.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of cell phones are hooked to the Web for
sending and receiving e-mail and for calling up weather reports,
stock quotes, movie listings, sports headlines and travel tips. The
Yankee Group, a technology research firm in Boston, predicts that
by the end of this year, 15 million phones in the United States
will be equipped to use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The next logical step, at least according to some visionaries,
is to turn cell phones into devices for handling any number of
purchases made on the fly: movie tickets, soft drinks or Happy
Meals. Some developers envision the eventual use of cell phones to
make major purchases and transfer cash from bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It will be years before m-commerce takes hold in a serious way.
But when it does, ``m-commerce will be bigger than e-commerce,''
declared Richard Siber, an analyst at Andersen Consulting in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machines are a favorite example among those peddling the
m-commerce concept. Rather than stand in front of a soda machine
fishing for a dollar bill that is neither too faded nor too
wrinkled, or one last nickel, you may someday simply dial the phone
number posted on the machine.
</P>
<P>
   The vending machine will be equipped either with the radio
portion of a cell phone so that it can receive the call, or with a
transceiver that works using Bluetooth, a wireless connection that
allows high-speed communication among devices within a short
distance of one another.
</P>
<P>
   The machine will then offer you a menu. You'll choose, say, a
Diet Pepsi for 75 cents and enter a PIN (or the machine will
recognize your telephone automatically), and out will tumble your
soft drink. For additional security, a few phone manufacturers are
experimenting with thumb-print recognition technology.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the advances in m-commerce are being made in Europe and
Asia, where Web-ready phones are increasingly commonplace. That is
because wireless companies in those parts of the world have
leapfrogged their U.S. counterparts by adopting a single technical
standard for digital cellular. The United States, by contrast, is
burdened with three different and incompatible standards. The
seamless consistency of the systems that are in place in Europe and
Asia makes innovation easier there.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Visa and the Finnish-Swedish bank
MeritaNordbanken, Nokia, the Finnish cell phone manufacturer, is
testing a system for making point-of-sale purchases with cell
phones. And at the CeBIT computer show in Hannover, Germany, this
past week, Nokia showed off a prototype of a mobile payment system
called PayPal.com. The system is also being demonstrated at the
Wireless 2000 show, put on by the Cellular Telecommunications
Industry Association, in New Orleans this week.
</P>
<P>
   PayPal.com, which is owned in part by Nokia, plans to merge with
X.com, an online financial services company. The PayPal.com system
has been in place for several months, and it is now migrating to
cell phones. It works like this: After opening an account on the
company's Web site, people can send money to one another via
e-mail. The PayPal.com method calls for just an e-mail address (or
eventually a phone number) to send, beam or dial in a payment. Once
the money is sent, the amount is charged to a credit card or bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   The recipient retrieves the money by filling out a form attached
to the payment, which in turn registers the recipient for the
service. PayPal.com then credits a credit card, deposits money to a
bank account or sends out a check.
</P>
<P>
   PayPal.com is especially popular for paying for merchandise on
eBay and other online auctions because it eliminates the need to
send checks through the mail. Since the service began last October,
some 350,000 users have signed up, and more than 10,000 new users
sign up each day.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of the cell phone into the process can change
things greatly, said David Sacks, vice president for strategy at
PayPal.com. He conjured a scene from the wireless future: ``Walk
down the street, a few blocks away from your favorite Starbucks,
pull out your Web-connected cell phone, you get a Starbucks menu,
click espresso, and it's sent. And you've not only ordered it, but
you've paid and you can go pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   PayPal.com does not displace credit cards or electronic bill
payment services. Rather, it extends the use of electronic fund
transfers to person-to-person payments and small cash payments.
That has made it particularly popular with eBay users who have
usually relied on checks.
</P>
<P>
   Tapio Hedman, vice president for communications at Nokia Mobile
Phones, said that m-commerce, when combined with information
delivery via the Web, makes the cell phone an especially powerful
tool. Not only can a phone be used to buy a bus ticket, but, he
said, ``if you're waiting for a bus in Finland in February, you
definitely want to know if it's 5 minutes or 25 minutes for the
next bus to come by.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacks, of PayPal.com, said, ``There are all sorts of things you
can do by wedding the payment to information about the payment.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the systems planned for m-commerce require that the cell
phones be linked to the Internet. Handset manufacturers like Nokia,
Motorola and Qualcomm, along with carriers like AT&AMP;T Wireless and
Sprint, are all complying with a standard called the Wireless
Application Protocol, or WAP, which optimizes the delivery of
Internet data to small-screen devices over digital cellular
networks.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wireless 2000 show, ``the buzz was all about wireless
Internet,'' said Mark Lowenstein, an analyst with the Yankee Group.
But in the United States markets, the number of cell phones that
are used for Web access remains small compared with the number in
Europe and Asia. ``We're culturally and technically embarrassingly
behind,'' said Mark S. Anderson, a computer industry analyst and
president of Technology Alliance Partners.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   TeleVend, a small start-up based in Israel, plans to sell its
own solution for the U.S. market, one that will work with any
mobile phone and will not require Internet access. The cell phone
user dials the phone number displayed on the vending machine, and
after a brief authentication process, out tumbles the candy bar.
The transaction can be charged to the customer's cell phone bill,
credit card or bank account.
</P>
<P>
   There's another twist as well: since the machine now has the
personal information associated with your phone, it can display a
brief advertisement customized to your tastes or dispense similarly
tailored discount coupons.
</P>
<P>
   TeleVend is planning a pilot program for the spring in a
commercial neighborhood in New York, in cooperation with a number
fast food and retail businesses, said Gedaliah Gurfein, TeleVend's
vice president for marketing. Later this year, TeleVend's
technology will include a speech recognition feature that will
allow consumers to make purchases based on a ``voice signature.''
</P>
<P>
   The high level of security provided by speech recognition will
pave the way for situations like the following one, Gurfein said:
``Imagine walking into Bloomingdale's and simply saying, `I'll buy
this, thank you,' to which a `voice' responds: `That will be $220.
Do you confirm?' You then say, `Yes, I confirm.' The machine says,
`Thank you, have a nice day,' and you walk out the door with your
purchase.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines is working with International Business Machines
and an e-commerce company called Modem Media to develop and test a
service that not only gives customers wireless access to flight and
gate information, but by next year will also allow travelers to
purchase tickets and change flight schedules using their handheld
organizers and mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that once the technical hurdles are overcome,
widespread acceptance of m-commerce will require a shift in how
consumers think about making purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is essentially modifying the behavior of
consumers,'' said Chris Shipley, publisher of DemoLetter, an
industry newsletter. ``Because if you're used to digging in your
pocket for loose change, picking up a phone and making a call to a
machine might be a little odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson agreed. ``You have to get people thinking about their
phones that way,'' he said. ``Even if they're using phones just
once for some kind of product purchase, then the door is open a
crack, and that's a huge opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit card companies don't want to be left out, of course.
Executives at Visa are experimenting with m-commerce in England,
where a pilot program in Leeds allows mobile phone users to
download money to their chip-based ``electronic purse.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 1,000 card holders are taking part in the trial,
which involves custom-designed Motorola StarTac mobile phones.
People insert a credit or debit card into a slot in the phone and
key in the amount to be transferred and a PIN. The e-cash is
deposited onto the card.
</P>
<P>
   Visa is also working with Nokia and MeritaNordbanken to put a
second chip into Nokia phones. ``We envisage the card holder using
it to make payments on the Internet,'' said Sandra Alzetta, senior
vice president for electronic commerce for Visa in Europe, ``but
also to make local payments, such as standing next to a parking
meter and sending details to the parking meter, or being able to
use it for payment inside a shop.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM, another m-commerce cheerleader, is developing a speech
recognition system that could be used for wireless purchases. ``Our
view is that instead of using keyboards or punching up numbers on
cell phone pads, people are going to be speaking to do any kind of
transaction,'' said Stephanie Hahn, a general manager at IBM.
``That can be speaking through your phone, or through a PDA device
or to your computer to do purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in the world of vending machines, those toiling
in the trenches of the automated merchandising industry are
slightly more skeptical of the notion of m-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that some day this kind of thing will happen,'' said
Kyriakos Spentzos, an engineer in Santa Rosa, Calif., who designs
control systems for vending systems. ``But for now, if I want to
buy a soda, I'm more likely to have 75 cents in my pocket than my
cell phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Spentzos said, it can cost as much as $40 per vending
machine to equip it with the electronics to perform such a
transaction. ``If you want to see these machines on every corner,
the price will have to drop considerably,'' he said. ``Unless the
cost comes down to around $5 extra per machine, no one will put it
into their machines.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedman, of Nokia, agreed that even in Helsinki, the capital of
Finland _ the country with the highest per capita cell phone use _
there are only a handful of experimental vending machines that can
handle a purchase from a mobile phone. Hedman said he had yet to
use his phone to buy a Coke. But, he added quickly, he had used his
phone to pay at the car wash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
