<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      03-01 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; What's Eating Ficus? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I was washing the leaves of my ficus tree when I discovered
that underneath every leaf, right at the base, there are small,
pinhead-size bumps, whitish and waxy, always in the same place. I
know ficus is susceptible to scale, so how do I deal with an
infestation this large?
</P>
<P>
   A. Anything on a plant that is so uniformly spread, so
consistent, is probably not an insect. Insects are freethinkers,
and are rarely much good at organizing (ants and bees excepted, of
course).
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the waxy spots on your Ficus benjamina are
glandular spots, characteristic of ficus. Different species have
different sites and numbers of spots. There is a theory that the
glandular spots exude a substance that attracts tiny fig wasps,
which are the plant's pollinators, but no one knows for certain.
One thing I am certain of is that they serve some purpose. Nature
almost never does anything just for fun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An Eon Here, an Eon There &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am interested in finding a source for tree seeds. Starting
a yew (which might grow for 1,000 years) or a sequoia (which might
grow for 3,000) seems an easy way to achieve immortality.
</P>
<P>
   A. With a tree's long view of life, it shouldn't be surprising
that their seeds are remarkably patient. Growing trees from seed
isn't like growing annuals or vegetables, where germination is
quick and everything happens during daylight time.
</P>
<P>
   In nature, seeds germinate only when they and the world are
ready for each other. Some seeds are not fully mature when they
leave the tree and need a warm or cool period to finish developing.
Others, including fringe tree and Carolina silverbell, need both
warm and cool periods, and in the right order.
</P>
<P>
   Some seeds have a hard coating that needs to wear away before
moisture can enter and germination can begin. Years of rain, being
blown over rocky terrain or a trip through an animal's digestive
system can do the trick. But for gardeners there are techniques of
scarification (sanding, nicking or filing nearly through the seed
coat) and stratification (controlled periods of moist warm or cool
temperatures).
</P>
<P>
   Tree seeds are more of a commitment than marigolds, so be sure
to get advice on the seeds' needs when buying. Of course, plant
only trees suited to your climate. There's not much immortality
having the tree wiped out by a New York winter.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for tree seeds include F.W. Schumacher Co., 36 Spring
Hill Rd., Sandwich, Mass. 02563, (508) 888-0659, free catalog; and
Sheffield's Seed Co., 273 Auburn Road, Locke, N.Y. 13092; (315)
497-1058; free seed list, with a lot of additional information at
www.sheffields.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Helping Holly &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Please tell me why the holly branches I cut are not growing
roots, even though they have been in water for three months. The
water has been changed regularly, and their leaves are still green.
What can I do to help them grow roots?
</P>
<P>
   A. Very little. Most shrubs are not like willows, where a casual
glance at a glass of water will prompt cuttings to grow roots.
Cuttings have to be taken at the right growth stage.
</P>
<P>
   For hollies, use 4- to 6-inch cuttings of semihard wood (after
that first flush of spring growth begins to harden, a few months
after it appears), with the lower leaves removed, so that just two
to five leaves remain. Remove a thin slice of bark along the lowest
inch or two of the stem. Dip the stem in rooting hormone powder,
covering the new wound, and stick the stem in a moistened medium,
half sphagnum peat, half perlite. Cover the pot with a plastic bag,
seal the bag to keep it humid and place in bright light but not
direct sun. Wait six weeks before gently tugging to see if there
are roots. If there aren't, wait longer.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(at)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
