<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BOSNIA-DAYTON-0302-CO     03-01 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-DAYTON-0302-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: Ohio EDs.
 &HT;    DAYTON MAYOR LAUDS SUCCESS OF SISTER CITY RELATIONSHIP WITH
SARAJEVO
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By ALEC SCHULTZ 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Holding his city up as a model, Dayton, Ohio Mayor
Michael Turner Wednesday said personal relationships have fueled
the success of their sister city relationship with Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, speaking at the National Press Club here, said the
people of Dayton worked to establish individual ties of friendship
to the people of Sarajevo, in war-torn Bosnia-Hercegovina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted them to call the people of Dayton their friends,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton was the site of negotiations between Serbs, Croats, and
Muslims to end the 3 1/2 year Balkan War. During the talks leading
up to the signing of the 1995 Dayton Accords, residents learned of
the toll of a bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Turner said, ``Our new friends in the Balkans have
given us a new perspective on our own city, and a greater
understanding of the importance of individual relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Those relationships have grown into a successful trans-oceanic
partnership, with the cities operating numerous individual exchange
programs. For example, more than 100 Dayton-area residents have
travelled to Sarajevo. While in Bosnia-Hercegovina, the Daytonians
stay in private homes. After their visit, the guests invite their
hosts on a trip to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``These exchanges have formed lasting friendships that have
changed the lives of Daytonians,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   To help prolong the friendship between the two cities, Turner
said other programs focus on young people. The University of Dayton
offers a scholarship program to Bosnian students that allows them
to interact with their American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what we have in common that can assist us in maintaining
the peace,'' the mayor said, adding that the exchanges have allowed
Dayton residents to discover the similarities between themselves
and the Bosnian people.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of there sister city relationship, Turner believes
that Daytonians have a distinct world view.
</P>
<P>
   While he believes that Dayton has proven that individual
relationships have an impact far beyond official government
intervention, financial aid, and military force, he adds that the
city's residents realize the importance of the United States'
attempts to mediate world conflicts _ even those that seem
insignificant. That's because sharing their homes with Bosnians has
brought the story of suffering straight to Daytonian's living
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
