<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3458 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     03-01 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRAME TO HOLD YOUR PIXELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem with old-fashioned picture frames is that they can
display only one photograph at a time. If you have a lot of
pictures, you need a lot of frames, and if you have a lot of
frames, you need a lot of space on your desk, bedside table,
mantel, walls and so on. That is rarely a problem for grandmothers,
who miraculously seem to have infinite space for photos of the kids
and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   But grandmothers of the near future are likely to display their
pictures in digital photo frames, which can show a nearly infinite
number of photographs, digital postcards and, in some cases, short
digital movies. The photos are shown on a flat-panel, liquid
crystal display mounted inside the frame, and the image quality is,
well, nearly photo quality. And the future starts now.
</P>
<P>
   Two of these new digital frames are already available, one from
Sony and another from a new company, Ceiva Logic. Several other
companies are planning to introduce frames in the next few months.
The first models range from expensive to absurdly expensive, and
they suffer from the usual first-run glitches and annoyances common
to groundbreaking products.
</P>
<P>
   But even with their faults, these new digital frames are so
compelling that they will probably be hot items when Mother's Day
arrives. Some 1.8 million digital cameras were sold in 1999, and
billions of digital photos are filling up hard disks and flying
around on the Internet. It is inevitable that demand will grow for
a convenient way to share and display all these photos, even among
people who get red-eyed and blurry just thinking about computers.
</P>
<P>
   These digital frames do not do anything that cannot be done, and
done better, on a desktop or laptop computer, but who wants a
computer hogging the bedside table?
</P>
<P>
   Sony introduced its PHD-A55 CyberFrame last year as a prototype
to show off its Memory Stick data storage device, which is used in
some of its digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The CyberFrame, priced at $899, has some impressive features,
including a small but bright 5.5-inch active matrix screen and the
ability to pivot automatically between portrait and landscape
formats and to display not only photos but also short video clips
with sound. It has been in such demand among gadget fiends that
Sony is scrambling to make more affordable models for the rest of
us.
</P>
<P>
   But the CyberFrame suffers from complexity, from its industrial
plexiglass design and from its total reliance on the Memory Stick
to get pictures and video clips into the device. If you cannot get
pictures onto a Memory Stick, the frame is just an expensive
paperweight.
</P>
<P>
   A more practical alternative is the Ceiva Internet Connected
Picture Frame, which costs $249 plus a monthly service fee of $2.99
or $7.99, depending on the plan. Although it lacks the superior
picture quality of Sony's active matrix screen, the Ceiva's clever
online connection, simplicity and lower price make it the more
compelling choice.
</P>
<P>
   Using Ceiva's technology, one can send up-to-the-minute pictures
of the kids to Grandma's bedside table anywhere in the country,
assuming that Grandma has a phone jack and a power outlet nearby.
The frame can store up to 10 pictures at a time, and it can display
them in sequence, like a slide show. As many as 250 photos can be
stored in a digital photo album on line, all of them ready to be
cycled through the frame. The owner of the frame can grant
permission for designated individuals to send photos to the frame
as well, but there are security safeguards to keep Grandma from
receiving unsolicited risque photos from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company, one does not need a computer, an
Internet account or any computer experience to enjoy digital photos
on the Ceiva frame. Technically that is true, but someone has to
set up an account, manage the photos and fiddle with various
settings on Ceiva's Web site to use the frame to its fullest. And
someone has to have a digital camera, or a scanner to digitize
traditional photos, and a computer to send the photos over the
modem and through the net to Grandmother's house, tra la.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance the Ceiva looks just like a black wooden picture
frame. In the center of the frame is a passive matrix screen big
enough to display a 5-by-7 photo. Viewed straight on, pictures on
the Ceiva screen are bright and colorful. From an angle, however,
pictures wash out or flip to negative colors, a common drawback of
passive screens.
</P>
<P>
   On the back of the frame are two ports, one for a standard
telephone wire and one for a power plug. Connected to the telephone
line, the Ceiva's built-in modem automatically makes a local call
(the $2.99 plan) or toll-free call (the $7.99 plan) to connect to
Ceiva's computers, where pictures are stored. The calls are usually
made each night after midnight, when the phone line is unlikely to
be in use, and typically last just a few minutes, long enough to
download a new batch of photos.
</P>
<P>
   Impatient viewers can press and hold a white button on the back
of the frame to force Ceiva's network to download new pictures
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The Ceiva frame is simple to use and will undoubtedly improve
over time. But it is facing tough competition from a couple of
upstarts.
</P>
<P>
   One is Digi-Frame, which will soon be selling two models,
including a small, battery-powered digital frame for travelers
($399). A larger Digi-Frame model ($599) has no direct Internet
connection, but it can retrieve pictures directly from a personal
computer or Mac via a standard cable. It can also take a memory
card directly from a digital camera. Prices have not yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive is the Storybox Connected Frame from Weave
Innovations. It is expected to go on sale in July for $299 plus a
monthly fee starting at around $5.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a sneak preview last month, the Storybox frame appears
to borrow the best features of the Sony and Ceiva models, including
an active matrix screen and a phone-line connection to the
Internet. It also adds an assortment of new tricks.
</P>
<P>
   The Storybox frame allows owners to share photos over the
Internet, but, like the Digi-Frame, it also has slots to accept the
standard memory cards used by most digital cameras, enabling people
to bypass the network. Through an alliance with Kodak, owners of
nondigital cameras can have their film developed and sent as
digital images to their personal storage space on the Storybox
network.
</P>
<P>
   Besides displaying photo-quality images, the Storybox frame can
also display news headlines, local weather and traffic reports,
stock quotes and other information (these services will cost extra
and may include advertising). Storybox owners will also be able to
order high-quality prints of favorite photos, plus a variety of
photo gifts, including T-shirts, coffee mugs and even old-fashioned
picture frames.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may find it hard to justify spending $300 on a
digital picture frame when a fully functional PC costs just a few
hundred dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   But digital frames of some sort are likely to be part of the
houses of the future, and these new digital frames are a window
into the future of Internet appliances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
