<SLUG> BC-CIR-POP-STAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIRTUAL POP STAR ON THE RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(lh) 
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, pop stars are so carefully packaged that critics
constantly harp about artificiality. But a new German crooner is
reveling in it.
</P>
<P>
   According to its creators, E-Cyas _ for Electronic Cybernetic
Artificial Superstar _ is the first fully virtual male character to
release a hit recording and video. The avatar's recording, which
has entered at least one German Top 100 chart, has the appropriate
if colloquially awkward title ``Are You Real?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the basic question, isn't it?'' said Walter Grassl, a
spokesman for I-D Media, the company that created E-Cyas. Before
his recording debut, E-Cyas had been the digital host of a German
chat room. The move from the Web to recording came through a
collaboration of I-D Media, Edel Records and Alex Christensen, a
techno-music producer. Grassl would not say if E-Cyas is merely
fronting for a human vocalist or if his voice is computer
generated. A sample can be downloaded at www.e-cyas.com.
</P>
<P>
   If I-D Media's plans come to fruition, E-Cyas will follow a
typical career track. The single will probably be distributed in
the rest of Europe and Japan (home to the first female virtual pop
star, Kyoko Date) later this year before reaching the United
States. A full album is in the works, and concerts featuring
projected images of E-Cyas are being planned (or threatened).
</P>
<P>
   E-Cyas faces a problem common to many celebrities: He receives
up to 100 e-mail messages daily, including some marriage proposals.
``It's strange,'' Grassl said. ``It's like a real pop star.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
