<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-COLLECTING-ART-NYT &LR;      03-01 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU WIN SOME,   YOU BREAK SOME WHEN YOU COLLECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Wis., Finland) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a night like any other.
</P>
<P>
   Until I knocked over the 2-and-a-half-foot-tall Finnish glass
candle pedestal, designed by Oiva Toikka in 1964. It stood in my
living room behind the Florence Knoll sofa. I paid $1,600 for it
two years ago at the Triple Pier Expo, a collectibles show in New
York. The purchase broke the ceiling on my expenditure for glass,
ever. It smashed into loose change in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   I was stunned. Then, I was weirdly sobered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddha's first message _ Line 1,'' Richard Shweder, a cultural
anthropologist at the University of Chicago whose field study is in
India, said to me two weeks later, when I started looking into the
incident, ``All suffering comes from attachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Has Shweder ever seen Kaj Franck's barware? I don't think so.
Buddha used his hands to drink. What did he serve his gimlets in?
</P>
<P>
   I have been collecting modern design for the last 10 years,
specifically Finnish glass. I wait for the spring show at the piers
the way other people wait for robins, or the first asparagus.
Breaking my biggest piece of it was anything but an act of design.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it? Setting up for supper with the television, I swung an
Alvar Aalto nesting table past it (only the best for the clumsy),
hit it on the chin, and over it went in an elegant back dive, like
an acrobatic swan.
</P>
<P>
   The Toikka Majakka (Lighthouse in Finnish) was a prize. Toikka,
a glass artist still working today, developed the technique
(blowing glass into a mold, then turning it like a lathe) that
produced the Majakka's beam of frozen light as the art director at
Nuutajarvi. The company, established in 1793 as a window and bottle
maker, employed other designers in the 20th century, including
Gunnel Nyman, Franck and, through its consolidation in 1987 with
Iittala, Tapio Wirkkala and Timo Sarpaneva, whose names crystallize
what is most collectible in midcentury-modern Finnish glass.
</P>
<P>
   When the bright surface of my living room floor rocked to a
stop, it was broken glass.
</P>
<P>
   I called a friend, dialing in a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg, I broke something,'' I said, too numb to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? An arm? A leg?'' he said. I stopped grieving.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, at work, colleagues laughed. They laughed again
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the confessions started.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thing?'' another friend said, relieved. ``It made me
nervous. I always thought I was going to tip it over.'' Others
agreed. Too many others.
</P>
<P>
   It was a cold winter scene when I deposited what was left of my
$1,600 of 1960s Finnish glass in the metal-mesh trash bin on the
corner of 20th Street and Ninth Avenue _ like a Chelsea version of
a mob dumping ground. The shapely leg of crystal startled patrons
at Le Bergamot as they left with breakfast croissants.
</P>
<P>
   At home, I started to question the existence of what survived.
The glitter that greeted my eye rang false.
</P>
<P>
   I'm middle aged (as I write, I've turned 48). Why did I suddenly
want to sell everything in my apartment? Was I ``in crisis?''
</P>
<P>
   I started making the calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a silver lining,'' said Dr. Carol Ryff, a professor of
psychology at the University of Wisconsin, speaking to me about the
incident. Ryff is a member of the MacArthur Foundation Research
Network on Successful Midlife Development, which released the
initial results of its 10-year study of midlife adulthood last
year. Researchers found that ``midlife crisis'' was a phrase, not a
fact: people in the prime of midlife were generally happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your reaction is obviously wrapped up with bigger issues than
the item,'' she said. Really? ``It's a kind of shattering of a
fantasy.'' (I wish she hadn't used that word.) She explained that I
had momentarily come to terms with my mortality, investing my
psychic energy, much like an emotional attachment to another
person, in an object that I then lost. The Toikka and I were both
living on borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things break; people die _ it's all a flash in the pan,'' Ryff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, where was the silver lining?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those midlife adults who have these sobering moments about
what it's all about,'' she concluded, ``who spend time reflecting
on those issues, who look at all of the past with equanimity and
say, `It's OK,' will have an easier time growing old.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then that I decided to replace the Majakka. I did not
want to look at the past with equanimity. I wanted to collect the
past, and rearrange it attractively.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem _ we'll find another one,'' said Eeva Musacchia, my
Finnish dealer. This roiled another wave of reaction: how rare
could an easily replaceable object be? I squelched it. ``Were you
insured?'' Musacchia asked casually.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't; I'm not. Now that I knew my self-worth had a glass
jaw, I called an insurance agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a tenants policy, if you break something yourself, you're
not covered,'' said Alan Breslow, a vice president of Ralph Parnes
Associates, a New York insurance agency. ``If somebody else breaks
it, you're covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Breslow recommended scheduling the collectible items in it in a
separate, second policy, which would insure me against myself. A
professional appraiser would determine the value of them; a
dealer's detailed receipt, upon purchase, would also suffice in the
event of a claim, Breslow said. I would have to work hard with a
``wear and tear'' item like my Knoll sofa to distinguish it from an
old couch, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Fine arts are comparatively inexpensive to itemize from an
insurer's point of view, Breslow said, less expensive than other
kinds of valuable property, like jewelry or cameras.
</P>
<P>
   In a fast-moving market like midcentury-modern design, it would
be advisable to reappraise a collection every year, not within the
standard three to five years _ or if you buy things frequently.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't replaced Toikka's candle pedestal, but 18 drinking
glasses in two sizes, designed in the 1970s by Wirkkala in amber
and light violet were an inexplicable gap in my collection _ the
minute I saw them.
</P>
<P>
   I really need drinking glasses more, don't I? People break them
all the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0211 </DOCNO>
