<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LAURA-INGRAHAM-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET GEORGE W. DO IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.) 
 By LAURA INGRAHAM  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The Bush campaign has often called the GOP primary contest a
roller-coaster ride. And, for the past few weeks, its tone should
have made everyone aboard sick.
 &HT;    The lowest dive so far came with Sen. John McCain's orchestrated
``Catholic Voter Alert'' telephone calls in Michigan and
Washington, the calls the senator first denied making, then denied
denying.
 &HT;    McCain's goal was to hurt front-runner George W. Bush by tying
him to religious intolerance at Bob Jones University, while helping
himself with his own base _ the media, Democrats and moderate
voters.
 &HT;    Even though he was forced to repudiate the ``Catholic Alert''
calls, McCain's attacks _ which he somehow maintains are not meant
to paint Bush as a bigot _ led the Texas governor to issue a
statement of ``regret'' for any misimpression left by his
appearance at the college.
 &HT;    Bush had a good night on Tuesday, but he shouldn't let his
delegate mop-ups in Virginia, North Dakota and Washington convince
him that McCain will ease up on his ``intolerance'' charge anytime
soon.
 &HT;    After all, McCain's salvo against Bush supporter Pat Robertson
and the Rev. Jerry Falwell came only a day after Bush's statement
of regret. The Arizonan singled out two dinosaurs of the Christian
political-activism network, while praising two lesser-known figures
who generally keep their outreach away from politics _ apparently,
the acceptable sort of Christian conservative.
 &HT;    McCain's strategy is obvious: He's writing off the South in hope
of winning California, New York and New England. He aims to chalk
up delegates by convincing voters that he's the best firewall
against those horrible, nasty zealots from down South, ``agents of
intolerance'' such as Robertson, Falwell and, by extension, Bush.
 &HT;    No, most Republicans aren't buying this, and won't. But many
moderates and Democrats are, and they can vote in open primaries.
That means Bush has to stop complaining about McCain ``sleaze'' and
do something about it _ as one Bush supporter said Tuesday on Rush
Limbaugh's show, ``Get off defense and hit hard.''
 &HT;    What had everyone so excited about George W. in the first place
is that he seemed to have a conservative message with a
multicultural constituency. When he broke into Spanish with ease
and reached out to minority communities in California, people took
notice.
 &HT;    This wasn't your dad's brand of conservatism. It was more
inclusive _ not because he was out criticizing bedrock Republican
principles, the way McCain does, but because he was speaking in a
more welcoming tone and reaching out to groups that most
conservatives had long written off.
 &HT;    It's time Bush got back to that approach. In the days between
now and the crucial California and New York primaries, he should go
where most Republicans fear to tread _ into the barrios, Harlem and
South Central, into community centers and inner-city high schools.
He should reopen the dialogue that he has been leading in his state
for the past five years.
 &HT;    Some of his advisers would deem such events ``too risky'' _
heaven forbid if someone heckled poor Georgie! But that sort of
``safe'' thinking is what got Bush into this mess in the first
place.
 &HT;    Taking his message of educational choice and equal opportunity
without quotas into urban areas may not win Bush many votes there,
but it's a start. And it would highlight McCain's weaknesses on
domestic issues and spike his attempts to tar Bush with the brush
of intolerance.
 &HT;    Imagine if, next time McCain tries to hint that Bush is
intolerant, the Texas governor has spent that morning meeting with
black ministers. Which candidate will sound disingenuous and petty?
 &HT;    If Bush is actually hopelessly ``trapped on the right,'' as
McCain and the media want voters to believe, why does the latest
Washington Post-ABC News poll still show him beating Al Gore in the
general election? And why does his base still include not only
Christian conservatives but also moderate, mainline Republicans?
 &HT;    On the heels of his wins on Tuesday, Bush has a major
opportunity to do far more than merely put Bob Jones University
behind him. With the right offensive-driving moves, he could run
the Straight Talk Express off the road, right into the Gore
campaign bus.
 &HT;    He might start by giving a major address on race in America,
praising the diversity of states such as California and denouncing
those who would seek to severely curtail immigration. Then go to
Tuskegee, Ala., and speak about the injustices perpetrated there
against black Americans.
 &HT;    Remember, when the leaves are starting to turn, Al Gore can be
counted on to be coloring the political landscape with racially
divisive rhetoric. We recently saw a hint of what to expect when
his campaign manager, Donna Brazile, charged that ``Republicans
would rather take pictures of black children than feed them.''
 &HT;    The more Bush does now to undercut those attacks, the more time
he'll later be able to devote to blasting Gore. Maybe he can start
by pointing out that Gore also made a controversial visit to a
religious institution _ a Buddhist temple.
 c.2000 Laura Ingraham  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Laura Ingraham is a lawyer and a special election correspondent
for MSNBC. She is the author of the upcoming book, ``The Hillary
Trap: Looking for Power in All the Wrong Places,'' due from
Hyperion in June 2000.)
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.) _ _ _ _  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
