<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3477 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     03-01 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV19-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAR. 19, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: The unfinished attic in my house has fiberglass insulation on
the floor with a vapor barrier under the insulation.
</P>
<P>
   The insulation was put down between the joists and I want to add
more insulation on top.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no more space left between the joists because
the old insulation fills the space up to the top of each beam.
</P>
<P>
   Should I install an additional vapor barrier and should I lay
the new insulation on top of the old fiberglass batts?
</P>
<P>
   A: Put down the new insulation by rolling the new batts across
the top of the joists and at right angles to the original
insulation.
</P>
<P>
   This provides another layer of insulation on top of the wood
joists (wood is not a good insulator) while also serving to cover
up any gaps left by the old insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Start spreading the insulation out near the eaves and work your
way in toward the center, using only unfaced batts. You do not want
an additional vapor barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a family room on the side of our house that was added
on some years ago. It has wood paneling on the inside and is fully
heated and insulated.
</P>
<P>
   This past month we noticed some kind of flying insects that look
like ants with wings. These seem to congregate down near the floor
in one corner of the room.
</P>
<P>
   I'm worried that these may be termites, but some say they are
merely flying ants.
</P>
<P>
   Without calling in a professional, how can we tell if these
really are termites or ants?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is a difference in appearance if you examine one of the
insects closely.
</P>
<P>
   Both a flying ant and a termite has four wings, but if it is an
ant the two wings in front will be a little larger than the two in
back. A termite's wings are all the same size.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the termite will have a straight, one-piece body, while an
ant has a narrow-waisted body that looks like it is made of two
segments or parts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can we paint our dull looking light gray asphalt roof
shingles a more colorful and darker color?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can paint the shingles with a good quality exterior latex
house paint, but bear in mind that at least two coats will be
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Also remember that you will have to repaint regularly to keep up
the appearance _ probably once every three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our living room was paneled years ago with plywood that came
with a dark finish.
</P>
<P>
   Can we apply a paint over this paneling in order to brighten the
room, and if so, what kind of paint would you recommend?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can paint the panels with any flat or semi-gloss finish,
but I would recommend a satin finish rather than a flat.
</P>
<P>
   You will first have to remove all wax, polish and soil on the
wood by wiping down with very fine steel wool dipped into paint
thinner, then wipe again with a rag dipped into the same solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Sand lightly and wipe off all sanding dust before applying the
first coat of paint.
</P>
<P>
   Use a stain killer such as Kilz or BIN for this first coat, then
apply the finish coat of satin enamel.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``INSULATION IN THE ATTIC'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: New insulation batts are rolled across the tops of the
joists at right angles to the original insulation.
</P>
