<HEADER>
A3482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LEWITT-MURAL-ART-NYT &LR;      03-01 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWITT-MURAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Calif.)  
 DON'T TOUCH THE WALL! IT'S BY SOL LeWITT  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By FRED BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, Carole and Dick Cline were looking for something to
hang over the fireplace in the sitting room of their new home,
which overlooks a golf course near Chicago. The couple's art
consultant, Deborah Lovely, brought by a few paintings but none
that worked with the couple's antique furniture and multicolored
rug, Cline said. Then Lovely suggested a Sol LeWitt mural _ a
``wall drawing'' in the artist's parlance. By Christmas, the couple
had something to match the rug: a geometric drawing in diluted
India inks applied with sponges, covering two walls of their
sitting room _ about 250 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   They just didn't have a chance to meet LeWitt. ``The joke around
here is, `Does Sol LeWitt really exist?''' Cline said.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred of the artist's wall drawings have been installed in
homes around the world, said Susanna Singer, LeWitt's longtime
agent. None was actually put there by LeWitt.
</P>
<P>
   What LeWitt sells _ for up to $100,000 a wall _ is a design,
with detailed instructions for how it should be carried out. (Among
other things, he recommends priming the wall with six coats of
Benjamin Moore Regal Satin Latex in Decorator White No. 215-01.)
His representatives, including the Paula Cooper Gallery in New
York, offer lists of qualified installers, who work at the
homeowner's expense.
</P>
<P>
   One LeWitt, a 10-by-12-foot rectangle of yellow paint and white
crayon, resides in the Greenwich Village town house of the artist
Pat Stier. ``It's very subtle,'' Stier said of the piece, which she
acquired about six years ago. ``People have leaned against it at
parties,'' she said, ``and I've had to rush over and tell them not
to. And the people who clean never know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt's drawings have appeared in kitchens, exercise rooms and
on stairways _ though that is his least favorite location, because,
he said, ``there tends to be a lot of traffic, and they can get
beat up.'' Lately, the artist, who is 70, has been declining
stairway commissions, he said, asking clients to ``please try to
find another wall.''
</P>
<P>
   One of LeWitt's first jobs, 45 years ago, was working as a
graphic designer for the architect I.M. Pei. (Among other things,
he designed the architect's stationery.) LeWitt said that was when
he realized he wanted to work like an architect: conceiving
projects, then letting others carry them out. Now he uses that
approach on public commissions, like the mural at the entrance to
Christie's in Rockefeller Center, and the wall drawings in a
retrospective now at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art. A part
of that show will arrive in November at the Whitney Museum in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   To LeWitt, having his drawings in homes is a ``two-headed
coin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have them any place, but in homes they get a lot
of wear and tear,'' he said. ``It's impossible for people to take
really good care of these things. They have kids, they have dogs,
they have cats. A museum has a staff.''
</P>
<P>
   People _ unlike museums _ move around. Frederieke Taylor, an art
dealer in SoHo, bought her LeWitt wall drawing in 1971 for $600. It
was a charity auction, she recalled, and ``nobody else bid.'' Since
then, she has moved three times _ on each occasion arranging to
have the drawing painted over, then recreated at the new location.
Twice LeWitt reconfigured the drawing to fit new room dimensions.
Taylor plans to call on him again, now that she has relocated to
Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt doesn't charge for reworking an existing drawing _ it's a
service he provides, because it has to be done right.'' Lately, he
said, he has been thinking about ``what happens when I'm not
here.'' He toyed with the idea of letting people he's worked with
make aesthetic decisions about placement and modifications. ``But
the trouble is, they'll die too,'' he said. ``And then you'll have
third and fourth generation people, and you'll be getting too far
from the source.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus he has decided that the ability to change drawings _ at
least officially _ will die with him. ``I can't think of any other
way to do it,'' he said. ``I don't see how it can be passed on.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be more LeWitts in homes if it weren't for the
price, a shortage of blank walls in most houses and the danger of
people bumping into the finished artworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One friend of mine has an early wall drawing, in graphite,''
said Arlene Semel, a Chicago decorator who has installed LeWitts in
several of her clients' houses. ``Whenever she has a party, she
positions a member of the wait staff right in front of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clines chose a room that's not frequented by their 13
grandchildren. But another of Semel's clients recently installed a
LeWitt in an exercise room. The opposite wall has a mirror, Semel
added, ``so the clients get two drawings for the price of one.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer, Lewitt's agent, said the artist occasionally rejects
residential commissions. ``He wants to make sure his drawings work
with the architecture, that they're not just decoration,'' she
said. That means it's all right to choose a wall drawing because
the colors are appealing, but don't ask LeWitt to change the orange
to blue because it goes with your decor,'' she said. ``And don't
send carpet swatches or paint chips.''
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt said he tries to be accommodating. ``It's hard to say no
to somebody who really likes the work,'' he said. ``But the space
has to be right.''
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt has no plans to install a drawing in his own house in
Connecticut. ``It's an old house, and there aren't any big
expansive walls that I could use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the Clines picked a wall drawing they liked from
several catalogs of LeWitts. Over the years, the artist's works
have gone from strictly geometric to far more colorful concoctions.
Lovely helped the Clines select a 1990 drawing, in colors created
from diluted Pelikan-brand inks. To be sure they liked the effect,
the Clines used a slide projector to display a transparency of the
drawing right on their wall. It looked good,'' Cline said. ``We
thought we were buying a nice little square over the fireplace.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rhona Hoffman _ a Chicago gallery owner who represents
Lewitt _ had bigger ideas. She arranged to have a scale model of
the room, along with photographs and elevations of the wall, sent
to LeWitt. He in turn adapted the wall drawing to fit the space,
covering not one but two walls with 200 triangles in combinations
of four colors. Soon, installers began painstakingly drawing the
outlines of the mural. Eventually, they began surrounding sections
with tape and applying the colored inks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they did all of one color at a time, you could almost
see it growing as each color came in,'' Cline said. The process
took 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing the Clines have not received is a certificate of
authenticity. (Their drawing is 639a and 639b _ for the two walls.)
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, there may be duplicates, as when a museum asks to
``borrow'' a wall drawing for a show. Hoffman said owners have sold
wall drawings (meaning the diagrams and certificates) at auction.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said she expects to take the artist to see the Clines'
drawing this summer. LeWitt said that he just might decide change
it (meaning the installers would have to come back).
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I work with are great, but they can't read my
mind,'' he said. ``There are some decisions only I can make.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
