<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-540&AMP;     03-01 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALUE OF HONG KONG INTERNET-TELEPHONE DEAL SHRINKS AS SHARES
TUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Shares of Pacific Century CyberWorks swooned
Wednesday, as the Internet start-up company suffered a hangover on
the morning after its audacious takeover bid for Hong Kong's
flagship telephone company was accepted by the company's British
parent, Cable &AMP; Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century's stock declined 7.9 percent, to 20.40 Hong Kong
dollars, or $2.63, a share. That had the effect of slicing $3
billion from the value of its $38.1 billion all-stock offer for
Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT. Pacific Century's alternative stock-and-cash
offer of $35.9 billion, which analysts said Cable &AMP; Wireless and
other HKT shareholders were more likely to accept, declined in
value by $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century's bruising ride on the stock market did not
surprise analysts in Hong Kong, who had expected the company's
shares to tumble as investors digested the mammoth size and
expensive terms of the acquisition. The shares had been suspended
from trading for two sessions while the company battled Singapore
Telecommunications for Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a new-economy company buys an old-economy company, its
stock price adjusts to old-economy values,'' said Marc Faber, the
head of an investment firm in Hong Kong. He said he expected
Pacific Century stock to fall to $1.29 a share within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts, however, said Pacific Century's shares would be
bolstered in the short run by being added to two influential stock
indexes: Hong Kong's Hang Seng and a regional index of Morgan
Stanley Capital International.
</P>
<P>
   Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT's shares plummeted 12 percent, to 22.75
Hong Kong dollars, or $2.93, a share, as the stock adjusted
downward to reflect the value of the Pacific Century offer. Those
shares had also been halted for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the gyrations on the stock market, Pacific
Century's 33-year-old founder, Richard Li, has assumed the mantle
of one of the power players in Asia's Internet future. Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp., which had thrown its last-minute support
behind Singapore Telecommunications with a $1 billion investment,
was eager to extend an olive branch to Li on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a relationship for a long time with Richard,'' said
James Murdoch, Rupert Murdoch's 27-year-old son, who oversees News
Corp.'s Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   James Murdoch had a drink with Li in Hong Kong on Wednesday
night to discuss the future of a pay-television and Internet
venture between Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT and Star TV, which is owned by
News Corp. Because News Corp. had backed Li's foe in the bidding
war, many analysts said they expected the joint venture to end
after Li took control of Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century has done little to dispel those expectations. A
senior executive, who insisted on not being identified, said
Tuesday, ``We don't know whether the joint venture is even worth
keeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at News Corp., however, said it would be hard to
unravel the venture without substantial financial costs. Murdoch
said, ``I can't imagine a scenario in which Pacific Century would
want to forgo all the content we bring and our expertise in
starting the world's only fully digital service.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   News Corp. does own extensive programming through its Fox
television network, film studio and sports rights. And it has
agreed to set up a similar Internet and interactive television
joint venture with Singapore Telecommunications. But the fact that
one of the mightiest media conglomerates is making overtures to
stay in business with nine-month-old Pacific Century is a testament
to how Li has overnight become a giant on the Asian landscape.
</P>
<P>
   By taking over Cable &AMP; Wireless HKT, Pacific Century gets a
network of high-capacity phone lines that passes a million homes in
Hong Kong. HKT has signed up only 90,000 customers for its
interactive TV service. But analysts said Li could strengthen that
with better marketing and improved service.
</P>
<P>
   Before Li can set about building the future, however, he must
close the deal with Cable &AMP; Wireless. His stock may come under more
pressure as investors dissect the balance sheet of the combined
entity. Pacific Century borrowed $13 billion to finance its bid,
meaning the merged company will lumber under a heavy debt load at a
time when its core telephone business is under attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take time for people to absorb the full consequences
of the deal,'' said David Webb, editor of Webb-site.com, an
Internet site for investors. ``Then they will realize they own the
world's most expensive utility stock.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
