<HEADER>
A3487 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-A     03-01 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYING MARTHA STEWART A PREMIUM FOR CONVENIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT10-11 and NYT17 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After visiting Martha Stewart's Web site last week, I would have
liked to talk to Stewart, one Polish-American to another.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to speak with her because as Polish-Americans, we
appear to have a lot in common. Stewart's site certainly makes the
most of her heritage. Her maiden name is Kostyra (that's ko-STY-ra,
according to the highly detailed About Martha page of her site),
and mine is Slatalla (that's sla-TELL-a, according to my dad).
</P>
<P>
   The similarities don't end there. Many of the old-fashioned,
frugal housekeeping techniques she remembers so well from her
childhood are familiar to me, too. Like her mother, my grandmother
saved the uneaten rice from Sunday dinner and fried it brown the
next day. No wonder, then, that Stewart's site sells such
food-saving staples as a set of glass refrigerator boxes to store
leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   So I would have liked to speak to Stewart. In the manner of my
rice-frying babka, I would have leaned forward, put my hand on the
sleeve of Stewart's crisply ironed blue work shirt (her tasteful
attire never fails to remind me of the generations my ancestors
spent toiling in the fields of Europe) and whispered, ``Martha,
droga Martha, you grew up in a house where people knew the value of
leftovers. Why are you trying to rip me off?''
</P>
<P>
   The problem I have with www.marthastewart.com has nothing to do
with the selection. Covering all facets of housekeeping from
kitchen storage to soap making, the site sells useful, high-quality
tools to help you in many endeavors, from dispensing aluminum foil
to treating your skin to the exfoliating wonders of crushed apricot
seeds. The inventory of more than 1,500 items includes a mix of
both nonexclusive, brand name products like Pillivuyt French
porcelain and Braun travel clocks and exclusive items like the
pressed-glass bunny dish ($18) Stewart cunningly commissioned after
being inspired by her own collection of early-20th-century
glassware.
</P>
<P>
   No, the problem is this: Many of the nonexclusive products at
Martha-Stewart.com are overpriced. Painfully overpriced. I know
this because I found some of the same items, with little effort,
for sale elsewhere on the Internet at much lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how she would have responded to my criticism,
unfortunately, because Stewart referred my questions to Lauren
Stanich, the executive vice president for consumer marketing at
Martha Stewart Living Omnimedia.
</P>
<P>
   And since I spoke with Stanich on the phone, I was not able to
clutch at her clothes either, or to hiss, ``Pani mnie
zawstydzasz,'' the Polish phrase I had memorized in the hopes of
persuading Stewart to rethink her pricing strategies. (Of course,
in retrospect, I'm not sure that telling Stewart ``I am ashamed of
you'' would have done the trick anyway. I found the phrase
underlined in my late grandmother's yellowed Polish-English
language guide.)
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I told Stanich the same things I would have told
Stewart, omitting the Polish curses. Stanich assured me that the
Web site was not trying to rip off anybody. ``Many times if we
don't have the cheapest price, the way we're trying to get around
that is by adding value to the customer, providing things like
instructions,'' Stanich said. For instance, she said, if you are
planning to buy an iron, you can click on a product preview that
instructs you in how to iron a shirt.
</P>
<P>
   I already knew about the site's value-added features, having
recently been in the market to buy an iron. In fact, that's how I
discovered the pricing problem in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart may well be, following the death of my grandmother and
the decline of the wringer washer, the nation's best-known expert
on laundry. And when it comes to ironing a shirt, I may take
certain liberties that Stewart would frown on, like not always
ironing the inside of cuffs. You will be able to read a defense of
that technique in my forthcoming book about modern housekeeping,
which I have tentatively titled ``I Rozkosze Maja Swoje Niesmaki,''
loosely translated as ``Even Pleasures Have Their Stings.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to choosing an iron, I was willing to follow
Stewart's advice only so far. The price for a premium iron on the
site was $125, awfully expensive considering that you can purchase
an iron at the local hardware store for as little as $20. Of
course, the site was selling the Cadillac of irons: Rowenta's
1,200-watt professional steam iron with a stainless-steel sole
plate, an auto-off safety feature and a fearsome ability to unleash
a ``powerful burst of steam'' when held either horizontally or
vertically.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, I went in search of a more detailed description of
the features of the Rowenta DE-871 at the manufacturer's Web site
and decided _ after reading about its powerful steam production
capabilities _ that I still needed it. But not at $125. A quick Web
search showed me I could save $35 by buying it from the Authorized
Appliance Service Co.
</P>
<P>
   Even better for someone as cheap, er, frugal, as myself, the
site also sold remanufactured models of new irons that had failed
factory inspections and were subsequently repaired, for $59.99; I
bought one of those.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The price difference prompted me to take a closer look at
MarthaStewart.com. I found that the Silpat nonstick baking sheets,
made of rubberized silicon ($24 or $38, depending on size), were
available from BridgeKitchenware.com for $17.95 and $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the Gingher scissors. MarthaStewart.com was
selling the dressmaker's shears for $30 and the pinking shears for
$40. But at Allbrands.com, you could buy the same models for $19.98
and $27.98.
</P>
<P>
   Have I mentioned the flashlights? MarthaStewart.com had a
Pelican Pet Tracker light for $18; the same model was selling for
$10.99 at Fogdog.com. The Pelican VersaBrite II Big Beam, $25 at
MarthaStewart.com, costs $11.90 at the MEI Research site.
</P>
<P>
   A Rowenta steam brush, $52 at MarthaStewart.com, was $34 at
Appliances.com. Also, MarthaStewart.com was selling an Atlas
Marcato cookie press for $35; the color was the only difference I
could find between that model and one for $22.99 at InterCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Even a book by Martha Stewart, ``The Best of Martha Stewart
Living: Weddings,'' which costs $50 on the author's site, was
available for a lot less: $35 at both Amazon.com and
Barnesandnoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   When I pointed all this out to Stanich, she acknowledged that
``we should be doing a better job to match pricing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do that in the catalog world,'' she continued, ``but the
online world is a little more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll say. I would expect Stewart, who has been selling things
online since 1997, to be shrewd enough to have figured out that she
should be leveraging the power of her popular brand to offer
products at more reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she seems to be hoping that the site's customers (who
Stanich says tend to be 40-year-old women who own homes, have
children and buy more than one item at once) will think that saving
time is more important than saving money, said Lisa Allen, a senior
analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some shoppers for whom convenience is everything,
and even having to make a few more mouse clicks may be a pain in
the neck for someone in a hurry,'' Allen said. But she added,
``That said, if I had bought one of those irons from Martha
Stewart, I would be miffed.''
</P>
<P>
   So I would say to Stewart, ``Kiedy pociag do Milwaukee
odchodzi'' _ no, wait, that means ``When does the train leave for
Milwaukee?''
</P>
<P>
   I meant to use the phrase right below it, ``Z calego serca,''
which means, colloquially speaking, ``I agree with all my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail address: Slatalla(at)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
