<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER02-COX     03-01 1933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Not all McCain campers happy
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's some squabbling within John McCain's campaign. His
communications director, veteran California strategist Dan Schnur,
reportedly will leave the campaign soon, apparently because of
McCain's initial decision to skip today's Republican debate in
California _ a decision McCain reversed with plans to appear by
satellite. Schnur likely will leave the campaign March 8, according
to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH TO SHOW ON DEBATE STAGE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says there's a ``little spring'' in his step
after his victories in Virginia, Washington state and North Dakota.
Bush also said he's planning to attend today's debate in California
in person, reversing earlier hints he would appear by satellite.
Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush will be there in person
``to send the signal we believe California is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ALL-IMPORTANT DELEGATE COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's primary trifecta in Virginia, North Dakota and
Washington state raised his delegate count to 170. John McCain has
105 and Alan Keyes five. A Republican needs 1,034 delegates to win
the nomination. On the other side, Al Gore has 42 of the necessary
2,170; Bill Bradley has 27.
</P>
<P>
   LIKE A MARATHON RUNNER IN THE BACK OF THE PACK
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers may be hinting that he quit the race, but Bill
Bradley insisted Wednesday that Super Tuesday is just ``the
starting point'' for his campaign. ``Mark Twain put it best when he
said, `Reports of my demise are greatly exaggerated,' '' Bradley
told reporters after speaking to Hispanic voters about health care
in Huntington Beach, Calif. He predicted his showing next Tuesday
would ``surprise some people'' and talked about campaigning for the
next group of primaries March 14.
</P>
<P>
   A READY-FOR-PRIME-TIME PLAYER
</P>
<P>
   Well behind and struggling to keep his campaign alive, Bill
Bradley will have five minutes of prime time on national TV
Wednesday to make a direct appeal to voters five days before the
crucial Super Tuesday primaries. In a taped spot at the end of CBS
News' ``48 Hours,'' Bradley will talk about why he would make the
best president of the four major candidates. It's scheduled for
10:54 p.m. EST and PST, and 9:54 CST and MST. But Bradley will be
competing with ``E.R.'' on NBC, a popular program.
</P>
<P>
   GOTTA BE NOTHING BUT NET FROM 3-POINT LAND
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Bradley turned out to be the ``ugly duckling'' in
Washington state's ``beauty contest'' primary, one of his
best-known supporters gave him slim odds of winning New York's
Democratic primary, and said losing it would cost him the
nomination. ``If he loses New York, he's out,'' former New York
City Mayor Ed Koch told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview. Koch said he gives ``odds 5-to-1 against'' Bradley in
the state's primary March 7. Said William Cunningham, a Democratic
strategist and informal Bradley adviser: ``Maybe he just has to
sink a few three-pointers.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD TO THE BIG ONE IN NOVEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has begun to look past a fast-fading Bill Bradley to the
fall campaign, and is expected to take what aides call ``a more
presidential'' approach. Gore's camp believes it has the Super
Tuesday states locked up and must now look ahead to the general
election where the challenge will be to have Americans view him as
more than just President Clinton's understudy.
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO THE BUSINESS OF BIG BUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Having blown the bulk of his $70 million war chest, George W.
Bush's campaign is ready to go back on the fund-raising circuit
with hat in hand. Bush aides told ABC News they have at least four
fund-raisers planned for March that are expected to raise several
million dollars. Bush himself is not likely to attend a fund-raiser
before March 14.
</P>
<P>
   GOING WHERE THE RATINGS ARE
</P>
<P>
   While the Democrats are duking it out on the debate platform
Wednesday night, the GOP presidential race will lighten up. George
W. Bush and John McCain are taking their acts to competing
late-night shows: Bush on David Letterman; McCain on Jay Leno. Al
Gore tried to loosen up his image with an appearance on Leno's show
Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
   THE SERMON FROM BOB JONES U.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones University in South Carolina had declined to comment
on the hubbub surrounding George W. Bush's visit. But it has
finally responded on its Web site to attacks against it. The
university described John McCain, Al Gore and Bill Bradley as ``the
political `three tenors,' '' who together ``sing the same off-pitch
tune of the liberal left.'' The statement added: ``Isn't it really
a compliment to Bob Jones University that the likes of John McCain,
Al Gore and Bill Bradley seethe and fulminate against us?''
</P>
<P>
   GAYS FOR GORE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's presidential campaign announced the formation of Gay
and Lesbian Americans for Gore. ``The group will work over the
Internet and in local communities to mobilize volunteers and
organize support for Gore,'' said a campaign press release.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY PATTERN CONTINUES, PART 1
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's victory in Virginia fit a pattern set in the
early primary fights: John McCain wins if non-Republicans swarm to
GOP primaries; the Texan wins if Republicans dominate their
primaries and caucuses. In New Hampshire and Michigan, where
McCain's had two victories over Bush, Democrats and independents
accounted for about half the total vote. In South Carolina and
Virginia, two Southern conservative states won by Bush, two-thirds
of the vote came from self-identified Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY PATTERN CONTINUES, PART 2
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is in position to wrap up the Democratic nomination _ in
practical reality if not in delegate strength _ by the time the
votes are counted next week in contests in 15 states. Bill Bradley,
whose insurgent's campaign soared in November and December, fell
short in Washington state on Tuesday, and Iowa and New Hampshire
before that. He's fallen virtually everywhere in the polls, and
faces the possibility of a coast-to-coast rout next week, unless he
unexpectedly decides to quit sooner.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-FLYING ON THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   John McCain raised about $10 million in February in a
fund-raising push that helped him gain ground on better-financed
rival George W. Bush. McCain aides said more than 40 percent of
McCain's February money came from donors on the Internet. And
because so many were small contributions, McCain will qualify for
an additional $5 million in federal matching funds. The government
matches the first $250 of each individual contribution for
candidates who agree to limit their spending. Bush, who did not
agree and is free to spend unlimited amounts, has not released his
February numbers. Final February figures are due March 20.
</P>
<P>
   PRO-MCCAIN INDEPENDENTS SHUT OUT IN N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In a setback for John McCain, a federal judge refused to allow
voters who are now registered as independents to participate in the
New York state's closed GOP presidential primary. Wendy Van Wie, a
McCain supporter, had asked that the state's 2.2 million
independent voters be allowed to participate in next week's
Democratic and Republican primaries. U.S. District Judge David Hurd
said that Van Wie could have become an enrolled Republican before
the Oct. 12, 1999, deadline if she wanted to participate. But Van
Wie registered as a Republican only after another federal judge
ordered McCain be placed on the ballot statewide Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   POINT AND CLICK GETS JUDICIAL GO-AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge's ruling has cleared the way for Arizona
Democrats to use the Internet to cast ballots in the March 11
presidential primary there. U.S. District Judge Paul Rosenblatt
denied a temporary injunction sought by the Virginia-based Voting
Integrity Project, trying to block what would be the nation's first
binding election for public office using the Internet as well as
traditional paper ballots. The group claims it would discriminate
against minorities and the poor. The Arizona Republican primary was
held Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH'S APOLOGIES PAYING OFF
</P>
<P>
   John McCain faces an increasingly tough contest Tuesday in New
York because Catholic voters are responding to George W. Bush's
repeated apologies for his appearance at Bob Jones University.
Independent, New York-based pollster John Zogby said another factor
was the tens of thousands of pro-Bush phone calls orchestrated by
Gov. George Pataki and state GOP leaders. Zogby said the 16
percentage point edge that McCain held over Bush among Roman
Catholic voters as recently as last Saturday has been eliminated by
Bush's repeated apologies. Catholics make up about 45 percent of
New York's GOP primary electorate.
</P>
<P>
   PAT BUCHANAN'S ON BUSH'S SIDE
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party presidential contender Pat Buchanan has come to
George W. Bush's defense, saying he is being unfairly targeted in a
``religious war'' within the Republican Party. ``I have opposed the
Bush family in politics for almost the entire decade of the
1990s,'' Buchanan said. ``Let me say there is not a shred or iota
of bias or bigotry or anti-Catholic bigotry in any member of the
Bush family.'' Buchanan was in St. Louis to court Reform Party
members, but in a meeting with reporters spent most of his time
defending Bush.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA POLLING INDICATES IT'S BUSH
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush retains a comfortable lead over John McCain in
California, according to the San Francisco Examiner poll conducted
for the newspaper and KTVU-TV by the Research 2000 polling
organization in Rockville, Md. Bush outpaces McCain 28 percent to
24 percent among all California voters, but his lead mushrooms to
41-30 percent among the Republican voters whose votes alone will
determine convention delegates. The poll has a margin of error of
3.5 percentage points for all voters, and 6 percentage points for
Republicans only because the sample size was smaller.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE HAVE YOU GONE, JOE D'MAGGIO?
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Willey, the White House volunteer who accused President
Clinton of making made a sexual advance toward her in 1993, said
she supports John McCain because she needs a hero as her president.
``He has integrity. He's honest,'' she said at a primary night
McCain rally in Richmond, Va. ``You just know you'll always get the
truth from him. I think we need a hero. I do.'' Willey also said
she thinks Al Gore would be as untrustworthy as Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   COMPLETELY FLUENT? QUE DICES?
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Los Angeles, Al Gore referred briefly to the
fading campaign of his rival, Bill Bradley, saying it is time to
unite. Paying attention to the diverse ethnic populations in
California, he had an interview with Univision, which he was asked
to conduct in Spanish. He declined, but he said he once ``was
completely fluent'' in the language.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO GOING WITH THE FAVORITES
</P>
<P>
   An independent statewide poll in Ohio shows George W. Bush ahead
of John McCain 53 percent to 36 percent. The poll of likely
Republican voters was conducted by the Institute for Policy
Research at the University of Cincinnati. A similar poll of likely
Democratic voters showed Al Gore ahead of Bill Bradley 66 percent
to 22 percent. The poll's margin of error is 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
