<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3502 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-WESTERN-FILMS-2TAKES-     03-01 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTERN-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENDING OUT A SEARCH PARTY FOR THE WESTERN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 (Eds: Graham Fuller is the movie columnist for Interview magazine
and the editor of ``Loach on Loach,'' about the director Ken
Loach.)  
 By GRAHAM FULLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two movies set in a once-renowned but now rarely visited arena
will open this year. Next month, Miramax will release ``Texas
Rangers,'' starring the television pinups James Van Der Beek and
Ashton Kutcher, among others, as wet-behind-the-ears recruits in
Stetsons and bandoliers who take on a band of renegades.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's ``Shanghai Noon,'' starring Jackie Chan as a
19th-century Chinese man trailing a Chinese princess in the
American West, follows in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Canada, the British director Michael Winterbottom
is shooting a frontier version of Thomas Hardy's novel ``The Mayor
of Casterbridge''; in the film, an Irish immigrant sells his wife
and child for a mine during the California gold rush of 1849 and 18
years later seeks to reclaim his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kingdom Come,'' as it is called, is ``not about shootouts,''
Winterbottom said recently, ``but about the emotional connections
between people.''
</P>
<P>
   One can imagine what John Wayne would have said if he'd been
asked to saddle up, by John Ford, say, for a movie based on such a
premise. In the words of Ethan Edwards, the driven, psychotic man
Wayne played in Ford's ``The Searchers'' (1956): ``That'll be the
day.'' (In his finest westerns, including ``The Searchers'' and
1948s ``Red River,'' Wayne played men who are often  &UR; unable  &LR; to
connect emotionally.)
</P>
<P>
   Remember the Western? The question is not unreasonable, given
that Americans born since 1975 _ the biggest moviegoers _ are the
first modern generation for whom Westerns and the cowboy mystique
are not a thread in the weft of their daily lives. The films that
have replaced the Western do not offer the cohesive reflection or
ongoing critique of the American way that it did, even as the most
nostalgic and sentimental of entertainments.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has emerged to replicate the Western's heady blend of
action, excitement, romance and poetry. Of course, try explaining
to a 20-year-old why the moment at the end of ``The Searchers,''
when Ethan turns in a ranch house doorway and saunters off into the
saffron desert behind him, is more tragically and hauntingly
beautiful than Leonardo DiCaprio's icy demise in ``Titanic,'' and
you will be regarded as insane. In the age when Leo is king, John
Wayne is a creature from another planet.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long ago that the Western was America's pre-eminent
genre. Its ethos and its codes were bound up with America's sense
of itself as the nation for which no frontier was uncrossable, no
enemy untameable, no mountain too high or forest too dense for
conquest.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, Westerns were jingoistic lies, and often worse,
and Ford, the director who is widely considered to be their
greatest proponent, was, at least until the twilight of his career,
the greatest liar of them all.
</P>
<P>
   However fallacious, the Western's blood-stirring representations
of the taming of the West held such recent sway over the public
imagination that, as late as 1995, Wayne and Clint Eastwood, the
actors most indelibly associated with the genre, ranked first and
second in a poll of the country's most popular stars _ and Wayne
had been dead for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   It could be further contended that the winning of best picture
Oscars by ``Dances With Wolves'' (1990) and ``Unforgiven'' (1992)
pointed to the Western's durability after it had supposedly been
laid to rest. More truthfully, these two ideologically opposed
films were signposts on the western's path to Boot Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Western went in and out of favor during the first 70 years
of its existence without relinquishing its status as the populist
national myth, the iconographic representation of the years of
westward expansion between 1865 and 1890 when the Indian resistance
was destroyed and the frontier was closed. It was not simply the
receding of the historical events on which the Western was based
that caused its eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, Samuel Peckinpah's ``The Wild Bunch'' allegorically
inscribed the failure of America's anti-Communist mission in
Vietnam, and in so doing proposed a counter-myth to the Western's
myth of righteous progressivism from which the genre has never
recovered. The jungle terrain of Vietnam _ ``Indian country'' in
American soldiers' parlance _ was an uncrossable frontier, the
North Vietnamese Army an unassailable enemy.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Soldier Blue'' and ``Little Big Man'' (both 1970) made
references to the My Lai massacre through their respective
depictions of the U.S. cavalry's slaughter of Cheyenne Indians at
Sand Creek (1864) and Washita (1868), they attacked not only
American intervention in Vietnam but also the Western's ingrained
racism.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Little Big Man'' deconstructed and devalued a big
chunk of Western iconography _ the captivity tale, the saintly
townswoman, the gunfighter, Custer's Last Stand. Richard Slotnick,
author of ``Gunfighter Nation: The Myth of the Frontier in
20th-Century America'' (University of Oklahoma Press, 1992), noted
the failure of ``assertively traditional or reactionary Westerns''
like ``Two Mules for Sister Sara'' and ``Ulzana's Raid'' that came
after ``Little Big Man'' and suggested ``the rejection of the
Western had gone beyond antipathy for a particular ideology to
rejection of the very idea that the frontier could provide the
basis of a national public myth.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Kevin Costner's ``Dances With Wolves'' supplied another
counter-myth, based on political correctness and historical
inaccuracy, that was fatal for the traditional Western.
</P>
<P>
   A relentless sentimentalization of Plains Indian culture,
Costner's film tapped into the New Age sensibility by turning the
Sioux with whom Costner's cavalry officer bonds into
environmentally conscious peaceniks. That the Sioux were as warlike
as the Pawnee Indians, whom the film vilifies, and rapaciously
wasteful in their slaughter of buffalo, was ignored by this box
office smash, which effectively terminated the racist dynamic of
the old-fashioned ``cowboys and Indians'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   (Released two years later, Michael Mann's ``Last of the
Mohicans,'' with its good and bad woodland Indians and its
unflinching images of their atrocities, was a much more authentic
portrait of the frontier than Costner's rhapsodic apologia.)
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, ``Dances With Wolves'' feminized and disempowered the
Western by bowdlerizing its violent _ that is, masculine and
imperialist _ ideological imperatives. Retrospectively, Eastwood's
``Unforgiven'' (1992) now looks like a reaction to it, just as
``Rio Bravo'' (1959), a championing of the communal macho
professionalism of lawmen, had been a reaction to ``High Noon''
(1952), the screenwriter Carl Foreman's bitter allegory of
McCarthyism in which Gary Cooper's hunted marshal goes it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Unforgiven'' was probably not intended as an allegory
of America's righteous war against Saddam Hussein in 1991, it may
certainly be construed as a justification of necessary violence,
however elegiacally framed. Eastwood's character, William Munny, a
widowed hog farmer, returns momentarily to his old life as a lethal
gunfighter, purging a corner of Wyoming of the forces of corruption
and cruelty with five quick killings at the picture's climax. So
nostalgic in tone was ``Unforgiven,'' that even in 1992 this seemed
like the Western's ferocious culmination.
</P>
<P>
   Munny, though, is also a single parent and the defender of dumb
horses and victimized prostitutes; in these respects he is not so
distant from Costner's Indian-loving cavalryman. At the end of
``Unforgiven,'' we learn that Munny purportedly took his children
off to San Francisco and became a dry-goods merchant.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The domestication of Eastwood's persona _ once the amoral
mercenary of Sergio Leone's spaghetti western ``Dollars'' trilogy
(1964-66) _ canceled the sustaining myth of the Western hero that
had been established in the first half of the 19th century by James
Fenimore Cooper's five ``Leatherstocking Tales,'' including ``The
Last of the Mohicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's Hawkeye, modeled on Daniel Boone, had posited for the
first time in a literary form the archetype of the rugged
individual who furthered the cause of civilization on the frontier
but whose use of violence to combat savagery, usually that of
Indians, condemned him to remain an outsider. This was the classic
situation, and the fate, of such followers of Hawkeye as Alan
Ladd's courtly gunfighter in ``Shane'' (1953) and of Wayne's Ringo
Kid in ``Stagecoach'' (1939), his Ethan Edwards in ``The
Searchers'' and his Tom Doniphon in ``The Man Who Shot Liberty
Valance'' (1962).
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberty Valance,'' Ford's last great Western and his saddest,
was a crisis for the genre that turned on the usurpation of the
primitive man of action's role in taming the West by the man of
words, the Eastern lawyer Ransom Stoddard (James Stewart).
</P>
<P>
   Ford undercut his earlier mythographic representations of the
West by showing how another kind of lie could be perpetuated: the
erroneous belief that it was Stoddard, not Doniphon, who killed the
monstrous Valance (Lee Marvin). The Western could not recover from
that theft anymore than it can recover now from the image of Clint
Eastwood wearing an apron and standing behind a counter.
</P>
<P>
   Our gunfighters have been emasculated, our Indians have been
politically corrected, and we live in an era of a president and
presidential candidates who, unlike Teddy Roosevelt, John F.
Kennedy and Ronald Reagan, naturally avoid _ in the absence of
geopolitical frontiers _ the propagandist rhetoric of
frontiersmanship. The absence of a frontier with a native foe
standing behind it is, of course, a happy absence, whatever that
may signify about such cultural products as films.
</P>
<P>
   But what does it say about the Western's prospects in the 21st
century? Frankly, no art form predicated on racism and imperialist
aggression is tenable these days: The only ``good'' Indian is a
living Indian. Thanks to ``Dances With Wolves,'' the educated
American public will not accept otherwise and nor, therefore, will
the studios.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the codes of the Western will continue to be
remythologized in urban or extraterrestrial settings, as ``The
Searchers'' was in ``Taxi Driver'' (1976) and partly in ``Star
Wars'' (1977), remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Ford's ``Stagecoach,'' John Wayne's outlaw and the
prostitute, played by Claire Trevor, ride off for a future together
that Thomas Mitchell's redeemed drunken doctor hopes will be ``safe
from the blessings of civilization!'' That dream of an agrarian
never-never land was, even for 1939, as featherbrained as the
utopian Indian encampment of ``Dances With Wolves,'' and is as
irrelevant to today's film audience as the genre's aesthetic values
and its imagery.
</P>
<P>
   The Western's West _ the wagon trains encircled by whooping
Indians, the ritual showdown between a sheriff and a gunslinger in
a deserted street, the heaving, smoky saloon with its ``dance hall
girls'' and hurdy-gurdy tunes, the endless vistas of Monument
Valley in Ford's films, the epic topographies of Anthony Mann's _
amounted to a magnificent spectacle. But even the Western addict
knows that for the mass-market moviegoer it has little currency in
the age of ``The Matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Western is not yet extinct, surviving, just
about, on television. Bill Pullman recently directed himself as the
title character of TNT's ``The Virginian,'' a faithful adaptation
of the seminal, oft-filmed Western novel by Owen Wister.
</P>
<P>
   Pullman's portrayal of the lean, virile cowboy from the South,
who courteously but ardently woos the schoolmarm and defeats
rustlers, reminds us that there is at least one contemporary actor
with the aura of Gary Cooper, who played the Virginian on screen in
1929.
</P>
<P>
   If the Western finally evaporates for good in the early years of
a new century, historians may point to Jim Jarmusch's ``Dead Man''
(1996) as the genre's distinctly nongeneric epitaph. In this bleak,
sometimes comic parable, which looks nothing like a traditionalist
Western, Johnny Depp plays an Ohio greenhorn called William Blake
who heads West to find that the ``dark satanic mills'' alluded to
in a poem by his namesake have swallowed up the prairie and turned
the new Jerusalem of the West into a capitalist hell.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes in the company of an Indian named Nobody, he drifts
into the Nowhere the frontier has become, a locus of madness,
squalor and disease, and dies there alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch's surreal movie gives an impression of a West far more
realistic than that depicted in most Hollywood Westerns. It is the
dystopian West one can read about in recent writings of revisionist
historians of the pioneer era _ and the West that John Wayne and
John Ford never knew or cared to know.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Western at the end of all Westerns, and it may prove
impossible to follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
