</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With TECH-VISAS. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOW HOUSE, SENATE BILLS ON H-1B VISAS DIFFER
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith's House bill would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase the H-1B visas from 115,000 to 160,000 for one year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Double the fee for each visa to $1,000 to fund college
scholarships in high-tech fields.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grant visas only to companies that are also hiring Americans
and giving raises.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require H-1B visa aliens to work full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Orrin Hatch and Spencer Abraham's Senate bill would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increase H-1B visas to 195,000 for each year through fiscal
2002.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exempt from the cap any foreigners working for U.S. colleges
or research institutions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exempt foreigners who received a master's or doctoral degree
in the last six months from a U.S. college.
</P>
