group, claims that nearly 269,000 high-tech jobs currently are
going unfilled, and that U.S. businesses are losing $4.5 billion a
year as a result.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said there is no ``credible or objective study
documenting the high-tech labor shortage.'' The National Science
Foundation, which was directed by Congress in 1998 to study
high-tech job needs, isn't expected to complete its work until
October.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's bill was co-sponsored by Reps. Tom Campbell, R-Calif.,
whose district includes Silicon Valley; Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., who
co-chairs the Congressional Internet Caucus, and Chris Cannon,
R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith's bill falls far short of what industry wants,
technology executives are praising a Senate bill introduced last
month by Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Spencer Abraham, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   That bill would increase H-1B visas to 195,000 for each year
through fiscal 2002. It also would exempt from the cap any
foreigners who work for U.S. colleges and universities or research
institutions. New exemptions would go to those foreigners who
received a master's or doctorate in the last six months from a U.S.
college.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would retain a provision of the 1998 bill
requiring a $500 per visa fee to go toward scholarships and worker
training programs in this country. In contrast, the Smith bill
would boost the visa fee to $1,000 per foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who has been a leading proponent of
increasing foreign tech workers, introduced his own bill to raise
the visa cap to 200,000 through 2002. But he has since indicated he
will back the Hatch version.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to H-1B visas comes from both the left and right.
Liberal Democrats with close links to labor unions and conservative
Republicans who want to limit immigration are united in their
dislike for an expanded visa program. Critics of the program also
say it is plagued by fraud and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such objections, some sort of visa expansion seems
likely this year for two reasons: the high-tech sector is flush
with cash to support congressional campaigns this election year,
and union leaders are focused on limiting trade with China, leaving
them with relatively little time or energy for the visa issue.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
