<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL FORECAST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Late winter weather will return to the Northeast as a
slow-moving storm in Maine strengthens and draws chilly air from
Ontario into New England. Periods of snow will accumulate several
inches in northern New York and Vermont with snow showers dusting
the higher terrain of the northern Appalachians. A sharp and colder
wind from the northwest will gust to 35 miles an hour at times from
southern New England to the Middle Atlantic region. While clouds
occupy the interior sections, the North Atlantic coast will turn
brighter.
</P>
<P>
   Drier and somewhat cooler air will move into the Southeast
behind a cold front. An active breeze from the north will combine
with clear skies to produce a cool day in the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   A dome of cool, dry air will be centered over the Middle West
promoting sunshine and a milder afternoon in the Great Lakes and
upper Mississippi Valley. Moisture streaming north from the Gulf of
Mexico will bring clouds to much of the Plains. A small, intense
disturbance traversing northwest Texas should bring a swath of
heavy wet snow from southeast Colorado to northwest Kansas.
Meanwhile, a cold rain will dampen the central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and a few heavy thunderstorms will form over north Texas
and Oklahoma along a warm front. A narrow band of strong to locally
severe storms may grow along a push of dry air in central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will spread back into northern California as a cold
front weakens over the interior West. The Northwest will stay dull
and damp, but the Southwest should be brighter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fine in Fairbanks &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks had one of its finest Februarys of record. The mercury
never stayed below zero for an entire day and only two occasions
brought a few flurries. The month ended with a mere trace of snow
for only the second time this century. Temperatures averaged more
than 10 degrees above seasonal levels with the mercury rising to a
record 41 degrees on February 2nd. Sunshine was abundant during the
second month in the central Alaskan city adding to the pleasantness
of mid-winter in the Arctic. Days are rapidly lengthening with
nearly 7 minutes of additional sunlight each day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Extended Forecast &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sunday: The deep chill of winter will remain well
north of the U.S.-Canada border as the polar jet stream retreats
northward. Across the contiguous states, scattered showers will
accompany low pressure crossing the Southeast while partly cloudy
and mild conditions cover the central states. Gusty breezes will
import cooler air in the Northeast while showers and mountain snow
affect the southern Rockies and Southwest.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday: Warmer air will surge northward into the lower
Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys on breezes from the south. A
return to milder conditions will also occur in the Northeast.
Formidable low pressure will churn though the Southwest states,
bringing heavy snow to the southern Rockies. Ahead of the low,
potent thunderstorms will erupt over Texas and the southern Plains
as humid air returns from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
