u w BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS &LR;      03-01 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOUSE VOTES TO WIPE OUT EARNINGS LIMIT FOR SENIORS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted unanimously Wednesday to repeal the
65-year-old law that docks the retirement checks of Social Security
recipients who continue to work and earn more than $17,000 per
year.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare display of bipartisanship, the House voted 422 to 0 to
eliminate the Social Security earnings limit, which was enacted
during the Depression to encourage senior citizens to leave the
work force to free up jobs for younger workers.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, seniors who continue to work from age 65 to 69 lose
$1 in Social Security benefits for every $3 they earn above
$17,000. About 800,000 seniors in that age bracket now lose some or
all of their benefits because of the earnings limit and that number
is expected to balloon as baby boomers reach the retirement age but
continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings limit does not apply to people 70 and older. The
cap is scheduled to rise to $30,000 by 2002 unless Congress
eliminates it.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the repeal of the earnings limit is strong in the
Senate, which is expected to consider the measure soon. President
Clinton pledged in a letter to House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., to sign it into law if it does not become bogged down with
other proposals.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas,
hailed the passage of the Senior Citizens Freedom to Work Act of
2000, calling the earnings limit ``a malevolent provision of age
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   As the law stands, a senior earning $26,000 per year would lose
$3,000 in Social Security benefits. Momentum for the change comes
as more Americans work well beyond the retirement age and are being
pressed into work because of a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Horace B. Deets, executive director of the AARP, formerly know
as the American Association of Retired Persons, said older
employees have the skills, expertise and enthusiasm employers
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when labor shortages loom in the horizon and people
are living longer, we should encourage, not penalize, older
workers,'' Deets said.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings limit has long been unpopular, but repeated
attempts to eliminate it have failed because lawmakers balked at
the cost. However, supporters gained new momentum this year because
the federal budget surplus can cover its short-term costs.
</P>
<P>
   Repealing the cap is projected to cost $8 billion in 2001 and
nearly $23 billion over a decade, according to the Congressional
Budget Office. But the repeal of the earnings limit would pay for
itself after about 20 years, according to the Social Security
Administration, because people who work past the retirement age
continue to pay into Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   During two hours of discussion on the House floor, Texas Rep.
Bill Archer, who chairs the House Ways and Means Committee, said it
was a ``great day for hundreds of thousands of working seniors
across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Archer, who introduced legislation to repeal the earnings limit
when he was first sworn in as a congressman in 1971, said the
penalty was ``unfair and backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we want to discourage any worker _ whether 17 or 67
_ from working?'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   Repealing the law would save as much as $150 million in
administrative costs, congressional supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to keep this resource _ these people who have
built this country _ we can't afford to keep them out,'' Hastert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., who heads the Social Security
subcommittee of the House Ways and Means panel, called the earnings
limit ``shameful'' and said it sends a bad message to seniors. He
later told reporters that Wednesday's vote was ``a meaningful step
toward Social Security reform.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., said the vote
indicated that Democrats and Republicans can work together to
rebuild the Social Security system and said the legislation would
``keep a generation of skilled workers in the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beginning to suffer from a serious worker shortage that
threatens our economic growth,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
judy &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
