<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NANOTUBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WISP OF CARBON, A WHIFF OF GASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(lh) 
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The nanotube is the Hercules of the submicron materials world, for
it is nearly a hundred times as strong as steel. Now, like a  &UR; ' &LR; 90s
update of the manly man, the molecules are turning out to be
sensitive as well.
</P>
<P>
   Two research teams, one at Stanford University and the other at
the University of California at Berkeley, have demonstrated that
nanotubes work well as tiny chemical sensors, sniffing out faint
amounts of gas rapidly at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   This new property may make them highly useful for detecting
oxygen as well as toxic exhaust gases like ammonia and nitrogen
dioxide, implicated in greenhouse warming and acid rain. Because of
the relatively simple structure of nanotubes, it may be possible to
manufacture them as sensing devices very cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Nanotubes are fullerenes, hollow molecules built of carbon atoms
_ like buckyballs, their soccer-ball-shaped chemical cousins. To
make nanotubes, carbon vapor is condensed into sheets of graphite
one atom thick, which spontaneously adopt a form resembling chicken
wire. To form a nanotube, a sheet spontaneously rolls itself into a
long, slender cylinder about a billionth of a meter in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Nanotubes are the great hope of many laboratories not only
because of their strength but also because of their electronic
properties. They may one day be faster, cheaper replacements for
silicon-based integrated circuits because the atoms that make up
the wall of the nanotube can be arranged so the molecules conduct
electricity like a metal or like a semiconductor. There are already
nanotube transistors a fraction of the size of conventional ones.
</P>
<P>
   But the use of nanotubes as chemical sensors was completely
unexpected, said Alex Zettl, a physics professor at Berkeley who
leads a group that has worked for years on the devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory never predicted this,'' Zettl said. ``Gases or
liquids weren't expected to have any effect on these perfect
wires.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Berkeley group put a nanotube in a vacuum chamber
and measured its chemical resistance after exposing it to oxygen,
``the resistance changed in less than a second,'' Zettl said.
</P>
<P>
   The major changes in resistance and conductivity reported by
Zettl's group came about as oxygen was added or removed because the
interaction of the nanotube with the gas molecules led to an
electrical effect that was easily detected in a circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The nanotube's potential as a chemical sensor is so unexpected
that much previous work on the tubes will have to be re-evaluated,
Zettl said. ``The tubes were thought to be insensitive to oxygen,
one of the most common gases of them all,'' he explained, so
laboratories often did not take precautions in keeping the tubes
away from air.
</P>
<P>
   Previous experiments with nanotubes were commonly done on
benchtops, not in enclosures like the ones used by Zettl's group.
``Now we will have to revisit all those old experiments to see if
they reflect intrinsic properties,'' he said. ``Even some of our
data will need to be re-interpreted.''
</P>
<P>
   Zettl hopes that a complete report of his group's work will
appear in a forthcoming issue of the journal Science; Philip G.
Collins is the lead author.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, now a postdoctoral researcher in the nanometer science
research division at International Business Machines' Thomas J.
Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y., said that in
retrospect, it was not surprising that the carbon nanotubes
detected the gases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually makes perfect sense that nanotubes should soak up
molecules and be affected,'' he said. Collins compared nanotubes to
a piece of activated charcoal placed in an aquarium to pick up
chlorine from the water.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did oxygen exposure markedly change the resistance of
the nanotubes, Collins said, but it also changed some of the
nanotubes from insulators to conductors and transformed their
semiconducting properties as well. ``The experiments suggest we can
use gases to control the properties of nanotubes on the molecular
scale,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   While Zettl's group investigated the effect of oxygen on
nanotubes, the researchers at Stanford looked at the effects of
nitrogen dioxide and ammonia.
</P>
<P>
   Hongjie Dai, an assistant professor in the Stanford chemistry
department, and his research group demonstrated that nanotubes
could effectively detect those gases: In their experiments, the
flow of electric current in nanotubes increased in response to
nitrogen dioxide and decreased when the tubes were exposed to
ammonia.
</P>
<P>
   Dai's nanotube sensor, described in the Jan. 28 issue of
Science, is a nanotube with metal leads at either end. When exposed
to nitrogen dioxide at a concentration of 20 parts per million, the
conductance of the tube increased thousands of times within 10
seconds. Dai's sensor operates at room temperature; conventional
sensors based on semiconducting metal oxides must operate at very
high temperatures for high sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University has patented the device and is exploring the
possibility of commercial uses, Dai said. The device might be
fabricated very cheaply because of its relatively simple
solid-state structure, making it competitive with larger, more
expensive sensors currently in use.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback of the device, Dai said, is that the changes in
conductivity dissipate slowly. After a nanotube detects a gas, as
many as 12 hours at room temperature must elapse before it can be
used again; the time is shorter if the tube is heated. That could
preclude the use of a nanotube sensor in many applications, said
Charles E. Kolb, president of Aerodyne Research, of Billerica,
Mass., an instrument company that makes sensors that can detect
nitrogen dioxide and ammonia in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of applications of pollutant sensors require relatively
rapid measurements of up to 20 times per second,'' Kolb said.
Aerodyne's sensors, which are laser-based devices, cost as much as
$100,000. Instead of using a solid state sensor, like a nanotube,
to detect gases, Aerodyne's sensors use spectroscopic techniques,
measuring the infrared absorption of the gases, to map the
distribution of pollutants from a distance _ making measurements
from an airplane or a mobile van, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Kolb said Dai's devices might one day be useful for measuring
exhaust inside automobile pipes or factory smokestacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are impressive for a solid-state sensor,'' he said.
``They have the potential to be very cheap and easy to fabricate,
if they can figure out how to get the gas out quickly and make
another measurement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
