<SLUG> BC-POPE-APOLOGY-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSLATIONS OF VATICAN APOLOGY ARE RELEASED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In preparation for Pope John Paul II's plan to deliver a
sweeping apology this month for the Roman Catholic Church's
historical failings, a Vatican document was released Wednesday
outlining the conditions and limits to the Holy Year act of
repentance.
</P>
<P>
   Among the errors listed in the document are divisions within
Christianity, forced conversions, the use of violence and
anti-Jewish prejudice. However, the document, entitled ``Memory and
Reconciliation: The Church and the Mistakes of the Past,'' also
stresses that many acts of earlier centuries cannot be judged
solely by contemporary moral standards.
</P>
<P>
   It draws a sharp line between sins committed by the church's
``sons and daughters'' and the church itself, which is ``holy and
immaculate.'' Citing past writings by John Paul II and his
predecessors, the document explains that ``the purification of
memory'' that the pope seeks to conduct ``can never mean that (the
church) gives up proclaiming the revealed truth entrusted to her.''
</P>
<P>
   The text of the pope's apology, which he intends to deliver on
March 12, has not yet been finished, Vatican officials said.
Wednesday's preparatory document was to have been officially
released in Italian on Thursday in Rome by Cardinal Joseph
Ratzinger, who as head of the Congregation of the Doctrine of the
Faith is responsible for its drafting. However, technical delays
forced the Vatican to delay its publication until next Tuesday,
while church leaders in France and Germany went ahead and issued
French and German translations Wednesday..
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an accident,'' said the Rev. Georges Cottier, a Vatican
theologian whose International Theological Commission helped draft
the document.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, who has made repentance one of the key themes of this
Holy Year _ and of his papacy _ has already delivered
groundbreaking apologies for the church's past errors, most notably
expressing regret in 1998 for the failure of many Catholics to help
Jews escape the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   That document, ``We Remember: A Reflection on the Shoah,'' went
further than any previous Vatican statement but disappointed many
Jewish leaders, who said the Vatican did not go far enough in
acknowledging the responsibility of church officials _ in
particular, the wartime pope, Pius XII, whose failure to publicly
denounce Nazism remains a bitterly contested issue between the
Vatican and many Jewish organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's document seems aimed more at reassuring
Catholics and church leaders who fear that the Vatican has gone too
far in apologizing for past sins. The document, which sets out a
theological framework for repentance by the church, notes that some
Catholics expressed ``reservations'' about a process of admitting
responsibility that could seem a concession to ``those who are
hostile'' to the church.
</P>
<P>
   The document sought to put the pope's call for a
``purification'' of the church within its proper theological and
historical context, Cottier said. He said that it would be
``absurd'' to take responsibility for all past mistakes and that
apologies worked best in an ecumenical sphere, where divided
branches of Christianity could seek mutual pardon and
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be done with the Muslims, because Islam does not
recognize the Christian notion of pardon,'' Cottier said. ``In
places where Christians and Christian missionaries are in a
minority, it would be taken as a sign of weakness. We couldn't
write it down that way, but that was the thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The document did directly address another Vatican concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``One must also evaluate the connection between spiritual
benefits and the possible costs of such acts,'' it states, ``taking
into consideration the unwarranted accents that the media can put
on certain aspects of ecclesiastical declarations.''
</P>
<P>
   A little like a Supreme Court brief, the document lays out the
theological precedents for a church apology, with citations ranging
from the Old Testament to pronouncements by recent popes. The
document notes that ``there is no precedent for seeking pardon for
past mistakes by the Magisterium,'' referring to church teachings
that Catholics view as infallible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Paul II is frequently quoted on the need for the church to
``purify'' itself of the sins of its followers and seek renewal.
But the document does not review church history in great detail. In
1998, the Vatican assigned a commission to examine the Inquisition,
but it has not yet published its conclusions. Instead, the document
alludes to forced conversions and the torture and burning of
heretics by noting, ``on various occasions in the past millennium,
dubious methods have been used to obtain just results.'' The
document deplores ``intolerant methods and even violence in the
service of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   It also dwells on contemporary Catholic lapses, including
indifference, ``ethical relativism,'' many Catholics' failure to
defend the unborn from ``abortion laws,'' as well as their neglect
of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mentioned a few errors, but we could have had a very
long list,'' said the Rev. Jean Louis Burgues, a French priest who
worked on the document and presented it in Paris on Wednesday. ``I
fear the list will never be finished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
