<HEADER>
A3581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-VIDEO-SKOL-VIOLENCE02     03-01 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SKOL-VIOLENCE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young singers seek to erase school violence with prayer
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's Saturday, and the kids at the
playground of Lake Worth's Bryant Park are mugging for the video
camera. There's 35 of them, all in black slacks and black shirts,
tossing footballs, playing with Hula Hoops. The oldest is 15 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest, 3.
</P>
<P>
   The children, who call themselves The Next Generation 2000, are
making a music video. Some have come from as far away as Tennessee
for today's filming.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by last year's violent tragedy in Littleton, Colo., the
group has released a locally produced single about ending school
violence and reinstituting prayer in public schools. About half of
the kids attend St. Ann School in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The children are led by Jacksonville resident Marie Drevet, a
voice coach who travels throughout the Southeast providing voice
lessons for kids. Last summer, Drevet began adapting new lyrics to
``A Little Good News,'' a song originally recorded in 1983 by
singer Anne Murray. As she traveled to Florida, Georgia and
Tennessee _ her home state _ Drevet talked to her students about
singing the adaptation. They agreed and eventually organized to fly
to Florida to film the video.
</P>
<P>
   In this new version, the children sing to America's adults,
pleading with them to help stop the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``School violence has gotten totally out of hand,'' Drevet
explains as the camera crew sets up a shot. ``Morality is no longer
taught in school anymore. That's why children have no respect for
each other, much less anyone else.... We believe every child should
be taught prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   This music video of the single is the culmination of work that
began last October, when the group did its first live performance
of the song at a Florida festival. A month later, the children
wanted to record it.
</P>
<P>
   Drevet contacted Rory Bourke, one of the three writers of the
original song.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out what it was about _ taking guns out of
people's hands _ I was behind it 100 percent....,'' says Bourke.
``It was a song that was used for a lot of good when it came out,
and it looked like somebody wanted to use it for some more good. We
were all behind this.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, the kids and their parents raised money to
record the song. Afterward, Drevet began pressing CDs at her home
to distribute.
</P>
<P>
   The harmonies are solid. The message, effective. Like children,
the lyrics ask big questions: Don't you think if the teachers would
only let us pray, show our friends a better way, we might save a
life today? ... Doesn't anybody understand what we're going
through? We need someone we can look up to, could that someone be
you?
</P>
<P>
   They're finding answers. Radio stations in Florida and southern
Georgia are playing the single. People _ including Florida Gov. Jeb
Bush _ have written the kids, offering emotional support. Others
are sending money, which will go to the costs of distributing the
video to television stations and school boards, and pressing 2,500
more CDs. They will be released to more radio stations March 15.
Folks who make a contribution will also receive a CD.
</P>
<P>
   The kids are smiling. The word is spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing that the song goes past Florida surprises me. I'm
really shocked. But I think it will make it,'' says Bianca Clark,
13, from Riviera Beach. ``Hopefully, we can get this message out
across the United States. I hope we can get the song in schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Drevet wants that. And she wants to realize the children's dream
of singing the song to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping we can raise enough money to do that, too,''
Drevet says, looking at the children as they play. ``Considering
the response from the people who've been hearing it and writing in,
I don't think that goal is unreasonable at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
