</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-AFGHAN-HIJACK-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN TO ALLOW ONLY 4 ASYLUM APPLICANTS FROM HIJACKED PLANE TO
STAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Only four of the dozens of passengers who applied for
political asylum after their plane was hijacked from Afghanistan
last month will definitely be allowed to remain in Britain, the
government said Wednesday night. Twenty-seven others have been
ordered to leave the country with their families, while the status
of the remaining passengers has yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   What to do about the Afghans, who arrived in Britain on Feb. 6
and spent four uncertain days aboard an Ariana Airlines Boeing 727
at Stansted Airport, has been a monthlong political headache for
the government. In the face of virulent anti-immigrant sentiment
from the political opposition and from a number of newspapers, the
home secretary, Jack Straw, vowed in February to rule on the asylum
requests personally. He would, he told Parliament, seek to ensure
that the Afghans left Britain ``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a written statement to Parliament on Wednesday, Straw
made it clear that it had not been a case of simply ejecting
unwanted people from the country. He had been obligated to consider
factors like the troubled domestic situation in Afghanistan, he
said, as well as the individual circumstances of each asylum
applicant.
</P>
<P>
   Having done that, Straw explained, he had decided to grant
political asylum to two men ``because I am satisfied that their
applications disclose a well-founded fear of persecution'' as set
out by the 1951 U.N. convention on refugees. The wife of one of the
men is to be given what is called exceptional leave to remain,
which means that her case will be reconsidered in four years; the
couple's child also will be allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 27 people he is ordering to leave the country, along
with five dependents, Straw said, ``I am not satisfied that they
have a well-founded fear of persecution by reason of their race,
religion, nationality or membership of a particular social group or
political opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, however, Straw is not forcing the 32 to return to
Afghanistan, where many have said they fear reprisals by the
repressive Taliban military government. Instead, he is trying to
find a third country that will accept them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He is saying that while their specific fears of persecution
are not well-grounded, the way the Taliban regime is at the moment
means that perhaps Afghanistan might not be the best place for
them,'' a spokesman for the home office said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the last year for which figures are available, 1,600
Afghans sought asylum in Britain, the spokesman said. Of those, 35
were granted asylum, 1,500 were granted exceptional leave to
remain, and 65 were told to leave the country. Asked why these
Afghans were not given exceptional leave to remain, as would-be
immigrants from Afghanistan usually are, the spokesman said,
``They're not being rewarded for being on that plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Straw said as much in his statement. ``In these cases,'' he
said, referring to the people he had decided to eject from the
country, ``I have decided that the public interest in deterring
future hijacks for the purposes of claiming asylum is a very strong
one and, therefore, I have decided that they should not be given
permission to stay in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The ejected Afghans will have the right to appeal the decision
when the government decides where to send them, the home office
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   When the jet landed in Britain after being hijacked on a
domestic flight from Kabul, the Afghan capital, it had about 170
people aboard. Of those passengers, 73 returned to Afghanistan on
Feb. 14, and two more have asked to return home. Fourteen people
have been charged with hijacking the plane, and six others and
their dependents, who are seeking asylum and are related to the 14,
have had their decisions postponed until criminal trials are held.
In eight additional cases, Straw said, he needs more information
before he can reach a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Lord Avebury, a Liberal Democrat, condemned
the government's treatment of the Afghans and said that the
circumstances of their arrival in Britain should have no bearing on
whether they were allowed to remain here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home secretary doesn't have to adjust our asylum policy to
the demands of the gutter tabloids,'' Avebury told the House of
Lords. ``The reception given to these people, and their treatment
since, has been not only inefficient and inhumane, but probably
unlawful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
