<HEADER>
A3585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-BRAVES-ROCKER-NYT     03-01 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-ROCKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER'S SUSPENSION CUT BACK BY ARBITRATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball's arbitrator Wednesday slashed by about two-thirds
Commissioner Bud Selig's suspension of John Rocker, the Atlanta
Braves pitcher who in a magazine interview had disparaged
foreigners, gays and members of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means that Rocker can begin spring training
immediately and he was to report Thursday to the Braves' camp in
Lake Buena Vista, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Selig had suspended Rocker for a total of 73 days, all 45 days
of spring training and the first four weeks of the season. But the
arbitrator, Shyam Das, cut in half, to two weeks, the in-season
part of the suspension. And he eliminated the remainder of the
spring training suspension, ending Rocker's exile at 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   Das also virtually eliminated the $20,000 fine that Selig
levied, reducing it to $500, which the Players Association
contended was the most Rocker could be fined under the collective
bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, at first glance, would seem to be a sharp rebuke to
Selig. In a statement, the commissioner said: ``I disagree with the
decision of arbitrator Das. It does not reflect any understanding
of or sensitivity to the importance social responsibility that
baseball, an institution that has endured for more than 100 years,
has to the public. It completely ignores the sensibilities of those
groups of people maligned by Mr. Rocker and disregards the player's
position as a role model for children.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Players Association, which had filed a grievance
challenging the commissioner's action, contended from the start
that the heavy suspension and fine were more for public relations
effect. The penalty was levied, a union lawyer said, ``with an eye
toward the arbitration process.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker must still undergo counseling, which Selig ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Although Das issued no written opinion with his decision, it
apparently was based largely on actions taken by commissioners in
the past. Some baseball officials felt Das' decision at least
upheld the commissioner's right to suspend a player for speech. The
Players Association had argued that the suspension was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time an arbitrator has reduced or
overturned a commissioner's disciplinary action against a player.
Baseball's drug history is filled with similar arbitration
decisions. Steve Howe, LaMarr Hoyt, Pascual Perez, Willie Wilson
and Ferguson Jenkins were among the beneficiaries of those
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Howe, for example, was suspended for life in June, 1992,
following another in a series of drug incidents, but the following
November an arbitrator ordered him reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the success of Rocker's appeal was the testimony of Scott
Sanderson, a former major league pitcher. Called as a witness at
the two-day hearing Feb. 10, Sanderson talked about the importance
of major league spring training to a major league pitcher. Selig
had said Rocker could begin participating in extended spring
training and/or with the Braves minor league teams April 3.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Sanderson said, among other things, he
testified about the significance of facing in exhibition games the
caliber of hitters a pitcher will see during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a pitcher's out there and you're facing competition you
know you're going to be facing during the season,'' Sanderson said,
``you deal with the aspect of adrenaline kicking in and what
adrenaline will do to cause your body to react in ways it otherwise
wouldn't. You push yourself, your body reacts differently. If you
don't have any of that in the spring, the very first time you're
called on a game and ask your body to react it can't the way you
want it to. And you take a chance on getting hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator's ruling prompted some criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Boazman, an Atlanta city councilman, who testified at
the hearing, issued a statement, saying, ``Hate and bigotry and
homophobia and racism have a place, evidently, and that place is in
major league baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
