<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3587 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VIDEO-GAMES-NYT &LR;      03-01 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIDEO-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL MEDIA MAY BE EVOLVING INTO ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As entertainment, it has faced its share of criticism: that it
is all technological gimmickry, a useless diversion for people with
nothing better to do than sit for hours in front of a screen.
</P>
<P>
   A movie screen, that is. For that is how some critics described
the fledgling motion picture industry at the turn of the last
century. But by the 1920s, movies were being seriously discussed as
an art form. And the discussion hasn't stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Are video games, now at the quarter-century mark themselves, at
the same crossroads, between developing into a widely appreciated
art and remaining an amusement for a select group? Henry Jenkins,
director of the comparative media studies program at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, would say they are. Jenkins
has spent 15 years studying the cultural and historical
relationships among film, television and, more recently, digital
media. At a recent conference on the future of video games he
organized at MIT, he proposed that the time had come to discuss
video games as an important art form.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins argues that this digital pastime will soon shake off its
label as a diversion for adolescent boys. In 1999, according to the
Interactive Digital Software Association, about 69 percent of PC
gamers and 54 percent of console game users were 18 or older. Women
accounted for 43 percent of PC video game players, a bigger
percentage than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is already recognized in terms of money. It was a
$6.1 billion business last year, up from $5.5 billion the previous
year and almost double what it was in 1995. According to the
software association, the day is not long off when money spent on
video games will be on a par with money spent on movie tickets.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, domestic box office revenues totaled $7.3 billion,
while video game software sales brought in $6.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Jenkins says, it is time to give Pokemon, Super Smash
Brothers and Spyro the Dragon _ three of the best-selling games of
the last year _ some respect for their aesthetic and cultural
value.
</P>
<P>
   As a media researcher, Jenkins has only to look at his students,
the first generation of adults who grew up playing video games, to
see the influence of Pac-Man and Frogger. Ten years ago, most of
his students wanted to direct films. ``Right now, he said, ``more
of them are interested in being game designers than movie makers.''
They discuss game strategy ``the way a decade ago students were
talking about David Lynch or Peter Greenaway.''
</P>
<P>
   But many things need to happen before video games reach the same
artistic level of movies, Jenkins said. Like video games, many of
the first movies revolved around action _ car chases, pratfalls and
pies in the face. But cinema quickly ``developed a sense of the
richness of its own formula,'' Jenkins said, something the digital
medium is still struggling with. Human emotion, for example, is
still limited in games to expressions like the grunt of the
football player who fumbles or the yelp of joy of a warrior who
captures the enemy flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rarely play a video game that makes me cry,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Other aesthetic improvements might be easier to achieve. Music,
which is now used as little more than background noise in games,
will be used to provide tension, much as it does in movies. When a
group of Jenkins' students presented a 30-minute montage of video
game clips at the conference, it felt a lot like a movie trailer,
complete with operatic soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the measure of whether video games have come of age is
how deeply they have embedded themselves in our culture. The
students presented game clips that traced the evolution of video
games through games that included Pong and Myst. The clips began
with the plain text ``you are standing in an open field west of a
white house,'' the opening line of the Zork I text adventure game,
circa 1981. The phrase elicited the same nostalgic murmuring from
the audience that the words ``a long time ago, in a galaxy far, far
away'' would from film enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   The grip that video games and their characters have on their
fans mirrors the way movies and their stars mesmerize their
audiences. Just as Clara Bow was proclaimed the first silver screen
star to have ``it,'' or sex appeal, Tomb Raider's Lara Croft is the
``it'' girl of the digital age.
</P>
<P>
   But where are the German Expressionists of the game world? And
the Charlie Chaplins? And can game creators overcome the inherent
repetition in their work, perhaps through advances in artificial
intelligence?
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins talks about creating a critical vocabulary to discuss
these questions. Right now, the only term he sees in that lexicon
is ``violence,'' a word that was often linked to video games in the
wake of the Columbine High School shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the predominant story out there today about this form,
whether or not this game or that game is violent,'' said Jenkins,
one of the few defenders of video games at a hearing on Capitol
Hill last spring. ``There is a huge universe of important questions
that need to be addressed about this medium precisely because of
its economic importance, its cultural importance, its social
importance. If the only articles ever written about cinema were
`all movies are violent,' we would think the critics, the
journalists, had missed something that was vital about the
emergence of that form.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' point is that sociologists might find more to study in
video games than a possible link to aggressive behavior. Geoffrey
Goldstein, a psychology professor at the University of Utrecht in
the Netherlands who has studied video games, said at the conference
that video play was not a sport for loners because even if people
don't play together, they discuss playing with friends. It turns
out to be not just a phenomenon among competitive little boys,
Goldstein said. In a study in which he asked women in a nursing
home to play video games, he soon found them bragging about their
Tetris scores every day over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will be the grandmothers who pull gaming into the
circle of social respectability and push newspapers to review games
alongside films and television shows on their culture pages.
Without some helping hand, the games could just as easily go the
way of comic books, which came of age in the 1920s. They are
another popular entertainment, but they have never expanded their
niche market much beyond the backs of adolescent boys' closets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1828EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TAYLOR-DANCE-REVIEW-A     03-01 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAYLOR-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL TAYLOR TICKLES EYES AND EARS, SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most popular choreographer working today is Paul
Taylor. He needs no guest stars to fill a house, and his wide
appeal to a general theater audience does not run counter to the
seriousness of his enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, Taylor dances are often fun. But those that are fun
are always complex as well. To be accessible and obscure at the
same time takes some doing, and the success of a Taylor work is in
its several layers of meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The gala evening that opened the Paul Taylor Dance Company's
two-week season at City Center on Tuesday night included an
unabashed crowd pleaser, Taylor's brilliant essay on the tango
without tango steps, ``Piazzolla Caldera.'' The piece was served up
as a treat for the gala and will not be repeated during the run.
But here, as in the rest of the program (``Company B'' and
``Arabesque,'' which had its New York premiere) there were several
options for the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabesque,'' which is one of Taylor's most intriguing pieces
on a formal level, can be appreciated at face value. It is highly
pleasing to the eye and ear, especially in its use of musical
selections from Debussy. The imagery suggests one of Taylor's
musings on the antiquity of his imagination; it has a familiar
ritualized aspect with occasionally archaic postures.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the work's deepest values lie in its
experiments with structure, extraordinary speed and music.
</P>
<P>
   That Taylor is one of modern dance's most musical choreographers
is a given. Never one to follow a beat, he avoids two fashionable
extremes: to ignore the score or to illustrate it.
</P>
<P>
   To play with music is not enough for him. He reveals, rather,
its hidden aspects or translates it into unexpected stage images.
More than anyone else Taylor tells us what many musicians do not
like to hear: that music is transformed by dance.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has heard the turbulent side of Debussy's music here. The
flute solo, ``Syrinx,'' has been used by many choreographers, and
its plaintive poetic sound has a darker subtext for Taylor. The
idea of Syrinx, the nymph changed into a reed to escape Pan's
amorous advances, is a good springboard for Taylor's surprising but
related image of a figure straining for release. Sylvia Nevjinsky,
the witchlike outsider in ``Arabesque,'' gives a solo of
clenched-fist tension a superb dramatic quality. She is a spirit
trapped inside a body that is not hers.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening ensemble, danced to the Scherzo from the String
Quartet in G minor, Nevjinsky puts her hands over Michael
Trusnovec's eyes. Blinded like Oedipus, he gropes his way on stage,
arms held forward. In the fifth section the Scherzo is replayed
with the same ensemble choreography but now it is Trusnovec who
blinds Nevjinsky, who also gropes her way off.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has said that he did not start out with a scenario but
wished to see where the music would take him. He is not the only
choreographer to have form generate content, and one can accept his
claim insofar as the music has colored the dynamics of his usual
idiom.
</P>
<P>
   That coloration is more powerful than moments that recall other
pieces in the Taylor archaic style, like ``Runes'' and ``Images.''
In those works one sacrificial victim replaces another.
``Arabesque,'' whose title refers to one of the musical pieces and
a decorative design, reduces the ritual replacement to two people
and suggests a less universal cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario that supposedly does not exist is something of a
weakness. Aside from the reversal between Nevjinsky and her victim,
the blinded blinding the blinder does not really tell us love is
blind. Revenge is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the music led him Taylor has come up with a neatly
packaged work, and its virtues are choreographic. It is unusual
that while the Scherzo is played twice, he does not run the
choreography backward the second time. Taylor likes to create the
equivalent of word games, and you have to look fast to see how
asymmetrical his changing patterns are throughout the ensembles.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Tipton's lighting creates a wondrous darkened space for
a royal cast. Santo Loquasto has costumed Heather Berest, Maureen
Mansfield, Annmaria Mazzini and Nevjinsky as little princesses in
gowns and tiaras, fugitives from Martha Graham's Greek pieces. Andy
LeBeau, Ted Thomas, Orion Duckstein and the marvelous Trusnovec are
bare-chested in tattered pedal pushers. Most of the choreography
has a familiar curved-arm look, but its signature is new: an
especially swift series of little leaps. Part skip, part stag leap
with knee bent up and other leg extended, this motor motif expands
into larger jumps that send the dancers flying across the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Nevjinsky, rotating her shoulders, locks into the fist-down
position that will later begin her solo. The second and third
sections, ``Reverie'' and ``Arabesque No. 2,'' usher in a playful
ensemble. Two dancers follow two more while crawling in a squat.
There is a sensuous tinge in the hip-thrusting silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Syrinx'' Nevjinsky, more intense than we have seen her,
stamps, tumbles, rotates her pelvis and ends in the flexed-wrist,
knee-up pose in front that is a recurring sculptural image.
</P>
<P>
   The company is in fine form and Francie Huber is stronger than
ever as the woman without a man in ``Piazzolla Caldera.'' Richard
Chen See and LeBeau are fine acrobatic drunks while Lisa Viola and
Patrick Corbin remain astounding in their convoluted encounter.
They make difficult partnering look like pure passion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
