<HEADER>
A3589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY02-COX     03-01 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENIOR CITIZENS FREEDOM TO WORK ACT PASSES HOUSE
 &HT;    By ANGEL WILSON and LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior citizens moved a giant step closer Wednesday
to being able to work without losing Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare show of unity for an issue involving change to the
Social Security system, the House voted 422-0 to repeal the Social
Security earnings test for those between 65 and 69. Currently, the
test reduces Social Security retirement benefits for workers in
that age group by $1 for every $3 they make above $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill does not affect people between 62 and 65 who
receive early Social Security benefits and continue to work. They
are penalized $1 for every $2 earned above $10,080.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the bill would take effect retroactively to Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   This Depression-era provision of the Social Security law was
designed to discourage the elderly from remaining in the work force
at a time of high unemployment. The limit has been gradually
increased and would have been raised to $30,000 by 2002. It does
not apply to those over age 70.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders indicated they would take up the bill soon, and
President Clinton has promised to sign the bill if it is sent to
him without extraneous provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the baby boomers begin to retire, it is more important than
ever that older Americans who are willing and able to work should
not have their Social Security benefits deferred when they do,''
Clinton said in a letter to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Repeal of the earnings limit may be the only substantive reform
to Social Security this year. Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., who
introduced the bill with Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, said it was a
matter of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earnings penalty affects over 800,000 hard-working seniors
each year, seniors who work because they have to, or they want
to,'' Shaw said. ``Regardless of their reasons for working, they
are losing Social Security benefits that they earned.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, said there was no longer a reason for the earnings test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in the world would we want to discourage any American,
whether they're 17 or 67, from working?'' he asked. ``Americans are
living longer now, and older Americans can work, they want to work
and they shouldn't be punished by an outdated law if they choose to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Groups representing the elderly hailed the bill's passage as
long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   AARP Executive Director Horace Deets called the bill ``good
labor, social and economic policy. At a time when labor shortages
loom on the horizon and people are living longer, we should
encourage, not penalize older workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra L. Butler, president of United Seniors Association,
called the bill ``great news for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The punitive nature of the earnings limit is obvious. By
itself, the earnings limit imposes a 33 percent marginal tax rate
on seniors. In combination with federal income and payroll taxes,
the earnings limit forces seniors to pay higher marginal rates than
millionaires. This is unconscionable,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   After years in which both political parties have preached the
need for Social Security reforms without coming close to agreeing
on a method, the easy repeal of the earnings test represented a
rare consensus. Still, each party accused the other of bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson criticized
Vice President Al Gore for not responding to a letter he sent on
Monday urging Gore to endorse the earnings test's elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton and Gore promised seniors they'd eliminate the Social
Security earnings limit in ... their 1992 book 'Putting People
First,' but it was really a case of 'Putting Promises First,' ``
Nicholson said. He noted that Clinton vetoed a Republican tax-cut
bill last year that included a provision to eliminate the earnings
test.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., released
a statement noting that Democrats have supporting the Clinton
administration's call for repealing the earnings test as part of a
more comprehensive Social Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said the GOP plan to eliminate the earnings test last
year also would have raided the Social Security trust fund to pay
for a $700 billion 10-year tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Wilson's e-mail address is angelw(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
