<HEADLINE>
`THE WAITING GAME': THE VERY BEST TIP: GO OUT AND GET A NEW JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Self-absorption is the primary characteristic of the
30-somethings who inhabit ``The Waiting Game.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Ken Liotti, who wrote the screenplay with
Kirk Lavine, plays like an 81-minute sitcom, which means that the
tone is light, the material is overly familiar, the execution is
unsurprising and frequently dependent on shtick, and many of the
characters occupy only one dimension. The cast nevertheless is
appealing, and when good fortune in career or romance eventually
befalls some of the characters, their happiness is the viewer's
reward for tolerating their unremitting egocentricity.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those waiting in ``The Waiting Game'' are waiting for
roles as actors, and while they wait, they wait on tables at a
Manhattan restaurant called Peter's Backyard, one of those places
that will seem familiar to anyone who has ever hurried through
dinner on the West Side in the mid-40s to make an 8 o'clock
Broadway curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Among the aspiring actors at work in the restaurant is the
oft-rejected Lenny (Will Arnett), who likes to quote Jack
Nicholson: ``Everybody gets their shot. You just have to be
ready.'' But his longtime girlfriend, Merris (Debbon Ayer), who has
a career in business, is growing weary of the life he leads. Andi
(Terumi Matthews), one of the waiters, understands Lenny. They can
and do say anything to each other, but they share a rule against
romance with actors: too much career jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Dan (Daniel Riordan), the hunk of ham who looks like a Greek
god, is nearly at the breaking point while waiting for a break and
is bedeviled by one of those diners whose instructive way of
ordering drives him to inner fury. Joe (Dwight Ewell), who is black
and gay, and Derek (Eddie Malavarca), who suffers from impotence
and confusion about his sexual identity, fall into the
one-dimensional category.
</P>
<P>
   While Andi becomes involved with a construction worker whose
sexual fidelity she is hired to test and Lenny and Merris break up
and Dan mounts a squirmingly pretentious one-man show and later
erupts into an Etna-like tantrum at an audition, the movie eyes its
characters and the city around them with affection and
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Waiting Game,'' their ordinary lives have become an
ordinary film.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE WAITING GAME
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ken Liotti; written by Kirk Lavine and Liotti; music
by Jim Farmer; production designer, Sonya Gropman; produced by
Mirjam Goldberg and Liotti; released by Seventh Arts Releasing.
Running time: 81 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Will Arnett (Lenny), Debbon Ayer (Merris), Dwight Ewell
(Joe), Eddie Malavarca (Derek), Terumi Matthews (Andi), Michael
Raynor (Franco) and Daniel Riordan (Dan).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
