<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS QUESTION CLAIM THAT OIL PRICES WILL DROP   SOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson withstood a
grilling from lawmakers over high oil prices Wednesday, as
legislators scorned his cautious forecast that oil-exporting
countries would increase production later this month and end a
year-long steep hike in fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, testifying before the House International Relations
Committee, rejected calls from lawmakers to quickly draw down
emergency government oil stocks, although he indicated _ as
President Clinton did on Tuesday _ that that option is still ``on
the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration is inching closer to dipping into the
600-million barrel Strategic Petroleum Reserve in Louisiana and
Texas for the first time since the Persian Gulf War, but Richardson
cautioned prudence while talks were underway with OPEC countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm guardedly optimistic that OPEC will increase production
when it meets on March 27,'' Richardson said. He noted that the
Mexican oil minister said Wednesday in Paris that he favored a
production increase. Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Venezuela are also
considering increases.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers, especially those from the Northeast, Midwest and
California, said the agreements to consider production increases
that Richardson brokered on a recent trip to six oil-producing
countries were vague and nonbinding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill, you came back with nothing,'' said Rep. Donald A.
Manzullo, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even if OPEC boosts production at its March meeting,
it will be too late to address soaring home-heating oil prices now.
``We're running out of time,'' said Rep. William Delahunt, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why has the administration sat idly by?'' asked Rep. Benjamin
Gilman, R-N.Y., who heads the committee. Gilman announced that he
would introduce legislation that would bar military aid to any
oil-exporting country involved in price fixing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open the spigot,'' said Rep. Sam Gedjenson of Connecticut, the
ranking Democrat on the panel.
</P>
</TEXT>
