<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, March 2 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-EARNINGS (Washington) _ The House voted 422-0 on
Wednesday to allow most Social Security recipients for the first
time to earn as much money as they want without sacrificing any of
their retirement benefit, repealing a Depression-era policy
intended to discourage older people from holding jobs so younger
people would have a chance. The unanimous vote was a rare display
of bipartisanship in the House, and reflected a consensus that the
earnings limits placed on Social Security recipients had long since
become counterproductive. The Senate is expected to take up a
similar measure soon, and President Clinton has said he would sign
the legislation. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT15.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-SHOT (Mount Morris Township, Mich.) _ A look at the life
circumstances of the 6-year-old who killed a first-grade classmate.
The county prosecutor says he came from a ``flophouse'' and used a
stolen gun he found there. By David Barboza. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   NY-BUSH-PATAKI (New York) _ With George W. Bush's convincing
victories in North Dakota, Washington and Virginia on Tuesday, the
governor of Texas turned yesterday to New York, hoping that the
vote in that state next Tuesday will help him finally nail down a
nomination that has eluded him through a frustrating six weeks of
contests. Bush, though, is not the only governor with a lot riding
on next Tuesday's vote, and that became abundantly clear on
Wednesday as Gov. George Pataki's apparatus lumbered to life,
trying to assure that Pataki does not join the list of Republican
governors who have failed Bush during his difficult political year.
By Adam Nagourney and Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-OUTLOOK (Cincinnati) _ Confronted by Bill Bradley's
humiliating loss in Washington state on Tuesday, many Democrats,
including some of his supporters, said Wednesday that he has no
chance of snatching his party's presidential nomination from Vice
President Al Gore. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-U.S. (Washington) _ When President Clinton pledged earlier
this week to block a German finance ministry official from assuming
the top post at the International Monetary Fund, in effect vetoing
the man the 15-nation European Union had collectively chosen to for
the job, he seemed to risk a diplomatic confrontation across the
Atlantic. What really happened, Clinton administration officials
and some European diplomats say, is that Clinton agreed to confront
Germany in a way that European countries applauded but were
unwilling to do themselves. By Joseph Kahn
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-REBELS (Dobrosin, Yugoslavia) _ Just across the
boundary line from Kosovo, guarded more visibly now by American
troops in watchtowers, armed Albanians wearing uniforms of a new
branch of the Kosovo Liberation Army are training for a battle the
West doesn't want them to have. Their numbers and leadership are a
mystery, but on this day fewer than 20 men, wearing a mixture of
German and American fatigues, did exercises in a muddy field with
their weapons, including a heavy machine gun on a tripod. On their
arms, they wear a cloth badge of red, black and yellow that looks
exactly like that of the supposedly disbanded and disarmed Kosovo
Liberation Army. The only difference is their name: the Liberation
Army of Presevo, Medvedja and Bujanovac, all towns in Serbia
itself, although their populations are largely ethnic Albanian. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
