<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT &LR;      03-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYDNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `ELEKTRA' TO ELECTRIC, THRONGS COME OUT IN SYDNEY MARDI GRAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN SHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ This city's summer festival season opened to
the conventional crescendos of grand opera and will close Saturday
with a three-hour gay and lesbian parade.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of performances by Vladimir Ashkenazy, Philip
Glass, the Netherlands Dance Theater, the Royal Court Theater and
30 other mainstream performers, the city's gays have taken over
with a three-week Mardi Gras, a collection of 130 diverse events
including body piercing and concerts by performers in drag.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted the city's Anglican and Roman Catholic archbishops
to issue a joint statement last week denouncing the celebration as
``an exercise in gross exhibitionism that promotes a homosexual
lifestyle and does not merit our presence or support.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Mardi Gras, David McLachlan, replied that
he was raised as a Catholic and that for him ``it was sad to see
how out of touch these church leaders are in helping people deal
with their sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   For the mainstream Sydney Festival, which ended Jan. 31, about
130,000 tickets were sold, bringing in $2 million, and a million or
more other spectators attended free concerts and exhibits. A light
show bathed the sail-shaped roof of the Sydney Opera House with
kaleidoscopic colors each night.
</P>
<P>
   The Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras, which has a budget of about $3
million, has brought in some $750,000 in theater and party tickets,
and about 250,000 people attended free events, said its general
manager, Mark Goggin.
</P>
<P>
   About 600,000 spectators are expected to line the 2-mile
downtown route to watch the 200 floats and 6,000 costumed
participants in the festival's finale Saturday. Television and
Internet rights to the parade, including live and recorded
coverage, have been sold in Australia, the United States and Europe
for a total of $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is bursting with crowd-attracting festivities this year.
The Summer Olympics, which start here Sept. 15, will have their own
cultural festival.
</P>
<P>
   During the Sydney Festival the Berlin State Opera's high-energy
production of Richard Strauss' ``Elektra'' filled a 2,000-seat
theater at premium prices, said the festival's director, Leo
Schofield. The Netherlands Dance Theater was another box-office
success, and the London production of ``The Weir'' by the Irish
writer Conor McPherson was sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Three local plays gave the festival some Australian flavor. In
``Small Poppies'' Geoffrey Rush depicted a 5-year-old's first day
at school. Six untitled sketches presented by Daniel Keene and
Arielle Taylor recalled the Beckett style, with bleak urban tales
played in half-light. ``The Sunshine Club'' was a feel-good musical
about interracial dating and dancing in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield said Sydney's January season of music and drama, which
he has directed for three years, was similar in some ways to the
Lincoln Center Festival. An added attraction is this city's 25-year
tradition of free evening concerts in the Domain, a 100-acre
downtown park ringed with giant fig trees. About 80,000 people
turned out with hampers and wine for an 11-group night of jazz; a
Sydney Symphony Orchestra program of undemanding favorites,
including the ``Tannhauser'' and ``1812'' Overtures, attracted
about 140,000 under a full moon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the major event of the Sydney Festival was an exhibition
of 242 drawings of the human figure, ``Michelangelo to Matisse,''
which was held over through Tuesday so more people could view it.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Mardi Gras has evolved from a kind of civil rights
march to an Australian institution that bills itself as the world's
largest gay carnival. This year's program emphasizes spectacle and
sponsors more than it does slogans, although social concerns
underlie the frills and frivolity.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Mardi Gras, including the Council of Churches, oppose
the increasing involvement of public institutions like Sydney's
main museum. The museum has organized an exhibition of body art
that is considered the festival's most controversial event.
</P>
<P>
   Some activists regard the criticism as a remnant of intolerance.
Tony Knight, a longtime Mardi Gras participant who supervises the
acting program at the National Institute of Dramatic Art, said:
``Mardi Gras has become an institution, but it remains a political
statement. Rights have been won, but there is no cause for
complacency. Prejudice still exists.''
</P>
<P>
   The glossy 140-page Mardi Gras catalog, paid for by sponsors in
the travel, media and liquor businesses, lists camp comedy,
feminist concerts, ``queer culture, soft-porn exhibitionism, artful
bad taste,'' social satire, sidewalk painting and plays with
messages from the gay world's frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   The 5,000 Americans visiting Sydney for the festival will see
some familiar acts, among them New Yorkers like Lypsinka, the drag
diva, and Patty Chang, a performance artist, as well as Randall
Wong, a male soprano from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   All this, taken in laconic stride, seems remote from the Sydney
of 1978, when homosexuality was illegal here (with penalties
ranging to 14 years in prison). Demanding changes in the law, about
1,000 gay Sydney men staged a a street demonstration that year.
Police officers arrested 53 of the marchers, but the courts
dismissed the charges. The protest developed into an annual rally
in a campaign that led to decriminalization of homosexuality in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, a multilingual melting pot of immigrant cultures, is now
considered a notably tolerant city. ``Inclusivity through
diversity'' is the buzz phrase here and the theme chosen this year
by the Mardi Gras artistic director, Jonathan Parsons.
</P>
<P>
   Still, acceptance of Mardi Gras is far from unanimous.
Australia's prime minister, John Howard, declined to issue a
message of support for the celebration. But Sydney politicians
praise the carnival for contributing to acceptance and harmony, not
to mention generating about $60 million for the city's economy this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
