<P>
   Extensive Genealogy Package With a Focus on Ellis Island
</P>
<P>
   With all the major home genealogy programs providing users with
baskets of historical records on multiple CD-ROMs, it seems the
only thing missing in the box these days is Ellis Island itself.
Sierra Home's Generations Family Tree Millennium Collection fills
that particular bill with an extensive collection of data from the
Ellis Island station, including immigrant records, census images
and ship's passenger lists. The company says the package is ``the
first compendium of Ellis Island information available to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics from the Department of the Interior, 40
percent of Americans can trace an ancestor back to Ellis Island,
making it almost a virtual ground zero of U.S. immigration.
</P>
<P>
   To help educate users on the topic, the Millennium Collection
package includes an hourlong video called ``Remembering Ellis
Island, Everyman's Monument,'' with Telly Savalas as host, and a
multimedia virtual tour of the Ellis Island experience.
</P>
<P>
   The package contains a book, ``American Naturalization Records
1790-1990,'' and a search engine programmed for hunting down
genealogy information on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The program contains a total of 21 CD-ROMs, including Civil War
muster rolls, the Social Security Index and landowner records.
</P>
<P>
   The Millennium Collection, which offers access to a total of
three billion names, runs on Windows 95 or 98 and is expected to
cost $69.95. The program can be ordered online at
www.sierrahome.com or by telephone at (800) 757-7707, or purchased
in software stores.
</P>
<P>
   The software lets users create their own family trees with
drag-and-drop editing and compile an index of relatives. An
image-editing program for touching up scanned copies of old family
photographs is provided. Also included _ for those who may have had
a relative on that big boat _ is the passenger list from the
Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL ARRANGEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of online travel arrangements has more than
doubled in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey of 811 executives by the research firm
Greenfield On-line, 24 percent made hotel reservations online, up
from 9 percent six months ago. Airline bookings online went to 28
percent from 13 percent, and online car rentals were up to 19
percent from 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FAST AND FASTER
</P>
<P>
   Fast food just got a little faster. Five McDonald's restaurants
in Southern California will now allow motorists with E-ZPass-type
transponders to order and pick up their Big Macs without stopping
to pay.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
