<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DOUBLECLICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOUBLECLICK DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet is an extraordinary tool for two-way communication.
Companies that wish to sell or exchange a user's personal
information ought to take advantage of this capability to get prior
approval from the person involved.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has gained in importance since the DoubleClick company
purchased the databases of Abacus Direct, which has the ability to
access 2 billion catalog-sales transactions. DoubleClick planned to
combine this with its own proprietary information, gained from
``cookies'' embedded in computers during visits to Web sites. The
result would be detailed consumer profiles that would be valuable
to Internet advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The Abacus database comes with millions of names attached.
Privacy advocates believe with good reason that, combined with the
DoubleClick data, companies would get a powerful tool to discover a
person's buying habits and any other information that could be
gleaned from their visits to Web sites. The Federal Trade
Commission is concerned enough to begin an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC and the advocates are right to worry. While DoubleClick
has yet to deploy its vast resources, the potential for abuse is
great. People with cancer might not want their insurance companies
or employers to know they have visited Web sites that discuss
treatment options. That is an extreme case, but even more routine
uses are troubling.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick spokeswoman Jennifer Blum says the company is trying
to make it easy for users to opt out. But the process it currently
uses encourages computer users to read a 730-word legal notice,
then switch to DoubleClick's own Web site, where they must scan a
294-word explanation of cookies before they can hit the opt-out
command. They ought to be able to do this with one click.
</P>
<P>
   Blum also says that DoubleClick will not include any information
on a person's health, finances, or anything of a sexual nature in
its advertising profiles. That's all to the good, but DoubleClick's
competitors, not in the spotlight, may not be as scrupulous.
</P>
<P>
   Blum also compares the collation of Internet data with the sale
of magazine subscription files to mail-order companies. But
direct-mail campaigns are a blunderbuss approach to advertising
compared to the finely honed approaches offered by Internet data
profiles. And consumer interaction with direct-mail solicitors is
far harder than the instant responses to DoubleClick and its
competitors over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   People throughout the Internet industry are concerned about the
privacy problem. The World Wide Web Consortium, which has an office
at MIT, is devising a compromise solution. Under this plan, people
would get a questionnaire in which they could specify the level of
Web privacy they prefer. Sites would automatically adjust their
information-gathering to an individual's level of comfort.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is not yet finalized, but in its latest version, people
would get this questionnaire only when they get a new Internet
Explorer or Netscape Navigator browser or upgrade the browser
program. This would leave millions of people, who are happy with
their existing browser, in privacy limbo.
</P>
<P>
   People who use the Internet deserve more comprehensive
protections. DoubleClick and other companies need only apply
technology widely available on the seamier side of the Web.
Whenever someone visits a pornographic site, he or she is
confronted with a prominent message warning that this is only for
viewers age 18 and over and that users should click a box to
certify that they qualify. Similar messages on less lurid sites can
offer people a choice of whether they will receive e-mail
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies are useful files that allow easy shopping on the World
Wide Web. Amazon.com and other companies who use them to get to
know their customers better should not have to change their
policies. But when companies seek to consolidate cookie-based
information and sell the results, Web users need to be forewarned
and armed with an easily used tool that allows them to opt out.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Edward Markey, Democrat of Massachusetts, and
other members of Congress have filed legislation that will force
companies to adopt these protections. Rather than be compelled by
Congress, these businesses would be wise to settle on an
uncomplicated means to let people choose whether they want
information about themselves used for commercial gain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
