<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-JAIL-BOS &LR;      03-01 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-JAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM BYGONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By H.D.S. GREENWAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is only one wing left of the stucco-walled and red-roofed
jail that the French called the Maison Centrale when they built it
104 years ago. The rest _ like so much else in Hanoi _ has been
torn down to make room for the new. Rising behind this remnant of
things past stands a new high-rise office complex called Hanoi
Towers.
</P>
<P>
   There are no prisoners now in what is left of the jail.
Vietnamese called it the Hai Lo Prison, but the American pilots who
did time here during the Vietnam war called it the Hanoi Hilton.
For the Vietnamese this is a shrine to revolutionaries whom the
French imprisoned and sometimes guillotined. ``Kept in prison cells
with chain, bare-handed patriots and revolutionaries yet fought
against Draconian custody regime, harsh living, and savage
suppression by the French colony,'' a brochure informs visitors.
Only in passing is it mentioned that from Aug. 5, 1964, until March
31, 1973, American prisoners of war were held here, mistreated and
tortured by their Vietnamese captors _ the same ``harsh living and
savage suppression.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of John McCain, who was imprisoned here for
five years, but on the shore of a lake into which he fell there is
a plaque commemorating his capture.
</P>
<P>
   What is remarkable is not so much McCain's undoubted courage in
the face of such adversity _ he refused early release that he could
have obtained _ but his lack of bitterness and his generosity
toward the Vietnamese people. He was a leader in establishing
diplomatic relations between Vietnam and the United States after
the war.
</P>
<P>
   The American ambassador to Hanoi, Pete Peterson, who did 6 1/2
years in the Hanoi Hilton, likes to tell visitors that he ``cannot
do anything about what happened yesterday, but I have an obligation
to do something constructive tomorrow and in the next hour.'' For
Peterson, too, there is no time and no room for bitter memories.
The past is the little that is left of the jail, now a museum. The
future, albeit an architectural disaster, is a new Hanoi Hilton
which actually is a hotel, with tourists and businessmen for whom
this broken jail is but a passing curiosity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
