<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e       03-01 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOPER-NOVEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW NIGHTMARISH CHILDHOOD EVENTS BECAME A 5-BOOK SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: The Netherlands, Calif.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The world as Dennis Cooper sees it is not for the
faint of heart. Out there in his slacker suburbia, beautiful boys
with vacant eyes wander aimlessly before being sodomized, mutilated
and hacked to pieces with an ax. But there is little hysteria amid
the bloodshed. Cooper keeps it cool with prose that evokes reverent
sound bites like ``intensely lyrical,'' ``smart and nervy'' and
``revolutionary'' from enamored critics.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there are those who call his work pornographic and
antihomosexual, although the writer himself is gay. As Edmund White
wrote in The New York Times Book Review, ``This is the very stuff
of Jesse Helms' worst nightmares.'' He meant it as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Cooper and his work will be the subject of a
scholarly discussion at New York University in Fales Library, which
houses his archives. The symposium continues Thursday with an
exhibition of Cooper's papers and a reading by friends, including
the writer Bret Easton Ellis, the painter Robert Gober and Thurston
Moore, the bassist of Sonic Youth. The event coincides with the
publication of ``Period'' (Grove Press), the final book of the
``quintology'' that began in 1989 with ``Closer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find Dennis' work to be some of the most exciting around,''
said Marvin Taylor, the library's director. ``The subject matter is
very, very difficult in that he tackles the aesthetic conundrum
that exists between the sheer beauty of the writing and the books'
content. Dennis brings us constantly to the moments of the
ineffable: love, desire, death, beauty. It is amazingly brilliant
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, 47, has spent half a lifetime translating the
unspeakable into being. ``Ever since I was a kid, I've sort of
found this area that was haunting and confusing and riveting and
frightening,'' he said in a telephone interview from his home in
Los Angeles. ``That's one of the reasons I started writing.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Arcadia, Calif., attended public school until the
eighth-grade, then transferred to a boys' school where, at 15, he
stumbled upon ``The 120 Days of Sodom'' by the Marquis de Sade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge influence,'' he said, recalling how the work
excited him into writing his own version. ``When I read Sade and
saw there was a piece of serious literature that dealt with these
issues that was brilliant, really intelligent and full of
philosophical rigor, it was quite a moment with me. I thought,
`This stuff can be literature and not just porn.'''
</P>
<P>
   After forsaking college on the advice of a writing teacher,
Cooper spent his 20s and early 30s writing short stories, essays
and poetry in Los Angeles and New York, discovering the films of
Robert Bresson along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found my voice when I saw him,'' he said. ``I had an
incredibly strong response because of the ways in which the work is
very controlled and meticulous. I saw how I could write about these
incredibly deep things and do it in a way that is acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 Cooper moved to Amsterdam in the Netherlands in pursuit
of love and, he acknowledged, to rid himself of a drug habit. There
he wrote ``Closer,'' the cornerstone of the series, to be followed
over the next decade by ``Try,'' ``Guide,'' ``Frisk'' and finally
``Period.'' ``Closer'' earned him a substantial cult following, as
well as critical praise for his elegant prose and literary
lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a sense I wanted to do a series that would be one
work,'' he said. ``The actual structure was very calculated. This
one book would be slowly dismembered down to nothing, a kind of
stripping away of things. And everything had to be in `Closer' that
I would work with in the other novels. Each book formally would
reflect the damage caused in the content of the book before it.''
</P>
<P>
   With its themes of beauty, youth, death and desire wrapped in a
bloody dressing, ``Closer'' was the start of Cooper's attempt to
explain away his own childhood nightmares: the day, at 11, a friend
accidentally hit him on the head with an ax and abandoned him as he
bled; the time, at 13, three boys his age were found raped and
killed in mountains where he often hiked and camped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to find where it happened,'' he said. ``I made a whole
pilgrimage to the site. I thought it was terrifying, yet I was
completely fascinated.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the memory of George Miles, the painfully fragile
boy who appears throughout the series to torment his lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper met the real George when, as a sixth-grader, the boy
``freaked out'' on acid. ``I took him out to this field and I
talked to him,'' he said. ``We bonded over that and we became
really great friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Older than George by several years, he assumed the role of
caretaker in their relationship, which, depending on the state of
George's mental health, fluctuated wildly. ``He made me realize
this kind of tendency to want to save people,'' Cooper said. ``He
also physically defined the kind of people I'm attracted to. I was
writing the books for him. Then I moved to Amsterdam and lost
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later he returned in search of George, only to learn
that he had shot himself in 1987. In ``Period'' the character
George departs Cooper's fictional world as a suicide and returns as
a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   That his work should be relegated to the porn, gay fiction or
even horror sections in bookstores is something he still finds
startling. Some readers, he said, ``either turn it into something
by Stephen King or they denude it as just so much extraneous
psychological disorder. As for the gay thing, I find that
definition incredibly reductive for people like myself who feel
alienated from gay culture and its mindless hedonism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when you write about this subject matter,'' he
added, ``it's so glaring and blinding that readers can't always see
what's really there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
