A3613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STRIKES-FILM-REVIEW-N     03-01 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIKES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`3 STRIKES': AN EX-CON ON THE RUN, DUCKING BULLETS AND JOKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a scenario in which a young black man, just freed from
the penitentiary for the second time, haplessly stumbles into a
situation that, thanks to the popularity of ``three strikes and
you're out'' laws, could put him on ice forever. He must
simultaneously try to prove his innocence and evade the police and
the angry criminals who come after him. In the hands of a director
like Charles Burnett or Sidney Lumet, this story might yield a
rich, tense psychological thriller rippling with righteous
political anger. It would have everything going for it:
Hitchcockian suspense, heart-swelling melodrama, and up-to-the
minute social relevance.
</P>
<P>
   None of which has anything to do with ``3 Strikes,'' which
elects to play this potential tragedy as farce. ``3 Strikes'' is
directed by D.J. Pooh, a co-writer of the screenplay for the first
``Friday'' movie who clearly wants to cash in on the success of
that film and its lesser sequel. There is a decent hip-hop-driven
score, with a title track (performed by Snoop Doggy Dogg) that
should insure big sales for the soundtrack album. There is also a
clever, fairly recondite blaxploitation reference, to ``Truck
Turner,'' a 1974 picture starring Isaac Hayes as a bounty hunter on
the run from an assortment of bad guys. And ``3 Strikes'' shares
with ``Friday'' (though not with ``Next Friday'') an easygoing,
affectionate sense of place _ South Central Los Angeles, in case
you hadn't heard.
</P>
<P>
   But ``3 Strikes'' is definitely a second-string effort, compared
with which even the pathetic last third of ``Next Friday'' looks
like something out of Ernst Lubitsch, or at least Mel Brooks. Once
he dreamed up his story, D.J. Pooh decided to pad it out with a
series of comic situations so tired you can almost hear them snore.
Come to think of it, the loud snoring of drunken old men _ to say
nothing of the amusing guttural and gastric noises they continually
emit _ is one of the film's prized comic devices, as are the
uncontrollable lust of a fat woman, a gunshot wound in a man's
buttock, and the observation that policemen are fond of doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Running, scrambling and pratfalling through this mess is Brian
Hooks, who plays Rob Douglas, a young man who seems to have been
sent to jail for being unbelievably annoying and who has apparently
been paroled for the same reason. When the friend who was supposed
to pick him up is detained by an unexpected lap dance (don't ask),
Rob ends up in a stolen car on the Harbor Freeway. There follows a
shootout with the police, and Rob, who only wants to see his parole
officer, his family, and his sullen girlfriend, Juanita (N'Bushe
Wright), soon finds that he is Los Angeles County's most famous
fugitive, the elusive Freeway Gunman.
</P>
<P>
   There is some real possibility for knockabout satire here,
almost all of it squandered. Hooks seems to think that loosening
his neck muscles and bobbing his head around makes him an inspired
physical comedian. But he's more like someone who flunked out of
the Wayans Brothers slapstick academy. He is not helped by D.J.
Pooh's jokeless script, or by the plodding pace of the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``3 Strikes'' does have its moments, most of them supplied by
George Wallace as Rob's irascible father and David Alan Grier as a
dingbat LAPD detective. These men know how to be funny, even when
the material they're given fails to be. E40 also has an inspired
turn as Rob's protector, a sharp-dressing entrepreneur who speaks
entirely in mystical, freeform hip-hop poetry.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, ``3 Strikes'' feels like a very long
late-night comedy sketch that occasionally veers beyond
tastelessness toward something worse. The film's climax comes when
a crowd of police officers opens fire on an unarmed black man. Will
anyone, at the present moment, think this is funny?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `3 STRIKES'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by D.J. Pooh; director of photography, John
W. Simmons; edited by John Carter; music supervisors, Aaron
Anderson and Andrew Shack; production designer, Thomas Fichter;
produced by Marcus Morton; released by Metro Goldwyn Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 83 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``3 Strikes'' has been rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It features the energetic
use of obscenities and racial slurs, as well as occasional gunfire
and periodic flatulence.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Brian Hooks (Rob), N'Bushe Wright (Juanita), Faizon Love
(Tone), E40 (Mike), George Wallace (Pops), David Alan Grier
(Jenkins), De'Aundre Bonds (J.J.), Antonio Fargas (Uncle Jim),
Vincent Schiavelli (Cortino) and David Leisure (District
Attorney). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
