<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3625 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-R-CIR-3D-ROTATION-ART     03-01 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CIR-3D-ROTATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO TECHNOLOGY TO MAKE THE HEAD SPIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Resending to add art note.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching video images on the Internet is one of those computer
tasks with more next steps than a mambo. Viewers have long been
forced to download many programs with many levels to squint into
little windows on computer monitors to see smudgy, sputtering
shadows.
</P>
<P>
   But with steady improvements in streaming technologies, online
video is beginning to approach _ at best _ the outer edges of
television-quality video. And for the first time, video on the
Internet can do something television video cannot: permit viewers
to take a virtually step into moving pictures and change their
perspective on what they see as easily as if they were turning
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   This immersive, interactive video has already been used by
Superbowl.com and ESPN.com to stream 360-degree videos of
behind-the-scene action at the Super Bowl in January. More examples
may soon show up in baseball dugouts and concert seats.
</P>
<P>
   The technology that makes immersive video possible is being
advanced primarily by two companies, the Internet Pictures Corp.,
or iPIX, based in Oak Ridge, Tenn., and Palo Alto, Calif., and the
Be Here Corp., based in Cupertino, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   For years, computer users have been able to view still pictures
that took advantage of immersive technology on CD-ROMs and DVD
discs. Pictures taken with a fisheye lens and processed with
software that stitched together two 180-degree shots of a single
scene or object let viewers rotate a 360-degree panorama by simply
moving their mouse around over the picture.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's Technology, Entertainment and Design conference
in Monterey, Calif., iPIX unveiled its immersive application for
moving images. Called iPIX Movies, the technology permits users to
tilt and pan across the image through 360 degrees, looking left and
right, up and down without interrupting the flow of various moving
images.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown its incredible capabilities,'' said James
Phillips, iPIX's chairman and chief executive, speaking of his
company's new video technology. ``It captures everything. It is an
application that transports you into spaces where otherwise you
could not go.'' The iPIX technology can be used in digital video as
well as in traditional movie cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the company announced its first commercial
applications of iPIX movies, in a deal with Discovery Online and
the Hawaiian Visitor and Convention Bureau to produce interactive
movies of the Hawaiian islands.
</P>
<P>
   A preview of an iPIX movie showed a lush scene of a Hawaiian
waterfall shot from a helicopter high above. By moving a computer
mouse over the scene, the viewpoint smoothly shifted within the
movie and kept shifting as long as the mouse was moving.
</P>
<P>
   While the film clip was shot with a single camera using a small
new iPIX lens and camera, the scores of possible angles from which
to view the scene gave viewers the impression that the waterfall
had been photographed with dozens of cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the applications of what the company calls
360-by-360-degree video were almost endless. He said he could
easily imagine iPIX cameras being strapped to race cars or athletes
so viewers could get a first-person point of view. He also noted
that an iPIX camera could serve as an all-seeing security camera.
</P>
<P>
   (Phillips even suggested that if iPIX movies had been around at
the time of President John F. Kennedy's assassination in 1963, the
mysteries of the grassy knoll might have been solved in playing
back video that would have photographed Dealey Plaza from
practically every angle.)
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way, Be Here's immersive video, called 360
iVideo, can capture full panoramas of moving images and play them
back. Unlike iPIX movies, however, Be Here's iVideo technology
captures and shows a more narrow range _ 360 degress horizontally
and about 110 degrees vertically.
</P>
<P>
   But Be Here's president and chief executive, Ted Driscoll, said
his competitor's system actually captured only 180 degrees
vertically and that much of that was at viewing angles unnatural to
human beings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to focus our attention on the part of the sphere
around your head,'' Driscoll said. ``Your eyes spend most of their
time looking along that equator. We rarely look straight up unless
you are at a sporting event and on the court with Kareem.''
</P>
<P>
   Since this new field is hotly competitive, neither company
leader offered precise details on how their video technologies
actually work. Phillips talked briefly about a new lens design and
powerful software to blend the images together. Driscoll said his
company's technology was less dependent on software and more
dependent on special optical systems in the camera itself.
</P>
<P>
   And while Driscoll said iVideos, like iPIX movies, could be
burned onto CD-ROM and DVD discs, his company's emphasis is on
putting the images on the Internet. Samples of iVideos can be seen
at the 360 Gallery at www.behere.com.
</P>
<P>
   Be Here's immersive videos can be seen using the Internet's
three primary streaming formats: RealVideo, Windows Media and
Quicktime.
</P>
<P>
   The iPIX and iVideos technologies may be adapted someday for
consumer use, but both Phillips and Driscoll said that would most
likely have to wait while the new format became established in the
commercial world.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the summer you are going to begin seeing this on broadcast
television,'' said Phillips, of iPIX.
</P>
<P>
   And one day, he promised, immersive video technology is going to
capture Dad's face from behind the home video camera and put him
back in the family picture where he belongs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
