<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COL-AGENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE MONEY, MORE AGENTS MEANS SLIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One prominent NFL voice was describing the ``slime factor'' at
the college scouting combine last week in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of walking through the hotel lobby,'' he grumbled,
``you could slide all the way to the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Very tacky stuff, but nothing new. It's just the sports
agent-types being image-trashed again. ``Slime'' is one of the few
printables these days when you are talking agents.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, those of us in the media benefit greatly from this.
The way it once was in the jock kingdom, most all ill deeds were
somehow traced to ``taken out of context,'' ``misquoted,''
``tabloid mentality'' or ``I never read anything you write but a
friend of a friend's friend told me you said ...''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the agents who catch most of the blame, be it from the
college or pro ranks. Some of that blame is deserved. A low-rent
element seems to be growing rapidly in the agent business, where
new faces pop up overnight, lured by the scent of what is perceived
to be easy money.
</P>
<P>
   At the scouting combine, it was considered a record number of
agents who circled around Indy like buzzards on roadkill. All that
college football talent had gathered to be tested for football
skills. The agents were attempting to recruit their piece of the
action.
</P>
<P>
   A week never goes by when a story doesn't hit print about an
agent-gone-dirty. Undercover payments to college jocks leading to
suspension by the NCAA is normal for the sports page. There's also
Tank Black, the former college football coach who became a
high-profile agent. Now Black faces a long-stretch in the slammer
based on state and federal criminal fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   Reality, of course, says sports agents are no different from
doctors, lawyers, preachers, etc. The good ones, and honest ones,
far outnumber the ``slime'' factor, even though there is the
tendency to generalize it the other way.
</P>
<P>
   The college people, however, will tell you the agent business is
worse than ever. The pros don't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   What then does the good agent do in these troubled times?
</P>
<P>
   If you are Irving-based Jordan Woy, a second-generation agent,
the answer didn't come easy. But his decision had one benefit. He
does sleep better at night.
</P>
<P>
   Woy dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   Not out of the agent business _ he still has 45 NFL players
under contract, and the list grows every year.
</P>
<P>
   But Woy canceled his ``recruiting'' trip to Indianapolis this
year. He also attended no college all-star games, which are also
must-be-there gathering spots for agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will no longer be involved in that area of the business,''
Woy said. ``To go through that process of dealing with the college
player, it almost makes you feel dirty. I don't like that feeling.
Working with the veteran NFL players _ and I've added like 12 new
ones this year alone _ is pure heaven compared to what goes on at
Indianapolis and the all-star games.''
</P>
<P>
   For 13 years, Woy has represented mainly football players, but
no matter the sport, the agent-business mushroomed during the
1990s. Why? Because the money also mushroomed in the '90s, more so
in the NFL than anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started, no player in the NFL made a million
dollars a season,'' Woy said. ``Now punters can make that. Money
changes everything and everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the agent business, it's been like the floodgates opened.
Suddenly everyone wanted to be an agent. Suddenly everyone wanted
to sign a client, and to do so came the theory of
promise-them-anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know lawyers who became agents who do things they would
never dream of doing as lawyers. They'd lose their license if they
did. Very stupid business decisions are made.''
</P>
<P>
   Fierce competition has pushed some agents to the illegal side.
And the college player of today who considers himself as draftable
by the NFL is aware certain agents have ready-made deals for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk to a kid you know to be a sixth- or
seventh-rounder at best, and it's a guarantee he will consider
himself a third-rounder at worse,'' Woy said. ``So what he wants
from you is a $40,000 Lexus, a personal trainer and living-expense
money going into the draft. Neither from an ethical or business
standpoint, could I do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Due to recommendations from other clients, Woy will represent
about six college players in the April draft. ``And that was only
after I gave them my upfront speech about what to expect,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Too many agents. Too many college players with their hands out.
It's a bad mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what a pleasure it is to now deal only with
veterans like a Ray Crockett, a George Teague and so on,'' Woy
said. ``Really, I do sleep better.''
</P>
<P>
   The same, of course, can't be said for college coaches and
athletic directors. \Ntagtop:Randy Galloway's ``Sports at Six'' can
be heard weeknights, 6-8 p.m., on WBAP NewsTalk 820.
\Ntagbottom:rgalloway\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
