u a BC-NASA-TOURISM-HNS &LR;      03-01 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-TOURISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS URGE U.S. TO FIND WAYS TO ENCOURAGE SPACE TOURISM,
BUSINESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Likely years away from sending the first
human explorers to Mars, the United States should encourage tourism
and foster other forms of private enterprise in space if it wants
to sustain a leadership role on the new frontier, a panel of
experts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The government should do for space travel what it did in the
early 1900s for civil aviation, the experts urged, such as
fostering a transportation industry that offers new opportunities
for private investment and employment.
</P>
<P>
   Without a successful transition away from glitzy but expensive
government-controlled projects, such as the U.S.-led international
space station and the Cold War-era Apollo moon landings, NASA faces
a loss of public and political support, some of the experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever else this country is doing in space, our very
character as Americans dictates that we should be opening up space
for the general public,'' said Tom Rogers, who chairs the private
Sophron Foundation, a privately funded space advocacy group in
McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   An expert in early missile guidance systems, Rogers was among
four panelists who addressed 150 aerospace professionals gathered
for the Human Space Transportation and Exploration Workshop
sponsored by Lockheed Martin and the American Institute of
Aeronautics and Astronautics.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rogers, NASA should pay private rocket companies to
launch the stream of supplies that will be needed by residents of
the new space station rather than haul them up on the space
shuttle. The $25 billion that the U.S. General Accounting Office
believes NASA will spend on shuttle supply flights over a decade of
space station operations could finance the development of two or
three new private rockets that would cost less than the shuttle to
launch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also said that the federal government should sponsor the
development of orbiting satellites that generate electrical power
used on Earth from sunlight. NASA could even look for ways to
sponsor human sporting events in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these would use people in space in novel ways that
would work to restore the zest for space activities on the part of
the general public,'' said Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' views were shared by Gary Payton, NASA's deputy
associate administrator for space flight, who for three years has
led efforts to develop a low-cost successor to the space shuttle.
The effort has been marred by delays and cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Payton noted that 55 years after Orville and Wilbur Wright's
first airplane flight in 1903, Boeing 707 jetliners began carrying
paying passengers. A similar period of time has passed since the
first launchings of the German V-2 rockets in World War II, and
still it is impossible to predict when the public might begin
boarding a passenger rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the way to show adequate leadership in human
spaceflight,'' Payton said. ``We need to engage the entrepreneurial
energy of the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Joe Rothenberg, NASA's associate administrator for
spaceflight, told the conference that his agency remains the solid
global leader in human space exploration despite a succession of
budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Even with adequate funding, NASA lacks the technologies to
protect its explorers from the threat of solar and cosmic radiation
as well as the other ill health effects that humans would face
during a long journey to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the public will remain supportive of NASA as it
attempts to overcome those obstacles with the research it plans
aboard the space station.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
