<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABC-WARNER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON CABLE AUDIENCE MAY LOSE ABC AFFILIATE THURSDAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Time Warner and KTRK-Channel 13 flap continued
Tuesday, with the ABC affiliate saying it still plans to leave
Houston's largest cable system by week's end _ as soon as 12:01
a.m. CST Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Disney/ABC has been negotiating 10-year retransmission
agreements for its stations in Houston, New York, Los Angeles and
other cities, representing 3.5 million Time Warner subscribers in
all.
</P>
<P>
   The parties agreed to a 30-day extension on the current
agreements, except in Houston, which ABC apparently is using as a
test case.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner spokesman Mike Luftman said a deal had been worked
out in early January to include the Disney Channel, now a premium
service, in the expanded basic cable package and to carry two other
Disney properties, Toon Disney and SoapNet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an actual written document, with all the i's dotted
and all the t's crossed, and it was ready to be signed,'' Luftman
said. ``(Disney/ABC) basically pulled it off the table and reneged
on it. Instead they said here's another deal, take it or leave it.
The additional cost of that deal was more than $100 million over
the (10-year) deal we had already agreed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner had agreed to pay Disney 30 cents per month per
customer for the Disney Channel, Luftman said, but ``they basically
turned around and said now we want 71 cents per customer. ... There
were other additional costs in the take-it-or-leave-it deal, but
that was by far the largest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those costs, Luftman said, would have to be passed on to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they had the leverage to extort it from us,'' he
said. ``At the moment, they're doing it by threatening to pull
their programming from Houston cable customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's analogous to a terrorist situation. When terrorists take
hostages, what they often do is they'll pick one out at random and
shoot them, just to show they mean business. That's kind of what
they're doing in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Florsheim, KTRK general manager and president, called
Luftman's comments ``nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no deal,'' he said. ``There were a number of issues
that were not resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're disappointed that Time Warner wants to engage
in a war of words instead of sitting down at the table to talk
about substantive issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a retransmission agreement, Channel 13 will go off the
cable system at 12:01 a.m. Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The day is uncertain because ABC requested a 24-hour extension
of the retransmission agreement, but no decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner-Houston, meanwhile, plans to make antennas available
to customers who request them and will offer the premium service
HBO Family in Channel 13's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of damage to go around if this happens,'' said
Time Warner's Luftman. ``There's no doubt that we will be hurt, no
doubt that Disney/ABC will be hurt and no doubt the customers will
be hurt. It's a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
