<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-PRIMARIES-RDP-HNS &LR;      03-01 1618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
BUSH RECLAIMS FRONT-RUNNER STATUS OVER McCAIN WITH WINS 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush scored an easy victory Tuesday in Virginia's
presidential primary, a landslide in North Dakota caucuses, and
reclaimed his status as front-runner for the Republican nomination.
He was locked in a tight battle with John McCain in a closely
watched contest in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, hoping to deny his challenger even a
psychological victory, was favored over former Sen. Bill Bradley in
the Democrats' nonbinding presidential preference vote in
Washington state, their party's only electoral action of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, after reviewing early tabulations in Virginia, exulted in
his return to the winner's column by telling supporters in
Cincinnati: ``We are one step closer to victory. We are one step
closer to having a united party, and we are one step closer to
getting rid of Clinton-Gore in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the Virginia result, according to exit polling,
was Bush's resounding draw among Christian conservatives, whose
leaders McCain attacked in a fiery speech Monday. The religious
right made up about 20 percent of the Virginia electorate, and Bush
won about 80 percent of their votes. The remainder of the voters
split about equally between Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, after phoning congratulations to Bush, questioned
whether the Texan's candidacy had real national appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as if he has a Southern strategy here,'' McCain said,
referring to Bush's victories in Virginia and South Carolina.
McCain looked forward to better results next week ``when we have a
broad cross-section of America voting all on that same day.''
</P>
<P>
   For both parties and the four major contenders, the contests
were seen as a dress rehearsal for next Tuesday, which will be the
biggest day of primary balloting in the nation's history and
include face-offs in California and New York. The need for a
victory was especially urgent for Bradley, whose once vibrant
candidacy is struggling to stay afloat after defeats in Iowa and
New Hampshire and a resulting drop in public-opinion polls, both
nationally and in key states.
</P>
<P>
   With all but a few precincts in Virginia reporting, Bush had 54
percent; McCain had 43 percent, and former Reagan administration
official Alan Keyes 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In North Dakota, with all precincts reporting, Bush had 76
percent to McCain's 19 percent. Keyes trailed with 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday's voting, McCain, the victor in New Hampshire,
Arizona and Michigan, led Bush 96-93 delegates, according to an
Associated Press count, with 1,034 needed to ensure the nomination
at this summer's Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush picking up 56 delegates in Virginia's winner-take-all
contest, and apparently 14 in North Dakota, he moved back ahead of
the U.S. senator from Arizona. Bush has chalked up earlier wins in
Iowa, Alaska, Delaware, South Carolina and U.S. territories
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But the incremental nature of Bush's accumulation of delegates
and his state-by-state battle with McCain was yet another reminder
of how far the Texas governor has slipped from the triumphal
timetable his top aides outlined only months ago.
</P>
<P>
   By that scenario, Bush was supposed to be ready to wrap up the
nomination next week and begin a general-election-style campaign
against the likely Democratic standard-bearer, presumably Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bush finds himself in a bitter and expensive fight that
seems to be as much about the ideological foundations of the party,
and especially the role of conservative Christians, as about who
will seek to lead Republicans into the post-Clinton era.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, top strategists for McCain have long acknowledged
that if their insurgent effort had not effectively knocked Bush out
of the race by Tuesday's round of voting _ a possibility foreclosed
by the governor's victory in South Carolina _ that the senator's
chances of ultimate success dimmed considerably.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's dependence on independents and Democrats will avail him
little in contests such as California and New York, where only the
vote of registered Republicans will count in electing those state's
huge share of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the governor's margin among
independent voters has grown, from a meager 19 percent in New
Hampshire to almost one-third in Virginia, according to exit polls
for news media.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in Virginia came a day after McCain went to Virginia
Beach, home of the Christian Coalition, for the express purpose of
excoriating its leader, televangelist Pat Robertson, and the
group's impact on the Republican Party. McCain identified Bush as
``a Pat Robertson Republican who will lose to Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused McCain of having ``a spiteful agenda'' and
belittled the Arizonan's claim as the political heir of former
President Reagan. Bush said Reagan had ``an optimistic agenda, as
do I.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's ploy may have backfired in conservative Virginia. Bush
said: ``The voters of Virginia rejected the politics of pitting one
religion against another.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia voters also had questions about whether McCain was
conservative enough. Six in 10 voters in the Old Dominion on
Tuesday said they were conservatives and they went heavily for
Bush, by a margin of about 3-1 over McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, only 12 of the 37 Republican national
convention delegates will be selected on the basis of Tuesday's
voting, with the remainder subject to the action of GOP caucuses
next week.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democratic contenders, the Washington state vote,
although offering no delegates, was the first contest since the New
Hampshire primary Feb. 1. Bradley spent six days straight in the
state outlining why he believed he was a better candidate than Gore
on a number of issues, including abortion rights, environmental
protection and campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, backed by the state's Democratic establishment, dropped in
over the weekend to tout his record in support of the state's
economic interests, including trade that helps aircraft giant
Boeing, based in Seattle. A Gore television ad featured scenes of
his ascent of Mount Rainier last summer, an event that he had
earlier insisted was a private outing with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state Democrats will use caucuses next week to
apportion delegates to their party's national convention at Los
Angeles in August. National Democratic rules allow only Iowa and
New Hampshire to hold binding presidential nominating contests
before the first Tuesday in March.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley fought against the growing idea that his was a lost
cause without a victory in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race has just begun,'' the former U.S. senator from New
Jersey said. ``March 7 is the take off date for this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had a different take on the short-term nature of his
party's contest and the potentially decisive nature of the voting
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``California will be the decisive vote in determining who the
Democratic nominee is,'' Gore told participants in a Hispanic
campaign event Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has bought time on CBS to air nationally a five-minute
commercial Thursday night that his spokesman, Eric Hauser, said
would be about Bradley's ``vision of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The voting came as a new Washington Post-ABC national poll
showed McCain with a far better chance at present than Bush of
beating Gore. The match-ups showed McCain beating Gore 56-39
percent and Bush leading the vice president more narrowly, 50-44
percent.
</P>
<P>
   During the day Tuesday, Bush continued to battle any impression
that, because of his visit to Bob Jones University during the South
Carolina campaign, he shared the school's anti-Roman Catholic
views.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made a point of visiting Fatima Family Center in Cleveland,
where he visited with leaders of the city's Catholic Charities
Services. Bush also used the meeting to promote his promise to
create more faith-based social service programs if he is elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting had been set up last weekend after Bush wrote an
open letter to Cardinal John O'Connor of New York apologizing for
having missed a chance to speak out against anti-Catholic bias
while at Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized McCain for making telephone calls to prospective
voters in Virginia and Washington state attacking Bush for speaking
at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't appreciate the politics that still go on out of
Senator McCain ... the politics of saying he's going to run a
campaign and tell the truth when in fact this is a man who
yesterday authorized calls into the commonwealth of Virginia
calling me an anti-Catholic bigot,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of politics that John F. Kennedy rejected in
the 1960s,'' Bush said, invoking the name of the nation's only
Roman Catholic president. ``It's the kind of politics we thought we
had put behind us in America.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides denied so-called ``Catholic Voter Alert'' phone
messages were being made in Virginia but said they were being used
in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that George W. Bush is trying to run a
Jekyll and Hyde campaign where he is a Pat Robertson and Bob Jones
Republican in one state and a compassionate moderate in another,
and he's not going to get away with it,'' said McCain campaign
chief Rick Davis. ``George Bush should take responsibility for his
actions and campaign tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Houston Chronicle reporters Greg McDonald, R.G. Ratcliffe and
Bennett Roth contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
