<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     03-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SPARKY Anderson had no illusions about making the Hall of Fame
during his career as a big-league player, which consisted of one
season as a second baseman with the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, in 477 trips to the plate, Sparky delivered zero home
runs, sacrificing power for consistency and hitting a steady .218.
Which may explain why his playing days were short.
</P>
<P>
   But he thrived as a manager, one whose ego was unlikely to clash
with the superstar players who crossed his path.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame added a large helping of cheer and charm
Tuesday when the Veterans Committee elected George Lee ``Sparky''
Anderson the 16th manager to be enshrined. No one ever described
him as a genius, but his teams in Cincinnati and Detroit won over
2,100 games, ranking him third on the all-time list behind Connie
Mack and John McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   That is mighty exclusive company for the son of a house painter,
who paid his dues in the minor leagues riding buses and eating a
lot of cheap hamburgers at roadside palaces.
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Anderson once worked in a Los Angeles
furniture factory, fastening legs on tables. Paid by the piece, he
once confided that he would put off going to the washroom in order
to crowd more table legs into his working day.
</P>
<P>
   Recollections of this kind tend to make a good man humble and a
bad man hostile. A good man, Sparky has never forgotten the hungry
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never looked down my nose at anyone,'' he says. ``Those in
our business who do tend to forget that their day will come. They
will be out on their ears, wondering where their friends went.''
</P>
<P>
   He raised the bar so high in Cincinnati, where he won five
division titles and reached the World Series four times, that it
happened to him. When the Reds finished second in 1978, 2{ games
out of first place, Anderson was fired after nine seasons. He had
taken a team of megastars _ Pete Rose, Johnny Bench, Joe Morgan and
Tony Perez _ and blended them into the Big Red Machine, the
greatest era Cincinnati had ever known.
</P>
<P>
   But Sparky's friends went with him, to Detroit, where he created
a powerhouse that won 104 games in 1984. The Tigers had no
permanent third baseman, first baseman, left fielder or fourth
starter, but they led the pennant race wire-to-wire.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tigers won the World Series that year the town, which
had been torn by racial strife, went slightly berserk. The
celebration lasted for days, and it took a heartfelt plea from
Sparky to get the fans to return home, promising not to torch any
more police cars. Joyfully, Detroit went back to recalling cars or
unloading them at book value.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame is going to be a merrier and more inviting
place simply because Anderson's friendly mug will be on display
there.
</P>
<P>
   He so loved his job that he once expressed a desire to continue
managing a baseball team until he was 80 years old. The remark
puzzled one of his rivals, Whitey Herzog, who noted that Anderson,
then in his 50s, ``already looks 80.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his history, it isn't surprising that almost no one ever
called him George, with the exception of an umpire named Al Clark,
who said, ``I refuse to call a grown man Sparky.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has finally caught up with his hair _ it turned
white when he was in his 20s _ his life isn't complicated by
vanity. He earned his immortality by recognizing that championship
teams enjoyed a quality called good chemistry. In his managerial
style he was an activist. He was quick to make moves and never shy
about explaining them.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first to create his team around the bullpen, changing
pitchers so abruptly that he became known as Captain Hook. In the
process, he developed an interesting policy. If only conversation
was required, he sent out his pitching coach. If he wanted to make
a change, he went to the mound himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often,'' he said, ``when you go to remove a pitcher, there is
a certain amount of guff involved. There is no reason for a coach
to take that. The manager gets more money and more credit if the
team wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson will tell you frankly that when he began his career as
a manager, he wanted to be loved. With the years came wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the manager and his players stick together on a
team,'' he says, ``the more disenchanted they get with each other.
As time passes, your faults become more exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the element of luck enters into it. With a
break, you can develop a combination of players who will rise above
the fringe stuff and play well together. But you must find the
right combination. That's why you will sometimes see great talent
on teams that keep losing. They have never learned respect for each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   That virtue, and more, the Tigers and Reds learned under Sparky.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
