u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-01 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ There's little doubt that if Craig Biggio
continues on the path he is on _ that is, the oft-beaten one with
headfirst dives into the dirt happening at the drop of a bunt _
he'll be a candidate for Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   There also is little doubt that if Biggio puts in a few more
years like the ones he has had of late, earning the career numbers
and accolades befitting a Hall of Famer, he will wear the Astros'
uniform into the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, Which Astros uniform? The rainbow sleeves? The
blue and gold shooting star? Or the spiffy new red-and-black
colors, with pinstripes and throwback script lettering?
</P>
<P>
   It is now the 13th spring of Biggio's big-league career. To say
he has seen a lot is an understatement along the lines of saying he
has a tendency to smudge his uniform a bit.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Biggio has worn three uniforms and gone through two
owners, four managers and a pair of home stadiums _ all without
ever departing from the team that drafted him or the style that has
defined him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people that have been here through all of it are me,
(assistant coach) Matt Galante and Denny (equipment manager Dennis
Liborio),'' Biggio said. ``Things change.''
</P>
<P>
   But Biggio stays the same. Confident. Focused. Undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   There was Biggio breaking in his new Astros duds the other day
as only he knows how. He slipped on his new batting helmet, looked
over the gloss and shine on it and scoffed.
</P>
<P>
   He began banging his head against a wall in the Astros'
Kissimmee clubhouse, pounding the helmet into it, back and forth,
side to side, putting nice little dents in all the right places. He
scraped his pine-tar-coated batting glove over the glistening star
on the front of the helmet, then tossed the helmet into his
baseball bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just warming it up a little bit,'' Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if not for the determination in this man's way, the
double meaning of Biggio's banging his head against the wall might
have been clear.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio's 13th spring easily could have been his most
frustrating. After three years of coming close to finally getting
over the playoff hump, the Astros weren't exactly gutted by
offseason moves that trimmed $10 million of payroll, but certainly
a few vital parts were removed.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio could have ranted and raged over the frustration of
losing All-Star-caliber players such as Mike Hampton and Carl
Everett. He could have wielded his formidable stature within the
franchise to demand explanations and answers, or even played out
his free-agent season and then moved on to a team with better
postseason prospects.
</P>
<P>
   But he has done none of it, and he won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'd still like to have a lefthanded starter,''
Biggio said. ``We had one of the best, but (Hampton) is not here
anymore. What happened was between Mike and the front office. There
was nothing we could do about it in this clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's no question Carl was one of the most important
parts of our offense. He was clutch. But you just go on and play
the same way you always have, no matter what. You have to care
about winning, and I still see that here.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the changes and uncertainties surrounding this club this
spring, there remains one sure thing and one reason to believe the
Astros yet again will throw themselves headfirst into the division
race. Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   While Hampton and Everett departed, and slugger Jeff Bagwell's
future with the team is likely next up on the negotiating table,
Biggio's services were secured with a recently signed three-year
contract extension worth $28 million.
</P>
<P>
   What it means is that Biggio will be an Astro at least through
the 2003 season, giving him enough time to adequately break in the
new helmet and work on numbers that are beginning to resemble Hall
of Fame totals.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this season, Biggio should surpass Jose Cruz for
the club's hits record (1,937) and also break the prestigious
2,000-hit barrier for his career. If his production stays close to
what it has been, Biggio should end his current contract with more
than 2,500 hits, 500 doubles, 500 stolen bases, 1,000 RBIs and 200
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing from his Hall of Fame resume might be a
championship ring. But he's not giving up on that, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of the Yankees, there is no sure thing,'' Biggio said.
``Except for last year, we've never been picked to win the
division, but we've done it three years in a row. If I didn't think
we have a chance, yeah, I'd be real upset. But I'm not upset. We
have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
