<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SHAKE-UPS IN TRAVEL INDUSTRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The business of Travel.
</P>
<P>
   If you are one of those fortunate few who either have the big
bucks to fly the Concorde to Europe _ or enough clout to make the
company pony up the fare _ here's bad news. This year, you might be
back on the slow flight with the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of yet another trade dispute between the United States
and Europe. This one is over hush kits. They are devices installed
on engines of older jets to quiet their noise. Newer jet planes are
much quieter.
</P>
<P>
   Some carriers have chosen to simply replace the old planes, or
their engines, with new ones. Others have installed the hush kits.
They can keep the older planes flying at a much lower cost than
buying new ones. That's especially true on many planes now used to
fly cargo.
</P>
<P>
   The hush kits were pioneered by U.S. companies, especially cargo
delivery services.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans say, however, that the hush kits aren't quiet enough.
They are contemplating banning airplanes using them _ or
replacement engines _ from their airports. Americans say that's
blatant protectionism. The European governments just want to expand
the market for airplanes sold by European manufacturer Airbus, they
say. They point out the European standards are stiffer than those
agreed to by the Civil Aviation Organization of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States and Europe don't come to an agreement by
May 8, look for the Clinton administration, under congressional
pressure, to ban the flights of the supersonic Concorde airplanes
into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Concordes are operated only by Air France and British Air. They
carry a minuscule portion of traffic over the Atlantic Ocean, and
make little money for the airlines. They operate them more for
prestige than profit, since Concordes are the world's only airliner
capable of breaking the speed of sound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INVESTORS GET SPECIAL FARES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The travel business, like others, is subject to that cynical
interpretation of the golden rule _ the one about how the person
with the gold makes the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations use their purchasing clout to cut special deals
with suppliers. Travel suppliers are no different.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, however, the buyers have gone a step beyond. Faced
with limited competition and high air fares, companies there are
doing what they can to keep alive a competing airline.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and DaimlerChrysler started the ball rolling when
they agreed to pay a monthly fee to start-up airline Pro Air. In
return, they get cut-rate ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the United Auto Workers is investing directly in Pro Air.
In return, union members get a 50 percent discount on published air
fares and can fly standby for just $25.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Air said the deal was part of a $36 million sale of stock in
the airline. As part of the deal, the airline also had to agree not
to fight any efforts by unions to organize the airline's employees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CRUISE LINE COURTING AGENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a travel agent, a bypass isn't something that happens to
your heart, but your pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   Bypass is when a travel supplier _ an airline, hotel, cruise
line or the like _ cuts out the travel agent and sells directly to
the customer. It happens when suppliers believe their direct
selling cost is less than paying a travel agent a commission to do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are pushing bypass. For example, Southwest Airlines is
getting 25 percent of its revenues from tickets sold over the
Internet, which mostly bypasses travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines seldom bypass. While many of us have to fly
somewhere, few of us have to go on a cruise. Cruises compete with
other vacations _ from a week at a resort to going to Las Vegas.
They have to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   One exception is Renaissance Cruises, which competes in the
upper end of the cruise market. At times, it has advised potential
customers to skip agents and buy directly. Instead of the standard
10 percent commission on cruises, Renaissance generally pays a set
fee to travel agents _ usually much less than the agents would get
on a similar sale with other cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Renaissance is trying to kiss and make up with
travel agents. It is flooding travel agent trade journals with
advertising. The company declines to talk about its advertising
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But Renaissance added a fifth ship to its fleet last December,
and has three more coming on this year. With a doubling of space,
perhaps it thinks it now needs the agents. The question is, will
the agents forgive and forget?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
