<SLUG> BC-AOL-WIRELESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL SEEKS MORE WIRELESS DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Fresh off announcing a half-dozen new partnerships
to make America Online content and services available through
wireless connections, AOL chairman Steve Case said Wednesday the
company will aggressively continue to seek more deals to achieve
its ``AOL Anywhere'' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work with as many companies as want to work with
us,'' Case told the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association's Wireless 2000 convention, which has drawn more than
25,000 industry executives. ``Our whole strategy is to partner,
partner, partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wireless officials, including Chris Gent of Vodafone
AirTouch PLC, have said they do not want to give away their
customers to content and e-commerce providers and become only a
wireless pipeline through which others reap profits.
</P>
<P>
   But Case said he thinks if companies try to ``lock people in or
out, I think inevitably you'll fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as obsessed (as others) about the customer ownership
thing,'' said Case. ``To me, it's how do you share customers, how
do you share revenues, how do we work together to build a bigger
market and share that in some equitable way.''
</P>
<P>
   At this week's convention, AOL announced six new alliances to
bring AOL content _ including e-mail and instant messages and
future offerings from Time Warner, which AOL is buying for $120
billion _ to subscribers through wireless phones and other devices.
Deals included pacts with paging giant Arch Communications Inc. of
Westborough, Mass., Motorola, Nokia, and BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Case noted that AOL's 21 million subscribers now spend an
average of an hour a day using the service, but noted: ``Guess
what? There's another 23 hours of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing the need for systems that ``bridge these separate
worlds'' through which people get information, including wireless
units, personal computers, and televisions, Case said: ``If you
view this just through the prism of the wireless unit or the PC, I
think you are going to miss the bigger opportunity, which is to
integrate these things in a way that will change the lives of
hundreds of millions of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
