<HEADER>
A3649 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-VENEZUELA-FLOODS-COX     03-01 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-FLOODS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: This is the text for a photo essay published by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Any questions, please call CoxNet at
404-526-5456.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Poquito a poquito,'' Marlene Karas heard a man say as he
shoveled mud from his home. ``Little by little.''
</P>
<P>
   Karas, a staff photographer for the Journal-Constitution, had
traveled with a reporter to Venezuela in February to cover the
efforts of Braves first baseman Andres Galarraga to help victims
recover from powerful mudslides. When the benefit ended. the
reporter left. Karas stayed behind, watching the victims help
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The mudslides had hit a week before Christmas. Walls of mud
crushed buildings, buckled roads, swept away neighborhoods, and
killed more than 30,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Karas toured Vargas state, a tourist area on the Caribbean
coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at how much damage there was,'' she said. ``It
was like the nuclear bomb had dropped. There were no people around;
it was desolate. And this was eight weeks after the fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In Caracas, too, there was damage. Homes in the poorest
neighborhoods, often little more than a few bricks topped by a tin
roof, had been reduced to nothing. Cars were destroyed. In various
places, Karas saw people guarding the few possessions they had
left.
</P>
<P>
   Things seemed hopeless. The country depends in large measure on
tourism and oil. Both had been badly hurt. Some hotels had
survived, but the roads to reach them had not. And the port from
which the oil was shipped had been damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was almost in disbelief,'' Karas said, ``in that I didn't
know how it was going to get started again.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she started to see. Working with her eye and with her
heart, she documented not only the damage, but people's efforts to
recover. Her lens recorded not only the homes that had tumbled down
a hillside, but a man laboring to dig his Jeep from under the mud.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it seemed pointless. Surely the Jeep would never run
again. But then it struck Karas that this Jeep might be all the man
had left. Maybe he could use the parts. When disaster hits, you
start with what remains.
</P>
<P>
   As she walked up a hillside in Vargas state, Karas heard the
sound of scraping. Her eye was caught by a small hole in the wall
of a building. From the hole emerged the hand of an old man,
holding a trowel.
</P>
<P>
   The old man was inside the building spooning out gallons upon
gallons of mud one trowelful at a time.
</P>
<P>
   And that, in the end, seems to be how the people of Venezuela
will recover. It is the only way they can.
</P>
<P>
   Poquito a poquito. Little by little.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
