<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-SPINOFF-ART-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT TECHNOLOGIES TO SPIN OFF 3 UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies Inc. said Wednesday that it would spin off
three units, creating a new company that would have about $8
billion in revenue and would sell business telephone systems, wire
cabling and office network systems.
</P>
<P>
   The news raised the price of shares in Lucent, one of the most
widely held stocks in the nation, by nearly 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While the new company, which has yet to be named, will focus on
the corporate networking market, Lucent will concentrate on
equipment and services for telecommunications providers. Analysts
said that market was growing at a rate of 20 percent a year as
telecommunications companies race to provide new data, voice and
video services, while the corporate market is growing only 4 to 8
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent shares closed at $68, up $8.50, on the New York Stock
Exchange. The shares have been depressed since a disappointing
earnings report in January.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher T. Stix, an analyst with S.G. Cowen, upgraded Lucent
to a buy from neutral, saying the spinoff would help increase the
growth profile of the company and improve operating margins.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that by spinning out the slower-growing parts of
its business, shares of Lucent should trade at a multiple similar
to those of companies like Cisco Systems Inc. or Nortel Networks
Corp. Even after Wednesday's gains, Lucent shares trade at about 87
times earnings; Cisco's shares trade at 181 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lucent, itself spun off from AT&AMP;T in 1996, remains the
world's largest maker of telephone equipment, it has fallen behind
Nortel in the fast-growing optical networking market and has been a
less aggressive competitor than Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff ``breaks the company into two pieces that are easier
to understand for the Street and that really had no synergies at
all,'' said Paul Sagawa, an analyst with Sanford Bernstein.
``Lucent was getting labeled as an `old world' company.
Post-spin-out, Lucent will get 75 percent of its revenues from
new-world technologies, like optical networking, Internet
infrastructure and wireless communications. We see the
post-spin-out Lucent as a really clear growth story.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said it would spin off the three businesses _ PBX's, or
telephone switchboard systems; Systimax structured cabling; and
local area networks _ to shareholders. Lucent expects to complete
the divestiture by the close of its fourth quarter, which ends
Sept. 30. The new company will employ 34,000, or about 23 percent,
of Lucent's 150,000 workers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Donald K. Peterson, currently Lucent's executive vice president
and chief financial officer, will become president and chief
executive of the new company, which will be based in Basking Ridge,
N.J. Henry B. Schacht, a former Lucent chairman and a current
member of the board, will be the new company's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this move, Lucent will focus on extending its leadership
in the highest-growth areas of communications networking,'' Richard
A. McGinn, Lucent's chairman and chief executive, said in a
statement. ``Lucent will concentrate greater resources on
fast-growing areas like optical networking, Internet
infrastructure, wireless, semiconductors, optoelectronics,
Web-based enterprise solutions linking private to public networks,
and professional design and consulting services for service
providers and enterprises.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinn said the new company would also have a strong position in
a growing market. ``The newly created enterprise company will rank
No. 1 or 2 in nearly every market in which it competes,'' he said.
``We are making the strategic choice to establish two financially
strong and independent companies that will deliver greater value to
our share owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent posted anemic revenue growth of less than 1 percent for
its fiscal first quarter, which ended Dec. 31; revenue totaled
$9.905 billion, up from $9.842 billion during the period a year
earlier. Including one-time charges and profits _ like merger
expenses and gains from sales of investments _ Lucent had earnings
of $1.25 billion, or 38 cents a share. That was less than half the
$2.544 billion, or 80 cents a share, reported for the period a year
earlier, including one-time events.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn said in a conference call Wednesday that Lucent's sales
would rise about 17 percent this year. In Cisco's fiscal year ended
July 31, revenue rose 43 percent, to $12.2 billion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
