<HEADER>
A3651 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FIDELITY-DOTCOM-BOS &LR;      03-01 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-DOTCOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIEDLITY LAUNCHES WEB INSURANCE BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Fidelity Investments bought the domain name
insurance.com in 1994, it wasn't clear how, or if, the mutual fund
giant would use the site. But it was a bargain at $70.
</P>
<P>
   The name sat on the shelf for two years, along with a host of
other sites Fidelity had snapped up. The idea was reviewed in
Fidelity's new-business group in 1996, then tabled again. Selling
insurance online was still a far-out concept, years behind the push
for stock and fund sales over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But Lou Geremia, a former Fidelity executive who had written the
business plan for insurance.com, never forgot the opportunity he
felt the firm had tucked away in its pocket. He went back to
Fidelity last June, this time to the firm's venture arm, and
pitched the strategy anew.
</P>
<P>
   This time it worked, and the result could only make insurance
executives and bankers green with envy.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Wednesday launched the site, which is meant to be an
objective research tool and quote service for consumers.
Ultimately, insurance.com wants to be an online insurance agency,
where customers can buy life, auto, health, and other coverage for
the same fees agents get from insurance companies when they sell
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to become their insurance agent,'' Geremia said. He
thinks the service will appeal to Fidelity's customers, 15 million
strong, many of whom buy investment products without a broker or
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a threat to independent agents, it is.
Agents are facing pressure on all sides, as insurers such as John
Hancock Financial Services Inc. sell policies both on the Web and
through its sales agent force. Fidelity already sells term life
insurance and annuities directly on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But the site will also team up with insurance companies that use
agents. Insurance.com can earn fees for referring business to
insurers; in such transactions, a consumer might be linked up with
an agent working for the insurer selling the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Eyler, a senior analyst at Forrester Research, said he
expects 10 percent of consumers to buy auto insurance online within
the next five years. As many as 50 percent will likely research
their insurance purchases online, he said, which could lead to
future sales. He estimated that in states where rates are
competitive, consumers could save an average $500 each by shopping
for car insurance on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But Fidelity is hardly alone in the online insurance sales
business. In addition to the traditional insurers who are selling
on the Web, there are other third-party firms offering quote
services, such as Quotesmith.com and InsurQuote.
</P>
<P>
   Geremia said insurance.com aims to distinguish itself from the
competition by focusing on life events, such as buying a house,
getting married, or having a baby. The company has hired Forefield
Inc., a group of financial advisers and lawyers, to provide its
content and advice on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an electronic filing cabinet, where consumers can
keep track of all of their policies, whether purchased on the site
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Observed Forrester's Eyler: ``There are a lot of very smart
(companies) who know this is the way to go. Success is going to
depend on who has the best advertising and the best fulfillment of
service.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, you won't find the Fidelity name or logo prominently
shown on the insurance.com page. In small letters at the bottom, it
states that the company is a Fidelity affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no Fidelity products on the site currently. We really
do want to be perceived as an independent and unbiased
marketplace,'' Geremia said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fidelity backing of the venture is significant, however.
Fidelity is financing it, just as it did with other ventures in its
Fidelity Capital group, including Boston Coach and Community
Newspapers. The board is made up entirely of Fidelity executives,
including Rod Rhoda, head of the investment firm's insurance unit.
</P>
<P>
   Geremia said the plan is to add outsiders before insurance.com
goes public. An initial public stock offering could come by the end
of this year or early 2001, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
