<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3652 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SUSAN-SMITH-COX     03-01 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSAN-SMITH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murderous mom Susan Smith still enthralls nation
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susan Smith's mother says her daughter is so mentally ill that
she has attempted suicide while serving a life sentence for murder
in South Carolina for the ghastly 1994 drownings of her two young
sons in a lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has mutilated herself, cutting her arms and wrists with
whatever object she could find,'' Linda Russell writes in ``Susan
Smith My Daughter,'' scheduled for publication April 1. ``Several
times she has been put on suicide watch for her own protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina Department of Corrections would not comment
on Smith's medical history.
</P>
<P>
   Brentwood, Tenn., author Shirley Stephens collaborated with
Russell in the latest of several books examining why Smith would
drive to the top of a boat ramp at night, release her car's
emergency brake and send her sons to their deaths strapped in their
safety seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still as simple as everybody still wants to know why,''
said Andrew Yex, a Los Angeles producer working on a Learning
Channel documentary, one of several media projects recently
produced or in the works about the crime that shocked America.
</P>
<P>
   Production crews for MSNBC, the British Broadcasting Corp. and
Tampa television station WTSP recently interviewed people around
Union, S.C., who were involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than five years since Smith, now 28, confessed to
killing Michael, 3, and Alex, 14 months, after lying to
investigators for nine days that a black man had carjacked her
children. A hometown jury found her guilty of murder in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Pope, the state solicitor who sought the death penalty
against Smith, said he believes ``the shocking nature of the crime
by the last individual you'd expect'' perpetuates the fascination
with the textile town tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like the girl next door; she was their mother,'' said
Pope, who during the trial tried to prove that Smith killed her
sons in hopes of winning back Tom Findlay, the son of a rich Union
textile manufacturer. In ending their relationship, Findlay wrote
Smith that he wasn't interested in a ready-made family.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Russell granted interviews to The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution in 1998 has she talked publicly about the
tragedy. She has yet to appear in a television interview since her
daughter's conviction, explaining recently, ``I am not going to be
exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who visits her daughter regularly in the Women's
Correctional Institution in Columbia, said prison officials haven't
placed Smith on suicide watch for about two years. On Jan. 8, 1997,
the state Corrections Department charged Smith with possession of
contraband, which Russell said stemmed from her possessing a razor
blade with which she had cut herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan is all over that, I think,'' said Russell, explaining
that she believes a combination of therapy and anti-depressant
drugs is helping her daughter, but with a painful side effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more well you become, the more sick you realize you
were,'' Russell said. ``She needed that before she came to the
point where she could forgive herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said collaborating on the book ``emotionally drained me,
but it helped me. I think Susan is reaching the point where she is
considering a book of her own. I think she has got to do something
to find peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephens, 65, said Russell contacted her in 1996 about writing a
book, at the suggestion of a member of her daughter's defense team.
After Stephens' literary agent was unable to sell the manuscript,
partly ``because it wasn't sensational enough,'' Stephens said she
decided that the publishing company she owns with her husband,
William, would publish Russell's story. The company, Authors Book
Nook, is selling the 304-page book on its Web page,
www.authorsbooknook.com. The book follows a predictable course,
relying on court transcripts to explain the boys' disappearance and
the nine-day national manhunt for them. Russell provides fresh
insights and details such as her daughter's request from jail that
her mother buy two red roses and place them on the coffin the boys
shared.
</P>
<P>
   As the search for the boys dragged on, Russell recalled how she
lost control. Grabbing her daughter by the shoulders, she pleaded,
``I want the children. Do you know where they are? Have you hurt
them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama,'' she said, ``You know I would never hurt Michael and
Alex.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell believed her. She writes, ``I do know I simply couldn't
entertain the thought that the daughter I love dearly and the
mother who loved her children with all her heart could harm her
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Months later, waiting for a jury to decide whether Smith should
be electrocuted, Russell recalled how family members gathered in a
courthouse room and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, I didn't know what I would do if she were
sentenced to death,'' Russell writes. ``It was too horrible to
contemplate. It is one thing to execute a vicious criminal; it is
quite another to execute someone with a mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's defense lawyers argued that she was suffering from
severe depression the night in September 1994 that she drove to
John D. Long Lake outside Union. Her lawyers called witnesses who
related the devastation of Smith's father's suicide when she was a
child and her sexual abuse by her stepfather, Beverly Russell.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1995 book, ``Beyond All Reason _ My Life With Susan
Smith,'' David Smith admitted to cheating on his wife, while
accusing her of cheating on him. ``People all over the world sneak
around on each other, lie to each other. ... But no one kills their
children. No one murders their babies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Russell's book contends that David Smith, after his wife
filed for divorce on grounds of adultery, embarked on ``an unholy
quest for revenge that pushed her to the edge and cost him his
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell writes that she shares the blame for not recognizing the
seriousness of her daughter's mental illness, dating back to her
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   After her father's suicide, Smith showed suicidal tendencies,
once taking so many aspirin her stomach had to be pumped out. In
hindsight, Russell writes that she assumed incorrectly after each
incident that her daughter had gotten better.
</P>
<P>
   Russell relates how she and her first husband, Harry Vaughan,
argued in front of their two sons and daughter. Russell regrets not
ever explaining to them why she and her husband had separated. She
never provided her daughter with details of how Vaughan died from a
self-inflicted shotgun blast.
</P>
<P>
   Smith apparently learned from her parents' reticence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She kept her fears and sadness to herself,'' Russell writes.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, Smith showed a suicide note to a teacher, who showed it
to Russell. She writes, ``What concerned me tremendously was the
fact she was talking with other people about things that should
have been kept within our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, when Smith was finishing high school, Russell
writes that she shared with her daughter a puzzling encounter with
a man she didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Once while swimming, the man said he felt as though he could
stay forever underwater where ``everything was so pretty and
peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell writes she told her daughter that drowning seemed ``an
easy death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered,'' Russell writes, ``if this was the reason she
chose water for her suicide attempt and the children's deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
