<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; MORE KNOCKS FROM AN UNGRATEFUL VISITOR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Abother in a series about visitors' reactions to us:  &UR; Dennis &LR; 
 &UR; Cavagnaro  &LR; forwards a report on Silicon Valley from the London
Evening Standard, in  &UR; Zoe Williams &LR; ' column, ``Slut's Guide.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams says she liked the sound of Silicon (high technology,
enormous riches) Valley (lush and verdant). However:
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley is no single place, she writes. ``There are six
bits of it. They're all called things beginning with `San,' apart
from the ones beginning with `Sunny,' and actually they're not
places at all, they're splodges of nothingness along a big nothingy
motorway. If you want to find geeks, you have to really want to
find them, even before you factor in the cast-iron truth that they
never go out, and they get their social kicks in Internet chat
rooms with pretend people.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams describes visits to several South Bay bars, at which
she is ultimately approached by one ``geek'' (her term) or other.
``Sooner or later, they will start to address some information to
their feet _ it will be well-thought-out, knowledgeable and have
your best interests at heart. It will crucify you with boredom ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a Good Time Girl in the world who could have a
good time here,'' the columnist concludes. `` &UR; Mary Poppins  &LR; would
lose her marbles. It's no place for a slut.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KATHIE LEE: THE IN-DEPTH REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kathie Lee Gifford &LR; 's decision to drop out of ``Live With Regis
and Kathie Lee'' has been analyzed by gossipists all across the
country:
</P>
<P>
   - The announcement came ``at a time when it appeared tensions
were building on the air between Gifford, 46, and Philbin, 65, over
the sizzling success of his game show, `Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,' '' said the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Kathie Me, who is obviously feeling very upstaged by co-host
Reege ... is planning to park her butt in her summer manse (in
Nantucket) once her TV deal runs out in July. Oh, joy,'' said the
Boston Herald.
</P>
<P>
   - Gifford carefully announced her decision on Tuesday, opined
MSNBC, because of the printing schedules of the supermarket
tabloids, so they couldn't ``rehash all her problems with Frank.
... This way, they'll have to wait until the next week, and then it
might be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   - But what will she do in TV retirement? Gifford, who has
written books on child-rearing and a 1995 memoir, ``Listen to My
Heart'' (Hyperion; $13.95), may combine a literary career with
mothering. ``Kathie Lee seems to be a very involved mother,'' wrote
a customer reviewer who calls the book ``heartwarming'' on
Amazon.com. ``She is not afraid to discuss Cody's bowel functions
in detail. Everything about Cody is cute. Every detail. A must-have
book!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Reading of the Israelis' decision to make public the prison
diaries of war criminal  &UR; Adolf Eichmann &LR; , Personals turned to the
Web to see if a copy of the journals was already online. The Alta
Vista search engine found no copies of the diaries, but a notice
from CD Now invited the browser to ``own the music of the Eichmann
diary.''
</P>
<P>
   - The Miss USA contest this year _ and the next two _ will be
held in Gary, Ind., a city that ``is thriving,'' said  &UR; Maureen &LR; 
 &UR; Reidy &LR; , president of the Miss Universe Organization, which runs the
pageant. The event is owned by  &UR; Donald Trump &LR; , who owns a casino
and hotel in Gary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Donna Karan &LR; , a friend of  &UR; Jo Schuman Silver &LR; 's, attended
``Beach Blanket Babylon'' last weekend and didn't mind the
giant-sized knockoff of her DKNY beret, worn by the show's Monica.
Karan vowed to come back with her pal,  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; , who she
thought would love the ``BBB'' parody of the singer as egomaniac.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Andrew Demcak &LR;  saw a sign on a Berkeley construction site
that said ``No Parking Zone Until After Feb. 30th.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year I've lost 33 pounds. ... I am a fat person
and I accept my fat completely, so I feel strange jogging to lose
weight. It's almost as if it is something which is against my
values to want to be less fat. But I am a diabetic and I had to
reduce my blood sugar, which is connected to being fat. Most people
are proud when they lose weight. I find myself apologizing.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; David Crosby &LR;  to Personals &LR; ' &LR;  spy  &UR; Baird Jones &LR; , at an HBO
premiere party in New York for ``If These Walls Could Talk 2.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3656 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-REBELS-ART     03-01 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-REBELS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DOBROSIN ,  Yugoslavia: at us.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The soldiers can return fire, he said. Wouldn't that encourage
the Albanians to fire on the Americans if the Serbs came, to make
it seem as if the Serbs were shooting? He shrugged again, saying he
could not provide his name.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans now have checkpoints and towers along the three
main roads into the area, officials said. But despite those, it was
a simple matter to drive over primitive country roads of mud, ice
and snow in a four-wheel-drive vehicle and avoid any checkpoint, in
a region that has for centuries been used by smugglers and drug
runners.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters were nervous Wednesday, even brusque, and would not
give their names or allow photographs of their faces. In fact, they
did not really want journalists around at all.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday they shot up a car belonging to the office of the
U.N. high commissioner for refugees, which had come from Belgrade
and apparently did not stop at one of their checkpoints. An
Irishman was wounded in the leg, and the fighters, embarrassed and
worried about a possible Serbian response, took the man and his
Serbian interpreter to the Americans near the watchtower for
medical help.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters say their organization was born on Jan. 26, when
two local farmers here, brothers named Isa and Shaip Saqipi, 36 and
32, were killed by the Serbian police as they were returning to the
village from cutting wood in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers say the Serbs of the militarized police were on an
operation, with full uniforms, flak jackets and heavy weapons,
including a tank. Some seven Serb policemen were in the village,
with 40 more in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last time the Serbian police have shown up here,
but this village of about 1,500 now has fewer than 30 families
living in it, the rest having fled into Kosovo, staying with
friends and relatives in Gnjilane, Malisevo and Podgradje, where
the Americans have another checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live here with one eye open,'' said Halim Hasani, a teacher
in the village. ``We're always ready to flee.'' He said people were
afraid now even to go shopping in Bujanovac, because the Serbian
police had checkpoints along the road and sometimes turned the
villagers back.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 1945 until today, the municipality of Bujanovac has not
given a penny to the village of Dobrosin,'' Hasani said. And he
said that except for the police, no Serbian official, whether tax
collector or postman, had shown up in the village for two years.
``Really we're in Kosovo and we want to be in Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But of course they are not in Kosovo. Hasani asked, ``If the
Serbs attack in Dobrosin, can the Americans come to help?'' Told
that the answer seemed to be no, he seemed very thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the presence of the fighters might bring the
Serbian police back to Dobrosin, he went silent, then said,
``Possibly.'' He stopped, then added hopefully: ``But they attack
no one. They are only working to defend our land.''
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes these fighters do attack, and they are being
disingenuous when they say their group was born with the deaths of
the Saqipi brothers a month ago. The Serbian police have been
complaining of attacks on Serbian villagers around Medvedja since
the late summer, and U.N. officials in Pristina say the group has
been active in Dobrosin at least since November.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January three Serbs were killed in nearby Mucibaba,
closer to Presevo, and the Serbs moved at least four units of the
Interior Ministry's militarized police to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Ambushes of policemen have intensified, with one killed and
three wounded last weekend. One Albanian fighter was also killed in
a shootout. And the Serbs say they found a bomb over the weekend in
a courthouse in Bujanovac, which they blamed on ``armed Albanian
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Attacks on moderate or loyal Albanian politicians in Serbia have
also increased, including the murder last month of Zemail Mustafi,
the Albanian vice president of the Bujanovac branch of President
Slobodan Milosevic's ruling Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   And more Albanian civilians _ nearly 300, according to the
United Nations _ have gone into Kosovo from Serbia proper since
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``KFOR is being played with by these guys,'' said a senior U.N.
official, who is assuming that their leadership is based in Kosovo
and tied to parts of the supposedly disbanded Kosovo Liberation
Army.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the official says he believes that the leaders
are associated with Rexhep Selimi, who headed the rebel group's
ministry for public order and security. But no one seems to know
for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. James Shufelt, in an interview at the U.S. military
headquarters at Camp Bondsteel, said: ``The concern here isn't that
the Serbian police will come across, but that Albanian attacks on
the Serb police and army will inspire a response great enough to
cause public clamor for a KFOR response.''
</P>
<P>
   His commander, Gen. Ricardo Sanchez, said: ``The Presevo valley
is a significant concern for us. We are making a significant effort
to control the activity running across that boundary. I don't
believe we can ever fully seal the border between Serbia and
Kosovo. But we have sent a clear message that any cross-border
insurgency will not be tolerated or supported.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, ``we've gotten some very good
feedback that the people of Dobrosin feel better because of our
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Better, but perhaps emboldened, too. The fighters are exercising
within sight of the U.S. watchtowers, and say that once, when the
Serbian police were near the village, U.S. helicopters flew
overhead and the Serbs withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Vahid Sylejman, 39, a villager, said he was sure the Americans
would come to their rescue if the Serbs came again. ``Why else are
they there?'' he asked, pointing to the tanks on the ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Zajidi said: ``We have a kind of protection from the Americans.
If they were not on the hill, no one would be left in this village
at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
