<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3659 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-BAXTER-BUSH-COX     03-01 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush looking more relaxed, confident
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ George W. Bush was a much different candidate when he
came to town this week than on his first campaign trip here last
year _ or for that matter, in the frenzied days before the South
Carolina primary a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was already asleep in a Gwinnett County hotel Tuesday night
when news arrived of his victory in Washington State, topping an
evening when he also won big in Virginia and North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Looking relaxed with his front-runner status for the first time,
Bush beamed at a large and enthusiastic rally the next morning at
the Gwinnett Civic Center. This was billed as a ``One on One with
Gov. Bush,'' and the candidate took a dozen questions from the
floor, town-meeting style, on subjects ranging from OPEC to this
week's shooting of a six-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But this big, boisterous event could also be viewed as the
moment when the presidential campaign diverged from the intimate,
retail style of the early, spotlighted states and into a series of
mass-media, multi-state contests that begins with Titanic Tuesday
next week and culminates in the General Election this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Retail politics, and John McCain, have left their mark. Bush's
organization is still buttoned-down, as it was before the jolting
competition with McCain forced changes in its approach, but the
candidate has become vastly more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   After taking questions at the rally Bush ducked into a side room
for a series of short one-on-ones with local television, strolled
into the media filing room for an availability with the traveling
press, sat around a table for another 20 minutes with some local
print reporters, then zipped downtown for an editorial board at the
Journal-Constitution before flying away, feet propped on the
bulwark of his charter jet, still answering questions from an
Austin reporter who sat at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates give a lot of interviews, but McCain's
continuous dialogue with the media has clearly had an effect on
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In the media room, Bush carefully walked around a question about
whether he could be friends with McCain after the tough exchanges
they've had in the past few weeks. Later, asked jokingly about
McCain as a running mate, Bush answered in a way that showed the
grudging respect he has learned for his opponent - and the distance
that has grown between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game in politics, if I really wanted to play the game,
would be, 'Oh, John would make a great vice president.' But I mean,
he deseves better than that. This is a man who's still got a shot
to be the president,'' Bush said. ``The old-style politics is to
start talking about your opponent in terms of the vice-presidency,
and I'm not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he meant McCain still had a shot this year, Bush said,
``He's a viable candidate until he says, I quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it was in the spirit of not taking things for granted
that he came to this rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia's an important state, not only in the primary but in
the general election,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of this setting for a rally the week before Titanic
Tuesday probably had less to do with shoring up support in Georgia
than it did with its effectiveness as an image of a wider national
campaign, one less susceptible to the ravages of retail and the
tire burns of the Straight Talk Express.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
