A3660 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBN-ROCKER-REAX-COX     03-01 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker's teammates seem willing to forgiveBy Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ The teammate that John Rocker insulted will be
waiting for him. So will the core of influential veterans who make
the Braves clubhouse ``a doctor's office.'' And the manager he
accused of lying.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker has had 10 weeks to formulate his comments for this
morning's reunion with his old team, and the meeting could
determine his future with the Atlanta Braves. But his teammates
might never be in a more receptive mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the one to judge anybody,'' said first baseman Randall
Simon, whom Rocker disparaged as a ``fat monkey.'' ``We are all
sinners and we all make mistakes sometimes, and we are all forgiven
the sins we have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why not forgive the man and give him another chance and
hope that chance will be appreciated, so he can go about his
business and try to treat people better?''
</P>
<P>
   The team held a 40-minute players-only meeting Wednesday to
address that precise issue. Tom Glavine and a few other veteran
players stood up to assess Rocker's return and to make sure, as one
said, ``We're all on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, this is good,'' catcher Javy Lopez said. ``It's better
to get this over with. Go through hell now. Then when the season's
starts, it'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The reduction of Rocker's suspension did not come as a surprise
to the clubhouse. His confrontation with the team is an inevitable
part of the process; a shortened punishment just hastens it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good for us,'' shortstop Ozzie Guillen said. ``I'm not
surprised. Are you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have him show up and explain everything,'' catcher
Eddie Perez said. ``I think he will. He needs to talk a little with
everybody and be the same guy that we know from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something John's going to have to deal with a lot more
than anybody else in here,'' reliever Terry Mulholland said. ``I
know it's a hot issue with a lot of people, but I don't see where
his actions would have any effect on me or any other people. We all
have choices in life to make, and you hope everybody makes the
right choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there something specific that the Braves want to hear from
Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there have to be changes,'' Tom Glavine said. ``I'm
not sure what they are. But there are issues that go beyond what
was mentioned in that article.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see what he's going to do,'' Simon said. ``How he's
going to handle himself and all those things. Let's see what
happens. I hope everything goes fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Can John Rocker make it right with the team he maligned?
   ``Yeah, I think so,'' Perez said. ``We need him to be quiet
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker? Quiet?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's going to be tough,'' Perez said. ``But we have a
lot of old tapes around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
