<HEADER>
A3663 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-GLF-COMPTON-COX     03-01 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COMPTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compton may have heart of a champion
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Erik Compton has a pulse pounding for two people today
at the Doral-Ryder Open. It's for him and for a girl who gave him
the heart that has been beating in his chest for 8 years.
</P>
<P>
   They will be on the first tee at Doral's Blue Monster today,
making history. Compton, a redshirt freshman at the University of
Georgia, becomes the first heart transplant recipient to play in a
PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   They have had other firsts: Compton is the first
heart-transplant recipient on a full scholarship in NCAA history
and the first to play in the U.S. Amateur. Some day, the way things
are progressing, Compton, 20, will become the first
heart-transplant recipient to earn a PGA Tour card.
</P>
<P>
   And that will be just one more reason to thank the girl for
allowing him to live. Eight years ago, when a virus attacked
Compton's heart and enlarged it to where it would not beat
normally, he needed the transplant before his 13th birthday. Now he
is changing shoes in the same locker room with Greg Norman, David
Duval and Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down inside, when I go to bed every night, I'm not
thinking so much about the golf, that here I am with somebody
else's heart,'' Compton said. ``I think about that somebody is not
here, and I am here right now. It's something special that I keep
with me, and I think that keeps driving me to do better. . . . I'm
taking the person who is with me this week on a very nice journey,
I would say.''
</P>
<P>
   That the journey begins in Miami makes it magical. It's where
Compton watched the Doral tournament since he first picked up a
club as a youngster. He worked with Jim McLean, the resort's
instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being out here with my friends, running around
getting autographs and trying to find balls in the lake,'' Compton
said. ``I am in awe, very much in awe, about these guys. Now, I'm
sitting here on the third hole (in a practice round), and Norman's
helicopter is flying over. . . . I'm sitting in the locker room,
and these guys are running around in their boxers. It's a lot
different. It's something I never thought I would see.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton's invitation to the event came because he is a Miami
native and a heart-transplant recipient. But if he can contain his
nerves, he might make the cut. Compton, 20, occasionally hits
300-yard drives; he averages around 280. He also knows Doral's
greens so well that he can strike putts without even checking the
break. He's a former American Junior Golf Association player of the
year. In November, he won the Golf World collegiate tournament at
Palmetto Dunes on Hilton Head Island, shooting 13-under par.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I'm putting and hitting, I feel really confident,''
Compton said. ``I think that I have a good chance of making the
cut. (But) I could go out there and be nervous and shank it all
around the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton has earned respect from other golfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him last year and he's a great kid,'' said Curtis
Strange, who awarded a courageous athlete award to Compton in
Chicago. ``That's the kind of stories we need out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton has strived for normality at every opportunity. He faces
an annual biopsy and twice daily takes anti-rejection pills, which
can break down his immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just like any normal 20-year-old,'' Compton said. ``I go
out there and say the wrong things and jump around and be a punk,
but when I look at everything at the end of the day, I really
realize how far I've come with my game and my life. . . . It
doesn't make a huge amount of difference in my life if I miss a
small putt to lose a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Gilbert, of Rochester, N.Y., will be at Doral this week.
Gilbert, who also has a heart ailment, met Compton at the U.S.
Amateur at Oak Hill in 1998. Their families ate dinner together
that week, have communicated through e-mails and will be reunited.
Compton lost his first-round match that week, but gained a lot more
through Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had seen he in some articles right after his surgery,''
Compton said. ``He had lost hope, and he was ready to give up. He
lost a lot of weight, and he was very depressed about his body. But
just going through a lot of the things I went through, it helped
him to see me on the golf course making something happen and
starting a new life.''
</P>
<P>
   The life this week isn't too shabby, Compton noted. After months
in a hospital, a 20-year-old college kid gets pretty wired about
somebody cooking up a free stir-fried lunch in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing,'' he said, ``was going in the locker room and
shaving with a Mach III razor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
