<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3664 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-TUCKER-ROCKER-COX     03-01 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUCKER-ROCKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ruling nearly as offensive as comments
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shyam Das doesn't have the final say, you know.
</P>
<P>
   If he did, John Rocker would be getting off very light: a 14-day
regular-season suspension and a $500 fine. Geez, the suspension is
only four days longer than a Yankees outfielder named Jake Powell
got in 1938 for racist comments, and you'd think that the
subsequent 62 years of enlightenment would have raised the
appropriate sanction more than that. And the $500 fine, well,
that's a joke, considering that baseball usually doesn't consider
any dollar figure with fewer than five, six, seven or eight zeroes
worth mentioning.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred dollars. That's almost as offensive as Rocker's
comments. I mean, he will make 10 times that much per inning.
</P>
<P>
   But, alas, none of this is surprising. In recent decades,
baseball arbitrators almost always have overturned or reduced
suspensions and fines. If Das had done otherwise in his
baseball-arbitrating debut, it would have been the biggest upset
since the '69 Mets. And in fairness to Das, it's not necessarily
unreasonable to conclude that if Roberto Alomar was suspended only
five days for spitting in an umpire's face, maybe Rocker shouldn't
have been suspended for a month, as he was by Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, Alomar should have been suspended for two months. So
Rocker benefits, I guess, from a system as crazy as his comments.
Which is not to say he's necessarily getting off as light as it
seems. Because, remember, Das doesn't have the final say. ...
</P>
<P>
   Oh, his word is final about the suspension and the fine. But
Rocker's future in baseball _and, more immediately, with the Braves
_ will be decided by his teammates, his manager, his general
manager. Now that Das has ruled, their deliberations begin.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this probably is the venue where the case should have
been adjudicated from the start. The heart of the matter is not
whether Selig wants Rocker in the game in April. It is whether the
Braves want him in their uniform.
</P>
<P>
   And their decision, unlike Selig's, will not be subject to
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   There are real problems with Rocker remaining a Brave, from the
abstract issue of clubhouse chemistry to the concrete issue of
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   His chances of sticking around are enhanced by his teammates'
calm, pragmatic professionalism _ one of the things, come to think
of it, that he ripped in that Sports Illustrated article. But no
one expects reassimilation to come easily or quickly.
</P>
<P>
   John Schuerholz says there is a market for the tarnished closer
if he chooses to trade him, a possibility the GM pointedly does not
minimize. But because Rocker is young, talented and, by baseball
standards, cheap, there has been no rush to unload him.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Braves argued against a reduction in Selig's
sanctions, Das' ruling that Rocker can report to spring training
probably benefits the team. Better, surely, to deal with the mess
when the games don't count than when they do.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rocker ruckus is far from over, the final Rocker verdict
far from reached. And there's nothing more Shyam Das can do for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
