<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-ATL-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta groups want Rocker out
 &HT;    By Paul Donsky
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A coalition of metro Atlanta community groups is
calling for the Braves to trade John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The group blasted an arbitrator's ruling on Wednesday that cut
Rocker's suspension in half and dramatically reduced his fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been insulted by this arbitrator. And I hope and I
pray that the Braves would do the right thing,'' said
</P>
<P>
   the Rev. Timothy McDonald, president of Concerned Black Clergy.
``John Rocker needs to be traded. Send him to Montreal or wherever,
make him a foreigner... Trade John Rocker and make all of us
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition represents about 30 local organizations, including
clergy, AIDS groups and various ethnic and cultural groups. It
formed after Sports Illustrated published a story in which Rocker
made comments offensive to gays, blacks, Asian-Americans and
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference yesterday, the coalition said it has asked
the Braves for a face-to-face meeting with Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to look in the face of the coalition members who
represent the diversity which is Atlanta and say to them, 'I'm
sorry,''' Atlanta City Councilman Derrick Boazman said. ``We hope
that he would be contrite. Whether or not his heart is as dark as
his comments, we don't know that. Only John Rocker would be able to
answer that.''
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb NAACP President John Evans said he is shocked Rocker is
getting off with such a light punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any of us ... were working for somebody and made all kinds
of raunchy comments, we would be fired immediately,'' Evans said.
``So what we are finding here is that profits still govern the
kinds of decisions that ought to be made on some moral and
character basis in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. McDonald said the arbitrator's ruling sends a dangerous
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a message that says hatred is okay. Racism is OK. Bigotry
is OK. Homophobia is OK,'' he said. ``You can call people what you
want to call them, you can say what you want to say, you can label
any way you want to label, and in our society, it's okay. We'll
give you a slap on the wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
