<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3671 &Cx1f; tab-z
w d BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV15-     03-01 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV15-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV15 
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: RISOTTO WITH FENNEL AND MUSHROOMS OR
ASPARAGUS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20-MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text.  (th) 
 By MARIAN BURROS 
 c. 2000 Foxcraft Ltd.  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    This week's column is not devoted to a menu, though it would
take very little to turn it into one. It is, instead, a wonderful
technique that one of the country's best chefs, Patrick O'Connell
of the Inn at Little Washington in Washington, Va., has devised for
making risotto in two stages so that when you truly want a virtual
no-work dinner, you can have something as satisfying as risotto and
have it ready in 15 minutes.
 &HT;    My quick version, that has often appeared in this column, takes
25 minutes and you really have to hustle to get it done. Using
Patrick O'Connell's technique you can make risotto on the weekend
for two workday nights and leave very little work for the last
minute.
 &HT;    Add a salad and you've got dinner.
 &HT;    You can use this recipe to make any kind of risotto you like.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Make-Ahead Risotto with Fennel and Mushrooms or with Asparagus
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Time: 30 to 40 minutes (15 to 20 minutes for the make-ahead
risotto; 15 minutes to finish the dish)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    For the make-ahead risotto:
 &HT;    
 &HT;    8 cups no-salt added chicken stock
 &HT;    1-1/2 tablespoons olive oil
 &HT;    Small onion to yield 1 cup chopped
 &HT;    2 cups arborio rice
 &HT;    
 &HT;    1. In a small saucepan, bring 4 cups of chicken stock to a boil.
Reduce heat, and keep stock at a simmer.
 &HT;    2. Heat medium nonstick saucepan until it is very hot; reduce
heat to medium and add oil. Add onion, and saute until onion is
translucent. Add rice, and stir until it is evenly coated.
 &HT;    3. Reduce heat to medium-low. Slowly add simmering stock, about
1 cup at a time, stirring until rice absorbs liquid. When all stock
has been absorbed, remove risotto from heat. Immediately spread
onto a baking sheet to stop the cooking, and cool as quickly as
possible; rice grains will still be a bit raw at center.
Refrigerate uncovered until chilled, then transfer to a covered
container. Partly cooked risotto may be refrigerated for up to 2
days.
 &HT;    To finish half the risotto with fennel and mushrooms:
 &HT;    
 &HT;    About 1-1/2 to 2 cups no-salt added chicken stock
 &HT;    1 large bulb fennel or 2 small
 &HT;    2 teaspoons olive oil
 &HT;    4 ounces whole mushrooms, any kind
 &HT;    Few shakes salt
 &HT;    Freshly ground black pepper
 &HT;    
 &HT;    1. Trim bottom of fennel and remove tough outer portions and
top. Slice remaining bulb thinly.
 &HT;    2. Heat a nonstick pan large enough to hold the fennel and
mushrooms until it is very hot. Add 2 teaspoons oil and saute the
fennel until it is almost tender, a few minutes.
 &HT;    3. Heat 3 cups stock to a simmer.
 &HT;    4 Wash trim and slice the mushrooms and add to the fennel as it
cooks.
 &HT;    5. Spoon half of the partially cooked risotto into a saucepan
large enough to hold all the ingredients.
 &HT;    6. Add 1 cup stock and cook over medium-low heat, stirring until
stock is absorbed. Repeat until stock has been absorbed and the
risotto is tender. Stir in the fennel and mushrooms; season with
salt and pepper and serve.
 &HT;    You may not need all the stock. The risotto should be creamy,
the rice tender but firm.
 &HT;    Yield: 2 servings.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    YOUR PANTRY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Olive oil
 &HT;    Onion
 &HT;    Salt
 &HT;    Whole black pepper
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SHOPPING LIST
 &HT;    
 &HT;    10 cups no-salt added chicken stock
 &HT;    Package arborio rice
 &HT;    1 large bulb fennel or 2 small
 &HT;    4 ounces whole mushrooms, any kind
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Nutrition Information per serving: 640 calories, 17 grams fat,
20 milligrams cholesterol, 435 milligrams sodium, 20 grams protein,
100 grams carbohydrate
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    To finish the risotto with asparagus:
 &HT;    1-1/2 to 2 cups no salt added chicken stock
 &HT;    1 pound asparagus
 &HT;    Few shakes salt
 &HT;    Freshly ground black pepper
 &HT;    
 &HT;    1. Bring chicken stock to simmer.
 &HT;    2. Wash and remove tough stems from asparagus by breaking
asparagus where tender part meets woody party. Cut spears into
1/2-inch pieces. Add to simmering chicken stock and cook about 5
minutes; remove asparagus when they are tender but still firm.
 &HT;    3. Spoon remaining half of partially cooked risotto into a
saucepan large enough to hold all the ingredients.
 &HT;    4. Add 1 cup stock and cook over medium-low heat, stirring until
stock is absorbed. Repeat until stock has been absorbed and the
risotto is tender. Stir in the asparagus; season with salt and
pepper and serve.
 &HT;    You may not need all the stock. The risotto should be creamy,
the rice tender but firm.
 &HT;    Yield: 2 servings.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    YOUR PANTRY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Olive oil
 &HT;    Onion
 &HT;    Salt
 &HT;    Whole black pepper
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SHOPPING LIST
 &HT;    
 &HT;    10 cups no-salt added chicken stock
 &HT;    Package arborio rice
 &HT;    1 pound asparagus
