<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3672 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      03-01 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH SAYS MCCAIN SHOULD BE `ASHAMED' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By Dan Freedman  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Fresh from his clean sweep in three states'
Republican primaries, Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Wednesday he
plans to win ``every state I compete in'' and that his opponent,
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., should be ``ashamed'' for portraying
Bush as anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hop-scotched across the country, appearing at rallies in
suburban Atlanta, and St. Louis and Springfield in Missouri before
flying off to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in Los Angeles, Bush, McCain and former ambassador
Alan Keyes will hold their final debate before ``Super Tuesday,''
the major round of 13 Republican contests including the big prizes
of New York, with 101 delegates, California with 162, and Ohio with
69.
</P>
<P>
   McCain backed out of the debate last weekend citing scheduling
conflicts but jumped back in after his defeats Tuesday in
Washington, North Dakota and Virginia. McCain will take part in the
debate via satellite. Bush too had thought of joining the debate
through satellite but decided Wednesday to attend in person.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly in an upbeat mood, Bush greeted supporters in Duluth,
Ga., northwest of Atlanta, saying, ``You might notice I walked in
with a little spring in my step.'' He added that this week's
primary victories ``helped us take a step closer to ending the
Clinton era in Washington D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign staff hailed the Tuesday primary results,
particularly in the state of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its progressive tradition and concentration of
independent-minded voters, Washington ``was a state supposedly made
to order for McCain,'' Bush's spokeswoman Karen Hughes said.
``Obviously, that did not occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush now has 178 Republican convention delegate votes, according
to his staff's calculations, and McCain has 103. Needed to win the
nomination: 1,034.
</P>
<P>
   In California a Los Angeles Times poll Wednesday showed Bush
ahead of McCain among Republicans 47 percent to 26 percent. In the
state's so-called ``blanket'' primary all candidates, regardless of
party, appear on a single ballot, and the top vote-getter will win
the ``beauty contest.'' But delegates to the national nominating
conventions will be selected on the basis of party-member votes
alone.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Bush-McCain race is a seesaw. A Zogby
International poll Wednesday showed McCain leading Bush by 44.1
percent to 38.4 percent. Last week, the same poll showed Bush
leading McCain 43.5 percent to 40.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on winning New York,'' Bush told reporters. ``I plan on
winning every state I compete in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush trails McCain in Connecticut, Vermont and Massachusetts
polls, but he leads the Arizona Republican in Georgia, Ohio and
Missouri. All hold primaries next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush showed throughout the day that he was still sensitive to
the fact that McCain surrogates have called Catholic voters and
criticized Bush for speaking at Bob Jones University in South
Carolina and failing to reject the school's anti-Catholic
statements.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday McCain went further by labeling two strong Bush
supporters, Christian conservatives Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell, as ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the McCain tactics, Bush told reporters after the
Duluth rally, ``I don't like to be called an anti-Catholic bigot.''
As governor of Texas, Bush said, he has ``a record of being
inclusive. The people of Texas know my record. People know my
heart. And John ought to be ashamed of running that kind of
campaign. It's going to backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush cited Catholics quoted in the Boston Globe as backing him
in his dispute with McCain. Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston said
that Bob Jones University is a regular stop on the Republican
campaign circuit and that no previous candidate who spoke there has
been accused of anti-Catholic bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that place (the university) has some strange views,
but that doesn't mean one shouldn't go there and speak,'' Law told
the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush has sought over the last few days to refute
any perception that by appearing at the school and not mentioning
its anti-Catholic sentiments as well as its ban on interracial
dating, he was condoning those practices.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend he apologized for failing to bring them up during
his Bob Jones appearance. On Tuesday he spoke at a hastily arranged
rally in Cleveland at the Fatima Family Center, a Catholic charity.
And on Wednesday, Bush addressed supporters at a rally at St. Louis
University, a Jesuit institution.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after the Duluth rally, Bush mocked
McCain's strategy of aiming first to attract independents and
Democrats and then branching out to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a Republican primary,'' he noted. ``I intend to
consolidate the party, consolidate the base and reach out to
independents and Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the fatal shooting of a 6-year-old girl by a
6-year-old boy at a Michigan school on Tuesday, Bush said the
parents or guardians of the boy who did the shooting ``need to be
held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor asked, ``How did this boy get a gun?'' He called
for technology that would ensure that only a gun's owner could fire
it, and said owners should use trigger locks. But he added that he
didn't want ``the trigger-lock police knocking on people's doors''
and therefore opposed making the locks mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed making such locks mandatory. The
issue is a sensitive one for Bush because his victory strategy
involves carrying his home state of Texas and other states in the
South and West where gun enthusiasts vote in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Wednesday that technology is on its way to perfecting
a mechanism that unlocks a trigger only when matched, for instance,
to the fingerprints of its owner.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)earstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
