<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-PUERTO-RICO-STATEHOOD     03-01 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-RICO-STATEHOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PUERTO RICO'S GOVERNOR PRESSES FOR VOTE ON STATEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello lobbied Congress
Wednesday to join a White House-led effort that could clear the way
for the former Spanish colony to become the nation's 51st state.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello urged members of the House and Senate to approve a
White House request for $2.5 million to underwrite a landmark
federal effort to end Puerto Rico's ambiguous political status as a
U.S. commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello said the support of leading Republican and Democratic
presidential candidates for Puerto Rico's self-determination offers
an ``opportunity'' to resolve the nagging political status
``problem'' that dates back to the U.S. acquisition of Puerto Rico
after the Spanish-American War in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a willingness and a sensitivity that maybe this is a
time to finally resolve this century old problem,'' Rossello told a
news conference following meetings on Capitol Hill. ``I think the
elements are there for a significant movement this year and a
conclusion during the next term to this conundrum.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, a pro-statehood Democratic ally of President Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, made
no direct reference to the growing Hispanic political influence
that is being courted in key electoral states such as New York,
Texas, California and Florida by the Democratic and Republican
presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   But Rossello noted that during his meetings with seven members
of Congress on Wednesday, ``certainly we've impressed upon them the
fact that this is a year where significant advancement can made.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossello said he hopes that a White House conference with
members of Congress and political leaders from Puerto Rico could
begin deliberations shortly that ``would result this year in a
definite recommendation'' on a binding plebiscite in Puerto Rico
giving voters a clear choice between statehood, independence and
continuation of commonwealth status.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-statehood advocates contend that three prior referendums on
Puerto Rico's political status were torpedoed because the ballot
was either too confusing or it included the option of ``none of the
above.''
</P>
<P>
   As a commonwealth, Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens by birth and
subject to conscription into the armed forces but they do not vote
in presidential elections or pay federal income taxes. Puerto Rico
receives more than $11 billion annually in federal payments. The
island's 3.8 million residents are represented in Congress by a
popularly elected non-voting delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico, with a population about the size of South Carolina,
would qualify for two U.S. senators and seven members of Congress.
Puerto Rico's population is larger than 25 states that have voting
representation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The White House-backed effort to update Puerto Rico's
commonwealth status was a little noticed sweetener in a deal that
Rossello struck with Clinton on Jan. 31 to permit the Navy and
Marine Corps to resume modified combat training on the small Puerto
Rican island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello is working with the Clinton administration to rally
public support in Puerto Rico behind the hard-won compromise _ a
deal that ignited the largest protest march in a generation in San
Juan on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on Vieques calls for Washington to provide $40
million in economic development assistance to the island's 9,300
residents, reduce noisy military training and hold a binding
referendum on future Navy use of the island by February 2002. The
Navy owns two-thirds of the Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   If residents vote for the Navy to leave, the Navy will withdraw
by 2003. If residents vote to permit resumption of live-fire combat
training, the plan calls for the White House and Congress to
provide another $50 million in assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello is banking that winning a binding referendum to settle
Puerto Rico's political status with the United States will quell
opposition to the deal he struck on Vieques. The two-term governor
steps down next January.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico gained its commonwealth status in 1952 after half a
century as a colony.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to revamp Puerto Rico's political status have a
checkered history. In the last referendum, on Dec. 13, 1998, voters
confronted five options, including statehood, independence, ``free
association,'' commonwealth status and ``none of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 50.3 percent of the voters opted for ``none of the above,''
defeating the 46.5 percent of the voters who favored statehood.
Independence won 2.5 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the referendum was not binding. Legislation to
hold a binding referendum had stalled in the Senate after winning
approval in the House in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier referendum on Nov. 14, 1993, voters rejected
statehood and voted to retain the island's existing political
status. Commonwealth status won 48.4 percent of the vote; statehood
won 46.2 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The breadth of Rossello's meetings on Capitol Hill underscored
the bipartisan appeal of an issue that is of keen interest to many
Hispanic voters, including the Puerto Rican voters in New York who
can cast ballots in the Senate race that pits Hillary Clinton
against New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello consulted on Wednesday with Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee Chairman Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, and House
Resources Committee Chairman Rep. Don Young, R-Ark. _ two key
Republicans with jurisdiction over U.S. territories. Rossello also
met with Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, R-Fla., a prominent
Cuban-American with influential ties in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   And he met with Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.;
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.; Rep. Patrick
Kennedy, D-R.I., the chairman of the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee; and Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., chairman of
the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello is a popular fund-raiser among Hispanic audiences who
has pledged to campaign for Hillary Clinton and Gore's bid for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig said last week that the Navy is
hoping that public support will rally behind the compromise so that
the federal government can avoid rounding up and arresting the
several hundred protestors camped on the 899-acre bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff between the Navy and Puerto Rico began last April
19 when a Marine pilot mistakenly dropped two bombs on a target
range observation post, killing civilian security guard David Sanes
Rodriguez, 35, and wounding four other civilian workers on the
range. The outcry in Puerto Rico forced the Navy to suspend
training Atlantic-based forces on the target and maneuver range
that had prepared U.S. combat forces for every overseas operation
since the outset of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate forced the Navy in December to prepare the
aircraft carrier battle group led by USS Dwight D. Eisenhower for
operations in the Mediterranean and Persian Gulf without combat
rehearsals on Vieques. The Navy plans to use many of the same
alternatives in April to prepare the aircraft carrier battle group
led by USS George Washington for deployment overseas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
