<HEADER>
A3679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CANDIDATES-GUNS-BOS &LR;      03-01 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATES-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS HE SUPPORTS TRIGGER LOCKS FOR GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day after one first-grader fatally shot another at a
Michigan elementary school, gun control re-emerged as an issue in
the 2000 presidential campaign and forced Texas Gov. George W. Bush
to strike a delicate balance on the politically sensitive issue of
childproof trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people use trigger locks,'' Bush told reporters in
Atlanta Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican front-runner has often said he supports urging
gun makers and buyers to voluntarily add trigger locks. But
Wednesday a spokesman said he ``would have no problem'' signing
legislation mandating the devices.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stopped short, however, of actively calling for such a
measure, a version of which has been stalled in Congress for
months.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's muddy position reflects the difficult political pressures
he faces as he tries to appease core Republican conservatives and
respond to a growing public call for gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and his main rival, Arizona Sen. John McCain, were
pressed on the issue Wednesday as new details emerged about a
six-year-old boy near Flint, Mich. who found a loaded gun in his
home and brought it to school Monday, where he shot and killed a
six-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a horrific succession of school shootings
nationwide -- and the shooting of five more people at two
Pittsburgh restaurants Wednesday -- is bringing new scrutiny to the
candidates' positions on how to control gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even before this week, events like last year's massacre at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., have had voters and
candidates unusually focused on the issue, said Robert Spitzer, a
political science professor at the State University of New York and
author of ``The Politics of Gun Control.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the presidential campaign has reflected the fact
that voters have become ``more pro-gun control'' over the past 10
years, as the country becomes less rural and a smaller percentage
of households own firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Democratic and Republican candidates still differ
sharply in their approaches to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, both Vice President Al Gore and former
Senator Bill Bradley have talked frequently about measures to
toughen background checks, require trigger locks on new guns, and
create new licensing and registration systems to better track
firearms used in crimes and require that owners learn gun safety
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports the registration of all new guns and licensing for
new gun buyers, who would be required to pass safety tests. Bradley
would ``go much farther,'' in his words, by requiring that every
one of an estimated 65 million handguns in the country be licensed,
and that even current owners pass safety courses and be registered.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has also criticized Gore for casting votes against gun
control measures while he was in Congress, going so far as to say
Gore was ``pro-gun'' during the 1970s and 1980s. But Joe Sudbay,
political director for Handgun Control in Washington, D.C., said
the two Democrats ``are very similar'' in their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The real distinctions, Sudbay said, are between the Democrats
and the Republicans, whom he described as ``both very pro-gun and
both strong supporters of the gun lobby, especially the National
Rifle Association.'' Neither Bush nor McCain, for instance, has
proposed new licensing and registration measures.
</P>
<P>
   Sudbay said that Bush has shown no record of supporting gun
control measures in Texas, and encouraged the passage of two major
bills supported by the gun lobby. One measure allowed Texans to
carry concealed handguns with a permit. Another barred Texas cities
and counties from filing civil lawsuits against the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said Wednesday the Texas governor
prefers to enforce existing gun laws rather than pass new ones, and
believes strong leadership can quell gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor recognizes that solving this problem is more than
about laws, it's about condemning these acts of terror and changing
our culture,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan added that Bush supported a measure passed by the
House of Representatives last year to close the so-called ``gun
show loophole'' allowing convicted felons to purchase firearms from
unlicensed dealers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   But Sudbay said that provision, supported by the NRA, would
require only cursory checks and would allow dangerous felons to
slip through undetected.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that Bush was praised in an NRA fund-raising
letter last October which read, in part: ``Al Gore never met a gun
control proposal he didn't like -- while George Bush has staked out
just the opposite position.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudbay described McCain's record as almost indiscernable from
Bush's. While McCain has slightly moderated his positions on guns
in recent months -- dropping his one-time opposition to mandatory
trigger locks, for instance -- he has rarely supported gun control
measures during his 18 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for instance, voted against a gun-show background check
last spring. The senator also opposed the gun-control lobby's two
most prized achievements: a 1994 federal ban on assault weapons
ban, and the 1993 Brady Bill, which required a five-day waiting
period and background check for handgun purchases from licensed gun
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see how we tell a law-abiding citizen who wants to
purchase a firearm for the purpose of protecting his or her family
that they must wait to exercise that right,'' McCain says on his
campaign web site.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday both Bush and McCain say they support developing new
technology to create ``smart guns'' that can only be fired by their
owner, possibly through the use of computer chips or fingerprint
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Bush questioned whether trigger-lock laws could be enforced,
however, fretting about ``trigger lock police knocking on peoples'
doors, saying, `Show me your trigger locks, please?' .''
</P>
<P>
   But Sudbury said the criticism misses the point, because trigger
locks would be added in gun factories, not private homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
