<SLUG> BC-MA-BIGDIG-ACCOUNTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI TO HIRE ACCOUNTANTS TO SIFT BIG DIG FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL REZENDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seeking to shore up the damaged credibility of Big Dig
manager James K. Kerasiotes, Governor Paul Cellucci Wednesday
announced he would hire a major national accounting firm to oversee
the massive Central Artery contruction project and report directly
to one of Kerasiotes' political foes in the administraiton.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, having just returned from Washington where he lobbied
federal officials on behalf of the project, said he has directed
Secretary of Administration and Finance Andrew S. Natsios to hire
the firm in order to address a ``credibility problem'' created last
month by Kerasiotes' surprise announcement of a $1.4 billion cost
overrun on the $12.2 billion Big Dig project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure we have double-checked and triple-checked
the numbers,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios, who has clashed with Kerasiotes and advised Cellucci to
fire him, said the administration decided it was necessary to hire
an outside firm to guarantee ``full disclosure'' of the Central
Artery's financing.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he is looking for recommendations on how to save
money and for more accurate projections of future costs, including
change orders that he said are responsible for much of the current
cost overrun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to look at the process they use to make our own
determinations about what costs are, what the change orders are,
and how you price them and keep track of them,'' Natsios said.
</P>
<P>
   Jermey Crockford, Kerasiotes' chief of staff at the
Massachusetts Turnpike Authority, said Kerasiotes has put aside
past differences with Natsios and plans to cooperate with the firm
Natsios hires.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks it's absolutely a good idea,'' Crockford said. ``We
have a lot of eyes on us now, but it's obviously complicated so the
more people who come in and see if they have a different take on
what we're doing and ideas about what steps might be taken, the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Crockford said Kerasiotes met Wednesday with Cellucci to discuss
plans to enhance Natsios' oversight of the project, and later met
with members of the Legislature now considering a Cellucci proposal
to close the $1.4 billion funding gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was talking to legislators to reassure them that things are
going forward, that work is continuing, and that we think we have
our hands around the problem,'' Crockford said, ``and he cited this
as something he thought was a very good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kerasiotes' assurances were delivered the same day
legislators learned that all of the bids submitted for one of the
project's final contracts came in at least $21.8 million over
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of money,'' Cellucci said, adding that
administration officials will try to make up for it by having the
new accounting firm identity areas where costs can be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's move to hire his own accounting firm comes as a team
of federal auditors has descended on Boston to audit the project's
past accounting practices, a move spurred by Kerasiotes' failure to
deliver on repeated guarantees that the Central Artery/Ted Williams
Tunnel project would be completed ``on time and on budget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
