<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canadian men win major tournament
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How 'bout them Canucks, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Many of their countrymen have been fretting about the national
malaise in ice hockey _ the loss of NHL teams to U.S. cities and
the increasing prominence of European players. Meanwhile, the
Canadian men's soccer team on Sunday won its first major tournament
in a sport as unfamiliar in the Great White North as it is to many
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Canada claimed the CONCACAF Gold Cup by stunning Colombia 1-0 in
Los Angeles. A qualifier for the World Cup only once, in 1986,
Canada rounded up most of its roster from the lower divisions of
English and Scottish soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Canada qualified for the quarterfinals on a coin flip, then
shocked Mexico in overtime and pulled off a milder upset of
Trinidad &AMP; Tobago in the semifinals. Goalkeeper Craig Forrest, who
plays for West Ham in the English Premier League, was named MVP
after producing three shutout victories and stopping a penalty
kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a complete outsider,'' said Holger Osieck, Canada's
German coach.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexico and the U.S. -- both eliminated in the
quarterfinals -- are favored to get two of the region's three World
Cup spots, Canada's performance should make the CONCACAF qualifying
more competitive. One of the interesting sporting stats in that
country is that it has more registered soccer players than hockey
players.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad kicks off global 2002 World Cup qualifying Saturday
against the Netherlands Antilles by searching for a new coach.
Bertille St. Clair was fired Tuesday, and three starters have been
dropped from the team, as well, in light of their Gold Cup showing.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S., eliminated in the quarterfinals, plays Tunisia next
Sunday in a friendly at Birmingham's Legion Field.
</P>
<P>
   Feyenoord ends Lazio bid
</P>
<P>
   Dutch teams have been taking a beating in the European Champions
League this season, but Feyenoord's late rally to defeat Lazio 2-1
in Rome on Tuesday was one of several upsets as second round group
play resumed this week. Jon Dahl Tomasson came off the bench to
score in the 78th and 84th minute as the Rotterdam club ended
Lazio's attempt to tie Ajax Amsterdam -- ironically Feyenoord's
most bitter rival -- with a record 19 straight undefeated matches
in Europe....Real Madrid had been feeling good following last
week's 3-0 Spanish league win over Barcelona, but visiting Bayern
Munich came away with a 4-2 victory on Tuesday....Marseille has
been in miserable form in the French first division, but got a
terrific goal from Robert Pires from a sharp angle on the goal line
to defeat Chelsea 1-0....On Wednesday, Barcelona's Rivaldo and
Mario Jardel of Porto each scored twice, but the Spanish club won
comfortably 4-2....Defending champion Manchester United beat
Bordeaux by a 2-0 count, with Ryan Giggs and Teddy Sheringham doing
the honors.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Vieri injury blow
</P>
<P>
   Inter Milan striker Christian Vieri will miss at least the next
two weeks because of a pulled thigh muscle, putting him out of the
club's critical Sunday match against AC Milan, as well as next
week's contest with Lazio. Inter, in fourth place in Serie A and
seven games behind Juventus, is still missing Ronaldo to a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   England: Shearer to quit
</P>
<P>
   England captain Alan Shearer, citing family reasons along with a
clear decline in his play, will retire from international play
following this summer's European Championships. The Newcastle
striker, 29, has scored 28 times in 57 caps for England but has had
a frustrating run the last two years.... Tranmere Rovers coach John
Aldridge has been charged with misconduct by the Football
Association for allegedly striking Leicester City player Theo
Zagorakis during the Worthington League Cup final on Sunday.
Zagorakis, who was sitting on the bench, applauded a red card
issued to Tranmere's Clint Hill, and Aldridge charged the opposing
sideline in anger. Leicester won 2-1, with both goals coming from
Matt Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Ribbeck feels the heat
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified national-team player has caused a stir this week
for alleging in an interview that coach Erich Ribbeck is losing his
authority with players. The player told Kicker magazine that
several team stars, specifically striker Oliver Bierhoff and
midfielder Jens Jeremies, made ``some very loud comments'' at
halftime of Germany's 2-1 friendly loss to The Netherlands last
week while Ribbeck stayed mainly in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
