<HEADLINE>
INJURY RASH LEAVES FLYERS SEEING STARS, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 FIXES SPELLING OF SAMUELSSON, GOALS FOR THORNTON, (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ The Philadelphia Flyers come to town with an injury
list close to, if not, as formidable as any the Stars have
fashioned this season.
</P>
<P>
   Key players who weren't on the ice for the Flyers last night:
captain Eric Lindros (back), center Keith Primeau (rib), 18-year
veteran defenseman Ulf Samuelsson (left rotator cuff) and
defensemen Dan McGillis (groin) and Luke Richardson (right
collarbone).
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' point of view: tsk, tsk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, there's no sympathy from this camp for teams that
come in and have a few injuries,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams deadlocked, 1-1, in their other meeting of the
season, in Philadelphia. The injuries definitely soften the
anticipation of on-ice matchups. Stars defensemen Derian Hatcher
(6-foot-5, 230 pounds) and Richard Matvichuk (6-2, 215) trading
paint with Lindros (6-4, 236) and company is as anticipated a
matchup as any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know if I look too forward to it to be honest,''
Hatcher said. ``When you know you're playing against him 25
minutes, you have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars get the Flyers on the tail-end of back-to-back road
games. The Flyers lost to the Blues in St. Louis Tuesday night.
\Nsubheds:Thornton fitting in In the past five games, Stars forward
Scott Thornton has two goals and an assist. Putting pucks in the
net had seemed like a lost art to Thornton in Montreal. Two goals
in five games might not seem like many, but consider the 11-year
veteran has only four this season and his career high is 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get your hands above your head for a change,''
Thornton said. \Nsubheds:Langenbrunner plays with pain Each game,
Jamie Langenbrunner plays with a sore neck stemming from a nagging
pinched nerve. The forward has missed 14 games because of it. Last
night was to be his third game back after missing three consecutive
games with soreness.
</P>
<P>
   He endured a crosscheck to the back late in Friday's game
against Chicago that sent him to the ice face-first and kept him
there a few minutes, sending team trainer Dave Surprenant to his
aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult; it wasn't that hard of a hit that got me, so
that was frustrating,'' Langenbrunner said. ``It's more the
irritation in it right now that's causing the problems. It's there
pretty much all the time. You just deal with it.''
\Nsubheds:Lukowich swaps stick Rookie defenseman-turned-forward
Brad Lukowich traded in his thicker hockey stick for a
slimmed-down, graphite model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm using \RMike\S Modano's pattern now. It's the exact same
stick; it's unbelievable,'' said Lukowich, who is taking a crash
course in learning how to play forward. He only chuckled when it
was suggested that now he'll score as Mike does, too.
\Nsubheds:Briefly For the third consecutive day, a hip flexor kept
Brett Hull from skating. The injury isn't serious but won't go
away, Ken Hitchcock said. Hull, who is not expected to miss any
games, has earned points in six consecutive games (two goals, six
assists) going back to Feb. 18 at Phoenix. The Stars are scheduled
to visit the White House on March 16 in honor of their Stanley Cup
victory. Hitchcock said center Joe Nieuwendyk, out since Jan. 19
with a separated right shoulder, could return in 10 to 14 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
