<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts urge investors to tread carefully
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Raise some cash, keep an eye on the Federal Reserve
and don't panic.
</P>
<P>
   That's a sampling of advice investors are getting these days as
they try to make sense of a stock market torn between technology
bulls and blue chip bears.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed gets some of the blame for this turn of events by having
raised short-term interest rates in an effort to restrain what it
sees as a potentially inflationary economy.
</P>
<P>
   This has put a dent in financial, cyclical and other
interest-sensitive stocks of the so-called ``old economy,'' which
sent the Dow Jones industrial average tumbling 12 percent in the
first two months of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors have flocked to the stocks of chip makers,
telecom companies and Internet service providers that are being
touted as pillars of the ``new economy.'' Those stocks have boosted
the Nasdaq composite more than 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of the Nasdaq outperforming the Dow continued
Wednesday. The Dow rose a mere 0.1 percent while the Nasdaq
advanced 1.9 percent to close at another record, 4,784.08.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of market that confirms the importance of asset
allocation, according to investment advisers and money managers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, buy technology, but also raise some cash in anticipation of
buying bargain-priced blue chips down the road. And don't ignore
the Treasury market, where yields are attractive now but may not be
in six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for investors to have exposure to a wide
variety of asset classes,'' said Jack J. Calhoun Jr., senior vice
president of Capital Directions in Atlanta, which manages $150
million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers also say every investor needs a personal allocation
formula based on factors such as income, age and objective.
</P>
<P>
   Investment advisers see no early end to the dominance of
technology stocks. But they caution investors to approach them with
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to argue that we're in a new economy, but it's not a
given that all the stocks floated by this rising tide will
ultimately prove their worth,'' said Calhoun. ``A few of these
stocks will prove to be worth their lofty valuations, but what
about the other 50-to-60-to-70 percent that don't?''
</P>
<P>
   Another complication in today's market is that market indexes
give investors a misleading picture of what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average stock in the broad market has been in a bear
market for quite some time, despite the fact that the indexes are
making new highs,'' said Robert M. Balentine, chairman of Balentine
&AMP; Co., which provides advice on some $3.5 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that a majority of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
stocks are trading as much as 25 percent below their highs. A drop
of 20 percent is generally regarded as a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Balentine thinks investors should hold 5 percent to 10 percent
of their assets in cash to be ready for bargain hunting. He also
said his firm has increased portfolio weightings in small- and
mid-cap stocks and in international stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Investors typically increase their cash allocation by selling
shares of their least attractive stocks, or by adding new money to
the portfolio, Balentine said.
</P>
<P>
   At Kays Financial Advisory Corp., Scott Kays, president and
founder, recommends investors look seriously at Treasury bonds,
because their attractive yields are likely to disappear soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The supply of long-term bonds is going to dwindle (due to the
federal budget surplus) and as a result, the Treasury is not only
cutting back on new issues but buying back existing bonds,'' he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   He also contends that the Fed's attack on inflation will be
successful, putting additional downward pressure on bond yields.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury yield has already dropped from a high 6.75
percent in January to 6.15 percent as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be surprised if this window of opportunity lasts six
months,'' Kays said. ``By then, the Fed will have raised short-term
rates at least one more time, and the long rates will be lower.''
</P>
<P>
   But as good as the window of opportunity in the bond market may
be, most advisers say common stocks are still the best long-term
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone with a time horizon over five years probably should
have the vast majority of money in stocks. They have outperformed
any other asset class,'' said Greg Paulette, president of Global
Capital Management, which manages $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our suggestion is to be fully invested.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
