A3689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-CALIF-LOGGING-HNS &LR;      03-01 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-LOGGING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SUIT SEEKS TO END SOME LOGGING PRACTICES IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Environmental and fishing industry groups filed
a lawsuit Wednesday asking a federal court to prohibit certain
logging practices that they allege kill threatened coho salmon in
privately owned forests.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit could affect commercial logging operations from
Santa Cruz County to the Oregon border.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Information Center in Garberville,
the Pacific Coast Federation of Fishermen's Associations and other
groups filed the lawsuit in U.S. District Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that the California Department of Forestry
does not have strict enough rules and practices to protect the
coho's streams under the U.S. Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most significant lawsuit of its kind in the nation
regarding private logging,'' said Peter Galvin, conservation
biologist with the nonprofit Center for Biological Diversity in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Fisheries Service, the federal agency
responsible for protecting the coho, has said repeatedly that ``the
state forest practice rules are inadequate to prevent the continued
decline of coho salmon,'' Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of an emperor-wears-no-clothes kind of thing. It's a
public secret that logging on private land is killing coho salmon.
But the state Department of Forestry refuses to take action,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says the state agency has taken no enforcement
action nor rejected a logging plan to protect the silvery coho.
</P>
<P>
   Every year the state approves logging on about 285,000 acres,
the suit says. The largest logging companies are Sierra Pacific,
Pacific Lumber Co., Simpson Timber Co., and the Mendocino Redwoods
Co., which was started in 1998 by the Fisher family, owners of
retail giant the Gap, when they bought land from Louisiana Pacific
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Lucke, the Department of Forestry's assistant deputy
director for forest practice, said for the past two years the state
has been vigilantly looking out for the coho when considering
logging plans. About 1,000 plans are approved every year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at each plan individually. In the coho areas, we look
for the habitat requirements of the fish species and mitigate the
plan to protect that habitat,'' Lucke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work with the National Marine Fisheries Service. They don't
go out on every plan. But when they come up with recommendations,
we include those in the plan,'' Lucke said.
</P>
<P>
   Tharon O'Dell, resources manager of Simpson, said landowners and
forest land managers have added protections since the coho on the
North Coast was listed as threatened in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But the suit alleges that coho salmon are injured when the state
agency approves logging plans for timber companies that aren't
strict enough to safeguard the fish's habitat.
</P>
<P>
   When the state doesn't require that loggers leave wide enough
buffer zones of trees along the banks, up to 300 feet, it is
allowing degradation of streams through silting from erosion, the
suit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the agency doesn't prevent timber cutting on unstable
soils, which also adds to the erosion, nor stops the logging during
wet winter months when heavy equipment can pack down or create
gullies on the land, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Other activities that harm salmon are gravel mining, dredging
and road building, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Forestry sent out a mass mailing to foresters
about the protections, O'Dell said. ``We've been focusing on
increasing shade and woody debris and decreasing sediment and
stream temperatures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
