<SLUG> BC-TRIE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democratic fund-raiser Trie admits
 &HT;    illegal gifts
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Democratic fund-raiser Yah Lin ``Charlie''
Trie testified for the first time Wednesday that he funneled
hundreds of thousands of dollars in illegal foreign donations into
the Democratic National Committee's coffers four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Arkansas restaurateur and friend of President
Clinton denied that he was part of a conspiracy by the Chinese
government to influence American politics and that he had acquired
sensitive technology from American businesses as a spy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest joke,'' said Trie during the daylong
hearing before the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee.
``If China wants to influence United States government policy, it
hires Henry Kissinger, not Charlie Trie.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), a member of the committee, said Trie's
role as a conduit for foreign funds will come back to haunt the
Democratic Party in 2000, particularly Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be an election year issue, because Al Gore is right
in the thick of things,'' Barr said. ``This shows that the DNC was
willing to sell its soul to the Chinese military and other foreign
governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Trie told the congressional panel that he parlayed his
friendship with President Clinton into lucrative overseas business
contacts in Asia. He admitted that he took money from those
contacts, sending about $1.2 million to the Democratic Party and to
Clinton's Legal Defense Fund. All of that money has since been
returned.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the donations, Trie offered donors access to
Clinton and top Cabinet officials.
</P>
<P>
   Barr peppered Trie about his involvement in soliciting a
high-ranking military official in the People's Liberation Army to
join a group of top Democratic donors known then as the Business
Leadership Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 invitation to Lin Ruo Qing was facilitated by Trie,
documents show. Trie said he had no recollection of the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Trie used the hearing to apologize for causing so much trouble
for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that I made many mistakes,'' Trie said. ``I got
caught up in the whirlpool of politics and fund-raising and was in
over my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
