<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-MLB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker to join Braves on Thursday
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ It's over. Or maybe it's just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker's 19-day wait ended Wednesday when arbitrator Shyam
Das cut his suspension in half, to 12 games, and sent the
25-year-old closer to spring training.
</P>
<P>
   He can pitch in a game as early as April 18, against the
Phillies at Turner Field, as opposed to the May 1 date originally
imposed by commissioner Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is expected to join the Braves here today when they open
their exhibition season against the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   His work will start in the clubhouse, where he will continue to
try to repair the damage he did in a Sports Illustrated story in
December with his insulting comments against minorities,
foreigners, homosexuals and some of his own teammates.
</P>
<P>
   No meeting is scheduled for Rocker to address his teammates, but
he will have plenty of opportunity to do so in a more casual
setting if he chooses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I'm going to react when I see him,'' said
Brian Jordan, one of the more outspoken Braves when the story came
out. Jordan has not talked to Rocker since last season, although he
said he has forgiven Rocker. ``We're just happy to get it over
with,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Rocker said Wednesday he expected that his son would meet
with teammates individually, especially the ones he tried to reach
in the offseason but never talked to. They include Jordan and
Randall Simon, the player Rocker referred to in the article as a
``fat monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel certain John and Randall will meet just as soon as
possible,'' Jake Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Rocker said she spoke to her son John before he left
Atlanta on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very business-like, very serious, very
matter-of-fact,'' she said. ``He's focused on doing what he needs
to do to get everything together.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves general manager John Schuerholz said Rocker plans to
address the media in a news conference this morning. The Braves
clubhouse is closed to the media until the Braves begin batting
practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves met for 40 minutes regarding Rocker after their
workout on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I've said all along, and it seems to be the case
with other guys, which is I forgive him for what he said,'' Tom
Glavine said before the meeting. ``We'll have to see how things go
from here on out. He still has a lot of bridges to mend. We said
we're willing to give him the opportunity, so we'll see what
happens. We'll see what he does with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves enjoyed a quiet first two weeks of camp, which will
end today, at least for a couple of days. About 50 members of the
media gathered at the Disney complex on Wednesday as word spread of
the Das decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll all be better off to get him in here and deal with the
initial onslaught now and be done with it, rather than four weeks
from now,'' Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who saved 38 games last season, might not be in the
clear yet. Schuerholz hinted Wednesday that he Rocker still might
be traded. When asked if Rocker would return to his role as closer
April 18, Schuerholz said, ``If John regains his effectiveness and
remains with us, he'll have a very good chance to be our closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz acknowledged that other teams had expressed interest
in Rocker. Among those is believed to be Montreal, who would send
the Braves closer Ugueth Urbina and a pitcher for Rocker and
starter Bruce Chen.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who agreed to terms with the Braves on Tuesday for a
one-year deal believed to be worth $350,000, had his fine reduced
from $20,000 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Selig was angry about both reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with the decision of Arbitrator Das,'' Selig said
in a statement. ``It does not reflect any understanding of or
sensitivity to the important social responsibility that baseball,
an institution that has endured for more than 100 years, has to the
public. It completely ignores the sensibilities of those groups
maligned by Mr. Rocker and disregards the player's position as a
role model for children.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
