<HEADLINE>
READY FOR SPRING? HEAD TO THE FLOWER SHOWS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill., Pa., Canada)   By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The snowdrops are blooming and the species tulips are popping
up. Some mornings, the air is balmy and the sun has that golden
light that says, ``Spring!'' Put on a lighter coat and freeze to
death by the afternoon, when the winter wind blows up again.
</P>
<P>
   That's the signal to get on the train and head for your favorite
flower show _ to wallow in woodland gardens impossibly blooming
with dogwoods and shadbush, and drool over English gardens stuffed
with blue delphiniums. Take a notebook to write down the names of
all those hot annuals (hello orange and red, farewell pastels), and
a camera to snap pictures of great plant combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few shows coming up in March.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA FLOWER SHOW _ ``Gardens for the New Millennium,''
sponsored by the Pennsylvania Horticultural Society, March 5
through 12 at the Pennsylvania Convention Center, 12th and Arch
Streets. A futuristic community of the 22nd century will feature
everything from backyard aquaculture and a solar-powered spa to a
windmill farm and a thriving farmers' market. More than 2,000
entries in the amateur competitions, from bonsai to rare plant
specimens. Hands-on play station for trying out the latest
gardening gizmos; cooking demonstrations by celebrity chefs.
Weekdays, 10 a.m. to 9:30 p.m.; weekends, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. For
information and tickets: (215) 988-8899 or www.philaflowershow.com.
</P>
<P>
   PRELUDE TO SPRING _ Inside the Enid A. Haupt Conservatory at the
New York Botanical Garden, now through April 23. Woodland walk
lined with white-barked birch, tulips, daffodils, purple hellebores
and grape hyacinths. Jasmine-covered gazebo, flowering shrubs,
black pussy willows. In April, catch the foxgloves, delphiniums,
lilies and fragrant stocks. Then take a trip from the tropics to
the desert on the ecotour, ``A World of Plants.'' Tuesday through
Sunday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Closed on Monday. For information: (718)
817-8700 or www.nybg.org.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND SPRING FLOWER SHOW _ ``Symphony for the Senses,''
sponsored by the Massachusetts Horticulture Society, March 11
through 19 at the Bayside Expo Center in Boston. Strong emphasis on
fragrance, color and elements that provide sound, like chimes and
running water. Garden follies, woodland oases, tropical water
gardens and alternatives to grass lawns. Children's Festival, March
17, from 4:30 to 8:30 p.m., with hands-on activities, storytelling,
music and annual poster contest. Tuesday to Saturday, 10 a.m. to
9:30 p.m.; Sunday and Monday, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. For information:
(617) 536-9280 or www.masshort.org.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO FLOWER AND GARDEN SHOW ``Through the Garden Gate,''
March 11 through 19 at the Navy Pier's Festival Hall. About 25
theme gardens; ``masterpiece urns'' painted by Chicago artists (to
be sold at silent auction); table settings by top flora designers;
lectures; cooking demonstrations; Chicago Botanic Garden's ``plant
doctors,'' who answer gardening questions. Also, a children's
treasure hunt sponsored by the Morton Arboretum, a Mad Hatter's tea
party, home improvement tips from Norm Abram of ``This Old House.''
Monday through Saturday, 10 a.m. to 8 p.m.; Sunday, 10 a.m. to 6
p.m. For information: (312) 321-0077 or www.chicagoflower.com.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO FLOWER AND GARDEN SHOW _ At the Cow Palace, March
16 through 19. Five acres of exhibits, including 23 gardens by
leading designers; 400 exhibitors; art exhibit featuring botanical
artists, watercolor painters and topiary photographers; bonsai and
ikebana shows; new-plant symposium by Pacific Horticulture
Magazine; seminars by such experts as Daniel Hinkley and Renee
Shepherd. Amateur competition by California Garden Clubs. Thursday,
March 16, and Sunday, March 19, 9 a.m. to 6:30 p.m.; Friday, March
17, and Saturday, March 18, 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. For information: (800)
829-9751 or www.gardenshow.com.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO FLOWER AND GARDEN SHOW _ ``Canada Blooms,'' sponsored by
the Garden Club of Toronto and Landscape Ontario, March 22 through
March 26 at the Metro Toronto Convention Center. With the help of
1,200 volunteers, there will be lindens, birch, ash, dogwood,
magnolias and 50,000 bulbs in full bloom, as well as 34 gardens
featuring a 3,300-square-foot extravaganza of rock, water, art and
plants; 600 entries from Canadian horticultural societies and
garden clubs; seminars; demonstrations; and an orgy of new
products. Live music and dance in the evenings. Wednesday through
Saturday, 10 a.m. to 9 p.m.; Sunday, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. For
information: (800) 730-1020.
</P>
</TEXT>
