s t BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-BIGSUR-$     03-01 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-BIGSUR-$ADV05-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARM JADE STONES BETWEEN YOUR TOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., March 5) 
(jt) 
 By JAN BENZEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone's tired of hearing how tired working mothers are all
the time, so I won't say how tired I was when I set out for a
three-day respite at two resorts on the California coast in
November. Let's just say I was not at all sorry to abandon
fourth-grade homework, a second-grade class dinner, the subway, my
office, two weekend soccer games and the cat box. I was sorry only
to leave the other working parent in our household behind. But not
as sorry as he was.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I needed a psychic tuneup, and a change of scenery. I needed to
see the cliffs of Big Sur. Preferably from a spa.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My sights were set on the Post Ranch Inn, about which I had
heard accolades. Its least expensive room, at $395, was available
for one night. For the other two days, I planned to head north
toward San Francisco and a bit inland, to a brand-new place in
Carmel Valley wine country called the Bernardus Lodge. Its spa
building wasn't finished yet, but it promised full service with
in-room treatments, and a discount on lodging. I booked two nights
at $245, and invited my West Coast friend Tish to desert her
three-child household and join me for as much of my lark as she
could.
</P>
<P>
   People love to cast aspersions on Big Sur, with its touchy-feely
Esalen-tinged aura. Those sniffy about anything new age will not
like it. Those spooked by winding two-lane roads precipitously
carved out of rock above crashing waves will not enjoy getting
there. Big Sur is not for everyone, but to me, it's Shangri-la. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To attempt to describe the rugged drama of that particular
stretch of coast would be futile, especially as I saw it on this
trip, tootling along in my turquoise subcompact rental car, with
the sun a blazing fireball dropping into the Pacific from a sky
streaked with orange, magenta and purple. My only wish was to be
seeing it instead from Sierra Mar, the Post Ranch Inn's gorgeous
restaurant of glass, steel and wood that seems suspended in air
over the Pacific. By the time I got to Sierra Mar, the stars were
out.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been swiftly checked in to my room in the Butterfly House,
where a fire was laid and the refrigerator stocked with gourmet
root beer, Hawaiian flatbread crackers, macadamia nut cookies and
other imaginative treats, all free. The duvet on the big, high bed
was covered in blue denim, and a day-bed-window-seat looked perfect
for an afternoon of reading under a charming half-moon window. On
the bed was a gift: a package of California wildflower seeds.
Binoculars for bird-watching were in a drawer. There was no TV. The
bathtub _ more like a grotto _ was what really won me over. Tiled
with slate (imported from Rajasthan, India), the tub was deep and
plenty big enough for two, with jets. A long window opened out from
the tub onto my small wooden deck. Handmade lavender soap and bath
salts awaited. I lit the fire, tuned into some campy musicals on
the elegant sound system and splashed happily in my pool of steamy
lavender till dinner time.
</P>
<P>
   I was beginning to regret that I hadn't sent the kids to their
grandparents and brought their father along. Post Ranch Inn, like
the slightly more democratic (and also earthily beautiful) Ventana
just across Route 1, is not really a place to go alone. The few
times I saw other guests _ at the restaurant, sitting on a bench
cliffside or in the spectacular infinity pool that offers the
illusion of still water edged by air _ those guests were in pairs,
mostly men and women, some gay.
</P>
<P>
   Still, my solitary state didn't faze the young, proficient Post
Ranch staff. I had a lovely table by a window at Sierra Mar, and an
attentive pony-tailed waiter who was delighted when I chose a glass
of Edna Valley chardonnay from the extensive, award-winning cellar.
I also ordered borscht made from local organically grown beets and
a delicious tuna steak. When I passed up dessert and coffee he
brought me a Chinese takeout carton with four or five perfectly
made little truffles and tarts. The telescope was set up for
stargazing on the deck but I didn't want anything technological to
come between me and the sky.
</P>
<P>
   I woke up in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   The inn is on a cliff 1,100 feet above the Pacific. On my way to
the yoga yurt for the 8 a.m. class, I detoured to look out over the
ocean. There was no water to be seen, only the tops of fluffy white
clouds. We were floating in sunshine, above them. There was
absolute quiet. The air smelled of lavender, rosemary and pine.
</P>
<P>
   With daylight I could see what makes Post Ranch so special.
Opened in 1992, it is situated on land claimed in the mid-19th
century by William Brainard Post, a sailor from Connecticut who
became one of the first homesteaders in Big Sur. The founders of
the 30-room inn have maintained ties to the Post family and built
unobtrusively with wood and steel in tones that blend in with the
redwoods and dusky brown hillsides. The most magnificent _ and most
expensive _ units are right at the edge of the cliff, each rounded,
with grass and wildflowers growing over the back and roof, a deck
on the Pacific side and a two-sided fireplace, so the occupants can
splash in their grottos by firelight. The midrange rooms are called
Treehouses _ they're triangular and on stilts. Everywhere the
feeling is of being at camp. Camp with goosedown comforters and
room service.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, room service spurred my only quibble. Since the
breakfast buffet didn't begin until 8:30 and I'm not one for yoga
on an empty stomach, I ordered breakfast, included in the room
price, delivered to my room. It arrived on time. The cut fruit and
fancy granola were perfect, but everything was cold, including the
breads. And of course it was breakfast for two. An unfortunate
trend among hotels these days is do-it-yourself coffee, which I
made with the classy little Krups setup, but wished it had arrived
on a tray in a pot, accompanied by a warm croissant.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
