<HEADLINE>
JOURNALIST RETURNS; 12 OTHERS MISSING IN CHECHNYA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Radio Liberty correspondent Andrei Babitsky has
returned home safely after a six-week ordeal in Chechnya, but 12
other journalists are still missing in the war-ravaged republic.
</P>
<P>
   One of these, Vladimir Yatsina, a photographer for the official
Russian news agency Itar-Tass, was presumed to have been killed
after witnesses said this week he had been shot by Chechen fighters
fleeing Russian forces in the mountains south of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   In the Chechen conflict's environment of ``if you're not with us
you're against us,'' both the separatist rebels and the Russian
forces have been more concerned with propaganda advantage than with
press freedoms or the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky, whose blistering reports of Russian military excesses
from the war-zone infuriated the Kremlin, was missing for six weeks
before resurfacing last Friday. He said was detained by Russian
forces on Jan. 16 and repeatedly beaten before being freed early
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yatsina's death at the hands of Chechen rebels followed a much
longer ordeal. He was kidnapped last July, held for ransom for
seven months and forced into hard labor, before reportedly being
shot last week, apparently for being unable to keep up with his
fleeing captors.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Babitsky denied Kremlin
assertions that he had been handed over to Chechen rebels in
exchange for Russian POWs. Instead, he said, his captors were
pro-Moscow Chechens, who were tied to the Federal Security Service,
successor to the Soviet KGB.
</P>
<P>
   He described the exchange as ``a poorly planned operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised that our security services are unable to
professionally neutralize one journalist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky said his new captors, who later identified themselves
as loyalists of a pro-Moscow warlord named Adam Demiev, took him to
an unidentified home in Chechnya. There, they tried to force him to
make one videotape demanding $2 million ransom from Radio Liberty
and another where he pledged to take up arms against Russia and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But while Babitsky's case sparked an international outcry,
Yatsina's plight _ as well as that of the 23 journalists who have
been killed in Chechnya since 1995 and 11 others who are still
missing _ received scant attention.
</P>
<P>
   Yatsina, 51, disappeared after traveling to Chechnya on July 19,
1999 to photograph rebel bases for a Canadian newspaper. According
to press reports, he was taken captive by the rebels, who demanded
$2 million for his release. The ransom was later lowered to
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Alisher Orazaliyev, a businessman from the Central
Asian republic of Kazakhstan who had been taken hostage by Chechen
militants and later freed, said Yatsina was shot by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Orazaliyev said Yatsina was gunned down by the rebels, who were
escaping with their captives in the face of Russia's military
onslaught. According to Orazailiyev, Yatsina, who was weak from
forced labor and suffering from a bad heart and weak legs, was shot
for being too ill to walk in the mountains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3697 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-BIGSUR-$     03-01 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIF-BIGSUR-$ADV05-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: warm croissant.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had to hurry a bit to get to the yurt (in Big Sur you can say
yurt with a straight face), a humble round latticework structure
covered, except for a hole at the top open to the sky, with heavy
canvas against the early morning chill. Amber, a young curly-headed
instructor with pretty silver toe rings, was leading three men
(some silver-haired), and four women (some Hollywood blonde), all
looking fit and prosperous even in their sweats, through a good,
fairly strenuous class of slow sun salutations, caterpillars,
downward dogs and child's poses. She ended by laying small, cool
silken pillows filled with fragrant flaxseed over our closed eyes.
``Yoga is like the headlights on your car,'' Amber intoned. ``It
lets you know where to go next.''
</P>
<P>
   Next? I wanted to stay here forever. I wandered serenely past
the 50-foot lap pool and up along one of the several gentle trails
through fields and woods on the 98-acre property back toward camp,
and stopped in at the breakfast buffet to pick up a newspaper. The
bountiful spread included warm vegetable frittata and breads, and
coffee, all made.
</P>
<P>
   But who needs coffee when you're booked for a Big Sur Jade Hot
Stone Massage? Most treatments at Post Ranch can be had in your
room (including couples' tandem massages), but there are also a few
treatment rooms in the lower level of one of the Butterfly Houses
near the small library. Here I met Lauren for 90 minutes of the
most deeply soothing experiences imaginable. She arranged two rows
of smooth black basalt stones, heated in a roasting pan, on her
massage table and had me lie back with my spine between them, which
was far more comfortable than it sounds. Then she began placing
more of them down my chest. ``This one will really feel good,'' she
said, laying a big oval rock on my stomach. ``That's the belly
stone.'' It did. She tucked hot rounded rocks into my hands, then
came the jade in the middle of my forehead for my third eye. (You
have a third eye when you're in Big Sur.) There were even small
jade stones tucked between my toes. Next, Lauren took a hot stone
and used it to massage me, smoothing out my warmed muscles until
they felt unrecognizably relaxed and long. When she had me lie on
the stones on my stomach, I could see through the face cradle that
she was barefoot, and she too had silver toe rings.
</P>
<P>
   The Bernardus Lodge brochure depicts a wildly fertile landscape
of lush vineyards against a green mountainside. So imagine my
surprise when, rounding a corner on Carmel Valley Road, I came upon
large plots of caked brown dirt with hopeful baby grapevines poking
up at widely spaced intervals flanking the entrance to the Lodge.
The inn was getting its finishing touches when I was there, but
those vines have a long way to go to live up to their advance
press.
</P>
<P>
   It's not really fair to compare the Bernardus Lodge to the Post
Ranch Inn. The Bernardus is closer to civilization, busier, more
boisterous, less about nature, more about creature comforts.
Bernardus, best known for its Bordeaux-style reds, does have
vineyards, but they're 17 miles away, and the vintner's tasting
room is two miles down the road in the funky hamlet of Carmel
Valley. The new 57-room lodge is appealing, with mustard and rose
adobe-style buildings, a big, welcoming lobby with open beamed
ceiling and flower and fruit arrangements, where new arrivals are
handed a glass of good wine. Outdoors, there is a large fireplace
where people gather to eat and drink, a croquet lawn and a
good-sized pool with fresh towels arranged expectantly on lounge
chairs. The valet carpark station is heated from above.
</P>
<P>
   My spacious room was pretty, too, with a vaulted white ceiling
and a two-story clerestory window. The bathroom was huge, probably
three times the size of my kitchen at home, with a separate,
oversized shower, a closet for the toilet, an oversized tub and a
double sink. But the overall effect was more suburban dream house
than get-away-from-it-all luxury. There was a TV. The fireplace was
gas-burning. The contents of the refrigerator, under an odd
copper-topped counter billed as a wine bar, were not free. The bed,
though, was great: king-sized with feather bedding, lots of
pillows, a puffy coverlet in cream and butter-yellow striped fine
Italian cotton. But I could hear traffic, and the view was of the
valet parking. Tish was coming the next day; I resolved to see if I
could get us a better room.
</P>
<P>
   I had one in a twinkling. Dylan, a young concierge, took me
immediately over to see a room farther back toward the hillside. It
was on the first floor and so didn't have a vaulted ceiling, but
the bed was just as nice, and the tranquil view from the patio was
of the Santa Lucia Mountains, the pool and an olive tree.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan, who had grown up in Carmel Valley, also recommended
hiking in Garland Ranch Regional Park, a mile away, pointing out
his favorite trails and some low-key restaurants for lunch. Service
at Bernardus was exceptional; perhaps they were still in dress
rehearsal mode, because staff members frequently checked with me to
make sure everything was all right. Turn-down brought more wine, a
complimentary half-bottle with crackers and cheese. All this
flowing wine was more than I could drink; I packed the bottles in
my suitcase, along with the lavender soap from Post Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Tish and I hiked in the park. We spotted a few people on horses,
and others with dogs, on the hillside dotted with cottonwood, oak
and laurel, their leaves gold and silver. We swam in the heated
pool and lounged around in our fluffy robes, feeling incredibly
lucky to have uninterrupted hours to catch up on years of each
other's lives.
</P>
<P>
   I'd had an uninspired room service breakfast of French toast the
first morning, so we went to the Bernardus restaurant with some
trepidation that night. We were pleasantly surprised by top-flight
food _ the mesquite-grilled beef was especially good with a glass
of Bernardus' 1995 Marinus, a cabernet-merlot blend.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the increasingly testy tones when I phoned home, I
figured this indulgence was going to have to last me well into the
next millennium, so I went all out and signed up for the spa's
special: a Hawaiian Lomi Lomi massage, followed by a lavender
facial. The therapist had been taught the basics of massage by her
Samoan grandmother, she told me, as the gas firelight flickered and
strains of Hawaiian music wafted from the CD player. She said a
silent prayer over me, and used combinations of friction, pressure
and smoothing strokes with her forearm, basting me in flaxseed and
sunflower oil. I didn't have to move for the facial, which was the
best in my admittedly limited experience. I hadn't caught her name
on the way in, but as I left, my eye fell on her name tag. In
California, your masseuse can be named Zenith.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
