<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NY-VILLAGE-HOUSE-ART-     03-01 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VILLAGE-HOUSE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRANGE HOUSE AND ITS STRANGE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NANCY HASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like many people who meander through the storybook
streets of the West Village, Tom Fontana had always wondered about
the strange house on 13th Street near Eighth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Set at the end of a row of brownstones, with its elegant
Venetian window arches and stepped gable, the three-story brick
house looked like a reproduction of a 17th-century Dutch guild
hall. But the formal front doors and a chunk of the ground floor
had been hacked away in a renovation of shocking proportions. In
their place was a rubble-strewn gated courtyard that dropped off
sharply in the center, where a metal stairway led to an exposed
basement. The house seemed to cantilever precariously above the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century building bore the unmistakable signs of a
radical renovation, circa 1969. A plaque commemorated this event as
``The Great Building Crack-Up.'' Day-Glo doodles on basement window
panes were peeling. By the time that Fontana _ the television
writer and mastermind of ``Homicide'' and ``Oz'' _ first stumbled
upon the house, in the 1980s, it looked as though it had been
through a bummer of a trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wrote the place off as one of those fantastic artifacts
that make New York great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, four years ago, Fontana, in search of some outside space,
decided to move from his two floors of a brownstone on 23rd Street.
One day, going to the ``Oz'' set above Chelsea Market, he saw in a
broker's window a photo of the strange building on 13th Street.
</P>
<P>
   For Fontana, 48, who has a passion for New York history and
knows better than most the value of a remarkable, twisted
backstory, 251 West 13th Street proved irresistible. The plot lines
were shadowy; the personalities as quirky and complex as those of
his ``Homicide'' cops.
</P>
<P>
   He dove into the history of the period, and the building's
checkered past, like a sleuth, discovering that it was built in
1887 as the Jackson Square library by Richard Morris Hunt, a
legendary figure of the Beaux-Arts period and the architect of the
main entrance of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. It had been a gift
to the Free Circulating Library, predecessor of the public library
system, from George W. Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   A striking renovation, commissioned by Robert Delford Brown, an
artist who bought the building in 1967 for $125,000 (after the
library moved into the Jefferson Market), was also one for the
books, but in a different way. The building was redone _ some say
undone _ by Paul Rudolph, the giant of '60s modernism. ``Underneath
the mess was pretty much the story of the city,'' Fontana said.
</P>
<P>
   It would take him two years to painstakingly recast the
9,000-square-foot structure as a harmonious blend of 19th-century
grandeur and airy modern simplicity. The cost of the work was $1.7
million _ about the same as the building's price.
</P>
<P>
   He has kept the top two floors as his living space, accessible
by a private entrance, and has put offices for his writing staff on
the main floor and editing suites in the basement. ``It's like
living in an Escher painting,'' he said as he stood on the top
floor looking down the central staircase.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Fontana knew what he hoped to achieve. He
also knew the limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Hunt archivist in Washington could not unearth the
architect's original blueprints and too much of the original
building had been destroyed in Rudolph's renovation so there was no
chance to do a purist's reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana is a pro at bringing back the dead (witness his recent
``Homicide'' reunion movie, with every character who was ever a
regular). But he did not want to live with ghosts, either the
19th-century kind or those who frequented the zany pad that Rudolph
had made three decades ago for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown used his residence as a performance space to stage his
frequent happenings.
</P>
<P>
   (In an early one, he displayed 3,500 pounds of meat in a
cooler.)
</P>
<P>
   Brown hung around with Claes Oldenberg and Jim Dine but was not
known to take himself very seriously. He concocted the conceptual
First National Church of the Exquisite Panic on his premises, with
two central commandments: Live, and Do Not Eat Cars. (He instructed
the faithful how to reach the state of Nevada because nirvana was
too hard to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, who had been dean of the Yale University School of
Architecture, had used many of his characteristic flourishes on the
space. The building had largely been gutted to create multiple
levels. There was lots of Mylar and plenty of smoked glass and
glass bricks that let in some light but not the view. The myriad
staircases were made from planks connected only by the skimpiest
metal tubing. ``When we would poke around the place, Tom was
terrified every time he had to walk up a flight,'' said Ron
Bentley, Fontana's architect, a partner in the B Five Studio.
</P>
<P>
   While the underlying design ideas may have made sense in the
infamous town house Rudolph designed for Halston and his own
still-intact home on Beekman Place, here the budget seems to have
been too small. ``To put it plainly, the construction was shoddy,''
Bentley said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph's work started in controversy. A year before he
irreparably altered the facade, the three-year-old Landmarks
Commission had decided to make Greenwich Village a historic
district. Its lawyers asked Rudolph in writing to modify his plans,
though they could not yet insist on it legally. Rudolph let the
sledgehammers swing days before the law was passed.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 69, who now lives in a two-room apartment in Zeckendorf
Towers, dismissed the controversy as ``another example of how
people resist change.'' He called his relationship with Rudolph
``full of conflict,'' which was just what he wanted. He said,
``Someone asked me why I didn't choose Robert Venturi, and I said,
`To see the sparks fly.'''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fontana decided to keep Rudolph's open layout. Fontana, who is
divorced, lives alone and, like Brown, enjoys partying and
appreciates flowing spaces that afford little privacy. He wanted a
bachelor pad that would mix informality with Hunt's solidity and
urbanity. It was a tricky feat, but one that Fontana (who counts
Lucille Ball and Tolstoy as influences) has largely managed in his
own life.
</P>
<P>
   Although he spent much of the early 1980s working in Los Angeles
(``pure hell,'' he said simply), he eschewed the Hollywood Hills
for an apartment in one of the city's few prewar high rises. He
does not own a car or use a computer (he writes scripts in longhand
on legal pads). Although he generally wears jeans and a baseball
cap and peppers his speech with exuberant profanity, his scripts
have been lauded by critics for their Chekovian nuance.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana decided right off not to recreate the building's
19th-century ornamentation and detailing. He even left exposed the
mismatched brick on the 30-foot renovation-scarred side walls that
Rudolph had stripped bare. But he replaced the floating steps with
an imposing yet unadorned central staircase. ``The place was
ridiculous,'' Fontana said. ``I wanted it to have dignity, but not
be too elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   With 18 years of experience supervising television set
construction (he is also a co-owner of three restaurants), Fontana
knew where to spend and where to scrimp. He didn't splurge on
redoing the work spaces on the two bottom levels.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the ground floor, however, there are hints of the
history and of the grandeur of the floors above. Fontana's own
office, the back room, which Hunt designed to protrude into the
yard, has a vaulted roof inlaid with round glass insets that are
dimpled like the bottom of old-fashioned Coke bottles. During World
War II, it had been tarred over for the blackouts and most of the
insets had cracked or shattered. Fontana spent $60,000 to have them
recast. On a sunny day, the light throws dancing shadows on the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Fontana's energy and cash went into reimagining the huge
space on the second floor that was once the library's main reading
room. Brown used it as a painting studio that he called his Temple
of Hilarity. Halfway up to the 15-foot ceiling was a crude balcony
with some cheap tables and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Now floor-to-ceiling mahogany bookcases are filled with
Fontana's 6,600 volumes (the original library opened with 6,601).
The top rows are accessible by a new narrow black metal catwalk
that Bentley designed to suggest the room's historic underpinnings.
The ceilings are custom-milled mahogany, copied from the only room
in the building, now a guest room, that survives from the Hunt era.
</P>
<P>
   A nine-foot refectory table is the only piece that he has
purchased thus far. Bentley created herringbone oak floors and
replaced Rudolph's 12-foot single-pane smoked glass front windows
with clear double-pane glass framed in mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   There are no curtains yet, so at night passersby stop to stare
up at the stunning room.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Public Library's archives, users of
the Jackson Square Branch ``largely comprised writers, artists and
other professional people.'' James Baldwin, Ring Lardner, W.H.
Auden and Gregory Corso all used it, the archives say. But they
certainly never went there for a Wild Turkey-soaked dance party
like the one Fontana gave on New Year's Eve for 400 people,
including the rap impresario Russell Simmons, who stayed until
dawn.
</P>
<P>
   He covered floors with cardboard, a move he quietly
congratulated himself for later.
</P>
<P>
   Above the main floor, the setup is less grand, by design. A
mezzanine, which Rudolph had enclosed to create another bedroom,
now overlooks the library. Above are the living quarters, including
a master bedroom and a den with a built-in wet bar and humidor, a
fireplace and a huge plasma-screen, high-definition television.
Fontana plans to spend much of his time there with friends like the
actor Dean Winters (``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit''); his
producing partner, Barry Levinson; and Bruce Paltrow, the
television auteur who gave him his big break, back in the early
1980s, writing ``St. Elsewhere.'' Paltrow's wife, the actress
Blythe Danner, has agreed to help decorate.
</P>
<P>
   A small top mezzanine, added on by Rudolph as a
body-painting-studio-cum-deck and crowned by a soaring plaster
vault, now has been enclosed as Fontana's writing loft. (His new
show for UPN, ``The Beat,'' due on March 21, will focus on two cops
on the Lower East Side.) On a shelf sits a gift from a pal who
obviously knows him well: it is a Tom Fontana action figure that
comes packaged with a tiny bottle of Wild Turkey, a miniature box
of Cohibas cigars and a thumb-size yellow legal pad.
</P>
<P>
   But the favored outdoor space _ Fontana's holy grail _ is on the
roof, behind the gable at the front of the building, accessible
from the writing loft by a walkway. The sun-splashed south-facing
roof had not been used by either Hunt or Rudolph. It now holds
Fontana's contribution to the building's evolution: a luxurious
deck with a suburban-size grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me if I have a summer house, and I tell them I
can't imagine why I would,'' he said, gazing out over the rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when people pass, they won't say, `Wow, look at that
strange building,''' he continued. ``They'll say, `Wow look at that
guy up there in that strange building with that huge smile on his
face and a cigar in his mouth, cooking up some big steaks.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
