<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-DIGICOM-COLUMN-NY     03-01 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DIGICOM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL COMMERCE: THE CONSUMER INTERNET MARKET AND ITS B2B COUSIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest entrant in the Internet economy's continuing game of
buzzword bingo is ``business to business,'' predictably shortened
to ``B2B.''
</P>
<P>
   B2B is just what the name implies: businesses selling to other
businesses, using the Internet to cut transaction costs and
increase efficiencies. It is a $1.76 billion market that, according
to Forrester Research, will reach more than $1 trillion in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who have been around the industry since before
Internet Time welcome this new fixation _ actually, we welcome
anything remotely resembling focus in this wacky business
environment _ but we also find it amusing, in that Yogi Berra,
``deja vu all over again'' kind of way.
</P>
<P>
   And we are a little wistful that it did not happen sooner.
Because a good case can be made from even the most recent past that
any successful consumer technology must first be forged in the hot
fire of the business environment. That has not been the strategy
employed by many consumer e-commerce and media companies.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1990, the PC industry pioneer David E. Liddle opened the
inaugural Digital World conference _ an event based on the radical
notion that media, communications and digital technology were on
the verge of converging _ with a caveat: to leapfrog the stolid
business market for the glittering horizon of a consumer market was
not a wise strategy.
</P>
<P>
   That is because all technology-based consumer goods, he said,
must go through three phases.
</P>
<P>
   The first is an appeal to enthusiasts who love the technology
for its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   In the second phase, which would be today's B2B, someone figures
out how to use the technology in his or her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, controls start to become standard _ it is
important that it works in the way you expect it to,'' he said.
``There's kind of a social covenant between the producer and buyer
where your investment is repaid in terms of productivity or some
other valued metric.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameras and cars and PCs, for example, all started their life
cycles with as many variations as there were manufacturers. As
people started using them for work, manufacturers began migrating
shutters and gas pedals and menu bars to predictable, if not
standardized, locations where they behaved in mostly predictable
ways.
</P>
<P>
   A product only moves to the third, or consumer, phase, Liddle
said, when it becomes cheap and widely available, no longer just a
tool of someone's trade, but a discretionary purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Liddle was recently nominated to the board of The New York Times
Co.
</P>
<P>
   B2B products that succeeded in the consumer market were able to
do so because manufacturers took seriously the social covenant with
their business customers, working to provide them with tangible
value. The resulting standards made the products both easier to use
and cheaper to build, thus more attractive to a mass market.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the technology standards embraced by the largely
consumer-focused Internet industry have long been in place. Today's
Windows-based operating systems, along with TCP/IP, the Internet
protocol, and HTML, the lingua franca of the Web, are ubiquitous.
And yet, the consumer Internet market is something of a mess.
</P>
<P>
   Hackers are waging war on consumer Web sites, stealing credit
card numbers, planting destructive software on the computers of
unwilling accomplices. Why? Because they can; there was no
financial incentive for anyone to invest early in the technologies
and common-sense customer care that would have kept them out.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, successful Internet companies like Amazon.com,
eBay, RealNetworks and Microsoft are electronically spying on
people's browsing habits, sometimes installing software on
consumers' computers without permission. Some companies even track
their customers' movements through the network, collecting and
selling personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because they can, and because consumers have not yet
realized the need or exercised sufficient market influence to stop
them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, financial institutions are lobbying Congress for
``digital signature'' legislation that would release them from
traditional requirements to provide consumers with legal documents
on paper. Instead, the companies want to deliver documents like
mortgage lending agreements online. Why? Because it would cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that absent their possession of such documents _ for
whatever reason _ consumers relinquish their claim to legal
recourse.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. While consumers are thus besieged, it seems that
the only social covenant held truly sacred by many consumer Net
companies is with their investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how things change in the business-to-business Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, B2B companies are ``certainly going to make money
off information'' in much the same way that today's consumer
companies hope to by siphoning personal data, says Larry Downes, an
expert in business-to-business practices on the Internet and the
co-author of the book ``Unleashing the Killer App,'' published by
the Harvard Business School Press, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've captured 40 percent of a virtual commodities
market,'' Downes points out, ``you can collect some very
interesting data about your customers to create future products.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, he says, is that the B2B strategy is based on
enhancing, not demolishing, customer relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't stealing information from your customers; you
aren't violating their rights,'' he says. ``You're doing it to
serve them. These B2B communities are relatively small, so they are
very sensitive about doing things that would be against the
interest of their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, he says, America Online or Yahoo ``have millions of
transient customers who turn over very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Downes says B2B companies' smaller scales means their
reputations are much more valuable than the number of transactions
they do.
</P>
<P>
   This is apparently not so for consumer Internet companies. In
the hopes of eking out another book or CD purchase or two by
sacrificing their customers' privacy, or saving a little money by
not having to mail out legal notices or adequately secure their
systems, they seem more than willing to risk the wrath of _ and
eventual abandonment by _ their customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Downes is convinced it will not be long before people find a
way to create a kind of ``consumer proxy'' on the Internet _ their
own little B2B application, as it were. Then watch how quickly the
consumer Internet moves to mend its ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business-to-consumer would be business-to business if
consumers were speaking with one voice,'' says Downes. ``Right now
it doesn't operate that way, but when people can band together as
consumers and act on their collective will, then these companies
won't be able to afford the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-27-00 1730EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
