<HEADER>
A3707 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-SUN-MICROSOFT-PRA     03-01 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SUN-MICROSOFT-PRANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUSINESS STUNT MISSES THE MARK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sun Microsystems' chairman, Scott McNealy, is
well known for his merciless teasing of Bill Gates and Microsoft.
(McNealy likes to point out, for instance, that while both he and
Gates attended Harvard, only McNealy graduated.)
</P>
<P>
   But one recent attempted prank against Microsoft appears to have
fallen short.
</P>
<P>
   For the Feb. 17 public event to roll out Microsoft's ambitious
Windows 2000 operating system, Sun marketing executives had hired a
fleet of 20 bright yellow trucks used by the pest-control company
Western Exterminator.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to pay the drivers to circle the San Francisco
Moscone Convention Center during the Microsoft event inside. The
idea was to draw attention to a news report that there were still
63,000 ``bugs'' in the Microsoft program when it was shipped to
customers _ even though the Microsoft executive in charge of
Windows 2000, James Allchin, had sent an open letter to customers
earlier in the week denying the report.
</P>
<P>
   Near the appointed hour, the trucks were lined up a few blocks
away from the Convention Center. But the mission was aborted after
the Western Exterminator manager learned that it was McNealy's
company, rather than Gates' Microsoft, that had hired the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about Gates' reaction, the manager called in his
fleet. ``He could buy the company and close it,'' he was reported
as saying of Gates.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the moribund marketing stunt, a Sun
Microsystems spokeswoman, Susanne Vagadori, said ``If you want an
on-the-record response it would be along the lines of, `Yeah,
wouldn't that be an appropriate and amusing joke on Microsoft?'
That's sort of why we looked into it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-27-00 1708EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      03-01 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE PLANS TO COLLECT TAX ON SOME INTERNET TRANSACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Testing the ability to enforce national tax
laws in cyberspace, the European Commission is planning to collect
sales taxes on music and software delivered over the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Though not yet complete, the proposals would eliminate what
European officials view as a big loophole that benefits U.S.
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those U.S. companies have already begun to complain that
they would be saddled with onerous responsibilities that could
stifle electronic commerce in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate has also exposed practical difficulties in
adapting national taxes to a world in which music and art fly
across borders.
</P>
<P>
   Under proposals developed by the European Commission in
Brussels, companies would have to collect what is known as a
value-added tax, a type of sales tax, on products they sell and
distribute over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are products like computer software, music and videos
that can be turned into digital code and downloaded by customers
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Value-added taxes are a major source of revenue for most
European governments, and tax rates vary by country from about 12
percent to more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to physical goods, like books or clothes, the
taxes have been collected by stores and mail-order companies or by
customs officials if the products were to be shipped across
national boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   In those transactions, the tax rate is based on the rate of the
country where the product originated.
</P>
<P>
   But ``virtual'' products defy that system, because they can be
sent just as easily from the United States or an offshore tax haven
like the Cayman Islands as they can from a local store in France.
</P>
<P>
   European officials say that this gives U.S. software companies
an unfair advantage over European competitors. They are also
worried that online vendors of all types will shift growing volumes
of sales from sources outside the European system for tax
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Under proposals that officials are debating in Brussels,
products sold in digital form would be taxed based on the rate in
the customer's country, meaning that companies operating in the
United States would have to collect the taxes on all sales to
European customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without any changes, American companies would unquestionably
have an unfair advantage,'' said Oliver Sueme, a director of the
Electronic Commerce Forum, an industry association in Cologne,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a step in the right direction, toward a global
framework for electronic commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. companies say efforts to extend the existing tax system
will prove extremely complicated and prove unenforceable anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area that is still developing, and Europeans should
not rush in to develop a solution right away,'' said Howard
Liebman, a lawyer who heads up a working group on tax issues at the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Liebman said, companies would have to
determine where a customer actually lives, distinguish between 15
tax regimes and differentiate between private individuals and
companies, because the two types of customers are treated
differently for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   To make things easier for businesses, some European officials
have suggested requiring companies to register for business in one
European country and turn their tax receipts over to that country.
</P>
<P>
   But that idea is opposed by many European financial ministers,
because it raises difficulties of distributing the tax money back
to the correct countries.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on both sides of the Atlantic warn that an overly
demanding system could backfire, because many companies will simply
ignore the tax rules altogether and run their Internet sales
operations from offshore tax havens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be requirements, but this is still a system based on
voluntary compliance,'' said Voelker Kebish, a senior researcher on
tax law at the University of Muenster in Germany, who is part of an
advisory group to the European Commission. ``Increasing the
complexity could discourage businesses outside the European Union
from complying.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM is lobbying against the tough new proposals. Smaller dot-com
companies are worried as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says that to grow e-commerce they need to increase
market access, but I fear that this would be an impediment to
market access,'' said Peter Harter, a vice president at EMusic.com
Inc. of Redwood City, Calif., which sells music over the Internet
and owns 20 percent of Crunch.com, a British music distributor.
``It would be very invasive for us to track down where all our
customers are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
