<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-TAXES-$A     03-01 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-TAXES-$ADV27-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    CROSS-CURRENTS OF INTEREST ROIL THE INTERNET TAX DEBATE
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As more Americans begin using the Internet each
day, they are discovering that online shopping can be convenient,
fast and _ perhaps best of all _ free of sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Now some political leaders want Congress to guarantee that the
Internet will remain a tax-free zone. They say the lost sales tax
revenues are a small price to pay for today's robust ``new
economy,'' which is generating other revenues as incomes and
property values rise.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of governors, mayors and Main Street
merchants are asking: is this fair? Why should one group of
retailers escape the burden of collecting taxes, while others must
gather the revenues needed for schools, roads, police and more?
</P>
<P>
   And at a time when the gap between rich and poor is so wide,
many question whether it's good public policy to allow
Internet-savvy consumers to avoid sales taxes while poorer people
without computers bear a hefty tax burden.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy may get more attention this week as the nation's
governors gather for the annual winter meeting of the National
Governors' Association.
</P>
<P>
   The governors, who will meet Monday with President Clinton and
Tuesday with senators, are promoting a plan to make online
retailers begin collecting more taxes. At the same time, they want
to push state legislatures to simplify local tax rules and rates to
better fit the borderless Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   The governors' proposal is just one of many different plans
being floated in Washington, but virtually everyone agrees that old
laws, drawn to fit the business environment of the 1900s, must be
updated for the new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people who think this is a great time to
overhaul the tax system,'' said Steve Papermaster, an Austin,
Texas, high-tech entrepreneur and member of the executive council
of Technology Network (TechNet), a political action group. ``We now
have a significant lag between old legislation (and) the reality of
today's digital economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no other taxes are less in sync with the global Internet
than local sales taxes, imposed by roughly 7,500 taxing
jurisdictions. When ``special purpose'' taxes for certain
districts, such as downtowns, are counted, the country may have
more than 30,000 different sets of sales tax rules, creating a
potential nightmare for online merchants who ship goods everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when sales taxes were first imposed in the 1930s,
they were seen as a simple way to tax the rich, who were the only
people who could afford to shop in those depressed times.
</P>
<P>
   To help poor families, many states provided exemptions for food.
But today, tax officials find themselves struggling to define what
is a food.
</P>
<P>
   In California, ``a bottle of still water like Evian is not
taxed, but a bottle of Perrier is taxed because it has bubbles,''
and that makes it a snack, said Richard Prem, a partner with
Deloitte &AMP; Touche, an accounting firm. Such exemptions ``make it
very tough to comply with the rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though complicated, sales taxes are popular because they take
pressure off of income and property taxes. Today, 45 states impose
sales taxes, which collectively raise more than $150 billion
annually, or about a third of state revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But the drawbacks of sales taxes are becoming more apparent as
commerce shifts to cyberspace, where merchants sell to people in
all states.
</P>
<P>
   For now, online retailers operate like mail-order companies that
send packages around the country. Supreme Court rulings have
determined that a company can be forced to collect sales taxes only
from customers who live in a state where the company has a
``physical presence,'' such as its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   While mail-order companies never significantly threatened state
coffers, the frenzied growth of online sales is raising concerns.
Internet sales are expected to total roughly $20 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Such commerce is still so new that projecting sales growth over
several decades is impossible, but ``the trend is definitely
upward,'' said Donald Bruce, an economist at the University of
Tennessee. He recently completed a study that estimates states will
be losing $10.8 billion annually because of Internet sales by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Congress has been willing to ignore the fears of
governors and mayors. In 1998, Congress passed the Internet Tax
Freedom Act, imposing a moratorium on any new Internet taxes until
October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   To provide a blueprint for online commerce after 2001, Congress
also created the Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce, a
group of 19 people drawn from businesses, statehouses and federal
agencies. That group, which will hold its final meeting in Dallas
next month, is supposed to make recommendations to Congress by
April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Many tax experts fear that commission members' opinions vary so
widely, no consensus will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter what the commission suggests, it's far from clear
what Congress will do.
</P>
<P>
   Many people assume Republicans object more than Democrats to
Internet taxes. But many Republicans hate state income taxes even
more than sales taxes, and fear that if the Internet erodes the
sales tax base, then income taxes might have to make up the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Internet debate does not split neatly into
``conservative'' and ``liberal'' sides, corporate lobbying efforts
have been somewhat muddled. Many retailers themselves are divided
on the tax issue because they operate both traditional stores and
online outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially powerful lobbying group, affluent
homeowners, may also have conflicting interests: they wouldn't want
to see property taxes rise, but they like buying electronics, books
and other goods from online merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Given how tangled the issue is, congressional action seems
unlikely in 2000, said Henry J. Aaron, a senior fellow and sales
tax expert at the Brookings Institution, a Washington research
center. ``It's an election year, so I don't think much will
happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while Congress may want to push the issue to the back
burner, the National Governors' Association plans to turn up the
heat. The organization wants states to take the initiative by
streamlining and standardizing tax definitions, forms, rules and
audit requirements. Once taxes have been simplified, the
association would have online merchants collect taxes with the help
of state-certified software and ``trusted third parties'' to
compute and remit taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But not every governor agrees. For example, Virginia's Gov.
James Gilmore, a Republican and the chairman of the advisory
commission, says Internet companies ought to continue operating
under the rules for mail-order companies because that arrangement
has allowed Internet companies to create millions of jobs.
Internet-generated prosperity is boosting state revenues from
income, corporate and property taxes, making online sales taxes
unnecessary, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And while lawmakers and governors bicker among themselves over
sales taxes, Internet entrepreneurs also are split. Some say
cyberspace should be a tax-free zone, while others believe states
do need sales tax revenues to provide the services and
infrastructure needed in a fast-growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   But even those online retailers who would be willing to collect
taxes say Congress or the states must vastly simplify taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to collect taxes for thousands of jurisdictions ``would
be a nightmare,'' said Andrew Busey, founder of living.com, an
Austin-based online retailer. ``You could get software to do
anything, but it's a matter of how long it takes to build and how
long it would take to integrate it with your existing systems and
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   All that effort would slow the growth of the Internet, Busey
said. But a simple, uniform tax system would raise revenues while
taking minimal time away from building the new economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would certainly make it a lot easier on us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
