<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-MINDSPRING-MCQUAR     03-01 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MINDSPRING-MCQUARY01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    EarthLink president vows to remain close to workers
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ EarthLink President Michael McQuary sees himself as a
behind the scenes executive making sure the company runs smoothly
and employees are happy.
</P>
<P>
   McQuary, or ``McQ'' as he's known to his friends and associates,
was happy to keep the company on track as president and chief
operating officer of MindSpring, while Charles Brewer, the
company's charismatic founder, hit the media circuit. Now McQuary
is EarthLink's standard bearer for core values and beliefs that
were MindSpring's foundation. It's a role he is passionate about
and takes very seriously. At the company's Atlanta headquarters, he
talked about his ideals and aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do you fall in the new organizational structure of the
new company?
</P>
<P>
   A: I report to Garry Betty, EarthLink's chief executive officer.
I have the business units and operations of the company reporting
to me. Garry used to have to be back in Pasadena (Calif., where
EarthLink was based before the merger) minding the store. Now he's
able to go out looking for the next big deal to take us to the next
level. This allows us to split some responsibilities and not worry
that things are a shambles back home.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does it bother you that you don't have the same job you had
prior to the merger?
</P>
<P>
   A: Once you get over the ego impact of not running everything,
it takes a lot of pressure off. I can focus on things. In the past,
I reported to Charles and everyone else reported to me and that was
pretty stressful. What I can do now is focus and make sure the
company's energy and Garry's energy is communicated to everyone in
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've got big responsibilities, but you also place a big
emphasis on your employees.
</P>
<P>
   A: I have to make sure I have a calming effect. I've had this
adage that the higher up you are the more of an impact you have on
the people down below. If the CEO sneezes, the top executives get a
cold. If the top executives get a cold, the middle managers get
pneumonia and if the middle managers get pneumonia, some of the
people on the front line are going to die.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So how do you keep the folks on the front line from dying?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's important for me to be accessible. I'm a lot more
accessible than Charles or Garry.
</P>
<P>
   I spend a lot of time walking around the company just seeing
what's going on. People feel they can approach me, and that's the
most important thing. People all around the company just look at
me, and they say ``There goes McQ.'' There was an employee I helped
find a new job at our Seattle offices and before he left, he
brought his replacement by to my cubicle _ I don't have an office _
and he said, ``Here's McQ _ I don't really know what he does but if
you need anything, he's the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's a very personal approach.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it's business, but it's personal, too. You can't keep
your personal life out of the office. There is still a mystique
about working here. The tactics of fear and intimidation have no
place here. The people who work here know they are valued and their
ideas are valued. Your work environment does make a big difference.
Way before Charles started MindSpring, he had this job he just
hated. He'd come home every day just grinding his teeth. Grinding
your teeth about your job is no way to live.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A lot of people, particularly investors and Wall Street
analysts, were disturbed by MindSpring's and EarthLink's decision
to give up being profitable in order to grow the company. Was that
a tough decision to make?
</P>
<P>
   A: We know how to be profitable and we can get there again in a
quarter if we needed to. But I never wanted us to be a nice little
profitable Internet company. We wanted to be a large company that
can make a difference in the way the world does business. There are
an awful lot of people rooting for us to win, but there are a lot
of cynics looking for us to lose the way. But I'm still president
of the company and we still know what's important.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you really think a list of core values and beliefs can
make that big a difference?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, I do. People say you can't be as big as AT&AMP;T or IBM and
still cling to those value systems. People think there is a
tradeoff, you can't have huge profits and a great work environment.
</P>
<P>
   Our ultimate goal is to change the way the world does business.
It would be so easy to turn our back on the value system or lower
our service standards, but we can only accomplish our goals of
being wildly profitable, having lots of customers and happy
employees if we cling to those beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There have been rumors that you are considering leaving
EarthLink, but it sounds like you plan to be around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   A: I've still got several things I need to accomplish.
Eventually the company will be more valuable than it has ever been
before. I'm in an important role where I can contribute to the good
of the company. I won't leave until I've accomplished my personal
goals. And I probably won't do anything after I leave here. There's
a lot to be said for going out on top and that's what I'd like to
do. Another five years feels about right. This type of work can be
all-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
