<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN EDUCATION ISN'T A GAME TO SQUANDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATERSON, N.J. _ There wasn't a whole lot of sympathy in Jane
Silverstein's third-floor office at Kennedy High School the other
day for Erick Barkley of St. John's and other celebrated
student-athletes who have recently run afoul of those confounding
college basketball rules.
</P>
<P>
   The seniors in Silverstein's Science, Technology, Engineering
and Math program (STEM) have their own college-related financial
headaches, and they aren't holding their breath waiting for a
philanthropic phenomenon to cure them. Darryl Jackson, for
instance, recently learned that one of the New Jersey state schools
he applied to had agreed to pick up his first-year tuition, a
promising start, but it still left him with a long haul to go on
the expensive road to a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson, a lanky young man with handsome braids and an
engaging smile, the routine of applying for scholarship aid and
loans, in bits and pieces, will be a course load of its own. As he
has already set on a double major (computer science and math), he
makes time between the demanding classes he takes at Kennedy and
the prodigious amounts of homework and the pocket-money jobs he has
held at places like Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   He knows this financial puzzle would all fit together so much
better if he could dissect a defense the way he can disassemble a
computer, if he could score like his cousin, James Lattimore, the
school's reigning basketball star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard UMass is interested in him,'' Jackson said of
Lattimore, a 5-foot-9 guard who averages 24 points and nine
assists.
</P>
<P>
   By his own recent admission in The North Jersey Herald News,
Lattimore has never been much of a student, and said that major
college programs have backed away from recruiting him because he
doesn't have the grades to play ball next year. Yet one Atlantic 10
coach reportedly told Lattimore a single successful semester at one
of those welcome-wagon prep schools would guarantee him a full
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his vertical leap and a system that hardly requires
academic heights, we may assume, given minimum classroom effort,
that Lattimore will go to some college, somehow, some way, and free
of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Rodger Green, a senior and another of the ``STEMers,'' as
Silverstein calls the 250 students in her (pardon the word)
program, should be so lucky. Currently carrying a 4.3 grade point
index (the .3 is for extra advanced placement honors credit) and
hoping to become a pediatrician, Green was recently accepted by a
private school that happens to play basketball in the Big East. He
was offered $22,000 in academic scholarship aid over four years.
But it still costs $25,000 a year to attend this particular school.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nondribbling student population, we should understand
that Green and Jackson are the lucky ones. ``There's a lot of kids
who don't have grades as high as me but they have a lot higher
grades than someone like my cousin,'' Jackson said. ``It's
discouraging for them because it's so competitive to get into a
good school, and even if they do, how much money is going to be
available for them?''
</P>
<P>
   Probably not enough, and then which educator or famous college
basketball coach is going to command space in the newspaper to rage
at the higher authorities on their behalf? Who is going to appeal
to the bureaucrats' sense of compassion, in the eloquent way Duke's
Mike Krzyzewski pleaded for Erick Barkley during an interview last
week on a New York City sports radio show?
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski called Ernie Lorch, the Riverside Church benefactor,
a ``saint'' and called upon the National Collegiate Athletic
Association to stop harassing Barkley and the other inner-city kids
whom society has an obligation to educate _ provided, of course,
they can rebound and spot up for 3.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Silverstein, 39 years on the job at Kennedy High, said she
is not ``offended'' when she hears this talk and when kids who are
at best marginal students are begged by universities to come. She
just wishes her telephone would ring the way it does in the
basketball and football offices, and someone would ask, ``Who are
your six best students in math?''
</P>
<P>
   She understands that sports raise visibility, make money. She
admits she can't compete with the stars on television so many of
the boys believe they can be. And she never makes the false
assumption that the star athletes are also, uniformly, academic
flops. But by and large, ``the colleges hire them to a job,''
Silverstein said. ``They're on the college payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   From the math and science office and the academic trenches of
the inner city, it is that plain and simple. ``Coach's'' sanctimony
does not add up, or compute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
