<P>
   AETNA-BID (Undated) _ Aetna Inc., the big Hartford-based health
insurer, said Wednesday that it had received a $9.9 billion
purchase offer from ING America Insurance Holdings, a
Netherlands-owned financial services company, and Wellpoint Health
Networks, a California-based national managed care company.
Securities analysts said the offer opened the possibility of a
bidding war for Aetna, the nation's biggest health insurance
company, which replaced its chief executive last week under
pressure from investors who were dismayed by a 50 percent decline
in Aetna stock prices amid disappointing business reports by the
company. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Top display)
</P>
<P>
   AZERBAIJAN-U.S. (Washington) _ Pro-Armenian activists have kept
Azerbaijan on a United States blacklist since 1992 _ the only
former Soviet republic to be punished in this way _ thanks to a
well-coordinated lobbying effort by Armenian- Americans and a
strong coalition of Armenia supporters in Congress. But the
Azerbaijanis are pushing back. President Aliev himself has engaged
in face-to-face lobbying, and some high-powered hired professionals
are working behind-the-scenes. And big oil has been acting quietly
on Azerbaijan's behalf. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
