<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-(TRIMS)-NYT &LR;      03-01 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT VOIDS RULING THAT FAVORED EX-CONVICTS ON SUPERVISED
RELEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ark., Fla., Ala., Ga.)   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that a federal
prisoner's term of ``supervised release'' begins when the inmate
gets out of prison, even if it is clear that the person should have
been released months or years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision means that an inmate receives no credit
for a prison term that has turned out to have been unduly prolonged
_ due to a retroactive change in the law, for example, as happened
in this case.
</P>
<P>
   The decision overturned a 1998 ruling in an inmate's favor by
the federal appeals court in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate, Roy L. Johnson, was convicted in U.S. District Court
in Detroit of federal drug offenses and using a gun in connection
with those offenses. Under federal sentencing law, a drug
conviction automatically requires a period of supervised release,
which is essentially the equivalent of parole, to follow any prison
term. Johnson was sentenced in 1991 to 51 months in prison and
three years of supervised release.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the firearms portion of his conviction was vacated
under a Supreme Court decision that narrowed the definition of what
it means to use a gun in connection with a drug deal. By that time,
Johnson had served more than two years beyond his sentence for the
drug offense alone. He was immediately released.
</P>
<P>
   He then argued that his supervised release should have started
running from the date, two and one-half years earlier, on which he
should have been released.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed, ruling in
Johnson's favor in the sentencing dispute that had split the lower
federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion Wednesday overturning the appeals court, Justice
Anthony M. Kennedy adhered to the text of the federal law governing
supervised release. That law provides that ``the term of supervised
release commences on the day the person is released from
imprisonment.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be little question about the meaning of the word
`release' in the context of imprisonment,'' Kennedy said, adding
that the law's reference to ``the day the person is released''
suggested a ``strict temporal interpretation, not some fictitious
or constructive earlier time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute does not say `on the day the person is released or
on the earlier day when he should have been released,''' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   As well, he said, the purpose of keeping a former inmate under
monitoring for a defined period is rehabilitation. ``The objectives
of supervised release would be unfulfilled if excess prison time
were to offset and reduce terms of supervised release.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers and the
Federal Defender Association had jointly filed a brief in the case,
United States vs. Johnson, No. 98-1696, supporting Johnson. They
said that ``principles of due process and fundamental fairness''
entitled him to credit for his erroneously lengthened prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In other action Wednesday, the court dismissed a case it had
planned to use to decide whether states are constitutionally immune
from suit under the Americans with Disabilities Act. The parties in
the case, Alsbrook vs. Arkansas, No. 99-423, had reached a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The case was one of two that the justices had scheduled for an
April 26 argument on this significant federalism issue.
</P>
<P>
   The other case, Florida vs. Dickson, No. 98-829, also had been
settled. It was dismissed last week. Each case concerned a separate
provision of the disability law.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissals mean the court will not be able to resolve the
issue this term, although it is highly likely the justices will
grant review in one of several pending cases that present variants
of the state immunity question, on which the lower federal courts
are sharply divided.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely candidate for review is an appeal filed in late
January by the state of Alabama, challenging a ruling by the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Atlanta, that states are not
immune from suit under the act.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, University of Alabama vs. Garrett, No. 99-1240,
all parties filed a motion with the Supreme Court this week seeking
an expedited review and telling the justices that they were willing
to get ready for an April argument. The court denied the motion
Wednesday, meaning that the justices will defer a decision on
whether to grant review. The court generally holds no arguments
after April, so the case would be argued after the new term begins
in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
