<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3719 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD     03-01 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI BILL MAY UNDERCUT BARAK'S DEALINGS WITH SYRIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Reworks lede to unite ideas of breakdown of coalition unity
and the potential of the draft legislation to undermine Barak's
future negotiations with Syria) 
(jt) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak suffered a political blow
Wednesday when three of the six parties in his coalition government
joined forces with the opposition to approve a bill that would
require an absolute majority of all eligible voters, and not just
those who report to the polls, on any future referendum on peace
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would make any such future referendum extremely
difficult to pass, revealed the instability of his broad-based
coalition and complicates his peacemaking efforts at a time when he
is trying to entice Syria back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   The draft bill, which defied Barak's appeals for coalition
unity, could well get tied up in committee deliberations and be
prevented from returning to the floor for months. Many doubt it
will ever become law.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's approval Wednesday, by a 60-53 vote, sends a
signal to Syria, which is already skittish, that even if Barak is
willing to concede the full Golan Heights in negotiations, he may
not be able to win public backing for what he promises.
</P>
<P>
   It also reveals a collapse of discipline within Barak's
coalition, points at the possibility of defections, and bodes ill
for the array of key decisions ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In public comments, Barak characterized the vote as a
``parliamentary trick'' and said it would not deter him from his
goals. ``I don't take lightly what happened today in the parliament
but we can't read too much into it,'' he said. ``Some 1.8 million
citizens have given me a mandate to bring a new future to the state
of Israel and no parliamentary trick will stop the majority from
deciding its stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coalition did not elect me,'' Barak said. ``The people
did. And what is connected to the coalition, believe me, I will
deal with the coalition at the proper time.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition parties that chose to challenge Barak were Yisrael
Baaliya, the Russian immigrant party, the National Religious Party,
which represents the Jewish settlers; and Shas, the ultra-Orthodox
Sephardic party that has been Barak's most difficult political
partner.
</P>
<P>
   They rallied behind a young Likud leader, Silvan Shalom, who
sensed the possibility to thwart Barak and limit prospects for
peace with Syria at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Shalom, rather than Ariel Sharon, the aging Likud leader,
succeeded in galvanizing the opposition by luring the Likud's
natural allies within the government back to conservative
ideological ground.
</P>
<P>
   Shalom criticized Barak for neglecting domestic concerns and
abandoning his entire original agenda to concentrate on one goal:
``leaving the Golan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about all the things you promised, Mr. Prime Minister?''
Shalom said, speaking in the Parliament. ``What happened to the
social issues?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the students that were promised free tuition? What
about the parents of three- and four-year-olds that were promised
free education? What about the taxi drivers and the handicapped and
all the rest? The only thing that concerns you is the Golan.''
</P>
<P>
   Any withdrawal from the Golan Heights will have to be approved
by an absolute majority _ 61 members _ of the Parliament. Shalom
said he believed that an absolute majority of the people was
needed, too. Since voter turnout is about 80 percent here, that
would require the government to win 65 percent of those votes, by
the estimates of experts.
</P>
<P>
   Many saw this as a thinly disguised attempt to nullify the
pro-peace Israeli-Arab votes and insist on a ``Jewish majority.''
Yossi Beilin, the justice minister, said the bill was not only
``anti-democratic and racist,'' but ``empowered the abstainers,
those who left the country, those who don't care whether there is
peace or not.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ahmed Tibi, an Israeli-Arab lawmaker, said the effort was as
discriminatory as anything discussed by the right-wing Austrian
party that Joerg Haider just quit as leader, a party that Israel
has condemned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who attacks Haider should have clean hands himself,''
Tibi said. ``This proposal is Israeli Haiderism in its most clear
form and a mark of Cain on a democratic society that wants to tell
others what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning the broadness of Barak's coalition was a
risky proposition. He intended to marry left and right, secular and
religious, dove and hawk inside the government to obtain maximum
backing for his diplomatic efforts. But he ended up with a balky,
riven government that cannot be counted on to support him. He was
forced to ask three Cabinet ministers to return from trips abroad
to cast their ballots in Wednesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, which with 17 seats is the third-largest party, has
threatened to quit the coalition several times, but has not. While
Shas leaders said that they were voting Wednesday on their
ideological opposition to a withdrawal from the Golan Heights, many
suspected a more parochial concern.
</P>
<P>
   In their ongoing battle with the leftist education minister,
Yossi Sarid, they have been frustrated recently at Sarid's
reluctance to grant more authority to a deputy education minister
from their party. On Wednesday, even if they were voting their
hearts, they also wanted to encourage Barak to push Sarid to give
in to their demands by flexing their political muscles, party
members said.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers in Barak's party criticized him for failing to
take the time to win over Shas and its leader, Eli Yishai, before
such a critical vote. ``He should have sat with them for four
hours, eight hours,'' said Uzi Baram. ``He should have listened to
them. To what Eli Yishai has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   And, just as many of Barak's critics were forecasting the demise
of the coalition, some centrist and leftist lawmakers called on him
Wednesday to reshape his government. ``The prime minister has two
choices: change his coalition or call early elections,'' said Amnon
Rubenstein of the leftist Meretz Party.
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, leader of the Russian immigrant party, said he
was not defying Barak or backing Shalom but acting on principle.
``When you are making painful decisions with the potential to split
the people of Israel,'' he said, referring to the withdrawal from
the Golan, ``you cannot do it with a majority of one vote.''
</P>
<P>
   If Barak takes this as a suggestion to include the views of his
coalition partners in his decision-making, it will have served a
purpose, Sharansky said. For now, he said, his party, which
consists of only four members, will remain in the government and
try ``to bring broader consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Russian immigrant lawmaker, Yuli Edelstein, said the
vote should send a message to Hafez Assad, the Syrian president.
``Under no situation will there be a majority in the Parliament or
in the public for a withdrawal from the Golan in exchange for
obscure guarantees from a dictatorial regime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From a different perspective, Shimon Peres, the former prime
minister and an ardent dove, agreed that Assad should learn from
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could create a problematic situation,'' he said. ``I
believe the Syrians must understand that they cannot go on
attacking the peace process and keeping away from the table and
doing whatever they can to make a negative impact on the Israeli
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have been disappointed that Barak's recent
overtures to Assad _ hinting that he would back a full withdrawal
from the Golan Heights _ have gone unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
