<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-01 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TOWARD `TITANIC TUESDAY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In his powerful Virginia speech declaring war on
the religio-pols who long dominated the selection of Republican
losers, John McCain turned his campaign into a crusade reminiscent
of Dwight Eisenhower's 1952 upset of Robert Taft.
</P>
<P>
   Will McCain's blast at intolerance resonate in the major states
that will largely determine the nominee? We've learned to discount
wild guesses of pollsters; we'll find that out next week in New
York, Ohio and California.
</P>
<P>
   It makes more sense to speculate about the possibilities after
those outcomes. Let's assume, for argument's sake, that Republican
voters in New York and other Eastern states rebel against the party
bosses. That is where McCain's attack on the capture of Bush by the
self-righteous right has hit home.
</P>
<P>
   Further assume that the races in the South go mainly to George
W. Bush and that McCain and Bush split the Midwest. That would mean
the eyes of the nation would be on California: who wins the biggest
delegation in this winner-take-all state probably will win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The oddity is that California offers voters two contests. One is
derogated by politicians as a ``beauty contest'' in which all
voters choose among candidates of both parties; it's a kind of
super-poll to indicate who will carry this overwhelmingly
Democratic state in November.
</P>
<P>
   The other California contest, which Bush backers insist is the
only important one, counts registered Republicans only to choose
delegates to the convention in Philadelphia this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In that GOP-only count, Bush is said to be leading 2-to-1. But
California conservatives are not Southerners; only one registered
Republican in five self-identifies as a member of the religious
right. Despite Bush's significant victory among Republicans in the
state of Washington this week, momentum is with McCain here.
Anything can happen in Thursday night's debate; expect that
internal GOP race to tighten up.
</P>
<P>
   Now take the big jump, as few observers dare. What if, in the
wide-open super-poll, McCain and Al Gore run neck-and-neck in
Democratic California, with Bush trailing and Bradley last? And
what if, as McCain demonstrates that winnability, Bush takes the
Republicans-only count?
</P>
<P>
   That would mean that McCain would win the overall election but
lose the whole delegation. Bush forces would say that those are the
party rules and that's tough.
</P>
<P>
   What would McCain forces in California say? They ain't sayin',
and I don't consult with them. But Republicans are speculating that
if California voters demonstrate that McCain would win and Bush
would lose that biggest state _ then the Republican convention
would have to take a hard look at any California ``delegation of
losers.''
</P>
<P>
   What heresy! And yet, and yet _ as we saw in the 1952 convention
(to cries of ``Thou Shalt Not Steal!''), the party that wants to
clean up the mess in Washington cannot ignore the will of the
majority to win.
</P>
<P>
   If huge numbers of voters in the nation's largest state say that
McCain would hotly compete for the state in November and Bush would
write it off, as his father did in 1992, then practical pols here
and elsewhere would suddenly rethink all previous conceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The credentials of any delegation of guaranteed losers, rejected
by the state's swing independents, would be subject to challenge.
Delegates in convention assembled would look November defeat in the
face and try to figure out a way to let March winners be winners.
</P>
<P>
   But if Bush has the huge Republicans-only California delegation
in his pocket, won't he have a majority if the decision gets to the
convention floor? No; delegates cannot vote on their own challenged
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   At Philadelphia's convention hall as in California's voting
booths, the majority of delegates rule. Whoever wins the ``beauty
contest'' here may just prevail. But McCain would have to show
clear-cut winnability in California on March 7 to stampede the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   It may embarrass the McCain people and infuriate my Bush friends
to raise this open-convention possibility now, but what are seers
for, if not to foresee? It could be a crazy notion, but this is one
crazy year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
