<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3734 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHANDLING-ALIEN-FILM-     03-01 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHANDLING-ALIEN-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVELY COMFORTABLE ON THE PLANET SHANDLING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)  (af) 
 Bruce Newman's most recent article for the Arts &AMP; Leisure section
was about the director Oliver Stone.  
 By BRUCE NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ He has made remorseless fun of his own lips, his
teeth, his rear end and, of course, his hair. Don't get him started
on his hair. During Garry Shandling's years as a standup comic, he
even joked that there was a mirror over his bed reassuring guests
that ``Objects in Mirror Are Larger Than They Appear.''
</P>
<P>
   In Shandling's world, it is all about him, all the time: punch
lines to the gut, the roundhouse, rim-shot comedy of
self-annihilation.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Shandling at the ultimate remove from his own id.
Playing an alien in the movie ``What Planet Are You From?'' _ his
character has been sent to impregnate an Earth woman and bring back
the child as part of a plot to take over the universe _ he has been
shorn of the outward appurtenances of manhood and reduced to
wearing a Freudian clip-on.
</P>
<P>
   (On his planet the men are all eunuchs and there are no women,
which doesn't quite explain the need for this interplanetary Club
Med expedition, but if the screenwriters didn't worry about that,
why should you?) This mechanical apparatus produces hydraulic
whining noises during lovemaking, though most of the whining in the
picture still comes from Shandling. It is all about him, after all.
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Mike Nichols, also stars Annette Bening
and John Goodman as a sort of jumbo Javert who is onto the scheme.
It opened Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Planet Are You From?'' exists in a kind of parallel
universe, where men are from Mars, women are from Venus and
relationships are from hunger. The film creates its own emotionally
stunted interior logic for the relationship between the alien,
named Harold, and Bening's character _ a promiscuous, romantically
needy alcoholic _ by first running Harold through a dating gauntlet
that consists, in its charmless entirety, of a topless cocktail
waitress, a sexually frigid stewardess and a nymphomaniacal
adulteress.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with this parade of harridans, what is a righteously
randy alien to do but exploit, lie to and impregnate an emotionally
fragile woman?
</P>
<P>
   That Shandling, as principal author of the script, plays this
all for laughs seems to invite an obvious question: Does he like
women?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fair question,'' he says. ``I think that as I've gotten
older I like women more. But relationships are certainly my
nemesis. I think that, not unlike some other Jewish men I know, I
have mother issues that lead to me having difficulty in
relationships. And yet I sometimes think, Buddha wasn't married,
Jesus wasn't married, and the pope wasn't married. And no one
looked at them and said: `What? You have commitment issues?'''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Shandling is equating himself with any of the major
above-the-title divinities, but he does not resist the image of
himself as a slightly lesser celestial being, navigating from one
star date to the next. ``Relationships may be the final frontier
for me,'' he says. ``I'm very comfortable with myself, and with
being alone, so I'm not driven to be in a relationship. I'm far
more content now than I've ever been in my life. But, you know, if
there's something I'm missing, I'm the first to want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Contentment, after all, has its limits on Shandling's planet.
```I wouldn't want to be me' is one of my favorite sayings,''
Shandling adds, wincing brightly. If you ask whether he means it,
however, this approximate smile collapses into a puddle of abject
uncertainty. ``I'm not sure,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Bening has said that Shandling wrote the script ``from his
heart,'' and surely any heart that beats in syncopation with an
alien from another planet is one worth having. Shandling has placed
himself inside the glowing breast of E.T., and buffed up his little
man's dialogue with what sound like excerpts from the Penthouse
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know comedians who have a dark side, a lot of
unhappiness,'' Bening says. ``Garry doesn't. You never feel like,
`Oh god, he's making jokes again!' or that it comes from some sort
of insecurity. He's a very strong person, and his humor seems to
come from his ebullience, the way he sees the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Tucson, Shandling saw the world as a place blasted
by sunshine. He blasted back. ``I was one of those kids who didn't
quite fit in in high school, as I think you would expect,'' he
says. ``You don't end up like me if you fit in. Humor did work in
high school and I was funny, but I was not that popular. In other
words, things were sort of like they are now.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been launched into his low, observational orbit around
the Earth when he was 10, after his older brother Barry died of
cystic fibrosis. ``It made me think about the issue of life and
death very early,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He studied electrical engineering at the University of Arizona
in the mid-'70s until he walked out of a lab one day to get a drink
of water and never came back.
</P>
<P>
   His sense of dislocation gave him permanent outsider status no
matter where he went, eventually allowing him to write from the
point of view of an extraterrestrial. ``I don't feel like I fit in
in Hollywood,'' Shandling says, ``so it's not difficult to
extrapolate not fitting in on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What Planet Are You From?'' takes the assimilationist view
that sex in America is a matter of life or death, which is only one
of the ways in which it is obvious that this is a film made by men.
Nichols has taken the ``Men Are From Mars'' view that women want a
friend who will hug them, while men care about little other than
sex. It is precisely the sort of reductive thinking that accounts
for the movie's glazed slickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most young men think about sex, and think that women are
sexual objects,'' Shandling says. ``And as we get older, we realize
there are elements that are far more important.'' He is awash in
sincerity. ``Or almost as important,'' he says. Then he winces
again. (Shandling winces a lot.)
</P>
<P>
   The sincerity of Shandling's acting and his commitment to
carrying the film came into heated dispute when Nichols accused him
early in the production of showing up for work unprepared, then
demanding excessive retakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garry and I took some time to find each other,'' Nichols says.
``He never knew the lines. He came in knowing apparently much, much
less than me about it. And at first I was sort of startled, and I'd
think: `Well, what do you (italics)mean(end italics) you don't know
the lines? You wrote it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, Nichols realized that this was his star's way of staying
in the moment _ where his style of humor is most alive _ rather
than becoming ossified by lines that he had written (with the help
of the co-writers Michael Leeson, Ed Solomon and Peter Tolan) years
earlier. But that came with all the nervous tics and twitches that
are Shandling's comic stock in trade.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After smaller roles in films, including ``Love Affair'' with
Warren Beatty and Bening and ``Hurlyburly,'' ``What Planet'' is
Shandling's debut as a leading man. ``I'm sure he was nervous,''
Nichols says. ``I think he is professionally insecure. But it's a
two-edged sword, that kind of constant insecurity, because it's a
burden on you also.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, who had John Travolta impersonating Bill Clinton in
``Primary Colors'' and now has Shandling doing an impersonation of
a human being, seems intent himself on impersonating Ivan Reitman
or possibly even John Landis. In this picture he has a baby that
urinates like a casino fountain, and a running penis joke. It is
difficult to watch these refinements on Nichols' previous work _
which includes ``Carnal Knowledge'' and ``The Graduate'' _ without
wanting to mutter the word ``plastics.''
</P>
<P>
   The arc of Shandling's career has taken him from writing sitcoms
like ``Welcome Back, Kotter'' to standup comedy and then the
1986-90 Showtime series ``This Is Garry Shandling's Show.'' After
that came a stint as the regular guest host for Johnny Carson on
``The Tonight Show,'' an experience that helped inspire his HBO
talk-show auto-da-fe, ``The Larry Sanders Show.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1998, during the last of the ``Sanders'' show's seven
seasons, that Shandling's 20-year business relationship and close
friendship with his manager, Brad Grey, suddenly ruptured.
Shandling filed a lawsuit charging Grey with using their
relationship to build his management and production businesses, and
asked for $100 million in damages. Grey countersued alleging breach
of contract, and the suit was settled last year with an exchange of
some television rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't pleasant, but it was something that had to happen,''
Shandling says of the feud. ``It's certainly a relief to have it
behind me, but I was in the middle of that when we did the last
season of the show, and I was able to compartmentalize it.''
Shandling was not necessarily known for compartmentalizing his
insecurities or restraining his disappointments when he was
writing, producing and starring in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now find that I can throw the neurotic switch when I need it
to get some comic material,'' he says, ``and throw it off when I
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``What Planet Are You From?,'' what he throws off most often
are his clothes for frequent love scenes, not least of all with
Bening. For someone who has frequently used insecurities about his
own body to get laughs, Shandling holds back precious little. ``I
think I look pretty good in the movie,'' he says. ``I worked out a
little bit. I mean, I don't think I look like a gentile, but I
think I'm handsome from both the front and the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Any awkwardness he felt was only exacerbated by working naked
with Bening, who is the wife of Shandling's close friend Beatty.
``She was kind enough not to make fun of me at any point during the
nude scene,'' Shandling says, ``which of course would have really
emasculated me. I got enough of that from the craft services
people. During several takes, I was making love to her but I was
actually thinking about Warren. I felt he would want that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Shandling must decide what (italics)he(end italics) wants.
Should he reinvent himself as a film star? Or go back to the grind
of television, where he is undeniably most at home? He has what he
calls ``a fantastic idea for a television series that I wouldn't
want to be in,'' as well as plans for two movies (he might also
direct next time).
</P>
<P>
   Soon he will begin work on an episode of ``The X-Files,''
written and directed by his friend David Duchovny, in which Fox
Mulder discovers that a movie is being made about his life.
Shandling stars as the movie Mulder and has a love scene with
Duchovny's real wife, Tea Leoni. ``These men,'' Shandling notes
dejectedly, ``seem to have faith in me that I will be a worse lover
than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   At 51, he seems determined for the first time in his career not
to let his ambition define him, to surprise anyone who
underestimates his capacity for love. ``I'm at an interesting place
in my life where I feel oddly content,'' Shandling says. ``I'm a
late bloomer, and I may just show up Beatty and get married well
after the age he did. I'm curious myself to see how it all unfolds.
I'm sort of willing to be whatever I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2033EST &QL; 
