<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW U.N. ARMS CHIEF CALLS FOR IRAQ TO ACCEPT WEAPONS MONITORING
PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United Nations' new chief arms inspector
for Iraq left the government of Saddam Hussein no hope of getting a
better deal on the monitoring of its weapons programs Wednesday,
and said it would have to accept inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The arms chief, Hans Blix, said at a news conference a few hours
after taking office that he would expect Iraq to give inspectors
unimpeded access. He also pledged that standards for the
inspections would not be lowered. But he did point out that he was
not leading a commando force and would not seek to humiliate the
Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Blix, 71, a former foreign minister of Sweden and the director
general of the International Atomic Energy Agency from 1981 to
1997, said he had no plans to go to Iraq to smooth the way for his
new commission or to make any other overtures, as some of Iraq's
supporters have proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should have to tempt them to cooperate,'' he
said. ``The first step would be for Iraq to accept the
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Iraqis, who have publicly dismissed the new
inspection system, should instead see the benefits in cooperating,
including an improvement in Iraqi living standards. In theory, at
least, the system could lead within a year to the suspension of
sanctions that were imposed after the invasion of Kuwait in August
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Blix spoke on the same day that Hans von Sponeck, the relief
coordinator in Iraq who has resigned as of March 31, held a news
conference to lament how badly the Iraqi population is suffering
under sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Von Sponeck, who said the Iraqis were living in unacceptable
physical and intellectual deprivation, acknowledged that what he
called ``internal and external factors'' contributed to the
situation. But he declined to discuss how much responsibility for
the situation, if any, fell on the Hussein government.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the Security Council sanctions committee dealing
with Iraq began to approve a list of educational, agricultural,
food and medical goods that Iraq will be allowed to import almost
automatically _ or at least without extensive scrutiny _ on the
advice of U.N. officials.
</P>
<P>
   Blix sought to allay fears that he would make the search for
illegal biological, chemical and missile systems easier for Iraq.
He continues to be criticized by some independent arms control
experts who said he failed to detect a nascent Iraqi nuclear
program when he was director of the atomic energy agency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said he planned to allow experts from Unscom, the
now-disbanding first arms inspection body, to compete for jobs on
the new commission. But he said they would have to agree to work
for the United Nations and not operate on loan from governments, as
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Some Security Council members, in particular Russia, wanted to
start with an all-new inspection team. But disarmament experts said
that would handicap inexperienced inspectors and give Iraq an
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Blix said he was optimistic that Iraq would ultimately agree to
inspections, and he added that his door is open to the Iraqi
government if and when they want to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iraqis may tend to look upon inspections as a penalty
which they like to minimize,'' he said. ``I think the way they
should look at it is as an opportunity they should maximize.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3737 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BOYD-GAINES-THEATER-2     03-01 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYD-GAINES-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THOSE WHO DANCE AND THOSE WHO DREAM ABOUT IT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Mich.)  (af) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Boyd Gaines emerged from his dressing room after a
matinee of ``Contact,'' famished and drained. He apologized for the
time he had taken in collecting himself, and when it was suggested
that post-performance recovery is the entitlement of every dancer,
he shot his visitor a withering look.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got that absolutely right,'' a member of the ensemble
chimed in as he passed in the hallway beneath the Vivian Beaumont
Theater, where the hit dance-play is now ensconced. ``Boyd (begin
italics)is(end italics) a dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a hint of ribbing, along with comradely encouragement,
in his colleague's voice, which changed the color of Gaines'
disposition to one of outright embarrassment. This is clearly not a
performer who gazes into a mirror and thinks: Hey there, Astaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they called me about doing the part, I kept trying to
talk them out of it,'' Gaines said a short time later over a plate
of roast chicken and steamed vegetables in the cafeteria of his
alma mater, the Juilliard School, across West 65th Street from
Lincoln Center. ``I literally thought Susan Stroman had mixed me up
with someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Stroman, the director-choreographer of ``Contact,'' did not
have the wrong number. Though Gaines did not know an extension from
an under-arm side by side, he was the performer Stroman wanted as
the central figure in the final, swing-dance-inspired entry in her
trio of dance plays.
</P>
<P>
   The evening, set to recorded music ranging from Bizet to the
Beach Boys, has proved so popular it has moved from Lincoln
Center's smaller Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater to the larger,
Tony-eligible Vivian Beaumont, where it is in previews before
officially reopening on March 30.
</P>
<P>
   It is fortunate that Gaines did not make a persuasive enough
case against himself, for his moving performance as Michael Wiley,
the successful if suicidally lonely New Yorker of the show's title
piece, is one of the most emotionally rewarding facets of
``Contact.''
</P>
<P>
   That his face is familiar to regular theatergoers _ he won Tony
Awards in 1989 and 1994 for ``The Heidi Chronicles'' and ``She
Loves Me'' _ deepens the audience's own contact with the
production. It's a distinction he shares with one other actor in
the 22-member ensemble, Karen Ziemba, the star of the second
offering, ``Did You Move?,'' who turns in an equally affecting
portrayal as a Queens homemaker browbeaten into submission by her
bullying husband.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these stage veterans serve as the show's touchstones,
reminding us that what we are watching here is more than dance
theater _ it's dramatic art.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing ``Contact'' a second time, you are struck afresh by the
cleverness of Stroman's casting choices. In ``Did You Move?,''
Ziemba's 1950s housewife breaks into a comic dream ballet in an
Italian restaurant, but it's the actress' infectious Imogene
Coca-ish exuberance, rather than the dancing alone, that gives the
piece its buoyancy.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gaines seeks out the girl of his dreams during a
hallucinatory hour set in a dance club, and contrary to the cliche,
he is not transformed by love into a latter-day Gene Kelly; he is
just a guy trying to take a few steps in a new direction. (The
curtain-raiser, ``Swinging,'' is a playful takeoff on an
18th-century Fragonard painting, ``The Swing.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was creating the pieces, I wanted people to be able to
relate to Boyd and to Karen, to be able to empathize with them,''
Stroman said. ``That is indeed what anchors the second and third
pieces. Karen, in addition to being an accomplished dancer, never
changes from being that middle-class housewife. Boyd has a very
vulnerable quality, and the character of Michael Wiley is about
somebody taking chances in unfamiliar territory. And, the fact is,
Boyd himself is taking chances in unfamiliar territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Although their paths never cross in the show _ Ziemba appears
only in the second piece, while Gaines' performance comes after the
intermission _ you can feel how much of the evening is molded to
the contours of their personalities, how much depth of character
and feeling their presence adds. The stories Stroman and the author
John Weidman have created are linked in all kinds of nuanced ways;
one of them is in the idea of identity, of accepting yourself for
who you are.
</P>
<P>
   Another is in the tension between holding back and letting go,
of the damage done to the psyche in bottling up one's emotions, and
the surprising payoffs in opening the heart to all of life's
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   To dance or not to dance: that is the question in ``Contact''
for the troubled and, as the evening progresses, increasingly
complex characters. Ziemba's housewife is shriveling inside because
she is not allowed to express herself. Gaines' adman is
self-destructing because he does not know how to express himself.
One is desperate to dance; the other desperately needs to learn
how.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The characters' attitudes, it turns out, are mirrors for those
of the actors. The Georgia-born Gaines says that as a Juilliard
acting student he was a complete washout in dance classes. ``They
hated me,'' he recalled with a laugh. ``They said, `If you don't
learn a pirouette, we don't know what we're going to do with
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ziemba, on the other hand, did little but pirouette as a little
girl growing up outside Detroit, and imagined herself with a
classical career. ``I danced with the Ohio Ballet,'' she said one
afternoon, while sitting in the lobby of the Beaumont. ``I wanted
to be a concert dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaines and Ziemba, both Manhattanites and both married, also
have both been subjected to the proverbial ups and downs of careers
on the stage. After years of well-thought-of work, both had highly
visible disappointments a few years back, Gaines in a Roundabout
Theater Company revival of Stephen Sondheim's ``Co.'' that failed
to transfer for an anticipated commercial run on Broadway; Ziemba
in the slender Kander and Ebb musical ``Steel Pier.''
</P>
<P>
   It meant a great deal to both actors that Stroman asked them to
create original musical characters with such identifiably human
foibles.
</P>
<P>
   I have had a lot of people, especially men, come up to me and
say, `I'm that guy who can't dance,''' Gaines said. One of his
character's most endearing moments in ``Contact'' comes when,
nursing a drink at a bar, he finally summons the courage to join
the Girl in the Yellow Dress (Deborah Yates) on the dance floor,
but his body refuses to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This character's journey is about bravery _ you can't be truly
brave unless you are truly afraid,'' Gaines said. ``We've all known
this person: socially adept, but unable to make personal
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   It took some marshaling of courage for Gaines to overcome his
inhibitions about dancing, especially because it was with a
Broadway-caliber corps. The first weeks of the initial workshop
production, in a rehearsal room, felt like a foreign-language
tutorial to him: ``They were teaching us to do the steps. I equated
it with learning Russian: `OK, here are 40 new words.'''
</P>
<P>
   His dancing partner, Yates, was a huge help _ ``she was
incredibly patient, and later she forced me to lead her'' _ but at
some point, he became so conscious of his body that he stopped
thinking like an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stro kept saying, `You're not acting,''' Gaines said, invoking
Stroman's nickname. `` `You're just doing the steps.'''
</P>
<P>
   He and Yates practiced until Gaines felt confident he would not
look foolish. ``Now, it's like juggling,'' he said. ``It's getting
a certain number of balls in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziemba, unlike Gaines, had worked with Stroman on several other
shows, from the Kander and Ebb Off Broadway revue ``And the World
Goes 'Round'' to ``Crazy for You'' on Broadway, and her knowledge
of dance proved as essential to ``Contact'' as was Gaines'
peripheral experience of it. The wife in ``Did You Move?'' is an
archetype, a woman frozen in a servile role in a loveless marriage;
an actress of warmth and some comic skill was required to make her
more than merely pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a change for Ziemba to discover a character through
snippets of classical music, rather than the traditional
musical-comedy accouterments of abundant dialogue and song.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what I did had to do with the music it was connected
to,'' she said. In ``Did You Move?'' the wife passes into a trance
each time her husband, played by Jason Antoon, leaves the table for
the buffet. ``At first, the music has a lot of plucks of the
violin: she's discovering her feet, it's prickly, it's not total
abandon yet,'' Ziemba said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how movement and body language and the right kind
of music underneath creates total understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   It is, in fact, the variations Ziemba and Gaines have discovered
in the harmony between music and movement that give ``Contact'' the
quality of a complete piece of musical theater, even if it is not a
traditional one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this physical show going on and this emotional show
going on,'' Gaines said. ``The most fun is when I feel I have them
in balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
