<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-ANNA-NICOLE-HNS &LR;      03-01 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNA-NICOLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PLAYBOY PLAYMATE INHERITANCE FIGHT DELAYED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Former Playboy Playmate Anna Nicole Smith must wait
until at least September to get her day in court over claims she is
entitled to half of her deceased billionaire husband J. Howard
Marshall II's fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The trial in which Smith and Marshall's two sons are fighting
over the oilman's estate was to begin next week in Harris County
Probate Judge Mike Wood's court. But a Texas 1st Court of Appeals
ruling Wednesday has postponed it.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The delay is the result of a motion by Marshall's elder son, J.
Howard Marshall III, 63, who was allegedly disinherited over a 1980
family business dispute. The younger son, E. Pierce Marshall, 60,
of Dallas, took over the business and says his father's 1992 will
left him the entire estate.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall III, co-owner of a Los Angeles electronics company,
claims his father resolved their differences and promised to will
him half of the estate. But, he alleges, his brother conspired with
Charles Koch, president of Wichita, Kan.-based Koch Industries, and
Don Cordes, the company's lawyer, to deprive him of his rightful
half.
</P>
<P>
   When Marshall II died at 90 in 1995, almost all his wealth was
tied up in the stock of Koch Industries, a pipeline and mineral
conglomerate he helped found and which is the nation's
second-largest privately held company.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall III also sued Koch and Cordes.
</P>
<P>
   Wood ruled in December that Koch and Cordes, who live in Kansas,
would not have to appear for the Texas trial because their alleged
involvement did not occur here.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall III appealed, hoping to avoid a separate trial in
Kansas against Koch and Cordes.
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas law, trials are automatically delayed while such
jurisdictional appeals are pending.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid delaying the probate trial, Wood severed Marshall III's
claims against Koch and Cordes into a separate case.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall III appealed this decision as well, saying it violated
the spirit of the Texas law to delay trials with unresolved
jurisdictional issues.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge appellate panel unanimously agreed, saying the
probate trial cannot start until the court rules on whether Koch
and Cordes can be tried in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling will be made on an expedited basis. Wood rescheduled
the trial for Sept. 1, hoping for a decision by then. He also wants
to avoid a summer trial because so many lawyers are involved and
vacations might cause scheduling conflicts, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 31, also claims E. Pierce Marshall defrauded her out of
half of the estate by coercing his father to sign documents giving
him control of the fortune.
</P>
<P>
   E. Pierce Marshall says his father knowingly signed all the
documents and gave Smith all he intended, about $8 million to $10
million in cash and jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who met her future husband in 1994 while she was a
topless dancer in Houston, is also involved in a Los Angeles
bankruptcy proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   E. Pierce Marshall intervened in the proceeding to protect his
interest in his libel lawsuit against Smith. Last year, U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Samuel L. Bufford said Smith was entitled to all
she was seeking against E. Pierce Marshall, an estimated $820
million. The judge issued the order to punish Marshall for
allegedly destroying evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Bufford rescinded the order in January, saying he would file an
amended order. E. Pierce Marshall's attorneys have said Bufford had
no jurisdiction to award Smith damages related to the estate.
</P>
<P>
   E. Pierce Marshall denied destroying evidence, saying he was not
in control of the materials in question and that Smith's California
attorneys were simply attempting to harass him through duplicative
court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
