<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3745 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CHILD-SHOT-2TAKES-NYT     03-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-SHOT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE PAINT PORTRAIT OF A TROUBLED CHILD WHO TOOK LIFE OF
CLASSMATE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CHILD-MENTAL) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT MORRIS TOWNSHIP, Mich. _ His father was in and out of
prison. His mother, evicted from her own home, sent him and his
brother to live with an uncle in a dilapidated house here, just
north of Flint.
</P>
<P>
   There, he did not even have his own bed and fell asleep in a
place that neighbors say was filled with noise, drugs and guns.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, the 6-year-old got his hands on one of those
guns, stuffed it into his pants pocket and went off to first grade,
where he killed a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, cars paused outside the white clapboard residence,
as passersby tried to get a look at the home of a troubled child, a
boy who police say did not fully comprehend what he did when he
used a .32-caliber handgun on the 6-year-old girl, Kayla Renee
Rolland. She was shot once in the neck just before 10 a.m. Tuesday
in front of a group of about 22 first graders as they made their
way into the hall of the Theo J. Buell Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   The boy put the gun in a desk after the shooting and simply
walked away. &QL; 
Questioned by detectives, the boy did not cry, police said, and
afterward sat and drew pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This young boy appears not to have many advantages in life,''
said Arthur A. Busch, the Genessee County prosecutor, who said the
boy probably would not be charged and was released on Wednesday to
an aunt.
</P>
<P>
   Although the authorities appeared to take a sympathetic attitude
toward a young child who took another child's life, many residents
said the real sympathy belonged with Kayla's family and questioned
whether it was safe to send their children back to school.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The authorities say the boy's own father, serving time in jail
for a parole violation involving a burglary, said the boy was
living in a ``crack house.'' The neighbors say they suspected it
all along.
</P>
<P>
   In a raid Tuesday night, the authorities found a stolen handgun
and some narcotics in the home and jailed the boy's uncle,
Sirmarcus Winfrey, on an outstanding warrant for theft. Another
man, age 19, who lived in the home, who the authorities said
brought the stolen gun used in the killing into the home, turned
himself into the police on Wednesday afternoon. The authorities
said they were considering bringing charges of involuntary
manslaughter against whoever brought the gun into the house.
</P>
<P>
   They are also considering pressing charges of child neglect
against the family or guardians of the child, whose name was
withheld.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my position that we have, at this point, enough evidence
to establish child neglect,'' the prosecutor said. ``My attorneys
will go to court even today to argue that the court should take
jurisdiction of this little boy. I am very concerned about the
placement of this little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, the boy's parents appeared in court for
a hearing about custody of the boy and his brother. A judge moved
to have the state gain custody of the children, saying the boy's
mother was a drug addict who had admitted that she had exposed the
children to marijuana on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said there were also reports that the mother had
physically abused one of her children. The boy's father, who was
brought from the local jail, spoke to the court, saying he was
sorry for what had happened and acknowledging that he had not
always been a good father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it had never happened,'' he said. ``I just feel sorry
for the other child.'' The mother sobbed nearby, wiping her eyes
with tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Robert Pickell said that he went to the jail Tuesday
night to ask the boy's father if he knew anything about the gun.
The sheriff said the boy's father said the child was frequently in
trouble and had been in fights at school.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the boy did not seem to comprehend what had
happened and appeared nonchalant when interviewed by detectives on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was their impression the boy didn't understand what he had
done, did not appreciate the consequences of his actions and
appeared to take this as some sort of, well, that this just kind of
happens like on television,'' Busch said at a crowded news
conference on Wednesday morning. ``This is a young boy, 6 years
old, who cannot obviously form criminal intent. He does not seem to
understand the gravity of the event.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after the shooting, the schools in this working-class town
remained closed. Flags flew at half staff. Grieving residents left
flowers and notes and toys at the doors of the school.
</P>
<P>
   The horror at Buell Elementary School, authorities say, was born
of the anger of a little boy who found a deadly weapon under a
blanket on the bed at home and used it on a young girl he had
quarreled with the day before.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chad Bullard, who lived next door to the boy's family for three
years before the family was evicted, said the house had been raided
by the police several times.
</P>
<P>
   It was a home where cars were always stopping, late into the
night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't the best of neighbors,'' he said. ``I tried to
avoid them because there was always conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he often quarreled with the family. The boy and his
8-year-old brother often teased his dog, and when Bullard tried to
stop it, the boys' parents often intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would say, `Stop yelling at my kids,' and I would say,
`You need to take care of them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard said the mother worked during the day and into the
evening and that the boy's father was not around very often.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the boy's mother was evicted from the home.
She moved elsewhere and often sent the two boys to stay with her
brother and at least one family friend, in a house on Juliah
Street, about a half mile from the school.
</P>
<P>
   The two-bedroom home is a kind of makeshift auto shop. A
Corvette sits on the front lawn, propped up by cement blocks.
Another car, its hood ajar, sits to the back of the house next to a
weathered John Deere snowmobile, which appears to be undergoing
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   There are auto parts and mangled hub caps scattered outside the
house, candy wrappers, soda bottles and wires and equipment out
front. The windows are shaded with old blankets and broken windows
are patched up with blue tarp. A deep and muddy hole sits to the
left of the house. And a dull light burns inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't associate with them,'' said Will Oscar, a 31-year-old
neighbor who said he is planning to move soon. ``There was always a
lot of traffic there; I heard gun shots. I didn't feel safe. My car
was stolen out of my driveway twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Oscar said he did not know the boy and his older brother were
living next door. He said the mother often dropped them off there.
They sometimes teased his dog, but otherwise the boys were ``just
normal kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In school, the boy was often in trouble, the authorities said on
Wednesday. He had a social worker and had been in several fights.
The authorities said they had heard that the boy had recently been
in a quarrel or scuffle with six-year-old Kayla Rolland.
</P>
<P>
   Three boys, who were walking by Buell Elementary School on
Wednesday, said they witnessed the fight on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fighting with that little girl a few days ago,'' said
13-year-old John Owens, who was walking by the school yard after
school let out on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked by and said `Chill out,' said Julius Irving, 10.
Wayne Morris, 14, said: ``Then this guy tried to get him to stop it
and he picks up this stick and starts hitting him. And the kid was
a lot bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne says there are lots of drugs in the area. ``We walk down
the street and we hear guys say, `Weed? Weed?''
</P>
<P>
   Maranda Ide, an 8-year-old third grader, said she heard the gun
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in my class, writing from the dictionary,'' she said.
``I heard something go 'bang,' and I immediately started crying,
because I knew it was a gun shot, because we hear gun shots all the
time around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maranda said she didn't sleep on Tuesday night, but she is not
too afraid to go back to school. ``I think tomorrow will probably
be the same as it was before the gun was fired. But I think I'll
probably cry for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for reopening the school. The front door is
jammed with flowers, bunnies, teddy bears and candles. Cards read,
``Kayla, we won't forget you.'' There are baskets of M&AMP;M's and
sunglasses, drawings of broken hearts, splashed with crayon.
</P>
<P>
   Rasu King, a 31-year-old woman from the neighborhood, said she
was dropping off a candle and a teddy bear. ``I hope people realize
how serious this is,'' she said. ``If you can't go to elementary
school, you can't go anywhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BOOK-CLUB-MERGER-NYT &LR;      03-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CLUB-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK - OF - THE - MONTH CLUB AND LITERARY GUILD AGREE TO FORM
PARTNERSHIP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two book club titans that battled for decades to guide popular
literary tastes completed a partnership deal Wednesday that
executives say will ultimately transform the institutions into a
digital hybrid catering to dozens of narrow markets.
</P>
<P>
   Threatened by fierce pressures from price-cutting online
booksellers, the Book-of-the-Month Club and the Literary Guild
agreed to form an alliance arranged by the companies that control
them _ Time Inc., a subsidiary of Time Warner Inc. and Bertelsmann
AG, respectively. The deal involved no exchange of money or shares.
</P>
<P>
   The companies had announced plans to forge an alliance in
December, but they offered few details at the time because terms of
the deal were still under negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   With the pairing, the traditional book clubs will evolve into
interactive digital clubs with some of the same features of an
online bookseller _ live chats with authors, electronic polls,
member bulletin boards, reviews and book excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the competitive pressure we might not have made the
deal,'' said Markus Wilhelm, the president and chief executive of
Bertelsmann's Doubleday Direct, which operates the Literary Guild
along with some 35 other clubs. ``We will expand on the Internet to
which we are losing market share in the general-interest area. We
felt that we had hit the ceiling for our traditional book clubs,
and therefore, we have to expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday Direct would manage the new company, which would have
combined annual revenue of about $900 million, a membership of more
than 8 million book club customers and more than 3,000 employees,
according to executives close to the negotiations. The partnership
would have a share of more than 70 percent of the $1.25 billion
book club market.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann and Time would each retain a 50 percent stake in the
partnership, which brings together a collection of about 50
existing book clubs ranging from the general interest
Book-of-the-Month-Club and the Literary Guild to the Crossings Club
for Christian families and the Quality Paperback Book Club.
</P>
<P>
   The partners have picked Wilhelm to be the chief executive of
the combined book clubs. The new company, however, still lacks a
name, a board and a chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both companies have to make significant investments into the
development of their interactive businesses and their
infrastructure,'' said Wilhelm, who could not estimate the total
cost for such a transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's hope is a combined book club that would operate
more efficiently in what has become an increasingly competitive
bookselling market, Peter Costiglio, a spokesman for Time Inc.,
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when the online booksellers started offering 50
percent price discounts for books on the New York Times best-seller
list last year, the general-interest book clubs like the Literary
Guild and Book-of-the-Month-Club immediately watched their market
share dwindle.
</P>
<P>
   To counter that erosion, Doubleday Direct created an interactive
division that developed plans to create 12 online book clubs this
year and 20 next year. Instead of appealing to a broad range of
members _ as the Literary Guild does _ the aim was to reach narrow
interest groups seeking a depth of titles on particular themes that
are vetted by experts in those fields. The logic was that online
booksellers had been ignoring these groups to appeal to a broader
following.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last year Doubleday Direct started a club called
Black Expressions featuring African-American literature; it grew to
have 40,000 members within three months. It also started a virtual
book club called Venus that offers titles exploring sexual themes
and is promoted with brochures that vow: ``Venus is a very personal
club. All of our packaging is discreet, so no one will have the
slightest clue. We promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Still to come later this year is another club called Mango that
will aim at young women in their 20s, and Rhapsody, a club
featuring mass-market romance novels.
</P>
<P>
   These digital book clubs still rely on some basic time-tested
rituals that have endured for decades. For instance, buyers can get
several books for a low price, and in return, agree to future
monthly purchases that are made automatically unless a customer
checks off a ``negative option.''
</P>
<P>
   With the alliance, Bertelsmann and Time Warner are combining two
old literary institutions with distinctly different cultures. The
Book-of-the-Month Club, which is based in New York, was started in
1926 by Harry Scherman, who invented the first American book club
with a gimmick that featured august literary judges who would
gather around an oak table and a tray of sherry to anoint the
monthly selections by a Quaker-style consensus process.
</P>
<P>
   The Book-of-the-Month Club was considered more literary and less
commercial than the Literary Guild, which was started a year later.
</P>
<P>
   While the Book-of-the-Month-Club offered more nonfiction to a
more heavily male audience, the Literary Guild featured more
fiction choices for a membership dominated by women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
