<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-PLEA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge sets arraignment for teen who shot classmates for April
 &HT;    By Henry Farber
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ T.J. Solomon, the teen-ager who shot and wounded six
classmates at Heritage High School last May, could enter a plea
April 6 in Rockdale County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sidney Nation set the arraignment date this week. Solomon
could plead guilty or not guilty or make one of a handful of other
pleas. They include pleading guilty but mentally ill or not guilty
by reason of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never disputed that the shots were fired by Mr.
Solomon,'' said defense attorney Jana Harris. ``The depths of his
illness, the circumstances surrounding the case _ these are the
things that will be looked at at the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing ethical boundaries, neither Harris nor District Attorney
Richard Read would discuss whether the case is likely to reach a
jury. If Solomon, 16, pleads guilty or mentally ill, he will be
sentenced without a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Solomon hid a rifle in his pants leg and also
concealed a handgun before opening fire in a crowded hall area at
Heritage, exactly one month after the rampage in Littleton, Colo.,
that left 12 students and a teacher dead.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Heritage students suffered critical injuries.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on all counts, Solomon would face prison sentences
totaling up to 350 years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
