<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET DECISION
</P>
<P>
   Home Secretary Jack Straw will decide Thursday whether Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, 84, is free to return home to Chile for health
reasons after 17 months under house arrest in England or must face
extradition to Spain to stand trial on torture charges. Though a
decision to release him is subject to legal challenge, it was not
clear whether any group would bring an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: PEACE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie
Ahern, have set a three-week timetable to try to end the stalemate
over resumption of home rule for Northern Ireland. Talks will be
held in Belfast for two weeks and in Washington with President
Clinton at St. Patrick's Day celebrations. The two prime ministers
will ``take stock'' of any progress at a European Union meeting in
Lisbon on March 23 and 24, according to Blair's office.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SECRETS REMAIN
</P>
<P>
   The release of secret archives failed to shed new light on the
1936 abdication of King Edward VIII, his suspected sympathies for
the Third Reich and the antagonism the mother of Queen Elizabeth
II, the 99-year-old Queen Mother, felt for Wallis Simpson, Edward's
wife. The government withheld key documents, and Vernon Bogdanor, a
professor of politics at Oxford, said, ``My hunch would be the
papers held back are matters affecting the royal family and the
Queen Mother.''
</P>
<P>
   FINLAND: PRESIDENT SWORN IN
</P>
<P>
   Finland inaugurated its first woman as president, Tarja Halonen,
56, who promised to work for greater equality between the sexes and
a reduction in regional distortions in the distribution of wealth.
A Social Democrat and onetime student radical, she has been foreign
minister since 1995. She succeeds Matti Ahtisaari, who stepped down
after a six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: AIDE QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Facing a trial on corruption charges, former Foreign Minister
Roland Dumas has quit as head of the highest judicial body, the
Constitutional Council. Dumas had been on leave because of an
investigation into his reported involvement in kickbacks from the
Elf oil company. But after magistrates concluded there was enough
evidence to go to trial, Dumas' colleagues put pressure on him to
resign. Dumas, who denies any guilt, is accused of getting his
mistress a fake job with Elf.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CUBAN `ILLEGAL'
</P>
<P>
   Jose Imperatori, the Cuban diplomat expelled from the United
States, has overstayed his 48-hour transit visa, prompting Foreign
Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy to say, ``He's now breaking the
law.'' Imperatori slipped away at Montreal airport on Saturday and
took refuge in Cuba's embassy in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ZEDILLO SOARS
</P>
<P>
   President Ernesto Zedillo has reached his highest popular
approval rating, scoring 7.2 out of 10 in a national poll by the
newspaper Reforma. The strong rating of Zedillo, whose six-year
term ends on Dec. 1, is expected to help his party's candidate,
Francisco Labastida Ochoa, in presidential elections on July 2.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF TRIAL ADJOURNED
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the hijacking trial of Nawaz Sharif has adjourned
proceedings until Monday, giving the former minister time to retain
new lawyers or to persuade his previous ones to return. Sharif's
defense team quit last weekend, protesting the judge's ruling that
their client's testimony must be given in secret.
</P>
</TEXT>
