<HEADER>
A3754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GA-BUSH02-COX     03-01 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-BUSH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush enjoys interplay with Georgia crowd
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush
was in Georgia on Wednesday for a town hall meeting to rally
suburban voters before the state's Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might notice I walked in with a little spring in my
step,'' said an invigorated Bush, fresh off victories in Virginia,
North Dakota and Washington state. ``They all helped us take a step
closer to ending the Clinton era in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   That set off the loudest applause of the morning from the 2,200
people in attendance at the Gwinnett Civic and Cultural Center in
Duluth.
</P>
<P>
   Gwinnett County was a natural selection for Bush's only stop in
Georgia before the Tuesday presidential primary. Gwinnett, Cobb and
north Fulton counties represent about 25 percent of the state's GOP
vote. Campaign strategists said they want to be sure they motivate
Republicans to get to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's chief Republican rival, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, has
no plans to visit Georgia before the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Cathy Cox predicted Wednesday that 38 percent
of Georgia's 3.4 million registered voters will turn out for next
week's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ``one-on-one'' with voters in Gwinnett on Wednesday
included questions and answers from audience members.
</P>
<P>
   One man asked the Texas governor in Spanish what Bush would do
to help Latino children. Bush translated for himself, slipping in a
joke first. ``What he said was, `You're doing a fabulous job,' ''
said Bush, laughing with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Bush then told the man that his message has been the same for
everyone _ personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman mentioned Georgia's new education bill, now before
the General Assembly, pointing out that it did not address safety
in schools. Bush referred to an incident in Michigan this week in
which a 6-year-old boy allegedly killed a classmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does a boy get a gun?'' Bush asked. A woman in the back of
the room shouted, ``Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said parents must take control of their children and be
responsible about guns.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
