u p BC-MCCAIN-REAGAN-NYT &LR;      03-01 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-REAGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ON THE AIR, McCAIN AND REAGAN'S SON CLASH OVER THE RELIGIOUS (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sen. John McCain refers to himself as a Reagan
Republican, but he is not afraid to get into a squabble with one.
Not even one whose last name is Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Michael Reagan's radio talk show,
McCain and the elder son of the former president got into an
argument Tuesday afternoon over accusations made against the
senator's campaign by the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter became so intense that it abruptly ended when
McCain's cellular phone began to break up and Reagan said, ``I
don't want to talk to him if he calls back.''
</P>
<P>
   In listening to the interview and reviewing a transcript, which
was circulated by the George W. Bush's campaign, it appeared that
it was Reagan who might have lost his cool because of McCain's
refusal to change subjects and answer his questions.
</P>
<P>
   What gave the exchange some drama was that it occurred at a time
when both McCain and Bush are staking claims to Ronald Reagan's
conservative legacy. Their efforts to co-opt the Reagan political
magic have thrust the younger Reagan, whose conservative talk show
is picked up by about 220 stations nationwide, into the role of
prominent namesake; last week he was a guest on the ABC program
``Nightline'' to discuss the invoking of his father in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan said in an interview Wednesday that he had remained
neutral in the race, which had been perceived by some as tacit
support of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But Reagan's neutrality dissolved after he asked McCain about
former Sen. Warren B. Rudman, R-N.H., his national campaign
co-chairman, who has been attacked by conservative groups allied
with Bush. The question Reagan posed, about Supreme Court justices
who might be appointed if Rudman is attorney general in a McCain
administration, was the same as one presented by right-to-life
groups in a South Carolina radio commercial attacking McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Several times in their talk, McCain said Rudman was ``a fine
man'' who had been attacked mercilessly by Pat Robertson, the
founder of the Christian Coalition. He challenged Reagan to reach
the same conclusion. ``It doesn't disturb you that Pat Robertson
would call up people and say that Warren Rudman is a vicious
bigot?'' McCain asked.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed, Reagan lost patience and declared after the call ended,
``He wants to talk about hate, and then he uses my father's name!''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Reagan was still steaming. ``For him to come on and
go off on me,'' he said. ``Of any conservative talk show in
America, I've been the most down the middle on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to McCain took pains to point out that Michael Reagan was
not regarded as a Reagan family spokesman. ``Mike doesn't like us,
he's a Falwell Republican, way out there,'' said Howard Opinsky,
McCain campaign press secretary, in a reference to the Rev. Jerry
Falwell, the founder of the Moral Majority.
</P>
<P>
   This further hurt Reagan's feelings. ``Is that a dirty word?''
he asked. ``You know about how many times I've talked to Jerry
Falwell in my life? I think twice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
