<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-RELIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID AGENCIES LEAVE SUDAN OVER DISPUTE WITH REBEL GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By IAN FISHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ Eleven of the biggest aid agencies working in
the continual crisis of war and hunger in southern Sudan have left
the region because of a dispute with the main rebel group over
their operations.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on a document that outlines an
``understanding'' between the agencies and the rebel group, the
Sudan People's Liberation Movement. The rebels had set a Wednesday
deadline for the forced removal of any aid group that did not sign
the paper. Over several days, more than 100 workers have left
programs intended to contribute $30 million this year to more than
1 million Sudanese. The agencies and other experts say ordinary
Sudanese will suffer _ in the long term, perhaps, die _ if they do
not return.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan, one of the poorest countries, has been locked in a
17-year north-south civil war. Famine killed 60,000 people in
southern Sudan in 1998, and the aid agencies provide health and
veterinary care, clean water, seeds and farming tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worried because we clearly see a gap there,'' said
Sharad Sapra, the southern-sector coordinator for Operation
Lifeline Sudan, an umbrella organization of aid groups organized by
the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebel officials minimized the effects, saying that the agencies
accomplished less than advertised and that the Sudanese had any
rate become too dependent on aid after 10 years of Operation
Lifeline Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not having it might help us in terms of self-reliance,'' said
Cmdr. Nhial Deng Nhial, the rebels' chairman for external
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Aid agencies are increasingly worried about neutrality and
independence, as groups like the Sudanese rebels contend that aid
organizations arrogantly do whatever they please, being richly paid
for ministering to the poor. In this case, 11 of the 35 agencies
that refused to sign the document included some of the biggest and
most influential, including CARE, Oxfam, Save the Children and
World Vision.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations say they did not sign because the pact could
give the rebels too much control over their operations. The
sticking point seemed to be a provision that would elevate the
``objectives'' of the rebels' ``humanitarian'' wing to the same
level as the principles that the aid agencies observe.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important to us is humanitarian principles,'' said
Philippe Guiton, director for the Sudan program for World Vision,
based in Los Angeles. ``If we think signing this document our
neutrality is at stake, we cannot sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, the aid officials said, they worried about
procedures for emergency evacuations, that the rebels would charge
high fees or taxes or that soldiers might compromise their
neutrality in ways such as demanding rides in relief vehicles. The
officials also said the rebels, accused of diverting aid food to
feed soldiers, would not include a clause to guarantee that aid
would help only civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel officials dismissed the objections, saying the real
problem is that big foreign aid groups do not want to be bound by
any rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else in the world, where on earth, do you move as you
wish, when you like and how you like?'' asked Elijah Malok Aleng,
executive director of the rebels' humanitarian wing, the Sudan
Relief and Rehabilitation Association.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels also noted that 24 of the 35 aid agencies had signed
the document, saying the 11 represented, perhaps, 30 percent of the
aid. The groups say the percentage is closer to 75.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
