<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-SIMS29-COX &LR;      03-01 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SIMS29-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    A splice of life
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ 4:30 in the afternoon, on the back patio of
Christopher Greta's house, and he's talking about the block parties
that Steiner Ranch residents sometimes have on the weekends. ``All
I have to do is tell my neighbors when,'' he says. A few phone
calls later, and dozens of families are participating. Margarita
machines are rented, hundreds of briquets are sacrificed in the
name of steak, and inflatable jump castles are brought in for the
42 children under the age of 11 who live in this far west Austin
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Greta house that holds Christopher, his wife Loree, daughter
Marlo, 8, and son Maxx, 7, bumps up against a small creek. While
Christopher sits on the patio furniture and drinks a glass of
water, the sounds of the creek mingle with the sounds of children
playing in the front yard. Basketball, tag and soccer are picked up
during a magical, summery time where winter should be carrying in a
discouraging cold wind, but isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Greta is talking about another game now, one called
The Sims, and the prospect that a reporter will rebuild his house
by computer, turn his family into digitally animated characters,
and roam them around a house to see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Greta, who as owner of Austin's Ad Ranch spends a lot of time
thinking about how ordinary people react to extraordinary images,
thinks it will be fun. ``What a great therapy,'' he says. ``Way too
often people get stuck in a routine and don't think about their own
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sims allows a player to create a family, put family members
into a self-designed or pre-built house and then run through the
minutiae of everyday life. There are dishes to be done, TV to be
watched, jobs to go to for money and virtual barbecues to organize.
While the concept sounds mind-bogglingly boring (who wants to take
out the trash, even just pretending?), the game is addictive,
thought-provoking and not just a little fun. It is to computer
games what ``Ulysses'' is to books. The mundane is elevated to art,
the question of what we do in a day is brought forth, and,
ultimately, we are left asking (as our mouse button twitches) what
is family, what is happiness and why does my Sim burn up the
kitchen when he tries to cook a souffle?
</P>
<P>
   The Sims is the cute brainchild of Will Wright, the creator of
SimCity, where instead of managing a family, you take control of an
entire city. Wright, who with SimCity took on the Herculean task of
making city management sexy, told the Austin American-Statesman
last year that he wanted to create an architectural simulation in
which you built a house and let virtual people run around in your
creation.
</P>
<P>
   In designing the game, however, Wright began to see that the
people inhabiting the homes were more interesting than their
surroundings. ``I was designing human behavior at an abstract
level,'' he said. ``That became so compelling, it became the game
play. ``
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who is chatty and friendly like Christopher Greta, said
he wanted to open our eyes to how we live our own lives through the
game, which incorporates lessons from psychology, sociology and
Feng Shui books in its mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I play (The Sims) a lot, I look at my house, my family,
my friends. People might play this and ask themselves if they're
really maximizing their happiness,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   A HOUSE FIT FOR A SIM
</P>
<P>
   Using photos of the Gretas taken at their home, the first step
in simulating their lives was creating likenesses for them. Using
their clothes as models, choosing somewhat similar faces from the
game's built-in choices and using their astrological signs to
create similar personalities, the family is created and thrust into
a neighborhood that is equal parts mansions and starter homes (This
is not quite reflective of the Steiner Ranch reality, but in The
Sims, there are homes for almost every budget).
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozing an existing house and building a new one from
scratch, we try to replicate as closely as possible the real Greta
home, from the red-brick exterior to the rear deck. Everything can
be chosen and applied manually, from the wallpaper to the kitchen
tile. Windows are put in place (should we use the frilly French
windows, the picture windows or the high privacy panes?) and a
second story is added to the house.
</P>
<P>
   A fireplace, staircase and hardwood patio later, and it's time
to go shopping. We cheat a little, using a code from the Internet
to bump up the measly $20,000 the game starts you off with to
surround the Gretas with the things to which they are accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   There's a dishwasher and large dining room table in the kitchen,
lots of bookshelves and toys in the kids' rooms and the best
toilets, bathtubs and beds that virtual money can buy. The house is
beginning to look like the Gretas' spacious, nicely furnished home.
</P>
<P>
   In the living room, a large console stereo sits next to a large
color TV. Couches tastefully complement wall patterns. A fountain
and a barbecue grill are on the deck, overlooking a creek that
babbles digital water. Upstairs, a dollhouse sits ironically in
Marlo's room, waiting to be played with.
</P>
<P>
   After all the work to build, all the shopping for just the right
light fixture for the guest bedroom, the adult Sim Gretas
ungratefully pull books off the bedroom shelves and sit reading,
ignoring all the riches we've surrounded them with. The kids are
impressed by the hedges, and then run off to meet the school bus,
which takes them away promptly at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   TRAGEDY AT SIM STEINER RANCH
</P>
<P>
   When you start playing The Sims, your characters are
undeveloped. They've got few, if any, skills. They are unemployed,
have only tenuous relationships with other members of the household
and their bladders always seem to be full, prompting constant
visits to the bathrooms, which you, as the player, must remember to
facilitate. Little by little, The Sim Gretas are expected to learn
to live and love. Soon after the game begins, Christopher and Loree
share a few cuddly moments, dancing in a hallway and flirting.
Loree cooks burgers for the family on the patio grill, and soon the
Sim Gretas are greeting an endless parade of curious neighbors who
want to greet the new Steiner Ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   The kids arrive home from school soon after. Maxx shoots hoops
on the family's basketball goal while Marlo goes upstairs to try
out her dollhouse for the first time. Using the upstairs computer
for a job search, Christopher secures an entry-level position as a
mailroom clerk, a far cry from his flesh-and-blood counterpart's
executive-level position. But in the Sim world, it's the best he
can do, starting out. Loree _ who helps run Ad Ranch in real life _
looks in the newspaper for a job, but can only find listings for
``petty criminal'' and ``sports mascot,'' also a far cry from the
somewhat better job market in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   After their first night in their new home, Loree and Christopher
are woken up at 2 a.m. by a phone call. Christopher rouses himself,
runs to the phone and answers. Nobody's there and the family has no
answering machine to field the call.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, a neighbor named Mortimer visits just as
Christopher arrives home from his first day at work. The visit is
short-lived, however. While cooking, Christopher starts a kitchen
fire that spreads, and eventually kills poor Mortimer, who bravely
stands by and screams ``Fire!'' before dying. The fire department
arrives, but not before the kitchen is gutted. The family learns a
valuable lesson: Soon after, a smoke alarm is installed in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   (A check on the real Gretas assures us that the kitchen, and
neighbors, are intact.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFE SETTLES INTO ROUTINE
</P>
<P>
   The excitement for the Sim Greta family isn't over. A burglar
finds his way into the home, but is promptly arrested when their
burglar alarm alerts police to the thief's presence, just like it
would happen in the real Greta's home. The kids come home with
their first report cards. Marlo scores A's while Maxx has to settle
for B+. This doesn't jive with reality: The real Maxx regularly
gets report cards with a teacher's effusive ``Wow!'' written on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher gets promoted out of the mailroom after improving
his mechanical and speaking skills. He's on track for a successful
business career. Loree continues to look for work online, but none
of the jobs seem to appeal. In the meantime, she manages the
household and socializes with new neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them aren't too desirable: Chip Snooty Patootie, a stock
character from the game, for instance, is a trust-fund brat who
teases the children, insults Loree and Christopher and doesn't seem
to get the hint when he's asked to leave. The real Gretas are glad
to report they don't have any such Snooty Patootie neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes relationships deteriorate: Christopher and Marlo argue
over a front-yard basketball game. But there is also a deepening of
commitments as the game moves forward: the possibilities stretching
out before the Sim Gretas include more children, house upgrades,
pool parties, career advancement and some quirky additions to the
game such as polygamy, floods and freak accidents like the one that
did in Mortimer.
</P>
<P>
   As in real life, life in the virtual Greta household is a mix of
free will and chance. Balancing hunger with energy with comfort and
a host of other variables, they fluctuate between fulfillment and
unhappiness. By steering them in the right direction _ cleaning up
life's little messes while sneaking in enough time for shooting
hoops and going to bed early _ time management becomes joy
management.
</P>
<P>
   When we leave the Sim Greta family, they all seem happy, if a
little hungry. That's quickly remedied by sending Christopher to
the kitchen to start preparing a family meal.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a happy life is hard work, and being unable to do it in
the game may be a bit of an indication that you may need to work on
your real life, Christopher says. ``If your little electronic
character is miserable _ hell, that's your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
