<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3769 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-SKY-CYCLE-FEATU     03-01 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SKY-CYCLE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKYCYCLE RIDES INDUSTRY ROLLER COASTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 5 or later.) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, things seemed like they were moving forward for
Skycycle, a North Hollywood rock quartet with a loyal following in
the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The group was recording its debut album, ``Ones and Zeros,'' for
industry giant MCA. The album, produced by the band, was full of
well-crafted pop songs by singer-guitarist Steve Isaacs, a former
MTV video jockey who also spent 16 months starring in the road
company of the Who's ``Tommy.''
</P>
<P>
   The disc was initially scheduled for release last August. The
label issued a single, ``Last Girl on Earth,'' which received some
airplay before Isaacs got the news that the album had first been
delayed, then pulled from the schedule and would likely come out
sometime in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christmas season was full of big label acts like Fiona
Apple and the Foo Fighters, so we went with the logic,'' Isaacs
said. ``There wasn't a lot we could do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The album languished on the shelf while Skycycle waited to hear
when it would finally hit stores. A little more than a month ago,
Isaacs got the call: Skycycle was dropped from MCA, but happily
free to take ``Ones and Zeros'' elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a rehearsal scheduled that day and everyone showed
up,'' Isaacs recalled. ``I thought everyone would quit then and
there. And I expected it to hit me in the pit of my stomach, but
the feeling never came. Instead, we all felt relief. A few years
ago, before the Internet, it would have been scary and extremely
disappointing. But this actually felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Skycycle _ named for the steam-powered rocket
Evel Knievel used in 1974 to attempt to jump the Snake River in
Idaho _ has a well-designed Web site (www.skycycleonline.com)
that's been attracting fans and newcomers for several years. During
the making of the album, in fact, the band posted a detailed
recording diary and kept fans apprised of developments concerning
MCA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ones and Zeros'' will soon be available for $13 through
Skycycle's site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more exciting to be captain of our own ship,''
Isaacs, 30, said Wednesday from his home near Universal City. ``I'd
much rather be captain of our own ship on the Internet than
swabbing MCA's decks. I have a fair amount of friends in the same
position.''
</P>
<P>
   With the many mergers and takeovers to hit the music industry in
recent years, Skycycle's story has a familiar ring. High profile
artists such as Aimee Mann and Michelle Shocked have sold their
albums through their Web sites, and it will probably be even more
common in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Web sites will be much more than merely promotional
tools,'' Isaacs predicted. ``I think they'll be the center of all
things. Look at it this way _ back in the old days, the Beatles and
Led Zeppelin would put out two records a year. A band not governed
by a marketing timetable is free to do as many as three records a
year if their fan base supports it.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs, a professional Web designer, believes the music industry
is being hurt by its own apparent resistance to the burgeoning new
medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very real threat to the industry,'' he said. ``I'm
not pretending to be a sage, but my instincts tell me the old
marketing model is going under. These giant entertainment monoliths
are way too top heavy to get anything done in a timely manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Skycycle has several local gigs coming up, including the Joint
in West Los Angeles on March 18, the Gig/Hollywood on March 23rd
and Dragonfly in Hollywood on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs, a native of the San Jose suburb Cupertino, was hosting
the open mic at the Highland Grounds in Hollywood in 1991 when an
MTV talent scout asked him to audition. He landed the job, moved to
New York and appeared on the music video channel from 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Nirvana hit, I was the only guy there who was also a
musician,'' Isaacs said. ``I had really long hair and got to talk
about all the bands I liked. But they axed me. I just wasn't much
of a team player and the honeymoon was over. See, the most
important thing for a VJ is to act like they really like the music.
When I'd introduce a Whitney Houston video, it was hard to fake
it.''
</P>
<P>
   After he lost the MTV gig, Isaacs remained in New York and
started a band. Soon, though, he was on the road as Tommy for 500
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got sick of it once,'' he said. ``There's a lot of
powerful music in that musical.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs formed Skycycle in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A.'s got a healthy music scene,'' he said. ``The town
suffered a slump after `95, and there's a big turnover of musicians
who come here to try and make it. And there's no real hometown feel
like there is in some smaller places. But it's still a great place
for bands.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
