<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3772 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WATER-AD-COLUMN-(TRIM     03-01 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-AD-COLUMN-(TRIMS)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PEPSI PICKS J. WALTER THOMPSON TO PITCH ITS BOTTLED
WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With bottled water _ no color, no flavor, no image to speak of _
turning out to be one of PepsiCo's star performers, growing far
faster than colas and other carbonated soft drinks, the company
plans to spend millions of dollars to promote its Aquafina brand in
the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling the next stage of the bottled water wars, Pepsi chose
the J. Walter Thompson agency, a part of the WPP Group, to develop
a campaign, expected to include television and print ads and a new
tag line, for Aquafina, which Pepsi began selling nationwide a
little more than two years ago. The size of the campaign, estimated
at $10 million and announced in December, shows how rapidly bottled
water has gained the respect of Pepsi executives and how big the
expectations are for Aquafina's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been in the lucky position of being the No. 1 water, we
are trying to lead the movement back toward branding and fewer,
bigger brands dominating the business,'' said Dawn Hudson, Pepsi's
senior vice president for strategy and marketing, noting that
marketing budgets for most water brands have been $2 million or
less, until now. ``It will go from being a commodity business to a
branded business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter of last year, sales of Aquafina rose 75
percent, compared with declining sales of Pepsi-Cola and a lower
double-digit growth rate for Mountain Dew. That was accomplished
with next to no marketing, compared with the millions spent on
advertising the soft-drink brands. In a conference call with
analysts last month, Roger A. Enrico, PepsiCo's chairman, said the
company wanted to increase supermarket sales, adding to its success
in vending machines and convenience stores, where people tend to
buy just a bottle at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just now in the process of getting the creative concepts
together,'' a Pepsi spokesman, Larry Jabbonsky, said of the ads,
which are expected to be on the air by summer _ prime water-selling
season. ``They will focus on Aquafina's purity and its
approachability, with a humorous edge.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   These won't be the first ads for Aquafina. Pepsi briefly
broadcast a television spot last year that showed a well-sculptured
runner, implicitly an imported-water drinker, who comes to an
untimely end against the side of a truck. Meanwhile, two ``regular
guys'' are shown drinking Aquafina. It was supposed to underscore
the generic appeal of the brand. The Aquafina tag line, ``Take me
to the water,'' is also likely to be replaced with something else,
Jabbonsky added.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Across the United States, which only recently embraced bottled
water as an alternative to soda, sales of the nonsparkling variety
have grown explosively, from 750 million gallons in 1997 to more
than 1.2 billion gallons last year. The annual growth rate over the
last five years has been about 30 percent. ``Even the very strong
1990s U.S. stock market performance pales in comparison,'' said
Michael Bellas, chief executive of Beverage Marketing, a consulting
firm that tracks beverage sales. He called bottled water in
containers of 1.5 liters or less ``the star category of not only
the bottled water industry, but also the entire beverage
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Water has been good for Pepsi. Aquafina is now the top-selling
brand in the small-bottle category, although it accounts for only
about 80 million cases a year, compared with about 1.4 billion for
Pepsi-Cola. The company makes money from each sale through
royalties paid by its bottlers. Using its existing distribution
network, Pepsi shipped Aquafina to the thousands of convenience
stores and gas stations where it already delivered other Pepsi
products, and its sales spiraled upward.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Coca-Cola noticed the trend, too, and put its own bottled water,
Dasani, on the market last spring. The structure is different,
however; Coke sells packets of mineral additives, which are added
to the water, to its bottlers. But like Pepsi, Coke gets most of
its raw material from municipal water sources, not any
fancy-sounding natural spring. Between their distribution systems
and their choice of sources, both Coke and Pepsi are likely to have
the biggest-selling national water brands within the next year or
so, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, consolidation and other changes are shaking up
the bottled water market. In January, Groupe Danone, which owns the
Evian and Dannon brands, announced it was buying the San
Francisco-based McKesson Water Products Co., makers of Sparkletts,
Alhambra and other brands, for $1.1 billion. Naya Inc., which has a
popular water that was distributed for years by Coca-Cola
Enterprises, the chief Coke bottler in the United States, declared
bankruptcy in December, although it continues to sell its product.
The company's problems were largely caused by a drop in sales that
came when it lost its Coca-Cola Enterprises distribution a few
months before Coke rolled out Dasani.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the top four or five companies are going to control
80 percent of the market,'' Bellas of Beverage Marketing said.
``It's changing now to the marketing wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said Pepsi's efforts would go beyond the ad campaign.
``It's not just about advertising,'' she said. ``It's presence
marketing, getting into more locations, having more types of
packages available, being part of more sports events.'' She called
water ``the ultimate thirst quencher'' and said Pepsi's goal was
``to sustain the momentum of the brand as the No. 1 brand.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994, when Pepsi put an initial toe into the market by
testing Aquafina in Wichita, Kan., it was considered a risky move.
After all, what's the point of offering consumers water if you can
get them to drink higher-margin Pepsi or Mountain Dew? And to make
matters worse, Pepsi practically bragged about the fact that
Aquafina came not from an exotic-sounding mountain spring but was
simply tap water, cleaned up in a bottling plant. Where was the
appeal?
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, American consumers by and large don't really care
about the source. And if bottlers don't have a Coke or Pepsi brand
to sell, they will find some other brand to meet the demand for
water. ``What Pepsi taught the industry was that coming from a
spring was not a requirement,'' said Jennifer Solomon, a beverage
analyst for Salomon Smith Barney. ``It was a big gamble, and it
paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear whether bottled water is capturing market share
that once belonged to sodas or whether it is displacing tap water
that people used to drink. Either way, ``Coke and Pepsi's entry
into this business is going to have a profound impact,'' said John
D. Sicher, editor of Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter. ``In
the years to come, a lot of the smaller regional spring waters will
have a more difficult time competing, even regionally, with the big
brands. The big ones will be marketed more heavily, and consumers
will demand them, and they will take up more and more shelf
space.''
</P>
<P>
   But there may be one niche market that the biggest players are
overlooking, said Scott Wilkins, a beverage analyst for Deutsche
Bank. ``If you buy into this health-conscious movement, which is
pretty well documented, there will be a market for nonpurified,
spring-based water that neither Coke nor Pepsi is addressing,'' he
said. ``Maybe the economics don't work for them to buy a source,
but Perrier and Danone are doing it all over the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
