<HEADER>
A3775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SOUTH-WATER-(TRIMS)-N     03-01 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-WATER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALABAMA, FLORIDA AND GEORGIA FIGHT CRUCIAL WATER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the Southeast, where rivers, swamps and marshes
abound and high humidity and heavy thunderstorms are not uncommon,
few ever thought that a lack of water would become a major problem.
But urban growth, particularly in Atlanta, and droughts in the last
two decades have precipitated a battle among three states that
experts call one of the biggest water wars in the United States in
the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But many see this week as the beginning of the end to the war as
the states either resolve the conflicts themselves or wind up in
court.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involves six rivers that have headwaters in Georgia
and then flow into Alabama or Florida. In 1997, the federal
government helped the three states form two commissions to work out
agreements on the management of the rivers. But those commissions
have not been able to agree, and now they face a deadline to do so
</P>
<P>
   David Feldman, a senior research scientist at the Energy,
Environment and Resources Center at the University of Tennessee,
described the problem, saying: ``In the Southeast, because of rapid
population growth and urbanization, especially in Atlanta, a lot of
these rivers are experiencing diverse and divergent demands. So the
same water that Atlanta has to use for its municipal water supply
is the water that upstream users need to support recreation and
flood control, and downstream users need to support agriculture,
urban growth and a very lucrative fishing industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The disputes center on two river basins. One is the ACF basin,
named for the first letters of the rivers it includes, the
Appalachicola, Chattahoochee and Flint rivers, which begins in
Georgia, runs along the Alabama border and ends up in the
Appalachicola Bay of Florida, in the Gulf of Mexico. The other is
the ACT basin and includes the Alabama, Coosa and Tallapoosa
rivers, which begins in Georgia, runs through Alabama and ends up
in Mobile Bay in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's main concern is to make sure it has enough water from
the two basins to sustain the growth it expects for Atlanta in the
next 30 to 50 years. The city has experienced explosive growth
since the 1950s. Georgia is also concerned with the effects of
limiting water consumption on its agricultural areas in the
southern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama is trying to ensure that it, too, will have adequate
water for growth in Birmingham and other areas, and it is trying to
protect its industrial and navigation water needs throughout the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is mainly concerned with protecting the northwestern
part of the state, the Appalachicola Bay area, which is an
important estuary, producing 90 percent of the state's oysters.
Water from the Chattahoochee and Flint rivers in Georgia merges to
form the Appalachicola River in Florida, which in turn supplies
important freshwater flow for oyster production in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The compact under which the three states are negotiating says
they must agree on a long-term water management plan, or allocation
formula, for the region. That formula must be signed by all three
governors. Then it will go before a federal commissioner. If that
official vetoes the formula, the states can renegotiate it or
decide to give up. In the latter case, or if the states do not come
up with an agreement at all, the disputes will probably go to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive for the states to forge their own agreement is
high, because they generally agree that their interests are at
greater risk if they have to abide by a court-ordered deal. But
their differences are stark enough that the negotiators on all
sides, who are in Atlanta for meetings of both commissions this
week, have expressed pessimism at their ability to resolve the
complex issues of these battles on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is somehow, through one of the most complex
situations I've ever seen,'' said Lindsay Thomas, the federal
commissioner who was appointed by President Clinton to oversee the
process, ``to provide for the needs of the three states without
destroying the ecology and environment of these river systems.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the two commissions held public meetings, with each
of the states' negotiators talking about their needs and proposals.
The day was supposed to be a preliminary deadline for the
commissions to come up with formulas the governors could sign. But
it was evident from the start that they were too far apart on the
issues to do that.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Tuesday's meetings, the commissions had scheduled
another series of meetings for this month. They have not yet
decided whether to extend once again their final May 1 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly, the sticking points center on Florida and Alabama
trying to get assurances from Georgia that it will not siphon off
too much water from the headwaters, thereby leaving the two
downstream states wanting.
</P>
<P>
   representatives of Georgia, which has been cast as a bully of
sorts by the other states and some environmental groups because of
its advantageous geographical position and the influence Atlanta
provides politically, maintain that their state is assuming the
most risk and so has to be the most careful.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kerr, Georgia's chief negotiator, said his state had to
make sure not to give away too much. ``If you're downstream,'' he
said, ``you can demand anything you want. But if you're upstream
and you're the one making the commitments to provide a certain
amount of water downstream, you have to be conservative. For us to
overcommit, just to make them feel good, would be foolish on our
part.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Feldman, the Tennessee scientist, said of the talks: ``Somebody
is going to have to blink, and make a compromise. Based on the
outcome of previous water wars, they will have to come to some
agreement, eventually, on the actual volumes of water that can be
withdrawn from the rivers. And then they will probably create some
sort of system to verify that. And it will most likely fall to an
independent tri-state authority to monitor the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
