<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY0229-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Staying in touch doesn't have to hurt your travel budget
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The question these days _ thanks to the way technology
has changed our lives _ isn't whether a person can go home again.
Instead it is whether a person can really leave home now.
</P>
<P>
   I spent a week away from work, out in the Pacific Northwest
where _ thankfully _ bears and steelhead trout outnumber computers.
Ten years ago, I really would have been out of touch. But (and I'm
not claiming this is a wonderful thing) it was very much like I
hadn't gone away.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when I traveled routinely, so I learned a lot
along the way about staying in touch. I'll leave the discussion of
the good and bad of that electronic tether for others, since there
isn't much we can do about that. The genie isn't just out of the
bottle, the bottle is shattered.
</P>
<P>
   So instead, we'll talk about practical ways of making it easier
and more affordable to stay connected. If you are a veteran
traveler, you probably know all this. But if you seldom venture far
from home, I may be able to help.
</P>
<P>
   The first item on the list is e-mail. While there are ways with
a national Internet service provider to set up a laptop or a
desktop computer to dial in to the local access number or a
toll-free number to get your mail, normally that isn't the easiest
solution, especially for someone who isn't an experienced computer
user.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't often travel, a free Web-based e-mail account
makes good sense for this purpose. You won't have to reconfigure a
computer to use it. Instead, you can use any computer, including
those you'd find at someone's home or a library or one of the many
retail establishments that charge an hourly fee to let you use the
computer. All you need to do is fire up that computer's Web
browser, go to the start page of the free service you use, and
enter your user name and password.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of these services, so I'll just name a few.
Check out free e-mail at Yahoo (www.yahoo.com), Microsoft
(www.msn.com) or AltaVista (www.altavista.com). If, like me and
several million others, you are an EarthLink customer, you can
check your mail from the Web (using your EarthLink user name and
password) at Www.springmail.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular phones are another way we keep in touch. Almost
everyone _ including a panhandler who stopped me on the street
recently asking for a quarter _ has one. You already know that your
cell phone almost certainly will work in another city. But you may
have a vague awareness that cellular companies tack on a roaming
charge for using your phone outside the home territory.
</P>
<P>
   I am a BellSouth Mobility customer. BellSouth no longer charges
a daily roaming fee (in the old days, the fee was about $1 a day).
But air-time charges are more expensive. I paid 59 cents a minute
for calls I placed in Portland, Ore. If I used the phone for
long-distance, that tacked on another 30 cents a minute. Frankly, I
didn't use the phone enough for the high charges to be a factor.
What did bother me, though, was that, because the cell phone has an
Atlanta number, people in Portland calling me had to pay
long-distance charges (and I was still liable for any per-minute
air-time charges). By the way, almost every cellular company _
including BellSouth Mobility, which offers the All-In-One Rate Plan
_ also has cellular agreements that charge the same rate for
long-distance and local calls.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't there long, so I didn't try to solve the problem. Had I
planned to stay, I might have looked into one of the cellular
telephone rental plans aimed at travelers.You can find out more
about them from In Touch USA at www.intouchusa.com or Cellhire at
www.cellhire.com. That way, I could have used a local number. On
the other hand, air-time charges (on top of a daily rental fee)
were actually higher than my roaming charges.
</P>
<P>
   Well, good luck on your trip. If you're like me, you'll be glad
to get home, where it's still possible to stay peacefully out of
touch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-28-00 1118EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
