<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DALLAS-SYMPHONY-ART-2     03-01 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-SYMPHONY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A TEXAS-SIZE AMBITION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Anne Midgette writes frequently about art, music and theater.  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tell a New Yorker that the symphony orchestra in Dallas is 100
years old, and the reaction will probably be surprise. The Dallas
Symphony Orchestra would like to change that.
</P>
<P>
   True, being 100 in Dallas is a little different from being 100
in, say, Philadelphia (where the orchestra is celebrating its
centennial this year as well). The Dallas Symphony's history has
followed a roller-coaster track of highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   The group that started in May 1900 as the Dallas Symphony Club
rose to see Antal Dorati and, briefly, Georg Solti as music
directors in the years after World War II. But it also had to
suspend operations during both world wars. It almost folded in the
1938-39 season, and in 1974-75, when Eugene Ormandy and the
Philadelphians were celebrating that orchestra's 75th anniversary,
the Dallas Symphony Orchestra was shut down for most of the season
because of a bankruptcy that nearly snuffed it out.
</P>
<P>
   But you get to reinvent yourself in America, and the Dallas
Symphony has forged a new identity as a healthy American orchestra.
In 1989, it opened the striking Meyerson Symphony Center, designed
by I.M. Pei. In 1994, it hired a young American music director,
Andrew Litton. In recent seasons the orchestra has visited Carnegie
Hall regularly, and this year it will make its second European
tour.
</P>
<P>
   It releases two to three CDs a year. Its composer's chair,
established in 1999, is filled by one of America's most successful
young composers, Lowell Liebermann. And the orchestra is aiming
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board has a mandate to get Dallas within America's
top-tier orchestras,'' Litton said. ``It's a long-term project. I
think it will take 10 years. And another five before the world
notices.''
</P>
<P>
   The $100 million question (that being the size of the endowment
the orchestra's president, Eugene Bonelli, hopes to raise in his
quest for international renown) is whether it is possible to buy a
tradition as something more than a good, solid, middle-of-the-road
American orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, Dallas has devoted considerable
resources to putting its cultural life on the national, even
international, map. The downtown Arts District, where the Meyerson
Center is located, did not exist 20 years ago. The symphony and the
Dallas Museum of Art had been housed in outdated buildings in a
complex known as Fair Park, a 15-minute drive from downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The vision and backing of a few community leaders helped create
the culture district out of whole cloth. The Dallas Museum of Art
opened its new Arts District premises in 1984; the Meyerson
followed in 1989. The Nasher Sculpture Park is to open in 2001, a
gift of the Dallas real estate magnate and sculpture collector Ray
Nasher.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Nasher and others dream of a new performing arts center
for the opera company, the last Fair Park holdout. All of this,
they hope, will gain the city a new cultural standing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the $82.5 million Meyerson Center _ which, if it had
been named for its lead backer, would be known as the Ross Perot
Center _ proves that with enough vision and money, you can indeed
elevate your status. Justly famous for its architecture, the hall
is also known for its sound. Its acoustical designer, Russell
Johnson, equipped the wood-lined auditorium with huge resonance
chambers, curtains that retract at the touch of a button and a
42-ton acoustic and lighting panel that looks like something out of
a science fiction fantasy as it rises and falls on wire cables over
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   From the audience's standpoint, the sound is impressive. But not
all the musicians agree. ``It can be a tricky hall to play in,''
the principal clarinetist, Gregory Raden, said. ``Onstage, you can
have trouble hearing each other.'' Orchestra players were quoted as
saying the same thing to Donal Henahan of The New York Times when
the hall opened.
</P>
<P>
   An important figure on the Meyerson's building committee was
Bonelli, a symphony board member for 15 years. In 1993 he switched
over to take charge of the orchestra's administration. As president
of the Dallas Symphony Association, Bonelli has gone out of his way
to stress his commitment to making the orchestra one of the best in
the country. Formerly a dean of the School of the Arts at Southern
Methodist University, Bonelli brings plenty of musical knowledge,
if not practical experience, to his task.
</P>
<P>
   But what will be most crucial to the endowment campaign is his
ability to raise money. Still profiting from the groundswell that
the Meyerson's opening created in the community, the Dallas
Symphony has a lot more backing than it did in, say, 1974, when it
went bankrupt during a period of local economic prosperity. Then,
businesses chipped in a mere $28,000, a pittance even in 1974
dollars. Now Texas Instruments alone has pledged to help underwrite
the orchestra's regular classical series for the next three years,
to the tune of $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Local businesses have also contributed to the recent redesign of
the Web site dallassymphony.-com. Four of them have worked with the
orchestra to create a technologically up-to-date site equipped with
such bells and whistles as live 32-bit Webcasts of concerts,
e-commerce and, come June, fully automated ticketing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag over three years: more than $10 million. Even
taking into account that this figure includes in-kind services from
the companies involved, it's a whopping sum that occasions envious
glances from other American orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another place the Dallas Symphony spends money is on recording.
Its label, Delos, stresses the importance of a two-way
relationship. What this means in practice is that the orchestra
itself covers the musicians' fees for recordings. Delos pays the
costs of preproduction, bringing in equipment, and marketing and
distribution. In these tight times for classical recording, there
is a feeling in the industry that orchestras will, more and more,
be going Dallas' route and assuming part of their own recording
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Symphony will also need to spend money to attract the
top-flight players necessary to achieve its high-flown goals, and
to add at least 10 to its current roster of 92. But however much it
spends, it may not be able to compete with all the cultural
advantages of the Northeast or the tradition of an orchestra like
Philadelphia's, which has lured away both the concertmaster, David
Kim (who spent the 1998-99 season in Dallas), and the principal
trumpeter, David Bilger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have an impact on the history of music,'' Kim said.
``I don't think I can do that in a Dallas or a Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   It is going to take a lot more money to change that. It also
means that an improvement in musical standards that began in 1977
under the previous music director, Eduardo Mata, and that has
continued since 1994 under Litton will have to be pushed further.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orchestra's level of technical expertise wouldn't need
apology in any city in the world,'' said Scott Cantrell, the new
music critic of The Dallas Morning News, which sponsors the
orchestra's main concert series. ``Whether Litton is one of the
profound and compelling interpreters of today is another
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Litton said he felt a ``closed'' quality about the orchestra
under his predecessor. Opening it up and helping it move toward a
more individual, freer playing style is a big part of his
self-assigned task. The repertory Litton favors tends toward big,
splashy works like Walton's ``Belshazzar's Feast'' or the Mahler
symphonies. Not much Haydn or Mozart appears on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players, there is a consensus that Litton's energy and
drive have led to more touring, more recordings, more exposure. But
he has proved an uneven interpreter. His energy, expressed in
Bernsteinian flourishes onstage, can be compelling, but it can also
spill over into coarseness. His tempos are audibly idiosyncratic.
He also has a predilection for the loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brass pushed to the very edge of vulgarity, and then,
just, drew back,'' a critic from The Times of London wrote of a
1997 performance of Tchaikovsky's Fifth Symphony at the Royal
Albert Hall. ``It seemed an emblem of the entire performance.
Litton would dare extremes of tempo and dynamics which, in other
hands, could well curdle into sentiment or flash into mere
histrionics. Yet he pulled it off.''
</P>
<P>
   This description of a kind of tightrope act, of snatching a
decent performance from the jaws of something far less classy,
could apply to a number of Litton's live and recorded performances.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from reviews, the orchestra can make a good first
impression, which it may not sustain on longer acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artistically, we're in a holding pattern,'' said Gregory
Hustis, the principal horn player. Audiences may feel the same way.
The last five or six seasons under Mata, and the first seasons
under Litton, were completely sold out. But attendance has declined
slightly over the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Litton seems unconcerned. His contract runs until 2003, and he
is clearly content with his position. ``You can tell when things
are right,'' he said. ``Why leave when we're on the up curve?''
</P>
<P>
   However harrowing the history, there can be little question from
the present perspective that the Dallas Symphony is a success
story. ``When I first came, we played background music while people
stood in line to get swine-flu shots at the North Park Mall,'' said
Hustis, a 24-year veteran. ``The musician's lot in the Dallas
Symphony is incomparable, it's so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   And some players see nothing wrong with embracing this new
status as an eminently respectable second-tier American orchestra
and leaving it at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For who we are and what we are, we do a pretty good job,''
said the flutist Harvey Boatright, who has played with the Dallas
Symphony for 40 years. ``If it makes some people happy to think
that we're shooting for the top, well, fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
