<HEADER>
A3782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS0229-CO     03-01 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS0229-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    If a program won't open, try the logical approach
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It occurred to me, while trying to help a gentleman
whose program wouldn't run, that the logician's art _ or is it
science? _ can often be used to solve a software-related problem.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume that one day your favorite program refuses to run,
returning instead an error message that reports it cannot find
wumpus.dll. Immediately we must determine whether this is the first
time you've run the program since installing it or if it has been
running properly up to this point.
</P>
<P>
   If the latter, then we can assume that wumpus.dll previously
could be found but now cannot. For the sake of abbreviating this
enterprise, we will instead operate on the former premise, that you
have just installed the program.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to determine if wumpus.dll in fact exists on
the computer. To help us with this, we could go to the Start menu
and use Find. Instead, we'll call up Windows Explorer, pull down
the Tools menu, and select Find and then Files or Folders. Enter
wumpus.dll and make certain the dialog box is set to search the
entire hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   If the search comes up with wumpus.dll, then obviously it is
misplaced. If the search does not find it, then it must exist
elsewhere, the only other logical place being, of course, the
CD-ROM from which you installed the program. Oh yes, it can happen.
An installation program can, for whatever reason, fail to install a
necessary file.
</P>
<P>
   If the file is not found on the hard drive, you have two
options. You can reinstall the program, or you can look for
wumpus.dll and try to install it manually. We'll examine the second
option, since the first needs no further explanation and, having
failed once, may fail again.
</P>
<P>
   Insert the CD-ROM in the drive and, once again using the Find
tool in Windows Explorer, search the entire disk for wumpus.dll. If
this fails, search one more time, but this time just for wumpus.
Sometimes programs on an installation disk have a letter clipped
off, and it might be something like wumpus.dl.
</P>
<P>
   If the search still comes up empty, and if reinstallation did no
good, then in the words of a great logician of the past, you are
out of luck and had better look up the number for tech support.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you find wumpus.dll, then it remains for you to
determine where, on the hard drive, your program expects to find
it. Occasionally the error message itself will provide a complete
path name. Otherwise, there are two main options _ somewhere in the
program's own directory or in the Windows directory. Try Find once
again, this time searching the entire hard drive for just the
suffix, using a wild card, like this: .dll.
</P>
<P>
   This will turn up every dll file on your system, and you'll find
a huge nest of them in C:(backslash)windows(backslash)system. Try
copying wumpus.dll there and see what happens. If it's a
proprietary extension, you'll probably find others in the program
directory or a subdirectory thereof. Try putting it there.
</P>
<P>
   More often that not, in my experience, this sort of logic will
get you up and running.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-28-00 1117EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
