<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-GARRY-SHANDLING-     03-01 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GARRY-SHANDLING-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT PLANET IS HE FROM?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: For use Friday, March 5 or later.) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garry Shandling has enjoyed a pretty good run making light of
his so-called inadequacies _ his hair, his lips, his bad luck with
women. It's an act that's so finely honed that it's difficult to
know where the persona ends and Shandling begins.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, before this interview began, Shandling asks what
his current co-star John Goodman had to say about him.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTER: He said all he had to do was look at you and he'd
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   SHANDLING: I'm insulted by that.
</P>
<P>
   Shandling maintains that he never intends to be funny. So when
people laugh at him, his feelings are hurt. Having said that, he
spends the next hour attempting to be as funny as possible, reeling
off self-deprecating one-liners and unprintable jokes with gleeful
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Shandling clearly has never lost his love for stand-up comedy;
in fact, he says he's anxious to return to the stage and ``see
where I'm at.'' How he'll find the time isn't exactly clear. He
finished the celebrated ``The Larry Sanders Show'' for HBO last
year, but he's looking to return to television with a series he's
developing. (He would not star.) He also has a movie that he'd
write and direct, and likewise expresses an interest to continue
acting in films.
</P>
<P>
   His current movie _ ``What Planet Are Your From?'' _ marks
Shandling's first attempt at carrying a feature film. He plays an
alien sent to earth to impregnate a woman, thus giving his people a
foothold on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The film's alien motif affords it plenty of opportunity to
comment on the Mars-Venus differences between men and women. But at
its core, Shandling (who co-wrote the movie) is still playing an
extension of his bemused persona, albeit one without genitalia.
(More on that later.)
</P>
<P>
   Here, Shandling discusses why he finds women so baffling, how
his love scenes with co-star (and friend) Annette Bening helped
Warren Beatty, and the possibility of a Garry Shandling self-help
video series coming to stores in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``What Planet Are You From?'' suggests that men and women
will never understand each other.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, that starts almost from the moment we're born. Whatever
training I received as a boy was very limited. I saw sex education
films, but there was no talk from the parents, no sisters in the
house. So I just figured you had to be cool, like the guys in the
movies, guys who always had some great come-on line.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you ever come up with a line?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not one that worked. One time, I approached a woman at a bar
and she said, ``Don't even bother.'' And I said, ``Is that an
Indian name?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: And things have never improved?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's always been a struggle, just like in the movie. As a
kid, you see your parents and you think, ``Is this what it's
supposed to be like? Am I supposed to stare at the TV all the time
Mom is talking?'' Because that's what my Dad did. So when I did and
the girl got mad, I was confused.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This movie, then, is somewhat an educational film.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's my gift to men and women everywhere. It's what I do. I
help others emotionally. Now I just need to come out with a Garry
Shandling self-help videotape series to really spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The film gets a lot of mileage from the alien's implanted
genitalia, which gives off a rather distinct humming noise when
aroused.
</P>
<P>
   A: I can no longer have a protein shake without getting turned
on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I think that's an important fact for people to know.
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughs) Well, in these alien movies, there's always one
discerning factor that allows us to tell that someone is the alien.
And I thought, ``What's never been done?'' The humming penis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Judging from all the humming in the movie, you must have
liked the idea.
</P>
<P>
   A: At first I thought it was too broad a concept, but it just
kind of hung in there, so to speak. After every draft, I'd say,
``Do we want to take out the humming penis?'' Sometimes I'd be
asking this question on the telephone, and I'd get a lot of strange
looks from people in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The movie also has a surprise _ a Garry Shandling nude scene.
Were you anxious about disrobing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Anxious is not the word! ... . I had never done a nude scene
before, and I had received many requests from the ``Larry Sanders''
fans to see more. So I said, ``OK, I'll be naked from the back just
to please people.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You are a giver.
</P>
<P>
   A: My (butt) is a giver. But getting back to the humming penis
... .
</P>
<P>
   Q: I thought we had pretty much covered that subject ... .
</P>
<P>
   A: What I wanted to say was, wouldn't it be great if women had
something where we could tell if they were interested? A little
beeping sound, maybe. I wish they would have those flashers like
those airport guys on the runway that say, ``Go ahead. You're
clear!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've never read any of those body language books?
</P>
<P>
   A: What do they know? I've never known if a woman is interested.
I've even had the experience where after I've made love to them,
I've thought, ``Oh, I made a mistake. They weren't interested.''
And that's way too late to realize that. You've already embarrassed
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since you're good friends with your co-star Annette Bening
and her husband, Warren Beatty, were you a little uncomfortable
filming a love scene with Annette?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just the opposite. I told her we should start practicing the
love scenes years before we shot the movie. She said, ``OK,'' but
Warren wasn't too happy about that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But then she actually became pregnant while you were shooting
the film.
</P>
<P>
   A: Warren thanked me for that. He said Annette would return from
those scenes she did with me very turned on and ready to go. It
made it easier for him. The energy generated by the movie's sexual
encounter was enough to put them over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You and Annette had sexual tension?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have sexual tension with myself, with all women friends and
with all people who interview me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Switching gears then to another kind of tension, was it a
relief to finally make this movie after being embroiled in lawsuits
with your former manager, Brad Grey?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was a relief. But I have a great ability to
compartmentalize my life. The lawsuit started during the last
season of ``The Larry Sanders Show,'' which was the best season of
``The Larry Sanders Show,'' ironically. So it didn't affect the
work. I dropped the lawsuits the moment I showed up on the set.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you miss the show?
</P>
<P>
   A: I miss the show when I bump into someone who was never on the
show and I think, ``Gee, they would have been great.'' Or I have
some ``Hollywood'' experience that would have fit right into the
show. I miss the cast. But I don't miss the grind at all. This is
as relaxed as I've been in 12 years and I like that. But things
will start humming again pretty soon, I'm sure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Humming?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bustling, thriving ... things will be in full swing. (Pause)
Can we just stop now? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
