<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-GAMER29-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Climb into the cockpit of Colin McRae Rally
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   'Tis must be the season for driving games because another one
has hit the shelves and will keep you blazing for weeks. Sony's
Colin McRae Rally ($50; www.playstation.com) is a hyper-realistic
rally game. If nothing else, this shows how much of a pain it must
be to be a rally racer. Besides choosing a car, you can also adjust
tires, gears, engines ... just about anything and everything that
will affect your racing. With Colin McRae Rally, you also have the
opportunity to race in all types of settings and on all types of
surfaces and you must adjust the car for each terrain. This serves
the serious gamer well, but sets a fairly steep learning curve for
the non-pro. While we'd like to recommend this to everyone, this
game better suits the gearhead.
</P>
<P>
   Say Soul Fighter in your best Sean Connery accent. Say it again
like you mean it, like you're angry. There you go. That's the
coolest part of this Red Orb ($40; Dreamcast; www.redorb.com) game
for the Dreamcast, a free-range, 3-D fantasy adventure/fighter with
befuddling swooping/panning camera work that ruins otherwise solid
game play. Splendid graphics show off the power of the Sega's new
superconsole and brilliant animation shows the depth and variety
gleaned from Red Orb's epic warrior arsenal. Alas, it's not so cool
when the cinematography lurches about in an effort to afford you a
better view of the fireballs being hurled you way or the sword
that's poised to prick your buff behind; it only manages to stymie
the fluid grace of an otherwise grand-scope 3-D fighter.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP:
</P>
<P>
   Who wants Regis Philbin sitting in their computer monitor?
Apparently, a lot of people, judging from the brisk sales of Disney
Interactive's Who Wants to be a Millionaire ($20; Windows PCs;
www.disneyinteractive.com). When we installed the game here, half
the Technopolis staffers stopped what they were doing to wait in
line for a chance to play the game. With work from the developers
of You Don't Know Jack, the game has a similar feel to that quiz
show, but its clear intent is to replicate the TV show as closely
as possible. You've got lifelines, all the music from the show, and
most importantly, Regis. He mercilessly taunts you when you do
badly and pounces on you with ``Is that your final answer?'' when
you hesitate. The game plays well, but has a bad habit of asking
the same questions you've answered in previous games. It also would
have been nice to have Regis read the questions out loud. An online
component to the show's popular Web site will soon allow users to
play along live on the Internet with the same questions that appear
on the show. Until that goes live, however, this CD-ROM should
satisfy any would-be millionaire's trivia craving.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
