 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Plenty of sites devoted to all things Macintosh
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you own a Macintosh, it sometimes feels that the
world is stacked against you. Although things are better than they
once were, many programs only come in versions for Windows and PCs,
and the lion's share of computer magazines are oriented toward the
PC.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same on the Web. While most of the computer information
there addresses the problems of the majority of American users who
run Windows, some excellent sites specialize in Macintosh
information.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious starting point on our Big Mac hunt is Apple
Computer's own site at www.apple.com. Because most Macintosh users
are passionate about the brand, you probably won't mind the
promotional nature of much of the information on the site. But
there's much more here than hype.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find tabs at the top of the opening page that can take
you to areas for customer support, the company store and _ among
other things _ a way to download the latest version of QuickTime
(used by both Macs and PCs to view video and images). Also, take
some time to click on the tab called iReview to get some excellent
recommendations on Web sites for news, travel, music, sports and _
of course _ the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a Mac addict, then a no-brainer choice is to drop in
over at MacAddict.com (macaddict.com). You'll find all the news and
reviews that the most dedicated Apple-ite could want. Also, you'll
get general industry news. For instance, last week there were
stories about computer hackers, Y2K and the Microsoft antitrust
settlement hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Tabs also will take you to the top Macintosh sites on the Net,
as well as to an area that will attempt to help you with any
problems you're having with the Mac or software for it. Make sure
you try out the tab labeled Fun, because that's where you'll hear
about the latest games for the Mac as well as find some freeware
and shareware games and fun programs for downloading. Also, if
you're into music files on MP3, you'll find some here, as well as
software for playing them.
</P>
<P>
   Another site worth visiting is called the Mac Observer at
www.macobserver.com/. This is a serious site for people who really
are obsessive about everything Apple. The Observer is fun to read.
For instance, a recent article talked about Apple's fiscal
first-quarter earnings failing to meet analysts' estimates. Then,
beneath that article, there was something labeled ``The Mac
Observer Spin'' discussing the wisdom of the Gulfstream V jet used
by Steve Jobs, taking a mild jab at Jobs and pointing out that
``this sort of thing is actually important to Wall Street types.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the handiest features for news junkies is the listing of
clickable links to various news stories about Apple and the
Macintosh. Because newspapers and even computer magazines
ordinarily don't offer great depth of Macintosh coverage, you'll be
able to supplement that diet with richer fare here.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you will want to take a look at Inside Mac Games. Most
computer users, including Mac fanatics, like games, and this site
offers advance views of some of the most popular ones. While you
can find dozens of Web sites that offer game reviews, this site
does an excellent job of providing the Macintosh perspective.
</P>
<P>
   You can do more than just read game reviews, too. Inside Mac
Games offers you the chance to download demo versions of some of
the popular games. While these demos won't be enough for a serious
game player, they do provide a way to check out how a game works so
that _ before you drop $50 to $70 on a new game _ you can find out
if you'll enjoy playing it.
</P>
<P>
   Hints also aid the game-impaired by helping solve some of the
problems that stop beginning gamers and may be informative enough
to let a grown-up compete successfully with a child.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-28-00 1117EST &QL;
</P>
