<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS WIN POINT IN LOUIMA CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The federal judge in the trial of three police
officers accused of a cover-up in the assault on Abner Louima
instructed the jurors Wednesday that they could convict the
defendants even if they were unconvinced that the officer they
supposedly tried to protect took part in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The jury charge, by Judge Eugene H. Nickerson, was a victory for
federal prosecutors because it allows the jury to find the three
officers _ Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese _ guilty
of conspiring to cover up Schwarz's role in the attack even if they
think that Schware innocent, as he asserts. Schwarz was
convicted of assaulting Louima last June.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset of the trial in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn,
the government has argued that Schwarz restrained Louima as he was
tortured and then, in a blizzard of telephone calls, forged a pact
with Bruder and Wiese to craft a false story to get himself off the
hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``In determining whether one or more of the defendants are
guilty of conspiring to obstruct justice,'' Nickerson told the
jury, ``you need not determine the extent of any role the defendant
Schwarz may have played in the sexual assault.'' The judge also
counseled the jury that any evidence suggesting that Schwarz was
inside the bathroom of the 70th Precinct station house in Flatbush
as Louima was attacked was not, in itself, enough to convict the
three men of hatching a cover-up plot.
</P>
<P>
   Although Schwarz was found guilty last year of pinning Louima to
the floor while another officer, Justin Volpe, thrust a broken
broomstick into Louima's rectum, the question of Schwarz's role in
the attack was one of the focal points of the current trial.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution presented several witnesses, including Louima,
who suggested that Schwarz was in the bathroom on the night of the
assault, Aug. 9, 1997. The defense put on a case _ based on the
testimony of both Schwarz and Volpe _ that rested on the
supposition that the defendants were telling the truth when they
said Schwarz was not in the bathroom, and that therefore there
could not have been a conspiracy to lie on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the three defendants have said that the jury charge
was unfair and that, by supporting it, the government had changed
its trial strategy midstream.
</P>
<P>
   Permitting the jury to convict ``despite the absence of proof of
at least Schwarz's presence in the bathroom,'' Schwarz's lawyer,
Ronald Fischetti, wrote to the judge, ``would not only permit the
government to constructively amend its theory of the case but would
cause undue confusion among the jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having seen and heard the battle lines drawn over whether or
not Schwarz was in the bathroom _ through the testimony of Abner
Louima, Eric Turetzky, Mark Schofield, Justin Volpe and Charles
Schwarz,'' the letter continued, ``being told that Schwarz need not
have played any role in the assault would be difficult to
comprehend.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Vinegrad, the chief prosecutor in the case, said at a
conference with the judge last week that a conspiracy to obstruct
justice could exist even if the underlying crime _ namely Schwarz's
part in the attack _ never happened. He added that the wording of
the judge's instruction was ``simply the law.''
</P>
<P>
   After being charged, the jury was sent out at about 10:30 a.m.
Three hours later, they asked to be read the testimony of Sgt.
William Hargrove, a former Internal Affairs investigator who
conducted the first interview of Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove testified that, during that bedside interview in Coney
Island Hospital, Louima said he was never paraded through the 70th
Precinct station house with his pants and underwear around his
knees, but had them pulled down only after he was in the bathroom.
In later statements and at trial, Louima said his pants fell at the
front desk and he was led to the bathroom with his buttocks and
genitals exposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
