<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CITY-REVIEW-SFC     03-01 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CITY-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOROW LOSES HIS FAITH IN `CITY OF GOD' 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KIPEN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beware novels about writers searching for their next subject. A
recent example was Kurt Vonnegut's ``Timequake,'' which drew the
kind of discreet, forgiving notices no self-respecting novelist can
bear. The newest entry in this category is ``City of God,'' but
thanks to E.L. Doctorow's well-worn vernacular charm, it's nowhere
near the debacle it could have been.
</P>
<P>
   To summarize the new Doctorow requires less an effort of
compression than one of collation, because ``City of God'' is
several alternating stories in one. The main strand concerns a
minister nicknamed Pem, whose faltering faith finally snaps when
mysterious vandals steal the large brass cross off the altar of his
impoverished lower Manhattan church. The cross then miraculously
reappears atop an ultra-Reform synagogue on the Upper West Side _
whose demure female rabbi flusters Pem even more.
</P>
<P>
   Like a slightly punchy gin rummy dealer, Doctorow shuffles the
principal narrative of Pem's spiritual crisis into and out of
miscellaneous other hands. Some of these hands come up winners,
some don't. The worrisome one's about Everett, the novelist looking
to transubstantiate Pem's story into a book, while others delve
into cosmology, the two world wars, the movies, Tin Pan Alley,
Einstein, Wittgenstein, even Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a mess, a farrago of 20th century oddments from a
gifted writer who's looking over his shoulder at Don DeLillo's
``Underworld.'' Worse yet, it sounds like a frustratingly
un-Doctorovian mess.
</P>
<P>
   Here, we might have thought, stood America's least postmodern
novelist. Doctorow has always felt most at home in the past,
writing almost exclusively historical novels long before their
current vogue. In 1975, ``Ragtime'' combined storytelling ambition
with outlandish popular success to a degree arguably never equaled
in American fiction. It would be easy to see him bobbing and
weaving here in ``City of God,'' ducking and feinting and winking,
and think, alas, another great yarn-spinner lost to the crack
cocaine of self-referentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, this depressing scenario ignores a couple of things.
First, for all its longevity on the best-seller list, ``Ragtime's''
syncopated style and cinematic crosscutting were never anybody's
idea of an unchallenging read. Doctorow wasn't a character in the
book, as he is here in the character of Everett, but he wasn't an
absentee landlord, either. He's always been a radical innovator,
just one who created plots that worked and characters we wept for.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Doctorow's diminished reliance on story this time around
parallels perfectly his theme: the challenge of faith in a dark
time. Pem falls away from God in precisely the same way that
Doctorow falls away from storytelling, his old rock and redeemer.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, though, where ``Ragtime's'' multiple plots
compounded the suspense, ``City of God'' has only one plot, and
some of Doctorow's digressions damp down the momentum instead of
ratcheting it up.
</P>
<P>
   Sophisticated readers who still prefer a little melodrama with
their metaphysics may feel crossed up by ``City of God,'' but those
who stick it out may find themselves unexpectedly moved. The book
starts out slow but gathers a formidable head of steam. Unlike so
many current books that end feebly or not at all, ``City of God''
gathers a reassuring gravity near the end that few readers of its
scattershot opening sections would have foreseen.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, underneath all the multiple-character
ventriloquism, the Doctorow style _ skeptical, funny, politically
engaged, New York public-school Jewish down to the last serif _
shines through undiffracted. Compressed, it can be found in his
single-word description of ``barnthwacked'' swallows twitching in a
farm field after a storm. More loosely, it's in this paragraph on
the glum phenomenon only recently diagnosed by pop psychologists as
``Sunday blues'':
</P>
<P>
   ``All New York is out this afternoon. We stroll around, watch
some softball, find a grassy spot for ourselves, unwrap the deli
heroes, uncork the Snapples, and prepare to have one of those
balmy, ritually relaxing Sundays when the sense of loss is in every
heart and a nonspecific melancholy seems to permeate the air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``City of God'' is a harder novel than ``The Book of Daniel'' or
``Ragtime'' without being a better one. Many, not least the
Doctorow faithful, will find it uncongenial in its reluctance to
please. But it artfully shows the 20th century's two much-mourned
and greatly exaggerated deaths _ the novel and God _ as two aspects
of the same fall from transcendence. More important, it dares to
imagine their resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
