<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-PRIVACY-     03-01 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-PRIVACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH WEB SITES MAY BE TRADING DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By KAREN HSU   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the most popular consumer sites on the Internet that
dispense medical information may be exchanging personal data about
users who visit there, in possible violation of antitrust laws,
consumer and government officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The sites, which often rely heavily on surveys visitors are
asked to fill out online, gather a wealth of information on the
health, medical history, prescription drug use, and other personal
information. Most of that information is given up voluntarily by
visitors to the site, but some of it is not, and few users realize
that the information could be traded or sold to other Internet
health-care sites.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent studies have confirmed that personal data is
being captured and exchanged with other companies, and the Federal
Trade Commission is reportedly investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Richard M. Smith, a noted Internet security specialist, said he
nearly fell out of his chair when he found out a medical Web site,
PersonalMD.com, had given his ZIP code to an advertiser on the site
without his permission or knowledge. He wouldn't have realized it
had he not known how to check the background coding instructions
for the Web page. An internal program apparently knew who to access
the information off Smith's computer and send it to the advertiser,
Doubleclick.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually sites are more subtle about what they send out,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of various Web sites has exploded, including
17,000 health-oriented sites that sell products and conduct
interactive health surveys, the whole area of privacy has not kept
pace, Smith said. Some sites include services such as keeping
entire medical records online or sending medication reminders.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and others worked on a report commissioned by the
California Health Care Foundation that was released a month ago.
The report focused on privacy with 21 of the most popular health
Web sites, and found that many of them violated their own privacy
policies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Web sites highlighted in the report was OnHealth
Network Co, which offered a survey called a Personal Health
Assessment. But what OnHealth didn't inform users was that an
outside vendor called WellMed collected the information for the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``OnHealth intentionally tried to hide the role of WellMed in
all this. So you are typing in all this data, which is immediately
going off to another company that you don't have a relationship
with,'' Smith said. After the report came out, the Personal Health
Assessment survey was discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   To add confusion last week, OnHealth was bought by
Healtheon/WebMD Corp., another Internet health-care company. A
spokeswoman for WebMD said that the OnHealth Web site will
eventually merge into WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know who owns the data anymore,'' said Zoe Hudson,
senior policy analyst at Georgetown University's Health Privacy
Project who was a co-author of the report. ``You thought you gave
the information to OnHealth, but now it's changing hands. This
merger may not concern the consumer, but it might matter if one of
those sites joined forces with their insurance company.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said that because health sites ask for more detailed
information than many other sites, she expected that the privacy
protection would be better. ``We were all surprised at the amount
that was leaving the site,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   According to another study of 1,009 US adults by the California
Health Care Foundation in January, it found 75 percent of them
concerned about health Web sites sharing information without their
permission. Some sites currently collect information such as Social
Security numbers, credit card numbers, lab results and insurance
information.
</P>
<P>
   Since the report come out, a few companies, including
HealthCentral.com and iVillage.com, have said that the FTC has
inquired about their privacy practices. In addition, industry and
government leaders have met to work on privacy Internet issues. In
1996, a coalition of ethicists, physicians and online providers
formed the Internet Healthcare Coalition, which recently endorsed a
draft of an International e-Health Code of Ethics. Another group of
for-profit health providers have also formed a group called
Hi-Ethics Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of both groups and Smith were in Washington last
Friday to testify before a Congressional subcomittee on privacy and
confidentiality about health Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that in the spring, we will be seeing a lot more
activity in self-regulation with privacy,'' said John Mack,
president of the Internet Healthcare Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privacy is a big issue for us. If we lose consumers' trust,
then we have lost the site,'' said Laura Hicks, a spokeswoman for
drkoop.com, which was profiled in Smith's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of unexpected that we are being monitored and
watched in this way. We think it's like a newspaper or a magazine,
but it's much more invasive,'' said Smith, who warns that it is
possible to put together a profile of a user from all the
information gathered by different companies.
</P>
<P>
   Since the report, some e-health companies are already changing
or clarifying their policies. For example, drkoop.com said that it
has rewritten the privacy policy so it is more consumer-friendly.
It has added information, such as how servers keep logs of sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-28-00 2018EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
