<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3806 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHANGHAI-SYMPHONY-ART     03-01 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHANGHAI-SYMPHONY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE)  
 AN ORCHESTRA WITH A POLITICAL ACCOMPANIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5)  
 (af)  
 Sheila Melvin is a freelance writer based in Shanghai. Jindong Cai
is the music director of the orchestra and opera theater at the
University of Arizona and a regular guest conductor of the Shanghai
Symphony.  
 By SHEILA MELVIN and JINDONG CAI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ In March 1927, Tan Shuzhen, 20, a Chinese
violinist, entered the rehearsal hall of the Shanghai Municipal
Orchestra and approached its Italian conductor, Mario Paci. The
orchestra was preparing for a concert to be held on March 26, the
100th anniversary of Beethoven's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orchestra was all foreigners,'' Tan said recently. ``The
rule was, they played in Shanghai for five years and then got one
year paid furlough. I knew they were missing a violinist, so I
asked if I could play.''
</P>
<P>
   This was no ordinary request: since the orchestra's founding in
1879 as the Shanghai Municipal Public Band, no Chinese musician had
ever joined its ranks. The orchestra was created by and for the
foreign residents of Shanghai who had lived in self-governing
concession areas since the Opium War in 1842.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paci just looked at me,'' Tan continued. ``Then he said, `Come
tomorrow.''' Tan appeared the next day and played in every
remaining rehearsal and concert. As the season drew to a close, a
Chinese worker in charge of laying out scores urged him to ask
Maestro Paci for his salary. Tan demurred but finally mustered
enough courage to ask if he was to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' came the reply. ``This is a chance for you to
study.''
</P>
<P>
   Tan, who later became vice director of the Shanghai Conservatory
and a renowned violin teacher and maker, was untroubled by this
rebuff. ``I didn't care about the money,'' he said. ``My goal was
to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Shanghai Symphony Orchestra, as it has been called
since 1953, celebrated its 120th anniversary. As the nation's
oldest symphony orchestra, it has done more to promote the
development of symphonic music in China than any other institution.
</P>
<P>
   Its claim to the title ``best orchestra in the Far East,''
bestowed in the 1930s, is long past. But if judged on the basis of
perseverance and dedication in the face of seemingly insurmountable
odds, the Shanghai Symphony stands alone.
</P>
<P>
   It began humbly, as an amateur band of Filipino musicians. After
the International Settlement, run by the Shanghai Municipal
Council, took it over in 1881, it gradually became more
professional. In 1906, the council recruited a German conductor and
six European musicians, but when World War I broke out, the German
musicians were drafted into military service and the German members
of the symphony's board of directors expelled. Paci arrived in
1919, beginning a 23-year tenure still respectfully known as the
Paci era.
</P>
<P>
   He changed the band's name to Shanghai Municipal Orchestra in
1922 and replaced the missing Germans with White Russians and Jews,
who came to Shanghai seeking sanctuary. He broadened the repertory
to include works by composers like Stravinsky, Bartok and Gershwin,
and increased the number of musicians from 37 to more than 50.
</P>
<P>
   As the quality of the orchestra improved, it began to attract
international attention and world-renowned soloists, including
Fritz Kreisler, Jascha Heifetz, Fyodor Chaliapin and Dietrich
Fischer-Dieskau. In 1930, Paci made headlines by leading the
orchestra in its first work by a Chinese composer, ``In Memoriam''
by Huang Zi, who had studied at Oberlin College and Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Concert attendees had remained as foreign as the orchestra; when
Arthur Rubinstein performed in Shanghai in 1935, he complained that
the audience was all European and American. But the appearance of
musicians like Tan began to attract a Chinese audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had ever seen a Chinese in the orchestra,'' Tan said,
``So many people came to see me.'' The orchestra officially
admitted Chinese in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   It struggled through the wartime years of soaring inflation and
Japanese occupation. Paci laid down his baton in 1942, and Tan quit
in protest when a concert was scheduled in honor of a Japanese
general.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist victory in 1949 brought peace and a stable
currency, but it also ignited a debate: could a symphony orchestra
serve the needs of workers, peasants and soldiers? At a conference
held to discuss arts policy in Beijing, leftists argued that it
should be abolished; moderates, among them Tan and He Luting, later
the director of the Shanghai Conservatory, argued for its
preservation. The moderates won, and the Shanghai Symphony was
placed under the baton of Huang Yijun and the control of the
Shanghai Municipal Bureau of Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Shanghai Symphony survived, its problems with
politics were just beginning. In 1950, cries for its abolition were
heard again after it played selections from ``Madame Butterfly,''
which leftists argued was an effort to spread imperialist culture
even as China fought against the imperialist United States in
Korea. Walking a fine line, the Shanghai Symphony managed both to
preserve its integrity and to adapt to the times.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign symphony members were replaced by Chinese: in 1951 the
56-member Shanghai Symphony still had 16 foreigners, but by 1958 it
was all Chinese, with Soviet advisers on hand to offer support and
training. Huang expanded the repertory to include more Chinese
compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Music, like all other art forms, was required to follow the
Communist Party's dictates to be realistic and to ``reflect
society.'' Composers strove to create Chinese symphonic music that
integrated Western concepts of harmony and form with Chinese
melodies, often drawn from folk songs or the music of minority
nationalities. Programmatic music was favored, especially vocal
works, because they were easier for workers, peasants and soldiers
to understand.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, politics became more intrusive. During the Four
Pests Campaign, conservatory students were forced to stand under
trees and make noise with their instruments: afraid to land,
sparrows (considered pests) fell from the sky and died.
</P>
<P>
   The Sino-Soviet split in 1961 led to the departure of Soviet
advisers, and orchestra rehearsal time was devoted to studying the
``nine criticisms'' of Khrushchev. A campaign was launched against
``formalism,'' condemning ``ivory tower'' music that sprang from a
composer's feelings rather than the real experience of the people.
</P>
<P>
   With the onset of the Cultural Revolution in 1966, Western music
was condemned as bourgeois. Jiang Qing, the wife of Chairman Mao,
created eight ``model operas'' that became the only theatrical
pieces staged in all of China, their melodies reorchestrated as
``revolutionary symphonies,'' which the Shanghai Symphony sometimes
performed attired in soldiers' uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 10 years, the Shanghai Symphony played only `Shajiabang'
and `Taking Tiger Mountain by Strategy,''' Chen Guangxian, the
manager of the Shanghai Symphony said, referring to two model
operas re-orchestrated for symphony. Red Guards tormented Shanghai
Symphony musicians and conservatory professors, accusing them of
betraying China, its music and its people by playing Western music.
</P>
<P>
   So merciless was the abuse that 10 professors and seven students
at the conservatory were said to have been driven to suicide. Tan
was locked in a conservatory closet for nine months and beaten
regularly with a stick, then sent to repair toilets. At the
Shanghai Symphony, Gu Shengying, 30, a piano soloist, committed
suicide together with her family, and Lu Hongen, the resident
conductor, was executed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Cultural Revolution ended with Mao's death in September
1976, and that November, the Central Philharmonic Orchestra in
Beijing held a concert broadcast nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played Beethoven's Fifth,'' said Xu Ximing, director of
the Shanghai Music Lovers' Association. ``It is about the light
that comes after a period of great difficulty, so it was very
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Orchestras and conservatories around the nation began the
arduous process of rebuilding. When the Central Conservatory in
Beijing reopened in 1977, 40,000 people applied; applications to
the Shanghai Conservatory were close behind. Overseas orchestras
traveled to China, famous musicians offered master classes, and
audiences increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1980s, everyone wanted to hear Beethoven,'' Chen said.
``People lined up to buy tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Young composers began to explore new compositional techniques.
But because realism and the preservation of Chinese music remained
official policy, experimental efforts like atonality were
criticized. Zhu Jianer, the Shanghai Symphony's resident composer,
traveled to Beijing to defend the work of young composers like Tan
Dun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained that the roots of their music actually lay in the
music of the Chinese nationalities,'' Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that symphonic music was revived in the 1980s,
many composers and musicians emigrated. Then, as economic reforms
advanced and popular entertainment options increased, government
financing and attendance at classical concerts declined. The
Shanghai Symphony struggled to pay wages, and its musicians were
forced to moonlight in hotel lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Money remains a problem. The Shanghai Symphony's 94 musicians
are underpaid and their instruments, which belong to the orchestra,
need replacement. Although the orchestra's foundation solicits
corporate contributions, few are forthcoming, and the orchestra
remains almost exclusively dependent on government support.
</P>
<P>
   The symphony is regularly called to play for political
celebrations, often on short notice, making it difficult to
maintain a regular training schedule or plan a season. Concert
attendance has increased, but audience development is still a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to propagate classical music,'' Xu said. ``We have to
train people from childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Communist idea of cultural outreach is to ``go
down to the countryside'' and take culture to the masses, but
moving an orchestra to a cornfield or shipyard is so cumbersome
that the Shanghai Symphony does so only a few times a year.
</P>
<P>
   A more constructive approach would be to bring audiences to the
concert hall, but this is difficult because the orchestra does not
have its own facility. Concerts are held in the Shanghai Concert
Hall, originally a movie theater, or the new Grand Theater. Both
spaces must be rented, and neither is acoustically suited for a
symphony orchestra, a sore point with the musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the orchestra's future looks brighter. Musically, it has
grown under the baton of Chen Xieyang, its music director since
1984. The string sections have played together for years and have a
balanced ensemble and flowing sound, though the woodwind and brass
sections are weaker than the strings.
</P>
<P>
   It is common here to attribute this weakness to physical
deficiencies in Chinese people, but the real explanation lies in
the quality of conservatory faculty and students. China has little
tradition of secondary school ensemble programs like marching
bands, so conservatories must recruit wind players with almost no
ensemble experience.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing history full circle, the Shanghai Symphony is
compensating by recruiting woodwind and brass players from the
United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Financial support for recruitment comes from the Shanghai
government, which hopes to make the city more attractive by
improving its cultural institutions. Additional funds for training
have also been allocated, and Chen, the orchestra manager, has
arranged for a steady stream of foreign conductors to work with the
symphony.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra is also striving to meet international standards
on issues like copyrights, royalties and artist contracts. It tours
overseas regularly and often gives concerts in other Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate its 120th anniversary, the Shanghai Symphony paid
homage to its origins in East and West. Chen, the music director,
led a concert of works by Zhu Jianer and Beethoven. A conference on
the development of symphonic music was held and a commemorative
book published.
</P>
<P>
   The book paid special tribute to the orchestra's foreign
founders, its first Chinese musicians and the musicians who lost
their lives in the Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his time locked in a closet, Tan said that endurance
and faith were his keys to survival: ``I just thought, `It's night
now, but the sun will come out eventually.'''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, has the Shanghai Symphony held together through wars,
purges, political movements and financial crises: with endurance,
faith and an unwavering devotion to music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
