<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN AIMS AT MODERATE WHITES WITH RAP ON RELIGIOUS RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, whose early campaign success seemed modeled on
Gary Hart's 1984 rush out of New Hampshire, now seems to be taking
a page from the playbook of another former Democratic candidate,
Bill Clinton, with his attempt this week to appeal to centrist
voters by making a public break with a highly-charged constituency.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's attack Monday on the religious right leaders, Pat
Robertson and Rev. Jerry Falwell, for fostering ``the politics of
division and slander'' was reminiscent of Clinton's tactic in 1992
when he admonished Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow Coalition for
hosting a rap singer, Sister Souljah, who had spoken of the Los
Angeles riots in words Clinton said were ``filled with a kind of
hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, the action largely succeeded in convincing
Democratic moderates that he would not kowtow to Jackson, whose
political manueverings in earlier presidential campaigns had
alienated many whites and divided the party.
</P>
<P>
   By assailing Governor George W. Bush's appearance at
fundamentalist Bob Jones University and branding well-known
Christian conservative leaders as ``agents of intolerance,'' McCain
made a clear bid for the support of Republican moderates as well as
independents. Ever since a divisive national GOP convention in
Houston in 1992, many Republicans have been privately troubled by
the influence religious figures wield in party affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In broad terms, the moves look similar,'' said Mickey Kantor,
who was Clinton's national campaign manager in 1992. ``You are
bearding the lion politically; taking on an established interest in
the party. It's somewhat gutsy.''
</P>
<P>
   The results are different, Kantor said Wednesday, because
Clinton retained the strong allegiance of African-American voters
even while he declared his independence from Jackson. McCain, on
the other hand, appeared to have antagonized the Christian
conservative constituency with his broadside.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls taken during Tuesday's primary in Virginia found that
Bush won the support of 80 percent of the religious conservatives.
Ten days earlier, the religious right supported Bush by a ratio of
only 2-to-1 in South Carolina, though their heavy turnout helped
lead to McCain's defeat in that state.
</P>
<P>
   According to McCain's advisors, the Arizona senator decided to
make his move after Robertson went to Bush's aid prior to last
week's Michigan primary with a recorded telephone message
criticizing McCain. Robertson, the founding father of the Christian
Coalition, also described McCain's national co-chairman, former New
Hampshire senator Warren Rudman, as a ``vicious bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   While McCain was careful in his Virginia Beach speech to praise
the work of some evangelical leaders who are ``changing America for
the better,'' he singled out Robertson and Falwell, who have played
a major roles in the Republican Party for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party should be defined by pandering to the outer
reaches of American politics and the agents of intolerance, whether
they be Louis Farrakhan or Al Sharpton on the left or Pat Robertson
and Jerry Falwell on the right,'' McCain said. ``The politics of
divison and slander are not our values.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's political director, John Weaver, acknowledged recently
that the senator's campaign had studied the history of the Hart
campaign in choosing to concentrate on a breakout strategy launched
from New Hampshire. No one in the McCain camp has linked their
latest move to Clinton's strategy, but there are intriguing
parallels.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Clinton faced a delicate task of dealing with
Jackson's following. Leaders of the Democratic Leadership Council,
a group dominated by Southerners, felt Clinton needed a schism with
Jackson to prevent moderates from deserting the party again, as
they had in 1984 and 1988. As Jack Germond and Jules Witcover wrote
in ``Mad As Hell,'' their book on the 1992 election:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton campaign, in addition to being on the lookout for
ways to reach untapped audiences, also continued to seek means to
show the candidate `going against the grain' to demonstrate that he
was indeed a different kind of candidate. An opportunity was about
to present itself in this regard, handed unwittingly to Clinton by
an irreverent member of the MTV generation -- a young rap
entertainer who called herself Sister Souljah.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton wrapped up his party's nomination in June, he
scheduled an appearance at a Rainbow Coalition conference in
Washington. The night before, the organization had heard Lisa
Williamson, a woman known as Sister Souljah say this of the race
riots that spring in Los Angeles: ``Yeah, it was wise. I mean if
black people kill black people every day, why not have a week and
kill white people.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton rebuked the Rainbow Coalition, saying
that Sister Souljah's remarks were ``filled with a kind of hatred
that you do not honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was indignant over Clinton's statement, but the
candidate's performance ultimately won the praise of many other
black leaders as well as moderate whites.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain heads into showdowns next week in New England, New
York, Ohio and California, where the Republican ranks hold less
religious conservatives than the Southern states, he appears to be
counting on his Virginia Beach speech to convince the moderates in
his own party that, unlike some previous candidates of his party,
he will not bow to the demands of leaders like Robertson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
