<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3812 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CARNIVAL-BRAZIL-ART-2     03-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNIVAL-BRAZIL-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SALVADOR, Brazil: the drummers.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In last year's carnival, a replica of the Caetanave was
commissioned by the popular musician Carlinhos Brown and became one
of the high points of the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The trios were playing anything and everything popular _
Paganini, Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, Ravel's ``Bolero,'' the
Catholic hymn ``Senhor do Bonfim,'' the Beatles' ``I Want to Hold
Your Hand'' _ all frevo-ized. In 1969, Veloso's song ``Atras do
Trio Eletrico'' (``Behind the Trio Eletrico'') became a nationwide
hit, and it was only then that trios eletricos became a profitable
symbol of Bahia.
</P>
<P>
   By this time they had passed out of Dodo and Osmar's hands;
starting in the 1960s, the entrepreneur Orlando Campos developed
the trios eletricos into a business. Now they work almost like
sports teams, with each one owned privately and charging high
prices _ up to $300 this year _ for the privilege of wearing the
trio's official shirt and dancing around the trio.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, Bahian music was changing, and the trios changed
along with it. In 1975 Moreira, who had just left the popular band
Os Novos Baianos, brought some radical modifications to the
tradition. He was the first to sing atop a trio _ though he
remembers that the first year it was a complete technical failure.
And he started to write an entire catalog of songs meant for that
purpose. He also incorporated afoxe rhythms _ derived from the
Yoruban heritage of this heavily African-influenced city _ into the
music and brought the drums onto the same platform as the other
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as Moreira was a rock musician, his form of rock was
heavily influenced by the sound of the trio eletrico. So it was
only natural that the trio eletrico would be equally influenced by
rock when Moreira got involved with it.
</P>
<P>
   Armandinho remembers buying distortion and phase-shifting pedals
for his small guitarra Baiana and working a strain of Jimi
Hendrix's ``Bold as Love'' into the theme song of his trio in the
early 1970s. ``When Dodo saw the pedals the first time,''
Armandinho remembered, ``he said: `I can't believe I worked so hard
to take all the distortion out of the sound, and now you're putting
it back in. It's either me or these pedals.' And he left, and
waited for me to get rid of the pedals before he got on the truck
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound system had progressed from old-fashioned loudspeakers
to sophisticated amplifiers; it was an imitation of a rock band's
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the thickening commerce around the trios since then has not
dampened their popular power or their suggestiveness. They can be
whatever the crowd is ready for. Carlinhos Brown has worked hard to
keep a spirit of creativity, surprise and renovation in the
procession of the trios; he owns the trio for the band Timbalada,
which last year was festooned with an amazing mixture of ancient
and futuristic totems (not to mention seminude dancing women).
</P>
<P>
   This year the singer Daniela Mercury has turntablists scratching
and mixing on her trio _ a first. The Brazilian-American musician
Arto Lindsay played noise-rock guitar on top of a trio during last
year's carnival; one of his dreams is to create a trio composed of
two smaller trucks that would move together, one bearing treble
speakers, the other bearing bass, for a strange, different sonic
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Santtana, an important member of the next wave of young
innovators in Brazilian music, sees a natural connection between
the pipoca (or popcorn, the term for the jumping, exploding crowds
around the trio) of carnival and the audience at Berlin's Love
Parade, a procession that is more like a mobile techno-music rave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trio is a rootsy thing, but it's not old, in the folkloric
sense,'' Santtana said. ``It's pop. And when I listened to the
techno music that they play in the Love Parade, I recognized many
things I heard when I was a kid in Bahia. I recognized the sub-bass
of the trios, and the high-hats _ things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   His debut record, to be released in two weeks in Brazil, is
called ``Eletrobendodo'' _ an invented word that refers to the trio
eletrico, the musician Jorge Ben and Dodo.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to capture the ecstasy of the trio experience in any
still medium. For such a valued part of a carnival culture, the
trios were scarcely photographed before the 1970s; aside from the
original car and the original paus eletricos, which remain in the
Macedo family's possession, the history is largely oral. That might
be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's not very photogenic, not very good for
television,'' says Caetano Veloso, ``carnival in Bahia has been
protected from becoming artificialized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
