<HEADLINE>
HARVARD OPTS OUT OF FINANCIAL ROLE IN HMO'S RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harvard University rejected Wednesday a proposal from
Massachusetts Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly to play a financial
role in the rehabilitation of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care,
according to hospital sources.
</P>
<P>
   University officials refused to comment, but they have
consistently insisted on participation by other large employers as
a condition of risking any of Harvard's own money to rescue the
ailing health plan.
</P>
<P>
   The state has said it may have to raise anywhere from $175
million and $225 million to save Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard and the major employers _ that's where the problem
lies,'' one hospital executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and his staff were not available to comment on the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's decision complicates but does not necessarily doom the
chances that Harvard Pilgrim can continue as the state's largest
nonprofit health insurer, according to members of the hospital
community. The attorney general is believed to be trying to cobble
together other alternatives, although no one involved in the
two-month-old Harvard Pilgrim crisis knew what the other options
were, or if they knew, would give any hint.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives are still waiting for Reilly to tell them
what he'd like them to contribute and on what terms. At one point
this week, hospital officials understood through intermediaries
that Reilly was trying to raise equal amounts of cash from multiple
sources to total $225 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital sources said that one proposal called for hospitals,
Harvard University and Perot Systems, a computer firm that is the
HMO's biggest vendor, to contribute $75 million each. But it was
unclear whether all three groups would contribute cash, or whether
some would put in cash loans while others would guarantee those
loans.
</P>
<P>
   According to this plan, hospital sources said, no one of these
groups would invest more than others, to guard against undue
influence in Harvard Pilgrim's management.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has called hospital representatives to a 5
p.m. meeting Friday, an indication he is not yet ready to lay a
proposal before them.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Keating, chief financial officer of UMass Memorial Health
Care, said that he and other hospital CFOs have been asked to
attend a meeting to review a ``surplus notes option.''
</P>
<P>
   Surplus notes are IOUs that would not count as debt on Harvard
Pilgrim's books, thereby raising the health plan's net worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is that the only thing holding it up is the
security of the loans, for the most part,'' Keating said. ``The
providers are sitting back and waiting to see what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital financial officers remain cautious about lending
Harvard Pilgrim any money. Without a guarantee from the state or a
private investor behind the surplus notes, ``it would not be a
prudent investment,'' Keating said. ``It's a risk we can't take. It
will literally put hospitals in bankruptcy if there's a default to
that extent.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for hospitals' reluctance is skepticism about the
financial impact on Harvard Pilgrim in 2001 and 2002 if hospitals
and doctors win what they consider to be ``catch-up'' increases in
payment rates from the HMO, which insures one-sixth of the state's
population.
</P>
<P>
   If hospitals become major investors in Harvard Pilgrim's
turnaround, they have an interest in its long-term fiscal
viability, one hospital financial officer explained, or they won't
get their loans repaid.
</P>
<P>
   But this investor role potentially conflicts with hospitals'
interest as health care providers in negotiating the highest
possible payment rates from Harvard Pilgrim.
</P>
<P>
   One executive at a major hospital network said the conflict of
interest could be mitigated by spreading out the loans among a
large number of institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital executive said that if a small group of hospitals
loan money to Harvard Pilgrim, then the HMO may have to cut
reimbursements to all hospitals to repay those loans and the
accompanying interest. In effect, the small group of investor
hospitals would be cushioned from lower reimbursements by the
interest on their loans, while their noninvesting competitors would
be put at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general and state Insurance Commissioner Linda
Ruthardt, who was named on Jan. 4 to administer Harvard Pilgrim
while its fate is worked out, are scheduled to file a progress
report with the court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly had said he hoped to indicate by then which path he was
pursuing _ recapitalizing the HMO as a nonprofit, selling it to a
for-profit company, liquidating it, or restructuring its debt to
give it time to recover.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general and his staff have said publicly and
privately this week that there are several for-profit suitors for
Harvard Pilgrim in the wings. Speculation has centered mainly
around Connecticut-based Oxford Health Plans and Anthem Insurance
Companies of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   However, a number of hospital officials and HMO industry
observers are skeptical that for-profit interest in Harvard Pilgrim
is great.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear there are four potential for-profit buyers, but I
personally don't think there's anything there,'' said one hospital
executive. ``I think it's smoke and mirrors right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That executive said he thinks for-profit companies are mainly
interested in scavenging Harvard Pilgrim subscribers if the HMO
folds rather than taking it over and turning it around.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there are for-profit buyers, ``I think people realize
that no for-profit is going to pay 100 cents on the dollar'' to
settle Harvard Pilgrim's debts, said one Massachusetts health
insurance executive.
</P>
<P>
   By these assessments, it appears that all the options for
Harvard Pilgrim involve some degree of risk or pain for hospitals,
which are reportedly owed more than $200 million by the HMO.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear what role the Legislature would be asked to
play in the Harvard Pilgrim endgame. There was talk of setting up a
commission to address HMO regulation and other issues raised by the
current HMO crisis, and possibly to consider state loan guarantees
or hospital relief, but those reports could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Mark Montigny, a New Bedford Democrat who chairs the
Senate Ways and Means Committee, said he told Reilly on Tuesday
that he would help expedite any necessary legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we learn what the short list of options is from the
attorney general, we have to be prepared to act very quickly,''
Montigny said. One concern, he added, is that all Massachusetts
HMOs should be subjected to the same conditions put on Harvard
Pilgrim as a condition of its rehabilitation so that the ailing HMO
is not put at a competitive disadvantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
