<SLUG> BC-IMF-U.S.-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STALLS SELECTION OF NEW IMF CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton pledged this week to block a
German finance ministry official from assuming the top post at the
International Monetary Fund, in effect vetoing the man the European
Union had chosen for the job, he seemed to risk a diplomatic
confrontation across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   What really happened, Clinton administration and some European
officials now say, is that the president agreed to play the heavy
because both U.S. and European diplomats had trouble communicating
across the Rhine.
</P>
<P>
   During the four months that Germany was aggressively promoting
Caio Koch-Weser to take over at the IMF, ending with Europe's
formal endorsement by the 15-nation European Union, officials from
the United States, Britain, Italy and France had regular
conversations in which they agreed broadly on two things: The next
head of the IMF should be a European and the European should not be
Koch-Weser, several Clinton administration officials and European
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Both U.S. and European officials said that Koch-Weser, a genial
55-year-old state secretary in Germany's finance ministry, lacks
the gravitas and financial expertise to lead the IMF at a time when
it is arguably more powerful than ever before. The problem for
fellow Europeans, and later for Americans, was that Germany ignored
some early signs of unease with Koch-Weser and started the nation's
most aggressive diplomatic campaign in years to install him as head
of the monetary fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``They mistook politeness for support,'' one administration
official said. ``In the end, they kind of backed us into a corner
and made us play big foot.''
</P>
<P>
   That description of events serves U.S. interests, of course, by
cloaking an unusual and potentially explosive decision in the garb
of a broader diplomatic imperative. It also contradicts public
statements that European ministers have made in recent days,
including several comments chastising Washington for its hubris.
</P>
<P>
   But European officials confirmed in interviews that they
supported Koch-Weser mainly to preserve European unity in the face
of an unyielding German campaign rather than because they agreed he
should head the IMF, a post held by a European ever since the
institution was created just after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, even as they publicly rallied behind Koch-Weser, Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin of France and Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
of Italy have been calling each other to discuss new candidates for
the job, diplomats told about the conversations said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition in Europe is solidarity on decisions of this
kind,'' one European diplomat said. ``But there is also an
understanding of the position of the United States. There is
certainly no crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the world often has a hard time selecting leaders for the
main international institutions _ succession at the United Nations
and the World Trade Organization has been contentious as well _ the
search for a head of the monetary fund shows how diplomatically
delicate, and deeply flawed, the search process has become,
administration officials and outside experts say. If there is a
single lesson from the search, it is that the current process,
whereby interested countries nominate their own citizens for key
posts and then use their diplomatic influence to support them,
needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' rejection of Koch-Weser _ and its decision at
this stage not to back anyone else _ means that when the monetary
fund conducts an informal vote on Thursday, there will almost
certainly be no winner. Aside from Koch-Weser, there are two other
candidates. Stanley Fischer, the American who serves as deputy
managing director, was nominated by a group of 20 African and Arab
countries. Japan has nominated Eisuke Sakakibara, a former finance
ministry official.
</P>
<P>
   What happens after that is uncertain. Clinton administration
officials and European officials say that they hope German
officials will realize after the straw poll, if they have not
already, that the nomination of Koch-Weser was a mistake. That
would clear the way for other possible European candidates,
including the British and Italian finance ministers and the head of
the Bank for International Settlements, who are more likely to
generate broad support, according to U.S. and European officials.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The search for a new IMF leader began last October, when it
became clear to top financial officials that Michel Camdessus of
France, who led the monetary fund for 13 years, planned to retire
two years before the end of his term. The post immediately
attracted a slew of potential European candidates. But the
strongest push came from Germany, which had made clear its
intention of taking a larger role in international institutions and
felt that the French, who have named most IMF directors, should not
claim this one as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans immediately put forward Koch-Weser. On paper, at
least, he had the perfect resume. An economist who worked for a
quarter-century at the World Bank, Koch-Weser had extensive
contacts in financial circles around the world, spoke six languages
and was perhaps the most cosmopolitan of all of Germany's small
circle of financial bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Koch-Weser also had good political ties at home, people who
worked with him said. He left the World Bank in Washington, where
he had risen to managing director, one of the five most senior
posts, to return to Germany soon after the election of Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder. The new chancellor named him state secretary at
the finance ministry, the No. 2 position.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Larry Summers made clear from the start,
including in conversations with Koch-Weser during meetings in
Europe and Tokyo, that he did not favor the German's bid to head
the fund. The two had known each other when both were working at
the World Bank in the early 1990s. Summers' main concern was that
Koch-Weser was a specialist in poverty relief and had no expertise
in finance. Moreover, the German was seen as a go-along-get-along
guy who thrived at the World Bank by working well with the
bureaucracy, not by leading it, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Koch-Weser's candidacy did not ring alarm bells at
the Treasury Department. Administration officials said the European
reaction to Koch-Weser was even cooler than their own, especially
among France, Britain and Italy. It was given low odds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The United States was drawn directly into the European fray by
Schroeder himself. Early last month, he called Clinton _ the two
have a close relationship, administration officials said _ and
lobbied him directly. Clinton used diplomatic language to convey to
Schroeder that Koch-Weser had not demonstrated that he had broad
support, not only in Europe but also around the world. Yet, in part
because administration officials still believed Koch-Weser's
chances of getting European backing were slim, Clinton assured
Schroeder that the United States had no objections to a German
candidate per se.
</P>
<P>
   Germany began promoting Clinton's friendly words as a tacit
endorsement, administration officials said. Schroeder promptly flew
to Paris to meet with President Jacques Chirac and Jospin. The
French, who had been the only Europeans to publicly challenge
Koch-Weser's qualifications, were told that Clinton had no problem
with Koch-Weser provided he became the unified European choice,
according to people told about Schroeder's conversation with the
French.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign gathered steam, Clinton administration officials
began fretting that they had been too passive early on. Summers;
Gene Sperling, the president's national economic adviser; Sandy
Berger, the national security adviser; and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright had a series of phone calls to debate strategy.
Sensing that a confrontation with Germany might be inevitable,
Berger and Sperling began doing their own research on Koch-Weser.
If they were going to risk German ire, they wanted to be certain
that Treasury's opinion of Koch-Weser was right, officials said.
Both Sperling and Berger ended up agreeing with the Treasury view,
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger was the most reluctant of Clinton's top advisers to risk
a diplomatic split with Germany, administration officials said. But
as the European Union endorsement became inevitable last week, he
agreed that it was better to try to stop the candidacy now than to
stay silent and possibly set off a bigger, public confrontation
later.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Clinton initiated a call to Schroeder. The message
was unmistakable: The United States wants a European for the job,
but not Koch-Weser. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
