<HEADER>
A3830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHILD-MENTAL-NYT &LR;      03-01 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-MENTAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING TO UNDERSTAND WHY A 6-YEAR-OLD KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (with CHILD-SHOT)  
 (bl)  
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the morning, the boy pulled out a pistol and killed his
first-grade classmate, Kayla Rolland.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, police said, he sat at a table and drew
pictures, seemingly unaware that something horrendous had happened.
</P>
<P>
   What does this say about the culpability of the 6-year-old who
turned a peaceful Tuesday morning at Buell Elementary School in a
suburb of Flint, Mich., into a nightmare?
</P>
<P>
   For the legal system, the question is relatively clear cut.
Because of just such contradictions in behavior, in the United
States and most other industrialized nations, children under the
age of 7 are not normally held responsible for crimes like murder.
And Arthur Busch, the Genesee County prosecutor, said Tuesday it is
unlikely that the boy will be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   But the issues are much murkier for parents, school officials,
government leaders and others who try to understand why young
children kill, and what can be done to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Garbarino, the author of ``Lost Boys: Why Our Sons
Turn Violent and How We Can Save Them'' (Free Press, 1999), said
that, in some ways, the age of the Buell boy was anything but
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys of 8-year-olds, he said, show that one-third said they
could get a gun if they wanted one. In several incidents around the
country, children 6 and younger have been caught bringing guns to
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing magical or automatic about the age,'' said
Garbarino, a professor of human development at Cornell University,
``There's no built in protection there. Quite the contrary, there
is a built in vulnerability. A young child is even more open to
cultural and family influence than an older kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Those influences, Garbarino said, include the availability of
lethal weapons, and ``ample opportunities to see on television and
in the movies how you threaten people, what it means to shoot
someone, and ample opportunities to learn about revenge and how
desirable it is in this society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the nation to be shocked and appalled and mystified and
stunned,'' he said, ``is either a kind of denial or hypocrisy.''.
</P>
<P>
   Garbarino and others said that whether a 6-year-old understands
the significance and permanence of death, however, depends on the
individual child, the circumstances of the child's life, and other
factors.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found in recent years that young children have
a more developed moral sense and a greater ability to grasp
abstract concepts and to reason rationally than was once believed.
</P>
<P>
   By the age of 6 or even younger, said Dr. Elliot Turiel, a
developmental psychologist and chancellor's professor at the
University of California at Berkeley, most children understand that
it is wrong to harm another person.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can understand that it hurts,'' Turiel said, ``and that
they don't want to experience pain and other people don't either.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it would be okay for one child to hit another without
provocation, he said, most children at 6 would say that it would be
wrong, and would stick to their conviction even if there were no
official rules prohibiting such action or if an authority figure
were to say that it was permissible.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for some children, he said, the threshold for retaliation
in response to another's actions might be lower than for others.
</P>
<P>
   In one study, Dr. Ron Avi Astor, then a graduate student at
Berkeley and now an assistant professor at the University of
Michigan, presented two groups of children with moral dilemmas.
Children in one group had a history of aggressive actions, the
others did not.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if it was okay to hit another child without
provocation, children in both groups responded that to do so would
be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was okay to hit another child who had teased them or
called them names, however, children with a history of aggression
were more likely to say that retaliation by hitting would be
justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``While both understand moral judgments,'' Turiel said, ``they
seem to make different judgments with regard to retaliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Most young children, experts now say, are also more adept at
understanding some abstract concepts _ basic notions of biology,
for example _ than previously believed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Gelman, a professor of psychology at the University of
Michigan, said that ``there is good evidence that children have at
least some beginning understanding of biological processes even in
the preschool years.''
</P>
<P>
   By the age of 5, for instance, most children understand that
getting fat is a consequence of eating a lot. And they show a basic
grasp of the notion of heredity: Asked if a baby cow raised with
pigs would be more like a cow or more like a pig, most children
said that the cow would still be a cow, Gelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what light _ if any _ such studies shed on the mind of a
6-year-old who guns down a classmate is uncertain. In the real
world, said Dr. Laurence Steinberg, director of the John D. and
Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation's Network on Adolescent
Development and Juvenile Justice, ``there is good reason to believe
that children of this age have difficulty envisioning the future
consequences of actions _ as most parents of children up to the age
of 11 will tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   The MacArthur network, made up of experts in the social sciences
and the law, is studying issues relating to crimes committed by
children, in an effort to determine at what age it is appropriate
to hold someone responsible for a criminal act. Steinberg, a
professor of psychology at Temple University in Philadelphia, said
the research is still under way. But he predicted the age would
turn out to be somewhere between 12 and 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't enough to say, did the child know right from wrong?''
Steinberg said. ``The issue is whether this individual had the
cognitive and emotional capabilities to stop himself from doing
something, even if he knew it was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   And a child's emotional state, said Dr. Donald Rosenblitt, a
psychoanalyst specializing in treating children and director of the
Lucy Daniels Center for Early Childhood in Cary, N.C., often can
have a direct impact on the ability to reason.
</P>
<P>
   Children who commit acts of violence, he said, often do not have
a real emotional understanding of injury and death.
</P>
<P>
   Life in a chaotic world _ growing up in a house where adults
come and go, and guns are lying out in the open, for example _ can
produce a child who cannot control aggression and who does not make
the distinctions between play and reality that he said are normal
at the age of 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child who uses a real gun to discharge these feelings,''
Rosenblitt said, ``shows a failure, at a very significant level, to
find other ways to deal with troubles, and this could come from how
they have been treated, or how they have seen people being
treated.'' What a 6-year-old boy who shoots a classmate may not
have had, he said, ``was the protective umbrella that a normal
child would have, one that would wrap his anger in a regard for
people and a sense of caring and empathy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
