<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3832 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-NY-PATAKI-740(2T     03-01 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NY-PATAKI-740(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH'S CAMP UNVEILS TOUGH NEW STRATEGY AGAINST McCAIN IN NEW YORK 
 (sw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY and RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fresh from his three-state victory for the Republican
presidential nomination on Tuesday night, Gov. George W. Bush on
Wednesday turned his attention to New York, unleashing a scathing
stream of attacks _ by mail, telephone, and radio _ that portrayed
Sen. John McCain as repeatedly voting against the concerns of New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy, tough and precisely targeted at different
regions of the state, was introduced on Wednesday by Gov. George
Pataki, the chairman of Bush's New York campaign, at an afternoon
news conference in Albany, where he labeled McCain as ``anti-New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday night, Bush began broadcasting a radio
advertisement featuring Geri Barish, a well-known Long Island
advocate for breast cancer research, who attacked McCain for voting
against legislation for some breast cancer research money. ``We
deserve a candidate with a record on women's issues we can trust,''
Barish said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks by Bush came as he and McCain approached what many
Republicans believe could be a climactic round of primaries next
Tuesday, and with Bush's New York supporters arguing that a
divisive defeat for McCain in New York _ a state where polls now
show the two men in a tie _ could effectively end McCain's
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   They suggested that Bush had, as he has in other major states,
handed over much of the control of his effort to local officials,
in this case, Pataki; William Powers, who is the state Republican
Party chairman, and Zenia Mucha, who is Pataki's chief political
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a coordinated campaign of mail, radio ads and
telephone calls, that seeks to highlight votes that McCain cast in
the Senate that may undercut him with voters across the state.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one piece of mail, sent to Republican voters in
districts with a heavy concentration of farmers, noted that McCain
had opposed allowing New York to enter the Northeast Dairy Compact,
which would have provided higher payments for milk. Another, sent
to the northern reaches of New York, pointed to votes McCain had
cast against aid to help people paying fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an absolutely consistent pattern of voting against the
interests of New York, whether it's specific things like voting
against aid for the ice storm recovery or the dairy compact, or
generic things like the whole transit thing where he voted to cut
us,'' Pataki said in an interview after the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The tough New York strategy ruptured anew the relationship
between Pataki and another prominent supporter of Bush, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani of New York City. Giuliani has resisted playing a
key role in attacks on McCain, apparently concerned that he is
being perceived as too harsh in his handling of his
all-but-announced Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After initially agreeing to join other Republican mayors on
behalf of Bush at a news conference scheduled for Thursday,
Giuliani abruptly withdrew from the event after seeing a release
promoting it as an assault on McCain for his Senate votes, one of
the mayor's advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   While the aide said the mayor would accompany Pataki when Bush
travels in the city on Friday and Saturday for several campaign
stops, Giuliani plans to refuse to engage in any attacks on McCain,
whom the mayor has described as a friend and a hero. This adviser
said that Giuliani believed Bush and his New York campaign were
making a mistake in turning the campaign so harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor wants to strongly support and campaign with Bush,''
the adviser said. ``But it's becoming increasingly difficult
because of the governor's office.'' This adviser said that the
mayor would not lend his name to any attacks on McCain, and had
already demanded that he not be included in a piece of campaign
literature attacking McCain for voting against relief for upstate
residents following severe ice storms.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's senior New York adviser, Guy V. Molinari, the Staten
Island borough president, ridiculed efforts by Pataki and Bush as
``stupid'' and ``immature.'' He argued that their tactics would
only succeed in weakening the Republican Party for the fall
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are making more dumb mistakes,'' Molinari said. ``What
are they going to do if John McCain ends up being the nominee of
the party? How do they swallow their remarks? We can reasonably
expect the Democrats to pick up these charges. This is the dumbest
thing in the world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of turning McCain's voting record against him was
reminiscent of what Vice President Al Gore did, to great effect,
against Bill Bradley, his Democratic opponent and a former senator
from New Jersey, earlier in the primary season. Gore, for example,
attacked Bradley during the Iowa caucuses for votes against
agricultural programs.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking in this case is the manner in which Bush and
his advisers appear to be tailoring attacks to appeal to different
parts of the state. The strategy reflects the unusual nature of the
New York contest: rather than just a statewide contest involving
Bush, McCain and a third candidate, Alan Keyes, Republicans in each
of 31 separate congressional districts will be voting for three
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The breast cancer radio ad, for example, is running mainly on
Long Island and in the New York City metropolitan area. Long Island
is expected to be a key area in the Republican vote _ that is where
Bush will start his New York state swing on Friday _ and the
incidence of breast cancer there has been a subject of concern
among public officials and voters alike.
</P>
<P>
   Barish has become a symbol of that effort, and a close adviser
to Pataki, so the advertisement by her could be particularly
potent, as she lists votes in Congress that McCain cast, such as
cutting financing for some breast-cancer research programs. ``John
McCain calls these projects, just `garden-variety pork,'' she said
in the ad. ``That's shocking. America deserves better. Next
Tuesday, John McCain won't have my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki scoffed at the suggestion that the attacks would only
weaken McCain in a general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, were McCain to be the nominee, many of those
Democrats would be out there pointing out the shortcomings of his
record,'' Pataki said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The severe turn taken by Bush's campaign in New York was
particularly notable given that Bush appears to have a definite
organizational advantage over McCain. He has the support of the
state Republican organization, giving him a ready-made machine to
contact potential voters, and make certain they go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Pataki has arguably as much riding on the outcome
as Bush, both because he has so identified himself with Bush's
effort, and because so many Republicans were critical of his
ultimately failed effort to avoid this primary by trying to keep
McCain off the ballot. Pataki's supporters have suggested that Bush
might consider the governor of New York as a potential candidate
for vice president; in any event, Pataki presumably does not want
to be remembered as another Republican governor who failed Bush at
a key time.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's New York supporters suggested that Pataki's desire
to prove otherwise accounted for the searing, layered assault on
McCain. The governor, though, shrugged off the idea that a Bush
loss in his state might hurt him. ``I'll leave that to the
pundits,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
