<HEADER>
A3834 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-COLLEGE-REPORT-TE     03-01 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLLEGE-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS HAVE VOICE, AND THEY PLAN TO USE IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pay attention. History is in the making. College basketball
players have started to organize themselves in an effort to make
their voices heard. Once they realize how much power they have, The
Powers That Be (re: NCAA) might require earplugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Student Basketball Council held its first official meeting
by teleconference Sunday night. Duke junior forward Shane Battier
was named chairman and spokesman of the 46-member group. They spent
their first meeting discussing college basketball issues ranging
from summer basketball recruiting to eligibility issues to getting
their slice of the $6 billion NCAA Tournament contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make our voices known and let people know within
the NCAA structure how players feel and produce recommendations for
real change,'' Battier said.
</P>
<P>
   The SBC grew out of a proposal that was unanimously approved by
the National Association of Basketball Coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have taken the initiative six months ago or six
years ago,'' said NABC executive director Jim Haney, who emphasized
that Battier was in charge of Sunday's teleconference. ``This is
one of those things that make so much sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them that they would have independence. We know there
are some issues that they might discuss that won't be particularly
comfortable for coaches. But these \Rstudent-athletes\S, along with
the coaches, are the ones on the front lines. They need to have
their opinions heard.''
</P>
<P>
   This has not been a great year off the court for college
basketball. Eligibility issues have sidelined players at Missouri,
Oklahoma State, UCLA, Michigan, St. John's and Auburn. In some of
those cases, the suspended players have been guilty until proven
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are immediately concerned and highly disappointed about the
image that a lot of players are getting due to perceived violations
of NCAA rules,'' Battier said. ``We feel that a lot of these
players are getting a bad reputation and are being vilified in the
eyes of the public when, in fact, nothing morally wrong has
occurred. So, as a group, we are trying to come together and
support our brothers who have been ostracized.''
</P>
<P>
   The SBC's executive committee will meet face to face during the
Final Four in Indianapolis. Battier wants to take advantage of the
media presence at that event by holding a news conference to
further advance the players' opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not naive. They see what's happening around them,''
Haney said of the players. ``They want to let people know what they
think is in their best interests. I have no doubt they'll expect
their opinion to hold weight; if they don't, they're going to want
to know why.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is this historic? The players have more power than they
realize.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this scenario: Let's say the SBC persuades the two
teams playing in the national championship game to stage a
sit-down. With a nation tuning in on CBS, the ball goes up for the
opening tip and the 10 players walk to their benches and sit for
five minutes. A statement is delivered to the media that says:
``This protest is in remembrance of our fellow players who lost
games due to unfair NCAA suspensions.''
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is a little organization, a little all-for-one
attitude, and college administrators will understand that
scholarship athletes have been treated like serfs. And those castle
walls are showing cracks.
Sanchez isn't Cleaves, Chaney says; he's better
Before the season, Temple coach John Chaney was discussing the
merits of his senior point guard, Pepe Sanchez. Sanchez was rated
as the nation's seventh-best point guard by one preseason
publication, the eight-best by another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody put a magazine in my face with this guy from Michigan
State, Mateen \RCleaves\S, who averaged about eight to nine
turnovers a game last year,'' Chaney said. ``And they've got him
down as the No. 1 point guard. He only goes to his right. I don't
mean to down the kid, but I really don't give a damn. I just think
Pepe's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The irascible and demanding Chaney had a point. If it's
difficult to make a case that Sanchez is the nation's best point
guard, it certainly can be said that he is more valuable to his
team than any other player.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls were a preseason Final Four favorite. But Sanchez
suffered a severely sprained ankle Nov. 21. Temple went 5-3 without
Sanchez. With him, the Owls are 17-2. In the eight games Sanchez
missed, Temple shot 33.8 percent and allowed 61.9 points a game. In
the 19 games Sanchez has played, the Owls are shooting 44.1 percent
from the field and allowing 50.9 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Argentina, Sanchez struggled in his first two
seasons at Temple. Chaney demands three things from his point
guard: get the ball to the scorers, don't turn it over, play
unyielding defense. Shooting and scoring are not on the list. It
wasn't until last season that Sanchez saw the light.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez averages only 6.4 points per game. His value to the Owls
can be seen in his 8.0 assists and 3.3 steals per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an old-fashioned point guard,'' Chaney said. ``He gets a
big kick out of a steal or a stop. The kind of shooters we have,
they wouldn't have had the games they did if he wasn't there. Every
game we play, we hang on his back. Without him, we don't stand a
chance of playing high-level basketball.''
\Nsubheds:Fast breaks Play to get in Thirty 34, 64. Those are the
numbers the NCAA Tournament stands by. Thirty automatic qualifiers,
34 at-large bids, a 64-team field. Next year, those numbers won't
be so neat and tidy.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Athletic and Mountain West conferences will get
automatic bids, bringing the number of conferences with automatic
qualifiers to 31. The NCAA, not wanting to change its 30-34
balance, will likely require a play-in game to determine who gets
the 64th spot in the 2001 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the NCAA, faced with 33 automatic qualifiers, staged
three play-in games. Those six conference tourney winners were
matched up based on their 1990 Ratings Percentage Index rankings. A
decade later, the format will be different. The men's basketball
committee will announce the playoff pairing when it announces the
field. The play-in game would probably be staged the Tuesday before
the first-round games.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it might work: Let's say that a team with a 200 RPI
ranking was an upset winner of the Southland Conference tournament.
If that team had the worst RPI among the 29 teams that won
conference tourneys, it would face the team with the next-worst RPI
from the 29 league tourney winners. (The Pacific-10 Conference and
Ivy League award their automatic qualifiers to their regular-season
champions). Trash talk Stanford's David Moseley on the play of
teammate Mark Madsen, who averaged 17.6 points and 12.6 rebounds
over the past five games: ```Monn
</P>
</TEXT>
