<SLUG> BC-BUSH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bauer calls for McCain to take back comments about religious
leaders
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After first standing by him, conservative activist
Gary Bauer urged John McCain on Wednesday to retract and apologize
for bitingly critical statements about religious leaders Pat
Robertson and Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not backing away from the speech,'' McCain responded in
his latest reversal of fortune, occurring one day after a triple
loss to Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must in the strongest possible terms repudiate Senator
McCain's unwarranted, ill-advised and divisive attacks on certain
religious leaders,'' Bauer said in a statement. ``Senator McCain
must not allow his personal differences with any individual to
cloud his judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a leader among social conservatives, endorsed McCain last
month after dropping out of the Republican presidential race
himself. He was with McCain on Monday when the Arizona senator
criticized the two men onstage, and he said afterward, ``If this
were an attack on Christian conservative voters, I wouldn't be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he criticized McCain's comparison of Robertson and
Falwell with the Rev. Al Sharpton and Louis Farrakhan. ``Such
rhetoric serves only to divide the party and place into the hands
of the liberal elite material to falsely depict Christian
conservatives as intolerant extremists,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized McCain's later statement, on his campaign
bus, that he was trying to battle ``the forces of evil,'' and was
hampered by the influence of Robertson and Falwell on the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning that, McCain said Wednesday, ``It was a lighthearted
attempt at humor. I did not say or mean to say they are evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush chimed in, too, saying he agreed with Bauer that McCain's
comparison of the two men with Farrakhan was inappropriate, ``but
that's the kind of campaign he's chosen to run.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's comments, and Bauer's repudiation, could help set the
tone for a critical debate scheduled for tonight, just five days
before the two men square off on Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bruised by losses in Michigan and Arizona, Bush got a
much-needed lift with his triple crown victory in the Virginia,
North Dakota and Washington primaries and is considered the
favorite to win California's 162 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain's hope for survival is to clinch New York's
101 GOP delegates and the 102 delegates in New England's five
states. Three polls released Wednesday show McCain either leading
Bush or in a dead heat in New York. McCain also leads in
Massachusetts, Connecticut and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening here is a civil war, north and south,'' said
pollster John Zogby, whose New York-based firm, Zogby
International, is nonpartisan. ``Just as the union troops stormed
Charleston in 1862, Bush attacked the state of Washington. That was
a big victory. ... He crossed the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the Austin American-Statesman on Wednesday that the
Washington state primary was pivotal and that he is confident he
will go all the way to the White House. But that victory doesn't
mean the contest is over, Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody says they thought Bush was going to win (the
nomination) in Washington, they're a fool,'' he said. ``The one
thing we've learned is that there's no momentum here. There's no
bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast is both delegate-rich and important symbolically.
Most of the New England GOP primaries are closed, meaning Bush
won't face the threat of crossover Democrats voting for McCain.
Only Vermont allows Democrats to vote in its primary.
</P>
<P>
   New York's primary is also closed and the state's Republican
establishment, all the way up to Gov. George Pataki, has staked
itself out for a Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   But California remains the Grand Old Party's grand prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush wins California and McCain wins the New England
(primaries), I'll be paying a lot more attention to California,''
said independent political analyst Stu Rothenberg. ``A lot of us
think that New England is quirky and not a particularly good
indicator of the rest of the country. You add California to Texas
and Florida and suddenly you're not an awful long way from the
nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin American-Statesman staff writers Ken Herman and Mark
Sherman contributed to this report, which also includes material
from the Associate Press.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
