<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND MEXICO ARE AT ODDS OVER TRUTH ABOUT LIE TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The chairman of a House committee with oversight
over drug policy said Wednesday that Mexico, embarrassed by the
poor showing of its anti-drug agents in lie detector tests, had
canceled the testing program last August.
</P>
<P>
   The legislator, John Mica, R.-Fla., said, ``Everyone was failing
the tests, so they eliminated the program.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mica's assertions _ which came on the same day that Mexico
was officially certified by President Clinton as a reliable partner
in the war against drugs _ were emphatically denied by Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Diaz de Leon, a representative of the Mexican attorney
general's office in Washington, said in an interview that Mexican
agents were still being given the tests. Last August, he said,
Mexico simply began excluding U.S. officials from witnessing the
tests because Mexican technicians felt competent to do them on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations about the testing came as the administration
announced that Mexico and Colombia, the two countries that are the
main source and corridor for most of the cocaine entering the
United States, were doing their share to stop the production and
smuggling of illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The countries were among 26 identified as tied to the world's
illicit drug trade in an annual report required by Congress. All
but two of the countries _ Afghanistan and Myanmar, the former
Burma _ were certified as cooperating with the United States to
stop drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The countries that fail to be certified as cooperating are
subject to U.S. trade sanctions, including the withholding of
investment credits by international lending institutions. In fact,
only a handful have been punished to the full extent.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Mexico's top narcotics official, Gen. Jesus Gutierrez
Rebollo, was discovered to be an associate of a leading trafficker
three years ago, authorities had routinely submitted members of the
country's elite anti-drug squads to lie detector tests as a way of
certifying their integrity.
</P>
<P>
   But last year Mexico began to exclude U.S. officials from the
sessions in which the polygraph tests were administered, arousing
suspicions about the integrity of the process, U.S. officials said
Wednesday. Dismayed, they said, they reacted by reducing
cooperation with several of the squads.
</P>
<P>
   In congressional testimony on Tuesday, William E. Ledwith, chief
of international operations for the Drug Enforcement
Administration, said the testing program had been ``shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledwith was asked to describe the ``problem areas'' in working
with Mexico on drugs. He cited Mexico's failure to arrest any major
traffickers recently, a string of frustrated extradition attempts,
and the suspension of the lie detector program in the elite squads,
which he called ``embedded units.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The polygraph program with embedded units was shut down in
August of last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Parham, a federal Drug Enforcement Administration
spokesman, said that U.S. officials are negotiating with Mexico in
an attempt to re-establish the tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
