<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-BOS &LR;      03-01 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER SET TO RETURN AFTER SENTENCE SLICED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a country! Somebody had to help Atlanta's John Rocker out
of the mess he made for himself three months ago. Arbitrator Shyam
Das came to the rescue Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Citing other rulings, Das issued a stunning decision in favor of
the 25-year-old Braves reliever, reducing three major elements of
the penalty issued Jan. 31 by commissioner Bud Selig: Rocker has to
pay only $500 of a $20,000 penalty; he can finish the remaining
exhibition season with the Braves; and he will only have to miss 14
of his original 28-day regular-season penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker is expected to be in the Braves training camp Thursday in
Kissimmee, Fla., where he is scheduled to meet with his teammates
and then hold a news confernce.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who was punished for making disparaging remarkers about
foreigners, gays, and minorities could make his first appearence
April 18 against Philadelphia at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Das's ruling was the result of a grievence filed in Shocker's
behalf by the Players Association. Despite a public outcry against
Rocker. The union had argued that the penalty was too great when
compared with past disciplines by the commissioner's office and
promised a nasty fight had not some adjustment been made.
</P>
<P>
   Das's decision, his first for Major League Baseball, merely
reinforced those changes, and the view that arbitrators had
overturned or reduced suspensions before.
</P>
<P>
   Selig's original penalty was believed to be the longest against
a baseball player for an action not related to drug use since Lenny
Randle of Texas got 30 days in March 1977 for punching his manager,
Frank Lucchesi.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the insensitivity of Rocker's remarks in a Sports
Illustrated article, Selig said he thought the penalty should be
more than a slap on the wrist. He still does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with the decision,'' said Selig in a prepared
statement. ``It does not reflect any understanding or sensitivity
to the important social responsibility that baseball . . . has to
be the public. It completely ignores the sensibilities of those
groups of people maligned by Mr. Rocker and disregards the player's
position as a role model for children.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the union expressed unhappiness, too. ``We're
disappointed that the penalty wasn't reduced more,'' said Players
Association lawyer Gene Orza.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions varied, in and out of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair,'' says Braves pitcher Tom Glavine said, one
of several players anxious to see how Rocker handles himself now.
``It allows him some of spring training to get ready for the
season. . . . If not, you run the risk of John ruining his career.
No one wants that. That would be unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actions speak louder than words. It's easy to issue an
apology. It's tougher to show remorse day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   Others still want Rocker pay a stiff price for his actions and
believes baseball should clean its own linen. Atlanta City
Councilman Derrick Boazman, leader of a coalition of minority
groups that has called for the Braves to release Rocker, said,
``Hate and bigotry and homophobia and racism have a place,
evidently, and that place is in Major League Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen activists marched outside Turner Field in Atlanta,
demanding the Braves quickly trade the reliever. An activist group
based in Orlando, Fla., planned a similar demonstration Thursday at
one of the main entrances to the Disney World complex where the
Braves train.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we're disappointed with such a light sentence _ a
reduction of what was already a slap on the wrist,'' said Boazman,
who testified at the arbitration hearing. ``Where are we to go as
fans?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The very fact that John Rocker appeals this suggests that he
does not understand the magnitude of his comments. He really
doesn't get it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Coleman, former National League president, said, ``Baseball
must be a socially responsible institution. The arbitrator's ruling
undermines the disciplinary system and sends precisely the wrong
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves general manager John Schuerholz said the ball club is
prepared to take Rocker back. There is no doubt about his talent,
based on the interest from other teams. Also, the Braves would like
to go through a pressure-free spring training and concentrate on
building a championship team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate there will be a problem,'' he said. ``I
think John realizes he needs to mend his place in this team with
his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall Simon, who believes he was the target of Rocker's ``fat
monkey'' comment in the magazine, said he is ready to forgive.
Simon said he hopes Rocker will address the team as a whole, as
well as offer him a personal apology. ``If he comes to me and
apologizes, everything will be all right,'' said Simon. ``He's one
of my teammates. Everybody makes mistakes. . . . He should give me
some respect. I think I deserve an apology so we can move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan, another of Rocker's harshest critics, said the
reliever has to change his ways. ``He has to be more mature dealing
with certain situations and dealing with his teammates,'' Jordan
said. ``He has to learn to control his anger. I think that's a big
reason he said what he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has all the answers, add Glavine. But a chance to talk
about what happened might produce a few make up their mind about
how they feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather deal with it now,'' he said, ``when the outcome
of the games doesn't matter, than have it drop on us right dab in
the middle of the season. We still have to exercise some patience.
It's already getting old, and even if he gets here (Thursday) of
Friday, it's not going to go away for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
