   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   IMF-U.S. (Washington) _ When President Clinton pledged this week
to block a German finance ministry official from assuming the top
post at the International Monetary Fund, in effect vetoing the man
the 15-nation European Union had collectively chosen for the job,
he seemed to risk a diplomatic confrontation across the Atlantic.
What really happened, Clinton administration officials and some
European diplomats say, is that Clinton agreed to confront Germany
in a way that European countries applauded but were unwilling to do
themselves. By Joseph Kahn. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``f'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-REBELS (Dobrosin, Yugoslavia) _ Just across the
boundary line from Kosovo, guarded more visibly now by U.S. troops
in watchtowers, armed Albanians wearing uniforms of a new branch of
the Kosovo Liberation Army are training for a battle the West
doesn't want them to have. Their numbers and leadership are a
mystery, but on this day fewer than 20 men, wearing a mixture of
German and American fatigues, did exercises with their weapons. On
their arms, they wear a cloth badge of red, black and yellow that
looks exactly like that of the supposedly disbanded and disarmed
Kosovo Liberation Army. The only difference is their name: the
Liberation Army of Presevo, Medvedja and Bujanovac, all towns in
Serbia itself, although their populations are largely ethnic
Albanian. By Steven Erlanger. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file)
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT17 and map.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
