<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY BACKERS ARE ALREADY IN MOURNING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Confronted by Bill Bradley's humiliating loss in
Washington state on Tuesday, many Democrats, including some of the
former senator's most prominent supporters, said Wednesday that he
had no chance of snatching his party's presidential nomination from
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And several of Bradley's top aides acknowledged that they had
received phone calls and e-mail messages from friends and
supporters, arguing that he should quit now to avoid the risk of
embarrassment of being shut out on Tuesday, the biggest primary day
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Even the general chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
Edward Rendell, who is supposed to stay neutral, spoke in an
interview as if Bradley had already bowed out. He said ``the reason
he lost'' was that the public was content with the Clinton-Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has not had a single victory, and many of his backers
said they were hard-pressed to cite one upcoming contest where he
could prevail.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were particularly distressed by the results in
Washington because, while it was a popularity contest with no
delegates at stake, Bradley had stumped there for six days, making
it something of a last stand. They noted that polls in states where
there are contests Tuesday, here in Ohio, New York, California and
elsewhere, show that Gore is swamping Bradley in state after state.
</P>
<P>
   ``A miracle still could happen,'' said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.,
one of Bradley's earliest and most vociferous supporters. ``We've
all had friends with cancer and the doctor says, `You have a 5
percent chance and we pray for a miracle.''' But in the next
breath, he said, a win in Washington ``was his only chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning Tuesday in Huntington Beach, Calif., Bradley brushed
aside such talk. ``Mark Twain put it best when he said, `Reports of
my demise are greatly exaggerated,''' he told reporters after
appearing at a health clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley even suggested that he was prepared to continue his
fight beyond March 7. And Bradley flatly denied that any of his
aides had suggested that he should drop out to save face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zero have come to me and said they think I should drop out,''
he said, pinching his thumb and index finger together into an O.
``Nobody has come to me. Nobody has sent a surrogate to me, at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of Bradley's backers are resigned to losing _ and a bit
dispirited. Only a few months ago, their candidate was coming on
strong, drawing national publicity as the politician who might
topple a sitting vice president. He was neck and neck with Gore in
polls in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore's backers are stepping up their calls for the
former senator to leave the race now. The vice president's camp is
eager to turn the focus to November _ and not be obliged to channel
any more resources into the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's best known supporters have not dared to call on him
publicly to quit. Yet they often speak of his candidacy in the past
tense. It is not whether he will withdraw, they say now, but when.
And many Democrats are already debating what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent backer of Bradley, Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., objected to the Washington state strategy,
acknowledging that he had pressed for the campaign to spend more
time in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But he, too, made clear that the campaign's days were numbered.
He pointed out a picture in the newspaper Wednesday of Bradley
looking detached, and chilly, as he campaigned on a ferry to
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that photo in the ferry was pretty dismal,''
Moynihan said. ``But look: no illusions. No regrets. And we'll
stick it out one more week.'' Asked whether there was any hope
Bradley could win, he replied, ``If you don't mind, don't ask me
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And asked, also, about the strategy to emphasize Washington
state, he said: ``It's a rather elusive thing. Bill seems to make
his own decisions. In any event, it did not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey conceded Wednesday that Bradley's best chance was to have
won Washington state so he could have drawn positive publicity
before the battery of contests on Tuesday. He said that at first he
thought the Washington approach ``looked like a dumb move'' but
that he had changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have had a news story this morning that Bradley won,
60-40, or did well,'' he said. ``He would have gotten a bump.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bradley's backers said they feared his public image
could take a beating if he was romped in California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's favorable rating of 21 percent is about even with his
unfavorable rating of 20 percent, according to the latest New York
Times/CBS News Poll, conducted Feb. 12 to 14. But the more he
loses, the more his negatives could increase. In December,
Bradley's favorable rating was 20 percent; his unfavorable rating
was 13 percent, according to a CBS News Poll.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's aides said that after spending more than a year
building toward March 7, quitting before the climactic day would
disappoint and possibly infuriate thousands of volunteers and
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas C. Berman, Bradley's campaign chairman, declined to
discuss the entreaties for his candidate to quit the race, saying
only, ``I hear a lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Berman lamented how difficult it had been for Bradley
to capture attention because of the more dramatic Republican race.
</P>
<P>
   He explained: ``If you're a Democratic voter out there in the
country and you say, `Look, there's all this coverage of the
Republican contest _ I guess the Democratic contest is over.'
That's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell, the Democratic Party chairman, said he had no objection
to Bradley's staying in the race _ for a while. He explained that
the Gore operation had already spent most of its advertising money
for Tuesday's contests. Even if Bradley wins two out of three big
states on Tuesday _ Ohio, New York and California _ Rendell said
that would not be enough to catapult him ahead because the race
turns south the next week. And, he noted, Gore is quite potent in
the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything that would give the senator enough
bounce,'' Rendell said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Reiss, a New York lawyer who was an early fund-raiser for
Bradley, said win or lose, she did not think her candidate should
withdraw before Tuesday. ``I think he feels a commitment to the
people who have worked for him and supported him financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Diekman, a longtime friend and adviser to Bradley from
Atherton, Calif., said she was unhappy about what appeared to be
the inevitable outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a terrific person who ought to be our president; that's
why I'm so discouraged,'' she said. ``We just won't want to see
Bill put through this meat grinder of invisibility or
inevitability.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many Gore loyalists stepped up the drumbeat, saying Bradley's
departure was necessary to heal divisions in the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really stopped being a race almost two or three weeks
ago,'' said Art Torres, chairman of the California Democratic Party
and a Gore backer. ``The sooner Bradley moves toward a consensus,
it obviously creates better unity and less expenditure of funds for
our nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   David Worley, chairman of the Georgia Democratic Party, put it
this way: ``It would be unfortunate if he woke up on Wednesday
morning on the wrong side of the biggest blowout in presidential
history. That's the way it's looking. The best thing would be to
stop now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
