<HEADER>
A3848 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-R-SOCSEC-EARNINGS-1ST     03-01 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SOCSEC-EARNINGS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE LIFTS LIMITS ON EXTRA INCOME FOR MOST SOCIAL SECURITY
RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art note)  (Expands on the earlier story, adds figures, adds 15th and 16th
grafs expanding rationale behind eliminating work restrictions and
adds quotes casting doubt on validity of the argument for
passage.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted 422-0 Wednesday to allow most
Social Security recipients for the first time to earn as much money
as they want without sacrificing any of their retirement benefits,
repealing a Depression-era policy intended to discourage older
people from holding jobs so younger workers would have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous vote was a rare display of bipartisanship, and
reflected a consensus that the earnings limits placed on Social
Security recipients had long since become counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, where there is broad support for the change, plans
to take up a similar measure soon. President Clinton has said he
would sign the legislation, which would not have any long-term
effect on the financial health of the Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, people 65 through 69 years old lose $1 of
their Social Security benefits for every $3 they earn above
$17,000. A 67-year-old man who earned $20,000 last year, for
example, would have lost $1,000 of his Social Security retirement
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings limit, which does not apply to people 70 and above,
is already scheduled to rise to $30,000 in 2002, but the
legislation passed Wednesday by the House would eliminate the limit
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted under the terms of the House bill, the change would
apply retroactively to earnings since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 people 65 or above lost some or all of their
benefits last year because they earned more than the limit,
according to the Social Security Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Those people would benefit immediately from the change, and
other people might decide to remain in or re-enter the work force
because of the opportunity to hold a job without sacrificing any of
their benefits. But the real significance of the shift might emerge
only over the next few decades as the 76 million baby boomers grow
older, creating a vast new pool of retirement-age people more
willing and able than previous generations to continue working.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have long sought repeal of the earnings limit,
saying it amounts to a tax. They were blocked for decades by
Democrats, who at various times have cited objections from labor
unions, the costs and the fact that relatively well-off people
would be the biggest winners.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition from Democrats has melted away over the years as
the population has aged and the economy has grown healthier. The
two parties agreed in 1996 to raise the earnings limit, and Clinton
called last year for the limit to be repealed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsors said repealing the earnings limit would
benefit the entire economy right away by removing a disincentive to
work at a time when the unemployment rate, at 4 percent, is so low
that employers are having trouble filling all the jobs they are
creating.
</P>
<P>
   They said the change also reflected increases in life expectancy
and the fact that more and more people 65 and older continue to
work at least part time by choice or necessity. But they said the
main justification for the change was simple fairness, calling it
unconscionable for the government to deny workers benefits they had
earned over their careers simply because they chose to remain
employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why in the world would we want to discourage any American _
whether they're 17 or 67 _ from working?'' said Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, who is chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are living longer now,'' Archer said. ``Older
Americans can work, they want to work and they shouldn't be
punished by an outdated law if they choose to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found evidence that raising or eliminating the
earnings limit will bring more people into the work force and lead
older people who already have jobs to work more. But there is
disagreement over how much of an effect any change has, with some
economists saying repeal could create a huge new pool of available
labor and others saying the effects would be negligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only a limited amount of evidence on the overall
effect'' on the labor supply from repealing the limit, Kenneth S.
Apfel, the Social Security commissioner, told Congress last month.
But, Apfel said, it was plausible that eliminating the limit would
``lead to a modest increase in work activity.''
</P>
<P>
   But the provisions that the bill would repeal are more complex
than Wednesday's debate on the House floor would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   While Social Security recipients lose some of their benefits in
years in which they earn more than the limit, they get some or all
of the reduction back after age 70, when their benefits are
readjusted to reflect their decision to continue working.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the change would not apply to people who take early
retirement benefits from Social Security, which they can do at 62
at a reduced rate. These people, 62 through 64, would continue to
be subject to a strict earnings limit, losing $1 in benefits for
every $2 in earnings above $10,080 a year. About 230,000 people in
that age category lost all or part of their benefits last year
because their earnings exceeded the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties agreed to leave the earnings limit in place for
early retirees _ effectively encouraging people not to take Social
Security before 65 _ because research has shown that people who
take a reduced Social Security benefits at age 62 are more likely
to end up in poverty than those who work to full retirement age.
The problem strikes particularly hard at widows of men who retired
early and who rely on their late husbands' benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of both parties acknowledged that they found it
uncomfortable to be enacting what amounted to an election-year
benefits increase in Social Security for some people at the same
time that Congress and the Clinton administration are deadlocked
over how to assure the retirement system's long-term solvency.
Without any changes, Social Security is projected to run short of
money to pay benefits starting in 2033.
</P>
<P>
   Under an earlier set of changes made in the 1980s to help
bolster Social Security's financial condition, the age at which
workers can claim full retirement benefits is already increasing
gradually over the next few decades to 67. Many of the proposals to
put Social Security on sounder footing call for further increases
in the retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   Repeal of the earnings limit would cost Social Security $22.7
billion in additional benefit payments over the next decade,
according to the Congressional Budget Office. But it would not have
an effect on the retirement system's financial condition over the
long run, the Social Security Administration said. That is because
the benefits increases would eventually be offset by a reduction in
the deferred benefits that would have been paid to workers starting
at age 70 to make up for the reductions in benefits paid from age
65 through 69.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
