<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3849 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW02-COX     03-01 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush: Pundits, opponents wrongly trying to label him
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Feet propped up in first class aboard his campaign's
charter plane, Gov. George W. Bush on Wednesday recalled what he
was doing during a key moment in what he is convinced is his
one-way path to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asleep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was bedded down for the night in a Marriott near Atlanta
late Tuesday when the networks declared him the winner in
Washington state's primary. The surprising victory completed a
triple sweep, including Virginia and North Dakota wins, that
restored him to front-runner status as next week's Super Tuesday
contests approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Some day, Bush predicted Wednesday as he flew from Atlanta to
St. Louis, the Washington state primary win over Arizona Sen. John
McCain will be recalled as a turning point in what has been a
strange race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Washington state is pretty interesting. I beat Al Gore
and Bill Bradley'' in addition to McCain, he said, referring to
ballots that included candidates of both parties. ``I think you'll
find that to be an interesting state, where all four of us were on
the ballot. ... I won the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   On a smooth flight on what has been a bumpy ride, Bush insisted
Wednesday he has never lost his belief that he will win The Whole
Thing. Throughout the wins and losses, and the rumors that he was
about to scrap longtime friend and adviser Karl Rove, Bush remained
positive that America wants him to move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir,'' he said, turning back from a glance out the window.
``I'm convinced I'll be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, working hard to avoid the kind of over-confidence that has
knocked off more than one front-runner, believes next week's Super
Tuesday contests might effectively end the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll have the 1,037 delegates,'' he said,
overcalculating by three the number needed to clinch the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But he believes there is a chance that results in the 13
contests could snuff out McCain's insurgent candidacy. And positive
signs pointing that direction continue to pop up unexpectedly _
including a statement issued Wednesday by Gary Bauer repudiating
McCain's verbal assault this week on Jerry Falwell and Pat
Robertson, icons of the Christian conservative leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must in the strongest possible terms repudiate Senator
McCain's unwarranted, ill-advised and divisive attacks on certain
religious leaders,'' said Bauer, who had endorsed McCain after he
dropped out of the GOP presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wild ride so far has taken him to places he did not
expect to go. The biggest unanticipated outcome is that he winds up
going one-on-one with McCain, who has stolen Bush's thunder as a
big-tent candidate drawing new voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign's infancy, Bush advisers thought he'd be in a
battle against a candidate coming from the right. Now, Bush is
their candidate of choice.
</P>
<P>
   But he insists he hasn't changed. Bush, who gives the same stump
speech every day, over and over, complained that ``the punditry''
is positioning him as some kind of right-wing candidate he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The filter is filtering out what I say on a daily basis, which
is the exact same compassionate conservative agenda I said in Iowa,
I said in South Carolina, I said in Washington state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not believe McCain's attempts to glue him to religious
right leaders such as Robertson and Falwell will be a
general-election hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's seen this game before.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember the '94 campaign, when Ann Richards tried to do
the same thing,'' he said. ``They can try it again in year 2000. I
am who I am, the people know that. ... People are trying to brand
me one way, and on the other hand John McCain is trying to call me
an anti-Catholic bigot. I got fire coming from all sides. But
eventually the people decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, at a news conference in Duluth, Ga., Bush
made it clear that his relationship with McCain has changed.
Earlier in the campaign, he went out of his way to note that he and
the senator were friends.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush twice declined to identify McCain as a
friend. The governor continues to complain daily about McCain
campaign phone calls reminding voters that Bush spoke at Bob Jones
University, a fundamentalist school with anti-Catholic biases.
McCain's campaign has criticized Bush for not condemning the
university's controversial positions during Bush's speech there.
</P>
<P>
   Offered a second chance to say whether he considers McCain a
friend, Bush said, ``I know what the question was. The answer was,
I try not to take things personally in politics, and I will, of
course, assess things once the campaign's ended. But calling
somebody an anti-Catholic bigot is beyond the reach.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
