<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3854 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-REEVES-COL-WETTEL     03-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COL-WETTELAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T CLOSE OUT THIS CLOSER YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The idea was to begin the weaning process
this spring. Somehow, we had to figure out how to say goodbye to
John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a foregone conclusion for a while now that the
Rangers' closer would be gone after this season when his four-year
contract expires. He is 33, and the Rangers would appear to have a
variety of less expensive closer-in-waiting options available among
Tim Crabtree, Jeff Zimmerman and newly acquired Francisco Cordero.
</P>
<P>
   The economic realities of the game alone _ teams are constantly
looking for ways to save money _ provided ample reason to believe
this would be Wetteland's final spring as a Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   The last roundup.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe not. The situation has changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't made the \RJuan Gonzalez\S trade,'' general
manager Doug Melvin said yesterday, ``and if we had re-signed
\RAaron\S Sele and \RTodd\S Zeile, then we might have had no choice
but to let him go.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now we have some flexibility and some options. It's
definitely not out of the question that we would try and bring him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't hurt Wetteland's case for returning that he has come
to camp this spring in perhaps the best condition he has ever been
in as a major-leaguer, which could be the prelude to a monster
season. That's indeed something to contemplate, considering he
produced 43 saves last year despite coming off winter elbow surgery
and a distracting ankle injury that hampered him for much of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In his three seasons as a Rangers closer he has chalked up 31,
42 and 43 saves. He is just four saves away from becoming only the
12th reliever in baseball history to register 300 saves. He was
recently honored as the Rolaids Reliever of the Decade.
</P>
<P>
   But what Wetteland brings to the Rangers' bullpen can't be
measured in mere numbers or awards. He is the unchallenged leader
of a relief corps that has become arguably the team's strongest
single area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned more from Wetteland in the last six months than I
had my whole life,'' said Zimmerman, the Rangers' rookie sensation
in 1999. ``He taught me how to be a professional, how to prepare
myself, how to react to adversity, how to react to success. He's a
great teammate and a great role model, all rolled up into one.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of teammates willing and able to step up and
throw accolades at Wetteland, which is good, because he has
absolutely no interest in talking about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be the best team guy I've ever been around,'' bullpen
coach Larry Hardy said. ``His first priority is always what's best
for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the only way Wetteland knows how to operate. I've never
seen anyone in sports who more genuinely cares about his teammates,especially his fellow relievers.
</P>
<P>
   `` I was handed the ball at 25 years old in Montreal and told
`You're our closer,' and I had done nothing to prove myself in the
majors,'' Wetteland said. ``I've never forgotten that. These guys,
every one of them, have an awesome attitude and an awesome work
ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand that they're a cog in the machine; they
understand what they do in helping each other. They've learned that
iron sharpens iron.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Wetteland's way of saying that the tougher you are, the
tougher you get.
</P>
<P>
   ``In helping someone else, I get helped myself,'' he said. ``No
one is above learning, and, if you don't think so, you're a liar,
because everyone needs humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boz \Rpitching coach Dick Bosman\S uses the same quote to open
every spring. He gathers everyone together and starts out by
saying, `It's what you learn after you know it all that's
important.' I learn something new every day.''
</P>
<P>
   What Wetteland isn't into is predicting the future. That, he
contends, is a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pointless to spend one second thinking about tomorrow,''
Wetteland said. ``Tomorrow hasn't been given to me yet. If I take
care of today, tomorrow will take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I be a Ranger? I don't know. Will I be a Brewer? I don't
know. Will I even be playing at all? I don't know. Nothing is
automatic. What I need to do here, starting the first day of
spring, is work diligently at what I do, to help this team to the
capacity that I'm supposed to, to help develop others in such a way
that somebody in this group could take over my job and the Texas
Rangers would have smooth sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's truly just as unselfish as he sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more concerned with everybody as a team than he is with
himself,'' Hardy said. ``He leads by example, but he also pushes
each one of \Rthe other relievers\S to get better at what they do.
Pretty soon it becomes part of a perpetual-motion machine, where
they're not just feeding off him but off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Wetteland's selfless approach may have done more
than anything else to pave the way for his departure. It's not a
matter any more of whether the Rangers can live without him,
because everything he does builds toward that day.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is much more simple: Why would they want to?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
