<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3856 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-FASTBALLS     03-01 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-FASTBALLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR RANGERS RELIEVERS CAN BLOW FASTBALLS PAST THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Tim Crabtree vs. Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' hard-throwing right-hander still smiles and gets
excited when asked about their confrontation last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Griffey was leading off the inning, and it was a one-run
game,'' Crabtree said. ``He fouled off a couple of pitches and
worked the count full. I said, all right, let's see who's better. I
threw a four-seam fastball down the center of the plate but up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw it but couldn't catch up to it. He swung and missed. It
was a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   What Griffey saw was heat. Pure heat. White-lightning heat.
</P>
<P>
   It's also something American League hitters should see in
torrents this season when facing the Rangers' bullpen. The Rangers
have four right-handed pitchers _ John Wetteland, Francisco
Cordero, Jeff Zimmerman and Tim Crabtree _ who collectively might
throw harder than any other foursome in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to watch,'' Wetteland said. ``Especially the
three-strikes blow away up in the strike zone, the hitter totally
overmatched. Back when I used to throw really hard, it was not
enough to strike a guy out. You needed to make them look ridiculous
so it would be fresh in their minds. That goes a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had some impressive heat in their bullpen last year,
but they turned the thermostat up a notch this off-season when they
acquired Cordero from the Detroit Tigers in the Juan Gonzalez
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one guy who can really throw it, it would be
Cordero,'' Wetteland said. ``His ball has tremendous velocity. It
explodes. It looks like it defies gravity with the way it rises.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cordero with a smile, ``I love to throw hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates called Sparky Anderson on Tuesday to
congratulate him on being elected to the Hall of Fame and... ``All
Sparky could talk about was Cordero this and Cordero that, how
great he could be,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Cordero, if he makes the team out of spring training, could
surpass Crabtree as the hardest thrower in the Rangers' bullpen.
Both regularly hit 97-98 mph with an occasional 100 mph pitch mixed
in.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, 33, admits he's no longer in that class. Those who
clocked him last year say he was topping out at a mere 95-96 mph.
But Rangers scout Bill Wood, after seeing Wetteland this spring,
said, ``As good as he looks, he might surprise people again.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman is the ``junk-baller'' of the bunch, coming in at
93-95 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I may have to start throwing a split-finger \Rfastball\S
to get by,'' Zimmerman joked.
</P>
<P>
   Oates admires a hard thrower as much as anybody but quickly and
sternly pointed out that 100 mph fastballs won't do much good
without location and movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are major-league pitchers and minor-league throwers,''
Oates said. ``You can throw 120 mph, but it's not going to do you
any good if you can't control that. Rafael Palmeiro, Mark McGwire,
Sammy Sosa, Tim Salmon, Ken Griffey ... You can't throw it too hard
to them. You've still got to be able to pitch at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Party pooper.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree said pitchers with heat can take two approaches: the
``bull rush'' and the ``high cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bull rush is you try to get ahead of the hitter, keep the
fastball down, try to hit the corners,'' Crabtree said. ``Once you
get ahead of the hitters, then you bring the high cheese. You say
to the batter: `Let's go. Let's see who's better.' Then you let it
fly. You put it at a hitter's chest, where it looks good, but
there's no way he can catch up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what 40,000 paying customers love to see, even if there
was no way Wetteland and Zimmerman could have made the All-Star
Game last year without their hellacious breaking pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throwing hard definitely pumps you up,'' Zimmerman said. ``But
we don't want to look at ourselves as one-dimensional pitchers just
throwing it as hard as we can. John's the perfect example. He's got
a great fastball, but he throws four quality pitches. He can fool
you as well as flat-out blow you away.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way wins ballgames, which is Oates' only goal. But they
don't put those radar-gun readings on ballpark scoreboards just to
show the difference between a changeup and a curveball.
</P>
<P>
   As Crabtree said: ``There's nothing more exciting than say, a
one-run ballgame, the opposing team has a power hitter up, and we
have a power pitcher out there on the mound. It's one of those
confrontations that's fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   It's coming to a Ballpark near you.  &LR; tagtop:T.R. Sullivan, (817)
390-7760
\Nsubheds:High heat Rangers scouts Bill Wood and Rudy Terrasas rank
the top 10 hardest-throwing relievers in baseball: Player, team
Normal fastball 1. Billy Wagner, Astros 100 mph 2. Bill Koch, Blue
Jays 100 mph 3. Matt Anderson, Tigers 99 mph 4. Robb Nen, Giants 98
mph 5. Troy Percival, Angels 98 mph 6. Matt Mantei, Diamondbacks 98
mph 7. Paul Shuey, Indians 98 mph 8. Tim Crabtree, Rangers 97 mph
9. John Rocker, Braves 97 mph 10. Roberto Hernandez, Devil Rays 97
mph
Sharon M. Steinman Rangers closer John Wetteland says: ``Back when
I used to throw really hard, it was not enough to strike a guy out.
You needed to make them look ridiculous so it would be fresh in
their minds.''
nn
</P>
