<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology Shares Propel Nasdaq to Yet Another High
</P>
<P>
   Soaring telecommunications and technology stocks pushed the
Nasdaq composite index further into record territory. The Nasdaq
rose 87.39 points, to 4,784.08, topping the closing record of
4,696.69 it set Tuesday. The Dow Jones industrial average added
9.62 points, to 10,137.93. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
climbed 12.77 points, to 1,379.19.
</P>
<P>
   Many Disapprove of IMF Nominee
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton pledged to block the appointment of Caio
Koch-Weser as head the International Monetary Fund, he seemed to
risk a diplomatic confrontation across the Atlantic. But he
actually was voicing objections from several European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Spinning Off Three Divisions
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies said that it would spin off three units into
a company that will have about $8 billion in revenue and will sell
business telephone systems, wire cabling and office network
systems. The news raised the price of shares in Lucent by $8.52, or
15 percent, to $68.125. While the new company will focus on the
corporate networking market, Lucent will concentrate on equipment
and services for telecommunications providers.
</P>
<P>
   Auto Sales Near Monthly Record
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. auto industry is poised to have its second best month
ever for sales after General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler
reported higher vehicle sales for February. The seasonally adjusted
annual selling rate is expected to be about 19 million cars and
light trucks when the few remaining companies report sales
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco Responds to the FTC
</P>
<P>
   With wide gaps remaining in settlement talks, BP Amoco and ARCO
accused the Federal Trade Commission of misinterpreting antitrust
law in its effort to block the companies from completing their $30
billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Halting Deceptive Telephone Ads
</P>
<P>
   After receiving thousands of consumer complaints about
dial-around long-distance services, the federal government
announced that it would begin to crack down on what two agencies
described as the widespread deception in the way such services have
been promoted. ``They aggressively market the cheapest rates, but
they don't tell you what's in the fine print,'' said William
Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, which
issued guidelines with the Federal Trade Commission to make
advertising more complete.
</P>
<P>
   Two Book Clubs Form Partnership
</P>
<P>
   The Book-of-the-Month Club and the Literary Guild agreed to form
an alliance in which the traditional book clubs will evolve into
interactive digital clubs with some of the same features of an
online bookseller.
</P>
<P>
   Europe Collecting Some Sales Taxes
</P>
<P>
   Testing the ability to enforce national tax laws in cyberspace,
the European Commission is planning to collect sales taxes on music
and software delivered online.
</P>
<P>
   Objections to High Prices for Oil
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson faced sharp questions over the
high price of oil products as legislators heaped scorn on his
cautious forecast that oil-exporting countries would increase
production later this month and reverse a steep climb in fuel
costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
