<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES     03-01 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CAMPAIGN TRAIL, GORE IS THE STEALTH CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT1 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nothing captures Vice President Al Gore's
relationship with his traveling press corps _ and the state of mind
of the Gore campaign _ like the scene here Tuesday night, when Gore
was winning a soaring victory over his all-but-vanquished rival,
Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was sequestered in a hotel room here to watch the returns
from Washington state. He had planned no public events, but was
going to make a conference call to supporters in Seattle. The only
access that reporters would have would be when they were escorted
to his suite to watch him make the call.
</P>
<P>
   When the time for the conference call came, there was no escort
in sight. So the reporters pulled out their cell phones and dialed
the 800 phone number to connect into the call themselves. The
telephone operator said the call would be placed in just a few
moments. As it turned out, the wait dragged on for more than half
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore finally made his conference call, reporters were in
hotel elevators, where they had no cell-phone access.
</P>
<P>
   For all that has been made of Sen. John McCain's accessibility
during this campaign season and how the Arizona Republican has used
his ``Straight Talk Express'' bus to hold unending conversations
with his traveling press entourage, Gore's campaign operation
provides a vivid counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters covering the vice president can go for days without
seeing him. Because many are consigned to a press charter while
Gore flies in Air Force Two, they can sometimes be in a different
city.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the vice president has become an extremely
disciplined candidate, saying just what he wants to say and going
no further.
</P>
<P>
   While this might rankle reporters, it has proved a successful
strategy. He is undefeated so far in the primaries, and has the
Democratic presidential nomination within his grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has little reason to change to an unscripted format and its
obvious pitfalls, especially while the Republicans are getting
plenty of publicity chewing each other up. Moreover, he wants to
avoid being drawn into discussions of political tactics and
strategy with national reporters. Surveys show that voters are
bored by campaigns about campaigns, and that such chatter
reinforces a negative image of candidates as calculating
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the vice president remains unusually distant from his
traveling press corps, especially for a former journalist.
</P>
<P>
   He was not always this way. As recently as a year ago, when he
was traveling with just a few reporters and was not so much in the
spotlight, he was more willing to engage in spontaneous
conversation. But over time, he made blunders _ claiming a central
role in the creation of the Internet, for example _ that got him
publicity he did not want.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, his advisers told him that the trappings of
the vice presidency made him seem too imperious, and he went
through a very public transition in which he tried to relate to
voters in a more human way, wearing casual clothes and holding open
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Gore was warming up to voters, he was clamming up to
the press. The campaign wanted to ensure that he was delivering
only the rehearsed message of the day, not random comments that
were ``off-message.''
</P>
<P>
   To see just how focused Gore has become on this task, go back to
the scene in the hotel lobby here on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The escort finally arrived and the traveling horde of perhaps
two dozen journalists took the elevator to the vice president's
suite. When everyone was assembled, Gore said nothing _ this was
supposed to be a ``photo op'' only _ until a reporter asked, ``How
you feeling?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful to the people of Washington state because, based
on the projections, it looks like a big win, but I'm not taking
anything for granted,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He was then asked what message he had for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, well, I don't, uh, have any, uh, message, uh, for, uh, for
Senator Bradley,'' he responded slowly. ``Uh, I, I, my message is
for the, the voters of the country. Uh, I ask for their support.
I'm not taking a single vote for, for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Another question came. When would it be time for him to start
unifying the Democratic Party?
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Gore aides started trying to remove reporters
from the room. Gore answered, ``I, I am not taking a single vote
for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Much cross-talk ensued as the aides continued trying to hustle
reporters out and Gore asserted, with the same rote-like repetition
with which he famously said that there was ``no controlling legal
authority'' over his fund-raising techniques, that he was not
taking a single vote for granted. This was an important message to
convey to voters in later primaries whose support Gore needs to
guarantee him the nomination, but it provided no grist for the
journalists, which was exactly the point.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To a reporter's final plea for a news conference _ what is
called a ``press avail'' _ Gore cupped his ear in parody of
President Ronald Reagan, who pretended to want to hear reporters'
questions as he ducked under a noisy helicopter blade. Lacking a
helicopter, Gore pointed to the television. ``Oh, look,'' he said,
cranking up the volume and calling out to the last reporter being
yanked from the room, ``Thanks for coming to this press avail!''
</P>
<P>
   Gore conducted his last ``press avail'' of any significance (for
perhaps 20 minutes) on Jan. 19 in New Hampshire. A month later,
when reporters began writing news articles mentioning that the
campaign was coming up on the one-month anniversary of no news
conference, he held a quick news conference on Feb. 19 in
Springfield, Mass., from which most of the regular traveling press
corps was absent. That was also the day the Republican primary in
South Carolina completely dominated the political news.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has become adept at limiting the national
media's access and making the candidate appear accessible through
the local news media. He is a frequent guest on drive-time radio,
and he pays for satellite hookups to distant cities.
</P>
<P>
   What the listener or viewer often does not know, however, is
that by now the Gore campaign _ and anyone who listens to a
succession of these interviews _ can predict the questions in
advance. And Gore has a predictable batch of answers.
</P>
<P>
   Stock question: Will your relationship with President Clinton
hurt your candidacy? Gore's stock answer: Clinton is his friend; he
made a mistake; he has done good things for the country, and Gore
has to run on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Would you rather run against John McCain or George W.
Bush? Answer: ``Whichever one loses.''
</P>
<P>
   Question: Who will you pick as your vice president? Answer:
``I'm not letting myself think openly about it because I haven't
won the nomination yet.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The vice president's visit, not what he says, is big
news in most media markets. The local press usually starts
trumpeting the visit two or three days in advance, covers it live
while Gore is there, and provides another day or two of local
reaction (almost always positive) after he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   So legendary has Gore's unavailability become that Bradley
called up reporters traveling on Gore's bus and reached them by
cell phone. As he said to one: ``I wanted to give you the chance to
speak to a presidential candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
