<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3860 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      03-01 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
CONFIDENT BUSH CRITICIZES GORE IN WAKE OF PRIMARY WINS OVER McCAIN 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULUTH, Ga. _ Presidential hopeful George W. Bush sounded like a
general election candidate Wednesday as he repeatedly criticized
Vice President Al Gore, while rival John McCain, bruised from a
triple loss in Tuesday's primaries, wagered his future on the
upcoming California primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also revealed that his bitter and yet
unfinished primary fight with McCain may have caused some
long-lasting wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Having restored his front-runner status with victories Tuesday
in North Dakota, Virginia and Washington state, Bush displayed a
renewed self-confidence speaking to about 800 supporters at the
Gwinnett County Civic Center. Bush criticized Gore on issues such
as education reform, tax cuts and appointments to the U.S. Supreme
Court, and never named McCain during his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also took the lead in the race to collect the delegates who
will determine the party's nominee at the national convention this
summer. Bush now has 170 delegates to McCain's 100.
</P>
<P>
   McCain stepped up his appeal for support among California voters
Wednesday as he sought to dispel perceptions that his campaign for
the presidency may be sputtering to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   At rallies in Southern California, McCain acknowledged that the
success of his ``reform crusade'' may hinge on the outcome of
Tuesday's California primary, where 162 Republican delegates are at
stake. More than a dozen states also vote that Super Tuesday in
what will be the biggest collection of primaries in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is a microcosm of America,'' the senator told a
cheering crowd in Riverside. ``What you do next Tuesday will have
an incredible impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Super Tuesday states, polls show McCain ahead in
Massachusetts, tied with Bush in New York and trailing in others.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times poll of California voters released Wednesday
shows Bush ahead of McCain among GOP voters by 21 percent. Bush
also leads McCain by 6 percent among voters in general, including
independents and Democrats who plan to vote in the GOP race even if
it doesn't count toward the delegate prize.
</P>
<P>
   The two men debate with third-place rival Alan Keyes Thursday
night in Los Angeles. But before that serious event, Bush and
McCain each got to compete by wisecracking for ratings, if not
votes, with appearances on the late-night talk shows Wednesday.
Bush appeared on CBS's ``The Late Show with David Letterman,''
while McCain was a guest on NBC's ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno.``
</P>
<P>
   Although the senator sounded optimistic about his chances in
California, his advisers, for the first time since his big win over
Bush in the New Hampshire primary, did not.
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, McCain's chief political adviser, told reporters
that without California's delegates, there was no way McCain would
be able ``to make the math work out'' without at least sweeping the
northeastern primary states.
</P>
<P>
   Even before all the results were in in Washington state Tuesday,
McCain was trying to characterize his attempt at the White House as
something other than a quest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our mission is to get people involved ... we've had some
success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But later, he noted that if he continued to win the popular vote
but lose among Republicans, he would cause a stir within the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a split decision, that's going to be a debate
that's taking place within the Republican Party,'' McCain told
reporters.``Do they want somebody who won the majority or do they
want somebody who only won Republican votes?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush _ who earlier in the campaign repeatedly referred to McCain
as ``my friend'' _ afterward refused to say whether the Arizona
senator was still. As soon as the Republican campaign became a
horserace after McCain swamped Bush in New Hampshire, the two have
waged an intensely negative campaign that peaked when McCain linked
Bush to Southern fundamentalists who hold anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the question was,'' Bush said the second time he
was asked about his friendship with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to take things personally in politics, and I'll of
course assess things once the campaign ends, but calling somebody
an anti-Catholic bigot is beyond the reach,'' Bush said. ``I don't
accept that kind of campaigning, and I'm not going to tolerate that
kind of campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   At St. Louis University, a Jesuit school, Bush rallied amid
signs that read, ``Catholics for Bush,'' and said: ``I don't
appreciate the politics that's happening in America today using
religion as a race card.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain seemed ready to put the personal politics aside, telling
a town hall meeting: ``Look, Governor Bush is a good man from a
good family, and he would make a good president of the United
States. But I would make a better president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina and Michigan earlier this month and in
Tuesday's primaries in Virginia and Washington state, McCain's
campaign called Catholic voters to criticize Bush for speaking at
Bob Jones University in South Carolina, a school whose founder
expressed anti-Catholic sentiments. Bush has since apologized to
Catholics for not denouncing the schools' anti-Catholic and racist
sentiments while speaking there.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted McCain compared evangelists Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell to Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan in his pivotal
Virginia Beach speech on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louis Farrakhan preaches hate. Louis Farrakhan is a hateful
person who has preached an anti-Semitic message which is ugly,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain criticized Bush for a Jan. 30 appearance on Fox News
Sunday in which Bush said the Nation of Islam would be eligible for
federal funds under Bush's proposal to turn more government social
service programs over to faith-based organizations. Bush's
statement was denounced by the National Jewish Democratic Council.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Wednesday he was answering a question about the Muslim
faith, not the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how we can allow public dollars to fund programs
where spite and hate are in the core of the message,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his contest with McCain has allowed him to consolidate
the Republican base before the general election. Bush has been
winning among core Republicans, but McCain scored victories in New
Hampshire and Michigan with the help of independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have a candidate who can bring people
together, who can consolidate, not a candidate who has divided
people up. That's really the difference right now where we're
headed in this primary,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm the nominee, I'll begin to reach out to Democrats and
independents who heretofore have not participated in our
primaries,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain hardened his attack Wednesday on Bush's positions by
challenging his new campaign finance proposal as a ``joke'' because
it does not set strict limits on contributions. He also laughed at
Bush's assertion that he is a ``reformer with results,'' noting
that the governor has increased spending in Texas and has not
identified where he would cut wasteful spending or how he would
preserve Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   While continuing his battle with McCain in news conferences,
Bush's focus before his supporters was on Gore, the front-runner
for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized Gore as backing education programs that
emphasized federal funding for facility construction over improving
results, for declining to support Bush's $483 billion tax cut plan
and over judicial appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental difference between me and Al Gore is who are
we going to put on the bench,'' Bush said. ``Appointments to the
Supreme Court will have a lasting effect on the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Gore will put jurists on the court who will legislate,
while he promised to put on ``strict constructionists.'' Bush
afterward declined to say whether a strict constructionist judge
would uphold the controversial Roe vs. Wade decision abortion
rights decision as standing precedent or overturn it as a
constitutional ``stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A strict constructionist judge is one who strictly interprets
the constitution,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
