<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-DAY02-COX     03-01 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DAY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush jaunty in Georgia
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A confident George W. Bush predicted Wednesday _ the
day after he drubbed John McCain in two primaries and a caucus _
that not only will he eliminate his pesky Republican opponent
within a few weeks, but he also fully expects to become the next
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir,'' Bush said quietly Wednesday as he flew to St.
Louis after an overnight stay in Atlanta. ``I'm convinced I'll be
president.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain isn't looking quite that far. He focused on next week's
do-or-die Super Tuesday contests in 13 states. This week's stinging
losses in Virginia, Washington state and North Dakota highlighted
McCain's underdog status, a position he sought to exploit Wednesday
in delegate-rich California, Super Tuesday's biggest prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``The establishment is intent on breaking me,'' he told a crowd
in Riverside, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sought to downplay any sense of Bush's possible
inevitability as the party's nominee, saying he has learned at
least one lesson in this up-and-down primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I can assure you about the election next
Tuesday, it will not be what you predict,'' McCain said at a news
conference after the Riverside town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, in an interview with Cox Newspapers aboard his
campaign jet, said he may have guaranteed his nomination with the
victory in Washington state. Some day, he said, that primary will
be recalled as a pivotal moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of the three states yesterday were open primaries. I think
Washington state is pretty interesting. I beat Al Gore and Bill
Bradley,'' he said, referring to ballots that also included
candidates of the Democratic Party. ``I think you'll find that to
be an interesting state where all four of us were on the ballot _
independents, Democrats, crossovers here, crossovers there. I won
the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls show Bush won Tuesday by relying on a solid
foundation of Republican voters who gave him a solid victory in
South Carolina less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's inability to draw Republican votes in Washington stood
as the most troubling aspect of his defeat. But other problems
dogged him Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator's attack Monday on fundamentalist Christian
leaders Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell as ``agents of
intolerance'' was intended to reinforce McCain's argument that he
can attract not only Democratic and independent voters, but also
moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the speech seems to have rallied conservatives and some
previously undecided voters to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was gaining some support here (in California) because he's
so anti-establishment, but now people are going to vote for Bush,
not because they support him, but because of the perceived bigotry
and divisiveness in McCain's statement,'' said Steve Frank,
president of the National Federation of Republican Assemblies, a
union of conservatives within the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash grew Wednesday with conservative activist Gary
Bauer urging McCain to apologize. Bauer endorsed McCain after
dropping out of the Republican presidential race last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must in the strongest possible terms repudiate Senator
McCain's unwarranted, ill-advised and divisive attacks on certain
religious leaders,'' Bauer said in a statement. ``Senator McCain
must not allow his personal differences with any individual to
cloud his judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters his comments were aimed at Falwell and
Robertson, not religious conservatives as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain refused to back away from his description of Bush as
a ``Pat Robertson Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``I talked to Gary and I hope we can work things
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer criticized McCain's comparison of Robertson and Falwell
with the Rev. Al Sharpton and Nation of Islam leader Louis
Farrakhan. He also criticized McCain's later statement, on the
campaign bus, that he was trying to battle ``the forces of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain tried to downplay those comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a half-hearted attempt at humor,'' he told reporters.
``I did not say and did not mean to say they are evil. (But) They
are bad for our party. ``
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who campaigned in St. Louis on his way to California, said
he agreed with Bauer that McCain's comparison with Farrakhan was
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louis Farrakhan preaches hate,'' Bush said. ``Louis Farrakhan
is a hateful person who has preached an anti-Semitic message which
is ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he does not believe McCain's attempts to glue him to
Robertson and Falwell will be a general-election issue. Others have
tried that approach _ and failed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can try it again in year 2000,'' Bush said. ``I am who I
am, the people know that. People are trying to brand me one way and
on the other hand John McCain is trying to call me an anti-Catholic
bigot. I got fire coming from all sides. But eventually the people
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he left Georgia, Bush made it clear at a news conference
in Duluth that his relationship with McCain has changed. Earlier in
the campaign, he went out of his way to note that he and the
senator were friends. On Wednesday, Bush twice declined to identify
McCain as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush continues to complain daily about the McCain campaign's
phone calls reminding voters Bush spoke at Bob Jones University, a
South Carolina fundamentalist school that has expressed
anti-Catholic biases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgive people,'' Bush said, ``but this kind of campaigning
is not necessary in his campaign and he ought to be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Offered a second chance to say whether he considers McCain a
friend, Bush said, ``I know what the question was. The answer was I
try not to take things personally in politics and I will, of
course, assess things once the campaign's ended. But calling
somebody an anti-Catholic bigot is beyond the reach.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
