<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   A WINNING ADVANTAGE: There is more than one winner and one loser
at each turning of the primary circuit. In Virginia, the big winner
beyond Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was former Gov. George Allen,
who is already running fast and hard for the Senate seat held by
Charles S. Robb, a Democrat. Allen was co-chairman of the Bush
drive, and he scored in his own behalf in delivering a big party
vote to the Bush victory on Tuesday. He compounded his advantage in
the final heavy days when he was one of the chief spokesmen for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Francis X. Clines
</P>
<P>
   COSTLY CRITICISM: When Bob Offutt ran for the Texas State Board
of Education in 1996 with the backing of the state's Republican
establishment, he raised $20,000 from a single political action
committee alone. In this year's race he has raised a total of only
$2,500, including a $2,000 loan from himself, while his leading
opponent in the Republican primary on March 14 has raised more than
$25,000. The difference? In between, Offutt traveled to New
Hampshire to criticize Gov. George W. Bush's education policy and
endorse Steve Forbes. ``To put it in a nutshell, you don't tug on
Superman's cape,'' Mona Taylor, a political consultant, told The
Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Ross E. Milloy
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE BACKS INTERNET VOTING: A federal judge ruled on Tuesday
that Arizona Democrats would be allowed to vote on the Internet in
their primary on March 11, despite a lawsuit that would block
online voting on the ground that it could discriminate against
minorities. But Judge Paul G. Rosenblatt of federal District Court
in Phoenix said the court might have to set aside the election if
the numbers showed disproportionate participation by whites with
Internet access, according to a transcript of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Rebecca Fairley Raney
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARY PLANS FOR 2004: This year's presidential primary
calendar is not even half over, but Democratic and Republican
leaders in the South are already arguing that it should be
reconfigured for 2004. Sen. Richard C. Shelby, R-Ala., said this
week that his state should hold its 2004 primary between the early
primaries in New Hampshire and South Carolina. Alabama will not
vote until June 6 this year, presumably well after both parties'
contests have been settled. At a hearing in Atlanta on Saturday,
Georgia Democratic leaders told national party officials that at
least one Southern primary should have an earlier date, and thus a
more influential role, in the 2004 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Kevin Sack
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   MISSOURI TRADE-OFF: Challenged by his opponent to return an
honorary degree from Bob Jones University in South Carolina, Sen.
John Ashcroft, R-Mo., has said he will return the degree if his
Democratic opponent, Gov. Mel Carnahan, returns money he has
received from groups that support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be glad to return this honorary degree, and all my
honorary degrees,'' Ashcroft said in a statement, ``if my opponent
will send back his political money from special interests that
support partial-birth abortion.'' He called Carnahan's veto of a
bill banning the late-term procedure that opponents call
partial-birth abortion the ``most offensive insult to Catholic
voters in modern Missouri history.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Dirk Johnson
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND
</P>
<P>
   NEW VERMONT POLL: Their state may be dwarfed by New York and
California, but Vermonters also vote on Tuesday. A poll released
Wednesday indicated that they would favor Sen. John McCain of
Arizona and Vice President Al Gore. The Mason-Dixon Polling and
Research Inc. poll of likely voters found that among Republicans,
53 percent supported McCain and 34 percent backed Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas. Among Democrats, 56 percent supported Gore and 35
percent backed Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   The poll had a margin of sampling error of 4 to 6 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Carey Goldberg
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE: Republicans, Los Angeles, 9 p.m. ET, live on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: New York City, Hartford and Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: New York City and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Los Angeles.
</P>
