<HEADER>
A3863 &Cx1f; tth-z
r w BC-ASBESTOS-SPI &LR;      03-01 1522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTANA ASBESTOSIS VICTIMS TELL THEIR STORIES TO LEGISLATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four quiet people from Libby, Mont., came here this
week to show lawmakers what it's like to be dying of asbestosis.
They found themselves watching a legislative tornado of
name-calling, dueling experts and frenzied lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just working stiffs from Libby, but 300 or 400 people in
our tiny town have got the disease and the legislation that's
supposed to help us out won't do a damn thing for almost any of
them, including those that are close to dying,'' says Les
Skramstad, a vermiculite miner who worked at the W.R. Grace mine
outside Libby.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation the Montanans came to oppose is the Fairness in
Asbestos Compensation Act. It is a highly contentious package of
laws promoted, for the most part, by GAF Corp., W.R. Grace and
others in the asbestos industry. For almost three years this bill
and earlier versions have been pushed hard, mostly by Republicans
on the Senate Commerce and the House Judiciary committees.
</P>
<P>
   Like much legislation, the verbiage sounds noble and beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsors insist it will end the logjam of hundreds of
thousands of victims waiting for their day in court and prevent
personal injury lawyers from pocketing large chunks of the
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, mostly unions, victim's groups, consumer
coalitions and the Association of Trial Lawyers of America, say it
should be called the ``Asbestos Industry Relief Act,'' since it
will prevent thousands of terminally ill victims from filing suit
for holding the industry accountable for the disease they
contracted.
</P>
<P>
   The battle is getting sloppy, even by Washington standards.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that more than $6 million has been spent in
lobbying by both sides and the conflict has grown far beyond
Republicans snarling at Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Industry lawyers and attorneys for the victims are denouncing
each other as ambulance-chasing hacks delaying the process to
increase their fees.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, some of them industry consultants, developed the
medical screening criteria for the law. But other physicians,
including some nationally recognized pulmonary and cancer
specialists _ those who traditionally treat the patients _ call the
proposed standards ``antiquated,'' ``exclusionary'' and
``barbaric.''
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated by public-interest groups that over the past 25
years settlements have been made in more than a half-million
asbestos cases and another 450,000 may be pending.
</P>
<P>
   Since the EPA's ban on asbestos mining and the manufacture and
sale of asbestos-containing products was overturned in 1991 after
an industry-sponsored lawsuit, several government agencies fear
that a new generation of victims may be created.
</P>
<P>
   As with many legislative debates, those voting on the
compensation bills must deal with facts, statistics, history and
interpretation provided, to some degree by committee staff, but,
for the most part, by lobbyists on both sides. For example, the
language for the bill originally presented to House Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) was written by a Harvard law
school professor working with an asbestos industry-funded group.
</P>
<P>
   Most members of Congress admit it's often difficult to put a
face on the people affected by legislation being debated.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday and Wednesday, the group from Libby showed any committee
member who was willing to meet with them precisely who will be
impacted by the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Skramstad, 63, was diagnosed with asbestosis six years ago. His
wife, Norita, and two of their three children also have the
disease, having been contaminated with asbestos dust on his work
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Priest is 72 and was diagnosed with asbestosis last year,
17 years after her husband Virgil, died from it. She dragged a
wheeled canister of oxygen behind her as she shuffled across the
marble floors of the congressional buildings she visited. Her
neighbors lugged three extra tanks of oxygen and worried she would
run out.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Redman is 44. She and her brother and sister all have
asbestosis, also from the dust on her father's work clothes. He
died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gayla Benefield doesn't have asbestos, but her mother and father
both died slow, painful deaths from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   For two days the Montanans told their stories to anyone who
would listen. Tears sometimes flowed as they recounted life and
death with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law, if passed, would have exclude all of these people
from any protection,'' Benefield said, indicating her friends and
their families. ''The medical criteria and lengths of exposure that
the asbestos industry wants included would just slam the door shut.
There would be no place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan Whitehouse, the Spokane chest specialist who first
recognized that scores of people in Libby had asbestos-related
diseases, examined the medical history of the more then 300
patients he has treated or is treating and, according to Benefield,
determined that 78 percent would be excluded under the screening
criteria of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a bunch of people who have already had
settlements made and others who are near death,'' she says. ``I'm
not sure that these congressmen have a clue of what they're really
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Montanans walked into a House Judiciary Committee
hearing. Within a minute after their arrival, Hyde adjourned the
session and left the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's committee office was asked to comment on Whitehouse's
finding, but didn't return calls.
</P>
<P>
   At least one member of his Judiciary Committee did not hesitate
to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Libby have been let down by one government
agency after another over the years,'' said Rep. Marty Meehan,
D-Mass., ``Those who could have stepped in, made Grace do the right
thing and provide some relief, instead passed the buck and pointed
the finger elsewhere. Now the regulators are beginning to make up
for it. But the damage is largely done.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan spoke about the fact, reported by the Post-Intelligencer
last December, that the tainted Libby ore was sent to at least 60
processing plants around the country. ``One of those plants is in
my district,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee was expected to approve the bill this
week and send it on to the House for a vote, but it may no longer a
done deal. The committee's vote has been delayed for at least a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Public reaction to the Post-Intelligencer series and the
resulting investigations by the EPA, the Consumer Product Safety
Commission and other federal agencies have increased visibility of
the debate, according to a Congressional Quarterly report this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all those red flags out there, I question why we're
rushing into marking up this bill. I could see an argument for
moving ahead if we had at least done all we could to get to the
bottom of these medical criteria and see what they mean for flesh
and blood human beings like those here today. But we haven't,''
Meehan said, pointing to the four people from Libby.
</P>
<P>
   Congress was further jolted last month when Bruce Vento, a
popular Democratic representative from Minnesota, announced that he
was retiring because he had been diagnosed with mesothelioma. Vento
got the disease, a deadly cancer of the lining of the lungs, after
being exposed to asbestos as a youth while working at a brewery.
</P>
<P>
   The latency period, the time from when someone is exposed to
asbestos to the first serious signs of disease, can be as long as
40 years. Many of the people dying today worked with asbestos when
it was called a ``miracle fiber.''
</P>
<P>
   In thousands of different products, it was found in every home,
factory and construction site. Asbestos manufacturers knew the
hazards, but most kept silent. Some fought, and continue to fight,
government attempts to regulate use of asbesteos. The lethal
exposures and the lawsuits piled up.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the U.S. Supreme Court asked Congress to solve the
problem, calling the backlog of cases a judicial nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The bill calls for the establishment of an Office of Asbestos
Compensation under the Justice Department. Government-approved
doctors, using criteria defined in the law, would be gatekeepers,
issuing a pass to qualifying victims who wished to sue or seek a
government-ordained settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress shouldn't add insult to injury. It shouldn't be the
latest in a long line of potential protectors who in fact failed to
protect,'' Meehan said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Some Congressional staff members old enough to remember the
years of debate to pass laws to help coal miners suffering from
Black Lung disease, say they see similarities which are alarming.
Miners in West Virginia, Pennsylvania and other coal states often
fought lengthy battles with local Black Lung certification boards
who were sometimes staffed with coal-company doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say they're sure that wouldn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   The four from Libby don't believe them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
