<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLLEGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 COULD BE SHORTCHANGED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With impressive non-conference victories,
sparkling individual performances and two dominant teams, this
might be the best regular season in Pacific-10 history.
</P>
<P>
   The league is 5-0 against the Big Ten and has beaten Kentucky,
Michigan State, Texas, Duke, Auburn, North Carolina, Purdue and
DePaul.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State's Eddie House tied the conference scoring record
with 61 points. A few weeks later, USC's David Bluthenthal had 28
rebounds and Arizona's Loren Woods blocked 14 shots. No conference
in the country has a better group of freshmen. Stanford and Arizona
are headed for top seeds in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, it's been all smiles and good cheer at the
league office in Walnut Creek. But the jocularity could end
Selection Sunday (March 12) if just three teams make the NCAA
Tournament. And unless someone gets hot, that's exactly what will
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at who's in, who's out and who's on the brink:
</P>
<P>
   Stanford: The Cardinal (24-1, 13-1) clinched a bid weeks ago. It
has beaten Duke, Auburn, Iowa and Georgia Tech. Its record (24-1)
and power rating (No.7 in the RPI) are superb. Even if it loses at
Arizona next week, Stanford probably has clinched a No.1 seed.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left is placement. If the Cardinal wins the Pac-10
title outright, it probably will play in Tucson. (The Selection
committee likes to place conference champs in their home region.)
</P>
<P>
   But if Arizona wins the league and plays in Salt Lake City the
Wildcats can't play in Tucson, of course Stanford probably goes to
the South.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona: The Wildcats (24-4, 13-1) aren't making the Selection
committee's job easy. They've defeated Kentucky, Texas, Michigan
State and Stanford and probably will clinch a No.1 seed if they
beat Oregon on Saturday and Stanford next week. But that seems
unlikely given star center Loren Woods' back injury. (He's out
several weeks, at least.)
</P>
<P>
   How will the injury affect Arizona's seed? Wildcats athletic
director Jim Livengood is on the Selection committee and will
provide a detailed report on Woods' tournament status. If he's out,
the committee could drop the Wildcats a spot or two.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if Woods is expected back for the tournament, the
committee could disregard losses incurred without him - just as it
will disregard Michigan State's losses without Mateen Cleaves and
Temple's losses without Pepe Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon: The Ducks have solid power ratings (30th in Sagarin,
34th in RPI), and they have several impressive non-conference wins
(Minnesota, Wake Forest and Gonzaga).
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to their victory at USC last week, the Ducks (19-7, 10-5)
probably are one win from clinching an at-large berth. That could
come this weekend against the Arizona schools or March 11 against
Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   However, forward A.D. Smith's injury - he's out several weeks
with a broken cheekbone - could cost the Ducks a few spots in the
seedings.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State: The Sun Devils (16-10, 8-6) are difficult to
evaluate. Yes, they're playing well in the stretch and have a
chance to finish fourth. But their best non-conference victory is
Colorado State, and they have a non-Division I win (American
U.-Puerto Rico) that the Selection committee will disregard.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the critical 18-victory plateau, ASU must win three of
its last four games. That makes tonight's showdown at Oregon
critical - for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   Cal: With a freshman-dominated roster, coach Ben Braun has done
a superb job getting the Bears (15-11, 6-8) this close to a
tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   But even Braun probably can't overcome last week's loss at
Washington State. With a power rating in the 60s and only one
impressive non-conference win (Gonzaga), Cal needs to win three of
its last four to have a chance. That means sweeping the L.A.
schools this weekend and winning at Arizona State next week.
</P>
<P>
   USC: The Oregon loss was devastating, and it left the fading
Trojans (14-12, 6-8) with one realistic path to the tournament: win
three of their last four (Cal and the Washington schools) and hope
for a break.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do 17-win teams make the field, but Sam Clancy's return
could place the Trojans in a different category. If he'd been
healthy all season, they'd surely have two or three more victories.
Then again, he was healthy when the Trojans lost to Utah State,
Long Beach State and St. Bonaventure.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA: With a lofty power rating (No.28 RPI), the Bruins have
become convinced they can make the tournament with 17 wins.
</P>
<P>
   They're misinformed. Power ratings are important, but they
aren't the most important criteria. The Selection committee values
late-season performance above all; record against quality teams is
a close second.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins (15-11, 6-8) win three of their last four and
reach the 18-victory plateau, they're in - no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't - if they get swept in the Bay Area, then sweep
the Washington schools - they're in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting those games would give UCLA a 5-5 record in its last
10. That includes two heartless losses in the desert. It's hard to
justify inviting a 17-win team that lost by 29 points at Arizona
State in mid-February. It's also hard to justify inviting a 17-win
team that would have two losses to Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, the Bruins had better win tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
