<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA TOURNAMENT HOPES ON THE LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the rest of the nation, the NCAA Tournament
begins March 16. For the UCLA Bruins, it begins tonight at Cal in
the first of four games to determine their postseason fate.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (15-11, 6-8) must win three of their last four to
secure a tournament berth. If they lose tonight, they must defeat
No.1 Stanford on Saturday to keep pace a situation they're
desperate to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be single elimination, but it's awfully close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play each game like it's a first-round game,''
Bruins senior forward Sean Farnham said. ``To get there, the best
way is to be mentally prepared like it's an NCAA Tournament game.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of qualifying for the tournament the minimum standard
for a successful season in Westwood tonight's game probably is the
most important UCLA has played in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   On the final weekend of the 1980 regular season, coach Larry
Brown's 15-9 team visited the Bay Area needing two wins to make the
tournament. Behind senior forward Kiki Vandeweghe and freshman
guards Rod Foster and Michael Holton, who's now an assistant coach,
the Bruins swept Cal and Stanford, made the tournament and charged
to the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, the program again sits on the brink of
tournament rejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's pressure fighting for the Pac-10 title or playing in
the West (region) or playing for a high seed,'' Bruins coach Steve
Lavin said. ``But this is a different form of pressure. This is the
first time with two weeks to go that we've had NCAA Tournament
ramifications.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the Bruins are better prepared today than they were
last week after miserable performances in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   They reduced turnovers against the Oregon schools, refined their
offense and gained a speck of momentum. Their practices are more
intense and their spirits are rising.
</P>
<P>
   They also have revenge on their minds. If the Bruins had
defeated Cal last month in Pauley Pavilion, they wouldn't be in
this predicament. Instead, they botched several last-minute
possessions, misused their timeouts and lost to a team with five
freshmen playing extensive minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They embarrassed us,'' UCLA forward Rico Hines said. ``It hurt
to see their younger guys get a win in Pauley. We're definitely
thinking about revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric update: Center Dan Gadzuric has practiced sparingly
this week after injuring his knee against Oregon State, but he
expects to play today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I banged it when I dove on the floor,'' he said. ``Monday, I
did some individual workouts to break a sweat. But (Tuesday) I was
able to run. I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming on strong: Guard Earl Watson struggled for most of the
season but has flourished since point guard Ryan Bailey entered the
starting lineup six games ago. Bailey's presence frees Watson to
roam the court, score from the wings and rebound aggressively.
Watson is averaging 15.6 points and shooting 60.3 percent in the
six games.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he was named Pac-10 player of the week for his 41-point
effort against the Oregon schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's found a happy medium,'' Lavin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
