<SLUG> BC-ABC-CABLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE MAY KNOCK ABC'S TV STATION OFF CABLE SYSTEM IN HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Va.)  (rk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an increasingly bitter dispute between Time Warner Inc. and
Walt Disney Co., an ABC television station in Houston is due to go
dark early Friday morning in more than 650,000 homes served by the
Time Warner cable system.
</P>
<P>
   Disney, ABC's parent, has asked for several concessions from
Time Warner for the right to continue transmitting the signals of
its Houston station, KTRK, on the cable system. Along with several
lesser demands, Disney has asked Time Warner to change its Disney
Channel from a premium or pay cable channel to a basic channel and
to pay it 71 cents for every subscriber to its cable systems, a
relatively high figure.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome in Houston, which could spill over to other cities,
including New York, will be closely watched for what it could mean
for future negotiations between broadcasters and cable operators
and how networks might use the growth of satellite television
service as leverage.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have become increasingly aggressive recently in
dealing with cable systems. Late last year, Fox pulled its signal
from a group of communities served by the cable systems of Cox
Communications Inc., including Dallas and Fairfax, Va., to win a
place for its movie channel. The dispute was resolved after a week,
and the movie channel is now being carried.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives assailed Disney's tactics as
``blackmail,'' ``terrorism,'' and ``extortion.'' Disney executives
said Time Warner had engaged in a pattern of ``preferential
treatment'' for its own channels at the expense of channels owned
by Disney and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a last-minute deal can be arranged _ and executives from
both sides said they were not even talking Wednesday _ viewers in
Houston cable homes served by Time Warner will lose access to ABC,
as of 12:01 a.m. Friday. After that, they will be compelled to use
old-fashioned antennas or sign up with a satellite distribution
company to receive ABC programs.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute threatens to affect other cities where Time Warner
has cable systems, principally New York, where the company has 1.2
million customers. ABC granted a 30-day extension in New York; the
new termination date is March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ABC said it selected Houston to begin this showdown because it
offered the best opportunities for viewers to get access to ABC in
other ways. ABC Thursday will begin offering $99 rebates to viewers
in Houston for purchases of satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Luftman, the vice president of communications for Time
Warner Cable, labeled the Disney position ``an extortion demand''
and likened Disney's tactics in choosing Houston as the city to
fight out the dispute to ``terrorists taking hostages and then
taking one out and shooting him in the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Iger, the Disney president, accused Time Warner of
refusing to negotiate in good faith out of desire to give
``preferential treatment'' to channels owned by Time Warner,
including the Cartoon Network, which is a direct competitor to the
Disney Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Iger noted that the Disney Channel was moved from Channel 33 to
Channel 66 in New York, while channels owned by Time Warner, like
CNN and TBS, have been moved down to the lowest channels. The
low-numbered channels tend to have the heaviest traffic on cable
channels.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies gave directly opposite accounts of how the
negotiations have gone. Fred Dressler, the senior vice president or
programming for Time Warner Cable, said he had a deal completed
with ABC but for one small detail in December.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agree that ABC changed the terms after the AOL-Time
Warner merger was announced in January. Patricia Matson, the senior
vice president of corporate communications for ABC, said the
company was already unhappy with the terms but that the merger
increased ABC concerns, because it would be dealing with a more
powerful organization with control over cable and internet access.
She would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Dressler said the Disney channel switch would cost Time Warner
an additional $100 million. ABC executives said the figure was
vastly overstated.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, both sides agree, Disney offered to take the
entire Disney Channel issue off the table and simply take a cash
settlement for the rights to carry ABC's stations. No cable system
has ever paid a broadcaster for rights to its signal. The offer was
declined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
