<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEWS ANALYSIS: BY MOST ANY MEASURE, McCAIN'S BLACK TUESDAY  
(js) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Before Washington state's votes rolled in late
Tuesday, aides to Sen. John McCain tried to minimize Gov. George W.
Bush's victory in Virginia, which had reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The only place Bush had shown any strength, McCain aides said,
was in the most conservative section of the country, the South,
with victories in South Carolina 10 days earlier and now Virginia.
McCain himself chimed in, ``Seems as if he has a Southern strategy
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But in fact McCain was comprehensively beaten on Tuesday: in a
big Southern state with one foot in the mid-Atlantic region,
Virginia; in a small, isolated Midwestern state whose economy is
based on agriculture, North Dakota; and in a Northwestern state
with a progressive tradition, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was by some margin the biggest wipeout of the Republican
presidential campaign, and it came just one week before 13 states
hold Republican primaries and caucuses in what may prove to be the
decisive moment of the fight for the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   New polls taken in a number of those states since McCain's
victory in Michigan a week ago, but before Bush's sweep on Tuesday,
show tough going ahead for the Arizonan. He has taken a narrow
lead, within the margin of error, in three New York surveys, and he
has an enormous lead of 36 points in Massachusetts. But he trails
Bush by 21 points in the latest Los Angeles Times poll of
Republican voters in California, the nation's most-populous state,
and Bush also holds double-digit leads in Maryland, Missouri and
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Bush's campaign looked wobbly. Now he has regained
the initiative, and he said he felt a spring in his step Wednesday
morning as he began campaigning in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's biggest problem is his inability to shake Bush's hold
on Republican loyalists, whose votes will decide the allocation of
New York and California delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Washington primary tells me,'' said David Olsen, a
political science professor at the University of Washington, ``is
that Bush has done what he needed to firm up his base, but the cost
may be the election in November. Bush had to move so far to the
right he may have trouble getting back to the center in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Bush is having problems in attracting crossover votes,
which he would need to beat the Democrats. But he has months to try
to overcome that shortcoming; McCain has only a week left to woo
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like neither Bush nor McCain made much headway here
on the other guy's turf,'' said Stuart Elway, an independent
pollster in Seattle. ``It was the same old stalemate that we have
seen in the other states.''
</P>
<P>
   In the popularity contest in Washington, which was open both to
Republicans and to independents, Bush led McCain by only 9,000
votes, with more than 200,000 absentee ballots still to be tallied.
But among Republicans, whose votes were the only ones counted in
selecting delegates, Bush trounced his rival, 58 percent to 38
percent, gaining 7 of the 12 delegates at stake. McCain took 5.
Twenty-five more will be named in caucuses next week.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made his strongest showing in King County (Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   The Washington system is similar to that in California, where
some politicians have suggested that McCain will do well in the
popularity contest while Bush gets most of the 162 delegates, the
largest bloc at the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota uses a caucus system, and the turnout was small on
a frosty night. But Bush thoroughly trounced the field, beating
McCain by 76 percent to 19 percent and taking 14 delegates to 4 for
McCain and 1 for Alan Keyes, the former State Department aide who
has hung on doggedly.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia as in Washington, it was the Republicans who
propelled Bush to victory, which gave him a fat packet of 56
delegates. McCain prevailed among Democrats in the Old Dominion, 87
percent to 11, and among independents, 64 percent to 31. But
Republicans constituted more than 60 percent of the electorate in
the primary, and Bush took the votes of two-thirds of them.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity was even more marked between voters who identified
themselves with the religious right, fully 80 percent of whom went
for Bush, and those who did not, who opted for McCain by a narrow
margin, 52 percent to 45 percent. McCain certainly did not help
himself, and may have damaged his chances, with his attack on Pat
Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell, the two Virginians who are
among the most prominent Christian conservative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   When voters were asked, without any particular target specified,
whether McCain had made unfair attacks, almost half said he had,
and Bush won the votes of three-quarters of them. Only a third said
Bush had made unfair attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The figures on the religious right came from an exit poll by a
consortium of the television networks and The Associated Press. No
comparable figures were available for Washington, where no such
poll was taken. So it is difficult to judge what effect, if any,
McCain's harsh criticism will have in the big Northern industrial
states with no particular affinity for the religious right whose
primaries are scheduled for next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain raised the stakes in Virginia by spending heavily in its
most expensive media market, the Washington suburbs, and making
several campaign stops in the state. From that perspective, his
showing was a disappointment, and Gov. James S. Gilmore III, who
backed Bush, gloated that McCain's campaign bus, the Straight Talk
Express, ``ran out of gas in Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the entire Republican establishment arrayed against
him, and with a very late start in organization, McCain made a
contest of it. He lost by 9 percentage points, considerably less
than the polls had suggested, and he did very well in Norfolk,
Virginia Beach and the rest of the Hampton Roads area, where
several vast military installations are situated. He carried
Charlottesville, home of the University of Virginia, and the
Virginia suburbs of Washington, including Arlington, Alexandria and
Fairfax County.
</P>
<P>
   That was not enough, though, in the face of huge Bush majorities
in the suburban Richmond counties of Henrico and Chesterfield.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is a must-win state for the Republicans in November,
and one party leader here said on Tuesday night: ``Clinton lost the
state by only a couple of points four years ago. I worry that if
McCain and Bush keep battering each other, the way Reagan and Ford
did in 1976, the result will be the same. They let Jimmy Carter in,
and these guys may end up electing Al Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
