<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-BRADLEY-MEDIA-ART-N     03-01 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BRADLEY-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER BRADLEY'S RULES REPORTERS AT ARM'S LENGTH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art note)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley had just finished a talk
on gun control at a San Francisco hospital when he looked into his
audience and said, ``If you'd like to ask any questions, I'd be
pleased to answer them.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, Pamela Tam, a reporter for KPIX, the San Francisco
affiliate for CBS, piped up from the rear of the crowd: What was
his reaction to the shooting of a first-grade girl by a classmate
in Michigan that morning? But Bradley quickly cut her off.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' he said, ``We were going to do the people.'' But
midsentence, he caught himself and relented. ``Go ahead,'' he
continued. ``You didn't know the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules,'' as Bradley's campaign has unofficially sought to
define them, go something like this: Voters get to ask lots of
questions at almost every event, almost every day. Reporters must
wait for news conferences. In a busy week, there will be four of
them. Sometimes fewer. And all tend to be short. (Fifteen minutes
or less.)
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, for instance, Bradley answered Tam's
questions, and took a follow-up. But then he fielded several
questions from his audience on issues like health policy and police
brutality, giving long, detailed answers. Then he left, without
taking any more questions from the 20 or so reporters in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Again Wednesday, Bradley spent nearly half an hour answering
questions from voters at a health clinic in a Latino section of Los
Angeles. Afterward, his news conference with reporters lasted less
than 10 minutes, time enough to answer four questions.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that Bradley is avoiding reporters. Indeed,
he has spent a large chunk of each day recently doing interviews
with local news organizations as he tries to spread his message to
the 16 states that hold Democratic primaries and caucuses on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But he devotes relatively little time to schmoozing with the
press crew assigned to trail him every day. Though he can be
playful with certain reporters and photographers _ knocking their
pads out of their hands, tossing basketballs at them, nodding to
them in crowds _ he rarely strikes up conversations with them
between events.
</P>
<P>
   And on his charter airplanes, Bradley sits in the front, where
he can be seen poring through files and briefing books, while the
reporters stay in the rear. On occasion, Bradley will stroll back
to chat, off-the-record. But that happens almost exclusively when
the restroom is in the tail section.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, reporters sometimes shout questions at him as he
enters events or shakes hands with voters afterward. But he will
not always answer, and he can be terse or testy when he does.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the New Hampshire primary in February, for
instance, Bradley was visibly annoyed with a throng of reporters
who clung around him as he tried to greet voters. He muttered
one-word answers to their questions and then canceled a visit to
another polling station out of concerns that the cameras and
reporters were angering voters.
</P>
<P>
   And in Los Angeles last month, Bradley was shaking hands and
signing autographs in a crowd of middle school students when a
television reporter tossed him the kind of feather-pillow question
most politicians practically beg to be asked.
</P>
<P>
   What did the endorsement of Michael Jordan, just announced that
morning, mean for Bradley's campaign, the reporter shouted through
a crowd of teen-agers. Another politician might have delivered a
breathlessly exuberant sound bite ready-made for the 5 o'clock
news. But Bradley could barely hide his irritation with the
reporter's intrusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a big help,'' he said, then moved on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
