<SLUG> BC-LOG-OFF-AND-LIVE!-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET SURFING HARMS YOUR SOCIAL LIFE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RESENDING from Feb. 29)   (This 350-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``l''
lifestyle news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By CHERRY NORTON  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ People who use the Internet for as little as five hours
a week are less likely to talk to or visit their family and friends
and are in danger of shutting themselves off from society,
according to new research.
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet expands so people can shop, chat with friends
and conduct business online, researchers from the Stanford
Institute for the Quantitative Study of Society in America have
found that the technology is having a damaging social impact even
when people use it in modest amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Those who spent 5-10 hours a week online reported a 25 percent
fall in social activity _ spending less time talking on the phone
or face to face.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Norman Nie, director of the Stanford Institute and his
colleague, Professor Lutz Erbring, have published preliminary
results from the biggest study yet into how the Internet is
changing daily life.
</P>
<P>
   They found that as people increasingly turned to the Internet
for their needs they were isolating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Although 60 percent of the time they spent online came from
watching less television, the rest was at the expense of seeing or
talking to people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who use the Internet at even modest amounts, of five or
10 hours a week, are reporting that they see fewer people, talk to
fewer people and go out less often. This merits concern,'' said
Professor Nie.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers questioned 4,113 adults in nearly 3,000
households across America. More than half had Internet access and
one-quarter used the Internet for between five and 10 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   These people reported that since they had gone online they spent
8 percent less time attending social events, 13 percent less time
with family and friends and 26 percent less time talking to people
on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   According to Professor Nie there is no doubt that people do form
strong relationships over the Internet but it is not the same as a
healthy social life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't share a coffee or a beer with somebody on e-mail, or
give them a hug,'' he said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
