<HEADLINE>
TROJANS LOOKING FOR LEADERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ When USC coach Henry Bibby looks at tonight's
opponent, Stanford, he sees more than the No.1-ranked team in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby also sees a team with leadership, something he feels the
Trojans have lacked at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a legitimate leader in Mark Madsen, who demands they
play hard on every possession,'' Bibby said. ``Once you get a
leader, you can go wherever you want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   So do the Trojans have that leader?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly,'' Bibby said. ``We really don't have that leader
that steps up. Jarvis Turner has at times, Brian Scalabrine has at
times, Brandon Granville has at times, but we don't have that
consistent leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have one guy who says, `Enough of this nonsense, if
you're not on board, get off.'''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting update: This week's commitment from 6-foot-5 guard
Travis Hanour of Laguna Beach High secured the Trojans their No. 1
priority of the spring signing period. He is projected to play
point guard, shooting guard and small forward next season after
averaging 25.7 points, 9.7 rebounds and 5.4 assists for the
Artists. Hanour also shot 40 percent on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some comparisons with (Stanford guard) Casey
Jacobsen,'' Laguna Beach coach Bret Fleming said. ``You don't see a
lot of kids his size with point guard skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona and Utah coaches were reportedly upset this week that
Hanour committed early and canceled recruiting trips to their
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans might also sign his teammate, 6-9 forward Chris
Manker, although no decision has been made. He would likely
redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   Manker is scheduled to visit Colorado State, Oregon State and
Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   There were erroneous reports that Compton Centennial forward
Ellis Myles might commit soon, but USC has not offered him a
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame decision: Forward Sam Clancy (broken foot) is still
scheduled to make a decision before tonight's game to see if he can
play. Clancy has been out since Jan.20, but will definitely play
Saturday against Cal if he cannot go tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine shines: Scalabrine is making a case for the
Pacific-10 Conference Player of the Year award, although his
chances obviously have been hurt by the team's recent slide.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine is averaging 21.7 points, 6.4 rebounds and shooting
55 percent from the field in Pac-10 games. He has set a new
career-high in two of his past four games, and scored 100 points in
the past four games.
</P>
<P>
   He is currently second in the conference in scoring, fifth in
field-goal percentage and 13th in rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a candidate, but I don't know how it will work
out,'' Scalabrine said. ``There's a lot of good players who are on
the top teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Bibby is backing Scalabrine as player of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's had that type of year. If we can finish on a
solid note, he can get that,'' Bibby said. ``In my estimation, he's
the best player in the Pac-10. Before he got hurt, I thought Sam
Clancy was the best player. That's why we were 6-1.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon further review: Although Scalabrine appeared to merely trip
on his own when he fell going for an inbounds pass with seven
seconds left in the 80-77 loss to Oregon, the game film revealed he
actually tripped on forward David Bluthenthal's foot.
</P>
<P>
   Bluthenthal was wide open on the play, but Granville threw the
ball toward Scalabrine, who tripped, which allowed Oregon to regain
possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wide open,'' Bluthenthal said. ``There was no one around
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
