<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABC-WARNER-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV RIVALS EXTEND DEADLINE BY 24 HOURS IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN HODGES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The local ABC affiliate and Time Warner Cable on
Wednesday extended by 24 hours their deadline for reaching a new
retransmission agreement, keeping the station on the cable system
until midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no day-by-day extension _ the one we granted
ends at midnight, and we won't change that,'' said KTRK-Channel 13
president/general manager Henry Florsheim.
</P>
<P>
   When KTRK is pulled off the cable, what Time Warner's 680,000
Houston subscribers will see on that channel is the cable company's
explanation of why the ABC station is not being carried.
</P>
<P>
   ``After midnight (tonight) the ball is in their court,'' said
Ron McMillan, president of Time Warner-Houston Division. ``Every
other (ABC) market is getting 30 days more. Only in Houston are we
getting one day. Disney has chosen to make an example out of
Houston for the entire country.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting Saturday, Time Warner will put a ``free'' sample of its
premium channel, HBO Family, on the cable spot until the dispute is
settled.
</P>
<P>
   KTRK countered that it will give the first 1,500 Time Warner
subscribers to switch to satellite dish a $99 rebate.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's one-day delay came after Disney/ABC extended by a
day its own deadline to pull its station from the cable system.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's delay prompted a letter from Fred M. Dressler, Time
Warner's corporate negotiator, to Bob Iger, president/CEO of The
Walt Disney Co., saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that you saw fit to extend the retransmission
consent for almost all your ABC stations. We are sorry you have
chosen to punish the people of Houston because you are dissatisfied
with the terms of an agreement your representative agreed to with
Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to lose ABC in Houston for even one minute, and
we are willing to take any extension ... while our negotiations
continue,'' Dressler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have offered several solutions to this dilemma. However, we
cannot capitulate to this heavy-handed approach to negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said Dressler, senior vice president of programming, is
continuing to negotiate by phone with Anne Sweeney, president of
Disney/ABC Cable Networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations are in progress, contrary to what ABC local
management continues to say,'' McMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Channel 13's Florsheim denied negotiations are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one call between Dressler and Sweeney Tuesday, and
it lasted minutes. There were no negotiations,'' he said. ``And
there were none (Wednesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Since December, Disney/ABC has been negotiating its 10-year
retransmission agreements for stations it owns in Houston, New
York, Los Angeles and other cities, representing 3.5 million Time
Warner subscribers. In all those other cities, ABC has given a
30-day extension.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner claims that Disney reneged on an original verbal
agreement to put the Disney Channel on basic cable in Houston,
where most Time Warner subscribers are paying extra for it. The
deal would have added the two new Disney cable channels, Toon
Disney and SoapNet, a soap opera channel.
</P>
<P>
   However, McMillan said, ``the company changed its mind and asked
for an additional $100 million, which we are not prepared to pay or
to pass on to our subscribers.''
</P>
<P>
   Florsheim disputed that, too: ``There is no deal, and there
never was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that they are the 800-pound gorilla that owns
75 percent of the cable in Houston, and as a producer of product we
are very concerned about getting our product on cable,'' he said.
``What this is all about, is our inability to get Time Warner to
talk to us. Right now we are not talking, and we cannot reach a
deal without talking. The only way to get them to talk is, there's
got to be a line in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now, they're putting their own paid channel on Channel 13,
the most-used channel on the system,'' he added. ``If they are
going to give a preferential position to some of their own product,
we object to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The city grants cable franchises, but has no jurisdiction in
this dispute because it cannot get involved in programming.
</P>
<P>
   But City Councilman Carroll Robinson, chairman of the city's
Transportation, Technology and Infra-Structure Committee, wrote
McMillan and Florsheim on Wednesday, asking them to sit down and
talk with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome his help,'' said McMillan. ``This type of dispute
is exactly what the cable industry tried to tell Congress would
happen under the 1992 Cable Act.``
</P>
<P>
   He said ``four to five hundred'' callers had requested the free
antenna kits to pick up broadcasts of KTRK and many more such
requests are expected Friday.
</P>
<P>
   KTRK-TV also has had hundreds of calls from viewers asking what
they can do, Florsheim said. The channel is telling them ``to call
Time Warner and ask them to get back to the negotiating table,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,500 rebates KTRK is offering are for satellite dishes and
receivers for DirecTV. The satellite company will offer free
standard installation to consumers who sign up by May 5. DirecTV
will also offer Houston subscribers a free local channel purchase _
which usually is an added charge of $5.99 a month _ until April 2.
DirecTV's subscription rates are comparable to cable's.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, DirecTV added KHOU-Channel 11 to its satellite
lineup, which now includes the four biggest network affiliates _
KTRK-Channel 13 (ABC), KPRC-Channel 2 (NBC) and KRIV-Channel 26
(Fox). No other local channels are available on satellite. PBS is
offered as a national feed, rather than Houston's KUHT-Channel 8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
