<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WCC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE CONTROLS DESTINY AT WCC TOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The easiest thing for Pepperdine to do is win the
West Coast Conference tournament, which starts this weekend, get
the automatic bid to the NCAA Tournament, then sit back and let the
other bubble teams worry about their future.
</P>
<P>
   If the top-seeded Waves, who open Saturday against Loyola
Marymount at Santa Clara's Toso Pavilion, go on to win the WCC
tournament championship Monday, they're guaranteed a spot in the
Big Dance. If they slip, their fate rests with the NCAA selection
committee, were nothing is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pepperdine (22-7) has a tournament-friendly win total,
an RPI rating in the 40s and the regular-season WCC crown, the
Waves don't want to leave anything to chance.
</P>
<P>
   The key for Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff is getting that
message across without suffocating his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a balance there,'' van Breda Kolff said. ``You
don't want to tell them on the first day that if you win, you go,
but if you lose, there's no chance. We'll do what we've been doing,
and that's to let things play out and take it one game at a time.
The fact is we need to win three games in three days, and we feel
like we are capable of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine ended the regular season with a 71-42 win at St.
Mary's, two days after a discouraging loss to San Diego, only its
second setback over the previous 14 games. Going into the St.
Mary's game, the Waves knew they were the WCC regular-season
champions, thanks to Gonzaga's loss to Santa Clara the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine could have coasted at that point, knowing a loss to
the Gaels would not affect their status. Instead they played one of
their best games of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the sign of a good team,'' van Breda Kolff
said. ``We talked about not being satisfied and the importance of
going out there and playing well, and that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping down the roar: If everything goes according to plan,
Pepperdine should easily get past Loyola Marymount in the first
round. The Lions have lost 14 games in a row, haven't beaten a
Division I-A team all year and will lose coach Charles Bradley, who
announced his resignation last week, at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley rarely talks to the media, but assistant Ronnie Stubbs
said the Lions are making the most of a difficult situation.
Players still show up to practice and coaches still teach, even
though no one is sure where they'll be after Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always talk about how you deal with adversity. Right now
determines how you deal with life in general,'' Stubbs said. ``If
you're going to be successful later on, how you react now can shape
that. And that goes for the coaches and the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine forward Tommie Prince is always concerned about
Loyola Marymount, no matter the record or situation. The Waves
swept the two-game regular-season series against the Lions.
</P>
<P>
   `'Ever since I've been here they've always played us tough,''
Prince said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
