<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED REACTION IN NEW YORK TO REDUCTION IN ROCKER SUSPENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID KOEPPEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The news that an arbitrator had decided to reduce the
suspension of Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker drew mixed
reactions from baseball fans around New York City Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Some expressed disappointment and anger, others criticized
Commissioner Bud Selig's initial decision to suspend Rocker as a
violation of his freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed to the incident several years ago when the former
Oriole Roberto Alomar spit on a major league umpire, calling it a
more serious offense. Alomar was suspended for just five games,
though that penalty was levied not by Selig but by Gene Budig, who
was then the American League president.
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator, Shyam Das, cut Rocker's regular-season ban from
28 days to 14, and cut his fine from $20,000 to $500. He also said
Rocker could begin spring training immediately.
</P>
<P>
   George Evertz, 29, of Brooklyn, condemned the decision and said
baseball should have taken an even harder line and suspended Rocker
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're sending the message that this is what happens to
someone who fans the flames of hatred,'' said Evertz, who works for
the Immigration and Naturalization Service. ``If they just kicked
him out, that would send the right message to anyone else who wants
to spew this garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Evertz predicted that if Rocker did not open his mouth again
this season, the incident would eventually be forgotten by the
public.
</P>
<P>
   But Andre Stewart, 36, a security guard who works at the South
Street Seaport, believes that Rocker will be tagged permanently as
a racist by his teammates and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed by this decision; they should have kicked him
out for the whole season,'' he said. ``These athletes have legions
of fans, they have to be careful what they say. He only apologized
under pressure, he just threw something out there for the fans to
believe and they didn't buy it. He's going to get really booed.
Especially in New York, fans are going to react.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sullivan, a 33-year-old bartender in Lower Manhattan, said
he disliked Rocker as a person but defended his right to say what
he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Mets fan, so I really hate him,'' said Sullivan, a Bronx
resident. ``What he said was really stupid, but there's no law
against being stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``His real punishment will come from the other players and fans.
He's going to get his due. This is going to stay with him his whole
career.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
