<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-BRAVES-ROCKER-1ST     03-01 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-ROCKER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER'S SUSPENSION CUT BACK BY ARBITRATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES, additions thruout) 
 (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball's arbitrator slashed by about two-thirds Wednesday
Commissioner Bud Selig's suspension of John Rocker, the Atlanta
Braves pitcher, who in a magazine interview disparaged foreigners,
gays and members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of missing all 45 days of spring training, Rocker will
be permitted to join the Braves at their Lake Buena Vista, Fla.,
camp, which he is expected to do Thursday. Instead of missing the
first four weeks of the season and 24 games, he will sit out only
the first two weeks and 12 games. Rocker, a 25-year-old closer, has
missed 13 days of spring training, so the arbitrator, Shyam Das, in
effect, reduced the suspension from 73 days to 27.
</P>
<P>
   Das also sliced the $20,000 fine Selig levied against Rocker to
$500, the maximum amount a commissioner may fine a player under the
best-interests-of-baseball provision in the major league rules.
</P>
<P>
   Selig was not happy with the ruling, but he was not the first
commissioner to have a suspension reduced or overturned by an
arbitrator. In fact, baseball's drug history is filled with similar
arbitration decisions.
</P>
<P>
   This ruling, at first glance, would seem to be a sharp rebuke to
Selig, but the players association, which had filed a grievance
challenging the commissioner's action, contended from the start
that the heavy suspension and fine were more for a public relations
effect. The penalty was levied, a union lawyer said, ``with an eye
toward the arbitration process.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig, who has vehemently denied that suggestion, said in a
statement Wednesday that the ruling ``does not reflect any
understanding of or sensitivity to the important social
responsibility'' that baseball has to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It completely ignores the sensibilities of those groups of
people maligned by Mr. Rocker and disregards the player's position
as a role model for children,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension was the first of its kind in the 30-year history
of baseball's impartial arbitration procedure. All previous
suspensions by commissioners involved drugs or on-field incidents.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the setback, Selig gained one significant victory. By
allowing two weeks of the suspension to stand, Das found that the
commissioner had the authority to discipline a player for speech.
Das, on the other hand, obviously found the suspension too severe,
saying that Selig's action was ``without just cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Das, who did not immediately issue a written opinion explaining
his ruling, let stand the requirement that Rocker participate in an
in-season program of diversity training. Under Selig's penalty,
Rocker, a premier reliever in the National League, was not losing
any salary. He signed a new contract on Tuesday that will probably
pay him about $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Selig's action against Rocker was undermined in part by
precedent, including a 1988 incident involving Bob Knepper, a
Houston Astros pitcher, who reacted to the prospect of a female
umpire getting a major league job. Knepper spoke disparagingly of
women generally, and specifically of the National Organization for
Women after it criticized him.
</P>
<P>
   Knepper was not disciplined and, in fact, Major League Baseball
officials said at the time that he was entitled to his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker expressed his opinion about an assortment of people in an
interview that appeared in a December issue of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Rocker, who feuded with New York fans last
season, said the No. 7 train to Shea Stadium was like riding
through Beirut. He described the subway ride as including ``some
kid with purple hair next to some queer with AIDS right next to
some dude who just got out of jail for the fourth time next to some
20-year-old mom with four kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rocker complained about New York's ethnic
diversity, saying: ``I'm not a very big fan of foreigners. You can
walk an entire block in Times Square and not hear anybody speaking
English.''
</P>
<P>
   In suspending him Jan. 31, Selig said that Rocker's remarks
``offended practically every element of society and brought
dishonor to himself, the Atlanta Braves and Major League
Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The players association challenged the suspension and, as in
many drug cases of the past 20 years, gained a reduction, though
the union said it was disappointed that the arbitrator ``did not
accept all of our arguments.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Howe, LaMarr Hoyt, Pascual Perez, Willie Wilson and
Ferguson Jenkins were among the players who had drug suspensions
shortened or overturned. Howe was suspended for life by
Commissioner Fay Vincent in June 1992, after another in a series of
drug incidents, but the following November an arbitrator ordered
him reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the success of Rocker's challenge to Selig's action
was the testimony of Scott Sanderson, a former major league
pitcher. Called as a witness Feb. 10 during the two-day hearing,
Sanderson talked about the importance of spring training to a major
league pitcher. Selig said Rocker could begin participating in
extended spring training with the Braves' minor league teams on
April 3.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson said Wednesday that, among other things, he testified
about the significance of facing in exhibition games the caliber of
hitters a pitcher will see during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a pitcher's out there and you're facing competition you
know you're going to be facing during the season,'' Sanderson said
by telephone from Tucson, Ariz., ``you deal with the aspect of
adrenaline kicking in and what adrenaline will do to cause your
body to react in ways it otherwise wouldn't. You push yourself, and
your body reacts differently. If you don't have any of that in the
spring, the very first time you're called into a game and ask your
body to react, it can't the way you want it to. And you take a
chance on getting hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, Sanderson said, ``like to say it's just a game; all
they do is go out and throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``But if you're going to excel and make a career,
there's a lot more to it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the suspension, the Braves' president, Stan
Kasten, called Rocker's remarks repugnant and unconscionable and
said Rocker would probably have been suspended indefinitely had he
made them during the season. Thursday, the Braves will have to find
a way to make Rocker a part of the team again. Randall Simon,
widely considered Rocker's intended target when he called one of
his teammates a ``fat monkey,'' said that if Rocker apologized,
everything would be OK and he would move on.
</P>
<P>
   Although Braves officials have said they will take Rocker back
with no animosity, a baseball official said he believed they would
trade him as soon as they find a club willing to take him and the
fallout from his remarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
