Humble or jazzed up, bread puddings have stood the test of time.
Dried apricots (shown), cherries or cranberries are delicious as a
sweetener. So are fruits like pears, apples and peaches. (William
Berry/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) LOS ANGELES -- March 1, 2000 -- COOPER-NOVEL -- Dennis
Cooper has just produced ``Period,'' which completes a five-book
cycle. The world as Cooper sees it is not for the faint of heart.
Out there in his slacker suburbia, beautiful boys with vacant eyes
wander aimlessly before being sodomized, mutilated and hacked to
pieces with an ax. But Cooper, 47, keeps it cool with prose that
evokes reverent sound bites like ``intensely lyrical'' and ``smart
and nervy'' from enamored critics. (Marissa Roth/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- TAYLOR-DANCE-REVIEW -- The
most popular choreographer working today is Paul Taylor. He needs
no guest stars to fill a house, and his wide appeal to a general
theater audience does not run counter to the seriousness of his
enterprise. The Paul Taylor Dance Company performing ``Arabesque''
during its New York premiere at City Center on Tuesday night. The
piece is one of Taylor's most intriguing on a formal level, but it
can also be appreciated at face value. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- STUDENT-MUSIC -- Few works
by 20th-century composers are pegged to students at an intermediate
level. Ursula Oppens, a champion of contemporary music and a
concert pianist, coaching a student, Kirill Gerstein, for the
``Carnegie Hall Millennium Piano Book.'' The volume includes a CD
of all the mid-level works, performed by Oppens. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- March 1, 2000 -- SUB-CUBA-BOY-COX --
Marisleysis Gonzalez, cousin of Elian Gonzalez, cries as she
testifies before the Senate Judiciary Committee on Capitol Hill,
Wednesday. Gonzalez said Elian's father in Cuba has been attempting
to signal to the boy's Florida relatives that he really wants his
son to remain in the United States. Congress is considering
legislation by Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., that would confer
citizenship on the 6-year-old shipwreck victim. (Rick McKay/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BAKU, Azerbaijan -- March 1, 2000 -- AZERBAIJAN-U.S. --
Pro-Armenian activists have kept Azerbaijan on a government
blacklist since 1992 thanks to a well-coordinated lobbying effort
by Armenian-Americans and a strong coalition of Armenia supporters
in Congress. But the Azerbaijanis are pushing back. Heydar Aliyev,
the country's president, has engaged in face-to-face lobbying, and
some high-powered hired professionals are doing the same behind the
scenes. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) DOBROSIN, Serbia -- March 1, 2000 -- YUGOSLAVIA-REBELS
-- A fighter with a patch of the Liberation Army of Presevo,
Medvedja and Bujanovac (UCPMB), during training exercises Tuesday.
Senior officials of the United Nations and the NATO-led KFOR
peacekeepers in Kosovo say the men appear to be members of the KLA
who had refused to turn in their weapons and want to ``liberate''
what they call ``Eastern Kosovo,'' where at least 70,000 ethnic
Albanians live in the arc from Medvedja in the north to Presevo in
the south. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- March 1, 2000 -- FOOD-BREADPUDDING-1-COX -- A
classic New Orleans bread pudding, coming from the rustic French
and English traditions, simply has raisins as a sweetener. But
dried apricots, cherries or cranberries are delicious. So are
fruits like pears (shown), apples and peaches. (William Berry/The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RIVERSIDE, Calif. -- March 1, 2000 -- MCCAIN-2 -- Sen.
John McCain greets supporters as his wife Cindy looks on Wednesday
at a town hall meeting. As the GOP presidential race heads into its
deciding stretch, the fate of John McCain's insurgent candidacy is
increasingly tied to next week's California primary. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- March 1, 2000 -- SOCSEC-EARNINGS -- House
Speaker Dennis Hastert escorts Olivia Jackson, an employee with
Walmart, down the steps of the U.S. Capitol as they head to a news
conference, Wednesday. In uncommon election-year bipartisanship,
House Republicans and Democrats united Wednesday behind legislation
allowing 800,000 senior citizens between ages 65 and 69 to work
without fear of losing Social Security benefits. President Clinton
pledged his support. (Shana Raab/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- March 1, 2000 -- CUBA-BOY-COX --
Marisleysis Gonzalez, cousin of Elian Gonzalez, cries as she
testifies before the Senate Judiciary Committee on Capitol Hill,
Wednesday. Gonzalez said Elian's father in Cuba has been attempting
to signal to the boy's Florida relatives that he really wants his
son to remain in the United States. Congress is considering
legislation by Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., that would confer
citizenship on the 6-year-old shipwreck victim. (Rick McKay/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- CIR-3D-ROTATION --
Technology developed by iPIX uses a double-lens system, right,
attached to a camera to create 360-degree images, like these from a
bus tour of New York City. Computer users can tilt and pan through
the images online. (The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DEERFIELD BEACH, Fla. -- March 1, 2000 --
CIR-PHOTO-SHARING -- Right now there are more than 115 sites set up
to develop film or let people send photos via e-mail to friends and
create virtual albums, or to offer some combination of those
services. And by 2002, almost 10 percent of the photo finishing
revenues will come from online services. Andrea Millrad of
Deerfield Beach has been using online film processors for her card
business and for sharing photos. (John Ricksen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DURHAM, N.C. -- March 1, 2000 -- CIR-SWAP-SITES -- With
a string of new Web sites devoted to swapping unwanted items, it is
now possible that what you want can be bought with that old sewing
machine in the garage or your lightly dog-eared Dean Koontz novels.
Amanda Mack of Durham does not like to buy things online, but she
has traded balloon-flower seeds for marigold seeds at a swap site.
``I was kind of chuckling because I didn't think anyone would want
them,'' Mack said. (Jenny Warburg/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) RIVERSIDE, Calif. -- March 1, 2000 -- MCCAIN -- Sen.
John McCain listens to a supporter's words of encouragement as
McCain's wife Cindy looks on, Wednesday at a town hall meeting. As
the GOP presidential race heads into its deciding stretch, the fate
of John McCain's insurgent candidacy is increasingly tied to next
week's California primary. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LOS ANGELES -- March 1, 2000 -- BRADLEY -- Bill Bradley,
running for the Democratic presidential nomination, listens to his
aides while going over the site Wednesday of a televised debate
scheduled later in the evening between him and Vice President Al
Gore. Gore delivered a crushing blow to Bradley in Tuesday's
Democratic presidential primary in Washington, winning the state
where Bradley said he would make his most defiant stand, and where
he concentrated his resources for the past week. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- NY-VILLAGE-HOUSE-3 --
Television writer Tom Fontana in an office in his restored building
in New York's West Village. The building was built in 1887 as the
Jackson Square library by Richard Morris Hunt, a legendary figure
of the Beaux-Arts period and the architect of the main entrance of
the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Fontana who occupies the top two
floors as his living space and uses the bottom floors for business.
The renovations took two years and cost 1.7 million dollars. (Fred
R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- NY-VILLAGE-HOUSE-2 -- A
recently restored building in New York's West Village built in 1887
as the Jackson Square library by Richard Morris Hunt, a legendary
figure of the Beaux-Arts period and the architect of the main
entrance of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The restoration was
made by television writer Tom Fontana who occupies the top two
floors as his living space and uses the bottom floors for business.
The renovations took two years and cost 1.7 million dollars. (Fred
R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- NY-VILLAGE-HOUSE-1 -- The
restored reading room of a house built in 1887 as the Jackson
Square library by Richard Morris Hunt, a legendary figure of the
Beaux-Arts period and the architect of the main entrance of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art. The room was used by W.H. Auden and
James Baldwin. By the time Tom Fontana, a television writer, first
stumbled upon the house in the 1980's, it looked as though it had
been through a long journey. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) JERUSALEM -- March 1, 2000 -- CIR-ONLINE-PAYMENT --
Gedaliah Gurfein, vice president for marketing for TeleVend,
demonstrates who people can pay for softdrinks from a vending
machine using their cellular phone. Now, just when the language has
begun to absorb the letter ``e'' as a prefix, comes the latest
twist on electronic money and the language of the digital age:
mobile commerce, or m-commerce, which promises to turn your cell
phone or handheld organizer into an electronic wallet. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) RALEIGH, N.C. -- March 1, 2000 -- CIR-DENTAL-SCHOOL --
Todd Watkins at Vital Source Technologies demonstrating his
company's digital textbook atop a stack of the real thing that he
hopes someday will be replaced with his software. Starting this
fall, students at seven dental schools across the U.S. will be
asked to purchase a DVD containing the entire school's curriculum
-- textbooks, manuals and lecture slides -- for all four years of
dental school. While educators and electronic publishers have
talked for years about the advantages of creating digital
replacements for heavy and often quickly outdated printed
textbooks, digital textbooks have been slow to appear. (Jenny
Warburg/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- ZAGAT-PROFILE -- Tim and
Nina Zagat during a recent interview. Neither of the Zagats votes
in the restaurant surveys they publish, so they do not bother
trying to remain anonymous. But as acknowledged king and queen of
the dining scene, descending upon restaurants eight times a week,
their influence is such a given that it is merrily tweaked in the
current Off Broadway hit ``Fully Committed.'' (Chester Higgins
Jr./The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- March 1, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice President Al
Gore uses a television remote control while watching election
coverage in a hotel, Tuesday night. At right is Gore's daughter
Kristen. Joining Gore from his campaign staff are Donna Brazile,
his campaign manager, and Tony Coelho, campaign chairman. Gore
delivered a crushing blow to his opponent for the Democratic
presidential nomination, Bill Bradley, in Tuesday's presidential
primary in Washington. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CINCINNATI -- March 1, 2000 -- BUSH -- Gov. George W.
Bush greeted supporters Tuesday as voters made their decisions in
Virginia, North Dakota and Washington state. Bush won forceful
victories Tuesday over his rival for the Republican presidential
nomination, Sen. John McCain, in all the states. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
