<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Wednesday, 03/01/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) DOBROSIN, Yugoslavia -- March 1, 2000 --
YUGOSLAVIA-REBELS-2 -- Havere Saqipi, 15, at the graves of Isa and
Shaip Saqipi, her father and uncle, two Dobrosin woodcutters killed
by the Serbian police in January. Fighters in a newly formed branch
of the Kosovo Liberation Army say their organization was born that
day. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) UNDATED -- March 1, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W --
Baseboard molding is the wood trim that runs around the perimeter
of the wall at floor level. It serves as a decorative accent; it
also conceals the expansion joint between the edge of a wood floor
and the wall and covers gaps and flaws created as the house settles
and heaves. Whether you choose to install single-strip molding or
composite, the same basic techniques - mitering, coping and
scarfing - are needed. (Edward R. Lipinski/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) VARGAS STATE, Venezuela -- March 1, 2000 --
VENEZUELA-FLOODS-3-COX -- The week before Christmas, Vargas State
was hard-hit by floods and powerful mudslides which killed more
than 30,000 people. Passing through the debris of their home town,
two young girls skipped arm-in-arm, singing despite everpresent
reminders of the recent tragedy they've had to endure. (Marlene
Karas/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) VARGAS STATE, Venezuela -- March 1, 2000 --
VENEZUELA-FLOODS-2-COX -- The week before Christmas, Vargas State
was hard-hit by floods and powerful mudslides which killed more
than 30,000 people. ``Poquito a poquito,'' Sergeo Gonzalez said as
he tried to remove mud from his home, shovel-load by shovel-load.
``Little by little.'' (Marlene Karas/The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) VARGAS STATE, Venezuela -- March 1, 2000 --
VENEZUELA-FLOODS-1-COX -- The week before Christmas, Vargas State
was hard-hit by floods and powerful mudslides which killed more
than 30,000 people. The home of Maria Sariento de Lopez was filled
with mud several inches deep - an improvement over many of the
homes in the area. She peaked out the kitchen doorway to the dining
room where her daughter, Maria Elena, and her daughter's boyfriend,
Mauuel Falero, crawled over furniture to see what they could
salvage. (Marlene Karas/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- March 1, 2000 -- TECH-VISAS-COX -- U.S.
companies could hire an additional 45,000 high-skilled foreigners
this year under a bill introduced in the House Wednesday. Rep.
Lamar Smith, R-Texas, right, chairman of the House immigration
subcommittee, talked about the bill Wednesday in Washington while
Rep. Bob Goodlatte, R-Va., looked on at left. (Rick McKay/The Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) ATLANTA -- March 1, 2000 -- VIETNAM-PHOTOS-2-COX -- It
has been almost 25 years since the Vietnam War ended with the fall
of Saigon in April 1975. To mark the occasion, the Atlanta History
Center assembled a panel of veterans, refugees, journalists and
scholars to advise it on programs to go along with a new photo
exhibit entitled ``Requiem.'' The exhibit displays more than 200
pictures taken by the 135 photographers who died or became MIAs
during the war. (Sunny Sung/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) ATLANTA -- March 1, 2000 -- VIETNAM-PHOTOS-1-COX -- It
has been almost 25 years since the Vietnam war ended with the fall
of Saigon in April 1975. To mark the occasion, the Atlanta History
Center is running a new photo exhibit entitled ``Requiem.'' Bill
Poole, a lawyer and Vietnam veteran who helped plan the exhibition,
sat in front of a photograph which he took at Mocay Market in Tinh
Kien Hoa, Vietnam, during his tour of duty. ``I'm proud of what I
did in Vietnam,'' said Poole, 55. ``I think we were right to be
there.'' (Sunny Sung/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- COLLECTING -- William
Hamilton's Manhattan apartment in happier times, with the Toikka
glass candle pedestal behind the Knoll sofa, still intact. ``''It
smashed into loose change in seconds,'' he wrote of his prized
Finnish glass pedestal, which he accidentally knocked over. The
next day, the confessions started. `` 'That thing?' one friend
said, relieved. 'It made me nervous. I always thought I was going
to tip it over.' Others agreed. Too many others.'' (Jeffery A.
Salter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) CHICAGO -- March 1, 2000 -- LEWITT-MURAL-3 -- Two
hundred of Sol LeWitt's wall drawings have been installed in homes
around the world, said Susanna Singer, LeWitt's longtime agent. But
none was actually put there by LeWitt, who sells - for up to
$100,000 a wall - a design, with detailed instructions for how it
should be carried out. Sol LeWitt adapted a design, left, to suit
his clients' Chicago sitting room, but left the painting, right, to
installers. (Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) CHICAGO -- March 1, 2000 -- LEWITT-MURAL-2 -- Two
hundred of Sol LeWitt's wall drawings have been installed in homes
around the world, said Susanna Singer, LeWitt's longtime agent. But
none was actually put there by LeWitt, who sells - for up to
$100,000 a wall - a design, with detailed instructions for how it
should be carried out. An exercise room in Chicago was accessorized
with a LeWitt diptych found in a pattern book. (Steve Kagan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CHICAGO -- March 1, 2000 -- LEWITT-MURAL-1 -- Two
hundred of Sol LeWitt's wall drawings have been installed in homes
around the world, said Susanna Singer, LeWitt's longtime agent. But
none was actually put there by LeWitt, who sells - for up to
$100,000 a wall - a design, with detailed instructions for how it
should be carried out. When a Chicago couple wanted to embellish
their walls, they purchased 250 square feet of a LeWitt design.
(Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 1, 2000 -- ITALY-DOORS -- Several
Italian companies have recently introduced glass-and-aluminum wall
systems so sophisticated, they are not even known as doors.
Architectural without being massive, the wall system has glass
panels that are set into an aluminum frame and hung from ceiling
tracks. Jennifer Post, a Manhattan designer, has used the wall
systems to divide rooms, connect spaces, introduce light and add a
modern gloss. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
