<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MARCH 2
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-Y2K-LEAP-COMPUTERS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Feb. 27,
about the status of Year 2000 computer problems referred
imprecisely to a credit-card payment system made by CyberCash. A
small number of the 100,000 restaurateurs and small businesses that
use the system encountered billing problems because they had not
updated their software. The CyberCash system itself did not break
down.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MANAGEMENT-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Feb. 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Feb. 15,
about the daunting task of young managers who have to fire
employees included one example erroneously. IVillage.com says it
has never laid off employees for economic reasons and has not
recently trimmed its staff.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PATENTS-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Feb. 27,
about two new diagnostic tests for cervical cancer misstated the
ownership of one patent holder, Matritech Inc. It is publicly
traded, not private.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT (moved on Monday, Feb. 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Feb. 28,
about a comparison of teen-age pregnancy rates around the world
misspelled the name of the president of the Alan Guttmacher
Institute, which produced the study. She is Sara Seims, not Reims.
</P>
</TEXT>
