 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SWAP  &LR; _ Online trading has a whole new meaning now that a growing
number of Web sites are matching up folks who want to barter their
trash for other peoples' treasures. Many of these sites _ Spun.com,
Swaprat.com _ focus exclusively on used CDs for now, but others _
like Intellibarter.com _ list items as eclectic as photocopiers and
Hawaiian vacations. Where's the revenue? Some plan to charge small
per-trade fees in the future, while others follow the model of the
traditional used-CD shop, buying used goods cheap and selling them
at a mark-up. By Carrie Kirby
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SWAPSIDE _  &LR; While most swap sites are hoping they can persuade
adults to start trading their toys like children do, Pasadena's
Swap.com has simply set up a trading post for kids.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense: Children don't usually have credit cards or much
cash to buy things they want. And they get a lot of presents from
well-meaning adults _ often things they don't want. By Carrie Kirby
