<HEADER>
A3915 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     03-01 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Rolling Stone Finds Its Direction Home Courtesy of Emusic.com 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
What goes around, comes around for Rolling Stone.
<P>
   The magazine made its name by chronicling the rock and roll
revolution that grew up in San Francisco in the 1960s. But Rolling
Stone then forsook its hometown roots and moved to New York City in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Internet is revolutionizing the music industry,
Rolling Stone's electronic arm is coming home ... sort of.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine is staying put in its Manhattan offices, across
from Radio City Music Hall. But its Web site, at
www.rollingstone.com, has been acquired by a Silicon Valley
upstart, Emusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, which closed two weeks ago, Rolling Stone
magazine retains ownership of the domain name. On the site, the
magazine posts its extensive archives, its writers contribute
breaking news, and a staff of five Web-only writers and editors
post articles and review music.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine had licensed out the main business of running the
Web site to various Internet providers, most recently to a Chicago
company called JamTV that later became Tunes.com. In the deal that
closed two weeks ago, Emusic of Redwood City bought Tunes.com for
about $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Emusic owns the exclusive license to RollingsStone.com
until 2010, with an option to renew it to 2015. Emusic gives the
magazine company, which is still owned by founder Jann Wenner, an
undisclosed set payment each quarter and keeps everything above
that. Wenner also has an equity stake in Emusic.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, we have a venerable old media brand teaming up
with a prototypical Internet company. Emusic was established in
January 1998 and is led by 24-year-old Gene Hoffman _ that's right,
24 years old _ who says he's the youngest CEO of a Nasdaq company.
In the past quarter, it reported, ending December Dec.  &LR; 31, Emusic
had revenue of $423,000, while its net losses were more than $14
million. Its stock, which peaked in June at $35 a share, this week
hit its 52-week low. It closed yesterday at $5.59
</P>
<P>
   Emusic has grown largely through acquisitions; in addition to
snapping up Tunes.com, it also has bought DownBeatJazz.com and the
Internet Underground Music Archive, or IUMA.com. It says it's the
leading seller of downloadable music, with direct relationships to
post the digital MP3 formats of such artists as Elvis Costello,
Phish, Tom Waits, B.B. King and They Might Be Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rolling Stone brings to the table a huge brand, an unbeatable
brand,'' gushed Hoffman, the Emusic chief. But the magazine needed
training wheels online, he said, adding, ``This is a business in
which they were not fluent.''
</P>
<P>
   RollingStone.com likes the huge MP3 library that Emusic brings
and sees an opportunity to use its musical expertise to help Web
surfers navigate the MP3 maze.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much material out there, it's chaos,'' said Larry
Carlat, editor of RollingStone.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who do you trust to filter these things? People do trust
Rolling Stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual nature of a partnership between a venerable old
media brand and a flashy technology company is underscored by the
different routes Carlat and Hoffman took to their current posts.
Hoffman, who attended the University of North Carolina, came from
the geeky side of the business, having started a software firm. He
moved to Silicon Valley when he sold his company to Pretty Good
Privacy. He was a music fan who had managed bands and worked in
radio, and he launched GoodNoise Corp. in 1998, later changing the
name to Emusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   Carlat, on the other hand, is a New York magazine guy through
and through, having worked at Hachette Filipachi and Fairchild
Publications, and having written for Esquire, GQ and Self. He
joined RollingStone.com four years ago because, ``like a lot of
people in magazines, I always wanted to work for Rolling Stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 43, he'll be working with a 24-year-old  &LR; CEO who wasn't even
born when the Beatles, the Doors or Janis Joplin were in their
heyday. But that's OK, he said of Hoffman, ``He's old enough to be
my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MUNI METRO: &QL; 
Metro, a free newspaper now making waves in Philadelphia, may be
trying to splash down in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Metro gives subway commuters a quick read through the headlines
of the day. Already popular in cities from Stockholm, Sweden, to
Santiago, Chile, Metro ran into trouble when it launched in Philly
in January because of its unusual relationship with the local
subway authority.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of that deal, Metro is distributed at rail
stations,including some areas that other newspapers don't have
access to. That ignited the ire of the mainstream press, and
companies including Knight Ridder and Gannett sued the Southeastern
Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, trying to halt Metro's
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   That's not stopping Metro from looking to launch in other
cities, including San Francisco. Metro North America Vice President
Floyd Weintraub met with officials from BART and Muni to check the
chances of starting up here.
</P>
<P>
   BART spokesman Ron Rodriguez said Metro representatives made
``no formal or informal proposals.'' Muni spokeswoman Maggie Lynch
said, ``It isn't something we're actively pursuing. We have other
irons in the fire. Improving our service is our No.1 priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Weintraub said he'd love to bring Metro to the Bay Area. ``San
Francisco is a great city,'' he said. ``It has a great
transportation system. We think our product can be good for riders
and the transit agencies, if the conditions are right for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He said if the agencies express an interest, Metro will make a
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to fostd &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
