<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3916 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-EBAY-EBAY_SFCHRON &LR;      03-01 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wells Fargo, eBay to Start Billpoint Service  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;    c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Online auctioneer eBay and Wells Fargo announced an alliance
yesterday to let consumers make payments to other people by credit
card, a venture the companies hope will eventually replace checks
as the main way individuals send money to others.
<P>
   Billpoint, as the service is called, is starting as a payment
option on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   After refining its system on that site, the firm plans to roll
out the service to other electronic commerce sites and the general
public, aiming to seize a dominant share of payments between
individuals. EBay and Wells Fargo estimate the market at $100
billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like very much to see Billpoint become the
person-to-person and person-to-small-business payment standard,''
said eBay Chief Executive Officer Meg Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Most online auction buyers now pay for goods by check or money
order, which can delay transactions if sellers wait to ship items
until they receive payment.
</P>
<P>
   Using Billpoint, eBay buyers can use credit or debit cards to
complete a purchase. Sellers get paid immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Several young Internet companies, including PayPal.com, X.com
and dotBank.com, already offer person-to-person payment services by
credit or debit card.
</P>
<P>
   PayPal, for one, has already gotten wide acceptance. It was
cited as a payment option for nearly 300,000 items up for sale on
eBay yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't see much competition from big names in
consumer-to-consumer credit card payments,'' noted Scott Anderson,
an electronic commerce consultant with the Georgia firm Global
Concepts.
</P>
<P>
   That's likely to change fast. Several major Internet payment
powers are eyeing the online person-to-person market, using
customer credit cards, checking accounts or other systems as
payment vehicles. They say eventually individuals will routinely
use the Internet to send cash to one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's massively on our radar,'' said Ruthann Lorentzen,
marketing director of Transpoint, the Microsoft-sponsored
electronic payment company that the software giant recently agreed
to sell to online payment leader Checkfree.
</P>
<P>
   EBay bought Billpoint, a tiny Internet escrow company, for $125
million in May 1999. Wells Fargo, the West's largest bank, is
purchasing a 35 percent stake for an undisclosed sum.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts described the eBay-Wells Fargo alliance as a marriage
of convenience. EBay brings millions of customers looking for
payment options, while Wells Fargo offers an established
credit-card payment processing operation and a well-known name.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you introduce a product, it's often easier to do as an
ingredient of a familiar brand,'' said Chris Musto, an online
banking analyst with the Massachusetts research firm Gomez
Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Wells is already a leading Internet banking player, with 1.6
million online customers. Through Billpoint, it gets payment
processing income as well as part-ownership of a potentially
enormous enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   After a free introductory period, Billpoint will charge sellers
a minimum of 35 cents, up to 3.5 percent of the sale amount. In
addition, sellers must register with Billpoint to receive payments.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, anyone with an e-mail address can get payments
through PayPal and other services, and recipients don't have to pay
anything. The companies say they will get revenue as customers set
up accounts and deposit cash with them.
</P>
<P>
   Billpoint payments have nothing to do with the escrow service
eBay sells to customers who want purchases to be protected. A
customer who uses escrow can pay by check, money order or by credit
or debit card through Billpoint.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
