A3918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-     03-01 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY CHECKS INTO CLINIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla _ Darryl Strawberry checked into a
drug-rehabilitation clinic Wednesday in Florida, two days after he
was suspended for a year by Major League Baseball for violating his
after-care program.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry released a three-paragraph statement, typewritten on
plain sheets of paper, through the New York Yankees' media
relations department. There was no Yankee letterhead, no team logo.
``By the time you read this statement,'' the statement said, as if
to quote Strawberry, ``I will have checked myself into a
rehabilitation clinic, where I intend to be for the foreseeable
future. My goal is to take control of my drug addiction once and
for all and I believe that this step is required in order to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement continued: ``While I regret that I cannot say this
in person, I do want to express my sincere and heartfelt thanks to
the many people who have provided me with support through this most
difficult time for me and my family. My teammates, Joe Torre, the
Yankee organization and, of course, Mr. Steinbrenner, as well as my
doctors and the National Council of Alcohol and Drug Dependence,
have provided a bedrock of love, understanding and hope beyond
which I could have never imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also want to say to the fans everywhere, many of whom I
certainly understand are disappointed and perhaps even angry at me,
I will work every day of my life to restore the belief you have had
in me.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, declined to
comment on Strawberry's statement.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, 37, has been admitted to dependency-treatment
facilities twice before, in 1990 and 1994. Strawberry was suspended
for 60 days by Major League Baseball in 1995, after testing
positive for cocaine, and last year he was given a 120-day
suspension after being arrested for cocaine possession and
solicitation of prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading substance-abuse clinics in Florida is the
Hanley-Hazelden clinic in West Palm Beach, and there were reports
that Strawberry had checked in there. Several security guards were
posted outside the clinic but Jerry Singleton, the director of the
clinic, refused to confirm or deny whether Strawberry had been
admitted. The facility is part of the Hazelden Foundation, based in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The average patient stays for 28 days, Singleton said, and is
treated by a four-member team _ a medical director, psychiatrist,
psychologist and an addiction counselor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
