 _ SF CHRON  
 MAC Q&AMP;A/HENRY NORR  &HT;     New iMacs Work Well With MIDI Interface 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: I'm considering buying a new iMac, but I want to be sure that
I'll be able to hook up a MIDI interface to it for music
programming. Are MIDI devices compatible with the iMac? Where can I
buy one? And will I need an additional port to run MIDI and at the
same time be connected to both printer and keyboard?
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You're smart to check before buying, because when the iMac first
came out, and for a surprisingly long time thereafter, there was no
way to connect MIDI devices. Happily, that's now ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't know, MIDI stands for Musical Instrument
Digital Interface. It's the standard protocol for passing musical
data among computers, electronic musical instruments and
synthesizers. To use MIDI on a Mac, you need an external interface
box, which in turn connects to the musical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   There were two obstacles _ one hardware, one software _ when the
iMac appeared in 1998. For one thing, MIDI adapters were usually
made to connect to traditional serial ports, which Apple dropped
from the iMac in favor of the newer Universal Serial Bus (USB).
Second, the Apple software that manages the USB ports didn't
support MIDI.
</P>
<P>
   By now, though, many MIDI-makers, including big names like
Roland and Steinberg, have USB versions. You can find a good list
of them, with links to the vendors' sites, at
www.macintouch.com/imacusb.htmlMIDI.
</P>
<P>
   These devices aren't easy to find at local dealers or even mail
order and Web sites, but in most cases you can order them directly
from the vendor Web sites. Some are also available at USB Stuff, a
company that specializes in selling USB peripherals
(www.usbstuff.com).
</P>
<P>
   You're right that you'll also need another USB port, unless you
want to keep unplugging your printer every time you use MIDI. That
problem is easy to solve: Just pick up something called a USB hub,
a little box that connects to one of the iMac's USB ports and
provides several new ones in exchange (usually two, four or seven).
They're available at most dealers, with prices starting at around
$30.
</P>
<P>
   As for software, in addition to using Mac OS 9, you should
probably add a recent Apple patch called Audio Update, Version 1.3,
which you can download at
asu.info.apple.com/swupdates.nsf/artnum/n11573). The notes
accompanying the patch don't say explicitly that it affects MIDI,
but they promise ``improved USB audio support for computers using
Mac OS 9.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Browser Warning
</P>
<P>
   : Here's a problem no one seems able to help me with. My Mac
Performa 475, purchased in 1993, uses System 7.1p3. It works fine.
But recently, a dialog box started appearing whenever I open
Netscape. It says: ``Verisign Warning: You are using an older
browser with a security certificate that will expire soon.'' When I
proceed as directed, I am given a choice of two new browsers, one
for PCs and one for Power Mac. My computer is pre-Power Mac and I
don't think I can use any programs designed for Power Macs. Do I
have another option? If not, can I get rid of the dialog box?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: My advice: Learn to love those warnings until you're ready to
get a new Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Verisign is a company that develops software ``certificates''
that make it possible to do secure, authenticated transactions over
the Web. Both leading browsers, Microsoft's Internet Explorer as
well as Netscape Navigator, have such certificates built in.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that they were designed, on purpose, with a
finite life span _ in many older browsers, they were programmed to
expire Dec. 31, 1999. (The connection to the Y2K issue is strictly
coincidental.)
</P>
<P>
   For most users, the solution to this problem is simple: Just
download an up-to-date version of your favorite browser. But for
you and others with older Macs, things are more complicated because
both Microsoft and Netscape some time ago stopped developing
software for the Motorola 680x0 (sometimes written 68K), the chip
that powered all Macs until the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   There is actually a solution available for you, but I doubt it's
worth the expense and hassle. It turns out that Version 4.08 of
Netscape Navigator is compatible with pre-PowerPC Macs and has
certificates that are still valid. It's available on the Web at
www.netscape.com /download/archive/clientarchive 40x.html.
</P>
<P>
   The complicating factor is that that version requires Mac OS
7.6.1, according to Netscape, but you're still using System 7.1p3.
Apple will sell you a copy of System 7.6, but it will cost you $99
plus tax and shipping _ more than most dealers charge for Mac OS 9!
And then you'll have to download and install a four-floppy updater
to get to 7.6.1. If you're up for all that, you can find details at
til.info.apple.com /techinfo.nsf/artnum/n26170.
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't Apple make 7.6.1 available free, or at least at a
more reasonable price? Probably because doing so would let folks
like you get another year or two out of your old hardware, which in
turn would mean fewer sales of new Macs. It's decisions like that
that earned Steve Jobs his jet plane and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wiping Out Files
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have over 1,000 items, using up close to 20 megabytes on the
hard disk, in my browser cache. I think you've addressed this
question before, but could you please tell me again how to erase
all of those files?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually, I haven't answered that one before, but just about
every other computer Q&AMP;A columnist has, so I might as well take a
turn.
</P>
<P>
   Just launch your browser, go to the Edit menu and choose
Preferences. If you're using Internet Explorer, look at the list of
options on the left. Under the first item, Web Browser, you should
see 10 or so subcategories, the last of which is ``Advanced.'' (If
you don't see it, clicking on the triangle to the left of ``Web
Browser'' should reveal it.)
</P>
<P>
   Click on ``Advanced.'' On the right side of the Preferences
panel, under the heading ``Cache,'' there's a button labeled
``Empty Now.'' Click it and you're done.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to keep your cache growing right back up to 20
megabytes in the future, you can a smaller maximum size for it _
say, 5 or 10 megabytes _ by the value in the field labeled
``Size.''
</P>
<P>
   With Netscape Navigator the drill is similar, except that the
cache settings in the Preferences panel are under the last main
category, labeled ``Advanced,'' in the list on the left. (If
there's nothing under that heading, click on the triangle.) Click
on the ``Cache'' subheading, then on the ``Clear Disk Cache Now''
button. Here, too, you'll need to set a smaller size for the cache
to keep it from growing back to 20 megabytes. Note, though, that
Netscape lists the size in kilobytes, not megabytes, so if you want
to limit the cache to about 5 megabytes, type in 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever browser you use, be aware that the cache is there to
boost performance, and if you make it smaller, your surfing might
be slower, depending on the speed of your connection and how often
you return to the same pages.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mac Q&AMP;A runs the first Thursday of each month. Send questions to
Henry Norr at mac &LR; sfgate.com. Please specify what Mac model and
what version of the Mac OS you're using.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
