<SLUG> BC-SWAPSIDE-SWAPSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Kids Have Their Own Place to Trade Treasures  &HT;     By Carrie Kirby 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
While most swap sites are hoping they can persuade convince &LR; 
 &LR; adults to start trading their toys like children do, Pasadena's
Swap.com has simply set up a trading post for kids.
<P>
   It makes sense: Children don't usually have credit cards or much
cash to buy things they want. And they get a lot of presents from
well-meaning adults _ often things they don't want.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not really inventing something that kids don't do
already,'' said CEO Bill Keenan, whose says his three
grade-school-aged sons trade skateboard parts and other odds and
ends with their friends.
</P>
<P>
   But Web sites that cater to children are usually subject to fear
and scrutiny from parents. They also have to comply with stricter
laws than other sites. Starting April 21, the Children's Online
Privacy Protection Act will take effect, limiting the information
that sites can collect about children without their parents'
permission.
</P>
<P>
   In compliance with the law, Swap.com requires that parents give
their consent before a kid can sign up. In order to prove that
they're really the parent, mom or dad has to enter a credit card
number, an e-mail address and a telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   Online bartering presents an especially nerve-racking issue for
parents: In order to receive the goods they traded for, kids give
out their mailing address to the person on the other end of the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be another kid,'' warned Parry cq  &LR; Aftab, an
Internet lawyer who wrote the book ``The Parent's Guide to
Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a pedophile who goes out and buys buy  &LR; the
Pokemon things that kids really want, they'll trade them for
(nearly) nothing so kids will give out their address,'' she Aftab &LR; 
 &LR; said.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that risk, Swap.com offers to receive all packages
for children, then remail them, thus concealing the child's home
address from strangers. This service costs $5.77 per trade, in
addition to the 77-cent transaction fee that Swap.com plans to
charge when its free introductory offer ends.
</P>
<P>
   Parents could save the extra money and still protect the child's
address by arranging for the goods to be sent to a work address or
post office box, Aftab suggested.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Children age 10 and under should avoid trading things on the
Internet without a parent, but older kids should be able to barter
on their own, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Gaska, who lives in Florida, signed up her daughter
Shiloh, 11, for Swap.com. Shiloh traded two dresses she didn't like
for a make-it-yourself lamp kit and a doll. Gaska said she liked
the fact that the Web site e-mailed her each time her daughter
agreed to a trade.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Gaska had the option of contacting Swap.com and
canceling the trade.
</P>
<P>
   When Shiloh tried to list an unopened bottle of bath oil for
trade on the site, a representative from Swap.com called Gaska and
asked if the bottle had a safety seal on it. It didn't, so they had
to remove the item from the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was watching out for other people's kids, too,'' Gaska
said.
</P>
<P>
   The items available on Swap.com are not just Pokemon cards or
Barbie dolls _ some are surprisingly expensive. A Chevy S-10
pickup, truck,  &LR; full computer systems and electric guitars have all
been listed on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Parents always get an e-mail message alerting them that a truck,
or a doll or a videotape, is being traded. But lest parents skip
checking their e-mail for a few days, then come home to find the
family car missing and a new electric guitar in the den, Swap.com
calls and checks with a parent if an item seems outrageously
expensive, Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
