<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWAP-SWAP </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Making Little Deals Online  &HT;     By Carrie Kirby 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Madison Chabert, an actress who lives in Half Moon Bay, was dying
to attend last week's Grammy music award show in Los Angeles.
<P>
   Searching for tickets online, she stumbled across a Web site she
had never heard of before: IntelliBarter. Like eBay, IntelliBarter
of Santa Cruz serves as an online meeting place where people living
all over the world can get rid of stuff they don't want, and find
things they want. But unlike an auction, IntelliBarter _ and the
growing number of Web sites like it _ focuses on arranging trades,
not sales.
</P>
<P>
   To get the tickets, Chabert traded a signed photo of ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer'' star Sarah Michelle Gellar and a copy of the
script from the film ``Good Will Hunting.'' Now she's trying to
trade some TV scripts for tickets to the Academy Awards show March
26.
</P>
<P>
   IntelliBarter is one of many Web sites that have been launched
in the past six months by entrepreneurs hoping that swapping among
consumers becomes an Internet sensation. Other swap sites include
Switchouse (formerly known as SwapRat.com), WebSwap, MrSwap.com and
Qswap, all in the Bay Area. Based elsewhere are Swap.com, Spun.com,
SecondSpin.com and ExchangeAnything.com. But despite their
optimism, the concept of profiting by consumer-to-consumer
bartering is untested, and the sites face a number of daunting
obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists seem to like the idea: Sequoia Capital and
Accel Partners invested $13 million in WebSwap. And Swap.com, a
trading site for teenagers and children, has about $10 million in
capital, mostly from Pasadena incubator Idealab's venture capital
arm. Switchouse recently received $8 million in its first round of
venture funding.
</P>
<P>
   They are betting that consumers will like swapping because it's
useful and fun. Something that seemed worthless suddenly has value.
Outgrown baby clothes can be traded in for in-line skates. Unwanted
Christmas presents are swapped for office supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you're beating the system,'' said Michael Lin,
founder of San Francisco's Switchouse.
</P>
<P>
   And it's like a game: You make a wish list, post it on a swap
site and _ with luck _ a stranger comes forward to fulfill the
wish, in exchange for something you listed in your inventory. Or
someone offers you something you never thought of wanting. Some
sites even allow trading in services: ; &LR; one of IntelliBarter's
members _ presumably a dentist _ is offering dental implants for
trade.
</P>
<P>
   But swap sites need to persuade people to engage in a form of
commerce that many left on the playground when they outgrew trading
marbles and baseball cards. Swapping online involves hassle: On
most sites, you have to find another participant who has what you
want and come up with something they want in exchange. Then you
have to weigh, wrap and send the goods. Finally, you wait for your
goods to arrive _ if the person you swapped with comes through.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the companies persuade enough people to try bartering
online, can a business really squeeze much revenue out of cash-free
transactions among frugal individuals? While San Jose's eBay, the
Net's foremost auction site, is profitable, that site lists more
than 4 million items _ some costing more than $100,000 _ and takes
up to 5 percent of each sale.
</P>
<P>
   When no money is exchanged, and the goods are low-ticket items
such as compact discs, swappers may not be willing to pay much to
the Web site. So most of the sites plan to keep their transaction
fees under a dollar. At that rate, they're going to need a lot of
traffic to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man developed currency for a reason: to simplify
transactions,'' said Evie Black Dykema, an online retail analyst
with Forrester &UR;  &LR; Research. Dykema believes that all the barriers
that keep people from buying things online, such as the
inconvenience and expense of shipping things, will prevent the
barter market from ever becoming large enough to sustain more than
one Web site.
</P>
<P>
   MrSwap.com's founder, Patrick Ford, agrees that people don't
like to go to the post office to weigh and send packages. To solve
that problem, MrSwap.com will send traders an empty, postage-paid
mailer to send off a CD, game or video. This service costs $2.99
per order, just slightly more than it costs MrSwap.com to provide.
</P>
<P>
   MrSwap.com doesn't plan to charge a transaction fee. Instead, it
hopes to make money by letting retail partners _ such as Fingerhut
_ sell to its members, and by selling advertising. Another possible
revenue stream: MrSwap.com plans to distribute advertising leaflets
or free product samples in the empty mailers it sends its members.
</P>
<P>
   ExchangeAnything.com, a Massachusetts company that intends to
provide barter capabilities for a number of Web sites, is getting
around people's distaste for postage by arranging swaps according
to geographical location, then suggesting safe, public places where
the swappers can meet.
</P>
<P>
   But the main problem that swap sites face is that it's hard for
two people to agree on a mutually beneficial trade, especially if
the goods being exchanged are very different and difficult to
compare.
</P>
<P>
   To make matches more likely, Spun.com and SecondSpin.com are
concentrating on a commodity they see as extremely ``swappable''
because it's ubiquitous, inexpensive and has a narrow price range:
music on compact disc. Switchouse started out swapping CDs only and
is now introducing books, videos and games. MrSwap.com will launch
this month with similar categories.
</P>
<P>
   The founders of MrSwap.com decided that compact discs are a good
starting point when they learned in a survey that the average
consumer owns 109 CDs _ and only listens to half of them. Used CD
shops only pay $2 to $3 for a pre-owned disc, which means you would
have to sell five or six old CDs to raise enough cash to buy one
new one.
</P>
<P>
   But on most swap sites, you can trade one used CD for another of
about the same age and popularity. Or two of yesterday's Oasis
might net one copy of Santana's ``Supernatural.''
</P>
<P>
   On WebSwap, traders can swap absolutely anything, from lawn
mowers to baby-sitting service. To make swaps more likely among
these disparate goods, WebSwap's software searches for potential
three-way trades. So if the Grammy ticket holder hadn't wanted a
``Buffy'' photo, WebSwap may have found a third party who did want
it, and who could in turn provide something desirable, like a camp
stove.
</P>
<P>
   Or, Chabert could have offered to pay cash for the tickets or
sweetened the deal by adding cash to her barter goods. Both
IntelliBarter and WebSwap allow traders to use cash.
</P>
<P>
   MrSwap.com, Spun.com and SecondSpin.com eliminate the need for
``perfect matches'' by using virtual currency, or store credit.
Members sell CDs to the companies in exchange for points, and then
use the points to shop for other used CDs. This method is already
in use in offline barter clubs, where small businesses offer
services or goods to other club members, and get paid in barter
dollars instead of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer swapping may be fun, but business-to-business swapping
is where the money is, said Mary Cicalese, an analyst at Los Altos'
Internet Research Group. Parallel to the explosion in
consumer-to-consumer trading sites, business-to-business swap
forums have been starting up, with names such as BigVine.com and
uBarter.com. Unlike consumers, many small businesses are already
active in offline swapping clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer-oriented sites would do well to expand to
business-to-business swapping because the market is bigger _ $1
billion in goods are bartered by businesses in North America each
year, according to the International Reciprocal Trade Organization
_ and because getting rid of excess inventory is more vital to
businesses than it is to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pained every day by having 25 Pez dispensers in our
attic,'' Cicalese said. But in a business, excess inventory can be
fatal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
