<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEATHROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN TEXAS ORDERS RELEASE OF DEATH ROW INMATE WHOSE LAWYER
SLEPT AT TRIAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Tex. _ After 16 years on death row for a 1984 murder
conviction in which his lawyer slept through long portions of the
trial, Calvin Jerold Burdine was ordered released from prison
Wednesday by a federal judge because state prosecutors missed a
procedural deadline for granting him a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David Hittner of U.S. District Court, who voided Burdine's
conviction last year based upon the behavior of Burdine's lawyer,
had given prosecutors 120 days to set a new trial. The deadline
passed in January, and Wednesday Hittner ordered Burdine released
from prison within five days, although he did not bar prosecutors
from re-trying Burdine.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's order said that a retrial would provide Burdine with
another lawyer, affording him his constitutional right to counsel.
Thus a new trial would not violate Burdine's constitutional rights,
according to the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful development for Texas in that there is
someone looking out for the citizens and trying to keep them alive
in the face of bad lawyering,'' said William Moffitt, president of
the National Association of Criminal Defense Attorneys, in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Burdine was convicted in a state court in Houston in the April
1983 stabbing death of his former housemate and companion, W.T.
Wise. The conviction was upheld by the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals in 1986, but, last September, Burdine appealed the
conviction in federal court and won, when Hittner ruled that
``sleeping counsel is equivalent to no counsel at all.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the judge ordered the state either to retry Burdine
or release him within 120 days of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's order, Hittner appeared to be irritated with
state prosecutors when he wrote: ``Throughout its brief, the state
seeks to minimize its failure to comply with established procedural
rules as `excusable neglect.' However, a similar procedural error
by defense counsel in a capital case could result in a defendant's
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Contacted Wednesday at his Houston office, Hittner refused to
comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   A terse statement issued by the Texas attorney general's office
said: ``We are filing an immediate appeal and are confident the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals will block the release and keep
Burdine in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Moffitt, who has been a defense lawyer for more than 25 years,
said the case was unusual. ``The trend,'' he said, ``has been that
the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals generally passes on these kinds
of cases and allows people to die. I'm happy that a federal judge
at least has finally stood up and said, `Where there is an
ineffective lawyer, we're going to do something about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' death penalty policies have recently been the focus of
national attention both because of the number of people being put
to death and the visibility of Gov. George W. Bush's presidential
campaign. There have been 121 executions in Bush's administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
