<HEADER>
A3925 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WALMART-WALMART_SFCHR     03-01 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALMART-WALMART </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Wal-Mart.com Names Chief of Online Sites  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Jeanne Jackson, chief executive of Gap Inc.'s Banana Republic
division and head of Gap's Internet operations, was named yesterday
as CEO of Wal-Mart.com, the newly created online subsidiary of the
world's largest retailer.
<P>
   Wal-Mart.com, a joint venture with Palo Alto venture-capital
firm Accel Partners, is aiming for nothing less than to topple
Amazon.com as the Web's dominant retailer. The company expects to
go public by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 48, former president of Victoria's Secret, will leave
Gap Inc. at the end of the month. Gap said a trio of Banana
Republic executives will run the division on an interim basis after
Jackson departs. A new CEO will be chosen later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for her,'' said Janet Kloppenburg, an
analyst with broker Robertson Stephens in New York. ``She's been
very successful, and the Gap's sites are extremely well done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson placed 41st on Fortune magazine's 1999 list of America's
most powerful businesswomen.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has been courted by numerous other companies and
has consistently turned down all offers, Jackson told The Chronicle
that Wal-Mart's overture was too tempting to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   And she didn't just mean the oodles of stock options in her
compensation package.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will believe this, but that wasn't the most important
thing,'' Jackson said. ``I mean, you can only spend so much, and my
Gap stock has done so well already, I'm as comfortable as I want to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she admitted she'll be taking a hefty pay cut when she
moves from Gap's San Francisco headquarters to the
as-yet-undetermined Peninsula base of Wal-Mart.com.
</P>
<P>
   What compelled her to make the switch, Jackson insisted, was the
strength of Wal-Mart's brand and the company's commitment to
bridging the divide between its online and real-world sales.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wal-Mart has had an online presence since 1996, the
Arkansas company has struggled to establish itself as an e-commerce
powerhouse. Its partnership with Accel, announced in January, is
intended to reinvent Wal-Mart.com as a hip and cool place to buy
everything from books and CDs to toys and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what they don't know,'' Jackson said of Wal-Mart's
senior executives. ``They've stepped up to the fact that they need
partners who are Net savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Breyer, Accel's managing partner and one of three
Wal-Mart.com board members, said he first approached Jackson about
becoming CEO in December.
</P>
<P>
   The two had met only a month or so earlier, when, as chance
would have it, they were seated side by side on a flight from New
York to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent six hours together,'' Breyer recalled. ``I came away
extremely impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we moved toward finalizing the Wal-Mart.com deal, she was
the first person who came to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Breyer praised Jackson's management abilities, as well as her
strategic and marketing skills. ``She has an innate sense of what
consumers are looking for in an online experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sense will be put to the test as Jackson reconciles the
upscale style that is the hallmark of Banana Republic with the more
down-market sensibility of Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Her first goal will be to attempt to persuade at least a portion
of the 100 million customers who visit Wal-Mart stores each week to
give e-commerce a try.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart sees this as a more workable strategy than trying to
reach out to a whole new demographic, at least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also will seek to build on a recently established
alliance between Wal-Mart and America Online to create a co-branded
Internet service targeting rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is protecting the Wal-Mart brand,''
she said. ``If you tinker with that, you're tinkering with the
entire company.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson added that she isn't worried about grasping Wal-Mart's
well-entrenched corporate culture. ``My expertise is with great
brands,'' she said. ``Wal-Mart has one of the best brands out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Her past experience included stints at Federated Department
Stores, Saks Fifth Avenue and Disney. She joined Gap Inc. in 1995
as head of Banana Republic and soon took on the company's Internet
business as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson can only laugh now when she thinks how her life is
changing as a result of having shared a plane ride home with
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serendipity is an amazing thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
