<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BRAVES' COMPLEX, CIRCUS COMES TO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla., March1 _ Bobby Cox was pacing around the
batting cage watching the Atlanta Braves smack baseballs on an
empty field when Jim Schultz, the public relations director,
suddenly appeared in the dugout. Cox shouted to Schultz, summoning
him as if he needed a closer in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cox told Schultz that too many reporters were milling around in
the clubhouse so the manager planned to close it after the workout.
John Rocker had not even arrived at spring training, but the
ongoing distraction about the chatty and controversial reliever was
percolating.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves did inexplicably shut their doors, telling 20
reporters who were there that there was a team meeting.
Interestingly, several players were still on the field when the
meeting was supposedly taking place. It was a tense and hectic day
here and the atmosphere at the Braves' complex will turn into more
of a circus when Rocker rejoins the team for his first workout on
Thursday, following the reduction of his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see what he has to say,'' catcher Eddie Perez
said. ``Then, after that, we just need him to be quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   There were candid words, encouraging words and revealing words
from the Braves regarding the return of a 25-year-old whose own
disparaging words to a national magazine about various ethnic
groups have made him the poster boy for insensitivity. Since
Rocker's anti-New York diatribe, teammates, team officials, and
civic and political leaders have criticized him. Now Rocker's words
will be scrutinized once more as he has a chance to speak and
apologize to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John realizes that he needs to mend his place on this
team with his teammates,'' said General Manager John Schuerholz,
who did not discount the possibility of trading Rocker. ``I believe
that's his intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker told Tom Glavine he would apologize to his teammates,
including Randall Simon, whom Rocker referred to as a ``fat
monkey'' in the article. Rocker will also read a statement to the
news media, but the Braves were unsure if he would answer
questions. The Braves will also close their clubhouse on Thursday,
preventing reporters from seeing how teammates initially react to
Rocker. Major league baseball said it would not intervene and order
Atlanta to provide normal accessibility because this is an
extraordinary circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said all he needs to say to me,'' Glavine said. ``I'm
going to put more weight on how he acts every day and what he does
when he thinks no one is looking. As they say, actions speak louder
than words.''
</P>
<P>
   After Simon first heard of Rocker's remarks, he said that he
would ``bust'' him up. But Simon, who spoke eloquently on the
subject before a Braves official interrupted the interview,
softened his stance and will forgive his teammate as long as
Rocker's apology is sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time I was mad,'' Simon said. ``Everybody can be mad.
I got advice from my wife and my mother. Some of my friends said I
should hit him, some said not. I know anyone can make a mistake.
Why not give someone a chance?''
</P>
<P>
   Although Rocker will be returning, his future with the team is
not clear. Since Rocker will miss the first two weeks of the
season, the Braves will use Kerry Ligtenberg or Rudy Seanez as
their closer. Interestingly, Schuerholz, who never discusses the
names of players involved in trade speculation, spoke openly about
the possibility with Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been interest from other teams in John,'' Schuerholz
said. ``Whether he will be a Brave when the suspension is over, I
can't answer that with any more assurance than if you were to ask
me the question about anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz later said that Rocker would be the closer if he
maintains his ``effectiveness and remains with us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
