<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BOX-AYALA-BREDAHL-TEX     03-01 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-BREDAHL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAULIE AYALA COULD FIGHT FOUR TIMES THIS YEAR UNDER TOP RANK INC.'S
PROMOTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ As many as four fights loom for Fort Worth's Paulie
Ayala in 2000, but not the encore the reigning World Boxing
Association bantamweight champion wistfully wants most.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala capped his 1999 championship-winning season with a one-two
public relations flurry. Ayala was voted ``The Ring'' magazine's
Fighter of the Year, and his 12-round upset victory against the
formerly undefeated Johnny Tapia was selected as Fight of the Year
by the publication known as ``The Bible of Boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala logged 24 almost nonstop rounds in his victories against
Tapia and No. 1-ranked contender Saohin Srithai Condo of Thailand
in 1999, admittedly leaving himself with the mother of all tough
acts to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning all those awards last year, they've put me at such a
level to where, shoot, I want to fight myself,'' Ayala said with a
laugh. ``I mean, I want to beat that Ayala guy! But I guess what I
would say is I want to just try to defend my title and try to unify
it this year. Let's see if we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala's first action of 2000, and the opening round of promoter
Bob Arum's marketing plan for a fighter he projects as a ``midlevel
star,'' is scheduled to unfold Saturday night. Ayala will meet
Denmark's Johnny Bredahl, the reigning International Boxing Council
bantamweight (118-pound) champion, in a scheduled 12-rounder at the
Mandalay Bay Events Center. The bout will be Ayala's first in Las
Vegas since June 26, when he walked into the same ring in the same
arena as a 6-1 underdog and nobody and walked out as a real
somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of came out of nowhere,'' said Bruce Trampler, the
main matchmaker for Arum and Top Rank Inc. ``Paulie fought about 10
years to become an overnight sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he is poised to help Ayala, and Top Rank, cash in on
the most recent ``overnights.'' Ayala-Bredahl is the main event of
a four-fight TVKO pay-per-view card billed as ``Bring on the Heat.
Caliente!'' By world-title fight standards, it is a modest
production. Arum said the arena is being set up to accommodate
5,500 fans, approximately half of its boxing capacity. Competing
against the NASCAR Busch Grand National and Winston Cup races at
Las Vegas Motor Speedway this weekend, Arum said the fight has sold
approximately 2,000 seats. With brisk walk-up business on fight
night, Arum said the card could draw a respectable 3,500 to 4,000
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Paulie can be a midlevel attraction for us,''
Arum said at his office here yesterday. ``He'll never be an Oscar
De La Hoya. But we think that he can be a Johnny Tapia _ on that
level. Again, it's going to depend on how he draws on the
pay-per-view on this fight. It's going to also depend on how many
shots we can get him on HBO, because they're the ones that pay real
money. If we get him on HBO and in some marquee fights, he can make
probably as much as a half-million for a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he has been shopping Ayala to HBO executive Seth
Abraham for the cable network's newest boxing series, ``KO
Nation.'' Arum said the series is being slotted for late Saturday
afternoons in the fall, primarily from college campus sites. TCU,
for instance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The HBO stuff will definitely happen by the end of the year,''
Arum said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his crowd-pleasing style and squeaky-clean
lifestyle, Arum said Ayala's Hispanic-American heritage is working
in his financial favor. Ayala, 29, is scheduled to make a
career-best $150,000 for this fight, plus a percentage of
pay-per-view sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that Paulie will draw very well for us, particularly
in the Dallas-Fort Worth area, and in other areas in California and
the Southwest,'' said Arum, referring to potential Hispanic
pay-per-view buys. ``As far as we're concerned, those are the
markets now for boxing in this country. So, I look for exciting,
interesting Hispanic kids. They're the ones that enable me to
market boxing. And Paulie Ayala has always filled that bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum said part of the attraction to matching Ayala against
Bredahl, the WBA's No. 4-rated contender, is to expose the Texan to
the European TV market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a peripheral benefit that it showcases Paulie in Europe.
And that's great,'' Trampler said. ``But if you're rating
attractions in terms of the kind of shows we do, there's two weight
classes in boxing right now. There's the heavyweights, especially
where you've got Evander Holyfield and Mike Tyson and Lennox Lewis
and those guys, and there's whatever division Oscar De La Hoya is
in. Think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trampler said Ayala-Bredahl also delivers sizzle because it is a
``mixed-match'' racially.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the highest level \Rheavyweights\S, it doesn't matter what
flavor you are,'' Trampler said. ``Aesthetically, a little lower
down, if Paulie was fighting another Hispanic, it might not be as
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paulie's one of the better attractions below the
heavyweight/Oscar level. He hasn't risen to that double-digit
\R10,000-plus attendance\S level yet, but he may. He doesn't push
himself. He's not controversial. He doesn't get thrown in jail.
He's just a real nice kid. Sometimes it takes fans awhile to
appreciate ability, and the kind of character he has.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
