<SLUG> BC-PHONE-MARKETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC AND FTC MOVE TO CRACK DOWN ON DISCOUNT TELEPHONE SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government said Wednesday that it would
begin to crack down on what it said was widespread deception in the
way discount telephone services have been promoted.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown was announced by the Federal Communications
Commission and the Federal Trade Commission after the government
received thousands of consumer complaints about the services, which
advertise low rates for long-distance telephone calls, but include
additional fees that are advertised only in fine print.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies disclosed new guidelines intended to make
advertising more complete and less deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these ads are just galling to me because they are so
misleading,'' said William E. Kennard, the FCC chairman. ``They
aggressively market the cheapest rates, but they don't tell you
what's in the fine print.''
</P>
<P>
   At a joint news conference Wednesday morning, Robert Pitofsky,
the chairman of the FTC, held up a circular from Vartec, a small
phone company that advertised rates of 10 cents a minute in large
type.
</P>
<P>
   But in print so small Pitofsky needed a magnifying glass to read
it, the ad said that there was a minimum of 30 cents a call and
interstate calls were limited to 125 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you need a map as well as a magnifying glass to figure out
their rates,'' Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky also displayed a newspaper ad by AT&AMP;T that promised 7
cents a minute for all calls, and then noted in fine print an
additional monthly charge of $5.95.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Wednesday morning, AT&AMP;T ignored the
criticism and applauded the new guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``At AT&AMP;T, we have always adhered to the highest advertising
standards,'' said the statement, which was issued by James Cicconi,
the company's general counsel. ``Unfortunately that's not been the
case for all of our competitors. For this reason, we welcome the
guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said advertising practices had improved
recently. They also predicted that the guidelines would be an
effective remedy to past problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0527 </DOCNO>
