<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AUSTRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RESIGNATION PLOY IN AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, March 2: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jorg Haider's resignation as leader of Austria's Freedom Party
is a tactical stunt that changes little. With or without the title
of party leader, Haider remains the dominant figure in this racist
and Nazi-admiring party and, sadly, a defining force in Austria's
current coalition government. Europe, Israel and the United States
have rightly distanced themselves from Vienna, and should continue
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's resignation will cost him little in terms of party
power. Formal leadership now passes to his most loyal lieutenant,
Susanne Riess-Passer, who promises to continue their close
partnership. But as a nominally free agent, Haider will be able to
put a little space between himself and a coalition government whose
current unpopularity is likely to deepen as it proceeds with needed
tax increases and spending cuts. That could serve him well as he
pursues his open ambition to become chancellor after Austria's next
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Party won notoriety, and 27 percent of the votes in
last year's elections, by denouncing the presence of foreigners in
Austria in terms that echoed Nazi Party rhetoric. It wants to ban
all immigration, blaming foreigners for crime, drugs, welfare abuse
and the spread of tuberculosis in Austria's public schools. Freedom
also opposes the European Union's plan to admit the new democracies
of Central and Eastern Europe. Haider and other party leaders have
made light of Nazi crimes and urged respect for SS veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom's racist message siphoned votes from Austria's two
mainstream parties, the center-left Socialists and the center-right
People's Party. Both parties grew stodgy and complacent in their
long years of coalition rule. Still, 60 percent of Austrian voters
cast ballots for these two mainstream parties last October, and 7
percent for the environmentalist Greens.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Party leader, Wolfgang Schussel, erred badly in
imagining that the Freedom Party could be a respectable coalition
partner. Haider's resignation is not enough to reverse that
mistake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0528 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BPAMOCO-ARCO-FTC-NYT &LR;      03-01 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BPAMOCO-ARCO-FTC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AMOCO AND ARCO ASSAIL FTC ON OPPOSITION TO MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: West Coast)   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With wide gaps remaining in settlement
negotiations, BP Amoco and Atlantic Richfield Co. on Wednesday
accused the Federal Trade Commission of misinterpreting antitrust
law in an effort to block their $30 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed in federal court in San Francisco, the companies
offered the clearest glimpse of their legal defense, contending
that the FTC had failed to follow its own guidelines and that the
merger would ``benefit competition worldwide and in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers asked the court to stop the deal after the
commission concluded it was anti-competitive and could lead to
sharply higher prices for refiners in California and other West
Coast states where gasoline prices at the pump are already among
the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While lawyers for the companies recently began a new round of
settlement discussions, the two sides remain far apart. The
government has not altered its opinion even as BP Amoco has
essentially agreed to sell off the equivalent of all of ARCO's
Alaska assets in deals that it says would keep the market for
exploration competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The talks could continue until oral arguments in the case begin
on March 20. The commission's chairman, Robert Pitofsky, has grown
more cautious about approving large oil deals as the industry has
undergone a wave of consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's decision to try to block the deal has made the
proposed merger the largest in U.S. history _ both in terms of
combined revenue and purchase price _ to be challenged by the
government. But the oil companies have decided, unlike other
companies facing similar obstacles, to defend the deal rather than
abandon it, making the case an important test of the government's
interpretation of federal antitrust law, and one that could have a
substantial impact on future deals.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco and Arco asserted Wednesday that the commission had
basically bent antitrust law as it methodically tried to block the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FTC cannot demonstrate a lessening of competition in crude
oil sales to the West Coast,'' the companies said. ``BP Amoco and
ARCO do not compete in the U.S. West Coast states. BP Amoco sells
Alaska crude oil in those states; ARCO does not. ARCO sells refined
products in those states; BP Amoco does not. BP Amoco in Alaska
produces crude oil to sell to others; ARCO in Alaska produces crude
oil for its own refineries. Indeed, ARCO is a net buyer of crude
oil from other sources because it does not have enough to supply
its West Coast refining needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The oil companies also disputed the government's claim that the
merger would reduce competition for oil and gas exploration leases
in Alaska. Rather, they said, the revenues to both Alaska and the
federal government from leasing for exploration would actually
increase, not decrease, if the deal were completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FTC apparently has decided that in this case the normal
steps in the analysis should be ignored,'' lawyers for the
companies asserted. ``The reason is clear. Under proper analysis,
the FTC cannot demonstrate a likelihood of succeeding on its theory
that the proposed transaction is likely to lessen competition in
the sale of crude oil on the West Coast or in bidding for leases on
the North Slope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
