<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-01 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' GREEN TOO NICE TO BE A SUPERSTAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Somebody needs to tell Los Angeles Dodgers
right fielder Shawn Green he's playing this leading man role all
wrong. The public expects Leonardo DiCaprio, and he's giving it
Jimmy Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The first day Green reported to Dodgertown for spring training,
we could tell he didn't have a good bead on how to portray his
character. He was sitting in the training room talking with Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone when in walked retired pitching great
Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   Koufax is a primary vein that goes to the heart of the Dodgers'
mystique, but Green isn't supposed to get all flush in his
presence. The only thing the public expects to be more tenuous than
the modern superstar's grip on reality is his grasp of history. A
plausible performance would have been Green acting like it was a
coup for Koufax to be meeting him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Green behaved around Koufax the same way Malone's
10-year-old son would if he scored a personal audience with Haley
Joel Osment.
</P>
<P>
   His nerve left him like air from his lungs. He shyly greeted the
Hall of Famer as ``Mr. Koufax.'' Later, Green gushed, ``Mr. Koufax
is so down to earth, he takes the edge off.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Green could benefit from some direction by Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants outfielder wouldn't hesitate to remind Green he's
being paid for his home runs, not his wholesomeness; his
left-handed bat, not his boy scout's honor; his speed, not his
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown should pull Green
aside. Who better than he to advise Green that if he wants to come
across as believable in his role as one of the highest-paid players
in baseball he needs to strip a couple layers of polish from his
personality?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing sticks in the modern superstar's craw quite like the
knowledge that a rival is making more money. It's all about the
principal, and not the kind that sits in the bank, yielding
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Green has 84 million reasons to be serene. Over the length of
his six-year, backloaded contract with the Dodgers he will enjoy
the highest average salary of any position player in the majors.
That's no less than any club's leading man believes he is due but
more than Green acts like he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his contract, Green said, ``It's going to be nice
when some people pass me by.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that, talking as though setting the gold standard in his
sport was as discomforting as setting the pace in history's fastest
marathon. Somewhere in Port St. Lucie, Fla., Mike Piazza is shaking
his head.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, Green needs to hook up with Piazza on Sunday when the
Dodgers and Mets play an exhibition game. The one-time Dodgers
catcher evidently didn't get Green up to speed on greed when the
two players teed off last month in Las Vegas in the first round of
the resurrected Home Run Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Green also could use a few pointers on handling the fans. The
way he acts around the public is nothing like what we've come to
expect from the modern superstar. The first day of the Dodgers'
full-scale workouts here, Green gladly signed autographs inside
Holman Stadium while most of his teammates deferred until after
they had completed their workouts (if then).
</P>
<P>
   Green had just finished hitting and had a few hours of work left
when a teen-age boy wearing a New York Mets cap and a St. Louis
Cardinals T-shirt summoned the nerve to ask if he could have the
player's bat. To his wide-eyed surprise, he got it and a slightly
embarrassed smile from Green. Later that day the sixth-year veteran
would acknowledge, ``It's hard for me to say `no.' I want to please
people.''
</P>
<P>
   That simply won't do. You can't go around being nice to the fans
and then expect to be taken seriously in a starring role. The
Dodgers take on Baltimore in an exhibition game Monday. Perhaps
Albert Belle can be persuaded to pull Green aside and explain to
him that fans exist to be spit on, snarled at or stared straight
through.
</P>
<P>
   Green has none of the guile we've come to associate with the
modern superstar. He doesn't act like his personal information is
currency to be reserved for feeding the marketing machine.
</P>
<P>
   He oozes naivete. ``That would be a great word to use to
describe him,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros said.
</P>
<P>
   When Green mentioned to a reporter in Toronto last year that he
was exploring his Jewish heritage, he never dreamed rabbis would
try to reach him in every successive city the Blue Jays visited,
offering to officiate his bar mitzvah. It dumbfounds him that
synagogues in L.A. are competing for his membership.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for spring training, Green bought a house in L.A.
that is not in a gated community. It never dawned on him to seal
himself off from the public.
</P>
<P>
   That's not behaving at all like the modern superstar, who knows
fame runs with sycophants and psychos and arms himself accordingly,
with bodyguards and security systems and tons of wrought iron.
</P>
<P>
   There's no getting around it. When it comes to casting, Anne
Heche was more convincing as Harrison Ford's love interest than
Green is as the Dodgers' leading man.
</P>
<P>
   Green doesn't look the part, despite the fact he is strong and
supple and stands 6-foot-4. The modern superstar is expected to
wear tattoos like sunscreen and wear his weight in gold. Green, 27,
doesn't sport a tattoo, doesn't put diamond studs in his earlobes,
doesn't wrap gold ropes around his neck or wrists.
</P>
<P>
   His look is as austere as winter.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pity Raul Mondesi didn't leave a piece or two of his
jewelry behind when he migrated to Canada to take Green's place in
the Toronto outfield as part of the four-player deal that brought
Green to L.A. Goodness knows Mondesi had a few carats to spare.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing remotely flashy about Green is his swing. When
the ball comes off his bat, it's as breathtaking as light
reflecting off a diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers bullpen coach Rick Dempsey was pitching batting practice
the other day from behind a protective screen when Green stepped to
the plate and took a few cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball jumps off his bat so quick,'' Dempsey said. ``The
ball whizzes by the mound so fast, it's scary sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Gary Sheffield said he doesn't need to see Green at the
plate to know when he is hitting. ``All you have to do is listen to
the sound,'' Sheffield said. ``When he makes contact, it sounds the
same way every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Would you believe that's the most noise Green makes? In the
clubhouse he prefers to blend into the background. He acts nothing
like the modern superstar who is expected to sit at his locker
cubicle and yak on his cell phone or tell crude jokes to someone
across the room and generally suck all the oxygen out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Green can be drawn like a breath into a clubhouse game, so long
as it's chess. He and Karros went to war for two hours the other
day. When it became clear Karros had positioned himself for the
kill, Green didn't angrily sweep the pieces off the board with the
brush of his arm, as would be expected of today's leading man.
</P>
<P>
   Green played it out, same as he would if he hit a chopper back
to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Poor, misguided Green; he is infusing this character he has been
chosen to play with ability and courtesy and commitment and grit.
That's all well and good, but it won't play in Panorama City, much
less in Tinseltown.
</P>
<P>
   No, the public long ago was conditioned to discount genuine
greatness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
