<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-REID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE A TEEN - AGE DRUG DEALER, REID NOW SEEKS A CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ As a boxer, if David Reid does not take care of
things in the ring with his fists, his fate rests in the hands of
judges. But there was once a time when a Pennsylvania court judge
held Reid's fate in his hands, and his decision could have derailed
Reid's future as an Olympic champion and a world champion.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before the biggest fight of his career against Felix
Trinidad here at Caesars Palace on Friday night, Reid talked
candidly about his reckless years as a teen-age drug dealer in
Philadelphia and how his promising boxing career nearly got
sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   Reid faced three years in prison on charges of selling crack
cocaine, but a judge dismissed the charges and allowed Reid to get
on with his life as a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that if he saw me in his courtroom again he would
throw me in jail,'' Reid said. ``That was a chance of a lifetime,
getting off like that. I went on to win the Olympics, have a great
amateur career and now I'm in the pros.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid, who is 14-0 and the WBA superwelterweight champion, will
face the toughest test of his career against Trinidad (36-0), the
WBA welterweight champion. Reid will earn his biggest payday, $3
million, and Trinidad will make $4 million. The fight will be shown
on pay-per-view by Showtime Event Television, with the undercard
beginning at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, 26, has made a remarkable turnaround from the days when he
ran with a crew called the Marston Street Gang, selling drugs and
dodging bullets in North Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said he and some of his fellow gang members had been
sitting around one day when a car drove by slowly and someone began
firing from the passenger's side. The bullets missed Reid and the
others, but struck an 8-year-old boy in the back. The boy survived
the shooting, but he was severely injured.
</P>
<P>
   Al Mitchell, Reid's trainer, was a surrogate father for the
young boxer. Mitchell tried to get Reid out of North Philadelphia,
taking him to Northern Michigan University in Marquette, Mich.,
when Mitchell accepted a job there as the boxing coach in 1991.
Mitchell was also the coach of the U.S. Olympic boxing team. He was
trying to prepare Reid for the 1996 Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1992, Reid said, he had grown tired of his idyllic life
at Northern Michigan, where he was not a student. ``Too many trees,
too much fresh air, too slow, not enough noise,'' Reid said. ``It
was great for me, but as a young person then I didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid headed back to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went home that's all I knew was to sell drugs,'' Reid
said. ``I was selling crack. I never used it, because I knew what
it could do to you.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he sold drugs, Reid said: ``To eat. Money for
school. To buy clothes. I was young. I really didn't have to do it.
I could have gone another route, but I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his criminal activities nearly gave his mother, Marie, a
nervous breakdown. When Reid was 19, in 1993, he was picked up on
an outstanding bench warrant on a drug selling charge. Mitchell,
who had remained in touch with Reid, said he got his brother,
Arnold, who works at the state court in Philadelphia, to put in a
good word with the judge on Reid's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him this is a good kid, he just needs a break,''
Mitchell said he told his brother. ``About 85 percent of the kids
in the inner city need help. If someone doesn't pull you out,
you're going to get swept away.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid said he spent six days in jail on the bench warrant, but he
did not serve any time on the drug charges. He said the case was
dismissed, because the arresting officer in the case was himself
arrested and charged with selling drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said if he had gone to jail for three years, his life would
have been much different. ``I would have come out not wanting to
box,'' Reid said. ``I hadn't learned anything and I would have gone
back to the thing I knew, which was selling drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after he got out of jail on the bench warrant, he won
at the Olympic Festival. In 1996 he became the only U.S. boxer to
win a gold medal at the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say I've been through everything, but fighting
Trinidad is something I want to experience in my lifetime, because
being an Olympic champion you want to face the best,'' Reid said.
``It's either going to make you a man or a boy. This is the turning
point of my career. This right here is going to make me a man.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
