<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STORM-BARKLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA CRITICIZES ST. JOHN'S HANDLING OF BARKLEY CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president of the NCAA rebuked St. John's on Wednesday,
saying school officials had misrepresented the facts surrounding
Erick Barkley's eligibility case to the media and had refused to
follow the organization's procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Cedric Dempsey's statement was a departure from the NCAA's
policy of not commenting about possible violations _ the NCAA is
considering St. John's appeal of Barkley's suspension for receiving
tuition aid. His statement is also another sign of how contentious
the relationship between the two sides is.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA president disputed several claims made by St. John's
athletic director, Ed Manetta Jr., and its coach, Mike Jarvis.
Dempsey also challenged the school's defiant stance, which has also
been embraced by St. John's president, the Rev. Donald J.
Harrington, throughout the monthlong investigation into the Red
Storm's basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, a sophomore guard, was declared ineligible moments
before the Red Storm faced Seton Hall on Tuesday night, when the
NCAA ruled the $3,150 Barkley received from Riverside Church to
attend Maine Central Institute in 1997-98 violated the
organization's amateurism bylaw.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's statement, Dempsey disputed everything from St.
John's account of the hours leading up to that decision to the
repeated criticisms by university officials that the NCAA adheres
to a guilty-until-proven innocent credo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In media accounts today, St. John's has given the appearance
that the NCAA is holding up the process. Quite the contrary,''
Dempsey said in the statement. ``What held up the process is that
the university did not provide information necessary to make an
interpretation of NCAA legislation. The university has known there
was concern about the eligibility of one of its student-athletes
since Feb. 17. The university did not provide its final report to
the NCAA until late yesterday afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   At halftime of Tuesday's game, St. John's issued a statement
that said it had completed its internal investigation of Barkley's
tuition arrangement at 10 a.m. that day and ``at that time''
notified the NCAA there had been no violation. St. John's said the
NCAA informed them at 5:05 p.m., however, that a violation had
indeed occurred and Barkley must be ruled ineligible or the
university would face more serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey also challenged St. John's refusal to acknowledge that a
violation had occurred. Instead, Manetta asserted Tuesday that the
university and NCAA ``divert from each other on interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA staff works with its member schools every day to
interpret bylaws,'' Dempsey said. ``These bylaw interpretations
sometimes show that certain activities are contrary to rules and
are violations. The interpretation process is one that has been
used for years. When a university disagrees with an interpretation
of rules, it can take the issue to an interpretation committee for
review. St. John's declined to utilize this process.''
</P>
<P>
   Manetta said Wednesday that St. John's stands by its version of
the events. ``I can understand why the NCAA felt the need to defend
the process,'' Manetta said in a statement. ``I've read the press
release and I have no further comment other than to reiterate the
statement that we issued last night, which is accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey also indicated the NCAA has grown weary of St. John's
depiction of the organization as unfair and oppressive. When
Barkley was suspended on Feb. 5 for swapping cars with a family
friend who also was a Rucker League coach, Jarvis angrily compared
the NCAA to the Gestapo and said he felt he had been ``raped'' _
remarks for which he later apologized.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's has filed an appeal for Barkley's reinstatement that
will be ruled on by NCAA staff perhaps as early as Thursday. If
that appeal is denied, St. John's can ask the Division I
Reinstatement Appeal Committee to rule before the Red Storm's game
Sunday with Miami. That group is composed of administrators and
faculty members from across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, DerMarr Johnson of Cincinnati was suspended one game
and told to pay an undisclosed amount of restitution by the NCAA
for accepting $7,000 from a summer Amateur Athletic Union coach to
attend the same prep school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
