<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE NEGOTIATION INCHING ALONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Though slow and laborious, it appears
progress was made in negotiation between the Los Angeles Dodgers
and Adrian Beltre's agent, Scott Boras.
</P>
<P>
   Boras and Bob Daly, managing general partner and CEO, met for
two hours Wednesday at Dodgertown to discuss a multi-year deal. For
the first time during the negotiation process, financial aspects of
a contract were addressed.
</P>
<P>
   However, Boras wouldn't discuss the financial terms of what is
believed to be a three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exchanged a lot of data,'' Boras said. ``The dialogue is
good, the attitudes are good and we're doing our best. We got into
comparables (of how Beltre would measure to other players) and
discussions of more into the economics of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting Boras compared Beltre to other major-league
players who are making at least $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Daly would comment after the negotiating
session; the Dodgers media relations department failed to contact
Daly for a statement or to address requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Boras and Daly will talk again this afternoon and hope a deal
can be worked out before Boras leaves town Friday seems to be
fading. The negotiation is being bogged down by the unknown:
whether arbitrator Shyam Das will rule in favor of Beltre's request
to be a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, 20, is seeking free agency because the Dodgers signed
him at age 15, which is against baseball rules. A hearing date is
expected to be announced soon by Das, who just ruled on the John
Rocker issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of it is there are risks on both sides, and we
understand, and that's why we're negotiating,'' Boras said. ``But
this is not a customary negotiation. It is not something that is
standardized.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a player with Beltre's experience (one-plus year at the
major-league level) has his contract renewed by the club with
little incident or negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   As a player with less than three years service time, the Dodgers
must renew Beltre's contract by March 10. The club has its own
deadline of midnight tonight, but Boras made it clear that he's not
here to work on that. Beltre made $220,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be negotiating a one-year contract for Adrian
Beltre,'' Boras said. ``If the Dodgers are going to renew us,
they'll renew us. We're going to pursue this from the standpoint of
trying to resolve the issue as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Depth at shortstop: If Alex Cora wins the starting shortstop
job, which is what the Dodgers are planning, the club will probably
look to carry three players that have extensive experience at that
position.
</P>
<P>
   It may mean Jose Vizcaino, who manager Davey Johnson likes in a
utility role, and non-roster invitee Kevin Elster, who has the
right- handed power the Dodgers need off the bench, could make the
opening- day club.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you double-switch on the shortstop, you want to have
another middle infielder in case something happens,'' Johnson said.
``I have to have those parts, and I don't want to weaken my
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Castro will also be given a chance, but his lack of offense
is such an issue it makes him a long shot. Johnson also said
utility outfielder F.P. Santangelo and second baseman Mark
Grudzielanek, both of whom played shortstop, weren't part of the
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: The Dodgers signed pitchers Matt Herges, Jamie
Arnold, Kris Foster and Chad Ricketts and outfielders Kevin Gibbs
and Tony Mota to one-year contracts.... In need of power off the
bench, Johnson said he'll look at former Oakland slugger Geronimo
Berroa at first base to backup Eric Karros.... Sen. Jack Latvala
(R-Palm Harbor) officially introduced a bill to Florida legislature
that could provide $7 to $8 million of funding to various spring
training sites, including Dodgertown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
