<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNARMED MAN KILLED BY OFFICER JUST BLOCKS FROM WHERE DIALLO DIED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 23-year-old unarmed man was shot dead by a
plainclothes police officer Wednesday night after a struggle in a
Bronx apartment building just three blocks from where Amadou Diallo
was killed last year, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Malcolm Ferguson, who the police said was on parole for
a drug conviction, was shot once in the head, at about 6:30 p.m.,
and declared dead at the scene, said John Scanlon, the Police
Department's chief of patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of hours, scores of people had gathered behind
police tape on the street, some carrying signs in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said five housing officers who were part of an anti-drug
unit had been traveling to a public housing unit in the Soundview
section of the Bronx, but as they passed by, they noticed something
going on in a hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers went to go into the hallway, and one individual
bolted up the stairs,'' Scanlon said. ``An officer pursued after
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, on the second-floor landing, there was a
struggle,'' Scanlon continued. ``The officer's firearm discharged
and the individual succumbed.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m., Scanlon said that no weapon had been found on
Ferguson, but that there was ``a continuing investigation for
weapons and other evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the police had found that Ferguson was carrying ``a
quantity of heroin.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson had been arrested on drug charges six times dating back
to 1995, and was on parole until April 3 for selling drugs, the
police said. He was also one of dozens of protesters arrested last
Friday after the four officers who shot Diallo, an unarmed
immigrant, were acquitted of murder and manslaughter charges, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon said that the officer who shot Ferguson, Louis Rivera,
was Hispanic. Ferguson was black. Of the five officers in the unit,
one was white, two were black and the other two Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the head of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
who arrived shortly after the shooting, said that the police had
changed their story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not told there was a scuffle,'' Siegel said. ``I was
told initially that he was running from the cop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
