<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-Token-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        Democrats Bash Ridge on Education Remarks   By Laura J.
Winter   c. 2000 States News Service   WASHINGTON (March 1) -
<TEXT>
Pennsylvania's Democratic musclemen on Capitol Hill towed the party
line Wednesday admonishing Republican Gov. Tom Ridge for statements
he made about President Clinton's education funding priorities
Monday.
<P>
   Democrats the likes of former mayor Ed Rendell called Ridge's
comments partisan. The governor's spokesman Tim Reeves called the
Democrats' remarks ``Beltway backlash.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell, now chairman of the Democratic National Committee, Rep.
Bob Brady D-Philadelphia and senate hopeful Rep. Ron Klink
D-Pittsburgh called Ridge's statements ``offensive.'' They took
special issue with the governor's characterization of Clinton
administration programs and proposals as ``token little programs,
which really don't do anything except generate headlines and really
don't improve the public education.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor was referring to programs and proposals like
funding school construction, reducing class sizes by hiring 100,000
new teachers and Headstart - which already serves 30,000
Pennsylvania children, 7,000 of whom attend Philadelphia schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked he made that statement,'' Rendell said. ``Does
Gov. Ridge think that the 30,000 kids in Pennsylvania are
'token?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the governor meant is what he said,'' said Reeves. ``That
the Clinton Administration has forgotten what we know President
Clinton knew before becoming president. That is: the 'Beltway boys'
don't know best. There are literally 501 needs for our 501 school
districts. Some of the federal education initiatives are just what
they need and for some others it is not what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves added that during the governor's recent trip to
Washington, he pressed congressional GOP leaders to pay 40 percent
of Pennsylvania's special education bill - as is stated in the 1972
federal law - in order to free-up state education funds.
Pennsylvania receives 13 percent of its special education funds
from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In Ridge's proposed budget, the state will spend $97 million on
special education programs in Philadelphia - the missing 27 percent
in federal funds equals $26.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the governor in his meeting with congressional GOP
leaders missed an opportunity to bring federal school construction
dollars to Philadelphia and all of Pennsylvania. As part of his
budget proposal, Clinton asked Congress to give $24.8 billion in
tax credits to modernize schools and to appropriate $1.3 billion
for 8,300 renovation projects nation wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bit more offended because the city of Philadelphia is
effected,'' Brady said. ``I toured my district with the former
mayor. The schools are deplorable. The bathrooms don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have schools that are over 100 years old,'' Klink
said. ``What the governor is saying is let's put this on the
property owner and the taxpayer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
