<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CIGARETTE-TAX-680&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES TAX GONE FOR GOOD ON MOST CLOTHING; CIGARETTE TAX RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City shoppers found bargains Wednesday in
sweaters, slacks, leotards, lab coats and other garments as the
8.25 percent combined city and state sales tax was eliminated for
nearly all clothing and shoes at $110 or less _ this time, for
good.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut will cost the city $237 million in revenue in the
coming fiscal year, Department of Finance officials have estimated.
But Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, who has made sales tax relief a
priority for the past four years, predicted the repeal would
discourage New York shoppers from crossing the Hudson River to
avoid the tax, and the resulting spike in sales would ultimately
lead to thousands of new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In a classic example of one hand giving and the other taking
away, Wednesday was also the day that the state tax on a package of
cigarettes went up by 55 cents, to a total of $1.11, the highest of
any state. As the new tax took effect, newsstands that used to get
$3.65 to $3.85 a pack began charging $4.50 to $5.
</P>
<P>
   But clothing shoppers around the city Wednesday said they were
grateful for the sales tax break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked all night but somehow I found the energy to come out
and shop,'' said Carmen Flores, a registered nurse who headed for
Bloomingdale's as soon as she got off the night shift at Lenox Hill
Hospital. ``I'll probably end up spending just as much, but it
feels better knowing I'll save the tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sayevich, a New York businessman, said he waited until
Wednesday to buy clothes for his vacation. ``Basically, I'm looking
at this as a kind of bonus,'' he said as he emerged from Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   Before eliminating the sales tax, New York officials tested the
waters by staging seven sales-tax-free weeks, beginning in 1997.
Giuliani said these trials were a huge success, with some retailers
experiencing as much as a 77 percent increase in sales.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But some shoppers said Wednesday that they wished the ceiling
had been raised to $500, as it was during the experiment. Lora
Rassi, an interior design consultant from Manhattan, said the tax
relief would come in handy when she bought clothes for her two
sons, but not for her own wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to purchase things over $110,'' she said as she
examined _ and then rejected _ a pair of multicolored, sequined
slides that carried a $108 price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Four percentage points of the sales tax cut applied everywhere
across the state, with an estimated annual loss in revenue to the
state of almost $600 million, said Marc E. Carey, a spokesman for
the Department of Taxation and Revenue.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Local governments were given the option of deciding whether to
get rid of their sales tax, and only four cities besides New York
(Fulton, Norwich, Gloversville and Sherrill) and 14 of the state's
62 counties went along, creating disparities that are likely to
confuse consumers. In Westchester County, for example, the sales
tax now ranges from 2.75 percent in much of the county to 4.25
percent in Yonkers, New Rochelle and Mount Vernon. Rockland and
Suffolk Counties are tax-free, but Nassau County has a 4.25 percent
tax.
</P>
<P>
   Westchester officials rejected the sales tax exemption because
it would have cost between $27 million and $35 million, a loss that
would have required an increase in property taxes, said Susan
Tolchin, a spokeswoman for Andy Spano, the county executive. ``The
main problem in Westchester County is not high sales taxes,'' she
said. ``It's high property taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some confusion is also likely to arise when consumers try to
figure out which items are exempt and which are not. Belt buckles
and handkerchiefs are not taxed, for example, but handbags and hair
bows are. A sports uniform is tax-free, but a helmet or a catcher's
mitt is not.
</P>
<P>
   The exemption also applies to fabric, thread, buttons and snaps,
and to alterations made to tax-free clothing. But jewelry and
watches continue to be taxed. As do gowns for Barbie dolls and
coats for cocker spaniels. The exemption applies only to ``clothing
and footwear worn by humans,'' the department made clear.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sales tax relief was originally supposed to take effect on
Dec. 1 but was deferred at the request of the retail industry,
which feared that consumers would stay away from stores on the day
after Thanksgiving, a mega-shopping day known as Black Friday. But
that delay resulted in Wednesday's collision between the sales tax
cut and the cigarette tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers visiting newsstands and candy stores experienced sticker
shock.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Bent, who works in a theater box office, paid $5 for a pack
of cigarettes Wednesday and then went shopping for clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought a $40 jacket and gave the tax I saved over for
cigarettes,'' he said. ``It's a rip-off: you take away the sales
tax on clothes and raise the cigarette tax. I'm not getting a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional tax on tobacco _ intended to go toward providing
coverage for people without health insurance _ is expected to raise
about $273 million in the next fiscal year, said Carey of the state
taxation department. The last increase in the state's cigarette tax
came in 1993, when it climbed to 56 cents a pack, from 39 cents.
</P>
<P>
   For Muhammed Hossain, who operates a newsstand outside the
subway station at 72nd Street and Broadway, the tax increase was a
big blow. Still, his experience suggested that the increase would
have the desired effect of antitobacco groups, to discourage
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big drop in sales today,'' Hossain said as he was
hand-lettering a sign to reflect the new price. ``Nobody is buying
cigarettes today. Three customers gave their packs back when I told
them it was $4.50. One guy said: `This is my last pack. I'm
quitting.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
