<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR OPERA LOVERS, A WORLDWIDE WEB CYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (af)  
 By PETER DIZIKES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many opera buffs claim to be technophiles, but in my
observation, that usually goes only as far as their audio
equipment. They are generally happy to leave the world of computers
to the electronic music crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may be hard to imagine members of, say, the local
Wagner Society hunkering down to learn HTML, the Web has scores of
impressive sites about opera and is a rich source of information
about all aspects of this enduring art form.
</P>
<P>
   The sites include detailed reference collections, encyclopedias
of librettos, fan pages dedicated to performers, archives of rare
audio clips and global listings of schedules and performances _ the
better for planning that much-anticipated trip to Vienna or San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of opera, the Web is truly worldwide, and fans,
whether ardent or casual, have never had so much material at their
fingertips. Even a neophyte operagoer, using the Web, can easily
make arrangements to see a particular opera, study the libretto,
learn about its production history and sample some of its music.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious starting point for planning to attend a performance,
Operabase (www.operabase.com), available in six languages, contains
an exhausting (if not quite exhaustive) compilation of worldwide
schedules, recent reviews, festivals and opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   A searchable database even lets you to find out the activities
of specific performers: the mezzo-soprano Cecelia Bartoli, for
instance, will be appearing in Zurich, Paris and Berlin this spring
and summer, but not in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And Operabase's interactive global map is useful if you want to
fit some opera into a travel itinerary. I tried clicking on Europe,
then on Italy, and then Milan, and found that the schedule for La
Scala had been updated through next October. For each opera house
listed, ticket-ordering information was also provided.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have made plans to see a performance, go to the Public
Domain Opera Libretti site
(php.indiana.edu/(tilde)lneff/librettik.html). This site has a
formidable collection of 18th- and 19th-century librettos, and the
operas are listed by both composer and title.
</P>
<P>
   There are fewer modern operas, as these librettos are not yet in
the public domain. Translations are not provided, but there are
links to other libretto Web sites, as well as a lot of
bibliographic information about finding librettos in print.
</P>
<P>
   Those who just can't wait to get to the opera house can warm up
their vocal cords at home, using the Aria Database
(www.aria-database.com). It is a collection of the lyrics to more
than 1,000 arias, many of which also have sound files of the
background music in MIDI format. Of course, the sound quality of
these compressed files is not perfect. While listening to Don
Jose's ``Flower Song'' from ``Carmen,'' for example, it would be
hard to imagine that you were inside the Met.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, when it comes to singing along, your results may
also vary from Placido Domingo's.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of Domingo, the Tenorissimo site (www.r-ds.com), is
a thorough fan page that has a biography, a discography, a list of
Domingo's roles and links to the accompanying librettos. It also
lists his schedule, links to newspaper and magazine reviews that
are posted on the site the day they appear, audio clips and copious
photographs. It even has an audio file of his recorded New York
taxi message: ``Buckle your seatbelt for safety, because you are
important.'' Now, that's a fan page.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other fine fan sites about singers, and
Operaglass (opera.stanford.edu) is a good place to find links to
them. Operaglass itself is a trove of information, with a growing
collection of plot synopses, ``performance histories'' that show
when operas were first performed in various countries and a long
list of composers and their works.
</P>
<P>
   And for some aural history, readers can listen to singers from
earlier in the century at a Web site run by an idiosyncratic singer
named Carlton Higginbotham. This site (www.bassocantante.com) has
good audio clips of many famous voices, including Enrico Caruso and
Marian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   All told, opera lovers are taking to the Web so readily that I
may even have to change my long-standing image of them, and of
Wagnerians in particular. Although Wagner himself was chronically
wary of the future, at least 13 Wagner societies worldwide have
their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site of the Wagner Society of Northern California
(www.wagnersf.org) says, a bit awkwardly, ``Wagner is sometimes
best enjoyed in groups.'' True enough. And since these groups now
extend into cyberspace, perhaps opera is sometimes best enjoyed on
the Web, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
