<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-     03-01 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SENATE CAMPAIGN, CHARGES LINKING SUPPORTERS AND GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLEY COTTAGE, N.Y. _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton warned
elementary school children here about the danger of guns Wednesday,
her campaign staff sharply criticized New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani for accepting a donation from Charlton Heston, the
president of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani campaign countered with a statement saying that
Clinton was a hypocrite for bringing up the issue because her
campaign had accepted a donation from the rap impresario Sean
Combs, who was indicted last month on weapons possession charges
stemming from a shooting in December at a Manhattan nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Coming a day after a 6-year-old boy in Michigan shot a
6-year-old girl in a first-grade classroom, Clinton's comments were
calculated to buttress support from those who favor more stringent
gun control, which both she and Giuliani have advocated. In this
Rockland County hamlet, where she spent the morning talking to
students at Valley Cottage Elementary School, she said she would
strive to ``stop children from killing each other and stop guns
from getting into the wrong hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to end by asking you, because you are going to be such
good citizens, to do me a very big favor,'' Clinton said in a
gymnasium filled with fourth and fifth graders. She asked the
students to question their parents about whether they owned guns
and to promise that they would ``never play with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Her plea to the students, delivered before a phalanx of
television cameras, provoked an angry exchange between the managers
of the Clinton and Giuliani campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign manager, Howard Wolfson, issued what he
called a ``pre-emptive statement'' in the form of a news release on
Heston's $1,000 contribution in December to the Giuliani campaign.
``The National Rifle Association opposes the kind of sensible gun
control legislation that would save lives and prevent tragedy's
like yesterday's school shooting in Michigan,'' Wolfson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Giuliani's campaign manager, Bruce J. Teitelbaum,
said Clinton had undermined her position on gun-related violence by
accepting a $1,000 campaign contribution in October from Combs, the
entrepreneur rapper who performs under the name Puff Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mrs. Clinton wanted to make a statement about gun violence,
she should have returned that money,'' Teitelbaum told reporters at
City Hall. ``We're talking about hypocrisy and we're talking about
phoniness, and that is the core of what this is about.''
</P>
<P>
   In Rockland County, Clinton also traveled to Pearl River for a
lunch meeting of the Rockland Business Association. She told more
than 100 of the county's executives that she favored deregulation
of utility companies to lower costs for power and the creation of
business incubators for entrepreneurial concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended her campaign swing with a brief visit to nurses
picketing outside Nyack Hospital. The nurses, members of the New
York State Nurses Association, have been on strike for 72 days,
principally over what they say is inadequate staffing and the
requirement that they work double shifts, said Lee Levine, a
spokeswoman for the association.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose motorcade stopped for 15 minutes next to the line
of pickets, said she was making the visit as a ``morale booster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2317EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
