<HEADLINE>
NOTES FROM 1994 SHOW FED'S INNER WORKINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve began its last big round of
interest rate increases, in 1994, without any clear sense of how
strong the economy was, how many rate increases would be needed or
how the stock and bond markets would react, according to
transcripts released Wednesday of the central bank's policy
meetings for that year.
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts show the sway held over the policy-setting
Federal Open Market Committee by the central bank's chairman, Alan
Greenspan, and reveal how concerned Greenspan was even then with
the possibility that stock prices were becoming out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   After five years in which the Fed had cut rates and then held
them at low levels to nurse the economy through a downturn,
Greenspan recommended a quarter-point increase in the benchmark
federal funds target rate in February 1994, to 3.25 percent, to
forestall the threat that a recent surge in growth would generate
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately came under pressure from interest rate ``hawks''
to approve a half-point rate increase. But Greenspan pressed the
committee to go along with him, warning about the perils of a split
within the Fed and saying too big a move would destabilize the
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the committee voted unanimously to raise rates by a
quarter-point, as Greenspan wanted. It went on to raise rates six
more times in the next year, doubling the federal funds rate to 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, nearly three years before Greenspan began worrying
publicly about ``irrational exuberance'' in the stock market, the
Fed chairman was clearly concerned that investors were creating a
bubble in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when both the stock and bond markets fell sharply after
the February rate increase, Greenspan said the Fed had ``partially
broke the back of an emerging speculation in equities.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
