<HEADLINE>
TIMING TAKES ATTENTION AWAY FROM MISSOURI PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON and STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Super Tuesday isn't looking quite so super in
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   With California, New York and Ohio primaries taking place on the
same day as Missouri's March 7 voting _ and with big-prize Texas
and Florida to follow a week later _ presidential candidates and
their advertising dollars are rarely seen in the Show Me State.
</P>
<P>
   With 28 primaries or caucuses in little more than two weeks,
scarcity of time and money argue for skipping flyover country.
</P>
<P>
   So why should Al Gore come to Kansas City for a bite of
Missouri's 92 Democratic delegates when they could troll for votes
in Brooklyn and some of New York's 294 delegates?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that Missouri is being ignored on purpose,''
said Washington Democratic political consultant Annie Burns. ``It's
just that with these bigger states, Missouri would have had to have
its primary before March 7 to draw anybody's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Or why should George W. Bush spend days in a state that offers
35 Republican delegates when California offers 162?
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to play where the big enchiladas are,'' said Evan
Tracey of the Virginia-based Campaign Media Analysis Group.
</P>
<P>
   His company tracks where and when candidates buy television
time. So far, only former Sen. Bill Bradley has purchased blocks in
Missouri; commercials started airing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got all their money into running spots in California,
New York, Ohio,'' Tracey said. ``That's where there's the most at
stake in the next week or so.''
</P>
<P>
   The treasure trove of delegates available in 16 Super Tuesday
states easily ranks as the richest of the campaign. For Democrats,
31 percent of the 4,336 delegates are on the line. For Republicans,
nearly 27 percent of their 2,066 delegates are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Long gone, by measure of the 2000 campaign stopwatch, is the
time when a candidate could afford to blitz a small state such as
Iowa with radio spots, television commercials and mailed brochures.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller states such as Missouri, the campaign has moved to
the generic national monologues delivered on C-Span, the two-minute
stories squeezed into the network news and an occasional airport
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten something in the mail asking for money, but that's
it,'' said Harold Fridkin, a Kansas City lawyer and former aide to
the late U.S. Rep. Richard Bolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't sense there's much awareness among people that
Missouri has its primary coming up,'' he said. ``They just know
about the national campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that, he said, is because the local media haven't had
much to cover in the way of presidential campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dropped into Kansas City's Downtown Airport last week,
barely staying much longer than needed to refuel his plane.
Wednesday he sandwiched stops in St. Louis and Springfield while on
his way from Atlanta (Georgia has 54 GOP delegates) to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona is scheduled for an airport rally
Thursday night in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who grew up in Crystal City, Mo., officially announced
his candidacy there last year, stopped by the Kansas City Downtown
Airport last month but won't be here for the week leading up to
Super Tuesday. His wife, Ernestine, came to Kansas City on
Wednesday, however.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis supporters of Gore, who has come to Missouri 14 times
as vice president, hear he might stop in on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the bottom line,'' said Doug Hattaway, a national spokesman
for Gore, ``we have to go where the delegates are.''
</P>
<P>
   The political parties in Missouri pledge delegates in
dramatically different ways. For the GOP, all 35 delegates will be
awarded to the candidate who gets the most votes.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, the process is more complicated. Forty-nine
delegates will be awarded based on Tuesday's vote in the state's
nine congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   That March 7 vote also will determine the proportion of 26
delegates pledged to Gore or Bradley and chosen when party leaders
meet May 6 and 13.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the state will send 17 so-called ``super'' delegates to
the Democratic National Convention, mostly elected officials such
as Gov. Mel Carnahan and five members of Congress who are free to
back either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Any registered voter can participate Tuesday in any of the five
party primaries. So on Primary Day, voters can ask for a Democratic
or Republican ballot or one from the Libertarian, Reform or
Constitution parties.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's first primary was in 1988, the year U.S. Rep. Richard
Gephardt, a St. Louis Democrat, ran for president. However, efforts
to pass a law making the primary permanent failed, so caucuses were
held in 1992 and 1996. The law that created the 2000 primary and
made primaries in Missouri a permanent event passed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Rebecca Cook, an advocate of the primary
system, said the change will be a big improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the caucus system, only about 2 percent of Missouri
voters participated, and I found many Missourians wanting a primary
to have a better opportunity to be part of the presidential
selection process,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of Missouri's voters turned out for the 1988
primary, and Cook expects a similar turnout this year.
</P>
<P>
   But they'll be turning out for a contest in which the candidates
are slugging it out elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
