<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS MEET TO IRON OUT KINKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are plenty of excuses to explain a loss and
a tie in the Los Angeles Kings' past two games. But Bryan Smolinski
knows better.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings center met for 15 minutes Wednesday with coach Andy
Murray and linemate Glen Murray to discuss the lack of scoring and
intensity from the team's second unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better that we are fighting this now than during the
playoffs,'' Smolinski said. ``But we have to make sure this is a
two-, three- or four-game thing that everybody goes through. It was
good to meet and talk about things. (Murray) still has confidence
and that helps it not get out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   When Luc Robitaille, Ziggy Palffy and Jozef Stumpel were
sidelined in November and early December, the second unit carried
the offense. Smolinski was among the NHL's leading scorers and
considered the key to the deal that brought he and Palffy from the
New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, clocked with one of the league's hardest shots, had
three two-goal games in a five-game stretch. Donald Audette had 10
goals in his first 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   All that has faded. Smolinski does not have a goal in his past
seven games and one in his past 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no secret he has struggled,'' Andy Murray said
Wednesday, as the team was preparing for tonight's game against the
Carolina Hurricanes. ``We need him to work and play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Glen Murray had four goals on the Kings' seven-game trip but
played poorly in Tuesday's 1-1 tie with the Vancouver Canucks.
Audette's season has unraveled. He has one goal since Dec.14 and
spent six weeks on injured reserve with a badly sprained left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   During Audette's absence, rookie Jason Blake played the left
wing and showed good chemistry with the other two. Three games
after Audette's return, he was back on the second line and there
were comments on the bench about the loss of playing time.
</P>
<P>
   What made it worse in the tie with Vancouver was the Kings twice
botched 5-on-3 advantages on the power play. The blame didn't go to
the first line, which includes Palffy, the team's leading scorer
(63 points), and Robitaille, who has a career-high 14-game scoring
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski took the whole thing personally and has had several
discussions with Andy Murray looking for a solution.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been to the playoffs since the 1995-96 season with
Pittsburgh. With 19 games left and the Kings sixth in the
eight-team Western Conference race, Smolinski knows this should be
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to shut up and work hard,'' he said. ``It would
be great to get a goal. Even better to make it a power play goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0545 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-REPUBS-CATHOLICS-N     03-01 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REPUBS-CATHOLICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CATHOLICS PLAY DOWN STRIFE OVER BUSH'S BOB JONES VISIT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As New York's Republican primary approaches, Roman
Catholic leaders and laymen are playing down the importance of the
recent strife within the party over anti-Catholic fundamentalism,
saying they will likely vote on the basis of substantive issues
that touch their day-to-day lives and beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   From Bishop Thomas Daily of Brooklyn, spiritual leader of 1.7
million Catholics in Brooklyn and Queens, to Republican voters like
George T. Parker, a retired chemist in Rensselaer County, Catholics
said the dispute over George W. Bush's visit to Bob Jones
University was not the make-or-break issue of the election. The
school's president, Bob Jones, has called Catholicism ``the
religion of the Antichrist and a satanic system.''
</P>
<P>
   Daily said that while he considered the university's rhetoric
offensive, ``it's a matter of praying for them so they come to see
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Far more troubling, he said, was the Texas governor's record on
capital punishment. In recent years, Pope John Paul II and the
nation's Catholic bishops have become increasingly outspoken
against the death penalty. Since Bush became governor in 1994,
Texas has executed 120 convicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Catholics, if they're really concerned about issues,
even in regard to Governor Bush, they might be concerned about
capital punishment in Texas, where they put more people to death
than in any other state in the union,'' Daily said. ``That's the
more fundamental issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishop said voters in Brooklyn and Queens had more immediate
problems than debating whether Bush should have spoken at the
university. ``We have real concerns about immigrants and poor
people trying to survive, living two, three families to an
apartment to share the rent,'' he said, adding that health care and
education were also critical issues he hoped to hear the candidates
take on.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Richard Neuhaus, editor in chief of a conservative
monthly called First Things, said he considered Bush's appearance
at Bob Jones unimportant. ``Everybody speaks at Bob Jones,'' he
said. ``It's a major center down there, and politicians make
speeches where they have crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponent for the Republican nomination, Sen. John McCain
of Arizona, has repeatedly attacked the Texas governor for failing
to condemn the South Carolina school's anti-Catholic teachings and
its policy against interracial dating. The senator has used the
incident as a springboard for attacking some religious
conservatives on the Republican Party's fringe.
</P>
<P>
   The issue had the potential to be a significant one in New York
state, where 46 percent of Republicans are Catholic. But in
interviews this week, several Catholic Republicans described Bush's
visit to the school in terms more applicable to a missionary than a
politician, saying the Texas governor was ``reaching out'' to a
wayward element of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's trying to do is move it toward the center,'' said
Eva De Luca, 75, who meets each week with a small group of Catholic
women to discuss politics and other issues at St. John the
Evangelist Church in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she derided McCain's avowed goal of broadening
the party's appeal, saying, ``You don't exclude a major part of the
Republican Party, and then say you want to be inclusive. You're
cutting out a warm and important part of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   William Donohue, head of the Catholic League, a New York-based
national group that fights anti-Catholic discrimination, had
originally criticized Bush for his appearance at Bob Jones. But
then he formally called a truce after the candidate sent Cardinal
John O'Connor, the archbishop of New York, a letter apologizing for
not speaking up against the university's anti-Catholic record while
he was there.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's delay in apologizing was not lost on him, Donohue
said did not want the Catholic League ``to become the issue, by
being the one that demanded an apology, and then when he supplied
it, we said `that's not good enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``One of the great touchstones of Catholicism is
forgiveness for the wrongdoer who admits that he or she is wrong,
and there's nothing to be gained by beating this dead horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue said he believed, nevertheless, that anti-Catholic
bigotry was a serious problem in fundamentalist Christian circles,
one that some would prefer to ignore. ``There are some Catholics
who are so desperate to get a Republican back in the White House,
they're willing to overlook anything,'' he said. ``Our feeling is,
let the pus come to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue noted that Catholics had traditionally belonged to the
Democratic Party in New York, but that in the 1980s many were drawn
to the GOP by Ronald Reagan's charisma and by conservative
politics.
</P>
<P>
   But he warned: ``They didn't park themselves in the Republican
Party when they went over to Reagan. They're up for grabs. I think
Bush has alienated them.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, the 87-year-old retired chemist, said he voted
Democratic only once in his life _ for Franklin D. Roosevelt for
president. Parker said he had not decided how he would vote in the
Republican primary on Tuesday, but he said he had not warmed to
either McCain or Bush in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both playing politics and slapping each other around a
bit,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alexander S. Janow, a professional headhunter, called Governor
Bush's appearance at Bob Jones ``a terrible mistake,'' but said he
now considered it ``a moot issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Janow remembered the first vote he ever cast, in 1964 for Barry
Goldwater, the Republican candidate for president, who has remained
a lifelong hero. Before Goldwater's death in 1998, the former
Arizona senator said he feared that the religious right was
becoming too powerful in the Republican Party, Janow noted, adding
that he, too, worried about the party's alliance with ``intolerant
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Janow has not decided who will get his vote next week, but said
he was not averse to McCain's call for distance from the religious
right. ``I don't think the Republican Party will suffer for it,''
he said. ``In fact, it will be stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
