<SLUG> BC-INSURE-CONNELL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA MAY FACE HEALTH INSURANCE CRISIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ State Controller Kathleen Connell on Wednesday
said that the number of California residents without health
insurance continues to rise and could eventually have a negative
impact on the state's booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poorer health means a less productive work force and higher
medical costs for the state,'' Connell told an audience of health
care workers and economists at a symposium at the Skirball Cultural
Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, California spends $8.1 billion a year on Medi-Cal
alone to treat uninsured residents, which should increase to $10
billion by 2005, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium was sponsored by Connell's office and the
Healthcare Collaborative at the University of California, Los
Angeles. She also released a report titled ``The Importance of
Healthcare in California.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is immoral and deeply discouraging to think that in this
time of unprecedented economic growth and prosperity, so many
productive residents will be denied access to the most basic health
care,'' said Connell.
</P>
<P>
   In January, California's unemployment rate dipped to 4.7
percent. Over the 12 months ending in January, California's
employment grew by 3.1 percent compared with 1.7 percent
nationally. That translated into more than 350,000 new jobs in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the booming economy, one out of six uninsured people
in this country lives in California, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot expect to continue our current economic expansion
without providing comprehensive health insurance for California's
staggering 7.3 million uninsured residents,'' warned Connell.
</P>
<P>
   The number of uninsured increases by 23,000 every month, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   And 50 percent of California's uninsured live in households
headed by a full-time worker.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the health care industry agrees with Connell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Shield is looking at ways to increase access to health
care for the uninsured,'' said David Joyner, the company's vice
president of external affairs. For example, the Woodland
Hills-based company supports legislation to expand coverage under
the Healthy Families Program to parents of children covered by the
low-cost insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the rest of the nation, California is at a
disadvantage when it comes to providing health care coverage
through the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Only 48 percent of California companies now offer health
insurance to their employees, well below the national average of 61
percent, said Connell. The numbers are even worse for businesses
with 25 or fewer employees, she said, with fewer than two in five
offering their employees health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of the uninsured is predominately an affordability
issue, as the increase in the number of uninsured is driven by the
cost of health care,'' said Joyner. ``Policy makers concerned by
the uninsured should consider the financial impact of legislation
and regulatory mandates.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell noted that some companies are outsourcing health care
coverage to save costs. Xerox Corp. has opted to offer each
employee a flat amount of health care dollars to be spent on any
health plan he or she chooses.
</P>
<P>
   Employee are at risk for any overruns, but if they are fortunate
to have no health problems, they can pocket the savings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical health plan, the company would have swallowed any
increase in premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Connell added, ``The $63 billion health care sector has become a
dominant component of the state's economy. The changing
demographics of California will mandate the need for more and
improved health care delivery systems, products and technologies
between now and 2040.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
