<SLUG> BC-ADS-MORE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SURVEY SHOWS AD   TIME UP FOR THIRD STRAIGHT YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER ROSE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ How do you know there are too many ads on
television? Even the advertisers start grousing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Last November each hour of prime-time network television
contained an average of 16 minutes, 43 seconds of advertising and
other ``nonprogramming'' content, a jump of 59 seconds from the
preceding year, says a survey by the American Association of
Advertising Agencies.
</P>
<P>
   It's been this way for at least 10 consecutive years the
advertising group has been tracking the issue. And advertisers are
increasingly worried about it because they fear their messages can
get lost in the ad clutter.
</P>
<P>
   And prices for commercial time keep going up, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't measured this, but I would suggest there is a
direct correlation between the increase in clutter and a
diminishment in the effectiveness of our creative campaigns,'' said
Steve Grubbs, chief executive of OMD USA, a media buying firm.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Mandel, chairman of the AAAA National Television and Radio
Committee and an executive with the ad firm MediaComm Inc., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increases in clutter are a hidden increase in cost to the
advertiser and the economy. If the television industry doesn't
recognize soon that they are killing the golden goose, they will
lose the battle for the attention of consumers ... and the
attention of advertisers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising group measures both pure ad time and
nonprogramming time, which includes commercials, public service
spots and promotional spots for local and network programming.
</P>
<P>
   According to the AAAA, the amount of ad time has gone up by
nearly a minute and a half in just two years. Since 1991, the
average amount of commercial time in a prime-time hour has
increased by three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It's even more dramatic if compared with the '60s and '70s.
Watch an old TV show today, and you'll probably notice scenes and
credits chopped in order to make room for more commercials.
</P>
<P>
   They're not mentioned in the AAAA report, but children's shows
are the only class of programming during which the amount of
commercial time is regulated by the federal government. Guidelines
of a maximum 12 minutes of ads per hour on weekdays and 10 minutes
on weekends have been in place for a decade, following the
Children's Television Act of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of commercials carried on all other types of
programming is strictly up to the networks. In the face of stagnant
ratings, rising program costs and a booming market for ad time on
the part of dot-com companies, many networks have been packing more
and more promos and commercials into a typical hour.
</P>
<P>
   No network stood out in its ad time, with ABC leading the majors
by a small margin.
</P>
<P>
   Among the morning shows, ABC's ``Good Morning America'' averaged
about a minute more of ads per hour than its competitors on NBC and
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was last in total nonprogramming time, but showed the
greatest increase.
</P>
<P>
   And promos - those spots the networks run touting their own
shows seem to be becoming ubiquitous. During this year's Super
Bowl, there were almost as many commercials for ABC as for outside
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC spokesman said that network's head of promotion, Alan
Cohen, was out of the country and unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   George Schweitzer, executive vice president of marketing and
communications for CBS, said the network tries to be sensitive in
not running too many promo spots close together. Schweitzer said
these spots, which can be as short as five or 10 seconds, can
bother viewers when they're stacked together in quick succession.
</P>
<P>
   He said the amount of promos CBS runs has remained fairly
consistent over the past few years, and that the networks all
monitor one another and run a comparable amount of promo spots.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2325EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0551 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE-NYT     03-01 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY DISAGREE ON LITTLE IN A HARMONIOUS EXCHANGE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Meeting in their last debate before more than a
dozen states vote in primaries on Tuesday, Vice President Al Gore
and former Sen. Bill Bradley appeared uncharacteristically
harmonious together Wednesday night, going out of their way to
agree on virtually every issue and avoiding the kind of attacks
that characterized their raucous debate just over a week ago in
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley signaled early that he would not be too critical of Gore
when he passed up a chance to fault the vice president, as he
usually does, as failing to do more to combat racial profiling, and
they both then talked about their own proposals, forgoing their
usual potshots at each other.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wednesday night's was perhaps the most conciliatory of
their encounters, reflecting the recognition of both that with
Bradley's failure to win a single primary contest so far, the race
was likely to end soon.
</P>
<P>
   In one poignant moment, Bradley was asked what mistake in his
life he had learned the most from. He talked about how he learned
to fail from his rookie season with the New York Knicks in 1966-67,
when he had been heralded as the team's savior, only to be booed
and spit on by fans when he played poorly. Some of his supporters
have likened that traumatic year to the struggles of his current
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused me to ask myself, `You have to come to terms with
this,''' he said. ``I also began to see that life was not all good,
not all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, revising his answer after Bradley answered, said his
biggest mistake was not being kind.
</P>
<P>
   With both reining in the harshness that has characterized their
campaign, the two revealed just how ideologically similar they are.
Both were given a chance to condemn the evangelical right wing,
which they did. Both want legal recognition for gay partners,
although both oppose legalizing gay marriage. Both condemned racial
profiling. Both praised their wives.
</P>
<P>
   And both praised the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have watched any of the eight previous meetings
between Gore and Bradley, many topics seemed familiar, even if the
candidates answered the questions somewhat differently. Last week
in Harlem, for instance, Bradley asserted that the vice president
had shown a lack of leadership by not pressing President Clinton to
sign an executive order to ban racial profiling by federal
law-enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But when the question was raised Wednesday night, Bradley
avoided conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is the civil rights issue of our time,'' he
said, not mentioning Gore. ``It is no longer blocking people from
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has to stop. I want to be tough on crime. I want to
be tough on discrimination, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also passed on the opportunity to criticize Gore over
sending mixed signals on whether to allow China to join the World
Trade Organization. A few days ago, the former senator asserted
that the vice president had put ``the nail in the coffin'' of the
treaty that would bring China into the trade group when Gore
suggested to AFL-CIO officials that he might renegotiate the treaty
if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night, Bradley declined to make that argument when
a question about China and Taiwan relations was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Having repeatedly criticized Gore as a ``risk'' to the
Democratic Party because of his role in the campaign fund-raising
abuses of the 1996 presidential campaign, Bradley did not mention
Gore's problems Wednesday night. Instead, when a question about
money in politics was asked, Bradley spent more time talking about
the differences between himself and Sen. John McCain, the
Republican presidential candidate who has made an overhaul of the
system a centerpiece of his campaign. He noted that McCain was a
conservative on issue like abortion or the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore agreed. ``We can't talk about it too much,'' he said about
campaign finance reform. ``It is one of the major issues in this
campaign. It unites us, but it divides the two Republican
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes before the debate started, the Rev. Jesse Jackson
entered the room of reporters covering the candidates and announced
that he was endorsing Gore, whom he called ``the most qualified and
experienced candidate in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore team has sparked the greatest economic boom
in the history of this country,'' Jackson said. ``Therefore, the
vice president is perfectly positioned to continue this growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's announcement ends months of courtship by the two
Democratic candidates for his support. And while it is not clear
how many voters he might sway on his own, his endorsement is just
one of several by high-profile Democrats in recent days that have
added to the impression that the vice president has united the
party behind him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jackson called on Bradley to avoid creating the kind of
bitterness that split the party in 1980 when Sen. Edward M. Kennedy
of Massachusetts challenged President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That must not happen now,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to urge Bradley to quit the race. And he praised
the former senator for having raised important issues in the
campaign and having recruited athletes, including Michael Jordan,
into the party fold.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has his own history of bitterness with Gore. In 1988
when both men ran for the Democratic nomination, Gore and his
supporters criticized Jackson's position on Israel and other
issues, prompting Jackson to accuse Gore of negative campaigning.
</P>
</TEXT>
