<HEADER>
A4104 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-WEILDING-POWER-KAN &LR;      03-01 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEILDING-POWER-KAN </SLUG>
  
 IOUs PUT THE POWER IN YOUR HANDS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mid-level managers from some of the Kansas
City area's largest companies came for the Holy Grail of workplace
advancement _ the key to wielding power and influence.
</P>
<P>
   Eight hours later they had the secret: I scratch your back,
you'll scratch mine.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dwyer, director of the Management and Behavioral Science
Center at the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School, shared
his ``secret'' Tuesday at an Institute for Management Studies
seminar.
</P>
<P>
   First, Dwyer warned, don't confuse authority and power.
Authority is a temporary privilege granted by your position in an
organization. Power is the ability to persuade individuals over
whom you may have no authority.
</P>
<P>
   People who wield power best weren't born with charisma or
promoted into positions of responsibility over others. A powerful
person gets others to do what he or she wants by convincing them
it's in their best interest.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer, an executive and organizational behavior consultant,
admits his message is contrary in the team-based environments
fostered in many organizations. For him, power lies in one-on-one
influence:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to influence me, you have to plant in my head the
perception that your desired action is the best thing for me, that
it best fulfills my values.''
</P>
<P>
   He shuns mission statements and motivators that say, ``Do it for
the team,'' or ``It's good for the organization.'' Dwyer contends
teams and organizations have no values; values attributed to them
are the acting out of values held by their individual workers.
</P>
<P>
   If you get to know an individual and you scratch the other's
back by rewarding what he or she values, you create an
indebtedness, Dwyer says. And those psychological IOUs give you
power.
</P>
<P>
   When you do a favor for a co-worker (and toot your own horn just
enough to make sure it's known), the professor says, you maximize
your ability to get requested behaviors from that person in return
_ especially when you perceive the timing is right.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, immediately after you stay late and finish an
emergency project for your boss is the perfect time to ask for
tomorrow off in return.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the strategy is manipulative and self-serving. That's why
Dwyer cautions it must be accompanied by constant recognition of
and assistance to others. You need to fill a reservoir of good will
among co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   The more compliments _ handwritten notes are best _ you give,
the more others (bosses, peers or subordinates) will be inclined,
if not eager, to help you. You have made them feel good, and they
owe you something in return.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer also suggests that an effective tool for getting others to
do what you want is to say, ``I have a problem.'' You will get
better response than if you say, ``We have a problem,'' or ``You
have a problem,'' or ``The company has a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people want to help you _ not the organization _ provided
they trust and respect you and can tally up what they perceive you
have done for them. Everybody knows that, Dwyer says, but for most
people it's too much hard work to turn that secret key.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
