<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-COACH WATCHES LAKERS TOP BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the Los Angeles Lakers defeated the Portland
Trail Blazers on Tuesday, a familiar, professorial-looking
white-haired fellow watched the proceedings with great interest
from his seat at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Del Harris, the Lakers' coach for four-plus seasons until he was
fired in February 1999, is now working for friend Mike Dunleavy,
the Blazers' coach, as an unofficial consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did they do that?'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said with a
laugh. ``He's such a turncoat. They're paying him still in L.A.,
aren't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Harris' contract was to expire at the end of last
season anyway. Since his departure, he's worked briefly for one
longtime friend, Milwaukee Bucks coach George Karl, and now
Dunleavy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've coached many games against Del, and Mike too, so I know
there's only so much you can contribute,'' Jackson said. ``(The
Blazers) were well prepared, there's no doubt about their
preparedness, they know what we're going to run and everything
else, but execution beats that every time....
</P>
<P>
   ``Del's been very successful, he's had some good successes
against the triangle (offense), particularly. Mike has, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal was unaware his former coach was in the
building and working for the Lakers' biggest rival. But he said it
doesn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Del probably told those guys a couple of our guys' secrets,''
O'Neal said, ``but we don't have Nick (Van Exel) and Eddie (Jones)
and Elden (Campbell) anymore, so he probably only knows about me.
But nothing can break me.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers' personnel has changed a bit in the last year,
their offensive and defensive philosophies have changed to an even
greater degree under Jackson, which would seem to minimize Harris'
insights into the current team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he probably just told them personal stuff, like if you
bump this guy, he'll get mad, stuff like that,'' O'Neal said.
``What else is he going to tell them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have saw him,'' added O'Neal, who had his
differences with Harris. Would he have said hi? Yes. ``I'm a
cordial big man.''
</P>
<P>
   Bench boost: It's been a rare day that the Lakers' unheralded
bench has played a major role in a big win, but the reserves came
up huge at Portland, outscoring the Blazers' highly regarded second
unit, 25-18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's the experience of our players,'' Jackson
said. ``Rick (Fox), Brian (Shaw), Robert (Horry) are all
experienced players in the NBA. It is a pressure situation for
everyone, but it's not like they haven't ever been in this
situation before. And the capabilities are there for them to score.
Derek (Fisher), too, contributed last night....
</P>
<P>
   ``And then to win that kind of battle _ with their vaunted bench
and their backup situation - to win that on the road was a big
factor in winning the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
