<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S BACK! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY DON KETCHUM  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Admit it. You've been waiting a whole year for this.
Reaching into your desk drawer and pulling out the list of your
best excuses to e-mail the boss why you're not coming in today. Or
tomorrow or the next day . . .
</P>
<P>
   Cactus League baseball is back. So, break out the sun block and
prepare your taste buds for a hot dog, a bag of peanuts and a cold
one or two.
</P>
<P>
   The annual rite of spring begins today when six of the league's
10 clubs play their first game. The first full schedule of games is
Friday, March 2.
</P>
<P>
   In Tucson, the National League West Division champion
Diamondbacks open today, March 1, against the Chicago White Sox at
Tucson Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix area games feature the Milwaukee Brewers and Oakland
Athletics at Phoenix Municipal Stadium and the San Diego Padres and
Seattle Mariners at the Peoria Sports Complex. All games begin at 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will miss the fluid grace and lightning-quick bat of center
fielder Ken Griffey Jr., recently traded from Seattle to the
Cincinnati Reds. Plenty of smiles and home runs remain, however,
with the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa, the San Francisco Giants' Barry
Bonds, the Anaheim Angels' Mo Vaughn and the Diamondbacks' Matt
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   You also can see the Diamondbacks' 6-foot-10 left-hander, Randy
Johnson, the 1999 NL Cy Young Award winner, peering menacingly from
behind his glove.
</P>
<P>
   And don't worry, we won't tell the boss. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Are you, uh, ill and don't feel like working? Another season of
Cactus League baseball can provide chicken soup for the soul and a
chance to get an early start on that tan. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
