<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TREE-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTER NESTING IN A TREE IS ARRESTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How many police officers does it take to get a man
out of a tree?
</P>
<P>
   The answer in downtown Manhattan Wednesday was more than 50, as
a small armada of police officers _ including a squad on scooters
and a rescue team equipped with what looked like a super-size
inflatable mattress _ descended on City Hall Park to remove a
demonstrator who climbed an elm tree to protest the city's
bulldozing of a Lower East Side community garden last month.
</P>
<P>
   The event unfolded in the courtyard in front of City Hall, in a
tree that is more than 50 years old and stands just across from
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's office. The protester, Aresh Djavadi, 36,
climbed the tree at 9:30 a.m., carrying a dragon-fly puppet and a
sign that read ``11,000 vacant lots. Why take our garden plots?''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the dozen or so other protesters from Djavadi's
environmental group, More Gardens Coalition, also tried,
unsuccessfully, to perch in trees. By 10 a.m., the park had been
sealed off as 30 police officers prepared to remove Djavadi and
another 20 or so officers guarded the park's perimeter. Spectators
lined Broadway and Park Row, and City Hall staff _ including the
mayor's press secretary, Sunny Mindel, _ also went outside to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department Emergency Service Unit arrived in at least
three trucks, two of which carried small rescue boats and a medley
of other specialized rescue equipment. Before long, a blue and
white helicopter began to hover overhead, although the department
would not say whether it belonged to its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Djavadi, undeterred, continued to wave his dragon-fly puppet and
chant slogans, climbing even higher in the 70-foot, broad-reaching
elm as three officers went up after him.
</P>
<P>
   The police officers used portable fans to inflate a yellow,
10-foot-tall device intended for use in case of a fall. Meanwhile,
an officer reached Djavadi and put straps around his waist and
chest, giving him little option but to surrender. He did so at
10:55 a.m., and after climbing down the tree, was taken away in
handcuffs. He was charged with disorderly conduct, resisting
arrest, reckless endangerment and obstructing government
administration, Detective Robert Samuel said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar protests last year generated attention that led to the
preservation of 112 community gardens on city-owned lots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
