<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FLORIDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIALEAH SET FOR GULFSTREAM SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ South Florida's embattled race tracks
appeared to have taken a step toward some sort of peaceful
coexistence Wednesday when Hialeah Park announced it had reached an
agreement to run its season at Gulfstream Park starting two weeks
from Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which was declared ``a dead deal'' and ``a long
shot'' as recently as last weekend, was revived through a series of
all-night meetings that culminated with Wednesday's truce.
</P>
<P>
   Only the forthcoming season is involved, but both sides said
they detected good omens for the future of Florida racing, which
for 20 years has been torn by a dispute over which track could
operate during the desirable and profitable winter tourist dates.
</P>
<P>
   Hialeah will send its first landing party to Gulfstream next
week and will be in position to operate racing on March 17, the day
after Gulfstream closes its two-month meeting. But instead of
operating at the once-elegant jewel of a race track 15 miles south
of Gulfstream, Hialeah will be running its races at the more modern
facility at Gulfstream through May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Florida racing then switches to the Calder track, the third
point in the triangle, where it will be held for most of the rest
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that we've done it again, found peace in Florida
racing,'' said John J. Brunetti, the chairman of Hialeah. ``It's
been a long day coming. I, for one, feel this is a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonny Powell, executive vice president of Magna Entertainment
and the leading spokesman for Frank Stronach, who bought Gulfstream
last year, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though our leasing of our facility to Hialeah is
currently agreed upon for one season, we consider it to be symbolic
of the desire of our company and Stronach to work with all segments
of the Florida thoroughbred industry, including Calder, the
horsemen and breeders, to facilitate a positive spirit of
cooperation in order to make the highly respected Florida
horse-racing industry even stronger and more successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunetti said Hialeah would keep its barns open for trainers who
prefer to stable their horses there and train over its superior
surface. But he said not many other details had been reached. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
