<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley, Gore find common ground
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett and Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Calling a truce in their war of words, Democrats
Bill Bradley and Al Gore finished the last scheduled debate of the
Democratic primary season Wednesday with a largely high-minded
exchange that included none of their earlier animosity.
</P>
<P>
   The two agreed on a wide range of issues important to Democratic
voters and spent part of the time during their 90-minute debate
criticizing Republican candidates Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and
Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The civil, almost friendly encounter was a dramatic contrast to
their last debate in New York on Feb. 21, when they berated each
other on race, gun control and abortion. The change in tone, set in
a large measure by Bradley, may reflect the fact that Bradley
trails Gore badly in many key primary states and acknowledgement
that his attacks on Gore were not helping him.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again questions that 10 days ago prompted angry
outbursts from Bradley instead produced measured answers. Instead
of calling Gore the poster child for the National Rifle Association
when he was in Congress, Bradley directed his response at the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm there to beat the NRA,'' Bradley declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with that,'' Gore responded moments later. ``We have
to take them on.''
</P>
<P>
   The two tangled on one issue that arose during their last
debate, Gore's support of congressional legislation to prevent the
Internal Revenue Service from denying tax-exempt status to schools
that discriminate. Bradley said Gore's votes ``define who you
are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry you brought that up,'' Gore snapped. Gore described
his votes were on the issue of ``quotas,'' not extending tax
exemptions to schools such as Bob Jones University in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley refused to bite on a question that his presidential bid
was doomed, noting that only 250,000 Democrats had cast ballots so
far. But Bradley essentially declined to look beyond next week,
saying that Tuesday must be the ``take-off day'' for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates said they would nominate Supreme Court justices
who would not be strict constitutionalists, strongly implying they
would appoint justices that upheld Roe v. Wade, permitting legal
abortions. Both also said they would work with Congress to enact
strong hate crimes legislation to protect gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed that the federal government should not
over-regulate the Internet. Both candidates also suggested the
federal government should involve itself in local law enforcement
issues, such as the use of race to target suspects.
</P>
<P>
   They reserved some of their sharpest language for McCain and
Bush, calling them throwbacks who would turn back the clock on
abortion, gun control and race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore accused Bush of a ``calculated decision'' in apologizing to
Catholic leaders for his appearance at Bob Jones, which bans
interracial dating and whose founder has made anti-Catholic
statements.
</P>
<P>
   However, both Democrats were asked to defend their own meetings
with the Rev. Al Sharpton, who has fanned racial flames in his
native New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that he met with Sharpton privately, not publicly,
and said that he used the meeting to raise concerns about his past
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with everything that Rev. Sharpton has said or
done,'' Bradley said in answer to the question. ``But I think he
has grown. ... We have to allow people the right to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore headed into Wednesday's debate buoyed by more news that he
is solidifying his grip on the Democratic nomination. A Los Angeles
Times poll published Wednesday showed Gore with a 5-to-1 lead over
Bradley in California, which has the most Democratic delegates at
stake Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson endorsed Gore 15 minutes before the
debate began, calling the vice president the natural choice to
continue the economic policies of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
