<SLUG> BC-ASHCRFOFT-SCHOOLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASHCROFT SUPPORTS FEDERAL AID FOR ACADEMICALLY PRODUCTIVE SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri is proposing that
federal aid to failing schools in Kansas City, St. Louis and other
cities be tied to the schools' academic progress.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft planned to introduce a bill Thursday using federal
money to help failing schools emphasize basic classroom courses and
attract high-quality teachers.
</P>
<P>
   It would give additional money to schools on the rebound
academically and would make more college aid available to
high-achieving students in failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In conversations with school officials, parents and students
and in visits to schools in St. Louis and Kansas City, it was made
clear to me that federal resources should be doing more to benefit
the kids,'' said Ashcroft, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the bill calls for $800 million in additional funding
over five years _ $750 million of it for college assistance and $50
million for schools that regain lost state accreditation status.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City schools are to lose Missouri State School Board
accreditation May 1. St. Louis schools are on probation in lieu of
accreditation withdrawal. Ashcroft has mentioned the troubled
schools in his campaign for re-election against Gov. Mel Carnahan,
a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an effort to fix the blame; this is an effort to
fix the problem,'' Ashcroft said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's campaign manager, Marc Farinella, said Ashcroft's
bill is politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Ashcroft has not paid an ounce of attention to the
problems of urban schools until this election year,'' Farinella
said. ``Secondly, John Ashcroft was largely the reason the courts
ran those schools for two decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Farinella said that as governor from 1985 to 1993, Ashcroft
chose to litigate instead of negotiate a way out of the federal
desegregation order imposed upon the Kansas City and St. Louis
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnahan has finally made real progress in getting the courts
out of the way and returning schools to local control,'' Farinella
said. A federal court had lifted the desegregation order and
federal oversight of Kansas City Schools, but that was overturned
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft proposes that federal aid for schools failing to meet
state accreditation standards be based on whether they stress basic
skills courses, have more mentoring programs and hire and keep
high-quality teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that regain accreditation for two straight years would
have those funding restrictions lifted and would have access to $10
million annually, over five years, in new federal funding to reward
teachers and principals for improved student performance and for
professional development courses.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would at least double federal financial aid to
high-achieving students in failing schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
