A4129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-UPSTATE-JOBS-590&AMP;A     03-01 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UPSTATE-JOBS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 JOBS DATA PAINT A ROSIER PICTURE FOR UPSTATE NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upstate New York, where the economy remained bleak even as an
economic boom swept the rest of the nation, suddenly spurted ahead
of much of the country in terms of job creation, according to new
data for 1999 released Wednesday by the New York State Department
of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   And because job growth in and around New York City continued at
a white-hot pace last year, employment in New York state as a whole
grew faster than the national average for the first time since
1983, state officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The number of private-sector jobs upstate grew by 2.5 percent
last year, while downstate _ in the city, Long Island and the
northern suburbs _ private-sector employment jumped 3.2 percent.
Nationally, jobs grew by 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   New York state added almost 200,000 jobs last year, and is now
ranked seventh in terms of employment growth, behind Sun Belt
states like Nevada and Florida, but ahead of Texas, state officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those rankings are subject to change, economists cautioned, as
other states revise their 1999 economic figures to take account of
new data. It was just such a revision that pushed New York's
numbers up so sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The new jobs numbers could change the political climate in the
state, because the woes of the upstate economy have already become
an issue in the race for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Hillary Rodham Clinton said, ``If upstate New
York state were an independent state, it would consistently rank in
the bottom fifth of job growth.'' In 1998, the number of jobs
upstate grew by just 1.7 percent, while nationally jobs grew by 2.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Using the new 1999 data, upstate would rank about 13th, said
Stephen Kagann, chief economist for Gov. George E. Pataki. At a
news conference Wednesday, the governor called the new data ``clear
proof that this state is back.''
</P>
<P>
   The huge divide between upstate and downstate may also be
closing, at least economically. While New York City's job creation
and its suburbs continued at rates not seen since the 1950s, the
city's growth was outpaced last year by much of the Hudson Valley
and by Utica. The number of jobs increased in every major
metropolitan area, and the only city reporting slower growth than
in 1998 was Elmira.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a big dichotomy, but there's more of a
convergence now,'' said Jason Bramm, an economist at the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why or how the upstate economy has improved remains
unclear, although Pataki suggested that his administration's tax
cuts and regulatory reductions had played an important role.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing, which is extremely important to cities like
Buffalo and Rochester, continued to decline last year, cutting
almost 19,000 jobs statewide, or 2.1 percent. But service
businesses, whose employees range from computer technicians to
security guards, added 124,000 positions, an increase of 4.4
percent. And construction has been particularly strong, Kagann
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the huge revision _ the department of labor has
increased the job count for last year by about 60,000 from its
preliminary number, released in January _ economists generally
consider jobs data to be fairly reliable. Information is collected
from 18,000 companies around the state, and later replaced with
complete figures culled from records for the unemployment insurance
tax.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest revisions were in upstate cities like Buffalo,
Rochester and Albany, Bramm said. ``Has upstate suddenly staged a
rebound? No,'' he said. ``We suddenly realized upstate has staged a
rebound.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Economists are less confident in unemployment figures, which are
based on a far smaller survey and cannot be crosschecked against
tax records. In recent years, the unemployment data have not
tracked the job creation figures.
</P>
<P>
   For example, despite the big increase in new jobs last year,
unemployment upstate has not budged from the 4.1 percent level,
adjusted for seasonal factors, reported in January of 1999. In New
York City, by contrast, the unemployment rate has fallen to 6.1
percent from 7.4 percent during the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, unemployment averaged 4.0 percent in January, down
slightly from 4.3 percent a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
