<HEADER>
A4132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SKIING-FUN-NYT &LR;      03-01 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIING-FUN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIING: FINDING SOME ADVENTURE WHERE ADVENTURE IS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the ski and snowboard season heads into spring, it's still
not too late to infuse the waning season with a bit of adventure.
Groomed trails and the steeps are not bad for a steady diet. But
how about Snow-Cat skiing, a weekend clinic, or an overnight
excursion?
</P>
<P>
   One small way to stray from the straight and narrow is by
checking out the new toys available at most mountain rental centers
_ twin-tip skis, for example, or snow bikes. You can also rent a
new pair of high-performance shaped skis for an afternoon. Or you
can take a snowboarding or ski lesson to dust off residual bad
habits.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are up for more extended _ and yes, more expensive _
diversions, here are a few ideas:
</P>
<P>
   SNOW-CAT SKIING _ Although helicopter rides into powder fields
are fast and convenient, they are also expensive. But for a much
lower fee, Western ski areas are increasingly adding access by
Snow-Cat to their backcountry areas.
</P>
<P>
   The machines, ordinarily used for downhill grooming, are being
transformed into tank-like taxis for skiers and snowboarders. For
about $100 to $300 a day, these leviathans of the wilderness take
you to places where the powder is virgin and the hills are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   At Grand Targhee, Wyo., the out-of-bounds terrain covers 1,500
acres of mountainside with a 2,470-foot vertical drop. The
snow-laden slopes cater to about 20 people at a time _ 10 per
Snow-Cat. Last week, Targhee received 41 inches of new snow in a
24-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give out snorkels here as souvenirs,'' said Susie
Barnett-Bushong, a spokeswoman for Grand Targhee. ``But the snow
was so light, people actually needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to the best in powder conditions _ a day with
so much light and fluffy snow that skiers are said to need a
snorkel. White spray kicks up from downhill skis or snowboards like
a plume of spray _ enough to want that snorkel now and then for
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Other resorts that offer Snow-Cat skiing include:
Northstar-at-Tahoe, Calif.; Ski Cooper, Colo.; Big Mountain, Mont.;
and Deer Valley, Utah. Resort areas in the East usually do not have
deep enough snow or vast enough terrain to support Snow-Cat skiing.
</P>
<P>
   SKI CLINIC _ Tamara McKinney, the U.S. World Cup Alpine champion
who retired in 1989, is still in top form. Having joined forces
with Rossignol, the French ski manufacturer, she now gives
instructional clinics for women. A four-day seminar is being
offered this year from March 23-26 at Squaw Valley, Calif. ``We
want it to be an inspiring clinic where women can come and enjoy
skiing but also get technical advice and expert instruction,'' the
37-year-old McKinney said in a recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic is entitled Spirit of the Mountains. Participants are
being offered reduced room rates at the Resort at Squaw Creek, a
luxury hotel at the base of Squaw Valley's resort area. Rossignol
is making its newest skis and boots available to clinic members as
part of the $525-per-person entry fee (which also includes a
three-day lift pass at Squaw Valley). It will be a ``full-service,
luxury clinic,'' McKinney said. Special room rates start at $127 a
person based on double occupancy. The schedule includes videotaping
of participants during instruction and a subsequent race.
Information: (800) 401-9501.
</P>
<P>
   CROSS-COUNTRY TREK _ A two-day trip on cross-country skis or
snowshoes _ with a lobster dinner served in a canvas-covered yurt
at the end of the day _ is not your average wilderness adventure.
But it is a regular excursion for the Birches, a resort along
Moosehead Lake in Rockwood, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   It is situated on an 11,000-acre wooded preserve with 40 miles
of cross-country ski trails. Three yurts _ 12-foot round wood
structures covered with canvas _ are heated by wood-burning stoves.
Each is equipped with gas lights, a cooking stove and sleeping
accommodations (with linens) for four people.
</P>
<P>
   The cost for a two-day trip, including lunch and dinner and an
overnight stay in a yurt is $139 a person. The staff at the Birches
takes the lobster dinner by snowmobile out to the yurt. The resort
also hauls in personal luggage. The length of the season depends on
the level of snow pack on the trails, which this week was at an
ample three feet. For information: (800) 825-9453. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
