<HEADER>
A4134 &Cx1f; tab-z
r p BC-MCCAIN-SQUEEZE-INDEPE     03-01 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SQUEEZE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO-OR-DIE: MCCAIN MUST WIN CALIFORNIA, NEW YORK TO STAY ALIVE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The race for the Republican nomination for
president now enters its most intensive phase. The electoral
calendar is closing in on John McCain, with all the primaries which
really matter compacted into the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's sheer power of organization and his
establishment support should now start to count. Unless McCain wins
California and New York in a week's time, his campaign is all but
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican contest until now has been a guerrilla campaign
for McCain, as he picked off states one by one in bitter,
close-fought individual state races. The terrain and the style of
campaign favored an insurgent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it becomes a series of vast pitched battles, multi-state
primaries where he will find it far harder to score.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the primaries that are coming up are closed to Democrats
and independents, the constituency he has drawn on so far. The
Democrats will hold their own primaries on the same days, making it
harder to draw party switchers across to the Republican race.
</P>
<P>
   And the scale of the campaign _ from the Pacific to the Atlantic
_ favors Bush, who has already built campaign machines in all of
the key states with the millions of dollars that he has spent.
</P>
<P>
   The first hurdle comes next Tuesday when thirteen states vote
for Republican candidates, including New York and California, two
of the biggest prizes.
</P>
<P>
   In total, about a third of the country's population and the
Republican delegates are at stake. This is the single biggest event
in the electoral calendar.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is ahead in some of the polls in New York, behind in
others: it may be close.
</P>
<P>
   In California he is well behind. And even in New York, where he
may win, the voting system means he would not end up with all of
the delegates, whereas in California, the ``winner takes all''
system is used.
</P>
<P>
   There is more bad news: in California, though Democrats and
independents can vote, their scores do not count towards the choice
of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain could win the largest number of votes and still lose the
primary. This could make the results highly controversial and
perhaps even subject to a legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mega Tuesday'' also includes what amounts to a New England
regional primary, where McCain will probably win solidly. It is
possible that he could also make inroads in Ohio and Maryland. If
he won all those states and New York, but loses California, he
would still be trailing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Sky primary, three days later, again seems set to give
Bush solid support as Utah, Colorado and Wyoming vote.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain's home state of Arizona is not far away, the polls
in Colorado, the largest of the three states, show Bush in front.
That could all change with a victory in California, of course,
making the state yet more important.
</P>
<P>
   The following Tuesday, the second big event of the year will
deliver 16 percent of the delegates and it is here that McCain will
have his toughest day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Tuesday'' brings out most of the states in America's
South, which is fertile ground for Bush, as he showed in South
Carolina. Texas is his home state. In Florida the state's governor
is Jeb Bush, Bush's brother.
</P>
<P>
   In short, if McCain has not made some inroads before then, Bush
would almost certainly emerge as the clear winner on March 14 if
not before, with just short of the delegates he needs to win.
</P>
<P>
   Only if McCain can win California and capture some other large
states before then is he still in the race.
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to count the results, of course. McCain has
proved agile on the campaign trail so far, and the poll gaps
between the candidates are not large in some cases. A victory in
California would give his campaign huge momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of McCain's strategy are becoming clear. His
campaign has shifted ground in the last few days, attacking the
religious right. This will help him in some key areas where
Catholic, Jewish and socially moderate voters may make all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   It will underpin his support in the Northeast and New York, and
it could help in California and possibly Florida. In the South, it
will harden the vote against him, though this is probably lost
ground already.
</P>
<P>
   But it is an uphill fight. The hard arithmetic is that unless
McCain wins California and New York next week, and then takes
Florida the week after, his position looks impossible. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
