<DOCNO> NYT20000301.0571 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-COLUMN-SABRES-NYT     03-01 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HOCKEY: RESTLESS IN BUFFALO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mark Messier trade rumor is the hockey version of the Elvis
sighting. Wishful discussions on the subject are easy to start,
harder to verify. Having signaled his willingness to leave the
Vancouver Canucks before the March 14 trade deadline, Messier is
the subject of intense gossip. The New York Rangers and the New
Jersey Devils are in the swirl of speculation, and the Buffalo
Sabres were, too, for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Darcy Regier, Buffalo's general manager, called his Canucks
counterpart, Brian Burke, to ask about the availability of Messier,
a 21-year veteran who might have one more Stanley Cup run left in
his 39-year-old body. Burke told Regier he would not ask Messier to
waive his no-trade clause. That was the official answer. Mike Peca,
Buffalo's captain, has his own theory. ``Messier probably wouldn't
choose Buffalo as one of his destinations,'' Peca said.
</P>
<P>
   If that is so, that is a shame. Hard by the international
border, housed in a fine new arena, the Sabres are a prime
franchise with a loyal and enthusiastic fan base, the kind of
sub-Canadian team that deserves to convert its good community karma
to good results.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres will sell out 24 of their 41 home games this season,
not bad for a smaller market. But not all of those customers are
expressing happiness. Having watched their team reach the Stanley
Cup finals last June, the fans of Western New York are disappointed
to see the team struggling to make the playoffs this time.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Wednesday night's game with the Rangers at Madison
Square Garden, the Sabres ranked ninth in an Eastern Conference
that will send only eight teams to the tournament. They were 1
point behind the eighth-place Rangers, so the game had an added
edge beyond cross-state bragging rights. Regarding the attitude of
the paying public, Peca called the Buffalo fans ``very impatient,
and for good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of high expectations placed on us, by media,
fans and ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for Buffalo's struggles this season. Dominik
Hasek, the superstar goalie, had missed all but 19 of Buffalo's 64
games with injury. Collectively, the Sabres seemed to suffer a
post-playoff lapse, lacking enthusiasm for a long season after a
two-month tournament grind that ended in June with Dallas taking
the sixth and final game in overtime on a disputed goal by Brett
Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Peca said he understands the fan frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business now where athletes are being paid multimillion
dollar contracts and the ticket holders feel they can voice their
opinions,'' Peca said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a lot of that in Buffalo. But it has been good to
see us play our way out of it the last little while.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Wednesday night's game, the Sabres were 8-5-3 in
their previous 16 games and Peca had paced them. In the previous 17
games, he had scored 10 goals. But in the first 47 games, Peca had
only 6 goals.
</P>
<P>
   One of his best performances of the season came last week
against the Rangers at Marine Midland Arena. In the first half of
the game, Peca scored three goals and crunched Brian Leetch, the
Ranger captain, with a punishing body check. But after that, the
Sabres unraveled, losing by 6-3 as Hasek faltered and Petr Nedved
scored a hat trick for New York.
</P>
<P>
   That is the way it has gone for the Sabres all year.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from Buffalo's lineup Wednesday night was the rookie
Maxim Afinogenov, an exquisitely talented right wing with advanced
puck-handling skills. Afinogenov has 13 goals, fifth on the team,
in only 48 games, so his absence was curious for a team whose total
of 160 goals ranked 22nd in a 28-team league. Lindy Ruff, the coach
of the Sabres, kept him out of uniform for the second consecutive
game. Afinogenov is healthy, but the coach is not happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's slumping, he hasn't done a lot on the road,'' Ruff said.
``Most of his points of late have come at home. The guys who are
playing the best have to play. I can't give Max an extra inch or an
extra game to try to get him going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said his rookie star ``hasn't been creating'' in road games
and has been giving ``individual effort'' instead of working with
his teammates the way he does at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets a lot more attention on the road,'' Ruff said. ``Teams
lean on him more. They get the matchups they want on the road. If
we're trying to get the Peca line against a certain line, I can't
afford to get another change to get Max away from somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in Wednesday night's game, after taking a 1-0 lead, the
Sabres failed to score on two power plays. They are last in the
league on the power play. When a team reaches the month of March
without crossing the .500 mark, the reasons are many.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
