<HEADER>
A4138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT     03-01 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAK UP THE KIWIS: ROUT OF PRADA COMPLETE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ For the first time in the storied
history of the America's Cup, a syndicate outside the United States
has successfully defended the trophy that spent 131 years ensconced
in the halls of the New York Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after a dominating performance in which Team New
Zealand, the representative of the defending Royal New Zealand
Yacht Squadron, closed out the Prada Challenge in a five-race sweep
of the five-of-nine finals, another question has been raised: Will
it be another 130 years before anyone can wrest the cup from the
Kiwis?
</P>
<P>
   When pressed to discuss such matters as history or legacy in the
days leading to Thursday's victory, the Kiwi skipper Russell
Coutts' remarks never varied. Coutts insisted that the New
Zealanders' success was the result of a team effort, and for Race 5
he proved that his words were not empty ones by stepping off the
boat and handing the wheel to his 26-year-old understudy, Dean
Barker.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts' actions were all the more magnanimous considering that,
after Wednesday's victory, his record-tying ninth straight in cup
finals, he was in position with a victory Thursday to break the
fabled skipper Charlie Barr's nearly 100-year-old mark for
consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   With the veteran tactician Brad Butterworth virtually tattooed
to Barker's side and providing a personal wave-by-wave commentary
on the wind and his strategy, the youthful skipper picked up
exactly where Coutts had left off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a plan for our campaign to work new people in and it's
been a good thing,'' Butterworth said. ``Dean Barker's a great
yachtie. He's done a lot for us. I can't complain about how he
sailed the boat and I don't think anybody can.''
</P>
<P>
   If Barker was the least bit nervous, it didn't show. When Prada
attacked and tried to slip past the Kiwis' transom at the starting
line, Barker spun his bow down and closed out the Italians. Then,
timing his start perfectly, he led the Italians back to the line
and crossed 12 seconds ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a fantastic job at the start,'' Butterworth said. ``We
couldn't have planned it better and he couldn't have done it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the previous four races in this remarkably one-sided
America's Cup regatta, Team New Zealand was in absolute control.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an amazing feeling to finish this off in five races,''
Barker said. ``We talked about me coming on board earlier this
week. If we got a good lead, Russell said he was going to give me a
go. So today Russell asked if I wanted to race. How could I turn
down an opportunity like this?''
</P>
<P>
   The Italians, to their credit, did not lie down. The Prada
tactician Torben Grael did his best to dictate the action,
initiating a tacking duel with the Kiwis, but their boat, NZL60,
was the stronger vessel in every facet of the match. It had shown
better maneuverability in the pre-start dance, it was quicker
through tacks, and it was simply faster when the two boats legged
out.
</P>
<P>
   At the top mark of the first leg, the defender's lead was 24
seconds. And the Kiwis would never look back.
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon carried on, the breeze continued to build,
topping off at well over 20 knots for the first time in what had
mostly been a light-air series. If there was one downside to the
Kiwis' brilliant closing performance, it was that they finished the
series without showing the challengers what they had in the tank in
solid wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boat did really well today,'' Butterworth said. ``They're
not easy boats to sail, believe me. They tend to come together a
bit more in a breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Kiwis crossed the finish line 48 seconds ahead of Prada
_ under spinnaker, with whitecaps rolling down the gulf and spray
cleaving off the bow of their powerful black sloop _ for the first
time since they started dismantling the Italians more than two
weeks ago, they let loose with a show of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts clambered aboard and was soon joined by the rest of the
sailing team. Champagne followed, and corks were popped on the
Hauraki Gulf. In countless pubs and yacht clubs from Russell to the
north to Invercargill in the south, the scene was repeated
countless times. For the next three years, at least, New Zealand
will remain home to the America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep this team together and get better and better
and better, it would be great for this country,'' Butterworth said.
``Sailing has become something very special in New Zealand at this
moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2346EST &QL; 
