floods.
</P>
<P>
   That was last Sunday. For three days, she hung on not knowing if
or when help would arrive. She was into her fourth agonizing day,
without food or water, when the baby started to come.
</P>
<P>
   Racked by labor pains, she clung to the branches and, without
anesthesia, the infant was born.
</P>
<P>
   Sofia clung on, the lifeline of the umbilical cord keeping her
baby alive. And then suddenly out of nowhere, as if in answer to
her prayers, Sofia heard the clattering blades of a South African
air force helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than a dozen helicopters are operating throughout the vast
flooded area. ``We spotted her just in time,'' said an air force
medic named Godfrey, too modest to give his full name. ``I was
lowered onto the tree and helped her give birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Sofia and the baby were hoisted into the
helicopter. ``They were both doing well,'' Godfrey added.
</P>
<P>
   A South African television crew filmed the scene from another
helicopter. ``They winched down a paramedic first and he cut the
umbilical cord and cleaned them up,'' said a TV cameraman Adolf
Spangenberg. ``Then they winched up the baby, followed by the
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pedro, 26, and her baby, wrapped in a little bundle, were
taken to higher ground for medical help. After her ordeal, Mrs.
Pedro still looking dazed, said she was just ``happy'' that she and
her baby were alive.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll in the floods disaster is officially 200 but aid
officials believe thousands of corpses may be found when the flood
waters eventually recede.
</P>
<P>
   More than one million have been driven from their homes, with
numerous towns and villages completely submerged by water coursing
from the swollen rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 100,000 like Mrs. Pedro were left to cling to roof tops,
the branches of tall trees, floating debris or power pylons.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 4,000 other women are expected to give birth over the
coming weeks in difficult circumstances without medical assistance.
The U.N. Wednesday appealed for baby delivery kits to be included
in emergency aid supplies for Mozambique. &QL; 
