<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBITUARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Calif., Md., Pa., Mont., Fla., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Duning, 92, Composer for Films &QL;
</P>
<P>
   George Duning, an Oscar-nominated composer who wrote music for
films and television, died Feb. 27 at Alavarado Hospital in Los
Angeles. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Duning received Academy Award nominations for five film scores
he wrote for Columbia Pictures, where he worked from 1947 to 1962:
``Jolson Sings Again'' (1949), ``No Sad Songs for Me'' (1950),
``From Here to Eternity'' (1953), ``Picnic'' (1955) and ``The Eddy
Duchin Story'' (1956).
</P>
<P>
   Born in Richmond, Ind., on Feb. 25, 1908, Duning studied theory
at the Cincinnati Conservatory of Music and composition with Mario
Castelnuovo-Tedesco. He began his career playing trumpet in various
bands and then became musical director and supervisor of the NBC
radio show ``Kay Kyser's Kollege of Musical Knowledge.'' During
World War II he served as conductor and arranger for the Armed
Forces Radio Network, after which he joined Columbia. His scores
for the studio also included ``My Sister Eileen,'' ``That Touch of
Mink'' and ``Bell, Book and Candle.''
</P>
<P>
   His television credits included ``The Big Valley'' and ``Naked
City.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Lois, of Barrego Springs and La
Jolla, Calif.; two daughters, Kathleen Frankeberger and Patricia
Brayton, both of Port Townsend, Wash.; a brother, LeRoy, of
Lebanon, Ohio; two stepchildren; and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Blough, 98, Treasury Official under FDR and Truman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roy Blough, an economist who served in the Roosevelt and Truman
administrations, died Feb. 25 at a retirement home in
Mitchellville, Md. He was 98.
</P>
<P>
   From 1938 to 1946, Blough was director of tax research at the
Treasury Department and assistant to the secretary of the Treasury.
From 1950 to 1952, he was a member of President Harry Truman's
Council of Economic Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the 1950s, he was principal director of the economic
affairs department at the United Nations. He also taught at several
universities, including the University of Chicago, from 1946 to
1952, and Columbia University, from 1955 to 1970, when he retired.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote several books, including ``The Federal Taxing Process''
and ``International Business: Environment and Adaptation.''
</P>
<P>
   Blough was born in Pittsburgh on Aug. 21, 1901. He was a
graduate of Manchester College and received a master's degree and a
doctorate from the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Marie, died in 1992. He is survived by three sons,
Donald, of Providence, R.I., Richard, of Chicago, and William, of
Rock Hill, S.C.; five grandchildren, and four great-grandchildren.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jane Nickerson Steinberg, 83, Food Editor
</P>
<P>
   Jane Nickerson Steinberg, a former food editor of The New York
Times, died Feb. 27 at a hospital in White Sulphur Springs, Mont.
She was 83.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was Alzheimer's disease, said a son, John R.
Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   As Jane Nickerson, she was food editor of The Times from 1942 to
1957, when she moved to Lakeland, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   She was food editor of The Ledger, the newspaper in Lakeland,
from 1973 to 1988, her son said. In 1973, she published ``Jane
Nickerson's Florida Cookbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg was born on May 19, 1916, in Manhattan. She was
graduated from Radcliffe College and worked for The Saturday
Evening Post and Ladies Home Journal before joining The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Her marriage to Alexander Francis Steinberg ended in divorce in
1972. Besides their son John, of Lakeland, she is survived by their
two other sons, Josiah Bartlett Steinberg of Lakeland and Marc
Steinberg of White Sulphur Springs; their daughter, Alexandra
Kaghan Macaluso of Reston, Va.; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
