<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`PATHETIC'-FLOOD-AID-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FLOODWATERS ROSE, THE WORLD JUST WATCHED. WHY?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy 825-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RUPERT CORNWELL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Finally, a major if still barely coordinated relief
effort is under way for Mozambique. But as one of southern Africa's
greatest natural disasters in memory threatens to become even more
overwhelming, several burning questions remain.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the aid take so long to be mobilized _ and will it be
enough?
</P>
<P>
   Why were warnings of an imminent disaster misjudged when the
Zambesi and the Kyle Rivers were rising at three centimeters (over
an inch) per hour last week?
</P>
<P>
   And above all, why did the United Nations' quick response unit,
along with two officials from Britain's Department for
International Development, leave Mozambique last week?
</P>
<P>
   Now, at last, as the sheer scale of the flood catastrophe has
sunk home, Britain and other Western countries Wednesday began to
put together the assistance required to save the estimated 100,000
people already trapped and, to cope with as many more facing a
similar plight in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In the House of Commons, British Prime Minister Tony Blair
announced that Britain was sending two large transport aircraft to
Mozambique, carrying 69 inflatable boats, dozens of rafts and
several four-wheel drive vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft would be leaving Thursday, Clare Short, the
Secretary of State for International Development, said, promising
that the United Kingdom would ``do all in its power to get whatever
equipment we can get here as fast as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Other European countries are also despatching assistance, while
a giant American cargo plane landed at Mozambique's capital,
Maputo, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two more U.S. helicopters are also due shortly, to join those
from South Africa and Malawi already working flat out.
</P>
<P>
   The former colonial power Portugal has dispatched Luis Amado,
its top development aid official, to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But the flurry of action has not been not enough to mollify the
anger of international aid agencies at what they condemn as yet
another failure of the rich and self-centered West to respond with
sufficient speed to a crisis in a Third World country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this had happened in the West, the response would have been
entirely different,'' said John O'Shea, director of the Irish
relief agency Goal, who called the effort of the big powers so far
``pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all the noble promises of assistance, it was far from
clear how fast help would arrive. Short denied claims by some
newspapers that squabbling between her department and the Ministry
of Defense had held up the effort.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, every sign is that the crisis will worsen
before it gets better. According to Mozambique's President, Joaquim
Chissano, up to one million people are ``in movement'' _ refugees
in their own country.
</P>
<P>
   As some aid agencies admitted, one reason for the delay lay in
their own misjudgement. ``We were caught on the hop,'' Eileen
Maybin, of Christian Aid, admitted.
</P>
<P>
   She and most other observers believed that the worst of the
crisis was over by last weekend. Instead, new surges of flood have
come from inland along the great rivers, while another cyclone is
barrelling in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is terrible and going to get worse,'' Short
warned the Commons.
</P>
<P>
   But how to explain the failure to react to earlier warnings _ as
early as Feb. 18 _ when Zimbabwe was warning of imminent overflow
of the Zambesi and the Kyle Rivers?
</P>
<P>
   When the United Nations and the outside world did wake up to the
danger, there were familiar bureaucratic tangles in Europe while,
on the spot, tensions emerged between Mozambique and the U.N. Rapid
Response Unit, as the latter announced a $13 million appeal without
consulting the local government's own disaster agency, INGC.
</P>
<P>
   The quarrel was patched up when both sides launched a far larger
joint appeal for $65 million, but precious time and energy had been
consumed.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor has been the failure of Africa itself to respond.
Apart from some help from Malawi, a long tongue of whose territory
extends south into Mozambique, and Botswana, regional assistance
has been virtually limited to seven helicopters from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Despite working around the clock, by Tuesday the helicopters had
rescued barely 8,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, the continent's other potential ``superpower,'' has
provided nothing, while Zimbabwe, which has more than 30
helicopters, seems to have deployed most of them in the ruinous and
futile civil war in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Mozambique itself reportedly has but one functioning helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   None of this explains why logistical support from the massive
U.S. base at Diego Garcia in the Indian Ocean has not been
forthcoming, why the West dithered for a crucial two weeks, and why
its satellites and other assorted resources not detect southern
Africa's calamity-in-the-making.
</P>
<P>
   When the waters subside, and Mozambique is safe again, some very
hard questions will have to be answered. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
