<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-NUGGETS-NYT     03-01 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NUGGETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN HORN GETS REVENGE AS NETS TROUNCE NUGGETS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The last time the Nets played in Denver, Antonio
McDyess turned the game into his personal highlight show. He soared
above the rim for resounding dunks and lofted mid-range jump shots
with the soft touch of Patrick Ewing in his prime. Keith Van Horn,
who was supposed to be the Nets' answer at power forward, was
little more than a prop in McDyess' aerial spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn remembered that Denver victory, as well as McDyess's
performance, and set out Wednesday night for revenge. And in one of
his most efficient performances this season, he got it, scoring a
game-high 25 points and leading the Nets to a 94-81 victory at the
sparkling new Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, who also had 11 rebounds, wasted no time in washing
away the stain of last season's game. Hitting five of his first
eight shots, he scored 11 points in the first quarter and had 17 at
the close of a first half that had the Nets in front by 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, only the Nets' fourth in their last 27 trips to
Denver, improved the Nets' road record to 6-22 and sends them into
Thursday's game at Dallas on a high. Though just 25-31 over all,
the Nuggets are 19-11 at home.
</P>
<P>
   While Van Horn led the way early, Stephon Marbury shut the door
firmly on the Nuggets by scoring 9 of his 20 points in the fourth
period. Marbury, who also had eight assists, seemed to be purposely
exploiting the Denver point guard Nick Van Exel (2 points, 11
assists). Two years ago, while playing with Minnesota, Marbury was
stung by being left off the All-Star team in favor of Van Exel, who
was then a Los Angeles Laker.
</P>
<P>
   While Van Horn was the star, McDyess was not bad. He led the
Nuggets with 22 points and 11 rebounds, but made just nine of his
24 field goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn's excellence helped the Nets grab a 24-21 lead after
one quarter, but it was the team's bench that put the Nets solidly
in control. Coach Don Casey began the second with five reserves,
and after five minutes of play they had pushed the Nets' lead to
33-25. Scott Burrell did the most damage, scoring five consecutive
points by hitting a 22 footer and 3-pointer to turn a 1-point
deficit into a 4-point advantage.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess got the Nuggets close by scoring six straight points,
but the Nets closed the half with a 15-4 run. Van Horn led the
charge with 6 points, including two scintillating baskets on a
contested driving finger roll and a one-handed windmill dunk on a
breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' dominance was so thorough that the fans booed the home
team as it headed for the locker room. The Nuggets never pulled
closer than 11 points in the third quarter. The Nets, on the other
hand, were playing so well and enjoying themselves so much that
with four minutes left in the third, Kendall Gill whipped a
behind-the-back pass to Kerry Kittles for a fast-break layup that
made it 63-47.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between McDyess and Van Horn matched two of the
league's most promising young forwards. The 6-foot-9 McDyess, in
his fifth season out of Alabama, brought averages of 19 points, 8.3
rebounds and 1.94 blocks and a shooting percentage of .509 into
Wednesday's game. Van Horn, who is in his third season, entered
with averages of 18.1 points and 8.3 rebounds but was shooting just
41.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Facing McDyess was the second of four tough nights in store for
Van Horn on this five-game road trip. On Monday, he had the
misfortune of trying to guard Utah's Karl Malone, who abused him
for 35 points, 12 rebounds and 9 assists in Utah's 106-101 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the ostentatious Dennis Rodman awaits in Dallas,
and after a relative reprieve on Saturday in Houston, Van Horn will
have to deal with San Antonio's outstanding Tim Duncan, who is
currently out with a lower abdominal strain but is expected to
return later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as a challenge,'' Van Horn said. ``I'm not going
to shy away from it. Hopefully, it'll make me play harder and
better. Hopefully, I'll rise to the occasion and give my best
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, he did just that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
