<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRIETHRU-ART-400&AMP;ADD-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN SURRENDERS AFTER KILLING 2 IN RESTAURANTS IN PITTSBURGH
SUBURB 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 6th graf to correct typo in Burger King; 7th graf to add
info. on victims; 3rd graf after optional trim to CORRECT events in
doctor's office; adds new 4th graf after optional trim with quote
from one of the women in doctor's office) 
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILKINSBURG, Pa. _ A gunman who set his apartment on fire and
went on a lunchtime shooting spree at two fast-food restaurants was
taken into custody Wednesday after two people were killed and three
were critically wounded in this suburb of Pittsburgh, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, 39-year-old Ronald Taylor, surrendered after holding
police off for about two-and-a-half hours in an office building.
Taylor, who was arraigned Wednesday night, was charged with two
counts of criminal homicide, a charge that includes various degrees
of murder and manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Wilbert Young and police officials said they were
investigating whether the shootings with a .22-caliber handgun were
racially motivated. Taylor, who had no criminal history, is black,
while the five shot were white males, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The killings followed by one day the shooting death of a first
grader by a 6-year-old gunman in Mount Morris Township, Mich.,
leading President Clinton to urge Congress again to pass stricter
gun-control legislation. Clinton said the violent incidents ``call
on us to recognize the fact that we haven't done everything we can
do to keep these guns away from criminals and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's incident in this faded working-class suburb of
25,000 began about 11:15 a.m., when the police received a call that
a person had been shot and had been taken to a hospital. Officers
were given the address of the suspected gunman and arrived to find
Taylor's fifth-floor apartment on fire, the Wilkinsburg police
chief, Gerald Brewer, said.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, there were more calls saying that someone had
been shot at a nearby Burger King and three more persons had been
shot at a McDonald's, Brewer said, adding that the callers provided
a description of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The dead were identified as John Kroll, 55, of Cabot, Pa., and
Joseph Healy, 71, of Wilkinsburg. One of the wounded, Richard
Clinger, was shot while sitting in his van at McDonald's, witnesses
said. Healy was a former chaplain at Duquesne University in
Pittsburgh, said a stepson, Jim Alles. Kroll was a maintenance
worker at the apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   A maintenance worker at the apartment building told The
Associated Press that Taylor had become angry that the broken door
to his apartment had not been repaired quickly enough. ``He said,
`You're all white trash, racist pigs,''' the worker, John DeWitt,
told the wire service.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said of the standoff: ``I'm very proud of how the
officers responded. They used uncommon restraint in not taking his
life. That can be debated today and tomorrow, but today it was the
right thing to do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brewer said that the police were investigating a report that
Taylor had walked into a woman's home after he left his apartment,
telling her, ``I'm dead anyway, I just need to hide a couple of
minutes,'' and also saying, ``I'm just out to shoot white people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep hearing things, but we don't have anything factual,''
Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Robert Tuite of the Wilkinsburg police said that he and two
officers had spotted the suspect walking along a street and that he
turned and fired two shots, then went into an office building.
Taylor entered a doctor's office and briefly held two nurses and an
office worker hostage, Tuite said. Taylor then stepped out of the
office and the door closed behind him, allowing the women to
escape. One of the three, Joyce Ambrose, told WTAE in Pittsburgh
that the gunman had said, ``I have one bullet left, which of the
three should I use it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also entered a senior citizens center but took no
hostages, Tuite said, adding that he entered the building and saw
Taylor sitting in the hallway, about 40 feet away, with the handgun
in his mouth. Taylor later pointed the gun at his head, and talked
about killing himself, the lieutenant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to do that, relax, we'll get through this,''
Tuite said he told Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor pointed his gun at the officers several times but they
did not fire, the lieutenant said, adding that the officers felt
they had him isolated and that they had sufficient cover behind a
cement wall.
</P>
<P>
   Tuite said that he spoke to Taylor for about 15 minutes, and
that Taylor had asked for a cigarette, adding that when the suspect
was asked if he needed a light, he replied that he had a lighter
and had used it to set his apartment on fire.
</P>
<P>
   A SWAT team and a negotiator were called in from Pittsburgh, and
about 125 people, including 37 children from a day-care center,
were evacuated from the office building, other police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. John Fischer of the Pittsburgh police department, who
negotiated with Taylor, told reporters: ``His mood went from anger
to confusion, distraught, fear and remorse. He bantered back and
forth between killing himself and surrendering.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, gang activity and violent crime had
been significantly reduced in Wilkinsburg, Brewer said, adding that
his department's records showed no no prior arrests for Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Young sounded a similar note Wednesday night saying: ``We are
sad and shocked over this. We're totally surprised.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
