<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-MATTINGLY-5     03-01 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MATTINGLY-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEMS LIKE OLD TIMES: MATTINGLY IN YANKEE CAMP, NOW AS A COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ It was as if Don Mattingly opened a time capsule
Wednesday, breaking into a box of equipment closed years ago, stuff
he had not seen since his last game in 1995. His jersey still fit,
with the No. 23, and so did the baseball shoes and pants.
</P>
<P>
   Only the baseball cap was new, and when Mattingly drew that
down, it was as if he had never retired. The same sloped shoulders,
the thick forearms, the mustache, the easy throwing motion.
Somebody mentioned that the New York Yankees are currently in need
of a left-handed designated hitter. On his first day as the
Yankees' spring training instructor, Mattingly laughed at the
notion.
</P>
<P>
   He had watched Catfish Hunter serve as a coach in spring
training for years, and saw how much fun he had. After Hunter died
last year, it occurred to Mattingly that it was time for him to go
to spring training, the way Hunter had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to do what he was doing _ come back, enjoy,
stay in touch with baseball, but then go back to your family and
home,'' said Mattingly, who has returned to Yankee Stadium since
his retirement, including a 1997 ceremony when his number was
retired.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday he did not do much more than stand near the batting
cages and watch hitters. But that is typical of Mattingly, who
seems leery of overstepping his bounds. Joe Torre, the Yankees'
manager, asked him to work alongside Chris Chambliss, the hitting
coach. Mattingly is probably aware of the whispers last year that
he would replace Chambliss. Wednesday, Mattingly stood and chatted
with Chambliss, arms folded, his presence understated.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly has spoken of wanting to manage someday, but coaching
in camp this spring, he said, was just a way to keep in contact
with the game, for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they've got a great thing going,'' Mattingly said.
``I feel like I can learn from everybody around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of a managerial job, he said, ``is a good ways down
the road.''
</P>
<P>
   He retired after the 1995 season at age 34, with 2,153 career
hits, but without a World Series ring, because he ``didn't want to
leave home any more.'' Taylor, the oldest of his three children, is
almost 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won the World Series the next year, with Tino
Martinez playing first base, and Mattingly acknowledged Wednesday
that it was hard to watch the team win the title without him. But
as time passed and he embraced the precious days he could spend
with his children, Mattingly gained some perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest way to explain it to people, you could take three
World Series rings and put them in my right hand,'' said Mattingly,
holding his arms as if they were scales. ``And take that time with
my family _ my kids and watching what they've been through _ in the
other hand. If you're looking at a scale, my left hand is down to
the ground. It's really not comparable. I'm just so thankful. I
felt I did the exact right thing. It was perfect for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to leave the kids, I wanted to be a part of what
they were doing. If I had kept going, Taylor would've been in high
school and I wouldn't have known him. I know I left some stuff on
the table, base hits and stuff, but you know what? A hundred years
from now, nobody is ever going to think about it. I'm just totally
happy I did it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees are known as a close-knit, unselfish team, and Paul
O'Neill, Bernie Williams and others have attributed that to
Mattingly, saying the current legacy belongs to him. ``If it's my
legacy, then I got it from Willie and Goose and Nettles and
Piniella and guys that were here when I was coming up,'' Mattingly
said, referring to Willie Randolph, Goose Gossage, Graig Nettles
and Lou Piniella. ``It feels good to pass stuff on.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly has a small patch of short whiskers beneath his lower
lip _ the stinger, he called it _ and he laughed when asked about
it, knowing the owner George Steinbrenner's rule against facial
hair. ``I came from a beard to a goatee to this,'' he said, ``so I
went a long way. I could do another step. I just have to do it
slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossage is here now, and Torre mentioned his extra bushy
mustache. ``There are certain liberties those old guys get,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly will work closely with Nick Johnson, a star Class AAA
first baseman who is being groomed to replace Martinez in 2001, and
Wednesday, Reggie Jackson _ another spring coach _ introduced
Mattingly to Johnson, who seemed somewhat in awe.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 21, recalled that Mattingly was a good defensive first
baseman, a good player. ``I don't remember watching him,'' said
Johnson, adding with no disrespect intended, ``It was before my
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in camp know Mattingly much better than Johnson. ``What
can't you learn from him?'' Jeter asked rhetorically. ``If you're
Nick, you should take advantage of it. It's not too often you have
a player of Mattingly's caliber accessible to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez added: ``A lot of guys could learn a lot from him. It's
exciting for the organization and exciting for myself, just to have
him around.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius told teammates on the field about the first time
he ever met Mattingly, while playing for Oakland against the
Yankees, after Brosius reached first base in his rookie season.
Mattingly immediately began speaking to Brosius as if they had been
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Scottie, I've just finished this book, I know you'd love
it,'' Mattingly said, chatting along.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius is, in fact, an avid reader. He could not imagine how
Mattingly would know that. He wondered if Mattingly just told
everybody about books he was reading. He wondered if Mattingly was
trying to trick him into getting picked off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confused and suspicious,'' Brosius said. ``I was talking
with him, trying not to be rude, but I didn't know what to make of
it. I was like, `What's he trying to do.' I came to find out he's
just a nice guy, and that's the way he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-01-00 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
