r f BC-ABELL-PLEAD-KAN &LR;      03-01 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABELL-PLEAD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH SYSTEM CEO PLEADS GUILTY TO MEDICARE FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Richard Michael Abell, former president and
chief executive officer of Carondelet Health, pleaded guilty
Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Kansas City to defrauding
Medicare of more than $91,000.
</P>
<P>
   Abell, 60, was fired by Carondelet, which includes St. Joseph
Health Center and St. Mary's Hospital of Blue Springs, Mo., in
October 1998. On Wednesday, he waived indictment and admitted that
he fraudulently had caused St. Joseph Health Center to reimburse
him for more than $361,000 in personal expenses by claiming them as
business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Abell's fraudulent business expenses, in turn, had been
submitted over a period of several years to Medicare, the
government health program for the elderly. Medicare reimbursed St.
Joseph for a portion of that amount _ $91,114.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors said Abell had committed fraud from about
Jan. 1, 1993, to Oct. 5, 1998. Nothing in the government documents
released Wednesday indicated what Abell had spent the money on,
except to say that it had nothing to do with the business of St.
Joseph Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea represents another step in the federal
government's crackdown against Medicare fraud. Prosecutors saluted
the hospital for its cooperation in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Joseph Health Center demonstrated that hospitals and
federal law enforcement can most effectively fight health care
fraud by building a relationship of cooperation and mutual
support,'' U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   Abell and his attorney, Thomas J. Cox, could not be reached for
comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Abell, who is free on bond, faces a maximum sentence of 10 years
in prison without parole and as much as $250,000 in fines.
Paperwork included in the plea agreement shows he might face 10 to
16 months in prison. But the sentence ultimately will depend on the
findings of a presentence investigation and the final rulings of a
judge. A sentencing hearing is scheduled for 11 a.m. on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty plea represents a dramatic turn for Abell, the 1996
recipient of the Missouri Hospital Association's Distinguished
Service Award.
</P>
<P>
   A health-care administrator for nearly three decades, the
Overland Park, Kan. resident had executive positions at hospitals
in Tennessee and Kentucky before moving to Kansas City in 1986 to
join St. Joseph as its president.
</P>
<P>
   In a news release, Hill said St. Joseph had negotiated an
agreement with the U.S. attorney's office in September and had
agreed to pay $172,228 to resolve the case. The agreement was
reached without the filing of civil lawsuits, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization terminated the employee, took responsibility
for the financial damage done to a taxpayer-funded program, and
cooperated fully in determining the extent of criminal wrongdoing
that occurred,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   George A. Zara, who replaced Abell as Carondelet's president and
chief executive officer in 1999, said in a statement Wednesday that
the Carondelet board was ``confident it took the appropriate action
when releasing Mike Abell in October 1998, after an internal
investigation of his personal expense accounts. A further
investigation after Abell's release showed significant
improprieties on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   Zara did not address the specifics of those improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   Zara added that Carondelet ``demonstrates no tolerance for
employees who violate the mission and values on which Carondelet is
founded.''
</P>
<P>
   Zara said Carondelet will continue to support and enforce a
corporate responsibility program for employees.
</P>
<P>
   Carondelet spokeswoman Debbie Brinkoetter said that an insurance
carrier had covered the hospital's expenses in the Abell matter and
that the hospital had not sought restitution from the former
executive. Brinkoetter said Carondelet had not filed any lawsuits
against Abell and did not intend to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The crime Abell pleaded guilty to is a Class C felony. The case
was investigated by the FBI and the U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Health-care fraud has been the focus of a massive government
crackdown in recent years. In a Medicare kickback case that
attracted national attention, two Johnson County, Kansas physicians
and a former executive from Baptist Medical Center in Kansas City
were sentenced to prison last October.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Wade, a spokesman for the American Hospital
Association in Washington, said Abell's plea illustrates a rare
case of a hospital executive getting caught mixing personal
expenses with the hospital's Medicare allocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's medical ethics or business ethics, they're at the
core of what we do, and there's an important public accountability
and responsibility at stake,'' Wade said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
