</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-SHOWS-3TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONDON SEASON WITH THE STAMP `MADE IN THE U.S.'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from Europe.  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When it comes to theatrical invasions, there is a new
one here worth signaling: the influx of American shows, several of
them in their original productions. Think of it as a long-overdue
attempt to redress what some might call a theatrical imbalance,
because the traffic, of course, generally heads the other way.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, some kind of history was made last spring when
eight English or Irish stagings _ including those of several
American plays, ``The Iceman Cometh'' for starters _ all opened
within 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the British are absent from this Broadway season:
Michael Frayn's ``Copenhagen,'' with an American cast, and the
Donmar Warehouse revival of Tom Stoppard's ``Real Thing,'' with its
full West End company, will join the current revival of Peter
Shaffer's ``Amadeus'' on Broadway in the spring. And the Royal
Shakespeare Company returns to the Brooklyn Academy of Music with
three productions in May, a revelatory ``Don Carlos'' among them.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noting, though, that by that time, London will have
been awash in American exports, whether in the razzle-dazzle form
of ``Fosse,'' easily this city's biggest musical opening since
``The Lion King'' (another American show) last October, or in
transfers from New York to London of the plays ``Side Man,''
``Bash'' and ``Wit,'' their American creative teams intact.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Laurie Anderson will bring her multimedia piece ``Songs
and Stories From Moby-Dick'' to the Barbican Center. And in June
arrives ``Stop Kiss,'' Diana Son's play that was well received two
seasons ago at the Joseph Papp Public Theater in New York. Already
gone, but not forgotten, is the Bush Theater's admirable
presentation of Nicky Silver's ``Maiden's Prayer,'' with an
Anglo-American cast.
</P>
<P>
   Also departed this season, though in homegrown British
productions, were three dramas by Americans, the first two of which
have also been seen in New York: ``Goodnight Children Everywhere''
by Richard Nelson, ``Three Days of Rain'' by Richard Greenberg and
``Rose'' by Martin Sherman (this one-woman show starring Olympia
Dukakis arrives on Broadway later this month in a Lincoln Center
Theater production).
</P>
<P>
   All three plays were nominated for the Olivier Award for best
play, which ``Goodnight Children Everywhere'' went on to win. The
author, Nelson, is one of an increasing number of Americans whose
work is presented first in London; eight of his nine Royal
Shakespeare Company openings to date have been world premieres.
</P>
<P>
   This season, world premieres of new plays by two younger
American writers are being mounted by the newly reopened Royal
Court Theater in its studio-size Jerwood Theater Upstairs:
``Breath, Boom'' by Kia Corthron, 34, and ``Other People'' by
Christopher Shinn, 24. Shinn had great success at the same
theater's young writers' festival in 1998 with his play ``Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham Whybrow, the Royal Court literary manager, recalled a
letter that Shinn had sent to the theater several years ago in
which he and another young American dramatist described themselves
as, Whybrow said, ``talented writers who were having huge
difficulties getting plays on in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So naturally,'' Whybrow continued, ``you wanted to read those
plays overnight.'' Especially when, he added, ``many of the plays
we've responded to most of all are from writers who have not had
much success in the States.''
</P>
<P>
   The better-known American writers can open shows first in
England, as well. Arthur Miller's ``Ride Down Mt. Morgan,''
expected on Broadway later this month, was first seen in a West End
production here in 1991. Two of David Mamet's plays, ``Glengarry
Glen Ross'' and ``The Cryptogram,'' received their world premieres
here in 1983 and 1994, respectively, though it is the Mamet
revivals that have been causing a stir this season.
</P>
<P>
   First out of the gate was the Atlantic Theater Company's staging
of ``American Buffalo,'' starring William H. Macy and Philip Baker
Hall, which ended a sellout run at the Donmar Warehouse on Feb. 26
before setting up shop Off Broadway at the Atlantic, where it is
now in previews.
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial Mamet festival here gathers steam later this
month when Patrick Marber, the playwright (``Closer'') and former
stand-up comic, tries on yet another cap as an actor in a West End
revival of ``Speed-the-Plow,'' Mamet's 1988 satire about Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between this and other seasons: when Marber heads
out for dinner after his show, he may well find himself rubbing
shoulders with the likes of Kathleen Chalfant, Edie Falco, Jason
Priestley and Matthew Lillard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cross-fertilization is fantastic,'' said Ciaran Hinds, the
Belfast-born actor who made his Broadway debut last March in
``Closer,'' which was then playing across the street from ``Side
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``That company, I really, really enjoyed,'' Hinds said of the
American actors in ``Side Man'' who have reteamed for its London
run. ``I was so thrilled they gave Frank Wood that prize'' _ the
Tony Award for best featured actor. ``I thought, `Wow, what
control.'''
</P>
<P>
   An English player more than qualified to assess the shift in
traffic is Eileen Atkins, who has been a frequent presence on
Broadway and off for much of her career. (She is hoping to return
to New York in the fall in Yasmina Reza's play ``The Unexpected
Man.'') ``Thank God, I say,'' said Atkins of the American arrivals.
``I hope there's much more coming from over there. We inundate them
every so often, and the next year they should inundate us.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the good wishes of some British performers, American
productions in London have several major hurdles to surmount:
reviews by many more critics than in New York, a number of which
are sometimes contradictory if not indifferent; a tendency for
audiences to ignore any ballyhoo surrounding productions that
arrive sporting awards; and a reluctance by audiences to attend
shows that do not confirm Britain's worst prejudices about America.
</P>
<P>
   One result of this is that several New York hits have stumbled
in London. Paula Vogel's Pulitzer Prize-winning drama about incest,
``How I Learned to Drive,'' played to 43 percent attendance overall
during its 1998 summer run at the Donmar Warehouse, despite a
production by the Irish director John Crowley that in some ways
surpassed the long-running one Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mantello, the American director who is making his London
debut here with ``Bash,'' joked that if Vogel's lead character
``had pulled out an Uzi and killed her uncle, perhaps the London
reception would have been different.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Donald Margulies' ``Collected Stories,'' about a
writer and her protegee, twice seen Off Broadway, got poor reviews
on the West End last fall, despite the star presence of Helen
Mirren. At one performance not long before the run ended, 186
people were in an auditorium containing 884 seats, according to
staff at the Theater Royal, Haymarket.
</P>
<P>
   Given the risk, why make the journey?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just people backing their judgment,'' said the London
producer Robert Fox, who has worked often _ and to financial reward
_ on Broadway with many of David Hare's plays, among others, but
who suffered a setback at home when his West End version of
Terrence McNally's ``Master Class,'' starring Patti LuPone, flopped
in 1997. ``In the end,'' Fox said, ``people follow their instincts,
or they should.''
</P>
<P>
   But whereas an English play in New York might trade on its very
Englishness _ Pam Gems' ``Stanley'' comes to mind, about that most
quintessentially English painter, Sir Stanley Spencer _ it isn't
always a good idea for American plays to be too American in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culturally specific,'' said Stephen Daldry, the British
theater director, ``in particular, the American porch play that
American writers have cherished and loved for many years in terms
of their new writing, has seemed to have very little relevance to a
much more fast-flowing, abstract, experimental drama that has been
emerging in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   During Daldry's tenure as artistic director of the Royal Court,
plays like Jez Butterworth's ``Mojo'' and Mark Ravenhill's
``Shopping and ...'' had premieres at the theater before being seen
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The porch play,'' Daldry said, referring to the strain of
realistic domestic drama in American writing, ``not to mention that
thing of, `Oops, I wasn't loved enough by my father,' somehow
didn't have the relevance in this country. Like the Jewish play
didn't have the relevance. Like `Rent' didn't quite take off. It's
a matter of politics, ultimately. But it's not about excluding a
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Panter, a London producer and theater owner who incurred
critical scorn more than a decade ago when he attempted a West End
run of McNally's ``Frankie and Johnny in the Clair de Lune,'' said:
``We embrace Americans in music, movies and jeans. Why don't we
embrace them in theater?''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Neil LaBute's ``Bash'' and Mamet's ``American
Buffalo'' _ which work hard to be scabrous and unsentimental _ the
reviews have been rather embracing: generally favorable, even if
both productions had their detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved with other plays waiting in the wings have their
own rationales for attempting a run here. Daryl Roth, the American
co-producer of ``Wit,'' said she brought over Margaret Edson's play
``because it deals with death and cancer and John Donne.'' Roth is
one of the producers backing a 17-week West End run opening in
April and starring Chalfant in her original role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel like such an American slice of life,'' Roth
said about ``Wit.'' ``I hope people don't look at it as, `Oh, here
comes an American play.' This to me transcends that. It feels right
to me to do `Wit' in London; it feels right to do it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
