<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE AUDITOR SAYS MISSOURI DIVISION OF AGING `NEEDS SERIOUS
ATTENTION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri Auditor Claire McCaskill said the
state's Division of Aging isn't doing its job overseeing nursing
homes, missing about 400 inspections last year and not
investigating complaints quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   An audit by McCaskill's office released Wednesday also found 21
cases in which nursing homes or in-home care providers employed
someone who had abused or neglected the elderly before.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill said workers in the division's Kansas City office were
more often late in filing paperwork on complaint investigations
than employees in other regions. Also, Kansas City investigators
declared complaints unsubstantiated in about seven out of 10 cases,
compared with a statewide rate of about four in 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this audit will be a wake-up call to the Legislature
and the policy-makers that this agency needs serious attention. It
needs resources. We need some changes in the law,'' McCaskill said
during a news conference in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill's audit comes after a recent federal investigation
found inadequate state inspections of nursing homes in Missouri and
other states.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill recommended that the division catch up on inspections,
strengthen sanctions against unsafe nursing homes and set minimum
staffing levels in the homes.
</P>
<P>
   The audit uncovered no evidence of wrongdoing by the division,
McCaskill said. She blamed the problems partly on mismanagement,
partly on inadequate laws and partly on the fact that the
division's undersized staff is straining to meet the demands of an
ever-aging population.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dunn, who became director of the Division of Aging last
month, said he appreciates that Gov. Mel Carnahan has asked the
General Assembly for 30 new division positions for nursing-home
oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn admitted that his agency has struggled to keep up with the
2,500 required inspections because the 158 field inspectors also
are swamped with investigating, documenting and helping address
complaints and nursing-home violations.
</P>
<P>
   He said the agency will catch up on necessary inspections by the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn also defended the work of the Kansas City office, saying
the people there are committed to ensuring the safety of
nursing-home residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put people over paper. So sometimes a situation is
investigated and cleared up, but before the paperwork is done,
they're on to something else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill said she would like to see tighter requirements on who
can work in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The state maintains a list of people whom nursing homes cannot
employ because they have abused or neglected the elderly before.
</P>
<P>
   But the state also has two other employee disqualification
lists, one for those who can't work with children and another for
those who can't work with the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   The audit found more than 1,100 employees at nursing homes or
in-home care companies who had been disqualified from working with
children or the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill wants to prevent nursing homes from employing someone
whose name appears on any of the three lists.
</P>
<P>
   She also wants the Division of Aging to study whether current
sanctions are strong enough to make nursing homes safe.
</P>
<P>
   The audit found one home was cited for 111 deficiencies in its
last four inspections. In more than 200 inspections, homes had at
least 10 deficiencies but no federal or state sanctions were
imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, I believe if the Legislature reads this audit
thoroughly, they will want to do the things that we are
recommending,'' McCaskill said. ``I think they will realize this is
a problem we just can't ignore. It's too important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
