<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-01 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4168 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AMERICAN-SHOWS-3RDTAK     03-01 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-SHOWS-3RDTAKE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LONDON: it anywhere.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And although ``Side Man'' may focus on a family, it also boasts
the unusual backdrop of jazz, which, said its American co-producer
Ron Kastner, could work on its behalf. ``What I've been told by all
my English friends is that the one thing everybody says Americans
know best is jazz,'' Kastner said.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of a North American ensemble for the play,
including Falco and Priestley, who is Canadian-born, came about
largely at the insistence of the playwright, Warren Leight. ``It's
fair to say I lobbied very hard for that,'' Leight said. ``It's
partly loyalty to my New York cast and also self-serving; they know
the key the play was written in.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Side Man'' troupe was preceded in London by the three
Americans in the revival of ``American Buffalo'' directed by Neil
Pepe, while LaBute's ``Bash'' involves a stunning American acting
trio, Mary McCormack, Matthew Lillard and Zeljko Ivanek, who did
his drama training in London.
</P>
<P>
   About the three one-acts he has combined under one title, LaBute
said, ``They're terribly American plays about people who are in one
of the few, if only, religions that have sprung up in America.''
The playwright, who, like his characters, is a Mormon, said of his
desire to keep the cast of the play American: ``It just made sense
to start the play with people already at ease with the kind of
language I wrote. That gives it an added ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Daldry seemed to have no doubts on that subject. ``It is
absolutely paramount that shows from America should be seen in
their original productions in this country,'' he said, though when
he was running the Royal Court, it presented British stagings of
Mamet's ``Oleanna'' and John Guare's ``Six Degrees of Separation''
(the latter production did, however, retain its original New York
star, Stockard Channing).
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mendes, artistic director of the Donmar Warehouse and the
director of both ``Cabaret'' on Broadway and the current film
``American Beauty,'' knows both acting communities well. ``The fact
is,'' Mendes said, ``there is this huge strata of great theater
actors who have a film career but aren't widely known _ Kathleen,
Zeljko, Mary, even Bill Macy, although he does have a bigger film
profile than most. This is a chance for them to be seen in what is
still effectively one of the two theater capitals of the world.
That's very moving.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, other considerations can prevail. ``Fosse''
opened with local performers to some enthusiastic notices and a few
real notes of dissent (``So what is all the Fosse about?'' read the
headline over the review in The Evening Standard).
</P>
<P>
   But, said Ann Reinking, the show's co-choreographer and
co-director, ``To have this company that is entirely British _ they
take greater ownership if it's their own company in their own
country.''
</P>
<P>
   And somewhat surprisingly, Douglas Carter Beane vetoed a West
End run of his Off Broadway comedy, ``As Bees in Honey Drown,''
that would have happened about now, possibly starring Madonna. The
problem, Beane said, arose when the London producers insisted on
mounting a British version from scratch, directed by an Englishman,
Steven Pimlott, rather than the play's New York director, Mark
Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British press can be pretty rough on American plays,''
Beane said. ``They're not exactly nurturing an interest, whereas an
OK English play is given a chance in America.'' As a consequence,
he said, ``My feeling was and is, if the play was going to happen
in London, then it should get its best shot, which is to say with
the person who guided me through it the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Beane went on: ``It would have been nice to have been part of
this incredibly exciting American explosion on the West End.
They're all my pals. But it's not as if the play has a shelf life
of dairy. It's a good play and it will get done. Though I do regret
it about once a week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
