<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S TALK OF `EVIL' RILES BAUER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
RIVERSIDE, Calif. _ John McCain's - criticism of religious leaders
boomeranged Wednesday, March 1, when one of his top conservative
supporters demanded an apology for the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, a religious conservative who endorsed McCain last
month after dropping his own presidential bid, said McCain's speech
Monday attacking evangelists and political leaders Pat Robertson
and Jerry Falwell was out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must in the strongest possible terms repudiate Senator
McCain's - unwarranted, ill-advised and divisive attacks on certain
religious leaders,'' Bauer said in a statement. ``Senator McCain
must not allow his personal differences with any individual to
cloud his judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, March 1, McCain defended his speech, saying, ``I
stand by my comment.''
</P>
<P>
   John Weaver, McCain's national political director, after noting
that Bauer had seen an advance copy of the Monday, Feb. 28, speech
and had even been permitted to suggest some changes, was also
adamant. ``There won't be an apology,'' Weaver declared.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer was with McCain on Monday, Feb. 28, when the Arizona
senator criticized Robertson and Falwell. He told reporters after
the speech, ``If this were an attack on Christian conservative
voters, I wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigned in California on Wednesday, March 1, McCain
found himself repeatedly answering questions about statements he
had made on Tuesday, Feb. 29, aboard the Straight Talk Express, his
campaign bus. &QL; 
`FORCES OF EVIL'
</P>
<P>
   McCain had told reporters that Robertson and Falwell exercise an
``evil influence . . . over the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To stand up and take on the forces of evil _ that's my job,
and I can't steer the Republican Party if those two individuals
have the influence that they have on the party today,'' McCain was
reported as saying.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Wednesday, March 1, that his remarks were a part of
his ongoing imagery from the movie Star Wars and ``a lighthearted
attempt at humor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not say or mean to say they are evil,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters on his campaign bus Wednesday, March 1,
that he was not worried about getting bogged down in the religious
strife that sometimes seems to have engulfed the campaign. ``This
is about the heart and soul, the direction of the party,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also shot down earlier reports that national communications
director Dan Schnur had quit over disagreements on the handling of
Thursday's, March 2, GOP debate in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about our campaign is that people get to
disagree,'' McCain said. ``Sometimes, they even shout at each
other. . . We have a very freewheeling, very participatory
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   As McCain campaigned throughout Southern California, it became
clear that his forces believe victory could come in one of two
ways: As an all-out win of the state's delegates, something that
polls indicate is increasingly unlikely, or by capturing a majority
of the state's popular vote, which would include Independents and
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the majority of Republican votes in California will
take away 162 delegates of the 1,034 required to win the
nomination. Unlike many of the earlier states McCain has competed
in, if he puts together a majority with the help of Independents
and Democrats but lacks a Republican majority, he will receive no
delegates at all.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how he defines victory, it is clear that McCain,
who has targeted California for more than a year, knows he must
emerge from that delegate-rich state with something to show for his
efforts. &QL; 
`BEAUTY CONTEST'
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters in Riverside on Wednesday, March 1, that
he believes he can come away with victories both in the ``beauty
contest,'' or popular vote, and in the battle for GOP delegates.
</P>
<P>
   With his victories in Washington, North Dakota and Virginia on
Tuesday, Texas Gov. George W. Bush now holds 170 delegates to
McCain's 105 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who lost overwhelmingly among women in Virginia, also
seemed to step up his efforts to win the female vote by coming
close to saying he would pick a female vice presidential running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very logical to have a woman vice president,''
McCain said on Wednesday, March 1. ``And perhaps, in the next
cycle, a woman president.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain later said he wasn't promising a woman on his ticket, but
he pointed to New Jersey Gov. Christie Todd Whitman and Arizona
Gov. Jane Hull, both Bush allies, as qualified women.
</P>
<P>
   In a Los Angeles Times poll released Wednesday, March 1, Bush
led McCain 47 percent to 26 percent, with Alan Keyes at 6 percent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RIVERSIDE, Calif. _ John McCain's criticism of religious leaders
boomeranged Wednesday when one of his top conservative supporters
demanded an apology for the remarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
